<HEADLINE>
MIDEAST TALKS END WITH NO AGREEMENT, DESPITE PUSH BY CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: LEADS with White House announcing talks end with no
agreement; will be led after Clinton's speech, scheduled to begin
at 12:30 a.m. ET.) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ and DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The nine-day Camp David summit meeting, convened
by President Clinton in an attempt to settle the 52-year-old
conflict between the Palestinians and Israelis, ended without an
agreement Wednesday night, despite a fervent 11th-hour push by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   In a terse statement reflecting sharp disappointment at the
collapse of intense negotiations, Clinton's spokesman, Joe
Lockhart, announced shortly after 11 p.m.: ``The summit has come to
a conclusion without reaching an agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   For several hours before leaving the secluded mountain retreat,
Clinton shuttled between the Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak,
and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, in a last desperate
attempt to salvage the talks. But evidently he was unable to bridge
the differences on the major issues.
</P>
<P>
   And in what many observers considered a sign of trouble, the two
Middle East leaders remained apart all day.
</P>
<P>
   Israel Radio reported immediately after the breakdown that
Clinton had proposed that both leaders accept a partial agreement
that covered major issues _ including the territorial shape of a
Palestinian state and the fate of 3 million Palestinian refugees in
the Middle East _ but excluded a solution on the status of
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The White House declined to immediately pinpoint the major
sticking points, but in the last several days of the summit
meeting, reports filtered out that the question of Jerusalem was
the most intractable issue on the table.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton prepared to return to the White House to make a
statement before departing for a gathering of the leaders of the
seven major industrial nations in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was expected to give a news conference before flying back
to Israel, while Arafat was preparing to leave without making any
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who had pushed Clinton hard to call the summit and wanted
an overarching agreement ending the conflict to sell back home, was
expected to say that Arafat had failed to negotiate in good faith
and that the Palestinians should carry the full brunt of the
breakdown, an Israeli official said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of high tension and rapidly shifting moods. Late
into the evening, Clinton was still making an all-out effort to
salvage the talks. Briefing reporters at 5:30 p.m., Lockhart had
said that the talks were at a ``pivotal moment.''
</P>
<P>
   But in letters written in the last 48 hours, Arafat and Barak
made private appeals to Clinton, all the while gearing up to lay
the blame for a failed summit meeting squarely on the other.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the high-tension, high-stakes day see-sawed. At
midday, it seemed certain that the talks were fizzling out. By
early evening, when the parties were still entrenched at Camp David
and tentatively scheduled final news conferences were postponed, it
seemed possible that Clinton would be able to pull out an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But in an unexpectedly quick first climax, the Israeli
journalists accompanying Barak were ordered in the afternoon to
rush to their hotels for a security check so that their luggage
could be shuttled to Andrews Air Force Base for an 8 p.m. departure
for Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ran down, expectations were rife that there had
been a breakdown. Israeli television reported, and a U.S. official
later confirmed, that Barak had sent a letter to Clinton announcing
the prime minister's departure and laid the blame for the summit
meeting's failure on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian side is conducting negotiations insincerely
and is not willing to negotiate in a serious and practical manner
for a permanent peace between us,'' an Israeli reporter cited as a
direct quotation from the letter.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Palestinian negotiator, Abu Mazen, who himself was
heading to the airport to fly home to his son's wedding, brushed
off what he saw as an eleventh-hour Israeli tactic to increase
pressure on the Palestinians. Talks were ongoing, he said, and the
fate of Jerusalem, a seemingly intractable issue, was still on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television reported that Barak sent Arafat a message
that he was willing to return to Camp David for another round of
talks but that he might not still be prime minister by then.
Palestinian officials reported, in turn, that Arafat, seeing this
as a threat, retorted that if he made too many concessions, Sheik
Ahmed Yassin, spiritual leader of the Islamic fundamentalist Hamas
group, would be taking his place.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a briefing at the Thurmont Elementary School some 5
miles from Camp David, Lockhart gave the final day an extended
lease on life. He said that as he spoke, Clinton was sitting down
at the retreat's Birch Cabin to his second face-to-face session
Wednesday with the Arafat. Clinton had met with Barak earlier in
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the changing dynamic of refreshed momentum, Israeli
journalists returned to the press filing center, where one, Keren
Neubach, announced breathlessly that their bags were being returned
from the Air Force base to the Hampton Inn where they were staying.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton also received a letter from Arafat,
which arrived on Tuesday, before Barak's. He did not characterize
its contents, but Palestinian officials said that Arafat had
reached a peak of frustration on the eighth day.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart made clear that the two leaders were having trouble
making concessions on deeply emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders both want to go home with an agreement,'' Lockhart
said. ``The problem is the substance and structure of the
agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the extended deadline would have to stand.
``There comes a time when you have to put a time limit on
discussions,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
