<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: JERUSALEM PROBLEM TOO TIGHTLY TIED TO OTHER ISSUES 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: The following story is an added starter on The New York Times
front page) 
(With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Before sifting through the rubble of the failed
Camp David summit meeting, it bears noting that the mere fact of an
Israeli and a Palestinian leader confronting the intractable issue
of Jerusalem's sovereignty was a milestone in Middle Eastern
history.
</P>
<P>
   That nine days of high-stakes, high-level talks apparently
disintegrated in large part on that volatile issue, which Middle
Eastern leaders have never before dared to touch, is not as
surprising as the fact that they finally broached this taboo
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the status of Jerusalem need not have been a deal-breaker
if the Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, and the Palestine
leader, Yasser Arafat, had been willing or able to go for a partial
accord that delayed decision-making on this subject.
</P>
<P>
   But they were not. Or they could not because the interplay
between Jerusalem and the other issues was too intricate to allow
one issue to be solved or left unsolved without affecting the
overall balance of concessions.
</P>
<P>
   And that meant that one of the most momentous peace meetings in
modern history fizzled to a close on a rainy night that dampened
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of ending a 52-year conflict, it may have put in
jeopardy, temporarily at least, the whole notion of
Israeli-Palestinian peacemaking. It is possible that lower-level
negotiators will resume their work, but it is hard to imagine a
profitable dynamic when their leaders had visited and revisited
every compromise possible and rejected them conclusively.
</P>
<P>
   So the end of talks greeted the Mideast, which was about to wake
up when the talks finally broke down shortly before 11 p.m. here,
with an uncertain future at what was supposed to be the end of a
seven-year peace effort. And it raised the specter of violent
confrontations, of a genuine, street-level battle for Palestinian
independence building toward Arafat's pledged deadline of Sept. 13
for declaring a state.
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to know, at this point, if the talks did more
harm than good. The meeting, which the Israelis pushed for, but the
Palestinians resisted, was premised on the idea of averting a
violent climax to the peace effort. While the Palestinians
predicted failure, saying the summit meeting was premature, the
Israelis, and the Americans who eventually convened the meeting,
thought it better to try than not to try, considering the political
and social tensions building in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The language in Barak's closing letter to President Clinton did
not offer any suggestion that the meeting had brought the parties
closer, even though they were locked up in a presidential retreat
for nine days of intimate, emotional conversations. Instead, it
demonstrated, as did statements by the Palestinians, that the
mutual recriminations were not only still strong, but were perhaps
stronger than ever in Barak's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat met only three times during the nine days that
Clinton spent shuttling between them, and there is no evidence that
their relationship grew stronger in the bucolic setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day,'' said David Makovsky, a senior fellow at the
Washington Institute for Near East Policy, who has chronicled the
peace effort for the last decade. ``Camp David was high noon for
the Middle East, time to finish all the business of the 20th
century, but now we will be stuck there, in the past, for the
foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
   At the last minute, according to an Israel Radio report at 11
p.m., the Americans proposed a partial agreement that omitted
Jerusalem. Israel Radio said that Arafat would not accept it.
Earlier in the day, Palestinian officials made clear that Arafat
did not believe that he had a formal mandate from the Arab and
Muslim world to recognize the Israeli annexation of East Jerusalem
and concede it forever.
</P>
<P>
   But judging by what several Israeli officials said earlier in
the day, Barak also had been unwilling to consider a partial deal.
And by political calculations, he probably could not have done so
successfully, since, despite his pre-meeting assertions that his
disintegrating government would not hobble him, it inevitably did.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost his majority government when rightist parties
defected before the meeting, Barak faces an uncertain future as a
leader. And he would have under any scenario. But analysts believe
that he would have had the most trouble surviving if he returned
with a partial deal that entailed further Israeli concessions but
no resolution of the conflict, no end of claims, no way to declare
that peace had broken out. In this case, something probably would
have been worse than all or nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, politically, the middle ground was the most
dangerous route for Barak to take,'' a senior Israeli official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to bring home an agreement will spell an end, at
least temporarily, to Barak's grand dream of forging a
comprehensive peace between Israeli and its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But it could help him resuscitate his broad coalition, fleshing
out his minority government back into a majority. It could enable
Barak, if he chooses, to forge a coalition with the rightist Likud
government to face the tensions ahead. Or it could provoke him to
dissolve the government and call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Barak used his political weakness as a strategy before
and during the summit meeting. Israeli television reported that he
sent a message to Arafat that he would be willing to return to Camp
David for a second meeting but that he would probably have to do so
as an opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, though, reportedly had a retort. He sent a message back
saying that if he made the requested concessions on Jerusalem and
the refugees, he would be forced into retirement, too. And then the
Israelis would be left to face Sheik Ahmed Yassin, the spiritual
leader of the radical Hamas movement.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the land of the possible, the deep-seated
Israeli-Palestinian conflict almost seemed, improbably, on the
point of being solved, at least on paper. But even in the green
hills of Maryland, the arid land that is the center of their acrid
dispute was palpably close and the passions surrounding it still
too far from being tempered by reason and compromise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
