<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT LEAVES TALKS AS A FRUSTRATED PEACEMAKER 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Twice in the past seven months President Clinton
has invested enormous amounts of time and prestige in an attempt to
reach historic accords between Israel and its neighbors, first the
Syrians, then the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases his aides bet that changing times and the force of
Clinton's own personality as a mediator with a finely honed sense
for the middle ground might be enough to win agreement, and with it
a legacy for a president with six months and a day remaining in his
term.
</P>
<P>
   Twice so far, they have been wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is hardly about to be blamed for the failure of the
talks that collapsed Wednesday night between Israel's prime
minister, Ehud Barak, and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat. He
entered the talks with little to lose, save for his dwindling hoard
of time. Yet his reported outbursts of anger during the final hours
of talks Wednesday suggested how emotionally involved he has become
in an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the talks, one of Clinton's closest aides suggested
that, while no deal was certain, ``the stars are aligned.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak, White House officials had concluded, needed an agreement
if he had any hope of remaining in office after the collapse of his
ruling coalition. Arafat, they continued, knows that his own days
as the leader of the Palestinians are dwindling down.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. prosperity, they concluded, meant that Clinton might
well succeed in persuading Congress to allocate tens of millions of
dollars to support a Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may not have an opportunity like this for a long, long
time,'' the aide said more than a week ago, a theme Barak alluded
to Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the end, Clinton and his staff may have overestimated the
amount of political capital either side could put at risk. And now,
while the peace effort is by no means over, it will be harder and
harder to put the pieces back together again under Clinton's own
watch.
</P>
<P>
   That is a conclusion Clinton appeared to be grappling with
Wednesday night, as he reassessed his options over the next few
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   He could well attempt to bring the sides together again before
the Sept. 13 deadline Arafat has set for declaring an independent
Palestinian state. But as one of Clinton's close aides said
Wednesday, ``rebuilding momentum is very hard, which is why we want
everything we can to be done now.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is also possible that he may have limited options. There
was talk about bringing top Syrian officials back to the United
States after their talks in Shepherdstown, W. Va., broke down. It
never happened, and Clinton's later meeting with Hafez Assad,
Syria's leader until his death two months ago, was considered a
failure, evidence that even Syria's declining economy could not
overcome years of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It was soon after that confrontation with Assad that Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright and Clinton's national security
adviser, Sandy Berger, concluded that their best bet was to focus
on the ``Palestinian track'' of Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting the Palestinians to the table took a considerable
effort by Clinton. Placing the talks at Camp David was an effort to
re-create the magic of 1978 and 1979, when Israel and Egypt signed
their famous accord.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, no number of ``bridging proposals'' by the
president, no dealmaking over U.S. aid or land swaps in Jerusalem
could make the difference. And so Clinton left Wednesday night for
Japan as a frustrated peacemaker, the outlines of the deal that
hadn't happened _ at least yet _ precisely formed in his mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
