<HEADLINE>
SHOULDER PAIN NAGS SALMON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calilf. _ For the third straight game Wednesday night,
right fielder Tim Salmon was not in the starting lineup because of
an inflamed left shoulder. He had a cortisone injection Monday and
Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia wanted to give him at least
one more day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wear-and-tear injury,'' Salmon said. ``I've played with
it a long time. A lot of guys have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said he first began feeling some pain in the shoulder
just before the All-Star break, and figured the three days off
would clear it up. But when he jarred the shoulder trying to make a
sliding catch Sunday in San Diego, he aggravated it enough to ask
Scioscia for a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scioscia's been on me for two weeks to take time off,'' Salmon
said. ``I said, `No, I'll suck it up.' You try to play through
these kinds of injuries. But finally I said I needed a day.''
</P>
<P>
   One day has turned into three, and Salmon might be limited to DH
duty for the first few games when he does come back.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon came into the season with a .291 career batting average
but is hitting just .259 this year. He has 18 homers and 49 RBI,
but those numbers rank only fifth best on the team in both
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been swinging the bat well the past couple of
weeks,'' Salmon said. ``We were facing Seattle when it all started,
so sometimes when you think you're not swinging good, maybe it's
just good pitching. But then the last couple of days before the
break I was swinging at pitches I don't normally swing at. When you
have a nagging injury, you can get into bad habits.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Trade bait: If the Angels make a trade before the July 31
deadline, it most likely would be for a run-producing DH. But the
problem for the Angels is the makeup of their roster.
</P>
<P>
   They keep 12 pitchers on the roster and as a result begin each
game with only four players on the bench. So they can't afford to
carry a DH who can't play defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the way our club lines up right now,'' Scioscia said.
``Our bench has to be versatile. With a four-man bench, they have
to be multidimensional.''
</P>
<P>
   The bench consists of catcher Matt Walbeck (he can also play
first base), Scott Spiezio, who can play first, second and third,
Kevin Stocker and Benji Gil, who share the shortstop duties and can
also play second, and Edgard Clemente and Orlando Palmeiro, who can
both play all three outfield spots.
</P>
<P>
   __ Un-American: There has been talk around the major leagues
about realignment, but one scenario that hasn't been discussed is a
move by the Angels to the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia wouldn't mind such a move, considering how his team
played in interleague games this season (12-6) and how he uses his
DH more as a semi-day off for the regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``A case could be made for us being a better National League
club than American League club,'' he said. ``Our starting eight
match up with anybody. And we don't have a big bat (in the DH spot)
like Edgar Martinez's to take out of the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Schoeneweis update: Pitcher Scott Schoeneweis, who is
recovering from a strained rib-cage muscle, made his second rehab
start Wednesday, pitching for Triple-A Edmonton at Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis made 79 pitches in seven innings, allowing one
unearned run and two hits with six strikeouts and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis will need at least one more rehab start before
returning to the starting rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
