<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES GET A CHARGE OUT OF CLEMENS
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Derek Jeter will swing at just about any pitch within
two time zones of home plate. It's his nature, always has been,
always will be. His aggressiveness is why, at age 26, he is already
approaching 1,000 career hits.
</P>
<P>
   But someone as intelligent and seasoned as Tim Raines said in
spring training that Jeter would be a better offensive player if he
were more selective, and that probably applies to the New York
Yankees collectively. They are a better team when they are patient;
always have been, always will be.
</P>
<P>
   They waited for Detroit's Hideo Nomo to throw strikes at Yankee
Stadium Wednesday night, drew three walks and created hitters'
counts, then they pounded the right-hander for five extra-base hits
in a 9-1 thrashing of the Tigers. Roger Clemens pitched eight
innings, struck out 11 and won his fourth consecutive start, the
first time he has accomplished that since joining the Yankees last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens ascertained quickly that Brian O'Nora, the home plate
umpire, was calling a wide strike zone. O'Nora called strikes on a
fastball and a slider low and away _ Luis Polonia glanced back at
O'Nora after each _ and Clemens began attacking the Tigers with his
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Several Detroit batters griped about the strike calls as Clemens
looked on passively; Brad Ausmus, Rich Becker and others turned and
yelled at O'Nora.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens (8-6) kept pumping strikes, allowing only six hits, on
his way to his 255th career victory, good for 35th place. Clemens
has a 1.84 earned run average in his four starts since being
activated from the disabled list July 2.
</P>
<P>
   Batting second in the Yankees' lineup, Jeter took all five
pitches thrown to him in the first inning Wednesday night, most of
them low, for a walk, his second first-inning walk since April 24.
Before drawing a walk against Florida last Friday, Jeter had gone
55 consecutive games without doing so.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill took two pitches out of the strike zone, and with
the count in his favor, he looked for a fastball, got it, and
hammered it into the right-field stands for his 12th homer.
</P>
<P>
   After Scott Brosius singled and Jose Vizcaino doubled with two
out in the Yankees second, Knoblauch took a four-pitch walk from
Nomo, loading the bases. Jeter patiently took the first two pitches
thrown to him to get ahead in the count, then fouled off a pitch
and took another ball.
</P>
<P>
   With the count 3-1, Jeter ripped a line drive between the
outfielders in right and center. All three runners scored ahead of
him before he slid into third with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams walked leading off the third and came around to
score. That was the inning in which Nomo was knocked out after
surrendering six runs. David Justice finished the Yankees scoring
in the fourth, crushing a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter walked again in the eighth and has 26 walks this season,
after drawing 91 last year. But then almost all the Yankees are
collecting fewer walks this season. Knoblauch, their lead-off
hitter, has 24, after collecting 83 last year. Even Williams, their
most productive hitter, has 40 walks, after drawing 100 last year.
His batting average is about the same as it was last year, but his
on-base percentage is down almost 40 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' biggest victory of the season might have come on
Sunday, when they rebounded twice from multirun deficits to beat
the Phillies, 9-8. That comeback was fueled by the patience of
their hitters, their willingness to draw walks.
</P>
</TEXT>
