<HEADLINE>
WHITE READY FOR REHAB STINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Center fielder Devon White could be back in the
starting lineup as early as Saturday if all goes well on his
two-game rehab assignment, which begins today at Class A San
Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   After the short rehab, White will be evaluated by the Dodgers
medical staff and he could be given clearance to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm better. I'm definitely better,'' White said. ``I'm going
down to see pitches. It's just a matter of getting ready to get
back to the big leagues and play. I'll be down there for two days.
I've got two days to get my stuff ready and see how it feels and
see where I'm at.''
</P>
<P>
   However, White isn't expected to be given the starting center
fielder's spot back immediately. Instead, club officials said it's
likely White will be eased back into the position and split time
with Todd Hollandsworth.
</P>
<P>
   White batted .289 with three homers and nine RBI in 22 games
before the injury. Hollandsworth was hitting .238 with seven homers
and 21 RBI in 71 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged,'' Malone said. ``We've missed him. He can
play, and he's going to be a big help when he gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Davey released: Dodgers manager Davey Johnson was released
from Centinela Hospital Medical Center about an hour before
Wednesday's game and went to his La Canada-Flintridge home.
Johnson, who was admitted Sunday morning and diagnosed with an
irregular heartbeat, is expected to return to the bench Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dodgers officials wouldn't rule out Johnson returning
for tonight's contest against the Colorado Rockies. Upon his
release, Johnson and his wife, Susan, issued a statement of thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upon release from the hospital, we wanted to assure everyone
that we are doing fine and looking forward to getting back into the
baseball routine,'' the Johnsons said in the statement. ``We also
wanted to take this opportunity to thank all of our family and
friends who expressed their thoughts and concerns through warming
gifts, prayer, visits and phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming support for us, in addition to the tremendous
care and attention displayed by the wonderful staff at Centinela
Hospital Medical Center, have been invaluable throughout this
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Roster shuffle: Before Wednesday's game, the Dodgers placed
outfielder F.P. Santangelo on the 15-day disabled list with a
left-hand bruise. The move is retroactive to July 17. Also,
right-hander Mike Judd was expectedly sent to Triple-A Albuquerque
after allowing seven runs in four-plus innings in his spot start
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Those moves cleared the way for right-hander Al Reyes and first
baseman Chris Donnels to be promoted from Albuquerque. Donnels, by
far, is the more interesting individual. He gives the Dodgers
another left-handed bat off the bench. Donnels played parts of six
seasons with three major-league clubs, including the Mets, and was
hitting .334 with 26 homers and 80 RBI with the Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes came to the Dodgers in the Alan Mills trade to Baltimore
last month. He was 2-1 with a save at Albuquerque after going 1-0
with a 6.92 ERA with the Orioles. But the Dodgers promoted Reyes
because they want innings after their bullpen was worked hard
Monday and Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   However, Santangelo's move to the disabled list means he won't
serve his five-game suspension beginning Saturday. He's eligible to
be activated Aug. 1, and then he'll serve the suspension.
</P>
<P>
   __ Appeal update: It appears Gary Sheffield's appeal on his
five-game suspension will have to wait until the club travels to
Milwaukee at the end of August.
</P>
</TEXT>
