<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE ROUNDS PAY OFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG WILCOX  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You see guys like Jim Haffner at muni courses everywhere,
slashing at the ball with swings designed in front of the TV and
refined on the range. Sometimes, with enough work and athletic
ability, a golf swing actually emerges. Sometimes, too, the result
is a train wreck of body parts out of sync.
</P>
<P>
   All that matters, though, is that the swing we build gets the
ball around the course.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes the result is stunning even to ourselves, which is
why Newbury Park resident Haffner is in such a jovial mood these
days. He's had a career year, as the sterling-silver plate in his
trophy case indicates.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner, who plays to a 17.4 index, won the Treasurer Flight at
the 66th Southern California Golf Association Amateur Net
Championships at Borrego Springs Golf Resort &AMP; Country Club. This
is a major for everyone of us who has an SCGA index card stuffed in
our wallet.
</P>
<P>
   His two-round score of 125 bested runner-up David Cogsewell of
Oak Park by four shots.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner says luck and his game peaking at just the right time
added up to the win. He advanced from the qualifying stage on what
is called a card-off. He finished in a tie for the last spot and
got it by virtue of shooting the lower score over the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   So the trip to the desert became a lark.
</P>
<P>
   Haffner is 53 now and back surgery has forced him to alter his
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just going down there to have fun with my wife and spend
a couple of days in Borrego Springs,'' he recalled. ``I didn't even
play a practice round. The way I was looking at it was I got two
free rounds of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   That turned out to be good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually it was a big surprise,'' he said of the win. ``The
first day everything was clicking.''
</P>
<P>
   And what is neat about this tournament is that age is not a
factor. Golfers compete against others of their own ability and the
scores are adjusted for handicap. But the event is played strictly
by the book. There are no mulligans or conceded putts.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is this a hard event to win, it's hard to get into. The
SCGA entry forms go out early in the year and the available spots
are snapped up in a matter of a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And Haffner, a self-taught golfer, knows that golf is a quirky
game.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend after the SCGA event he headed to Arizona for an
annual weekend tournament with some friends. What he had the week
before was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went in there just brimming with confidence and immediately
fell flat on my face. I couldn't do anything. I couldn't shoot my
handicap. I just happened to be on that one weekend, that was it,''
he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   __ Longevity: Hall of Famer Gary Player always set his sights
high. No challenge was too great. Now the South African great has
another goal. He wants to become the first golfer to record a win
over six decades in a full-field event.
</P>
<P>
   He's a fitness fanatic, so he still has the physical skills.
</P>
<P>
   And while he's won 160 tournaments worldwide, this might be his
toughest task considering the skill level of today's players. He'll
take his shot this fall in the Transamerica at Silverado Country
Club in the Napa Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Trevino is the only other player to record a win over five
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Player won the 2000 Senior Skins Game, a sanctioned event. But
he doesn't count it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm talking about winning against a full field of the best
senior players in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Silly prediction: Despite what the oddsmakers say, there is
really no such thing as a favorite in a golf tournament. That's why
it's so silly installing Tiger Woods as the betting favorite in the
British Open.
</P>
<P>
   How goofy is this? Well, it was not that long ago that the smart
money was betting that Woods would never win a U.S. Open because
the set-up for that tournament did not fit his game.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Course at St. Andrews seems perfect for Woods, though.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't expect him to win the U.S. Open by 15 shots. I do
expect him to embrace the Claret Jug come Sunday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
