<SLUG> BC-VOUCHER-INITIATIVE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHERS UNION, ANTI-TAX GROUP JOIN TO FIGHT SCHOOL
VOUCHER  INITIATIVE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS and LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ In a strange political pairing, the state's largest
teachers union and a conservative anti-tax group have joined forces
against a school voucher initiative _ even though the two groups
are fighting each other on another school initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the voucher initiative accuse the California Teachers
Association of buying opposition to the voucher measure by agreeing
to pay the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association to be included in
the group's campaign mailings.
</P>
<P>
   Both CTA and the taxpayer's association deny the charge.
Nevertheless, the ``no on vouchers'' campaign is negotiating a
price for it to be included in the taxpayer group's campaign
mailers, The Chronicle has learned.
</P>
<P>
   Those mailers will also urge voters to oppose an initiative
similar to one the CTA spent $13 million trying to pass in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association was shopping around
its endorsement; we didn't feel like playing that game,'' said
Chris Bertelli, a spokesman for the campaign to approve Proposition
38, which would give parents a $4,000 check from taxpayers to pay
for their child's private school education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very odd. Here's an organization that's always been an
ardent opponent of a CTA-backed measure now taking money from the
CTA,'' Bertelli said.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a reversal of the taxpayer group's voucher stance. It
backed a similar measure on the November 1993 ballot that the CTA
spent heavily to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Like that 1993 measure, Proposition 38, the new voucher
initiative is the most heated issue on the November ballot. The
fight over its passage will easily be the most expensive initiative
campaign this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher's union has said it has budgeted at least $10
million to defeat Proposition 38, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the taxpayers association, its main goal this fall is
defeat of Proposition 39, a measure that would lower the approval
threshold for local school bonds from 67 percent to 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 39 is backed by Gov. Gray Davis and promoted by his
political team.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the taxpayers association spearheaded opposition to
Proposition 26, which would have lowered the bond approval
threshold to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest spending supporter was the CTA, at some $13 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the taxpayers association has been soliciting funds
to fight Proposition 39, which is supported by the CTA.
</P>
<P>
   Six days before the taxpayer group announced its position on the
voucher initiative, the group's direct mail firm, Lord-Butcher
Company, sent a memo to supporters of the voucher initiative
outlining the group's proposed direct mail campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, Bill Lord-Butcher, said he had approached both
sides of the campaign ``to learn what level of interest exists in
participating in the mailing program.''
</P>
<P>
   The memo says that the taxpayer group has yet to make an
endorsement. It then details the program and the cost: $850,000 for
four pieces of mail going to 1.25 million California voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never responded to it and then learned (the taxpayers
association) went the other way,'' Bertelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Lord-Butcher, a consultant hired to defeat Proposition 39, said
in an interview he told the pro-voucher campaign he had no control
over the taxpayer group's endorsement, and the memo was just a
breakdown of the mechanics of the direct mail program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be difficult for me to keep a straight face and say
this showed the endorsement was for sale,'' Lord-Butcher said.
``Shame on them.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the CTA did not agree to pay $850,000 to participate in
the direct mail program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased with the endorsement, but the CTA has made no
commitment to give money to Howard Jarvis to pay anything to
them,'' said Becky Zoglman, a spokeswoman for the union. ``Any
negotiations are made with the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Lenzner, a spokesman for the ``no on vouchers'' campaign,
said there were no conversations between the taxpayer group and the
campaign before the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Kris Vosburgh of the taxpayers association said ``no money is
going to either the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers Association or to any
of its committees.
</P>
<P>
   Vosburgh said ``money from the CTA'' would go to Lord-Butcher's
direct mail effort.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to announcing its opposition to the voucher initiative,
the taxpayer group reversed itself on Proposition 35, which would
allow greater contracting-out of state engineering projects.
</P>
<P>
   The taxpayer group initially supported the proposition, then
became an opponent. It opposed an initiative on the June 1998
ballot making it harder to contract out to private firms.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the campaign to defeat Proposition 35, which
is being advocated by the Professional Engineers in California
Government, said it is eager to work with the taxpayer group on
mailings but that eagerness had nothing to do with securing their
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They changed their position before we started talking with
them, said Steve Hopcraft, who runs the ``no'' on Proposition 35
campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
