 - LADN 
LOS ANGELES AIRPORT PACKED WITH FRUSTRATED PASSENGERS &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW and ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spurred by the booming economy and high gas
prices, air traffic at Los Angeles International Airport has soared
to record levels, jamming planes, terminals and freeways, officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines report flights are leaving at near-capacity, with air
traffic at LAX expected to rise by 5 percent this summer to nearly
6 million passengers a day, officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Airport officials report ``record usage at LAX,'' but could not
provide numbers for June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard from the airlines, in a general sense, that their
capacity is over 90 percent,'' said Tom Winfrey, a spokesman for
Los Angeles World Airports and LAX.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic passengers, he said, should report to the airport two
hours early; international travelers three hours before their
flight.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in passengers has been felt throughout the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some flights every day go out full,'' said Janis Magnuson, Los
Angeles station manager for TWA. ``Out of Los Angeles, with TWA,
we're doing good _ well over 90 percent, if not better.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of people flying out of LAX was up 7 percent this
spring compared to last year, officials said. International flights
were up 13 percent. While Winfrey said some airlines are adding
flights to take up the slack, officials with several airlines said
the additions were planned prior to the summer rush.
</P>
<P>
   A flush economy and record gas prices have encouraged more
travelers to get out of their cars and head for the airport, flight
industry officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The result: more passenger delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it seems like it's exceptionally crowded,'' said Mary
Stanton, 70, of Los Angeles as she stood in a United Airlines
ticket line to send her granddaughter off to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's vacation time, but there have been other years
that just didn't seem as crowded.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase in passengers has only worsened record delays
caused in recent weeks by air traffic control mix-ups, mechanical
difficulties, flight attendant shortages and summer storms, the
major holdup in flights.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole airline experience has really been very crowded,''
said David Stempler, president of the Air Travelers Association.
``There are lines at the ticket counter, at the newspaper stand,
the security belt, the sandwich bar _ then you get on the airplane
and there's still a line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a lot of tension.''
</P>
<P>
   From the airlines' perspective, however, business is good and
getting better.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, which ferries 22 percent of LAX passengers,
reported a 6.5 percent increase in passengers at LAX last month
from a year ago. Its airplanes ran at 80 percent capacity, a nearly
6 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out in L.A., our biggest carrier, we are running very strong
loads in all segments and that is expected to increase later this
summer,'' said Alan Wayne, regional director of public affairs for
United. International traffic is up 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Southwest Airlines marketing representative reported Fourth of
July capacity surpassed 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know that we're getting some record numbers systemwide,''
said Southwest spokeswoman Christine Turneabe-Connelly, who
declined to release any statistics. ``Of course, LAX is one of our
top 10 busiest cities, so we have seen record customer numbers
there as well.''
</P>
<P>
   An America West official said full airplane loads prompt
managers to shout, ``Keep hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers Wednesday seemed resigned to the crowds, if not
the delays.
</P>
<P>
   One frustrated traveler, Deirdre Kiely, 18, of San Jose, had
just dragged herself off an almost 13-hour flight from Dublin,
Ireland, when she learned her United Airlines flight to San
Francisco was canceled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exact same company did this to me four weeks ago,'' she
said angrily from her perch atop her duffel bag. ``I'll never fly
with them again.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the crowded skies, airports nationwide are
experiencing record delays this summer for the second year in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Brownlee, 62, of Redondo Beach, Calif., said it seems few
flights have empty seats anymore. ``I'm finding it difficult to get
mileage upgrades because the seats are already taken.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Mary Kay, was also indignant about being forced by LAX
security officials to constantly circle the airport in lieu of
waiting at the curb for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to move around if you get harassed.'' she said.
``It's very frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
