<HEADLINE>
OATES SAYS TRADE WON'T HURT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When the Rangers traded pitcher Esteban Loaiza
yesterday, they did so for two minor-league players. In doing so,
the Rangers improved their farm system, but manager Johnny Oates
said the trade shouldn't hurt the major-league team.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Oates said. ``In my mind, if we had given
the ball to \RRyan\S Glynn, \RMatt\S Perisho or \RDoug\S Davis,
they would have had five wins by now. I don't think this says we're
giving up. We're going to be just as good and in the long-term, we
could be better.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade also could have the benefit of giving Glynn and
Perisho the confidence that Loaiza is not longerout in the bullpen,
ready to reclaim his spot in the rotation should they stumble.
That's what happened last year. Glynn joined the rotation May 25
and made eight starts, going 2-3 with a 6.95 earned-run average
before losing his job to Loaiza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could help,'' Oates said. ``Less competition, one less
veteran to pick from. They still have to pitch. Doug Davis is still
waiting for his turn.''  &QL; 
OLIVER READY TO GO Darren Oliver, 2-4 with a 6.66 ERA, returns to
the rotation tonight, making his first start since June 16, when he
pitched against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. He has been on the
disabled list for the past month with weakness in his left
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver started the season 1-2 with a 5.15 ERA in his first eight
starts and then went 1-2 with a 9.92 ERA in his last five starts,
before going on the disabled list. He signed a three-year, $19
million contract in the off-season, but has yet to be the
consistent starter the Rangers that they were getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been right,'' Oliver said. ``As long as I'm healthy
and taking it pitch-by-pitch and doing everything I can, that's all
that matters. I just need to go out there and throw strikes.
Quality strikes, not just throw the ball down the middle of the
plate.''
SECOND-ROUND PICK SIGNS The Rangers announced that have signed
right-handed pitcher Randy Truselo, one of their two second-round
picks from the June first-year player draft. He received a $600,000
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have signed eight of their top nine picks. The one
holdout is University of North Carolina outfielder Tyrell Godwin,
who was taken as the 35th overall pick of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still working on that one,'' Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin said. ``He's the one guy that still hasn't come around
yet.''  &LR; subheds:Losing late  &LR; agatea:More on the Rangers' 5-3 loss
to the San Francisco Giants on Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time this season the Rangers have lost a game
when leading after the eighth inning. They lost four times in those
situations all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was the seventh time this season the Rangers have lost on the
road in the bottom of the ninth inning. Four of those have come on
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Going into last night, the Rangers have lost 25 times this
season, despite having a lead at some point in the game.
BRIEFLY The Rangers have signed former Tampa Bay Devil Rays
outfielder Rich Butler to a Triple-A contract. He was released by
the Devil Rays this year and has a career .223 average in 86
major-league games in 1997-99. The Rangers finished interleague
play with a 7-11 record, the first time in four seasons they've had
a losing record against the National League. Overall, the American
League was 136-115 against the National League. The Rangers' 5.40
ERA in 18 games against the National League was the third highest
by an American League team in interleague play.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
