<HEADLINE>
WITH WEBB AND SORENSTAM, IT'S TEE FOR TWO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
LIBERTYVILLE, Ill. _ Together, they peer down at peers from the
summit of most significant statistical categories kept by LPGA Tour
officials. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Season-money list? Annika Sorenstam is first, Karrie Webb
second. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Player of the Year race? Webb leads Sorenstam by a thin margin. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dynamic Duo also has placed a 1-2 hammerlock on tour
pursuers in terms of scoring average (Webb leads), greens in
regulation (Advantage, Sorenstam) top-10 finishes (Webb) and
victories (Sorenstam). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In LPGA circles, Webb and Sorenstam impact leader boards and
opponents' thoughts the way Tiger Woods dominates the PGA Tour. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got one Tiger. We've got two,'' Meg Mallon said,
summarizing the difference between the respective tours as they
prepare for today's opening rounds of major championships on
opposite sides of the globe. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the men turn into Tiger chasers at the British Open, the
quest for the LPGA contingent is to reel in Webb and Sorenstam _ or
Sorenstam and Webb, if you prefer _ at the Merit Club in the U.S.
Women's Open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Similar in their soft-spoken approaches off the course,
Sorenstam and Webb play entirely different games. Not surprisingly,
each plans a different approach for the Merit Club, which is the
longest course (6,540 yards, par 72) ever to host the Women's
Open. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam, 29, describes herself as a ``statistical nerd,'' who
tracks her weekly progress on a laptop computer. Asked about being
characterized by peers as a methodical player, Sorenstam replied:
``I take it as a compliment. I have feel in my game, but I don't
play with my heart. I use more strategy than most players. I have a
game plan, I stick with it and it works.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week, that includes a heavy dose of 7-woods and 3-woods off
tee boxes at the Merit Club, despite the course's wide fairways and
lack of trees. The idea, said Sorenstam, is to keep the ball in
play, remain patient, pad her tour-best greens-in-regulation
percentage (75.5) and accept whatever birdies fall her way. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Webb, by comparison, plans to break out the driver as often as
possible and aggressively create scoring chances. By her own
admission, Webb lacks Sorenstam's patience, [ on the course ]but
tries to compensate with power and creativity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``To win the Open, my biggest hurdle I have to overcome is my
patience,'' said Webb, 25. ``I go along and keep everything in, and
then I have one bad break or one bad swing and I just lose it.
That's what I have to work on.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The flip side is that Webb, like Woods, is willing to attempt
high-risk shots in quest of birdies. That paid off in a 10-stroke
victory at the Nabisco Championship, the season's first major
championship and one of Webb's four titles this season. Sorenstam
has five victories, along with a slight lead in the money race
($985,635 vs. $963,742), proving that the Dynamic Duo's differing
methods are equally effective[ capable of yielding fruit]. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Webb, the 1999 Player of the Year, her 20 titles in five
years have [ has ]been the continuation of a trend that began in
1996, when she [ Webb ]won four events, received Rookie of the Year
honors and became the first LPGA player to top $1 million in a
season. Sorenstam, the 1995 and 1996 Open champ, said Webb's
emergence _ particularly her six victories last season _ motivated
Sorenstam [ her ] to sharpen her focus this season. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I think golf is 90 percent mental,'' Sorenstam said. ``I
wanted to get going with Karrie. I knew what I was capable of and I
think that's what motivated me the most. When I stopped being No. 1
\Rin the [ golf ] rankings\S, I realized how much I enjoyed it and
how much it meant to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both players downplay any rivalry[ between them], Webb
admitted she is quick to check Sorenstam's scores at the end of
each round. But she does not dwell on them, even though Sorenstam
has cut Webb's lead in the Player of the Year race by more than 100
points in the past three months. Heading into the Open, Webb has
197 points. Sorenstam has 175.93. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't do anything about the way Annika is playing,'' Webb
said. ``And she's playing great. I can only do my best. And if my
best isn't No. 1 at the end of the year, I'm still going to be
happy with the way things have gone.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Peers, on the other hand, are becoming resigned to aiming for
the third spot on a weekly basis. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I always felt I was good enough to be one of the best
players,'' said Laura Davies, a 19-event winner in her 13-year
career. ``But now, because of what they're doing, I'm not good
enough and I need to get better. So I'm hitting a few more shots
every day.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Webb and Sorenstam, on the other hand, are hitting a few less
shots every tournament. That's why they figure as co-favorites at
the U.S. Women's Open. &QL; 
Webb vs. Sorenstam &QL; 
{Webb Category Sorenstam} &QL; 
25 Age 29 &QL; 
1st Player of Year rank 2nd &QL; 
2nd Money list rank 1st &QL; 
