<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIALS-TRACK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THESE TRIALS ARE RIGHT ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ After two days off, during which Marion Jones
had time to check with her investment guy and Michael Johnson could
decide which color million-dollar Nikes he'll wear next, it will be
back today to the business of picking Olympians.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Olympic Track and Field Trials resume with the opening
events of the decathlon and with finals scheduled in the men's
javelin throw and 3,000-meter steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   Another sold-out crowd of 23,000 is expected at dusty Hornet
Stadium on the campus of Cal State-Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The nightly chorus of applause for the new Olympians has been
raising both eyebrows and questions.
</P>
<P>
   No less than Lamine Diack, the new president of the
International Amateur Athletic Federation, the world governing body
for track and field, praised these trials and proclaimed them
indicative of the ``tremendous strength of athletics in America.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there isn't a lot else going on in Sacramento
these two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first four of the eight days of competition,
grizzled track watchers are describing the meet as decidedly ...
well, ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   No world records. Minimal upsets. The closest thing to an
intriguing storyline has been Johnson's tell-it-like-it-is
commentary in ``USA Today,'' during which he supposedly dissed,
among others, fellow sprinters Maurice Greene and Inger Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Both made the Olympic team in the men's and women's 100 meters,
respectively. And then they took off on His Goldenness for (pick
one) having an opinion, calling his coach a coach and not a
``guru,'' and showing up in a new curly hair style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's cute,'' said Antonio Pettigrew, who finished
third to Johnson in the 400 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Johnson politely responded.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Greene, as expected, won the 100. Jones quelled
Miller's yapping and won the women's 100, and then continued her
quest for five Sydney gold medals by making the team in the long
jump.
</P>
<P>
   The top three women's 1,500-meter runners all made the team _
Regina Jacobs, Suzy Favor-Hamilton and Marla Runyan. And the
country's No. 1-ranked shot putter, C.J. Hunter, survived a flurry
of 70-foot throws to make the team.
</P>
<P>
   The lone shocker of the first four days of competition came in
the men's pole vault, where American record-holder Jeff Hartwig
complained about his contact lenses being fogged and failed to
clear a height in the qualifying round.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, you would never know it from the four days of cheers. There
are high school football stadiums in Texas bigger than Hornet
Stadium. And the dirt concourses beneath the bleachers have been
wreaking havoc on camera lenses, white Nikes and reporters' laptop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   But as Diack said, ``I think what's happening here will help
tremendously. On my travel here, I found that everyone in the world
now is watching these trials. I saw it was on television in
Nigeria, in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be successful in the coming years if we continue to
have this kind of progress in our sport.''
</P>
<P>
   The likely withdrawal of Dan O'Brien from the decathlon due to
injury won't help the excitement level of the next three days. But
the final day, Sunday, is expected to be dramatic, featuring the
likely showdown in the 200 between Johnson and Greene. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
