<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7417 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-UCLABS-SECURITY-SFCHR     07-20 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCLABS-SECURITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ALAMOS, LIVERMORE LABS CLAIM ENERGY DEPT. TO BLAME
FOR  SECURITY TROUBLES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ and BERNADETTE TANSEY 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the wake of accusations of lax security at
the Los Alamos and Lawrence Livermore nuclear weapons laboratories,
officials from the University of California and the labs claimed
Wednesday they are being scapegoated for Energy Department
failures.
</P>
<P>
   Los Alamos Director John Browne said the department has relaxed
its procedures for safeguarding weapons secrets and provided
inadequate funding for security measures that were deemed necessary
at the two labs managed by the university.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said the Energy Department never responded to a 1999 memo
from lab directors at the Los Alamos, Lawrence Livermore and Sandia
national laboratories calling for bar-coded tracking devices on
classified computer storage media.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rules aren't adequate, is that the responsibility of
the DOE or the University of California? I maintain it is the
responsibility of DOE,'' Browne said at a meeting of the UC Regents
in San Francisco. ``If we don't have the resources or we don't have
the appropriate rules, the university is put in an awkward position
in oversight.''
</P>
<P>
   Regent Ward Connerly said the barrage of criticism against the
university from Congress and the Department of Energy has been
fueled by election-year politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public needs to understand we are just as concerned about
national security as anyone. The university is not asleep at the
wheel,'' said Connerly.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department Deputy Secretary T.J. Glauthier responded by
phone, saying that Energy Department security policies were strong
enough but lab scientists did not follow agency rules requiring
that visitors log in when visiting vaults containing classified
material.
</P>
<P>
   ``If procedures we did have in place had been followed, those
hard drives would not have disappeared,'' said Glauthier,
Richardson's top assistant.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aftermath of the security scandal at Los Alamos,
Glauthier said the agency will now require bar-code tracking of
classified files, and it will increase funding for security
measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in a way, John (Browne) is right that we have a
shared responsibility here,'' Glauthier said. ``We shouldn't get
into a finger-pointing exercise of who's at fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of both the Energy Department and the university
erupted when two hard drives packed with nuclear weapons secrets
went missing at Los Alamos earlier this year. The missing hard
drives were discovered months later behind a copy machine, and the
FBI is now trying to find out where they were and whether they
might have been copied or shared with unauthorized people.
</P>
<P>
   The hard drives turned up missing while the agency and the lab
were under scrutiny for the controversy surrounding scientist Wen
Ho Lee, who was indicted for allegedly transferring secret files
out of secured computers.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson announced last month he may end
UC's decades-long record as the sole manager of the two nuclear
labs and assign security functions to another contractor.
</P>
<P>
   The university is cooperating with the Energy Department as it
studies hiring a security contractor, but Browne has reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine a separate group of people coming in and
saying, `We are responsible for security,' because the individual
employees have the actual information in their hands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante, a regent by virtue of his office,
blasted Browne at the meeting for the lab's security problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are responsible, this university is responsible. If we are
going to take the responsibility of running these two facilities,
we cannot continue to have these kind of breaches,'' Bustamante
said. ``We owe it to the security of this nation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Browne insisted that he and other lab officials did make
attempts to tighten security.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, Browne and the directors of Lawrence Livermore
and Sandia national labs faxed a memo to the Energy Department's
deputy director, Ernie Moniz, requesting a better system for
managing classified information.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, then Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary loosened
controls on classified information. The directors wanted to return
to a bar-coded tracking system such as the one used before the end
of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   They never heard back from the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't been able to find the information we faxed to
them,'' Browne said he was told last week.
</P>
<P>
   Glauthier said the memo was lost because it did not come through
regular channels of correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   After the recent debacle with the missing hard drives, Browne
and Lawrence Livermore lab director Bruce Tarter started their own
tracking systems, without additional funding from the Energy
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Browne said his lab has bar coded 60,000 pieces of ``high
density media,'' including computer discs and hard drives. But it
will take about $60 million, he said, to tag all of the lab's 6
million pieces, and the lab does not have the funds in its $1
billion operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   The tracking system may not have protected the missing hard
drives, but it could have provided a record of who had them before
they disappeared, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Losing the management contract at the labs could prove both
embarrassing and costly to UC.
</P>
<P>
   UC receives $11 million a year to defray the costs of its
overhead in managing the two nuclear labs, as well as Lawrence
Berkeley National Laboratory, for the Department of Energy. UC can
receive as much as $14 million in extra fees depending on its
performance ratings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
