<SLUG> BC-COMPUTING-Q&AMP;A-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: EASY TIPS TO REGISTER DOT-COM  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: We'd like to register the name of our new business as a Web
address. Can you steer us to a company or two that can handle the
registration process? And how much does it cost?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Two of the leading companies in the field are Network Solutions
(www.nsi.com) and Register.com (www.register.com). Either one will
let you quickly search to see if the address you want is available,
and _ if it is _ let you register it for as little as $35 per year.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be disappointed, however, if your choice of a dot-com name
already has been taken by someone else. Most common words in the
English language _ and lots of uncommon ones as well _ have long
since been registered as Web addresses. You may have to get
creative to come up with a variation of your name that will be
available as a dot-com. Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Internet Offers
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm thinking about buying a new PC and have been intrigued by
the $400 rebate I can get if I sign up for three years of Internet
service (from Microsoft Network). It sounds almost too good to be
true. And you know what they say about that: If it sounds too good
to be true, it probably is. So what's the catch?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: There is no catch. Microsoft is just trying to attract new users
to its Internet service, which has not been as popular as the
company had hoped it would be. And the rebate strategy (plus some
good TV advertising) seems to be working. In the quarter that ended
in June, Microsoft signed up some 800,000 new MSN customers and now
has a total of 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   MSN is as good as any other ISP, so committing to a three-year
deal isn't the worst thing in the world. On the other hand, if
you're willing to put up with an on-screen ad banner, you can get
Internet access for free from companies like NetZero,
FreeInternet.com and Juno. And over a three-year period, that would
save you nearly twice as much as the $400 rebate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Add Attachments
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: How do I e-mail a document? It has columns, and I am unable to
copy and paste it into an e-mail message. I use America Online.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Any document that includes special formatting such as columns
should be sent as an attachment. That way, it accompanies the
e-mail without actually being part of it, and the formatting is
preserved. Attachments are a great way to send all kinds of files,
including photos.
</P>
<P>
   The only caveat is that the recipient must have software capable
of opening and viewing the attachments you send. But that's not
much of a problem because Microsoft Word and Excel have become the
lingua franca of word processors and spreadsheets, and almost
everyone has a program that can view graphics.
</P>
<P>
   In AOL version 5, you can easily attach files to e-mail. Just
open a new e-mail window, click Attachments in the lower left
corner and follow the instructions. You can even have more than one
attachment for the same message (my brother sends me several
pictures of his new daughter every time he writes).
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: When sending attachments, it's a good idea to
let the recipient know to expect its arrival. Many computer users,
wary of attachments that may be carrying computer viruses, will
automatically discard attachments from senders they don't
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Scan, Edit Forms
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: As an amateur genealogist, I send a lot of forms to government
agencies. I know I can scan and print the forms, but is it also
possible to enter information on them once they're in the computer?
That would save me lots of time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: You need something like OmniForm, a $120 program (street price)
from ScanSoft that lets you scan and edit almost any kind of form.
I haven't tried it myself, but it comes from the company that also
sells OmniPage, the standard for optical character recognition
software (OCR), which turns scanned pages of text into editable
documents. So I bet it would do the job nicely for you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Bad habits are easy to fall into, and if you're not paying
attention to how you sit in front of your PC, you could wind up
with painful _ and perhaps permanent _ stress-related injuries.
</P>
<P>
   You can reduce the risk by following a few simple guidelines:
Adjust your chair and keyboard height so that your feet rest
comfortably on the ground and your forearms are parallel to the
floor when you type. Raise or lower your monitor so that the top of
the screen is level with your eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Always put the monitor directly in front of you, not off to the
side. And position the PC so that the light in your room _ or the
sunlight outside _ doesn't splash glare all over your screen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail David Einstein at  &LR; computers(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
