<SLUG> BC-MCI-LAWSUIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 WORLDCOM FACES LAWSUIT OVER BILLING  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The California attorney general's office and the
Public Utilities Commission are preparing to launch a
double-barreled lawsuit against WorldCom for improperly billing
thousands of customers in the Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom, the nation's second-largest long-distance company,
sparked more than 9,000 complaints to the PUC during the past three
years, mostly over billing issues, more than any other
long-distance firm. And state regulators have already warned the
company, which also uses the MCI brand, that it needs to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``MCI is by far and away the worst big telecommunications
company in the state,'' said Charles Carbone, a consumer advocate
with the Utility Consumers Action Network, a San Diego consumer
group. ``Any action is long overdue.''
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit could be filed as early as Thursday said a government
source close to the investigation. But the action has already been
delayed in the past and could still be postponed. Plus, WorldCom
could always try to avert a suit with a last-ditch settlement
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom spokesman Les Kumagai said the company couldn't comment
on any ``speculative'' action. PUC President Loretta Lynch and a
spokesman for Attorney General Bill Lockyer also declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But regulators have already cracked down on WorldCom elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the New York State Public Service Commission fined
WorldCom $50,000 for slamming customers _ switching their telephone
service without permission. It also threatened to fine the company
$3 million unless it reduces complaint levels for local service.
</P>
<P>
   And last month, WorldCom agreed to pay the U.S. government $3.5
million to settle federal charges that the company slammed
customers. The Federal Communications Commission said it received
2,900 slamming complaints about WorldCom last year, more than any
other long-distance firm.
</P>
<P>
   California regulators helped the FCC with its investigation and
found that WorldCom also received far more slamming complaints in
California than any other long-distance provider. A source said the
main thrust of the state's case against WorldCom would also focus
on slamming complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Kenyon, who lives in San Francisco's Haight-Ashbury
neighborhood, said she was slammed twice by the company in the past
year.
</P>
<P>
   Kenyon, who uses MCI for her local phone company, said the firm
suddenly claimed her as a long-distance customer last spring. She
immediately called and wrote the phone company. But, Kenyon said,
``Nothing happened until I contacted the PUC,'' which ordered MCI
to switch her back and give her a $400 refund.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May, Kenyon said, it happened again. Kenyon, who works
for a Marin nonprofit that investigates housing complaints, said
the PUC ordered MCI to give her an $800 refund and switch her
service back again. This time, Kenyon also dropped MCI as her local
phone service. ``It doesn't pay for the stress of living through
that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom declined to discuss the slamming complaints. But when
it settled the FCC case, it blamed the problem on a ``few sales
employees, who have since been terminated.'' WorldCom also created
a 200-person ``consumer affairs and quality'' team to reduce
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, state regulators are concerned that even when
customers cancel WorldCom's service, the company sometimes
continues to bill those customers. A PUC judge, for instance, is
considering whether to sanction WorldCom because of complaints that
the phone company refused to stop billing about 50 customers for
local phone service after they signed up with rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically said their billing system was so screwed up
they couldn't fix it,'' said Carbone, the consumer advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Another customer, Mrs. Holden in Oakland, who asked that her
first name not be used, said MCI started misbilling her after she
switched calling plans.
</P>
<P>
   First, the company kept charging her the minimum fees for the
old calling plan (somewhere between $4 to $6 per month, she
recalled). Then, the company neglected to send her bills itemizing
the calls under the new plan. Instead, she just received a past-due
notice demanding payment.
</P>
<P>
   Holden said the company mostly ignored her complaints until she
sent a letter to the PUC and watchdog groups. Then, she suddenly
received copies of the bills via overnight mail. ``It's one of
those little annoyances,'' said Holden.
</P>
<P>
   Although WorldCom declined to comment about the PUC complaints
for this article, company executives have said in previous
interviews that they receive more complaints than rivals because
they spend more on telemarketing and aggressively signing up new
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Executives also say complaints have fallen in recent months.
Through the early part of this year, WorldCom generated 45 percent
fewer complaints filed with the PUC than AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at a pretty good trend,'' said Sally McMahon,
WorldCom's vice president of consumer affairs and quality in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   But WorldCom still received far more complaints per customer
than AT&AMP;T. AT&AMP;T has roughly three times as many customers as
WorldCom nationwide, and the ratio is even greater in California.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
