r f BC-MAC-APPLE-SFCHRON &LR;      07-20 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAC-APPLE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 APPLE'S NEW PRODUCT LINE IS SLEEK AND SIMPLE  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The speeds, feeds and colors keep changing, but not
the formula that's brought Apple Computer back from the brink since
the second coming of Steve Jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino, Calif., company Wednesday updated its entire
lineup of desktop computers, from entry-level iMacs to powerhouse
G4s. But the principles behind the products Jobs introduced during
a long keynote presentation at New York's semiannual Macworld Expo
trade show are the same ones he's focused on since retaking the
Apple helm three years ago this month: The only viable alternative
to the me-too PC game is to combine style and simplicity with
cutting-edge technologies, backed by slick marketing and
competitive pricing.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new products unveiled Wednesday:
</P>
<P>
   -- G4 Cube. The most eye catching of the new Macs _ and without
question the most original new computer, in terms of industrial
design, since the iMac first appeared in 1998 _ is the Power Mac G4
Cube.
</P>
<P>
   Due early next month at $1,799, it packs all the power (though,
of course, none of the expandability) of the company's big G4
desktop models into an 8-inch white cube suspended in a clear
plastic enclosure.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with Jobs' long-standing distaste for the fans that
generate the steady hum most computers make, the cube is cooled
entirely by convection, through a ventilation channel that runs
vertically through the machine. (Just don't put a book on top.) The
slot-loading DVD-ROM drive also opens at the top, popping out
ejected discs like a toaster.
</P>
<P>
   The system is so quiet that even when the hard drive is
spinning, it emits only about 20 decibels _ about as much as a
whisper at 15 feet, according to Phil Schiller, Apple's vice
president of worldwide marketing.
</P>
<P>
   For those who want to fill the void with more pleasant sounds,
the cube will come with external speakers, encased in spheres of
clear plastic, that were co-designed by Apple and Harman
Multimedia, the Northridge (Los Angeles County) maker of high-end
audio components.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Apple classifies the cube as part of its
``professional'' product line, and Schiller said the company
expects it to appeal to graphic artists and designers who don't
need the slots and bays that take up most of the space in the other
G4 models, as well as to executives, consultants, small-business
owners, academics and other professionals.
</P>
<P>
   But to judge by the crowd swarming around the cubes on display
in New York's Javits Convention Center, the stylish new machine
will appeal to a broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want one because it doesn't take up a lot of room on your
desk,'' said Chris Nelson, 10, of Niskayuna, N.Y., who said he now
uses a PowerBook portable. Marty Butherus, information-technology
manager at a St. Louis manufacturing company that runs entirely on
Macs, said he was interested for the same reason: ``Remember,
people have to have room for other things on their desks,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   And Jim Bontempo, a high-school student from Mentor, Ohio, said
he's ``ready to dip into the college fund'' to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   -- New iMacs. For the families and schools who are again
becoming Apple's bread and butter, as they were in the age of the
Apple II, Jobs rolled four new iMac configurations, featuring new
colors _ indigo, ruby, sage (gray-green) and snow _ and roomier
hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   And he cut $200 from the price of admission to the Mac world:
The new entry-level model, still called simply the iMac but now
indigo instead of blueberry, will sell for $799 when it ships in
September.
</P>
<P>
   For $999, previously the price of the low-end iMac, users can
now get a new version of the more advanced iMac DV, which offers a
wider choice of colors, a slightly faster processor, a bigger hard
drive and built-in support for wireless networking, with the
addition of Apple's $99 AirPort card.
</P>
<P>
   The DV version, like the new $1,299 iMac DV+ and the $1,499 iMac
DV Special Edition (now in ``snow'' as well as graphite colors),
also offers digital video editing capabilities: All three have
high-speed FireWire ports for connecting digital camcorders (as
well as a growing selection of other peripherals), and they'll come
with a new version of Apple's iMovie editing software.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the $799 iMac, the other three new configurations are
available immediately, according to Apple. To promote them, the
company is launching a TV ad campaign that will show them off to
such tunes as ``Blue Suede Shoes,'' ``Ruby, Ruby'' and the Kermit
classic ``It's Not Easy Being Green.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Dual-processor Power Mac G4s. Jobs began the ``professional''
portion of his presentation with a demonstration intended to show
that current top-of-the-line Macs outperform the fastest Windows
PCs on the market _ even though the fastest version of Apple's
processor, the PowerPC G4, runs at 500 megahertz, only half the
clock speed of today's fastest Intel Pentium III.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the 500-megahertz Mac completed a sequence of Adobe
Photoshop operations used to produce a poster for Disney's
``Inspector Gadget'' movie in 100 seconds, versus 124 seconds for
the gigahertz Pentium III PC.
</P>
<P>
   But then Jobs announced a step long rumored among Apple
watchers, but not generally expected this week: Starting Thursday,
the company will ship two processors as standard equipment in its
high Power Mac G4 models. He then ran the Photoshop sequence again,
this time on a system with two 500-megahertz G4s, where it took
only 61 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs then compounded the surprise by declaring that the extra
chip won't change prices: The 450-megahertz Power Mac G4, now with
dual processors, will sell for $2,499, the same as the previous
450-megahertz single-processor G4 system, and the 500-megahertz
equivalent will stay at $3,499.
</P>
<P>
   The low-end G4, with a single 400-megahertz chip, will retain
its $1,599 price.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Photoshop is one of only a handful of Mac programs that
can take advantage of multiprocessing under the current version of
the Mac operating system. But Photoshop is a key application in the
publishing and graphics marketplace, so the extra performance in
that program alone could reinforce Apple's already strong position
there _ even when Intel this fall delivers the Pentium 4, a chip
that is expected to give PCs a noticeable performance boost.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Chizen, president of Adobe, appeared on stage to hammer
that point home, calling the new G4 models ``the ultimate Photoshop
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Mac fans who don't use Photoshop won't get much benefit from the
dual-processor systems today. But that will change with the arrival
of Mac OS X, which is scheduled for release as a ``public beta'' in
September and in final form early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The new operating system will automatically distribute tasks
among both processors, so overall system performance will be
improved even when individual programs aren't optimized for
multiprocessing.
</P>
<P>
   All three conventional G4 models (but not the cube) will also
incorporate another potentially significant technological advance:
They'll have built-in support for ``gigabit Ethernet,'' a
networking scheme that moves data up to 10 times as fast as a
``100-megabit'' version used in other Macs and most new PC network
adapters _ and 100 times as fast as the classic form of Ethernet
still used in most offices.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, gigabit Ethernet adapters sold for about $1,500, and
now they're generally priced around $1,000, so building the
technology in without increasing prices makes the new Macs a real
bargain for those who need the fastest-possible network.
</P>
<P>
   The infrastructure needed to run such networks, however, won't
come free: Several Mac-oriented networking companies, including
Farallon Communications and Asante Technologies, Wednesday
announced four-port gigabit Ethernet switches priced between $1,300
and $1,500 _ roughly 10 times the price of similar devices for
100-megabit networks.
</P>
<P>
   -- Monitors, mice and more. Jobs also unveiled a new generation
of Apple monitors designed to reduce cable clutter: They get power
from the computer through the same cable that carries the video
signal, so users will no longer need to connect a separate AC
cable. The new, Apple-designed cable will also carry Universal
Serial Bus signals, and the monitors will have dual USB ports where
users can connect their mouse, keyboard and other add-ons.
</P>
<P>
   The new display line includes a 15-inch flat-panel LCD priced at
$999 and a 17-inch conventional CRT in a see-through plastic case,
priced at $499, as well as a new version of Apple's $3,999 22-inch
LCD.
</P>
<P>
   Because the new displays depend on the new cable design, which
is proprietary to Apple, they'll work only with new G4 models,
including the cube.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs also showed off iMovie 2, a new version of the digital
video-editing software Apple now bundles with all its desktop
models except the entry-level iMac. Among the enhancements in the
new release are a simplified user interface, better audio editing
and options to add such effects as sepia tones or to speed up or
slow down particular sequences.
</P>
<P>
   Apple also responded, at last, to near-universal displeasure
among its customers about the small keyboard and hockey-puck-shaped
mouse it has been shipping for the past two years. Among other
improvements, the new Apple Pro Keyboard offers full-size function
keys, more navigation keys and a new key that automatically ejects
a CD.
</P>
<P>
   The new Apple Pro Mouse is more innovative: It's elliptical in
shape; it has no buttons (you simply press down on the top of the
device); and like several recently released and well-received
Microsoft mice, it relies on optical technology instead of moving
parts, so it works on almost any surface and never needs to be
cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   The mouse and keyboard will be standard with all new desktop
Macs, and they'll be available, at $59 each, as an upgrade for
older USB-equipped Apple systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going from what many considered the worst mouse in the
industry to what we think is the best,'' Jobs crowed. And to the
delight of the thousands who sat through the long keynote, he
closed it by pointing out that glued to the underside of each seat
in the auditorium was a coupon entitling the user to get one of the
new mice free on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
