u s BC-BRITISHOPEN-BOS     07-20 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITISH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH OPEN IS HISTORY'S MAJOR
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ The search begins not at the first hole,
but at the 17th tee, for that is where the soul of St. Andrews
lives most fiercely. The Road Hole, it is called. You know that the
infamous road bunker awaits two shots away, but standing there,
your only thought is of the building that stands no more than 100
yards from the tee, blocking your view of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   What is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Old sheds,'' said the marshal. ``Used to be for the machines,
but now they are offices.''
</P>
<P>
   So players have to drive over the building?
</P>
<P>
   ``Aye. At least, they're supposed to.''
</P>
<P>
   You mean some don't?
</P>
<P>
   ``Aye, a player yesterday hit the building. A local qualifier.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens when the public plays? They have to hit over, too?
</P>
<P>
   The marshal nodded yes and smiled. ``Aye, why do you think there
are no windows on that side?''
</P>
<P>
   Aye, indeed. The 129th British Open has once again taken us to
St. Andrews, which has no equal simply because it has never tried
to be anything but what it is. Sitting in the shadows of history
that are so daunting they are measured in centuries, not decades,
St. Andrews remains the world's most beloved golf course,
withstanding not only the fury of Mother Nature but the wrath of
disgruntled players through the years.
</P>
<P>
   The first time he played here, Bobby Jones tore up his scorecard
and stormed off. Sam Snead in 1946 described it as looking like
``an abandoned golf course,'' and in recent years players such as
Scott Hoch and Lee Westwood have expressed their displeasure with
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've not enjoyed it so much,'' said Westwood, who once told
Mark James that St. Andrews wasn't in his Top 200.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Scotland?'' asked James.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Fife,'' snapped Westwood, who concedes that his only visits
to the birthplace of golf have come in October, when it has been
cold and wet. In the days leading up to the British Open, it has
been warm and dry, so perhaps there is hope, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can understand what the former champions around here say,
Seve (Ballesteros) and Tom Watson, people like that,'' said
Westwood. ``The first time (they came here) they didn't
particularly like it, but it has grown on them. I can see that
happening to me.''
</P>
<P>
   If it does, Westwood will join a fraternity that surely numbers
in the millions, for St. Andrews elicits more passion than any
other golf course. Just being here is a sacred experience, these
people will tell you, and you are on a golf course that is like no
other you have seen.
</P>
<P>
   Bless them, for they are right.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When St. Andrews was designed in about the year 1400, the
architect did not subscribe to the theory that golf should be fair.
The architect, of course, was Mother Nature, and caretakers of this
piece of property _ most especially Old Tom Morris from 1865-1903 _
have taken great care not to alter what she had intended.
</P>
<P>
   Morris widened some fairways, built the first and 18th greens as
they are today, and was responsible for adding sand to help grow
the grasses that are dominant here. The layout, however, was
dictated by nature and is quite simplistic _ nine holes out, nine
holes in.
</P>
<P>
   What you find along the way, however, is one of the most
challenging tests the game of golf can provide.
</P>
<P>
   To start with, there are 112 bunkers. Deep, nasty pot bunkers,
with steep walls and fluffy sand. They are hidden well, holes in
the ground, really, with steep faces that will make some players
consider hitting out sideways or even taking an unplayable lie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a mine field,'' said Bob Estes, who first saw St.
Andrews with his college golf team in 1985. ``The pot bunkers are
the mines. You just don't want to go in them. They're like
miniature water hazards, where, if you go in them you'll lose one
or maybe two shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the greens, all of them with undulations that
easily roll approaches far off line, forcing players to face lag
putts upwards of 100 feet. There are just four free-standing greens
_ the first, ninth, 17th, and 18th. The rest are double-greens. The
second green is also the 16th; the third also the 15th; the fourth
and 14th; the fifth and 13th; the sixth and 12th; the seventh and
11th; the eighth and 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Where to hit? You can't aim down the tree line because there are
no trees. Rough line? There's no rough to speak of. Aim at the
bunkers? Sure, though many times you can't see them. So what?
</P>
<P>
   The players will get a break this week. It's the British Open, a
huge attraction to spectators and a TV bonanza. Which means
construction objects. ``If you had to play this golf course without
having the TV towers and bleachers, you'd have no idea where to hit
it,'' said Tom Scherrer, who is making his British Open debut and
saw St. Andrews for the first time Monday. ``Half of us wouldn't
have any idea where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, they will know when to go, because hidden from view
on many of the holes are marshals who obediently pop into action
from out of the gorse and heather at certain points on the course.
They will wave red flags to tell you the group ahead is still in
range, green flags to advise all is clear.
</P>
<P>
   On his first visit to St. Andrews, in 1970, Tom Weiskopf looked
around and wondered what he had gotten himself into.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, this is so different. I had read about it, heard
about it, and I wanted to experience it, but I didn't know. I
didn't dislike it, but I said to myself, `I don't have the game for
this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   When he got to the 18th, he turned to his caddie and asked for a
sight line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father time,'' said his caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me?'' said Weiskopf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father time,'' said the caddie, pointing down the fairway,
more than 350 yards away to a building with a clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to aim for the clock, and so I did,'' said Weiskopf,
who soon fell in love with St. Andrews and links golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never played this kind of golf, but I was going to learn
how to play it. And it made me a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rock-hard fairways and wind. ``It's the only defense the course
has,'' said Peter Thomson, who won his five British Opens on
different venues, including St. Andrews in 1956. He adores the
place, embraces its tradition, and understands that it will test a
player's nerve as much as his skill.
</P>
<P>
   That St. Andrews has changed so little over the years makes
Thomson happy. When players go in a bunker here, they are
penalized, which, he reasons, is what a bunker should do. There are
times when you will get a bad bounce, other times when you get a
good bounce, and isn't that the glory of golf, he further reasons.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, John Daly won here during a week in which the wind
howled at various times. He shot 6-under 282, which was the highest
winning score in a British Open in nearly 10 years. In 1990, when
the wind was down, Nick Faldo posted 18-under 270, still a record
for the 24 British Opens that have been held here.
</P>
<P>
   That, said Estes, is the appeal to the place. ``They let nature
dictate the course conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   There's no manipulation, no changing the elements. It is what it
is.
</P>
<P>
   That means at least four par 4s _ including the 357-yard 18th _
will be driven by a host of players. That means if your ball comes
to rest against the lip of a pot bunker, you may have to just slam
it into the wall and hope it bounces out. That means, if you end up
on the road behind the 17th green, you need to play it where it
lies.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, it means that the building in front of the 17th is
in play. You have to drive over it to a fairway you can't see.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world's greatest par 4 in the world. Without a doubt,''
said Weiskopf, whose love affair with this tournament paid off with
a victory in 1973 at Royal Troon. He has become one of the world's
most sought-after course architects, but never could he draw up
something where you hit over a building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great, isn't it? That's part of it. What's wrong with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. Not a thing. Just as long as you pick out the correct
line. Which is? Well, caddies offer varying advice, though commonly
they will tell you to look at the big, white words ``Old Course
Hotel,'' take aim at the letter `C,' and have a little fade on the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Estes laughed. ``I'm not that good that I can aim at a letter. I
aim at a word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
