<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7423 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REVIEW-OFFICEMAC-SFCH     07-20 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-OFFICEMAC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OFFICE FOR MAC IS A MUST-HAVE  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Despite the common view of Microsoft and Apple
as archenemies, the reality is that Microsoft makes the lion's
share of Mac software. Its offerings dominate virtually every basic
category, from word processing and spreadsheets to e-mail and Web
browsing.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, however, especially in the early '90s when
Microsoft was working to establish Windows, updates to these core
Mac products were few and far between. They also lagged
considerably behind their Windows counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation _ antitrust jitters or simply a
recognition that there is money to be made in the resurgent Mac
market _ that neglect has turned around sharply in the past year or
two. Microsoft's Explorer 5 Web browser for Mac, for example,
boasts a truly Mac-like interface and many features not found in
the Windows version.
</P>
<P>
   At Macworld Expo NYC on Wednesday, Microsoft took the wraps off
the revamp of its flagship Office suite for Mac, which includes
Word (word processor), Excel (spreadsheet), PowerPoint
(presentation program) and Entourage (a new personal information
manager/e-mail application).
</P>
<P>
   While current users will find it reassuringly familiar, Office
2001 is a major overhaul. Most of the rework centers on making it
easier to use, more Mac-like and more integrated. This is in stark
contrast to earlier versions that kept adding layers upon layers of
obscure features, few of which were ever used.
</P>
<P>
   With Office 2001, Microsoft has added hundreds of templates,
sample projects and clip art files, all designed to get users up
and running quickly. The sample files do more than serve as
shortcuts, however. They spark ideas and offer professional design.
Some examples are newsletters, brochures, financial forms, resumes,
Web pages and labels.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've chosen a template (or just opened a plain document),
you're greeted with the new interface, which looks much like that
in Explorer 5, and takes advantage of Mac OS 9's built-in
appearance manager. Toolbars and palettes now float anywhere,
making it easy to customize your desktop for each application.
</P>
<P>
   Toolbars and palettes also facilitate much of the integration in
the new Office. For example, a Web browser toolbar in Word takes
you directly to Explorer, while the Data Merge Manager palette
makes it simple to do a mail merge with address book information
from Entourage or other standard database files. And the mail merge
can result in either printable documents or e-mail, a major new
feature.
</P>
<P>
   Another cool new feature that facilitates sharing info between
the various Office applications is Collect and Paste. This lets you
clip text, tables, pictures, charts, etc. and place them all on one
big clipboard for pasting anywhere else, separately, or all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft says that 81 percent of Mac Office users operate in
cross-platform environments with PCs, which is probably a fair
assessment. So another major area of improvement is in the ease of
sharing documents with PC users. Documents are code-identical with
PC Office files, so no conversion is necessary. Further, Office
2001 can now automatically append the three-letter file extensions
native to Windows, so Windows users can simply double-click Mac
Office files to open them.
</P>
<P>
   You can also now save any Word, Excel or PowerPoint document as
a Web page, ready for posting on your site. Limited HTML export
facilities were present in earlier versions, but Office 2001 goes
much further. You can literally save an entire PowerPoint
presentation in Web format with just one mouse click.
</P>
<P>
   Another handy option is to export PowerPoint presentations as
QuickTime movies. QuickTime movies can be played back on any Mac or
PC with the freely available QuickTime Player, without requiring
the PowerPoint application.
</P>
<P>
   While the improvements to Word, Excel and PowerPoint can be
viewed as incremental, no matter how useful or welcome, Entourage
is a new application that integrates well with the others and
finally brings a professional contact manager/e-mail program to the
Mac platform.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Outlook Express for Mac has e-mail and address book
functions only, without the calendar, task list and other features
available in Outlook for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could have called the new program Outlook, like the PC
application, but chose to go with a new moniker since the interface
and capabilities are quite different.
</P>
<P>
   Current users of Outlook Express for Mac will salivate over
Entourage's features. It can synchronize directly with Palm
handheld devices, import existing information from most other Mac
e-mail and contact management programs and integrates directly with
other Office applications, such as the aforementioned Mail Merge.
</P>
<P>
   You can use the calendar to keep track of due dates for Office
projects and set reminders. You can also create multiple custom
views on the information in Entourage that pertain to a particular
topic, such as all home or office work. Color-coding that works
across all facets of Entourage (e-mail, calendar, address book,
task list) also helps with organization.
</P>
<P>
   Entourage also offers support for Web standards like vCard and
iCalendar, so colleagues with PCs or Macs can make appointment
requests or send you their contact information.
</P>
<P>
   Office 2001 for Mac will ship this fall. For current Office
users it is a must-have upgrade; for others, the new emphasis on
ease-of-use, compatibility and integration should go a long way
toward erasing old objections. Entourage is simply the icing on the
cake.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Becky Waring at  &LR; becky(AT)waring.org &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
