<SLUG> BC-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY IS STILL A LEADER ON DL
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ORIOLES-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The whole thing looks suspect. Mike Stanley was
placed on the disabled list with a trumped-up injury _ one day it's
a shoulder strain, the next it's tendinitis _ and now he's
languishing in limbo two days after he was eligible to come off the
DL.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have room on their roster for Izzy Alcantara, a minor
league journeyman who has played just twice in the last three weeks
after offending the baseball sensibilities of manager Jimy Williams
and his teammates. But they can't find a place for Stanley, who
admittedly has been buried deep in a slump but has climbed out of
similar slumps in the past, and also is acknowledged as a key
leader of this team?
</P>
<P>
   General manager Dan Duquette has played such roster games
before. Last year, Reggie Jefferson had to go to the players'
association to be reinstated from the DL. Catcher Scott Hatteberg
had to threaten to do the same. And few veterans in the Sox
clubhouse are buying the argument that Alcantara must be kept here
because he is out of options and another team could claim him on
waivers. Their response to the possibility he could be taken: So?
</P>
<P>
   But while other players would be calling press conferences,
complaining of their predicament, Stanley has held his tongue after
flashing some bitterness when he was first placed on the DL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan-o has too much dignity and class for that,'' one Sox
player said Wednesday. ``And he's not going to call attention to
himself. He cares too much about the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, while the Red Sox waited for a game against the
Orioles that eventually was washed out and rescheduled as part of a
day-night doubleheader Thursday, Stanley tried to place a positive
spin on his situation. He planned to hit in the cage Wednesday,
then take some early hitting Thursday and talk again with Williams.
</P>
<P>
   While he concedes that anything is possible, that the Sox could
be buying time while they try to trade him or perhaps even release
him, Stanley said that after talking to Williams, he doesn't
believe that's the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the impression Jimy wants me to help him win some
games,'' Stanley said. ``He knows what I've been able to do for
them in the past, and thinks this time off may have been for the
benefit of me and the team.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks ago, after the team had just been swept in
Chicago by the White Sox and endured the embarrassment of
Alcantara's indifferent effort, Stanley called a players-only
meeting in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first meeting I've ever called in my life,'' he
said. ``Mo (Vaughn) used to call them, and last year we didn't need
to call any.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley acknowledged feeling a little apprehensive when he got
up to talk. ``I had the sweaty palms,'' he said. ``I talked the
first 10 or 15 minutes, then opened it up to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mo would have been a little more boisterous and loud
than the mild-mannered person I reflect, but we let everything get
out. Even if there were things that offended some people, we needed
to say what had to be said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked about how we had to look at where we are, not where
we've been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox took four straight from the Twins, pulling themselves
out of a tailspin that threatened to destroy their season at the
midpoint. They lost two of three to the Braves when they came home,
but played well, and now have won five of six since the All-Star
break.
</P>
<P>
   But now, just when it seems they have things turned around, the
Sox are braced for life without Carl Everett, who leads the club in
home runs and RBIs. Insurmountable? Stanley thinks not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain core of us who were here last year who
knows what it takes to win,'' Stanley said. ``We were in a pretty
deep funk there for awhile, but we've got to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   While no one is happy to be losing Everett (``he's given us a
huge lift''), Stanley said that sometimes a team draws together
after a crisis like that engendered by Everett's ejection Saturday
and certain suspension for contact with an umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you rally around things when you're put in that
situation,'' Stanley said. ``When you get backed into a corner, you
come out fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all realize what's ahead of us. But we've played and won
without Nomar (Garciaparra), and while Carl has been a major
influence on us this year, he wasn't here last year and we won. We
have to go back and do the little things we did last year, when we
didn't have Carl to pick us up.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who was warmly greeted by outfielder Rondell White and
coach Luis Pujols, among others, while Montreal was in Boston this
week, appeared in good spirits Wednesday, joking easily with
bullpen coach John Cumberland and Lee Thomas, one of Dan Duquette's
lieutenants, in the visitors' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said he has not spoken with Everett about Saturday's
incident. ``I don't think there was anything really that could be
said,'' he said. ``It's not something a person is really prepared
for. It happened in that moment, and you can't say, `Don't let that
happen again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, asked why more players didn't come out of the dugout
when Everett was raging at umpire Ronald Kulpa, said the players
were essentially caught by surprise. ``Usually the manager and the
coaches come to take a guy away,'' he said. ``It took us by
surprise that it lasted as long as it did. Plus, he'd already done
his damage. What were we going to do about it? Even if we'd gotten
there earlier, the damage was already done, the stuff he's going to
get suspended for.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost like, `The guy threw him out, let him go and get
his money's worth.' He'd already dug his grave by bumping an umpire
and doing whatever it is they say he did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
