<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7426 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-FOST-SFCHRON &LR;      07-20 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-FOST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA BYTES: DRIVE TO SUCCEED CONTRIBUTES TO DEMISE OF
YOUNG  DOT-COM EXEC
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Aaron Bunnell was the boss' son _ there was no
escaping it.
</P>
<P>
   But if working for his dad, tech magazine pioneer and Upside
Media Chief Executive Officer David Bunnell, meant that he could
slack off, he sure didn't show it.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell drove himself relentlessly, working all hours, pushing
his underdog Web site to greater heights.
</P>
<P>
   But that drive may have ultimately contributed to his demise. On
Monday, Aaron Bunnell, 26, was found dead in his room at the
Waldorf-Astoria hotel in New York.
</P>
<P>
   A champagne bottle was in the room, and his father, who flew to
New York immediately upon hearing the news, believes he may have
been taking uppers to fuel his work schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from a couple of his friends that he was getting very
burned out,'' said David Bunnell, a well-known tech publishing
figure who founded PC, PC World, MacWorld and other magazines. ``He
may have been stimulating himself to keep going and going. He
pushed it too far.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York City medical examiner is investigating, and Bunnell
said it may take six weeks to get the results.
</P>
<P>
   But the story that emerged as news of the death spread was of a
young, ambitious dot-com executive who poured everything into his
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this dot-com atmosphere, people get totally fixated on
work,'' said Adam Feuerstein, a senior writer at Upside Today, the
Web business that Aaron Bunnell spearheaded. ``It becomes their
obsession. Aaron worked all the time. If the software wasn't right,
he was in programming something. He worked and worked and worked.
You've got to step back, have some balance in your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Bunnell apparently knew he was working too hard, and,
according to his father, he had talked about cashing out his stock
options when the time was right and going back to his true passion:
filmmaking.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Bunnell had been in the prestigious filmmaking program at
the University of Southern California and was making documentaries
about World War II when he got the call from his father.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago, and David Bunnell was looking to expand
Upside's Web presence. ``We were just running on fumes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked him into coming up for a short time and doing some
work for me,'' Bunnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron moved in with his father, and the two drove to work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, David Bunnell paid his son out of his own pocket, but
when he saw how hard Aaron was working, he gave him a staff job. To
quell talk of nepotism, he had Aaron reporting to Gini Talmadge,
the company president and group publisher.
</P>
<P>
   In January, he put Aaron in charge of the Internet team and
started growing the online business. About 25 people work for the
Web site  &LR; (www.upside.com &LR; ), and Aaron had risen to become vice
president and editorial director of the online business. (The site
now features a tribute to Aaron from colleagues and other friends.)
</P>
<P>
   Adam Feuerstein remembers his job interview with Aaron Bunnell:
``We sat down, and he was wearing a ratty T-shirt and had a
baseball cap on backwards.''
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't take long for Feuerstein to see that ``he was one
of the savviest people when it came to new media and the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was real casual. He wore flip-flops to work and T-shirts
with holes in them, but he was really serious about his work,''
said Sylvia Carr, a senior editor on the site.
</P>
<P>
   He instilled the site with a sense of whimsy: It features a
``dot-com graveyard,'' mocking Internet firms that have gone out of
business, and each week it puts a different high-tech personality
on trial, with Oracle CEO Larry Ellison being found guilty of
immoral conduct, and Sun Microsystems CEO Scott McNealy being found
guilty of having a big mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Bunnell became something of a cheerleader, praising reporters
for their scoops, hailing every small victory. ``He definitely
celebrated with his staff,'' Carr said. ``We felt important to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   His hard work and his drinking may have taken a toll, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very worried about him working so late. I don't think he
was taking very good care of himself,'' Bunnell said. ``I knew he
drank. He would even have a few drinks and go back to the office.
He worked until 4 a.m. frequently. Sometimes he would work so late,
he would check into a hotel nearby. Other times, he would just
sleep on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   He went to New York last week to help develop a new Internet
radio venture, opening an office and studio for another 25 people.
His meetings had apparently gone well, colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll still be able to do it,'' said David Bunnell.
``If we can do it, we'll dedicate it to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuerstein said it was odd that no one had received an e-mail
from Aaron on Sunday; colleagues were accustomed to hearing from
him at all hours.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, David Bunnell received a call from a New York police
detective that a hotel worker had found Aaron in his hotel room.
David Bunnell flew to New York right away. Aaron's body will be
sent to Albuquerque, N.M., where his mother lives and where a
funeral will be held. There will also be a service in San
Francisco, possibly next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saddest part for me is that he lived with me these past
couple years and we rode together in the car to work,'' said David
Bunnell. ``This was precious time that can never be replaced. Aaron
was my constant companion and friend. We went to basketball and
baseball games together after work. He was funny and smart and
really hip to the dot-com world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows what he would have done,'' Bunnell said. ``At age
26, he was far ahead of me and I was really proud of this. It is a
great painful loss for me and a loss, I think, for the world at
large.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
