<SLUG> BC-COMET-SIGHTING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY VISITOR ARRIVING ON SUNDAY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DAVID PERLMAN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  A newfound comet will appear in the sky Sunday night. And while
it won't approach the brightness of comets that flashed across the
heavens a few years ago, it should still prove a worthy spectacle
to anyone with a pair of binoculars.
<P>
   The comet will appear as a faint, fuzzy blob just below the
familiar constellation of the Big Dipper. It is named Linear-S4,
for the Lincoln Near-Earth Asteroid Research project, whose
telescope at the White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico first
detected the comet in September.
</P>
<P>
   Linear appears to be a first-time visitor to the inner solar
system. It will fly around the sun next Wednesday in a long orbit
that will carry it within about 3.5 million miles of the Earth,
then far beyond the distant planet Pluto, astronomers say.
</P>
<P>
   Estimating how bright the comet will appear during the next few
nights is extremely tricky, according to National Aeronautics and
Space Administration astronomers at the Marshall Space Flight
Center in Huntsville, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   Even where weather permits, the comet will be only barely
visible to the naked eye, appearing as a very faint star. But
through good binoculars it could show up as a glowing ball with the
faintest of tails, like a smudge in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Linear will not approach the brilliance of comet Hayakutake,
which fascinated observers when it crossed the sky in 1997, nor the
amazing sight of comet Hale-Bopp the year before, which lured 39
members of the Heaven's Gate cult to kill themselves in order to
board a fancied space ship hidden behind the comet.
</P>
<P>
   Linear should be visible through binoculars for the next few
weeks, appearing above the west-northwest horizon soon after dark.
It will fade from view _ even in telescopes _ sometime late next
month or in September.
</P>
<P>
   The Lincoln asteroid project in New Mexico is run by the Lincoln
Laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and is
financed by the Air Force. Its highly automated telescope has
detected more than 397,000 asteroids in orbit around the sun.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those rocky objects may be only a few feet in diameter,
while others could be classed as minor planets several miles
across. Scientists agree there is a remote possibility that one of
the larger orbiting objects will hit the Earth one day in what
could be a major catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   The Linear comet is believed to have been launched on its
100-year voyage around the sun from a huge cloud of similar objects
that surrounds the solar system more than a trillion miles away.
Known as the Oort Cloud, it is often called the ``nursery'' of
comets.
</P>
</TEXT>
