<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ALL WORK AND NO PLAYBOY FOR GORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLA MARINUCCI and LYNDA GLEDHILL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   A night at the legendary Playboy Mansion is usually one hot
ticket. But as fast as you can say ``silicone,'' Congresswoman
Loretta Sanchez's choice of location for her next high-profile
campaign event has even fund-raising-friendly politicos making
polite excuses.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Vice President Al Gore nor Gov. Gray Davis will be
attending Sanchez's Aug. 15 party at the luxurious manse best known
for stars, starlets _ and whatever goes on when the two mix. The
Sanchez party, to be held during the Democratic National
Convention, has not only raised eyebrows _ but also handed
Republicans in California a few good punch lines.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, the Orange County Democrat who defeated Republican Rep.
Bob Dornan in a 1996 squeaker, is bravely sending out 600
invitations to the Los Angeles event, which benefits a Latino unity
group.
</P>
<P>
   Playboy representatives promise there will be a veritable orgy
of dignity: no trademark bunnies or bikinis, and absolutely no
rubbing elbows inside the mansion. In fact, Sanchez's fiesta won't
be inside, with the sexy waterfalls and jacuzzis, but outside, in a
tent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hugh Hefner, the 74-year-old pajama-clad founder of the
nudie magazine, is expected to drop in _ though there is no word
yet on whether his 25-year-old blonde bombshell girlfriends,
Brande, Mandy and Sandy, will come along.
</P>
<P>
   All the excitement prompted the media to ask if Gore, who will
receive his party's presidential nomination at the Democratic
convention and has aggressively courted Latino voters, will pass
this one by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know he was even invited,'' said Gore spokeswoman
Maria Meier Wednesday. ``We never said we were going to go, we
never committed, and we were never involved in that.''
</P>
<P>
   And Davis, who has raised millions already in his two years in
Sacramento, also appears to be nixing a chance to mingle with big
check-writers.
</P>
<P>
   A Davis spokesman said the governor already is committed to
attending a dinner that night at the home of supermarket mogul Ron
Burkle. Davis is the honoree at the private event.
</P>
<P>
   The disappointing news that two Demo bigwigs won't show did not
keep GOP state spokesman Stuart DeVeaux from taking off the gloves
on Sanchez, while at the same time borrowing a Tuesday night joke
from Jay Leno.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it poor taste, it just shows another example of
her lack of leadership,'' he said. ``But if Bill Clinton got an
invitation, I'm sure he'd be the first in line.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity sweepstakes has begun, and Al Gore is winning by a
landslide.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington, D.C.-based Center for Responsive Politics has
done an analysis of celebrity donors to both Gore and the GOP
presidential hopeful, Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Gore's check-writing camp includes a slew of Academy
Award winners: Nicolas Cage, Robert DeNiro, Michael Douglas, Tom
Hanks, Norman Lear, Jack Nicholson, Gwyneth Paltrow, Steven
Spielberg, Oliver Stone, Barbra Streisand, Warren Beatty and Tommy
Lee Jones, to name a few.
</P>
<P>
   There is also almost the whole Zappa clan: Ahmet, Diva, Sweezil
and Gail (no Moon Unit).
</P>
<P>
   But Bush? Well, it's short, and a little bit country: ``Coal
Miner's Daughter'' Loretta Lynn, Joe Bonsall, one of the Oak Ridge
Boys, and Larry Gatlin.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Green Party's Ralph Nader has done better. He got
actress Susan Sarandon, Bay Area-based Peter Coyote and _ need we
say more? _ Paul Newman.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Beatty again: He apparently can't make up his
mind between the Green and the Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
