u s BC-REVOLUTION-WIZARDS-BO     07-20 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVOLUTION-WIZARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION BEAT WIZARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Fernando Clavijo regained his winning touch
Wednesday night. Early in the season, Clavijo made a habit of
unexpected or unorthodox tactical changes which made the difference
in Revolution victories. This time, the 84th-minute addition of
Paul Keegan helped provide the difference in a 1-0 victory over the
Kansas City Wizards.
</P>
<P>
   A minute after coming in, Keegan flicked on a throw-in to Wolde
Harris, who converted on his second attempt past Tony Meola. The
result might have surprised supporters of both teams; the
Revolution entered the match with an 0-6-1 record since June 10,
and the Wizards fell for only the second time at Arrowhead Stadium
this season.
</P>
<P>
   And Keegan could be assuming an even more prominent _ and
uncharacteristic _ role when the Revolution visit San Jose
Saturday. Unless the Revolution acquire a defender, Keegan could
replace Mauricio Wright, who was cautioned and will be suspended
for the game, as a central defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't winning any balls on top, and we needed more
size,'' Clavijo said after replacing William Sunsing with Keegan.
``I wanted Paul to stay high and if we lost the ball, drop back. He
brings a lot of energy to the game, and he gives you everything he
has.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had played a conservative game, bypassing
midfield to go over the top to a three-forward alignment of Harris,
Sunsing, and Jose Luis Morales. Harris and Sunsing were most
effective pressing as the Wizards struggled to play out of the
back, but Morales, who is the team's most accomplished striker,
showed he is not yet in condition to be a sustained factor.
</P>
<P>
   Goalkeeper Juergen Sommer kept the Revolution in contention in
the early going, often simply by positioning and presence. Sommer
stopped a Matt McKeon point-blank shot, then stuffed Preki's
rebound in the 19th minute. McKeon, Mo Johnston, and Preki sent
open chances high and/or wide. Eventually, the Revolution defense
seemed to find cohesion. Leonel Alvarez limited Preki by working
with John Harkes in midfield to close space on the Wizards' most
dangerous offensive players.
</P>
<P>
   Preki departed in the 67th minute, leaving Kansas City with few
effective weapons. The return of Imad Baba and Ted Chronopoulos
from injury enabled the Revolution to neutralize the wing play of
the Wizards. And Wright stayed back to support young outside backs
Joe Franchino and Rusty Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution now have 29 points, 2 less than Dallas in the
race for the final playoff spot, with 10 matches remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't chasing enough in the middle in the first half, but
our intensity picked up in the second half,'' Clavijo said. ``We
started concentrating on forcing them to the outside instead of to
the middle. Maybe it was not too pretty, but I've played wonderful
games and lost. I want to play good soccer, but at the end of the
day the result is what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Revolution, approaching the sort of lengthy losing
streak that had destroyed their confidence in previous seasons,
were desperate for a win.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding play occurred quickly and unpredictably as the
Revolution turned an innocuous throw-in from their own end into a
goal. Chronopoulos bounced the throw-in to Keegan, whose back
header sent Harris in alone on goal. Harris outran Nick Garcia but
was stopped by Meola, then collected the rebound on the edge of the
goal area and finished into an open goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took two or three touches, and I was in the box, I shot to
Tony's left, and he did a great job to get a paw on it,'' said
Harris, who scored his ninth goal of the season. ``I think they
were flat-footed. They were expecting to win the header, but I was
expecting Keegan to get the ball and I was running onto it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was on the same page, and that's how we have to play.
Everyone attacks and everyone defends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
