<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7436 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ASSESS-     07-20 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: JERUSALEM DERAILED TALKS BEFORE LEADERS AGREED TO ONE
MORE TRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating and rewriting throughout)   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Before the Camp David summit meeting, pronounced
dead, was buried, it came back to life in a startling turnabout
suggesting that the contemplation of failure raised prospects too
grim for the Israeli and Palestinian leaders to accept.
</P>
<P>
   After nine stormy days in which each Middle Eastern leader
threatened to walk out, it was President Clinton's bag-packing that
drove home the unsettling possibilities of what the future without
a peace effort could hold. Clinton did not label it brinkmanship,
the assembling of his motorcade, the changing from casual to formal
clothes, the preparations for sealing hope for a negotiated peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But in a way it was. And somehow, the rebirth of the talks, with
no guarantees of any greater success, underscored a milestone in
Middle East history that got lost in the brief pronouncement of
failure. During nine days at Camp David, a Palestinian leader and
an Israeli leader confronted the intractable issue of Jerusalem's
sovereignty, a volatile, taboo issue that Middle Eastern leaders
have never before dared to broach.
</P>
<P>
   It is hardly surprising that the issue was responsible for
derailing the summit before it climbed back on track, an issue that
could not even be discussed much less resolved previously. And it
won't get any easier.
</P>
<P>
   But the status of Jerusalem needn't be a deal-breaker if Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and the Palestine leader, Yasser
Arafat, are willing or able to go for a partial accord that delays
decision-making on this subject. In the first nine days, they
weren't, but that meant that, before it was given a new lease on
life, one of the most momentous peace summits in modern history
fizzled to a close on a rainy night that dampened spirits.
</P>
<P>
   Until the second announcement, it seemed that instead of ending
a 52-year conflict, the summit might have put in jeopardy the whole
notion of Israeli-Palestinian peacemaking itself. It seemed barely
possible that lower-level negotiators would have been able to
return home and create a profitable dynamic when their leaders had
visited and revisited every compromise possible and rejected them
conclusively. Perhaps it is that eventuality that turned the
leaders' heads around and convinced them to stay, abetted by the
``powers of persuasion'' of Clinton, as his spokesman described it.
</P>
<P>
   At around 11 p.m. Wednesday here, the summit's supposed failure
greeted the Middle East region, which was about to wake up when the
talks broke down. It greeted them with an uncertain future at what
was supposed to be the end of a seven-year peace effort, and it
raised the specter of violent confrontations, of a genuine,
street-level battle for Palestinian independence building toward
Arafat's pledged deadline of Sept. 13 for declaring a state.
</P>
<P>
   Before the decision to stay on, people were already wondering if
the summit had done more harm than good or more good than harm. It
was impossible to know. The meeting, which the Israelis pushed for
but the Palestinians resisted, was premised on the idea of averting
a violent climax to the peace process. While the Palestinians
predicted failure, saying the summit was premature, the Israelis,
and the Americans who eventually convened the meeting, considered
it better to try than not to try amid the political and social
tensions building in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The language in Barak's closing letter to Clinton did not offer
any suggestion that the summit had brought the parties closer
together, despite the fact that were locked up in a presidential
retreat for nine days of intimate, emotional conversations.
Instead, it demonstrated, as did statements by the Palestinians,
that the mutual recriminations were not only still strong but
perhaps stronger than ever during Barak's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat met only three times during the nine days that
Clinton spent shuttling between them, and there is no evidence that
their relationship grew stronger in the bucolic setting.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost his majority government when rightist parties
defected before the summit, Barak faces an uncertain future as a
leader. And he would have under any scenario. But analysts believe
that he would have had the most trouble surviving if he returned
with a partial deal that entailed further Israeli concessions but
no resolution of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, politically, the middle ground was the most
dangerous route for Barak to take,'' a senior Israeli official
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
