<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7438 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLAN     07-20 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITCHERS' DUEL DECIDED BY PLAY AT PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Another Anaheim Angels starter pitched deep
into the game Wednesday night. In this case, it was Kent
Bottenfield, who pitched at least seven innings for the third
consecutive time.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Rangers starter Kenny Rogers was a little better,
holding the third-best hitting team in the American League in check
m in a 3-2 Rangers victory before 20,083 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended in controversy, as the final out came when
Rangers right fielder Scarborough Green threw out Scott Spiezio at
the score from second on a single by Kevin Stocker. Replays
appeared to show Spiezio touched the plate before the tag from
catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Even though at 35 he is hardly the same pitcher who threw a
perfect game against the Angels six years ago, Rogers changes
speeds well and keeps hitters off-balance. Rogers (10-7) allowed
only a solo homer by Bengie Molina in the fifth inning and an RBI
single by Spiezio in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also did a number on Darin Erstad, who went 0 for 4
with a walk. It was only the 15th game this season Erstad has gone
hitless, and the Texas pitchers got him in key situations.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad was up with runners at first and third and two outs in
the fifth, and Rogers struck him out on a 72-mph curveball out of
the strike zone. They walked him intentionally with runners on
second and third and two outs in the seventh and got out of the
inning. Then in the ninth, with the potential tying run on second
and one out, John Wetteland got him on a soft liner to second.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't exactly hammer Bottenfield (6-8), but two RBI
singles by Dave Martinez and a solo homer by Gabe Kapler (Taft High
of Woodland Hills) got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   The loss stopped the Angels from becoming the AL wild-card
leader. Instead, they remained tied with Oakland for the top spot
in the wild-card race. They still consider themselves contenders
for the d even a wild-card berth sounds appealing to an
organization that hasn't been to the playoffs since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take it any way you can get it,'' right fielder Tim Salmon
said. ``It would be nice to hang division banners up, but we've
been so close and just missed it. We'll take it however it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, the Angels reached a one-game playoff with
Seattle in 1995 and lost, and challenged for the division crown in
1997 and '98 only to fail in the waning days of each season. Is
this season just another tease for the Angels and their fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a pretty good club right now,'' Salmon said. ``We
have guys having fabulous years. You look at playoff teams and see
how some guys have career years. You wonder if this year is our
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither team scored in the first three innings, but the Rangers
turned a leadoff walk by Rafael Palmeiro in the fourth into a run,
Martinez getting an RBI single with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had just one hit against Rogers through four innings
but got something going in the fifth. With one out, Molina homered
to tie the game at 1. Benji Gil followed with a single and Spiezio
singled Gil to third.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when Rogers got tough. Edgard Clemente, subbing in
right field for the injured Salmon, was frozen by a 68-mph
curveball on a 2-2 pitch for strike three. Rogers then went to a
full count on Erstad and got him to chase a 72-mph curveball out of
the strike zone for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   The game didn't stay tied for long as Texas scored to go ahead
2-1 in the top of the sixth. Rodriguez led off with a double and
one out later scored on a single by Martinez. The Rangers' lead
became 3-1 in the seventh on Kapler's leadoff homer.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers came out with runners on second and third and two out
leading 3-2 in the seventh, and got a boost from reliever Doug
Davis. After intentionally walking Erstad to load the bases, Davis
got Stocker to ground out to second.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the eighth, Mo Vaughn had a leadoff single against
Davis, but Jeff Zimmerman came in and got Troy Glaus to hit into a
double play. That was big, because Garret Anderson and Molina
followed with singles. Zimmerman got pinch-hitter Adam Kennedy on a
popup to center to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland pitched the ninth for his 24th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
