u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-3RDLD-W     07-20 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-3RDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEAVING FOR JAPAN, BUT TALKS TO CONTINUE
</HEADLINE>
 (UPDATES with talks to continue) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JANE PERLEZ  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ In a dramatic turnaround, President Clinton
announced early Thursday morning that the Middle East peace talks
that were described by his spokesman as having failed to reach an
agreement would remain intact, and that the Israeli and Palestinian
leaders would stay at Camp David to continue meeting with Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that after the announcement that no agreement had
been reached, but there had been a substantial change of mind. ``We
all thought it was over,'' Clinton said at an elementary school
here, five miles away from Camp David. ``Then we discovered nobody
wanted to give up. And that should be encouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who met repeatedly with the Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, and the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, who
were at Camp David for nine days, then left for Japan. He is to
attend a meeting of the leaders of the seven major industrial
nations.
</P>
<P>
   The swing from announced failure to a renewal of talks came in
just over two hours. The presidential spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said
that the motorcade taking Clinton to the White House and then the
airport was set to leave Camp David when word spread around the
delegations who had never stopped negotiating that it really was
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we were getting ready to leave, it became clear there was a
willingness to stay and an unwillingness to let it break down,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who was preparing to give a midnight news conference
before leaving for Israel, canceled his departure plans. Similarly,
Arafat, who was ready to go too, decided to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat will meet with Albright over the next four days
to try and close the gaps on the main issues, Clinton said. On his
return from Japan, Clinton said he would assess the progress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spoke in a hoarse voice, said the two sides had
made an ``intensive effort'' and though the gaps remained
``substantial,'' there ``has been progress.'' He declined to stay
what the major stumbling blocks were, maintaining that the news
blackout which has been in force would remain in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   The last hours before Lockhart's announcement just before 11
p.m. that the summit meeting had ended without agreement involved
an intensive round of consultations by Clinton with the two leaders
and a series of discussions with their delegations. Just before the
public announcement of no agreement was made, Lockhart said that
word was passed to the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made the judgment that it was time to leave,''
Lockhart said. Then in the following 90 minutes the reversal
emerged, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called the summit meeting in a sweeping effort to close
the 52-year conflict between the Israelis and the Palestinians and
put on the table the major issues that the parties had been unable
to resolve.
</P>
<P>
   The question of the sovereignty of Jerusalem was reported to be
the main obstacle. And earlier in the evening, according to Radio
Israel, Clinton unsuccessfully proposed that Barak and Arafat
accept a partial agreement that did not include Jerusalem. This
accord would have dealt with the territorial shape of a Palestinian
state and brought a solution to the fate of 3 million Palestinian
refugees scattered through the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his aides appeared relieved that they had been able
to pull the summit meeting from the brink and push it into a new,
second phase. But Lockhart warned: ``I don't know if a few more
days will help the process.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was a day of high tension and rapidly shifting moods.
Late into the evening Clinton was still making an all-out effort to
salvage the talks, shuttling between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Clinton shuttled between Barak and Arafat _
who did not meet directly with each other _ fending off an Israeli
initiative to leave early and turning repeatedly to his advisers
and to the negotiators in search of some formula that would save
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   During the nine days of talks, Barak and Arafat apparently dealt
with every issue in the conflict _ from borders and the fate of
Jewish settlements to the right of return of Palestinian refugees
to the status of Jerusalem. But it was unclear whether the ultimate
stumbling block was a single issue, like Jerusalem, or the
trade-offs needed to fashion an overall agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Each side seemed to be gearing up to lay the blame for a failed
summit meeting on the other, and each leader appealed privately to
Clinton in letters written in the last 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The mood of the high-tension, high-stakes day seesawed. At
midday, it seemed certain that the talks were fizzling out.
</P>
<P>
   The day built to an unexpectedly quick first climax, when the
Israeli journalists accompanying Barak were ordered in the
afternoon to rush to their hotels for a security check so that
their luggage could be shuttled to Andrews Air Force Base for an 8
p.m. departure for Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock ran down, expectations were rife that there had
been a breakdown. Israeli television reported, and aU.S. official
later confirmed, that Barak had sent a letter to Clinton announcing
the Israeli prime minister's departure and laying the blame for the
meeting's failure on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Palestinian side is conducting negotiations insincerely
and is not willing to negotiate in a serious and practical manner
for a permanent peace between us,'' an Israeli reporter cited as a
direct quotation from the letter.
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Palestinian negotiator, Abu Mazen, who himself was
heading to the airport to fly home to his son's wedding, brushed
off what he saw as an 11th-hour Israeli tactic to increase pressure
on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that Clinton had also received a letter from
Arafat, which arrived on Tuesday, before Barak's. He did not
characterize its contents, but Palestinian officials said that
Arafat had reached a summit of frustration on the eighth day.
</P>
<P>
   If news of the letters lowered expectations of a deal, Lockhart
reported that Clinton had managed by late afternoon to keep the
leaders from walking out. ``They are still there, they are all
still talking,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart made clear that the two leaders were having trouble
making concessions on deeply emotional issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders both want to go home with an agreement,'' Lockhart
said. ``The problem is the substance and structure of the
agreement.'' But he added that the extended deadline would have to
stand. ``There comes a time when you have to put a time limit on
discussions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the day, Clinton telephoned other leaders in the Middle
East to brief them on the developments. They were the first such
contacts since the meeting opened.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Camp David, cabin fever combined with exhaustion and the
anxiety intensified as the day lengthened into night. Discussions
went on, Lockhart said, at the ``leader level, the negotiator
level, between teams and within teams.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared that an ultimate sticking point concerned the future
status of Jerusalem, the most divisive issue and one that has never
before been negotiated by Israeli and Arab leaders. It was seen as
the make-or-break issue, but it is possible that other stumbling
blocks remained.
</P>
<P>
   After conquering East Jerusalem from Jordan in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war, Israel declared that the city would ``eternally''
remain united and under exclusive Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The visit of the Egyptian leader, Anwar Sadat, to Jerusalem in
the fall of 1977 was interpreted by the Israelis as recognition of
Jerusalem's status as Israel's capital. But a year later, at the
first Camp David summit meeting between Sadat and the Israeli prime
minister, Menachem Begin, the question of Jerusalem threatened to
scuttle the entire conference.
</P>
<P>
   President Carter tried to find some sort of symbolic solution _
such as flying Muslim flags on the Temple Mount _ but the
suggestions were rejected by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   In the Oslo agreement of 1993, under which Israel recognized the
Palestinian Liberation Organization and the Palestinians renounced
all violence against Israel, the future of Jerusalem, along with
the fate of Palestinian refugees, final borders and some other
issues, was left for ``final status'' talks. The official position
of the United States has been that the fate of Jerusalem must be
negotiated between the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last seven years, diplomats, professors, demographers
and officials from both sides have tried to come up with various
arrangements that could satisfy the demands of both sides,
including ideas that involved autonomy for Palestinian
neighborhoods in Jerusalem and would allow the Palestinians to
claim the neighboring village of Abu Dis as their Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But these ideas were dismissed by the Palestinians as a ``Jewish
solution.'' Abu Dis, they argued, is not Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have watched Arafat over many years say that he always
set a benchmark: he would not be the Palestinian who went down in
history as the one who gave up Arab claims to East Jerusalem as the
capital of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, they point out, was not asking for a divided city but
rather shared sovereignty in an open and undivided city. Offering
municipal control over some neighborhoods, they said, fell far
short.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, for Barak, making concessions on a city that many
Jews regard as their capital by divine fiat was extremely
difficult.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
