<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ACE HOLDS ROCKIES TO ONE HIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Yep. Kevin Brown's right shoulder is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Really. Trust us. It wasn't just the Colorado Rockies and their
typical road performance.
</P>
<P>
   In his most overwhelming performance as a Dodger and one of the
most dominating in his career, Brown allowed one hit in eight
innings in a 9-1 win Wednesday against the Rockies at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, the Los Angeles Dodgers (48-45) leaped over
Colorado (47-45) into third place in the National League West
Division. The Dodgers began the night five games behind Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The only hit Brown allowed was a clean, ground-ball single
through the middle of the infield to Larry Walker, the game's third
batter. Reliever Mike Fetters walked one in a scoreless ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My shoulder's) stiff, but I was able to get through it and
keep working,'' Brown said. ``You never have everything working for
you. My fastball wasn't what I wanted it to be. (Location) was
probably my saving grace.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that kept Brown from his third career
complete-game one-hitter was the fear of overextending his right
shoulder, in which tightness forced him from his last start.
</P>
<P>
   Not even a hint of the ailment cropped up during his 104-pitch
masterpiece. Brown allowed an unearned run when Jeff Cirillo
reached on shortstop Alex Cora's first error in 36 games and Walker
singled.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Brown (9-3) was awesome. The only batter to reach
base after Walker's single was a four-pitch walk to Todd Helton
with one out in the fourth. Brown retired 23 of the last 24 batters
he faced, and only three of the 24 outs he got were recorded by
outfielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what a big-time pitcher does, he keeps you in the game
until you have the opportunity to do something offensively,''
Colorado manager Buddy Bell said. ``It was all Kevin Brown. He had
that sinker, sailer, slider. He's able to kind of make up (stuff),
too, as he goes along, which makes it tough. The SOB can pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   And, to think, Brown's start was actually in question as late as
Monday afternoon because he left his last start, Friday against
Anaheim, with tightness in his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But after being examined by team physician Dr. Frank Jobe, Brown
was given the OK to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught him in the minor leagues coming up and now here, and
for me,when he pitches his best it's when he's sick or a little bit
tired because it makes him a little more finesse,'' Dodgers catcher
Chad Kreuter said. ``It makes him more conscious of really hitting
his spots. When he throws 95 or 96 ith his fastball and his split
is around 93 or 94, sure it's easier to get guys out, but the
location night not be as good. You didn't see one ball hitting the
middle of the plate today.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Brown's mastery, it took a Dave Hansen three-run homer
to give the Dodgers the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield tied it 1-1 in the third with a single to center
and Hansen, getting a rare start at third base in place of Adrian
Beltre, followed singles by Shawn Green and Eric Karros with his
fifth homer of the season off Rockies starter Rockies starter
Rolando Arrojo. It gave the Dodgers a 4-1 lead, and was Hansen's
first non-pinch hit homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it would advantageous to our ballclub to use another
left- handed bat in the lineup,'' said Jim Tracy, the Dodgers bench
coach who is taking over as manager until Davey Johnson returns
from his irregular heartbeat. ``With Arrojo, I had seen him when I
was coaching in Montreal and was aware of the type of arm slot he
had and the type of pitches he throws to right vs. left-handed
hitters, and I thought it would be great to put another left-handed
bat in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers added five runs in the eighth inning to put the game
away. Kreuter had the big hit, a two-run double to right-center
field with the bases loaded. Alex Cora added a sacrifice fly and
Chris Donnels, just recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque, and Todd
Hollandsworth added RBI doubles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
