<SLUG> BC-AETNA-ING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AETNA TO SELL ITS INTERNATIONAL AND FINANCIAL SERVICES UNITS
</HEADLINE>
  By MILT FREUDENHEIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aetna Inc. has agreed to sell its international and financial
services units to the ING Group of the Netherlands for $5 billion
in cash, people close to the deal said Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, which ING planned to announce before the opening
of the stock markets in Europe Thursday, Aetna will create a new
health care company that will keep the name Aetna. Aetna's
shareholders will receive $35 in cash and one share of the new
company in exchange for each share of the old Aetna. ING will also
assume $2.7 billion of Aetna's long-term debt.
</P>
<P>
   ING plans to operate its growing U.S. financial business from
its existing headquarters in Atlanta. It also plans to keep a
strong presence in Hartford, where Aetna is based, and in
Minneapolis, the headquarters of ReliaStar, another recent purchase
by ING, people close to the deal said.
</P>
<P>
   They said ING had agreed to maintain the number of Aetna
employees at close to current levels, with future reductions mainly
from attrition as employees retire or leave.
</P>
<P>
   ING, the Dutch financial giant based in Amsterdam, has made a
series of offers to buy parts of Aetna as part of its strategy of
becoming one of the 10 largest insurance companies in the United
States. Earlier this year, Aetna rejected a tentative offer of $70
a share for the entire company from ING and Wellpoint Health
Networks of California. Under that deal, Wellpoint planned to
absorb Aetna's health care business.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna, the nation's biggest health insurance company, has been
struggling with unexpected increases in medical costs, which
reduced its profits. The company surprised investors on Tuesday by
announcing that its second-quarter earnings per share would fall
short of Wall Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would tighten its operations and raise its
rates as soon as current contracts expire. Aetna promised to
disclose details of its finances when it reports second-quarter
profit on Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna has also been wrestling with money-losing operations of
its big Prudential Health Care unit, which it bought last year.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been pressing Aetna to sell off units to generate
immediate value for shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts said the sale to ING could reduce shareholder
value over the long run. Kenneth S. Abramowitz, a health care
analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein, said before the deal was reached
that a sale for less than $12 billion would dilute the value of
Aetna's stock. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company said on Tuesday that its second-quarter earnings
would be 85 to 95 cents a share, well below analysts' estimates of
$1.20, according to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks
company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Aetna said medical costs in its core commercial health
maintenance organizations rose 10 percent to 12 percent in the
second quarter as members spent more time in hospitals, emergency
rooms, outpatient surgery centers and doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Abramowitz said Aetna would have to raise its rates by 12
percent or more next year to fix its problems, even if resistance
to the increase by customers stalled the growth of its membership.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Donaldson, who took over as chief executive of Aetna
in February had said he would split the company into health care
and financial units. Several senior health care executives have
departed, and Aetna is seeking a new chief executive to run the
health care business.
</P>
<P>
   Several Aetna health care executives left the company this year,
and analysts said that absence of experienced senior leaders might
have added to the company's operating problems.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
