<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-NUANGELS-LADN-(SL     07-20 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NUANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE ON PLAY AT PLATE
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHRU (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Another Anaheim Angels starter pitched deep
into the game Wednesday night. In this case, it was Kent
Bottenfield, who worked at least seven innings for the third
consecutive outing.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas Rangers starter Kenny Rogers was a little better,
holding the third-best hitting team in the American League in check
most of the night in a 3-2 Rangers victory before 20,083 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The game ended in controversy, as the final out came when
Rangers right fielder Scarborough Green threw out Scott Spiezio
trying to score from second on a single by Kevin Stocker. Replays
appeared to show Spiezio's foot touched the plate before the tag by
catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went out for an explanation and (home-plate umpire) Doug
Eddings said (Spiezio) never reached the plate,'' Angels manager
Mike Scioscia said. ``Why don't you go ask him for an
explanation?''
</P>
<P>
   Eddings refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was safe,'' Spiezio said. ``No question about it.
Obviously, someone else didn't think so. It's part of the game, but
it is frustrating. We thought we tied the game right there and it
ended up the game's over. Who knows what would have happened after
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was asked if he thought he tagged Spiezio before he
touched the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I was blocking the plate and we made the out,'' he said.
``It's a tough play to see the runner. On a play like that, I try
to sit on the plate and block the runner and that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have done well in one-run games at home this season.
They are 13-5 in one-run games at home and 20-16 in one-run games
overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our share of tough losses,'' Scioscia said. ``This
team has the ability to turn the page and we'll certainly do that
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Scoring opportunities were scarce for the Angels against Rogers.
Even though at 35 he is hardly the same pitcher who threw a perfect
game against the Angels six years ago, Rogers changes speeds well
and keeps hitters off-balance.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers (10-7) allowed only a solo homer by Bengie Molina in the
fifth inning and an RBI single by Spiezio in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also did a number on Darin Erstad, who went 0 for 4
with a walk. It was only the 15th game this season Erstad has gone
hitless, and the Rangers pitchers got him in key situations.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad was up with runners on first and third and two outs in
the fifth, and Rogers struck him out on a 72-mph curveball out of
the strike zone. They walked him intentionally with runners on
second and third and two outs in the seventh and got out of the
inning when Stocker grounded out. Then in the ninth, with the
potential tying run on second and one out, John Wetteland got him
on a soft liner to second.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't exactly hammer Bottenfield (6-8), but two RBI
singles by Dave Martinez and a solo homer by Gabe Kapler (Taft High
of Woodland Hills) got the job done.
</P>
<P>
   The loss stopped the Angels from becoming the American League
wild-card leader. Instead, they remained in a virtual tie with
Oakland for the top spot in the wild-card race. They still consider
themselves contenders for the division title, but even a wild-card
berth sounds appealing to an organization that hasn't been to the
playoffs since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take it any way you can get it,'' right fielder Tim Salmon
said. ``It would be nice to hang division banners up, but we've
been so close and just missed it. We'll take it however it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, the Angels reached a one-game playoff with
Seattle in 1995 and lost, and challenged for the division crown in
1997 and '98 only to fail in the waning days of each season. Is
this season just another tease for the Angels and their fans?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a pretty good club right now,'' Salmon said. ``We
have guys having fabulous years. You look at playoff teams and see
how some guys have career years. You wonder if this year is our
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers came out with runners on second and third and two outs,
leading 3-2 in the seventh, and got a boost from reliever Doug
Davis. After intentionally walking Erstad to load the bases, Davis
got Stocker to ground out to second.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the eighth, Mo Vaughn had a leadoff single against
Davis, but Jeff Zimmerman came in and got Troy Glaus to hit into a
double play. That was big, because Garret Anderson and Molina
followed with singles. Zimmerman got pinch-hitter Adam Kennedy on a
popup to center to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland pitched the ninth for his 24th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
