<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 MARINERS DOUBLE UP A'S BEHIND MOYER, McLEMORE  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Mark McLemore resurrected his bat with a
couple of key doubles, mixed in enough defense to fill a highlights
show and Jamie Moyer played hide-and-seek with the baseball
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That combination proved fatal to second-place Oakland on a cool
Coliseum night. The first-place Mariners padded their lead in the
AL West with a 6-3 win that made the difference between first and
second place in the division an imposing five games.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has won three of its last four and is now a season-best
17 games over .500 at 55-38. That's the best any Mariners' team has
done since the 1997 squad finished the year at plus-18 (90-72).
</P>
<P>
   McLemore, who drove in three runs with a pair of doubles _ his
first hits to drive in runs in a month _ cautioned against making
too much of the victory. Seattle and Oakland play four more times
in the next seven days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because we won this one doesn't mean we can sit back and
coast,'' McLemore said. ``This was one game.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another Thursday. Seventy more the rest of the way.
Those will be easier for the Mariners to win if McLemore can play
closer to his form of Wednesday night. A .226 hitter, he doubled
home two runs in the second inning and doubled in another run as
part of a three-run sixth.
</P>
<P>
   It's not true that McLemore hadn't had a hit in a month,
although it may have seemed that way. It was true, however, that
McLemore's last hit to drive in a run was last month. On June 19,
he'd singled to score a run, but since then, zip. ``I'm not a .220
hitter,'' McLemore said. ``I've been struggling all year. It came
together a little tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense was part of the package. In the space of four batters in
the third and fourth innings, McLemore turned three would-be
singles into outs with a combination of deft hands, great lateral
movement and acrobatic throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the thing you love to see, because with Mac, he doesn't
take the (low) batting average out to the field,'' infield coach
Larry Bowa said. ``That's part of being professional. And it's easy
to play defense when you're hitting .300. It's harder when you're
hitting .220.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easier to pitch when you get that kind of defense behind
you, too, and Moyer got plenty of it. All four infielders made
exceptional defensive plays to help Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer allowed just one hit in the first four innings and one run
in the first seven innings, running his career record against
Oakland to 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland played sloppy defense, couldn't hit and couldn't pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The reverse was true for Seattle, which was sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a solid game for us, top to bottom,'' manager Lou
Piniella said. ``Mac came up big for us tonight on offense and
defense, and the defense and the bullpen were great. And Jamie?
Well, he just knows how to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer glittered, allowing a two-out single in the first, then
not another base runner until the fifth, when the A's got two hits
and a walk to load the bases with one out. However, third baseman
David Bell started an inning-ending double play, as important a
play as the Mariners made all night.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Grieve broke up the shutout, leading off the seventh with a
solo homer, his 18th. An inning later, Moyer had to bow out after a
Ramon Hernandez pinch-hit two-run homer cut the Mariners' lead to
6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Rhodes took over and, as has been his wont all season,
quickly restored order.
</P>
<P>
   Kazuhiro Sasaki closed it out for his 23rd save. He struck out
the side, including blowing away right fielder Matt Stairs on a 3-2
pitch for the inning's second out. That was some sweet revenge for
Sasaki, because it was Stairs who beat Sasaki with a three-run
homer back on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   That loss had moved the A's one-half game ahead of the Mariners
in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Ten weeks later, the AL West has an entirely different
landscape.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
