<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7450 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     07-20 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETICS UNLIKELY TO TURN SINKING TIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Slugger Jason Giambi and his straggly hair
grace the cover of this week's Sports Illustrated. The messy look
is a metaphor for what his team is doing on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The A's, losers of 13 of their past 18 after Wednesday night's
implosion against the Mariners, have become another sort of fodder
for ``SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what 91 errors will do for you.
</P>
<P>
   One-a-day, just like the vitamins. Or two-a-day _ eight in the
past four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset with our defense,'' A's manager Art Howe said after
the 6-3 loss. ``We have to pick it up defensively. We're not this
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   It did not help matters that the A's were battered in Denver
before returning home for this eight-game stretch against the
Mariners and Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Call what happened at Coors Field, where the A's gave up 38 runs
in three games, a serious farewell to arms.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, when Oakland starter Kevin Appier struggled out
of the gate, you could feel the throats tighten in the A's dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Who was going to go out there and pitch long relief, if it came
to that? Giambi?
</P>
<P>
   At least he's a lefty. He might have thrown a loop in Lou
Piniella's left-leaning lineup, but Giambi didn't have the gas.
``Three games in 24 hours? I know I'm exhausted,'' Giambi said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Appier hung in there by necessity, serving up 10 hits
and six runs while the A's bullpen was put on mandatory bed rest.
</P>
<P>
   By the sixth inning, the crowd at Oakland Coliseum was peppering
their white-shoed team with a healthy dose of boos. ``I heard them.
Who can blame them?'' Appier said.
</P>
<P>
   The longer this goes on, the more Taco Tuesdays will be a big
part of the reason for A's fans to come out to the ol' ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   This was a Dollar Wednesday. A buck gets you a seat in the upper
deck, which helped explain the bump in attendance. Walk-up ticket
sales hit 14,700, bringing the house to a respectable 31,466.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't fair, of course.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are one of the franchises on Major League Baseball's
endangered species list.
</P>
<P>
   They're in the bottom third league-wide in payroll, at about $32
million. And last week, the ``commissioner's'' blue-ribbon panel
suggested the A's were a prime candidate for relocation.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks now, Howe's team has endeavored to keep pace with the
Mariners despite horrendous defense and the loss of 30 homers and
100 RBI in the injured John Jaha. While the Yankees' payroll has
soared to $115 million thanks to big trades, little guys like the
A's are more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to do something. I don't want to sell the
farm, but at the same time, we need to do something. Not that we
can spend a lot of money,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   If the A's were already seeing their chance to stay in the hunt
for the AL West title slip away, it wasn't exactly breaking news to
Howe. ``I don't feel we have the same energy,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the A's picked up Appier, Omar Olivares and Randy
Velarde at the trade deadline, and the club felt a boost. But at
this point in their season, the A's are tanking a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Howe was unwilling to completely concede that the fight
for the division was an uphill battle _ the grade of which is
starting to look like Mt. Shasta.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the Mariners executed extraordinarily well.
Mark McLemore could be seen diving to his left, diving to his
right, jumping up like Nureyev to make big plays.
</P>
<P>
   And that was McLemore getting his first RBI in a month to give
the Mariners a 3-0 lead in the second. The second baseman added
another in the sixth, putting Seattle up 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   David Bell single-handedly killed Oakland's best chance for a
rally in the fifth when he gloved Sal Fasano's grounder, stepped on
third, then threw the catcher out for an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   The A's are getting a sense of what the big boys can do in the
heat of battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made unbelievable defensive plays, which is what you have
to do,'' Giambi said. ``Jamie Moyer did what he always does, get
you to hit grounders. He gives you a solid performance every time
out. McLemore made some great plays. That's a veteran ballclub over
there. We're young and we're still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk about seizing the moment. The Mariners have opened a
five-game lead over the A's and given Bay Area baseball watchers
the distinct impression that the two clubs are heading in opposite
directions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just been in a real down time as a team lately. It's
depressing,'' Appier said.
</P>
<P>
   Howe tried to put a positive spin on the state of affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we need to have a good stretch here. I hope we can. We
can't seem to get things in sync,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In sync? The A's look like they're in the sink, circling slowly.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at
</P>
<P>
   206-448-8011 or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
