<P>
   What is the deal with Russell Crowe? Just being a movie star and
insouciant heartthrob would seem to be enough for most guys, but,
no, not randy Russ, who now evidently adds home wrecker to his list
of credits. That's the topic of (beginitalic)People's
(enditalic)cover story, and the saga of Meg Ryan's ``SHOCKING
SPLIT'' from Dennis Quaid to find ``comfort'' with the
``(beginitalic)Gladiator (enditalic)bad boy'' is a heartbreaker
from Quaid's perspective at least. The inescapable CBS series
(beginitalic)Survivor (enditalic)gets a six-page spread devoted
entirely to the instant-celebrity losers who got booted off the
island in the show's first few weeks; charming curmudgeon Walter
Matthau gets a loving send-off; and making a few campaign
appearances for her mom qualifies Chelsea Clinton for a 750-word
piece with a tag line crediting seven different staffers.
</P>
<P>
   Talk
</P>
<P>
   Right up front, Christopher Caldwell spends a tidy essay
decrying American anhedonia (''a loss of interest or pleasure in
all or almost all usual activities and pastimes''), and it's more
than just a good excuse to run a 1961 photo of Brigitte Bardot
riding a bicycle, which the editors also do, so thank you, editors.
Among the chief culprits, Caldwell guesses, is our unhealthy
obsession with health and longevity. ``Would Picasso have made it
to 91 without tobacco and sex?'' he asks. We'd answer, but, uh,
what was the question? A few pages later, George W. Bush's media
adviser Mark McKinnon is profiled; Tucker Carlson measures John
McCain's lingering coolness quotient; and there's an interview with
Elizabeth Hurley, who is no Brigitte Bardot circa 1961 but close.
</P>
<P>
   Discover
</P>
<P>
   The shudder-inducing cover story tracks the secret life of
parasites. Cringe at the tale of the hairy blood fluke, said to
reside in the bloodstreams of 200 million people worldwide. Say
``yuck'' aloud to the account of the microscopic crustacean
sacculina, which ``converts its crab host into a castrated,
mindless slave.'' Scratch yourself involuntarily at the knowledge
that many parasites have parasites themselves. Or quickly turn to
other headlines, such as the one above the profile of Yngvar
Isachsen, who studies what appears to be an ancient impact crater
in the Catskill Mountains. Another piece-a examines the extreme
measures scientists are taking to save the Leaning Tower of Pisa.
(beginitalic)Discover (enditalic)sometimes reads like ``Science
Lite,''' but this issue delivers. Great cover shot too. (It's a
hookworm, bucko, and he's looking right at you.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 0802EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 08:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7468 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-WOMENSPORTS-TITLEIX-A     07-20 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMENSPORTS-TITLEIX-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WOMENSPORTS-TITLEIX-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    HEADLINE HERE IN ALL CAPS(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING: Moving in ``A,'' ``L'' and ``S'' categories. 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DAVE WALKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You fill stadiums for big soccer games.
</P>
<P>
   You're the toast of Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   At America West Arena on Monday, you'll stage the second WNBA
All-Star Game, a celebration of acceptance that nonetheless
struggled to fill even $10 seats.
</P>
<P>
   You've come halfway, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three decades after Congress enacted Title IX and threw
the weight of law behind gender equity for amateur female athletes,
that's the official assessment of the Women's Sports Foundation, or
WSF.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're halfway'' to equity, said Donna Lopiano, executive
director of the WSF, founded by Billie Jean King in 1974 to seek
justice for women bucking the male-dominated American jockocracy.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say halfway isn't a long way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, the year before Title IX mandated that no American
``shall, on the basis of sex, be excluded from participation in, be
denied the benefits of or be subjected to discrimination under any
educational program or activity receiving federal financial
assistance,'' fewer than 300,000 girls played high school sports.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, according to foundation statistics, the total was 2.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Participation in intercollegiate athletics, also regulated under
Title IX, has grown at a slower pace, but nonetheless gains have
been substantial, especially in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, athletic scholarships for women totaled less
than $100,000 nationally, according to the WSF. Currently, the
total tops $180million.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the WSF's advocacy hotline averages three to four calls a
day from sports-program participants who suspect inequities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day there's a new unbelievable,'' said Lopiano.
</P>
<P>
   A classic example, close to home: Desert Vista High School
opened a few years ago in Phoenix with a sparkling baseball field
for boys but not a single softball field for girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's resistance - I think it's (lack of)
knowledge,'' said Sister Lynn Winsor, athletic director and coach
at Xavier College Prep in Phoenix. ``You go up to someone and say,
`You've got a wonderful boys' baseball facility with concrete
dugouts. And the girls are sitting on three little park benches.'
It's not that they don't want to - it's that they don't think of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Winsor, an Xavier coach and administrator for 26 years, serves
on a committee of the Arizona Interscholastic Association that
evaluates state schools for gender equity. It's not enforcement,
exactly, but rather positive reinforcement - the committee hands
out an annual prize to schools that have made the most progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look around Arizona, I think we're one of the better
states,'' said Winsor, who's also served as an officer for a
national coaches association. ``We've come a long way, especially
compared to some of the Southern states. They really have some
issues to deal with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of change. I'm impressed by what's happening.
Sometimes change is painful, but it's for the best.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights, or
OCR, is charged with enforcing Title IX. This summer, several
Valley high schools are upgrading facilities to comply, and an OCR
spokesman said there are no open complaints in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Desert Vista softball situation wasn't resolved until a
player's father threatened a Title IX complaint. Title IX scholars
dub it the ``Mad Dad'' phenomenon - fathers who played sports as
kids who now insist on equal opportunity for their daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has definitely been a father-led movement,'' said
Lopiano. ``It's not a women's initiative at all.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lopiano said, the women's movement did not initially
embrace sports as a battlefront.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sport was originally how we trained men for war,'' Lopiano
said. ``They didn't think it was a healthy thing for women at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dad was there right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she said, the first generation of mothers to enjoy Title
IX-decreed equality are coaching their young daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you thought Dad was rabid, wait until Mom gets into it,''
she said. ``You don't want to ever see your children discriminated
against.''
</P>
<P>
   College scholarships, which drive participation at lower levels,
are viewed as crucial to the continued march toward sports equity.
Title IX requires that women be awarded scholarship dollars
proportional to their participation in a school's athletic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Another index by which schools are measured is whether the
percentage of female athletes matches the percentage of female
undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   That test has proved somewhat vexing to sports administrators at
Northern Arizona University, where female enrollment has grown from
52percent to 56 percent in the past few years. In the 1998-99
school year, 48.5 percent of NAU's student athletes were women, up
from 36 percent in the 1996-97 school year.
</P>
<P>
   One way NAU achieved its gains is a rallying point for
gender-equity critics, who point out that Title IX has been most
painful to participants in minor sports for men. To meet equity
mandates, many colleges have eliminated teams.
</P>
<P>
   Attributing the cut to Title IX, Northern Arizona University,
which had recently added soccer and golf teams for women, last year
dropped men's swimming and diving. More than 50 Division I colleges
have killed wrestling programs in the past two decades. Gymnastics,
tennis {ndash} even baseball {ndash} have been threatened or axed
at colleges around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, fiscally you have to say, We can't add another
female sports if the dollars aren't there,''' said Steve Holton,
NAU's athletic director. ``The only way to stay in compliance with
the federally mandated law is to eliminate men's sports.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Title IX's inception, various male-sports coaches'
associations have mounted organized opposition, and repeated
efforts have been made to exempt football from equity formulas.
According to the Women's Sports Foundation Gender Equity Report
Card for 1997, women gained a net increase of 1,658 National
Collegiate Athletic Association programs since 1978. During the
same years, total men's programs also increased, by 74. However,
schools in the NCAA's Divisions I-A and I-AA, the largest
universities that tend to have the largest athletic programs,
showed a decrease in the number of men's sports programs, a net
loss of 152.
</P>
<P>
   According to the WSF, the explosive growth in female
participation in high school sports during the past couple of
decades didn't dim growth for boys programs. In 1971, 3.6million
boys played high school sports. In 1998, 3.7million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Title IX, I really can't see the sharing of resources
that was required to really give women the opportunity to play,''
said Lopiano. ``It has been a tooth-and-nail fight every step of
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The WSF estimates that 80percent of America's college and
universities are not yet in full compliance with Title IX, though a
recent Wall Street Journal/NBC News poll indicates that more than
three-fourths of the sample supported the drive to equity - even if
it means further cuts in men's programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think that the general public gets it,'' Lopiano
said. ``The problem is not the general public. It's the
decisionmakers holding the purse strings of sports, a small group
of dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   David F. Salter, author of 1997's (beginitalic)Crashing the Old
Boys' Network: Tragedies and Triumphs of Girls and Women in
Sports(enditalic), said that the 1996 Summer Olympics, where
several American women teams won gold medals, was a watershed
moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really look at the Atlanta Olympics as the culmination of
the first 20 years of the Title IX effort,'' he said. ``From there,
the growth and quality of females athletic programs has improved
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   But Salter warned: ``I'm afraid that men and women, fathers and
mothers will get the impression that because we have the WNBA on
television, because we have the World Cup soccer team getting a lot
of publicity, that we've overcome these Title IX challenges, and
the momentum slows or stops.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at Dave.Walker(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or
(602)-444-8625.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
