<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 08:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7473 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COL &LR;      07-20 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI- COLM-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ALL THE WORLD IS JOES'S STAGE(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's Wednesday, it must be Scotland, and a reporter from
the(beginitalic) Daily Record (enditalic)in Glasgow is calling to
ask about Sheriff Joe Arpaio's plan to put cameras in the booking
room of the Madison Street Jail and broadcast live over the World
Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it trrrue?'' says Gary Ralston, who, for a newspaper
writer, does a better than average impersonation of Sean Connery.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's told. But that was only in the paper yesterday, how
did you hear about it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I read about it in an Irish paper,'' he says. ``And some
British papers have stories as well. So, we'll be doing a feature
on the sheriff here. Is it true he said he wants the fellas
arrested with prostitutes to wave to the cameras so their wives
will see?''
</P>
<P>
   More or less. The sheriff says his Web camera will be a
deterrent, adding, ``Maybe those guys who get busted on Van Buren
(for soliciting prostitution) can wave to their wives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How funny,'' Ralston says, doing a better than average
imitation of Sean Connery laughing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would Sheriff Arpaio do such a thing?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's been about one month since his last big publicity
stunt, he's told.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dogs?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Back in June, Joe announced he would provide better
accommodations and more expensive food for the dogs under his care
than he would for the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's quite bold with statements like this, isn't he?'' Ralston
says. ``And they seem to go over quite well?''
</P>
<P>
   As evidenced by your call, yes, he's told. The month before the
dogs, there was the story about (beginitalic)60 Minutes
(enditalic)coming to town to interview Joe. And reports about a
movie company planning to film the story of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Ralston says, ``that made the papers as well. He wants
Robert De Niro or Joe Pesci to play his part, I recall. What do you
make of that?''
</P>
<P>
   I tell him it will be a first for American cinema. Most
biographical films fictionalize a real-life story. Joe's picture
would tell the true story of a purely fictional character {ndash}
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston called me because my name appeared in the newspaper
research he did, as well as in the thick file he received on
Sheriff Joe from Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you feel from guys like me there is an unfair
representation of Arizona (because of all the stories about
Arpaio)?'' he asks. He also wonders if I'm tired of talking about
the sheriff to out-of-towners. I've tried to stop, I say (in a
better than average imitation of Al Pacino in Godfather III), but
they keep pulling me back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It strikes me that this man could hire the sharpest PR talent
in the land and they couldn't do as good a job as he does,''
Ralston says. ``Why do you suppose that is?''
</P>
<P>
   I tell him it's because Arpaio is a naive genius. He's like
Grandma Moses, the painter, untrained in classic technique, but
still a master.
</P>
<P>
   He's the kid who's never played organized ball weaving through
defenders on the basketball court, faking a pass and going in for
an easy lay-up. What Joe's got, you can't teach.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter from Glasgow said he hopes to find out for himself
sometime soon, with an interview. Arpaio won't disappoint him. He
never does. After years of rehearsals and performances, he does a
better than average impersonation of a sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8978.
</P>
