<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; tad-z
b w BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0720-2     07-20 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0720-2NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: writes thru to update with talks to continue
 &HT;    CLINTON CONVINCES ISRAELIS, PALESTINIANS TO REMAIN FOR TALKS IN
HIS ABSENCE
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ In a dramatic last-ditch effort to salvage
faltering Mideast peace talks, President Clinton convinced Israeli
and Palestinian leaders late Wednesday to remain at Camp David for
the next four days while he journeys to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   When he returns _ as early as Sunday afternoon _ Clinton said he
will resume talks with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence, the negotiations will be lead by U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, though at a decidedly scaled-down pace
than the nine grinding days and nights of summitry that wound up
inconclusively Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had concluded that the summit had failed
Wednesday evening, and he was preparing to leave the presidential
retreat at nearby Camp David empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought it was over,'' Clinton told some 200 reporters
gathered in this Catoctin mountain hamlet to cover the Camp David
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton's presidential motorcade loaded and ready to convey
him to Washington for an early morning flight Thursday to Japan,
the parties agreed to remain at the presidential compound and
resume leader-level peace talks upon his return.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned that there remained no guarantee of success in
the talks, aimed at resolving the thorny territorial and security
disputes at the heart of 52 years of Israeli-Palestinian conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gaps remain substantial, but there has been progress,''
Clinton said, adding that he believed all parties needed to be
prepared ``to go the extra mile'' for peace.
</P>
<P>
   After staring at the prospect of a failed peace summit, Clinton
said, neither Arafat nor Barak wanted to return to the tumultuous
region without a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wanted to give up,'' Clinton said during brief remarks
early Thursday to reporters at the temporary media center set up in
a tiny elementary school in this town of 4,400.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat had been prepared to leave the Camp David
summit earlier at an acrimonious impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, in fact, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
released a statement declaring that the talks had collapsed in
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summit has come to an end without reaching an agreement,''
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a prepared statement
read to reporters just before 11 p.m. (ET) by National Security
Council spokesman P.J. Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   For several hours, though, Clinton shuttled between Arafat and
Barak, who haven't met directly since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   As the talks faltered through a wild day of brinkmanship, high
drama and heated negotiations, both sides blamed each other for not
yielding on the intractable issue of the future of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat came into the talks vowing to reject any accord that
didn't guarantee Palestinian control over East Jerusalem, the site
of some of the holiest shrines in the Moslem, Christian and Jewish
worlds. Israel captured that part of the city in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for his part, had pledged that an undivided Jerusalem
would remain the eternal capital of Israel, fully under Israeli
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was unable to bridge those differences, by Wednesday,
and said only that he would try again after his return.
</P>
<P>
   The president Clinton left Thurmont by motorcade shortly after 1
a.m. (ET) Thursday. He was scheduled to go to the White House and
then to leave early Thursday morning for Dulles Airport, outside of
Washington, where he was to board Air Force One for the 15-hour
flight to Okinawa, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There, far from the crucible of Mideast summitry and even
farther from the flesh and blood issues the talks were designed to
address, Clinton was to assume the role of elder statesman at hi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 0908EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 09:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7505 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN23-COX     07-20 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: GOP goal on marriage tax is to cast Democrats as
anti-family
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In case you were wondering, all that fuss in Washington over
fixing the so-called ``marriage penalty'' _ some couples pay more
together than they would filing individually _ isn't about the
marriage penalty at all. It's about snookering Democrats. Hey, this
is an election year, folks.
</P>
<P>
   So, Republican majorities in the House and Senate, with a few
Democratic crossovers, have passed legislation that, its
enthusiasts say, would end the cruel business of unfairly harrying
financially struggling couples and the unholy business _ the
religious right is still out there, to be played to _ of favoring
probably wanton singlehood over the presumed fidelities of the
marital couch.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no. Mostly no.
</P>
<P>
   The real game here is to put the Clinton administration and
specifically Vice President and White House aspirant Al Gore in a
blind alley and watch them squirm. It's working.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP legislation is designed virtually to force the president
to veto the legislation on the grounds that it is tilted too
heavily to well-off couples and, passing out goodies even to
couples who pay no marriage penalty, would create an irresponsible
drain on revenue.
</P>
<P>
   All true, by the way. Citizens for Tax Justice figures that just
15 per cent of the benefit from the core provision of the
legislation would go to low- and moderate-income couples earning
under $50,000 a year. They account for 45 percent of married
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of the benefit would go to the one-third of couples
earning better than $75,000 a year. And the payout would lavish
benefits even on the nearly one-half of couples who, thanks to
another tax code quirk, already get what amounts to a marriage
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   (Say this for the legislation. At least so-so and average
earners would benefit to a degree, which is more than you can say
for other GOP tax giveaways, most notoriously the inheritance tax
repeal, a boon only to our richest 2 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   The full-blown program -- more recently slightly moderated --
would open a sump that would drain $248 billion out of national
revenues over the next 10 years, compounding as time goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans rejected a proposal pitched by the White House and
congressional Democrats that would have limited benefits to couples
actually getting the short end now and would have targeted the
payouts more purposefully to mid-range incomes, with relatively
modest strain on revenues.
</P>
<P>
   But legislation that could pass White House muster _ and
independent analysis _ wouldn't give the GOP what it really is
after _ a chance for George W. Bush and Republican congressional
candidates to cast Democrats as anti-family and enemies of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, grandstanding, too, instead of haggling, Gore and
other Democratic candidates could denounce Republicans for enacting
legislation that, put another way, in fact uses tax policy to favor
the married and discriminate against young singles just starting
out and widow ladies.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but that wouldn't be fair, would it?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
