<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-SCHOOLS (San Francisco) _ New statewide test scores show
San Francisco-area charter schools generally doing no better than
traditional public schools at improving student performance. By
JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MORMON (San Francisco) _ The Mormon Church has backed off
its efforts to discipline a gay San Francisco man who sought to
resign his membership. A disciplinary hearing scheduled for Sunday
has been canceled, and Owen Edwards' request to have his name
stricken from church rolls has been granted, according to the
Mormon Church's Bay Area spokesman, Jay Pimentel. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DSL-MOVIES (San Antonio) _ Telecommunications giant SBC
Communications Inc. is gearing up to give its DSL subscribers fast
access not just to the Internet but to movies and games. By SANFORD
NOWLIN.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE-ROLLOUT (Undated) _ Steve Jobs has a new toy, and it looks
like a toaster. Apple's triumphant CEO, addressing the faithful at
the Macworld conference in New York on Wednesday, introduced a bevy
of new products, but it was the 8-inch Power Mac G4 Cube that
captured everyone's attention. By ALAN T. SARACEVIC.
</P>
<P>
   CAREERS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A recent survey by Hewitt
Associates underlines just how clueless a lot of workers are about
money, and how little Generation Xers have learned from the
mistakes of baby boomers. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONET-MUSEUM (Paris) _ Admirers of Impressionist painter Claude
Monet have a new mecca to visit here, a jewel of a museum
showcasing the world's largest collection of the master's work. The
elegant Marmottan-Claude Monet Museum has expanded, changed its
name and reopened with its entire Monet collection, much of which
had been in storage, on display. By ANTONIA KAPLAN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UNION-UNDERGROUND (San Antonio) _ The Union Underground has a
pretty good excuse for being inactive for several months. The
quartet was waiting on the release of its major-label debut album,
the Portrait/Columbia ``An Education in Rebellion,'' and rehearsing
for the ensuing near-endless tour of support. The wait is over. The
disc finally hit the streets Tuesday and is already making large
waves on rock radio. By JIM BEAL Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BIOTECH-FOODS (San Francisco) _ Environmentalists are grabbing
Kellogg's Tony the Tiger by the tail and scolding the Campbell's
soup kids in a new wave of activism against the spread of
genetically modified foods. A coalition of seven environmental and
consumer groups are leading a campaign to pressure the two food
giants to remove altered ingredients from their products sold in
the United States. By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   FRUIT-SMOOTHIES (Albany, N.Y.) _ In addition to ingredients such
as fruit and yogurt, smoothies may contain flavorings such as
vanilla extract, nutmeg, cinnamon and fruit-flavored liqueurs. If
you want to make your smoothie a meal, add protein sources such as
powdered milk, peanut butter or instant breakfast mix. By RUTH
FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   TEQUILA-PRICES (San Antonio) _ The taste of tequila is
distinctive, and its effects range from soothing to bewitching. But
what tequila drinkers are discovering is that its once relatively
moderate price has been shooting up. In San Antonio, where tequila
shots and margaritas are the preferred libation of many bar hoppers
and social drinkers, the price increase could force some to make
attitude adjustments. By DARYL BELL.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-RICKY-HENDERSON (Oakland, Calif.) _ Rickey Henderson watched
a third strike and just stood there, completely immobile, in his
tight little crouch, wordlessly stating his mind. The Oakland As
ran off the field, and still, Henderson didn't move. The Coliseum
crowd laughed. Even at 41, Rickey Henderson puts on a great show.
Even in another uniform, he is a vital part of Oakland baseball. By
GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS-NORTON (Stockton, Calif.) _ Ken Norton Jr. is quick
to put a handle on this year's San Francisco 49ers. ``We're a
bitter team,'' he said, referring to ``the embarrassment'' of last
year's 4-12 record and the preseason predictions the team could do
even worse this year. ``We're not accepting all the talk.'' By
BRUCE ADAMS.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Wichita Falls, Texas) _ In a sea _ really, more
like a mirage in the 100-degree heat _ of dropped passes in the
Dallas Cowboys' morning practice, No. 88 stepped in and saved the
moment, or at least more hand-wringing from the Dallas coaching
staff on the second day of training camp. No. 88 being new tight
end Jackie Harris, who snagged the number in the wake of Michael
Irvin's retirement. By BRENT ZWERNEMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Maybe it's a good thing evolution
is slow and can't keep up with technology. Otherwise humans would
be evolving into land octopuses. We'd be driving our cars using one
hand to dial a cell phone, another hand for personal grooming, two
hands to fiddle with the global positioning system and the stereo,
two hands to type e-mail and two more hands to handle the Whopper,
fries and Coke. We'd still be holding the wheel with our knees. By
ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Priests for Life, a group of
Catholic clerics, has launched a country-wide ad campaign to
convince voters to back candidates solely on the basis of their
position on abortion. They say they want to education the public
about abortion ``as it is.'' With all due respect, the public might
think twice about accepting 6,000 Roman Catholic priests' version
of ``abortion as it is.'' By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
