<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7556 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-CO     07-20 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Greasing up the old (and new) glove
 &HT;    For release, Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By HOWARD KLEINBERG
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kenny went out and bought his eight-year-old grandson a baseball
glove the other day. And now it was time to break it in, which
puzzled the child because most kids today just take their glove off
the store shelf and go straight to the field -- which is why the
ball bounces out of the glove so often.
</P>
<P>
   Anyhow, Kenny, who treks three miles with me each morning in an
effort to stave off overwhelming weight gain and joint lockup,
asked me if I remembered the kind of oil we used to grease our
gloves with when we were kids as he wanted to get some to break in
his grandson's new glove.
</P>
<P>
   This caused a great deal of thought. Even though I still carry a
baseball glove in the trunk of my car (you never know when a
grandson is going to honor you by asking for a game of catch) I
cannot recall the last time I oiled it, or if ever I did.
</P>
<P>
   My glove is a Fred Lynn model and he played in the major leagues
beginning in 1974. I don't believe he played into the '90s. Thus,
you know how long I've had that glove (with a beat-up baseball
jammed into its pocket and a strap wrapped around it to keep it
closed and formed.)
</P>
<P>
   So what was that oil we used to use as kids? Think more!
</P>
<P>
   My first glove was a Goose Goslin model. That ought to give away
my age, but it really doesn't. Goslin broke into the major leagues
in 1921 and played into 1935. But I didn't get the glove until the
1940s; it was used when I got it.
</P>
<P>
   Like other boys, I kept a bottle of that whatsit in my closet,
every once in a while taking it out and rubbing it firmly into the
pocket of the glove. Then I would pound it with a baseball until
the color of the pocket turned dark reddish-brown as opposed to the
lighter chestnut look of the rest of the glove.
</P>
<P>
   Don't kids rub oil into their d, or if ever I did it for them?
He said he didn't know and that his eight year old not only didn't
know that but also didn't know on which hand to put the glove.
</P>
<P>
   Make him put some oil on it, I told Kenny; maybe something like
WD-40 or Three-In-One oil or even Mazola oil. Soften up that
pocket, make it supple; the better to close your hand around ground
balls.
</P>
<P>
   No, Kenny insisted, he wanted the real McCoy -- whatever it is.
</P>
<P>
   The cartoonists show it as a light bulb flashing on over your
head, that sudden realization of what your brain was searching for.
Suddenly, the bulb over my head flashed on, a full 300 watts.
</P>
<P>
   Neatsfoot oil!
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't heard the word in years, hadn't uttered it. It just
came to me. This is not a sign of brilliance, or even high
intelligence. It's just a knack many of us have for remembering
things old while, conversely, not being able to recall what
happened just five minutes ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neatsfoot oil,'' I shouted to Kenny. ``Yes!,'' he exclaimed in
celebration, ``that's it, neatsfoot oil. Where would I get it?''
</P>
<P>
   So we started thinking again and decided that we used to get it
either from the corner hardware store or the drug store nearby.
</P>
<P>
   But, asked Kenny, what is neatsfoot oil? And so we thought again
but no light bulbs were forthcoming. Is it possible that the term
is in a dictionary? Well, yes it was.
</P>
<P>
   Neat's-foot oil, or neatsfoot oil (either way is OK) is a
``light yellow oil obtained by boiling the feet and shinbones of
cattle, used mainly as a dressing for leather.'' Aaaargh! I'm sorry
I looked it up; I thought it came out of the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Kenny hustled down to a hardware store and with
authority newly achieved asked for a small bottle of neatsfoot oil.
And they had it!
</P>
<P>
   Did you get some for me, I asked Kenny, thinking that perhaps my
glove drying out in car trunks lo these many years might need some
rejuvenation. No, he hadn't thought of that.
</P>
<P>
   It's just as well. Nobody's asked me to play catch for some time
now.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
