<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7576 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0721-CO     07-20 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    I still hear those waves crashing in Galveston
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ My first impression of Galveston was
literally a blur. I was 14 years old and there on a Scout trip.
Being terribly nearsighted and full of teen-age stupidity, I wore
my glasses into the surf so I would be able to see if I was about
to be bit by a jellyfish, or worse, a shark.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I wore black plastic-frame glasses that weren't in
style and which I terribly resented, my mother having made the
selection even though everyone knew wire-rims were the rage in
1969. Now, thick plastic frames are hip and wire-rims are passe, so
of course I still wear wire rims.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe losing my glasses was a Freudian slip, an unconscious
desire to rid myself of nerdiness. I was already three strikes
behind in the Pine Curtain, since:
</P>
<P>
   I was a Yankee still unable to lose the French-Canadian accent
of my forebears. I managed to accomplish this with great practice
by the next year and now draw quizzical glances from people when I
tell them I was born and raised in New Hampshire and lived there
until nearly 13. I have adapted. I can say ``as all-get-out'' like
a native.
</P>
<P>
   I was the shortest kid in Foster Junior High in Longview. That
may not be true, but it was my perception. Up in Live Free or Die
country, there are plenty of short Arcadians, so I didn't stick
out. Down here, I felt as if I had been transported into the land
of giants. It didn't take long for me to abandon all hope of
playing football or basketball, opting for baseball, swim team and
tennis, none of which I excelled at.
</P>
<P>
   I was a Catholic. In 1969, in Longview, being a Catholic was as
common as being, well, a Baptist in New Hampshire. The
Congregationalists were as exotic as denominations got in the
Granite State, and every little town had a parochial school, even
my hometown of Allenstown, which had at most 1,000 residents.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, with all this social pressure bearing down upon my
enraged teen hormones, is it any wonder I lost my glasses not 30
minutes after hitting the beach? Galveston was a romantic blur
whose focus has become sharper on return trips, but it's a town
that still appeals to me mightily. (This was well before one could
get eyeglasses grinded and delivered in an hour.) For us
red-landers, Galveston is a required summer vacation because it's
close, inexpensive, and the people and ambiance aren't much
different from what we're used to here. It's East Texas with sand
and salt water.
</P>
<P>
   There are better beaches in Texas, with blue water and sparkling
sand. South Padre, for example, and Corpus Christi. Galveston has
brown water, which we're used to here in East Texas, an
over-abundance of seaweed, and far too many trashy tourists who
leave their litter scattered along the shore. As I said, it bears a
similarity to home.
</P>
<P>
   There are coastal towns with more quaintness to them, such as
Port Aransas and High Island. But Galveston has a funkiness that's
hard to beat, with great food, cheap condos, the best micro-brewery
and hamburger joint in the state _ the Strand Brewery and Grill _
and one of the finest avenues in Texas _ Broadway _ with its
majestic homes, statues and palm trees. Plus, it's home to the
state's oldest existing newspaper _ still one of the best papers of
its size in Texas. There's no lack of news in Galveston given its
diverse population.
</P>
<P>
   Our standard stops:
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp 'N' Stuff, on Avenue O at about 39th street. Located in a
modest neighborhood in an ugly green building with asbestos siding,
the best fried shrimp in the city can be found here. This is the
place the locals are rumored to favor, though I can't confirm that.
All I know is that five fat shrimp with the trimmings cost about
$7. Five's plenty unless you're starving.
</P>
<P>
   The Strand, the restored historic town center. My favorite
attraction is the giant chessboard outside the brewery. I watched
two teen-agers play a game, moving pieces as tall as them, walking
among the bishops and knights to ponder their next move. 3-D chess.
There's hope in the world if kids still play chess instead of Doom.
</P>
<P>
   Mario's, a pizza place on Seawall Boulevard that plays oldies
music though most the cooks barely speak English. I always expect
``Godfather''-type music. Go figure. By the last day of vacation,
seafood has lost its luster, and it's time for some grease and
cheese. Mario's delivers.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Beach. It's crowded, the beach is strewn with the litter
of cretins, but you can get a decent hot dog and a shower, and the
people-watching can't be beat. Thankfully, alcohol is prohibited,
since many of your fellow tourists don't need additional stimulants
or depressants.
</P>
<P>
   There's a standing dream among us red-landers about moving to
Galveston upon retirement, and I always say, but where would you go
on vacation? Well, East Texas, of course. You could get away from
that annoying sand and salt-water breeze and still be somewhere the
rent's cheap, and the locals talk your language. Y'all come on up.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
