   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   OSTEOPOROSIS _ Two women share their struggles with
osteoporosis. We talk to a woman in her 70s who broke her hip as a
result of osteoporosis. The good news: the silent disease is
treatable and preventable. (Susman, Palm Beach Post). 40. WITH ART.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   EMMYS _ A review of the nominations for the 52 annual Primetime
Emmys. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEEKEND _ Phil Kloer's roundup of weekend TV options. (Kloer,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   STEELYDAN-FORMULA _ Call it the Steely Dan formula: a little
soul, a little substance, a little satire. And, of course, all that
jazz. For much of the '70s and early '80s, it was a sound that
defined a creative pop ideal. Even though the duo _ guitarist
Walter Becker, now 50, and keyboardist Donald Fagen, 52 _ had its
share of hits (Reeling in the Years, Do it Again, Peg, Rikki Don't
Lose That Number), this wasn't exactly music for the masses.
(Passy, Palm Beach Post). 45.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS AND REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-LOSER _ Movie review: ``Loser,'' comedy with Jason Biggs
and Mena Suvari. Grade: C-. (BLongino, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-BENEATH _ Movie review: ``What Lies Beneath''. Harrison
Ford and Michelle Pfeiffer in relationship thriller. Grade: B-.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-POKEMON _ Movie review: ``Pokemon the Movie 2000.''
Itwinning director of Forrest Gump concocts a reasonable facsimile
of the British master's. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-LOSER _ Either Billy Wilder is going to be very flattered
by the new teen romantic comedy Loser or he is going to have great
grounds for a plagiarism suit. Writer-director Amy Heckerling has
brought fresh qualities to teen films from Fast Times at Ridgemont
High to Clueless, but you would never confuse her for darkly
cynical satirist Wilder. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 30.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-TRIXIE _ Squint hard and you can almost see what Emily
Watson had in mind when she got involved in the painfully unfunny
``screwball film noir,'' Trixie. After stunning performances in
such sober social dramas as Angela's Ashes and Cradle Will Rock,
you'd yearn to break out into a brazenly comic role too. And it
sort of made sense for her to place her trust in director Alan
Rudolph, the resolutely offbeat filmmaker who has given
affectionate showcases to actresses from Geraldine Chaplin
(Remem-ber My Name) to Genevieve Bujold (Choose Me) to Julie
Christie (Afterglow). (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 35.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-POKEMON _ You would have thought one Pokemon movie would
have beenbe enough punishment for parents. Apparently not. The
forces behind this fad in all its many forms _ video game, TV
series and trading cards _ have made a sequel to last year's debut
Pokemon flick. It's as if they're trying to cash in before Pokemon
becomes another relic to add to the trash heap of kiddie culture.
Remember how hot those Beanie Babies once were? (Passy, Palm Beach
Post). 35.
</P>
