<HEADER>
A7583 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHARP-DRIVING0721-COX     07-20 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Electric cars aren't complete answer to cutting smog
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Recently I repeated a study that said consumers would
demand that a battery-powered electric vehicle be approximately
$28,000 less expensive than a comparable internal-combustion
vehicle before they would agree to own it. The survey was
sponsored, among others, by Toyota.
</P>
<P>
   Several readers questioned the findings, but I don't.
</P>
<P>
   One look at general sales trends of American auto buyers will
tell you that totally electric vehicles are facing a steep uphill
climb.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Mercedes-Benz, which is having a record sales year,
sells more M-Series sport-utility vehicles in this country than any
other of its models. General Motors says it expects the luxury
sport-utility market will maintain its momentum and grow an
additional 13 percent, all in spite of higher gas prices. In the
meantime, GM has virtually stopped making and leasing the only
mass-produced all-electric car, the EV1.
</P>
<P>
   The only reasonable alternative is the hybrid. Hybrids combine
gasoline and electric motors, resulting in mileage figures of more
than 60 miles per gallon. Only two are available, or will be soon,
the Toyota Prius and Honda Insight.
</P>
<P>
   The Prius is on the way, and it's selling like crazy in Japan.
Honda recently announced it will greatly increase the limited
number of Insights it sends to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent test drive, I found the Prius to be totally
``transparent'' with no discernible characteristics different from
a conventionally powered vehicle. And it had room for four people.
The Insight is a two-seater.
</P>
<P>
   When I drove GM's EVI, I was in constant fear of running out of
juice, and no charging facilities were available anywhere that I
needed to go. Yes, the vehicle had good power, but if I stepped
down hard on the throttle, the needle indicated that I had used up
almost 50 percent of its stored energy. Until battery technology
greatly improves, I can't see mainstream drivers adapting to
totally electric vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, research and development costs for alternative-fuel
vehicles are expensive for auto manufacturers. Those costs are
showing up on the bottom line consumers pay for their other
vehicles. It costs Toyota and Honda a lot more than the
$20,000-plus each they are charging to actually produce their
hybrids.
</P>
<P>
   Don't take this the wrong way. Electric and hybrid vehicles can
go a long way toward cleaning up the air. I spent three wonderful
weeks in the clean air of Iowa, South Dakota and Minnesota. But I
wonder if electricity is the only answer.
</P>
<P>
   How would we produce the power? Power companies also are being
blamed for contributing to air pollution problems, so how can they
meet the demand without producing additional pollution? Nuclear
power has its own problems, and coal or natural gas are limited
resources.
</P>
<P>
   The only plentiful alternative fuel is corn-based ethanol.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be ironic if after all the years that ``revenooers''
spent chasing North Georgians who were transporting a different
kind of corn alcohol that the government would mandate the use of
corn-based fuel?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
