<P>
   MOVIES-WHAT _ Gus Van Sant tried his hand at it. Brian De Palma
has practically built a career on it. So why shouldn't Robert
Zemeckis take a crack at making a thriller in the style of Alfred
Hitchcock? No one understood the psychology and mechanics of
suspense quite like Hitchcock, yet for much of What Lies Beneath _
a creepy little yarn of guilt, gullibility and ghosts _ the
Oscar-winning director of Forrest Gump concocts a reasonable
facsimile of the British master's. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-LOSER _ Either Billy Wilder is going to be very flattered
by the new teen romantic comedy Loser or he is going to have great
grounds for a plagiarism suit. Writer-director Amy Heckerling has
brought fresh qualities to teen films from Fast Times at Ridgemont
High to Clueless, but you would never confuse her for darkly
cynical satirist Wilder. (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 30.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-TRIXIE _ Squint hard and you can almost see what Emily
Watson had in mind when she got involved in the painfully unfunny
``screwball film noir,'' Trixie. After stunning performances in
such sober social dramas as Angela's Ashes and Cradle Will Rock,
you'd yearn to break out into a brazenly comic role too. And it
sort of made sense for her to place her trust in director Alan
Rudolph, the resolutely offbeat filmmaker who has given
affectionate showcases to actresses from Geraldine Chaplin
(Remem-ber My Name) to Genevieve Bujold (Choose Me) to Julie
Christie (Afterglow). (Erstein, Palm Beach Post). 35.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-POKEMON _ You would have thought one Pokemon movie would
have beenbe enough punishment for parents. Apparently not. The
forces behind this fad in all its many forms _ video game, TV
series and trading cards _ have made a sequel to last year's debut
Pokemon flick. It's as if they're trying to cash in before Pokemon
becomes another relic to add to the trash heap of kiddie culture.
Remember how hot those Beanie Babies once were? (Passy, Palm Beach
Post). 35.
</P>
