r l BC-PLANTWORKS0720-COX     07-20 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANTWORKS0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lantana is an annual or tender perennial in colder climates
 &HT;    By Diana Blowers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - The first time Lisa Johnson of Riverside saw
lantana, she nicknamed it the Fruit Loop plant ``because it had all
of the colors, and it smelled kind of fruity.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has had her multicolored lantana for about four years
and grows it as a perennial, although most experts consider the
plant, which also comes in solid colors, to be a tender perennial
best treated as an annual in our area.
</P>
<P>
   L. camara produces inch-wide clusters of small flowers with
contrasting eyes on upright, stiff stems in solid yellow, orange,
pink or white, as well as the multicolored variety that Johnson
grows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a gorgeous plant. It has nice deep-green leaves
and beautiful blooms,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although many gardeners love lantana's fragrance, others find
the smell offensive.
</P>
<P>
   In temperate climates, lantana is a popular deciduous shrub
growing to 3 to 4 feet tall. In tropical areas it can be invasive.
In colder climates, when grown as an annual, it is more likely to
grow to a height of 12 to 18 inches. Johnson also grows it as a
houseplant.
</P>
<P>
   Lantana grows wild in the tropics. It originated in Jamaica.
Several cultivars have been developed in recent years with various
colors of flowers. `New Gold' is a popular prolific bloomer with
golden-yellow flowers. `Dwarf Pink' has bright-pink blooms, and
`Irene' has deep-red blossoms. The blooms of `Radiation' blooms are
multicolored but mostly orange-red, and `Samantha' has cream and
yellow flowers with green-and-yellow foliage.
</P>
<P>
   The trailing lantana, L. montevidensis, has small clusters of
rosy lilac blooms with yellow centers. The trailing variety, which
also comes in white, has limber, cascading stems.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Midwest Gardener's Handbook,'' author Jan Riggenbach
recommends the `Patriot' series, which includes both mounding and
vining forms and comes in several color combinations of orange,
pink, red and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   Riggenbach recommends keeping lantana for several years by
digging it up in the fall, trimming back the roots and top to the
desired size and planting it in a pot, which should be placed in a
sunny window.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ``Time Life Plant Encyclopedia's'' Web site at
www.vg.com, lantana does best if it gets at least four hours of
direct sunlight and the soil is allowed to dry slightly between
waterings.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Diana Blowers by e-mail at dsb(at)donet.com.
</P>
<P>
   LANTANA
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Common name: Lantana, yellow sage, shrub verbena.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Genus: Lantana (lan-TAN-ah).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family: Verbenaceae (verbena family).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Plant type: Perennial shrub best treated as an annual.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Size: 1 to 3 feet tall and 1 to 3 feet wide.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bloom season: Summer into fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Color: Orange, pink, red, white, yellow and multicolored.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Light: Sun.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soil: Rich soil amended with compost or other organic
material.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pests: Rare.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Diseases: Rare.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Propagation: Nursery plants or seeds. Seeds need to be planted
12 weeks before last frost date because it takes seeds about six
weeks to germinate.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Uses: Beds, borders and as potted plants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Special note: Attracts butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
