<HEADER>
A7608 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-FRUIT-SMOOTHIES-HNS &LR;      07-20 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRUIT-SMOOTHIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FRUIT BLAST MAKES A SMOOTH TREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ It's not the fruit that makes a smoothie, it's
the milk. Or the yogurt. Or the ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Smoothies, by definition, are fruit blended with dairy products
to make a thick beverage, says Sharon Tyler Herbst in the ``Food
Lover's Companion.'' Fruit and juice mixed with ice is a slushy,
not a smoothie. Slushies are grainy and smoothies are, well,
smooth. Smoothies have the texture of a milkshake.
</P>
<P>
   You can tell something is more than just a passing fad when you
see stores devoted to the product in big shopping malls where the
real estate is expensive. Using that criteria, smoothies have gone
from a fad to a certified rage in recent years. But you don't have
to go to the mall to get a good smoothie. You can make them at home
fairly easily.
</P>
<P>
   There are two essential parts to every smoothie recipe:
</P>
<P>
   A base of milk, yogurt or ice cream: For smoothies with fewer
calories use skim milk, to make the smoothie thick, freeze the milk
in ice cube trays. For rich, decadent smoothies use ice cream. For
smoothies that are in between, use yogurt. Plain yogurt works fine
but to intensify the flavor of the smoothie, use a flavored yogurt
that will complement the fruit. For example, use strawberry or
banana yogurt in a strawberry smoothie.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit: Any combination of fresh, canned or frozen fruit can
be used. To make thick smoothies, freeze the fruit before blending.
To keep things easy, we cut our fruit into chunks and placed it in
a single layer in baking pans and froze. After making the
smoothies, any leftover fruit can be stored in freezer bags and
used as needed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the essentials, smoothies may contain flavorings
such as vanilla extract, nutmeg, cinnamon and fruit-flavored
liqueurs. If you want to make your smoothie a meal, add protein
sources such as powdered milk, peanut butter or instant breakfast
mix, suggests the American Dairy Association and the Dairy Council
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   As far as mixing the smoothies is concerned, the process is
simple: Put all the ingredients in a blender or food processor and
hit the button. Start with chilled ingredients and pour the
finished drink into chilled glasses to keep the smoothie cold
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with a straw.
</P>
<P>
   Some recipes:
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Blueberry Smoothie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   _ From Dole Foods
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) can crushed pineapple, drained
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe banana, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh or frozen blueberries
</P>
<P>
   Combine pineapple, banana, milk and blueberries in blender or
food processor. Cover; blend until thick and smooth. Serve
garnished with banana or mint.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Very Berry Smoothie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Grape juice accents the berry flavor in this terrific-tasting
drink.
</P>
<P>
   _ From http://www.epicurious.com.
</P>
<P>
   1 3/4 cups low-fat blueberry yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup grape juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups frozen blueberries
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen blackberries
</P>
<P>
   Combine yogurt and juice in blender. Add berries. Blend until
mixture is thick and smooth. Pour into glasses and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Grand Marnier Smoothie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   _ From http://www.epicurious.com.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup softened vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups fresh orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce (2 tablespoons) Grand Marnier, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly grated orange zest
</P>
<P>
   Orange slices
</P>
<P>
   In a blender, blend ice cream, orange juice, Grand Marnier and
zest until smooth but still thick. Pour mixture into 2 chilled
stemmed glasses and garnish with orange slices.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry Banana Sipper
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 servings
</P>
<P>
   _ From the American Dairy Council
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cold skim milk
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sliced fresh strawberries
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sliced banana
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Place all ingredients in a blender container; cover. Blend on
medium speed until smooth and frothy. Serve over ice in tall
glasses
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Sunrise Special
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   _ From the American Dairy Association and Dairy Council
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk or 1 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice concentrate
</P>
<P>
   1 banana, sliced and frozen
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons wheat germ
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   Place milk or yogurt in blender. Add wheat germ, orange juice
concentrate and honey. Add fruit and blend until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Peanut Butter Banana Blast
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   _ From the American Dairy Association and Dairy Council
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk or plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon powdered malt, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon natural peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1 large frozen banana, sliced
</P>
<P>
   Place milk or yogurt in blender. Add vanilla, cinnamon, malt,
peanut butter and banana. Blend until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Tropical Fruit Smoothie
</P>
<P>
   Makes 5 servings
</P>
<P>
   _ From the American Dairy Association and Dairy Council
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups lowfat milk
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe mango, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 large ripe papaya, peeled, seeded and shopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup guava nectar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   4 ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   In a blender jar, combine milk, fruit, guava nectar, honey and
ice. Process until smooth, scraping sides as necessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
