<SLUG> BC-CHARITY-THROUGH-WEB-PURCHASES-FAIRCHILD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITY BEGINS (AT) HOME  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of ``HIGH STYLE AND MORE.''
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 PLEASE NOTE: The word AT in parentheses has been used in the
headline of this story to indicate the symbol in an e-mail
address.  
 &HT;    
 By JESSICA KERWIN 
 From W magazine 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Too busy to make it to that $1,000-a-plate dinner, mail in a
donation or participate in an all-day walk-a-thon?
 &HT;    Now there's an easier way to save the world: by sitting at home
and shopping. In a rare convergence of corporate marketing and the
common good, a handful of new for-profit Web sites are leading
online shoppers to top Internet retailing sites, such as
amazon.com, cdnow.com and beautyjungle.com, then donating a portion
of each shopper's bill to a favorite charity.
 &HT;    Shoe fanatics will be happy to note that greatergood.com offers
a link to the Neiman Marcus site (among almost 100 e-commerce
sites), which means that there are two ways to buy Manolo Blahniks
without feeling guilty. One involves sitting in the store's shoe
department with your eyes shut while you sign the credit-card slip;
the other is to use greatergood.com's link to snap up a pair of
beaded mules for $545, of which a percentage (the site doesn't say
exactly how much) goes directly to a charity you specify. The
donation isn't tax deductible, but the karmic benefits alone make
it well worthwhile.
 &HT;    Likewise, once you've registered with iGive.com, ordering a new
Palm VII through iGo.com could send $37.43, or 7.5 percent of the
sale, to Habitat for Humanity. The possibilities are endless: Stock
up on Bliss products by linking to ibeauty.com, buy the new Elliot
Smith album at cdnow.com or bid on a vintage Pauline Trigere coat
at sothebys.amazon.com _ all in the name of philanthropy _ while
the retailer and the umbrella site absorb the cost of your
donation. For them, it's all about marketing.
 &HT;    ``We're an extremely effective way of gaining customers for
retailers,'' says Robert Grosshandler, president and founder of
iGive.com. ``An iGive customer tends to buy more often and buy
more, so they like sending us money.''
 &HT;    And it's not only the online marketeers getting in on the act.
Nonprofit organizations are quickly catching on and have begun to
use the Web themselves as a fund-raising tool.
 &HT;    Most major charities, including Doctors Without Borders
(dwb.org), Unicef (unicefusa.org) and the World Wildlife Foundation
(panda.org) have developed their own Web sites and accept online
credit-card tax-deductible donations directly.
 &HT;    Others, such as the National Audubon Society (audubon.org) and
Amnesty International (amnestyusa.org), have taken their
letter-writing campaigns digital. At redcross.org, you can even
download a stock-donation form to submit to your broker, while
helping.org offers lists of volunteer opportunities by zip code.
 &HT;    ``A lot of nonprofits are starting to take advantage of the ease
with which you can do auctions online as well,'' says Andrew
McInnes, director of special projects for amfAR (amfar.org). AmfAR
has used the method by auctioning the chance to attend its
star-studded Cinema Against AIDS benefit in Cannes on yahoo.com.
 &HT;    But to experience the power of Internet marketing at its most
beneficent, try making a contribution through thehungersite.org.
When you click a button, a pack of advertisements for the site's
sponsors pops up on your screen and 2 1/4 cups of rice are promised
to the United Nations World Food Program. Sort of like a
bike-a-thon, but easier.
 &HT;    Tony Hsieh and Alfred Lin, founders of the Internet
venture-capital firm Venture Frogs in San Francisco and of
charityfrogs.com, have taken a similar approach, pledging $1 to the
American Red Cross for each visitor's click of the site's ``ribbit
button'' until the sum totals $1 million.
 &HT;    A generous offer, to be sure, and one that separates the Frogs
from the dot-coms that might invest in a Super Bowl Sunday ad spot
instead.
 &HT;    ``It raises awareness for the Red Cross in a way that writing a
check just wouldn't,'' Hsieh says. ``But it also raises awareness
for our own company.'' c.2000 Fairchild Publications 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Jessica Kerwin is a writer for Fairchild Publications.)
