<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7625 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-LAZIO-FUNDRAISING-     07-20 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-FUNDRAISING-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO, LEADER ON HOUSING ISSUES, COLLECTS DONATIONS FROM INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 20 percent of the new single-family homes sold
annually in the United States are made in factories and installed
on site, ready-to-live-in realty born of assembly-line technology.
This industry is governed by an obscure series of regulations that
its lobbyists have long pressed Congress to overhaul. Now, the
industry is close to its goal, in large part because of Rep. Rick
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, the Republican candidate for Senate in New York, took up
the industry's cause in 1998, introducing a bill based on a
proposal that the lobbyists provided, industry executives say. He
has chaperoned the bill and subsequent versions since then,
sometimes over the objections of groups worried that the changes
would weaken consumer protections, and the House and Senate have
approved versions of the measure, with a compromise likely.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Lazio has been pursuing the industry's donations.
</P>
<P>
   He has collected more than $95,000 from industry executives and
political action committees, campaign records show. He began
receiving this money in 1995, soon after he let it be known that he
was considering sponsoring the bill, which would revamp
construction and safety standards for manufactured housing. He has
collected most of the donations since introducing the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at manufactured-housing companies across the nation
have responded to his entreaties, from Spirit Homes of Conway,
Ark., to Chateau Communities of Elizabeth, Colo., and Homes of
Merit of Lake City, Fla. Lazio has raised $12,550 alone from
companies in Indiana, a center of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been very aggressive and has had a lot of
fund-raisers,'' said Danny Ghorbani, president of a trade group
promoting the legislation, the Manufactured Housing Association for
Regulatory Reform, which notes that its factories have become
increasingly sophisticated, churning out homes that are sometimes
indistinguishable from those built from the ground up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot compare Mr. Lazio to the average congressman,''
Ghorbani said. ``Everybody involved with Congress has probably been
tapped for these aggressive fund-raisers by Mr. Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   Ghorbani added: ``I wouldn't say that it has anything to do with
the legislation. He is not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides said the donations from the industry were
unrelated to his decision to champion the legislation. Lazio
believes that outmoded regulations have hampered the industry,
preventing the creation of more inexpensive housing, the aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that Rick was fighting for affordable
housing, and manufactured homes are more affordable in many
instances than built homes,'' said Dan McLagan, a spokesman for the
Lazio campaign. ``Many first homes and homes for senior citizens
are frequently manufactured homes. This is serving populations that
often times find it difficult to afford housing.''
</P>
<P>
   It is perfectly legal to collect money from donors with
legislative interests, as long as there is no explicit promise of
official action for contributions.
</P>
<P>
   The contributions from the manufactured-housing industry help
illustrate why Lazio has been one of the most successful
fund-raisers in Congress: He has excelled at harvesting money from
donors with legislation before him, particularly those involved in
housing issues, according to an examination of his campaign
records.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is well positioned to do so. He is the only member to
serve on the Banking Committee and the Commerce Committee, both of
which are fertile ground for fund raising because they oversee many
wealthy industries. More important, he is chairman of the housing
subcommittee, so builders, real estate agents, mortgage lenders and
other housing interests often need his assent to get bills passed.
</P>
<P>
   Having raised so much money from these donors, Lazio is turning
to them again quickly because he is under considerable pressure to
collect money for his Senate campaign, given his late start in the
race against Hillary Rodham Clinton. In fact, soon after becoming a
candidate, Lazio named Lewis S. Ranieri, a pioneer in the mortgage
finance field who is one of his biggest contributors, as his
finance chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio declined to be interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   He is by no means alone in raising money from donors with
interests before him, though most members of Congress have
generally not been as successful. As of March, before he entered
the Senate race, Lazio had $3.5 million in his campaign account,
more money than any other House member. From 1995 through March,
Lazio raised an average of slightly more than $1 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick has been successful raising money from individuals across
the board,'' said McLagan, the Lazio campaign spokesman. ``He is a
housing chairman who actually understands the issues, and has a
well-documented passion for affordable housing. The people who
share that goal and share that passion support him. That's
democracy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Contributions from housing interests have not just flowed to
Lazio's official campaign committee. A political action committee
that he set up in 1995 in New York, which has more lenient donation
restrictions than the federal system, has also benefited.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1998, Lazio waged a fierce battle to defeat a
bill to expand a federal program that helps first-time home buyers
secure mortgages. The bill would have raised the limit on the size
of mortgages that the Federal Housing Administration guarantees by
33 percent to 163 percent, depending on the geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   The bill was opposed by private mortgage insurance companies,
which provide a similar service guaranteeing mortgages for people
who make low down payments or have shaky credit. The companies said
that the federal government was taking business away from them by
enlarging the program.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and Rep. Jim Leach of Iowa, chairman of the Banking
Committee, wrote a letter to the speaker at the time, Newt
Gingrich, saying that the bill would ``move us toward a
socialization of the financial mortgage markets'' and represented
``perhaps one of the greatest government expansions and intrusions
into the private sector since the Republicans have been in the
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats said at the time that they were puzzled by
Lazio's opposition, noting that the increase was intended to make
it easier for people to get FHA loans in expensive areas, including
his district on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, allied with some other Republicans, was able to scale
back the proposal before it passed in October 1998. The loan limit
increased by 16 percent to 26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a month later, on Nov. 2, just before Election Day,
Lazio's New York committee, Friends of Rick Lazio, received a total
of $23,500 from six of the largest private mortgage insurance
companies. The industry trade group, the Mortgage Insurance
Companies of America, coordinated the donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our contribution to him was our way of supporting him in all
the important work that he is doing that directly affects our
industry,'' said Glen Corso, a spokesman for one of the companies,
PMI Mortgage Insurance Co., which donated $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether there was a connection between the donations and
the fight over the loan limit, McLagan said, ``No, of course not.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has also collected sizable contributions from donors with
interests before the Commerce Committee, particularly Wall Street
and the broadcasting industry. Since joining the committee in 1997,
he has raised more than $50,000 from executives and PACs connected
to Citigroup, the financial services conglomerate that lobbied
heavily on legislation to modernize the industry, and more than
$43,000 from executives and PACs at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But at the heart of his fund-raising success has been the
housing industry.
</P>
<P>
   Take manufactured housing. For years, the industry has agitated
about a 1974 federal law that establishes construction and safety
standards. Company executives point out that the industry largely
built mobile homes back then, but these days their products are far
more advanced. ``The law was originally written for trailers and
mobile homes,'' said Edward J. Hussey, a prominent industry
executive who is vice president of Liberty Homes in Goshen, Ind.,
and has given Lazio $5,000 since 1996. ``We are now building homes
that go on foundations and look like any other house. We are
dealing not only with different building materials, but different
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest groups on all sides of the issue agree that the law is
obsolete, but consumer groups repeatedly complained that the
industry was trying to push through new regulations that would
water down consumer protections and essentially allow the industry
to regulate itself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, after being determinedly lobbied by the industry since
the Republicans gained control of Congress three years earlier,
Lazio introduced his bill, and one of the most influential groups
involved in the issue, AARP, which represents older Americans, said
the bill was unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Green, an AARP lobbyist, said the bill would have
established a committee to make regulations that would be dominated
by industry. The bill would have also scaled back the Department of
Housing and Urban Development's oversight of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had major reservations about the bill as it was originally
introduced,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time, donations from the industry were pouring in to
Lazio's campaign. In June 1998, Lazio collected nearly $13,000 from
executives of manufactured-housing companies. (AARP does not make
political donations.)
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations with some Democratic lawmakers, AARP and
other advocacy groups, Lazio agreed to modify the legislation,
reducing the industry's ability to control the rule-making
committee, which also includes consumer representatives. The 1998
bill passed the House overwhelmingly, only to stall in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio introduced the legislation again in February 1999, and it
underwent further changes in talks with opponents. In February and
March 1999, Lazio raised a total of nearly $22,000 from the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   In later negotiations, Lazio agreed to establish a process to
allow consumers to settle disputes with the manufacturers or the
companies that installed the housing. He wrapped the legislation
into a larger housing bill, and it has now passed the House. The
Senate approved a slightly different bill, which was sponsored by
Richard Shelby, the Alabama Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Several opponents of the original Lazio legislation, like AARP,
favor the changes in the House version, and no longer are fighting
the measure.
</P>
<P>
   McLagan, the Lazio campaign spokesman, said the original
legislation had been fair to both the industry and consumers,
explaining that Lazio believed that the federal Department of
Housing and Urban Development had not supervised the industry
properly. Housing agency officials disputed that criticism, saying
that Lazio was making the department a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   As for the donations, Hussey said they had not helped the
industry obtain special treatment. ``He is a very bright young man
and works very, very hard at what he does,'' Hussey said of Lazio.
``I think that he is a rising star, and that is why people are
contributing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
