<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7627 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-UNION-UNDERGROUND-HNS     07-20 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNION-UNDERGROUND-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     REBELS WITH A CAUSE: ROCK GROUP EMERGES FROM THE UNDERGROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM BEAL Jr.  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Union Underground's promotional photos are
enough to scare your grandma.
</P>
<P>
   With their piercings, tattoos and 2-foot-tall hair, the cats in
the Union Underground might even scare your daddy.
</P>
<P>
   In the flesh, though, in a Greek restaurant in broad daylight
and far away from the rock 'n' roll spotlight, the members of the
Union Underground _ San Antonio's best hope for crunching rock
success _ look just different enough from the civilian population
to make Grandma mutter something about kids these days.
</P>
<P>
   But on this particular late spring day three of the four Union
Underground members, Bryan Scott, 25, vocals, guitar; Patrick
Kennison, 26, guitar; and Josh Memolo, 25, drums (bassist John
Moyer, 24, was stuck in Austin) have larger concerns than
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been almost a year since our last gig,'' Memolo said,
looking like a man who just bit into a lemon. If looks can echo,
Kennison's and Scott's echoed Memolo's.
</P>
<P>
   The Union Underground had a pretty good excuse for being
inactive. The quartet was waiting on the release of its major-label
debut album, the Portrait/Columbia ``An Education in Rebellion,''
and rehearsing for the ensuing near-endless tour of support. The
wait is over. Though the release date changed several times, the
disc finally hit the streets Tuesday. The first single from
``Rebellion,'' ``Turn Me On `Mr. Deadman','' is already making
large waves on rock radio.
</P>
<P>
   So what sets the Union Underground apart from the herd of rock
bands?
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't wear (expletive) clown masks,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a DJ,'' Memolo added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a relentless attitude,'' Kennison said. ``It's never
enough and if it's worth doing it's worth overdoing until you can't
lift a finger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of aggressive stuff out there now but a lot of
it is a little too calculated,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   The roots of the Union Underground go back to a Scott/Kennison
middle school friendship. The band came together in '95. Memolo,
formerly with the band Ghodsonic, joined in '97. Moyer came on
board in '98.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the only guys we knew who wanted to do more than
headline the local clubs,'' Kennison said about teaming with Scott.
``We started recording our own tunes. To some people that might
have been backward. But we wanted to headline the local clubs and
the Alamodome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the only two guys not just in it to get laid and get
high,'' Scott added.
</P>
<P>
   When Kennison says the Union Underground has a relentless
attitude, he is not talking about some sort of tap dancing on the
rock 'n' roll lifestyle edge. He is talking about the band's
approach to doing business as well as making music.
</P>
<P>
   Before and after UU signed a recording contract, the band busted
its collective hump building a grass-roots following, passing out
handbills, putting together street teams to get the band's music
and stickers out around the country, writing songs, learning about
recording and producing those songs, and putting together an
impressive stage show.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to find four guys who do not (expletive) around,''
Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   The music on ``An Education in Rebellion'' is as straight-ahead
as rock gets in the '00s. There are no traces of rap-rock, no
overblown vocal gimmicks, no samples, no loops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always want to tell people our music is timeless,'' Kennison
said, ``and I know that's bold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything has its influences, but we're not metal,'' Scott
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we're not alternative,'' Memolo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't mind if people called us arena rock,'' Kennison
added.
</P>
<P>
   The trio went on to note what it thinks are the best three
albums of the past 15 years _ Metallica's ``Master of Puppets,''
Alice in Chains' ``Dirt'' and Guns N' Roses' ``Appetite for
Destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest compliment anyone could pay us is saying they like
the album top to bottom,'' Kennison said.
</P>
<P>
   So what about that album title, ``An Education in Rebellion''?
</P>
<P>
   ``It means going against the grain of the music business,''
Kennison said. ``It's about doing it yourself and teaching yourself
along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, regardless of the original meaning, people can
make it their own,'' Scott said. ``It's cool to let people get what
they want out of it. It sums up our lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Record labels release enough albums every year to boggle the
minds of even the most rabid music fan. Getting lost in the shuffle
is so common that it's amazing so many bands want to ante up for
the shuffle. Still, UU has expectations for its five-album deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten million copies sold,'' Kennison said with a deadpan
expression.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he added, leaning across the restaurant table, ``we've
never had that attitude in the past. We know what our songs should
be. We know what the show should be. That's the Union filtration
system. That's what we can control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're intent on building this into a long career,'' Memolo
said. ``We're not worried about sales, we're worried about the
second and third albums.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to writing and performing we have full
control,'' Scott said. ``But we don't have control over the disc
jockey in Akron. We can't worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest complaints from bands is once they sign a
deal the record label tries to change the sound, or the look, or
the songs. So far, Union Underground hasn't had that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Kennison were the lead producers on the disc. Most of
the recording was done in the quartet's studio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had half the record done before we had the deal,'' Scott
said. ``Then we tracked four or five new songs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we get off the first tour we'll have the second
album demoed,'' Memolo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every song we turned in after we signed the contract was
better than the song before,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there are no cover songs and no ballads,'' Kennison added
with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   While South Texas has long been a hotbed of rock 'n' roll music,
the interest has not translated into a slew of major-label music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about being from San Antonio?'' Scott asked
rhetorically. ``I'm going to be able to wear one of those
(Expletive) You I'm From Texas T-shirts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it helps the image of San Antonio to show people we're
not a bunch of redneck hillbillies,'' Memolo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People actually asked us if we could get to a fax machine,''
Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in New York and Los Angeles think image is so
important,'' Memolo added. ``We just do our thing. And we'll never
say we're from Austin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Union Underground is ready to get to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident,'' Kennison said. ``The Internet response has
been great. We're getting e-mail from around the world. We've also
distributed 200,000 sampler cassettes in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work hard and success isn't thrust upon you, you're
more ready,'' Memolo said. ``I believe the timing is right for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting signed is just the beginning,'' Kennison added, ``but
we have an album that can be listened to all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Jim Beal Jr. by e-mail at jbeal(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
