<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; tad-z
r w BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV23-C     07-20 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: IT'S PARTY TIME AGAIN
 &HT;    Moving in the Washington (w) and political (p) categories for
release Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The first time I attended a major national
political convention turns out also to be the last time the
delegates needed more then one ballot to decide on a nominee.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1956. The Democrats met at the Chicago stockyards,
tapping Adlai Stevenson of Illinois for a futile rematch against
President Dwight Eisenhower. As a copy boy for the old New York
Herald Tribune, I had a great seat as a final drama unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson decided to throw the vice-presidential nomination wide
open. In the ensuing free-for-all, Sen. Estes Kefauver of
Tennessee, Stevenson's bitter rival in 1952, beat an attractive new
political face, Sen. John F. Kennedy of Massachusetts, on the
second ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Says Reuven Frank, who produced NBC's pioneering gavel-to-gavel
coverage of the 1956 conventions: ``There are few who can still
recall _ and it is hard for the rest to recognize _ how important
and even exciting the conventions of (those) national political
parties were.''
</P>
<P>
   In their wake have come tightly scripted extravaganzas offering
what Frank calls ``ineffective windbaggery.'' But if these
gatherings have as died as news stories, the press stubbornly
refuses to bury them.
</P>
<P>
   Since the era of Huntley and Brinkley, whom Frank put together
in the NBC skybooth, wraparound convention coverage has been
relegated to the all-news cable channels. To bear witness as the
Republicans perform next week in Philadelphia, CNN alone plans to
send more than 500 people, including a slew of interns and Internet
mavens. Two weeks later, the parallel show opens among the
Democrats in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The audience for such political theater has thinned appreciably
since 1956, when Frank first sought to mine news out the
proceedings by sending four reporters with portable mikes onto the
convention floor.
</P>
<P>
   It's also being split among a half-dozen cable news outlets.
Coverage plans by the likes of CNN, Fox, MSNBC, PBS and C-SPAN
include perpetual Webcasts. They'll be competing for scarce
eyeballs with their over-the-air siblings and with a dozen or so
online-only outfits.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the convention handlers, who have alienated the
networks by depriving them of anything that even remotely smacks of
political warfare, will get into the news game themselves by
producing their own Webcasts.
</P>
<P>
   The old-line networks will make an appearance in both Philly and
L.A., if only a ghostly one.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the NBC peacock, which intends to skip the first two
nights, the Big Eye of ABC and ABC's Alphabet Soup are mounting
token efforts at coverage in the run-up to the sole ``must carry''
event: the major candidates' acceptance speeches.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, CBS finds noteworthy the remarks of retired Gen.
Colin Powell. ABC will dispatch Peter Jennings to cover the Monday
sessions of both conventions. On reflection, it scrapped plans to
use the halftime slots at preseason NFL football games and pushed
up their kickoff times by two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive is also in: MSNBC will solicit questions for its
online audience from Tom Brokaw and Tim Russert.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing up the rear, we in what the TV folks dub ``the pencil
press'' are coming in force as well. A good many will report on the
doings of media celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
