<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7641 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHICKEN-INSPECTIONS-0     07-20 1486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-INSPECTIONS-0723-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSPECTION EXPERIMENT FAILED TO CATCH DISEASED BIRDS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By ELLIOT JASPIN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ An experimental inspection program begun last fall
at an Alabama poultry processing plant passed along thousands of
pounds of chicken with tumors, pus, sores and scabs to unsuspecting
consumers, according to government records obtained by Cox
Newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   When problems at the Gold Kist plant in Guntersville, Ala.,
first came to light in February, Clinton administration officials
and the company said food leaving the plant was safe. And as
recently as last week, the Department of Agriculture announced its
experimental inspection program was a huge success.
</P>
<P>
   But inspection records from the plant that the government tried
to keep secret paint a picture of a plant unable to keep diseased
poultry from reaching the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Under the experimental program, company workers instead of
federal inspectors are supposed to find and remove substandard
poultry. But on some days last winter, the records show, company
workers failed to catch 25 percent of the diseased birds on one of
the plant's two production lines.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesperson for the Agriculture Department's Food Safety and
Inspection Service (FSIS), the agency responsible for the new
program, did not return repeated phone calls over several days.
Atlanta-based Gold Kist Inc. also would not comment on the federal
records.
</P>
<P>
   However, Delmer(cq) Jones, head of the union that represents
federal food safety inspectors, said he sees the experimental
program as an attempt by the government and industry to brainwash
consumers into believing it is OK to eat what he derisively termed
``wholesome diseased product.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unwholesome, adulterated product,'' Jones said, ``and it
is being allowed to go out to the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   The chickens are not considered a threat to human health because
poultry diseases cannot be transmitted to human beings. But federal
inspectors say diseased birds are supposed to be condemned because
they are not considered wholesome. Under the government's
definition, these include chickens with airsacculitis _ a common
respiratory disease that leaves pus inside the carcass _ or those
with tumors, sores, scabs or infections.
</P>
<P>
   Typically the Guntersville plant processes tens of thousands of
chickens a day. That means meat from thousands of diseased birds
will eventually reach consumers if even a small percentage of
poultry leaving the plant has tumors, infections or other diseases.
Chicken from the plant helps supply, among other customers, nuggets
for school lunch programs in 31 states, including Texas and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Following the company inspection, federal employees take several
samples of 10 birds every day to see how many defective carcasses
slip by. In addition to diseased birds, inspectors look for other
indications the birds are unwholesome, such as sores, bruises or
parts of the digestive tract clinging to the carcass.
</P>
<P>
   Copies of reports on these samples obtained by Cox Newspapers
through the Freedom of Information Act show that by the
government's own accounting methods, 40 percent of the samples
taken from October until the following February failed at least one
of these tests. The most common cause of failure was that a bird
was diseased.
</P>
<P>
   Under the experimental program, it is up to the company to
decide how it will improve its performance. But government
inspectors at Guntersville said the company did little, if
anything, to limit the number of diseased birds leaving the plant.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture Department officials initially refused to hand over
the test reports, saying that they were ``linked to the
deliberative process'' and if members of the public had access to
the information they might ``interpret the data and prejudge'' what
the government might do with its experimental program. After Cox
Newspapers threatened to take USDA to court, the government
reversed itself and handed over the data.
</P>
<P>
   Problems at the Guntersville plant became public last February
when food safety inspectors told Cox Newspapers that they were
unable to stop defective poultry from being shipped to consumers
because of the experimental inspection program.
</P>
<P>
   Five days after their allegations were published, Thomas J.
Billy, the head of FSIS, issued a press release saying, ``We have
no reason to believe product leaving these Gold Kist plants is
anything other than safe and wholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   However, records collected by Billy's staff show that on Dec.
22, 1999, and again on Dec. 28, federal inspectors found, after
taking several samples, that 25 percent of the birds passed by Gold
Kist employees on one of its production lines were diseased. In the
week prior to Billy's statement, the failure rate ranged from 10
percent to 16 percent during the night shift on one of the
processing lines.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Billy was not told about the tests before
he issued his press release or, if he was told, whether he thought
the failure rate was acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Food safety officials say even under the old system, in which
inspectors do a carcass-by-carcass inspection of birds after they
are slaughtered, some defective birds slip by. Prior to running the
experimental program, the government did a study that found
government inspectors missed diseased birds 1.3 percent of the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Anderson, a research economist for the Research Triangle
Institute (RTI), which conducted the study for the government, said
the figure was based on an analysis of inspections done by federal
employees at 16 plants _ including the Guntersville facility _ over
a 25-day period. Anderson said the institute did not provide the
government with figures on a plant-by-plant basis or the daily
failure rate.
</P>
<P>
   USDA hopes the experimental program will do no worse than the
error rate reported for the federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cox Newspapers analysis of the October-February
inspection reports found the failure rate among company inspectors
at the Guntersville plant was 4.3 percent _ more than triple the
rate of the baseline study.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the poor showing at the Guntersville plant detailed in
the federal records, FSIS issued a press release Monday that talked
about the program in glowing terms. Citing a recent RTI study that
monitored the program, Billy said defects in chickens being shipped
had been cut by 92 percent. Billy said, ``What this project is
about is getting closer to perfection.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the RTI study is from only seven of the 30 plants
involved in the experimental program. It could not be determined
from the information released by the government if the Guntersville
plant was among the seven surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   When problems at the Guntersville plant first came to light,
John Bekkers, head of Gold Kist, said the public was being ``misled
by a few union-activist'' USDA officials. However, company
officials later acknowledged to federal investigators that they
were having a problem with diseases ravaging the Gold Kist flocks,
according to a report by the Agriculture Department's Office of
Inspector General.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection reports also appear to confirm the accounts
several inspectors gave Cox Newspapers. They said that periodically
a flock would be delivered to the plant that had a large number of
diseased birds. When that occurred, company inspectors would be
overwhelmed.
</P>
<P>
   When Cox Newspapers graphed the number of diseased birds found
in samples taken by federal inspectors, it looked like the chart of
a feverish patient. Every few weeks the number of diseased birds
would spike to between 10 and 25 percent and then come down.
</P>
<P>
   Following the initial story on the Guntersville plant in
February, the OIG launched an investigation to, among other things,
determine if there were any violations of law or threat to public
health. However, the investigation was quickly completed after the
Government Accountability Project (GAP), a Washington-based public
interest group that protects whistle-blowers, questioned the
tactics of the OIG investigators. GAP said government investigators
were questioning federal food safety inspectors about their
contacts with a Cox Newspaper reporter, which GAP said violated the
Whistle-blower Protection Act.
</P>
<P>
   In its report on Guntersville, the OIG said there was a high
incidence of disease in the Gold Kist flocks being slaughtered at
the plant, but there was no violation of law or direct threat to
public health.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the experimental program was put in doubt earlier
this month when a federal appeals court ruled that the USDA could
not hand over its inspection tasks to company workers.
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Jaspin's e-mail addres is elliotj(at) coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
