</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (l and f coding)  
 BMW'S Z3 IS A VETERAN AMONG RISING TIDE OF DROP-TOPS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL   FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Time flies here in the world of autos.
</P>
<P>
   We are in the midst of a resurgence of drop-top sports cars,
touched off by Mazda's Miata well over a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Challengers followed in a trickle and then a torrent, but it
seems hard to believe the BMW Z3 is already a veteran bobbing on
that flood.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are with a 2000 Z3 2.3 roadster. The 2.3 (six cylinders,
2.5 liters) is not as powerful as the 2.8- and 3.2-liter versions _
a docile pup compared to the M Coupe _ but snappy nonetheless. It
is a far superior engine to the 1.9-liter, four-cylinder it
replaces. And, if you can do without the leather package, this is a
quality buy at $31,000. You can do a lot worse than this at that
price.
</P>
<P>
   The Z3 is a better-looking car than it was at introduction. It
still has the jutting-bully's-chin look up front, muscular and long
and humped. But the rear has been redesigned, given a rise and
flare that is far more pleasing to the eye than the chopped, low
box of the original.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the car you take for a comparison test if you are
considering a Porsche Boxster or a Honda S2000. If you want to get
into that league, you'll need the 3.2-liter for fair comparison.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're considering a Toyota MR2, Mazda Miata, or
Mitsubishi Eclipse Spyder, then stack this up against them. It may
cost a bit more but may be worth it.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it's as quick as most people want to travel.
</P>
<P>
   From start to 80 miles per hour is a sudden rush accompanied by
the subdued burble of the exhaust. Downshift from fifth to fourth
on the highway and you'll have at your disposal all the torque you
need for quick passing. It moves through traffic with precision.
</P>
<P>
   Take it on twisting back roads and you really get to play. Set
your inside front wheel on any curved line you want to follow and
it will stick to that line just as the M coupe performed _ as if
riding a rail.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.3 did not have the power of the M3 coupe I tested a year
ago, so it is hard to compare the body stiffness of the hardtop
with this roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say that, with this engine, body twist was negligent
and even the tightest turns did not seem to torque the body of the
roadster. Only on sudden bumps at higher speeds _ such as a joint
in the highway _ did I feel a shudder that might be attributed to
the 2.3 being a convertible.
</P>
<P>
   As for the five-speed manual transmission, the 2.3 used it all
and used it well. Dropping into third to set a course through a
corner gave a great sense of touch to the steering. Popping up into
fifth after passing someone and then moving back into the travel
lane was a smooth, gliding exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this, of course, can be attributed to the 2.3's Dynamic
Stability Control. If its control unit senses one of the rear drive
wheels spinning faster than the other, it cuts motor torque and
gently applies the brakes.
</P>
<P>
   Turn this option off and you move back a couple of decades to
when you could take a light, rear-wheel-drive car with some power
under the hood and induce oversteer with a quick jab at the gas
pedal. And that, too, can be fun.
</P>
<P>
   Be assured, however, that this is not a car you'd want to rely
on for ski trips to the north in winter, or even for your main mode
of transportation through snowy months.
</P>
<P>
   It sits too low to the ground and DSC in a rear-wheel-drive car,
I have learned, does not help much when you need to get up a snowy
slope or climb an icy patch. One Mercedes I tested, in fact, worked
better with its stability control system turned off.
</P>
<P>
   So picture this more as a nine-months-a-year car _ a car you
literally wear as you drive it. The fit is that tight once you are
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Its leather seats are slung low and wrap your thighs and
shoulders in support. Two long pockets up front give plenty of room
for the legs, though someone whose legs would fill those pockets
might find his or her head rubbing the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Ergonomically, it remains a bit retro _ silver trim to gauges,
an analog clock at center dash.
</P>
<P>
   Storage space inside is virtually nonexistent with shallow bins
on each door, and a center console with two cupholders and a
narrow, shallow bin that will hold a cellphone or a pair of
sunglasses, but not both.
</P>
<P>
   For trips, the trunk would hold two pieces of luggage of airline
carry-on size, so you would need to pack carefully. From my
experience, you'd expect to get about 20 miles per gallon on your
trip and you'd have to put up with louder than normal wind noise
from the closed convertible top.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the more expensive sports cars at the lower end
of the spectrum, but it is not so expensive that folks looking at
the others should not consider it. Its quality, performance, and
handling are pure BMW and the few extra dollars may well be worth
it to you.
</P>
<P>
   Nice touch:
</P>
<P>
   --The mesh net zipped between and behind the seats. It does a
great job of cutting airflow from the rear with the top down.
</P>
<P>
   Annoyance:
</P>
<P>
   --Operation of the convertible top. The button for the optional
automatic top is located at the back of the console and is hard to
find. When you do find it, you have to first unlatch the roof,
depress that button, hold a foot on the brake, and manually raise
the roof's first section a few inches before the automatic kicks
in. Way too complicated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Base price: $31,300 &QL; 
Price as tested: $35,570 &QL; 
Horsepower/Torque: 170/181 lb.-ft. &QL; 
Wheelbase/Overall length: 96.3 inches/159.4 inches &QL; 
Width/Height: 68.5 inches/50.9 inches &QL; 
Curb weight: 2,982 lbs. &QL; 
Seating: 2 passengers &QL; 
SOURCE: Manufacturer
</P>
</TEXT>
