<HEADER>
A7657 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-20 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL PLANTS AND NO FUN? TRY THIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people take gardening too seriously. We're afraid of
failure or wedded to a formula. We dig and we sweat and we worry
about the deer eating our shrubs or the borers killing our squash,
but most of all, we fret about how things look.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs we're lightening up, however. Garden catalogs
suddenly are full of funny little ornaments and sculptures, and
gardeners themselves are introducing brightly painted old furniture
and even silly signposts to garden plots once devoted purely to
plants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep adding more whimsical stuff to the catalog,'' says
Gardener's Supply spokeswoman Maree Gaetani. ``People have made
their gardens and they've reached the stage where they need to
decorate them. And they're willing to take more risks than they are
with interior decor. Also, people who have kids want their gardens
to be fun, child-friendly places. A little whimsy goes a long way
toward getting kids excited about gardening.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite an avalanche of humorous garden ornaments for sale these
days, however, writer Tovah Martin and photographer Richard Brown,
creators of the new book ``Garden Whimsy'' (Houghton Mifflin),
believe true whimsy cannot be mass produced.
</P>
<P>
   There is some high-end whimsy in their book, including unique
metal sculptures of a lumbering tortoise and a quartet of giant
frogs playing Dixieland at Les Quatre Vents, the Quebec estate of
Garden Conservancy founder Frank Cabot. There's also the ``ultimate
gazing ball,'' an 8-foot silver sphere that film director Rick
Levine made from polished metal for his garden in Kent, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, Martin and Brown feature creatively used found
objects, like the scarecrow on the cover, made from a classical
bust set on a stool in a Vermont vegetable garden, garbed in his
wife's pink chiffon prom dress. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Flamingos are out &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Whimsy can be hard to do because humor is hard to do,'' said
Martin. ``Nothing funny is going to last, and when it stops being
funny to you, it's time for it to go. I wanted to put photos of
lawn flamingos in the book, and Richard said we were too late. And
he was right. They're over. If it's been done before, don't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certain colors seem to lend instant whimsy, and they're not the
muted greens dominating Martha Stewart's line of exterior paints
for garden structures. The palette of garden gaiety tends to be
loud, fully saturated, and seldom found in the plant kingdom.
Flamingos may be out, but flamingo pink is in for garden
accessories, as are purple, chartreuse, scarlet, terra cotta, burnt
orange, and fuchsia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what it is with me and hot pink,'' says Michelle
Billings, who has used the color for lawn chairs and trellises in
her Ely, Vt., garden, where she sells bits of architectural debris
as well as flowers for garden ornamentation. Martin's neighbor
Peter Wooster bought a 1955 pickup truck because he fell in love
with its bright gold ``Velveeta'' hue. He now parks it near the day
lilies where it becomes part of his Roxbury, Conn., garden's color
theme. In New Hampshire, Alice Moir drenches birdhouses and benches
with royal blue paint to add that hard-to-grow color to her garden.
</P>
<P>
   Innovators are finding that structures painted such high
spirited hues help solve a problem well known to lovers of outdoor
color: Most gardens are mostly green most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Artist Robert Dash stimulated the growing interest in bravado
paint jobs at Madoo, his celebrated Long Island garden. Since the
late 1960s, he has been experimenting with painting doors, benches,
gates, arbors, and fences with colors that would make eyeballs
wince indoors, but that can be quite effective outdoors as framing
devices for the garden.
</P>
<P>
   Dash changes his tableaux throughout the year. As he relates in
his new book, ``Notes From Madoo; Making a Garden in the
Hamptons,'' one curved bedroom door opening to a long path gets
repainted according to the shades of the season: yellow in spring
when leaves are bright and new, dark blue as they mature, orange as
they detonate in autumn.
</P>
<P>
   Another artist who has influenced the whimsy trend is beloved
children's book illustrator Tasha Tudor, whose garden was
documented in the best-selling ``Tasha Tudor's Garden'' by Martin
and Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``She never used things as they were supposed to be used,'' says
Martin. ``For instance, she'd hang old farm implements in such a
way as to frame the view from a porch. That's part of the essence
of whimsy. Most of this stuff is already broken in and on its fifth
life.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wacky signs &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moir recycled an outhouse door (with the traditional half-moon
cutout) as a garden gate, says Martin, ``and my garden has old
industrial wheels in it as points of winter interest, and no one
can figure out what they were used for in their first life. These
are not things you're taking out insurance on.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin also likes wacky signs, such as the ones Kit and Marty
Sagendorf use to punctuate their property in Bridgewater, Conn. One
entry sports a sign advising ``Gratuities Appreciated,'' while
Qanother admonishes, ``Please Use Small Gate'' when, in fact, there
is no small gate. Such practical jokes come naturally to Kit, a
former cartoonist for Cosmopolitan magazine, and Marty, a physicist
whose father drew the comic strip ``Popeye.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin's favorite, however, is the Sagendorfs' mock signpost to
the weeds in their garden, with arrows pointing toward ``Ground
Elder,'' ``Nettles,'' and the ominous ``Something Very Nasty
Indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   The line between kitsch and whimsy is flimsy, warns Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your yard looks like a miniature golf course, you've gone
over the top,'' she says. ``But the whole point is not to worry
what others think and to have fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
