<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-PROFILE-ADAMS-ART-BOS     07-20 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-ADAMS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 PHOEBE-LOU ADAMS' ATLANTIC PASSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOMPSON, Conn. _ ``I think I'm a professional,'' Phoebe-Lou
Adams says. ``Give me the job, promise me the pay, and I will do it
as best I can.''
</P>
<P>
   For 55 years, Adams has practiced her professionalism at The
Atlantic Monthly, most visibly as the longtime proprietress of the
magazine's Brief Reviews column. The August column is her last: At
81, she's retiring.
</P>
<P>
   They just don't make careers like Adams's anymore _ or, for that
matter, people. ``There's just nobody else like her,'' says
Atlantic editor emeritus William Whitworth. ``She's just so smart
and sophisticated and witty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a complete sense of style,'' adds Atlantic poetry
editor Peter Davison, who likens Adams to Dorothy Parker and the
English novelist Ivy Compton-Burnett. ``She's always, as it were,
in position. She's always on the qui vive.''
</P>
<P>
   A woman taken on her own terms or not at all, Adams is in
appearance elegant, in manner superior, in expression tart. The
model she proposes for magazine journalism _ ``The idea is to get
to the point and don't fool around. Make it as amusing and
interesting as possible and, also, don't blow'' _ would seem to
double as a code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   Adams walks a little gingerly, the result of a recent
``collision with a friend's bathtub,'' as she puts it. Otherwise,
she wears her eight decades lightly. Her sparkling eyes and
dancing, slightly devilish brows could belong to one much younger.
She gave up salmon fishing only a little while ago, and her daily
ration of 1 1/2 packs of More Menthols she intends to give up not
at all.
</P>
<P>
   (When a visitor suggests Adams owes her distinctive contralto to
tobacco, she instead credits high school theatricals. ``We were
doing `Midsummer Night's Dream.' I had a helluva fine time playing
Bottom, but shouting through that donkey's head did it to my
voice.'')
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, is likely to confuse Adams with a superannuated
Tina Brown. She hails from an almost-vanished world and makes no
bones about it: a world of broad A's (it was a bahth-tub Adams
collided with) and ironclad discretion. When mention is made of her
18-year marriage to Edward Weeks, the editor of the Atlantic from
1938 to 1966, Adams gives a curt nod and says, ``That's nobody's
business.''
</P>
<P>
   By the account of others and on the evidence of the many
portraits of Weeks and memorabilia on display in Adams's house, it
was a deeply happy union for both parties, ended by his death in
1989. Nor was it in any way blemished by scandal (other than the
fact Weeks fell out of their canoe the first time they took it
fishing). She was single, he a widower, and, in Davison's words,
``it was very much a family affair.'' But in Phoebe-Lou Adams's
world some things aren't others' business, and marriage is one of
them, thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   It's the world of a Connecticut Yankee, as rectitudinous as that
of a Massachusetts Yankee, but perhaps harder-headed. Asked to
account for the difference, Adams says, ``I suppose what's behind
it is the fact Connecticut split off from Massachusetts because the
people didn't like the way things were done in Massachusetts. . . .
There's a sort of quiet cantankerousness, I think you might call
it, in Connecticut. Also, Massachusetts people are all such lousy
drivers.'' (On the last score, Adams speaks from experience: For 30
years, she made the 75-minute drive from Thompson to Boston, then
back again, each workday.)
</P>
<P>
   Her father, a machine-tool designer, came from around Thompson.
But it was near Hartford that he and his wife, another Connecticut
native, raised Adams and her sister (now deceased), in Warehouse
Point _ ``a farming town with a couple of gin mills,'' as she
fondly describes it.
</P>
<P>
   Adams attended a nearby private school, Chafee School (now
Loomis Chafee), and then majored in English at Radcliffe. Her first
job after graduation was running the library at a private mental
asylum in Hartford. ``We had to call the inmates `guests,' '' she
recalls. ``The place ran pretty heavily to very nice people who
were in there being dried out.'' In a preview of things to come,
her duties included writing book reviews for the asylum newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   Adams entered journalism in 1942, at The Hartford Courant, where
she spent three years as the self-described ``stupidest cub
reporter'' in the newsroom. She got to the Atlantic the same way
she got her low voice, via Chafee. A former headmistress had gone
on to become Weeks's secretary (a job change that speaks volumes
about the status back then of both women in general and that
magazine in particular). When the position of managing editor was
created, an assistant was needed. The former headmistress thought
of one of her alums.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd never had a managing editor before,'' Adams explains,
``and I'd never assisted an editor, so we had a fine time figuring
out what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   To Adams, the magazine whose staff she joined so long ago
doesn't differ all that much from the one whose staff she has just
departed. The Atlantic ``has changed very little,'' she says. ``It
is the world that has changed: new interests, new questions, more
relaxed tastes in some ways, and a great deal more niggling in
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Her view of the magazine mirrors her view of its home city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston? More tall buildings, more new buildings. Businesses
have shifted around, but the general tone of the place, so far as I
can see, hasn't changed. When I went to Radcliffe, they had
orientation for new students. We were told if you go shopping in
Boston you will get better service if you wear gloves and a hat.
Also, we were told never, on any account, go into Boston Common
alone after dark. Now that hasn't changed! I think it's always been
true: Even in the early days you could probably stumble over a
cow.''
</P>
<P>
   While reviewing has been Adams's best-known activity at the
magazine, her other duties have been extensive. She wrote numerous
travel pieces (a collection was published in 1964, ``A Rough Map of
Greece''). She did a stint as poetry editor (Dylan Thomas was among
the writers whose work she published). Weeks sent her to Havana
once to solicit stories from Hemingway (Adams got him to offer
two).
</P>
<P>
   One of her more unexpected editorial moments came when she
started to read a cover letter from a then-unknown writer
accompanying a short story he'd sent the magazine. ``I intend to _
I will _ become the greatest living American writer of the 20th
century. If you don't publish this story you will live to regret
it.'' Adams rolls her eyes at the memory. ``That's not the way to
win over an editor. Well, I started to read it and, somewhat to my
annoyance, it turned out to be a very fine story and we published
it. Who was he? James Jones, who went on to publish `From Here to
Eternity' and other fine stuff, though he didn't live up to his own
billing.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1952 that Adams began writing her brief reviews, five
to 10 per issue, and hasn't missed a month since. Whitworth marvels
at her achievement. ``I don't think many people realize how
difficult it is to write a really short review _ it's sometimes
just two or three sentences _ that manages to be funny and
informative and authoritative. It's a very difficult thing to pull
off, and she does it over and over and has for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams has passed judgment on some 4,000 books _ and that's not
counting all the ones ``I've half-read and ditched.'' Of the former
number, Adams says only a few loom large in memory: Kazantzakis's
``Zorba the Greek,'' Garcia Marquez's ``One Hundred Years of
Solitude,'' Borges's ``Ficciones,'' E. Annie Proulx's ``Accordion
Crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Without any more column deadlines, Adams intends to concentrate
on her garden, her watercolors, and her housemate, a ``surly,
inhospitable'' brindle cat named Spooky. Adams is in no hurry to
catch up on her reading. ``There are things I've never read that
I'd like to have a go at,'' she admits, ``but I have no plans. My
uncle had a full set of the works of Trollope. He had never read a
word of Trollope, and he always accounted for it by saying he was
saving Trollope for his old age. Lucky man, he never lived to
tackle Trollope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
