<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERTSON STEPHENS BUY A WINNER FOR FLEETBOSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN-SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It certainly seemed like a lot of dough at the time.
</P>
<P>
   You could hear and read the grumbling everywhere, including this
space, when BankBoston Corp. agreed to shell out $800 million for
high-tech investment banking firm Robertson Stephens in 1998. That
was nearly 50 percent more than what seller BankAmerica Corp. paid
for the same San Francisco firm just a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Dumb deal? At this point, it's proven to be anything but.
Robertson Stephens has already earned nearly $250 million for its
corporate parent, now FleetBoston Financial, and clearly exceeded
business expecations at the time of the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly in retrospect, the acquisition has contributed
greatly and the early criticism about the price being paid was
wrong,'' said analyst Gerard Cassidy of Tucker Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   The price itself is the subject of much corporate massaging.
FleetBoston reports that tax benefits and some staggered payments
reduce the real expense to $560 million. So far, Robertson Stephens
has already returned more than 44 percent on that sum.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions of investment banking firms, which underwrite
intial public offerings and advise clients on mergrers, by big
commercial banking companies like FleetBoston, were in vogue at the
time of the Robertson Stephens purchase.
</P>
<P>
   So far it appears to be one of the best of the bunch, though
Chase Manhattan Corp.'s acquisition of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist is
considered still too fresh for a fair comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts will tell you BankBoston picked a solid company and
managed tricky cultural issues well, at least so far. And then
there's the matter of timing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You buy a tech investment boutique just in front of the
biggest tech IPO boom in history,'' said Tom Theurkauf of Keefe,
Bruyette &AMP; Woods. ``It doesn't hurt to be a little lucky, too.''
</P>
<P>
   How does luck translate into actual business? At the time of the
purchase FleetBoston executives told analysts it forecast a
break-even year in 1999 based on revenues of $480 million. But
Robertson Stephens earned $99 million on revenues of $932 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were buying a good franchise and good people,
but we did not anticipate we'd have this incredible windfall with
their position in the market,'' said Charles Gifford, the
FleetBoston president who was running BankBoston at the time of the
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The first two quarters of this year have shown investors how the
Internet-heavy investment business at Robertson Stephens would
perform in deleriously good times and the darkest of the bad times.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens earned $122 million in the first quarter of
this year, more than all the company's profits of the previous
year, while technology stocks soared even higher and new issues
were hitting the market at a furious pace.
</P>
<P>
   All that action dried up for the next three months and the
company felt the pinch, but still earned $28 million on $293
million of revenues. Robertson Stephens fell down the quarter by
quarter rankings of most active investment bankers, but actual
profitability under dismal market conditions was just slightly
below earnings from the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The company's financial performance held up largely because it
gets less of its business from pure investment banking than you
might think.
</P>
<P>
   Just 36 percent of revenues are generated by corporate finance
work. Another 39 percent comes from brokerage activity and the rest
is produced from a list of other services led by merger and
acquisition advisory work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been growing a lot of different products and geographies
at the same time,'' said Robertson Stephens chief Robert Emery.
</P>
<P>
   One big growth area: the company's European operations, which
were launched a few years ago and will account for about $200
million of revenue this year, by Emery's estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens also made money by venturing further into the
risky end of high-tech stocks than many other firms. When Divine
InterVentures was advised to delay its IPO plans by Credit Suisse
First Boston, the company fired its bankers and replaced them with
Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   The stock offering hit the market July 12, led by Robertson
Stephens, but had been reduced by 40 percent. It was the investment
banking firm's first IPO since April.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the key for FleetBoston to continue to get the
most of its Robertson Stephens investment is to manage across two
drastically different corporate cultures.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford said FleetBoston wants Robertson Stephens to broaden its
areas of expertise to include more industries in the future.
``Sometimes their priorities don't mesh with what we think customer
priorities need to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Emery said his investment bankers have done that when it made
sense, extending into health care, real estate and other areas. ``I
would say we're working where it makes the most sense for our
clients and shareholders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Making so much money has a way of smoothing over the rough
spots.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
