<HEADLINE>
APPLE PRESENTS A TASTY NEW CROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You've probably already seen it on TV _ that vaguely
shocking white cube with a supercomputer inside, the most gorgeous
desktop machine that Apple Computer Inc. has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   When Apple CEO Steve Jobs waved his arm, and the computer was
rolled out onto the stage at MacWorld Expo Wednesday, there was a
sound in thousands of throats _ a cheer, a gasp, a groan of lust,
all mingled.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody else makes computers like this, and they waste their time
and money when they try. In the last couple of weeks, both Dell and
Compaq gave up on efforts to make stylish-looking home computers.
They realized that trying to beat Apple at that game is like trying
to out-talk Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs had much more to offer. There were small but necessary
improvements such as full-sized keyboards and a replacement for the
accursed hockey-puck mouse. There was the first dual-processor
Macintosh, allegedly twice as fast as the best Pentium PCs, and a
bunch of new iMacs with faster processors, bigger hard drives and
prettier colors.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jobs was done, you could feel the heat rolling off
the show floor in waves. Gone was the defensiveness and paranoia
sometimes found among Apple users. The people here are stoked with
a confidence I haven't seen at a Macworld in years. The decade of
exile is over, and Apple is once again in a position to take on the
world.
</P>
<P>
   They could be right. But if they are, it won't be due to all
this impressive hardware. As ever, Apple is being driven forward by
software. It's the code for these new Macs that could redefine
Apple's role in the computer business.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important product in the Apple stable, apart
from the iMac, is the iMovie video editing software. It turns the
iMac into the first plug-and-play desktop video system, letting
anybody create videos on the cheap.
</P>
<P>
   I fell in love with the program last year, after trying the
$1,499 iMac DV Special Edition. But now iMovie has been upgraded
with a host of new features at no extra cost. Meanwhile, you now
can get an iMovie-equipped iMac for $999, about the price of a good
camcorder. So you're in the movie business for $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1980s, when Apple introduced the world to desktop
publishing, laser printers alone cost $3,000, and the same again
for a Mac. Businesses snapped them up, anyway. Apple should have
little trouble persuading people to pay a third as much to make
their own professional-grade movies.
</P>
<P>
   You could do this sort of thing on a high-end Pentium almost as
well as on a Mac. But Apple will dominate this market with its
powerful, intuitive iMovie software.
</P>
<P>
   Even more important to Apple's future is a far more basic piece
of software _ the operating system itself.
</P>
<P>
   For years now, Microsoft Corp.'s Windows has been better than
the Mac OS in several important respects. It's simpler to run
multiple programs on a Windows machine, for one thing. And when one
Windows program goes down, I usually don't have to reboot the
computer altogether. But one bad program usually sends my entire
iMac into limbo.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's new operating system, Mac OS X, is supposed to fix all
this. It's running late; look for it early next year, the company
now says. But Apple has several machines here demonstrating the
beta, and it's hot. Running on one of the new dual-processor Power
Macs, OS X smoothly ran a couple of full-motion videos, some
real-time computer animations and an MP3 all at once _ the sort of
workload that would slow a typical PC to a crawl or crash it
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   I was even more impressed to see a terminal window where you
type text commands instead of clicking icons. And what commands!
Grep, top, kill _ all those old favorites from the arcane world of
Unix. Because the new Mac OS is built around a Unix kernel.
</P>
<P>
   Unix is vastly more stable than today's Mac OS, or Windows, for
that matter. Unix computers routinely run for years without a
reboot. If OS X lives up to that standard, Apple once again will
have a consumer operating system decisively better than
Microsoft's. I can imagine the billboards: ``It only crashes if you
drop it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Unix kernel means that a machine running OS X
will be able to run a great many Unix and Linux programs with
little or no modification. Mac users suddenly will have access to a
universe of new software. And with almost every major computer
company now writing Linux code, that universe is getting bigger by
the day.
</P>
<P>
   Cool hardware matters, of course. I learned that the hard way
when I foolishly predicted that the iMac would flop. I shook Jobs's
hand Wednesday and admitted I'd been wrong. He acknowledged the
apology with a winner's grace, saying the critics had just made his
people work all the harder.
</P>
<P>
   They're not just working on new ways to bend plastics, either.
The programmers are busy cramming value into Apple's multihued
polycarbonate, and their work will sell the next few million Macs.
Pretty packages and fast chips are all very well, but Apple is a
software company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
