<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATING A CAR BOOMERS WANT TO BABY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John E. Keilly, manager of a Ford Motor Company project that is
studying what kinds of vehicles baby boomers will want in the
future, is not a man to pull punches, even when assessing his own
company. Hard and honest assessments come with the job.
</P>
<P>
   So it is not surprising when he stands before members of the New
England Motor Press Association and says that, even as Ford has led
the pack in cutting-edge pickup truck sales, an ominous trend has
lurked in the other big part of what Ford sells: automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   In studies, Keilly says, Ford kept hearing, ``Ford trucks are
great, but their cars suck.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Ford's Leading Edge Boomer Project with a background
that included trucks, vans, and SUVs _ all popular with boomers in
recent years in a way that cars have not been.
</P>
<P>
   His task now? Analyze what Ford calls ``The revolution in
maturity.'
</P>
<P>
   The ``leading boomers,'' he says, were born between 1947 and
1955. ``Trailing boomers'' followed through 1965. Selling cars to
these combined groups is not the same as selling to a homogenized,
monolithic block.
</P>
<P>
   There are boomers who are now ``empty-nesters'' _ children gone,
they may not need that minivan or big SUV any longer. Some boomers
are having children late in life. Others are caring for their aging
parents. Others still are what Keilly calls ``boomerang catchers''
whose children, and perhaps grandchildren, have moved back in with
them.
</P>
<P>
   How to sell to this group that makes up 30 percent of the US
population?
</P>
<P>
   Don't just think cars, says Keilly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about trucks and cars,'' he says in seeming
contradiction. ``It's things like kitchens.''
</P>
<P>
   That has been a mantra at Ford ever since the day company head
Jac Nasser walked through the design department and told employees
he wanted them to know about American tastes in furniture, in
kitchen utensils.
</P>
<P>
   Keilly expands on this to say designers need to ask themselves
why the Big Bertha golf Club, for instance, sells so well. It is
all about an essence that goes beyond simply utilitarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want a product that everyone likes a little bit,''
he says. If you want to sell a car, it needs to attract a devoted
following.
</P>
<P>
   It is a phenomenon that appears to be enveloping the Ford Focus,
the compact yet roomy _ and inexpensive _ new model that is selling
not only to a targeted youth market but also to older buyers with
limited incomes.
</P>
<P>
   But as Keilly points out, a main reason boomers are
revolutionizing ``maturity'' is that they have a lot of money. And
women, in particular, he says, have more money than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoor magazines appeal to this daring and enabled generation
in ads that feature adventure vacations. Many may be, he says,
closer to their sixties than The Sixties, but they have not lost
their taste for experimentation, for causes, for daring.
</P>
<P>
   Which may be why Ford, as it seeks to boost its car lineup, can
offer as appealing and cutting edge _ though practical _ an auto as
the Focus, and at the same time have on the ramps its reborn
Thunderbird, coming back for the 2002 model year, or a souped-up
version of the Mustang, hot pony car of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the 2000 SVT Mustang Cobra R, with its muscular
looks, 385-horsepower engine, advanced suspension and top speed of
170 m.p.h.
</P>
<P>
   So as boomers age, and Ford works at one end of the spectrum to
attract new young buyers, it also must attempt to lure to its auto
lineup aging boomers, offering adventure and youthful appeal, even
while considering factors like vision, dexterity, mobility, and
weight.
</P>
<P>
   It is a balancing act, Keilly says, that means Ford designers
and marketers will have to look not just at meeting a budget in
producing a car, but also whether sticking to that budget will
affect customer devotion to any new model.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you've met your cost objective'' (in developing
and selling a new model), he says, ``doesn't mean the car has
succeeded.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
