<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-ROWING-THE-EAST-ART-B     07-20 1558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROWING-THE-EAST-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 FOR ONE ROWER, A REAL SCULL SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ When you consider that Nat Stone is rowing from
the Brooklyn Bridge to Eastport, Maine, consider first that he is
taking the long way _ the (itals)way(unitals) long way.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that he has almost finished ``rowing the circle,'' as
he puts it, meaning a roughly 6,000-mile navigation of the Eastern
United States that stretches northward along the Hudson River from
New York City, makes a westward turn into the New York State Barge
Canal, and then includes such watery biways as Chautauqua Lake, the
Mississippi River, the Louisiana bayous, the Intracoastal Waterway,
the Gulf of Mexico, the Straits of Florida, the Atlantic Ocean,
Cape Cod Bay, and _ early next week _ Boston Harbor.
</P>
<P>
   Consider especially that the 31-year-old former teacher has not,
despite what you might expect, been overwhelmed by the loneliness
of the long-distance rower. Instead, Stone, who more or less calls
Maine his home, has discovered an affable population of folks
who've not only been willing to offer him such necessities as a hot
shower and a cold beer, but have also invited him briefly into
their lives while trying to satisfy their curiosity about his.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask, `How can you spend so much time alone?' '' Stone
says after hauling his boat ashore for a one-day layover here. ``I
tell them I've been on the water for 240 days, and there's been
only one day that I didn't shake at least one hand.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the hands that Stone shook in Newport Harbor belongs to
David Stookey, editor/publisher of a newsletter called Open-Water
Rowing. Stookey allows that he's impressed by Stone's journey, not
so much as a physical feat _ rowers have crossed the Atlantic and
Pacific oceans, he points out _ but as a slow-moving window on a
variety of watery cultures. ``It's an intelligent traveler's way of
seeing the world,'' Stookey says.
</P>
<P>
   Stone grew up in Marblehead and annually summered with his
family in Maine. As a teenager, he sailed and rowed a small skiff
80 miles along the Maine coast. But it wasn't until shortly after
he graduated from Brown University in 1992, when he read a
biography of Howard Blackburn, a 19th century Gloucester fisherman
and later a long-distance sailor who failed at circumnavigating the
Eastern United States, that he became fascinated by the notion of
``rowing the circle.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of his college classmates were dutifully launching
button-down careers, Stone's adventurous and unconventional spirit
led him to the Zuni Indian Reservation in New Mexico, where he
taught school and founded a small newspaper. Still, he wanted
something more. So two years ago he returned to the Northeast to
begin his journey, despite having no experience or formal training
in sculling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was living a life that really didn't seem that memorable,''
he says. ``It's been great to be tested, to deal with changing
circumstances every day. And it's been great to be free of all the
little rules and regulations of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know why I like to be on the water so much,''
he muses. ``I just find it an amazing material to be on top of, and
with no median strip or traffic lights. And I'm mesmerized by the
wake of my own boat.''
</P>
<P>
   True, you could walk 6,000 miles and see the planet at about the
same leisurely speed, if from a slightly different perspective. But
when you're traveling in a 17-foot scull that's obviously outfitted
for something more than day fishing, people tend to become curious
about what you're doing. When they find out, they tend to become
excited. Like the jogger whom Stone encountered on April 24, 1999,
the very first day of his trip:
</P>
<P>
   ``What street is this?'' the rower hollered from the Harlem
River.
</P>
<P>
   ``110th Street! How far'r you going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bourbon Street!''
</P>
<P>
   Silence _ then a broad smile from the man on the riverbank,
accompanied by a fist punching the air.
</P>
<P>
   Such elicitations of amazement and encouragement have been
common. ``A rowboat is just unusual enough to surprise people,''
says Stone, his long suntanned face and dark eyes shaded by a white
canvas hat. ``They don't take it for granted. So it facilitates
conversation. It spurs curiosity.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone is an easy and charming conversationalist, a man who his
father, Boston lawyer John Stone, says ``has a facility to strike
up acquaintances.'' The two address books he has compiled during
his journey bulge with over 500 names. ``But I was expecting to
find camaraderie,'' he says. ``I mean, a major purpose of the trip
was to meet people along the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The folks whom Stone has met on the waterways have provided more
than opportunities for schmoozing. Whether it was handing over a
carton of powdered milk in Barataria, La., or offering a two-day
job as a caterer's assistant in New Orleans, strangers just seem to
want to help him. A couple in Mayville, N.Y., drove him in their
truck to a hot breakfast. A group of rowers near Pittsburgh gave
him the pair of lightweight oars he still uses. A couple in Cedar
Key, Fla., offered him their home to sleep in despite the fact they
would be away.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been constantly trusting,'' Stone says. ``I'll
find myself taking a shower in the home of someone whom I met only
a hour before. Or sitting at someone's dinner table, hearing his
life story and telling him mine. Despite the fact they're
constantly told to keep our doors locked, people are fundementally
trusting of other people. It's very heartening.''
</P>
<P>
   But there's been a disheartening side, too. Stone has seldom
been far enough from the engines of civilization to hear only the
sounds of birds overhead and water lapping against his boat. ``Even
in the most remote areas, I've rarely come across mechanical
silence,'' he says. ``Usually, if I've listened for it, I can hear
in the distance an airplane, or the engines of a towboat, or some
loudly accelerating car asking for attention.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking 100 days to row from the Brooklyn Bridge to the
Gulf of Mexico, Stone flew to Maine to work in his brother's
T-shirt screening business for six months and thereby earn more
money for the trip. (Total expenses excluding boats: about $1,500.)
He also purchased, for $2,200, a heftier craft for the ocean waters
ahead. He left Mississippi on Jan. 31 and hopes to reach the
northern coastal tip of Maine by Aug. 10. ``The circle'' was
officially closed when he rowed beneath the Brooklyn Bridge on June
29, but he kept going.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just become so content in this lifestyle,'' he says.
``It's so simple. The worst things that can happen to me are that
it's raining, I'm hungry, or I have no clean clothes. And it's
usually easy to solve those problems. Basically, my needs are food,
water, safety and good health. All the normal aspirations and
temptations of our culture have been removed. They have no weight
for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the trip hasn't made me feel that I don't want to
participate. It's provided perspective on what's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Some facts about Stone's stripped-down life:
</P>
<P>
   He carries about 70 pounds of gear. When not relying on the
kindness of strangers, he has either camped on islands or sandbars
or slept in his boat. When dining on board, he has lived largely on
peanut butter, jam, jelly, honey, saltines, and sardines. His
average speed on a calm day is about four-and-a-half statute miles
per hour. The longest distance he has covered in a single day is 78
miles, aided by the Mississippi's current. Usually he has been no
more than a mile from land. ``I'm on my third radio,'' he says.
``Two have been victims of salt.''
</P>
<P>
   Dangerous? Stone has not capsized or been swamped, not even by
5-foot waves off the coast of Mississippi. People told him the
Mississippi River would be a high-powered caldron of runaway
barges, poisonous snakes, and oversized mosquitoes. It wasn't. He
was warned that if he came ashore at Cairo, Ill., he would likely
be shot dead. On the contary, the captain of a tugboat docked at
the gritty river town invited him aboard to watch the Women's World
Cup soccer final on TV and to spend the night on a fold-out bed
(with washer and dryer!).
</P>
<P>
   To help pay his bills, Stone sold about four dozen $20
subscriptions to a carefully crafted if irregularly published
journal he has e-mailed from computers in public libraries. He also
uploaded photos to the Web (www.hometown.aol.com/rowingthecircle).
He talks enthusiastically of turning his journal into a book, and
warily of a possible trans-Atlantic row in the future.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not quite home yet. Boston, Cape Ann, and the craggy
coast of Maine lie ahead. As Stone rows diligently northward and
remembers the hundreds of people he's encountered, he'll probably
recall one Freddy Fisher, a lean rower and bicyle rider in his 70s
whom he met in Toronto, Ohio, about a year ago. Stone spent a few
hours with Fisher, talking about boats and travel and the older
man's experiences in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher also passed judgement on Stone's journey, telling him
what he already knew: ``You're doing the right thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
