<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-HOME-CERAMICS-BOS &LR;      07-20 1850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-CERAMICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLAY MASTER ERIC O'LEARY: MOLDED BY FAMILY TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MERIDEN, N.H. _ Eric O'Leary grew up in Old Sturbridge Village,
the famed central Massachusetts re-creation of early American life.
Between the ages of 5 and 10, he dressed in period costume and
lived with his parents and siblings over the potter's shop, where
his father worked as the resident ceramist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like living in a time warp,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The Old Sturbridge Village episode only confirms what he calls a
``destiny'' established at birth: a career in clay. His work is now
known nationally: a garden in Weston, Mass., another in Ohio, a
hospital in Pennsylvania, and, of course, the Museum of Fine Arts
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, now 50, was born in Alfred, N.Y., where his father was
attending Alfred University, which was and remains ``clay heaven,''
O'Leary says, ``whether it's for sculptural work or high-tech
industrial ceramics.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his office in the ramshackle complex of
middle-of-nowhere buildings where he works (an erstwhile New
Hampshire chicken farm his father bought in 1960) O'Leary opens a
box and pulls out a pot he made when he was 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole childhood was a process of three-dimensional drawing
in this wonderful plastic medium called clay.'' The vessel is
utterly of its era, the somber, brown-pot period of American clay.
Bulbous and striped in earth tones, the piece is also astonishingly
accomplished for a second-grader. On the other hand, O'Leary had
been throwing pots since the age of 5.
</P>
<P>
   In the four decades since, his pottery has taken on a timeless
quality and glazes so richly colored you want to eat them. Those
glazes drip down the sides of his signature garden benches and
planters, made of slabs of stoneware that can stay outside
year-round. The feathery strokes and torrents of color resemble
both abstract expressionist painting and Japanese calligraphy.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the benches have gotten longer, up to 4 feet, which has
given them an attenuated grace as well as increased seating
capacity. Two of the long benches are now parked in a gallery at
the MFA, a room otherwise filled with American modernist
masterpieces by the likes of Georgia O'Keeffe and Arthur Dove.
Museum director Malcolm Rogers had seen and was smitten by the
benches, and says he loves the ``interplay between two- and
three-dimensional forms now in that gallery.'' O'Leary also
recently added a playful egg cup, or hourglass-shaped, seat to his
repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   He works on an architectural scale as well, in projects
residential, public, and corporate. In partnership with landscape
architect Shinichiro Abe of ZEN Associates in Sudbury, Mass. (donor
of the MFA benches), he's done a Weston garden where his benches,
singly or in pairs, line up with an almost mystical precision along
a terrace of rectangular slates. This suburban haven mingles the
man-made and the natural, the grid and the meandering forms of
trees and rocks, in perfect, Japanese-inspired balance.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary has done mythic, figurative totems, including a ``Music
Tower'' that includes an entire orchestra among its population of
200 little clay people; remarkably comfortable ceramic chairs and
tables that clients use both indoors and out; an 18-foot-high
gateway that defines an Ohio garden; chunky ceramic and steel
benches for Donna Karan boutiques; fountains and lanterns that use
water and light to give the glazes extra sparkle and movement and
make them respond to changes in weather and season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's father, Jack, gave his New Hampshire studio the name
it still bears, Tariki, a Zen term his son translates as
``enlightenment through grace.'' It was not only clay techniques
but clay's spirit that Eric O'Leary inherited from his father. Jack
O'Leary died in 1982, but his philosophy still pervades the 8-acre
Meriden plot he bought because of its proximity to Dartmouth
College, where he taught in the 1960s after his Sturbridge Village
stint.
</P>
<P>
   The elder O'Leary was studying geochemical engineering at the
University of Michigan when he met one of Gandhi's associates and
made the decision to practice pacifism. He and his wife, Alice,
were working with troubled children in Philadelphia when World War
II broke out. A conscientious objector, he spent 6 1/2 years in
prison for his beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He practiced total noncooperation in his prison service,'' his
son says, a mixture of pride and awe in his voice. ``My father felt
that pacifism was an act of complete love. If you come to it with
less than that, you're part of the problem, not the solution.''
Eric O'Leary and his four siblings all became pacifists, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father's approach to life empowered his approach to clay,''
O'Leary says. ``I saw that on a daily basis. I didn't come to this
career casually. My parents struggled greatly to support five
children while my father worked as an artist. My commitment to a
creative life was eyes-wide-open.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, when his father was starting out as a ceramist,
``the American craft scene as we now know it didn't exist,''
O'Leary says. ``It was just pockets of people around the country
trying to reestablish traditions of design and working by hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The League of New Hampshire Craftsmen, with its promise of
marketing help and a support system, helped lure his father to that
state; O'Leary, too, has been active in the league.
</P>
<P>
   When his father started teaching at Dartmouth, O'Leary met other
artists on campus including such celebrated sculptors as Donald
Judd and George Rickey. The most influential encounter, though, was
with a Japanese living national treasure, the great ceramist
Fujiwara Yu, who came to Dartmouth for a residency, disapproved of
the college's primitive clay facilities, and ended up spending his
days working side by side with Jack O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job in high school was prepping clay for Mr. Fujiwara,''
O'Leary recalls, opening a large tome on the artist that includes
photographs of works labeled ``from his American period.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year at Vermont's Goddard College, a hotbed of education
innovation in the late '60s, O'Leary did what so many college
students did in that decade: He went to California.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father called one day and said, `If you're not too stoned,
get over to Peter Voulkos's studio,' which I did,'' he says.
Voulkos is one of the gods of American ceramics, famed for his
rugged vessels that look as if they erupted out of the earth.
``After I left his studio,'' O'Leary says, ``I thought, my own
family's studio is where I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   The prodigal returned to a lengthy father-son apprenticeship.
Both before and after his six-month California adventure, ``I spent
years doing traditional, functional, wheel-thrown ceramics with my
father,'' O'Leary says. ``I'd go to craft shows with him. It was
station wagons in fields then. There weren't galleries. Seeing it
all become so sophisticated over time has been astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   He's been part of that growing sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   ``After my father died, I decided to get out of the craft-show
world and see what I could do with furniture,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He'd already developed his now-classic benches, which made their
debut in 1971 when the American Dairy Association used them at a
convention for a most unsophisticated purpose: as milking stools.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   People's first thought on encountering O'Leary's ceramics is
often ``Japan.'' He's never been there, although that country's
ceramic traditions have profoundly influenced his work, in the
merging of functional and sculptural, indoors and out, in
simplicity of shape and spontaneity of surface design.
</P>
<P>
   He has also studied Japanese calligraphy, which piqued his
interest in two-dimensional work. He's made a series of wall tiles
akin to the lyrical abstract painting of Hans Hofmann or Helen
Frankenthaler.
</P>
<P>
   Other family members are also carrying on _ and extending _ the
clay tradition. Working with one of his brothers, Kevin, O'Leary
has developed a way to turn tiles into prints, by computer-scanning
them. O'Leary and his wife, Constance, have three children, the
youngest of whom, 10-year-old Kelly, is interested in carrying on
the family art form and actually helped with the figures in the
``Music Tower.''
</P>
<P>
   All along, he's continued the political work that ``has always
been an important aspect of my life,'' he says, ``whether it's
working against the Vietnam War or organizing organic-food
co-ops.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd been looking for a way to combine his expertise in clay and
his political work when he encounted the Connecticut-based Aid to
Artisans. Last year, he served as part of an ATA delegation to
Mexico, its mission to help local potters to stop using the
lead-based glazes that were, in effect, slowly killing them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mind-blowing,'' he says. ``Whole families are exposed
daily to lead. I talked to potter after potter who said, `I love
the sweet taste of lead.' They (itals)eat(unitals) it.''
</P>
<P>
   On one of his several trips to Mexico, a country he's fallen in
love with, in a particularly remote part of the north central
region, he found a vast, four-chambered wood-fired kiln the
Japanese had built 18 years ago. Part of a Japanese government
community development initiative, it had been long since abandoned.
He wants to get it going again.
</P>
<P>
   On his most recent visit to Mexico, earlier this year, he had to
walk three days to reach the traditional pottery village of Pio
Gordo, which, he says, ``is so isolated there's been little damage
from the drug wars. I went to another village where nearly all the
women potters' husbands had been killed by the drug cartels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How, as this outsider, do you help out?'' he wonders.
</P>
<P>
   One of his plans involves making a documentary video of a Pino
Gordo woman teaching her daughter to make the traditional coiled
pottery, and use the video to perpetuate and propagate the age-old
skill.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he's been hard at work on his biggest-ever
commission, for the main entrance of the Pinnacle Health System
hospital in Harrisburg, Pa. He's making what amounts to a mountain
range, a series of seven craggy stoneware peaks, up to 9 1/2 feet
tall, rising up from a reflecting pool. Their luminous colors
suggest semiprecious gems lurking in some complex geological
fantasy. Water will cascade through them. When the water is turned
off for winter, the pieces will be lit at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of the unforgiving `hardscape' of the hospital
buildings and the parking lot, I want to offer a place of respite
where patients' families can come and find a quiet bit of `wow!'
like you feel in nature,'' he says. ``Water is healing, both
visually and aurally. It flows to the lowest level and then
recycles into the air. That cyclical nature is like our lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The title of the piece,'' he says, ``is `Journey.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Tariki's Web site, which includes a price list and information on
commissioning work, is www.tariki.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
