<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7678 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-ISLANDS-BOS &LR;      07-20 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-ISLANDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKILL, OVERSHADOWED BY GENUFLECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
TEN THOUSAND ISLANDS 
By Randy Wayne White 
Putnam, 320 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Originality is almost impossible to achieve in crime fiction. By
its nature these days, the genre is self-referential, a kind of
endless _ and to fans, endlessly interesting _ variation on
predecessors. The trick for the good crime writer, then, is to
choose his or her models well and not be enslaved by them.
</P>
<P>
   These thoughts were provoked by Randy Wayne White's new
Florida-based novel, ``Ten Thousand Islands.'' It's the seventh in
his series featuring hard-boiled Doc Ford, a marine biologist and
sometime sleuth with a fast boat, quick hands, and a nose for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Once the exposition is laid out, the story about a long-dead
teenager and some ancient indigenous relics she uncovered is taut
and engrossing. Beautiful Dorothy Copeland was drawn to artifacts
fashioned by the Calusa people four centuries back, and among the
objects she found was a coveted gold medallion. Then Dorothy
herself was found dead, at 15, and her apparent suicide seemed
related to the mystical powers of the palm-sized chaguala. Now her
grave on Marco Island has been disturbed and her mother, Della, who
still owns a few of Dorothy's treasures, is in peril.
</P>
<P>
   White's a skilled writer and an especially gifted choreographer
of complicatedly violent action. The last 50 or so pages of ``Ten
Thousand Islands'' are as kinetically hair-raising as an Indiana
Jones spectacle. Technically, Doc's underwater contortions and his
climactic pursuit of the villains at 70 miles per hour in his
seagoing skiff are improbable. But White's clean, crackling prose
delivers the exciting, watery acrobatics with polished finesse.
</P>
<P>
   And the novel has some other, subtler virtues, notably its
interest in the history and anthropology of South Florida's
pre-Columbian Indians. The whole yarn is loosely based on a true
story, and White has sketched in some fascinating lore about a
sophisticated civilization that forcefully resisted the
Christianizing Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The primary mouthpiece for this information is nubile Nora
Chung, a precocious academic whom Doc allows to seduce him. Bear in
mind that he's given to dictums such as ``There is no such thing as
casual sex'' and other bits of terse and manly philosophy. ``In an
emergency situation,'' he pronounces, ``a man wants two things
covered: his testicles and his toes.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's pleasures far outweigh this macho silliness. But for
all his gifts, it's hard not to be distracted by White's conscious
debt to the late John D. MacDonald and his deservedly popular
Travis McGee novels. This is not the place to review the MacDonald
oeuvre, only to draw a few comparisons between his and White's
fictional world.
</P>
<P>
   McGee is a boat bum who lives on a houseboat he won in a card
game. He jogs to shake off hangovers and tone his tanned torso. His
best buddy is an eccentric intellectual named Meyer. The
investigations McGee and Meyer are drawn into often permit
MacDonald to reflect on Florida's environmental exploitation. Doc
Ford is a boat bum, too, and a marina habitue, though he lives on
Sanibel Island in a house on stilts. He jogs as a form of penance.
His sidekick, the brilliant and often chemically fueled Tomlinson,
is part Timothy Leary, part Columbo. And through his hero, White
too comments plaintively on the greedy destruction of Florida's
natural bounty.
</P>
<P>
   White would probably claim that these obvious parallels pay
homage to MacDonald without compromising his fictional voice or
cramping his imagination.
</P>
<P>
   I beg to differ.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the charm of much American crime fiction is the
configuration of serial characters. Think of Robert Parker's trio
of Spenser, Hawk, and Susan, and of the particular chemistry of
their interactions. It's one way to stamp some individuality on a
crime series.
</P>
<P>
   White's book, the only one in the series I've read, feels boxed
in by its identification with MacDonald's McGee novels. One of the
least welcome results, which may ironically stem from White's
effort to set Doc Ford apart from McGee, is a protagonist who seems
like a parody of his fictional forebear. Doc's laconic, tough-guy
worldliness borders on comedy _ unintentionally, as far as I can
tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten Thousand Islands'' left me wondering why White didn't
chart a more independent course to serve his obvious talent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
