<HEADLINE>
TV TURNS TO THE SISTERHOOD OF CAMELOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Another TV season, another network miniseries
about the Kennedys.
</P>
<P>
   The producers and stars of the newest one, NBC's ``Jackie,
Ethel, Joan: Women of Camelot,'' insisted Wednesday it will not be
exploitive _ a refrain that has become almost as familiar as the
subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   As the title suggests, the four-hour miniseries will differ from
films that have focused on the brothers: President John F. Kennedy,
Sen. Robert F. Kennedy, and Sen. Edward M. Kennedy. Instead, it
will be built around an aspect of the Kennedy story that executive
producer Sheri Singer says has been slighted, namely, the
``camaraderie and sisterhood that formed'' among the late
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, Ethel Kennedy, and Joan Bennett
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Singer indicated the miniseries, which is slated to air in the
election (and sweeps) month of November, will be an admiring
portrait of ``these three women who were so incredibly different
and would never have known each other under any other circumstances
and (were) thrown together in the most public way possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Women of Camelot,'' based on the book of the same name by J.
Randy Taraborrelli, will show ``how incredibly difficult it was for
these women to be married to these men at that point in time,''
said Singer. It will also, she said, chronicle ``how they were
there for each other'' during the ``unbelievable string of
tragedies'' they endured.
</P>
<P>
   Those tragedies, of course, included the assassinations of John
and Robert Kennedy. The miniseries, set from 1960 to 1980, will
apparently also touch on the Kennedys' marital troubles, along with
such events as the 1969 accident at Chappaquiddick that claimed the
life of Mary Jo Kopechne, a passenger in a car driven by Edward
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   It is territory that has been covered ad infinitum, but, Singer
said, ``There seems to be an endless curiosity in this country
about this family.'' The miniseries is being filmed in Toronto.
``We are building Hyannis Port on an empty strip of beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Hennessy, best known for her role in ``Law &AMP; Order'' from
1993 to 1996, plays Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis. Hennessy said
Wednesday that to prepare for the role, she watched hours of
documentary footage of Onassis, especially during the White House
years, 1960 to 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Holly, best known for the film ``Dumb and Dumber,'' plays
Ethel Kennedy. Holly said she was impressed by her character's
``moxie'': ``She was incredibly spirited, a little brash,
ambitious, and so dedicated to that family.'' The actress said she
has not met Ethel Kennedy, called the prospect ``sort of
frightening.'' Leslie Stefanson, who will portray Joan Bennett
Kennedy, was not present as the other stars addressed TV critics
here.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Joan Bennett Kennedy nor Ethel Kennedy have any
involvement with the film, and producers have no plans to screen it
for them before it airs.
</P>
<P>
   Singer said, ``I hope they'll be pleased'' by the latest TV
treatment of their lives. But, she added, ``It's possible they wish
there would never be another thing done on them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
