<HEADLINE>
TEENS ARE THE TARGET IN FORMULAIC, FUN `IN CROWD' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE IN CROWD 
Directed by: Mary Lambert 
Screenplay by: Mark Gibson and Philip Halprin 
Starring: Susan Ward, Lori Heuringcq, Matthew Settle, Nathan
Bexton, Tess Harper 
Running Time: 100 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 
2 1/2 stars 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A far cry from zombie-strewn ``Pet Sematary,'' director Mary
Lambert's claim to fame, ``The In Crowd'' is a J. Crew ad gone
very, very wrong. The clothes are terrific, the beach is a gas, but
there's something sinister afoot that even a perfect tan can't
conceal.
</P>
<P>
   As formulaic, teen-targeted thrillers go, ``The In Crowd'' is
entirely harmless and, on occasion, genuinely amusing. All the key
features of the genre are intact: first and foremost, the cast
numbers many beautiful and scantily clad young people. Archetypal
characters abound, such as the evil clique leader, her passive
sidekick, a clueless hunk, and the innocent victim. The arc of the
story is nothing if not reliable _ the characters meet, greet, and
drop clues that all might not be as well as it seems; tension
builds; chaos quickly ensues; and justice, finally, is done.
</P>
<P>
   What this films shares with ``Pet Sematary'' is a dearth of
suspense, which normally would be a strike against a thriller.
There will be no gripping of armrests or peeking through fingers.
But in an era where raunchy, violent films are routinely earning
PG-13 ratings to allow the lucrative teen market in the theater
door, the mild-mannered nature of this movie is actually
refreshing. And although it isn't a nail-biter, the film generates
enough interest in discovering the truth that one dutifully follows
the trail of crumbs to the shallow grave.
</P>
<P>
   While hardly distinguishing themselves as stars-in-the-making,
Lori Heuring as Adrien Williams and Susan Ward as Brittany Foster
bring a natural ease to their roles. Gorgeous blonde Adrien,
recently released from psychiatric lock-up, is reentering society
via a service job at a posh country club. (In the effort to
approximate a normal life, this is her first big mistake.) Gorgeous
brunette Brittany is the highest-ranking brat among the club's
trust-fund kids, whose parents buy them Hummers as a reward for
making it through rehab. Under the auspices of filling her endless
summer days with something other than sunbathing and cocktails,
Brittany befriends Adrien.
</P>
<P>
   Things start to go south when tennis pro Matt Curtis (Matthew
Steele), the object of Brittany's affection, takes an interest in
Adrien. As the film's slogan goes _ ``sometimes being popular can
be murder'' _ the bodies begin stacking up. The film's other slogan
_ ``what would you do to get in?'' _ becomes, needless to say,
extravagently ironic as the focus quickly becomes what Adrien can
possibly do to get out. Several lethal plot twists, evil frame
jobs, and impossible escapes later . . . well, we can't really say
what happens. Rest assured, the moral universe remains unsullied in
this lite, lo-cal thriller _ the cinematic equivalent of a fizzy
summer drink.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
