<HEADER>
A7683 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-20 1725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VACATION'S BEST DISCOVERIES CAN BE OUR KIDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever gone on a family vacation expecting to make
discoveries about the place you're going, only to return home full
of discoveries about your children?
</P>
<P>
   When we're away together as families, we tend to see aspects of
our children we hadn't before. The question is, are children
different on vacation or does our perception of them alter?
</P>
<P>
   Intrinsic personality traits, theirs or yours, don't change.
Interpersonal dynamics, on the other hand, do. ``When we're not
distracted by responsibilities, our focus on our kids is sharper,''
says parent educator Linda Braun, executive director of Families
First Parenting Education Programs of Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much that we're paying more attention as it is a
different kind of attention. Kids feel that, and they thrive on
it,'' she says. ``It's why vacation is a relationship-building
time. It can be transforming.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfettered time is so vital to family life that Braun urges
parents who can't go away to take a vacation at home. ``It doesn't
matter what you do,'' she says. ``The point is to change the
pattern of your daily life. Turn off the phone and e-mail and do
fun things together. Things you don't normally do.''
</P>
<P>
   What this time together changes is a child's sense of security,
says psychologist Christine Wekerle. Not that your children are
necessarily normally insecure, she's quick to add. Rather, she
says, ``There's a different level of safety for them, knowing you
are available whenever they want.''
</P>
<P>
   That translates to an unconscious, heightened sense of freedom,
which often leads a child to a developmental milestone, such as
taking a first step or mastering toileting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dynamic on vacation breaks up the stuck place he was in at
home,'' says Braun. ``It could be emotional _ you're more relaxed
so he is, too _ or situational: He isn't afraid to sleep in a
big-boy bed because, in the beach house, your bedroom is right next
to his, or in a motel, you're all in one room.''
</P>
<P>
   On their family vacation last year, Wekerle's middle son, Colin,
then 7, conquered his fear of the ocean, going body surfing and
deep-sea fishing, where land wasn't even in sight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an incredible blossoming,'' says Wekerle, who was
pleasantly surprised to see such determination in her son. It
didn't go disappear with vacation, either. She's convinced the
increase in initiative that teachers saw in him in September was
spill-over from how good he felt about himself for mastering his
fear.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics could argue it was a matter of timing: Colin was simply
ready to make a developmenal leap. That's part of it, sure, but
psychologist Sanford Portnoy tells parents not to underestimate the
magic of family vacation time.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a kid's perspective, you're not just more available,
you're also more fun,'' he says. ``Plus, when you're on vacation
together, you're all sharing the same new experiences.'' That not
only strengthens your connections to each other as a unit, but also
provides the peephole to see your children in new ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be open to it, though,'' Portnoy cautions.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the Lincoln Memorial in Washington when children Katie
and Dave, now 26 and 24, were 4 and 2, Portnoy read aloud from the
Gettysburg Address on the wall. The kids weren't paying any
attention, however: The pigeon they spotted on Lincoln's head was
far more interesting. In another city when they were older, Portnoy
and wife, Joan, marveled aloud at the architecture. That, too, was
lost on Katie and Dave. Their eyes were on the ground. They had
spotted some bugs they had never seen before.
</P>
<P>
   In situations like this, it's easy to be frustrated or angry
that children aren't paying attention to your would-be lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Get over it, advises Portnoy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids don't see the same thing we do, even when we're looking
at the same thing. That's delightful in its own way,'' he says.
Portnoy is president of the Massachusetts Psychological Association
and coauthor, with his wife, of ``How to Take Great Trips With Your
Kids, Revised Edition'' (Harvard Common Press).
</P>
<P>
   ``The best advice is to let them experience things in their own
way,'' he says. Indeed, the less we push children to be on our
agenda, the more fun everyone will have.
</P>
<P>
   Another scene flashes before Portnoy's eyes. They are in Cork,
Ireland, and Dave is 5. They have just had apple pie for dessert,
except in Ireland, it's called apple tart. When they get back to
their room, Dave picks up a coloring book. The instructions on one
page are to circle the apple pie. ``You mean apple tart,'' Dave
says aloud to the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small thing,'' muses Portnoy, ``but I remember it still
because it was a moment of discovery for me about my son.'' His
5-year-old, he realized, was very adaptable and very funny.
</P>
<P>
   Being on your children's agenda doesn't mean abdicating to their
every whim; that will leave you feeling cheated. It does mean,
however, that you anticipate their needs.
</P>
<P>
   Younger children as well as older ones who are sensitive to
change can suffer from lack of familiar routines, says parent
educator Deb Kratz, coauthor of ``The Field Guide to Parenting''
(Chandler House).
</P>
<P>
   Her advice is to work around the youngest child's schedule. ``If
he's cranky because he doesn't nap or because it's two hours past
his dinnertime, everyone else will be miserable, too. What's the
point?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a young child is excited to go and even if he's traveled
before, there's still stress involved. ``Kids who whine, `I want to
go home,' are either telling you, `I'm having a hard time making
this transition,' or they're wondering, `Will I ever get home
again?' '' says Wekerle. She recommends validating and labeling
feelings _ ``I bet you're missing your very own bed, huh?'' _ and
answering the unspoken question: ``You know, we will go home again,
but not for five more days.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as adults have expectations for vacation, so do children, a
point Braun says parents tend to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get everyone's hopes and wishes out on the table before you
go,'' she says. To avoid having a cranky adult along (and let's
face it, a cranky adult can run a vacation as quickly as a cranky
child!), share expectations with your spouse first, including
clarifying whether either of you expects to spend time on work,
then solicit your children's. In Wekerle's family, there are five
children, so lists can get long. She tells the four who are old
enough to write to star their top two items with the promise that
she and her husband will do all they can to accommodate those,
especially if the same wish is on more than one list. That often
leads to sibling collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   For children of any age, including most teenagers, the most
common expectation is for uninterrupted time with you. ``Let them
know beforehand if/how much adult-only time there will be, so they
won't be disappointed,'' suggests Wekerle.
</P>
<P>
   When vacation involves a reunion with extended family,
sociologist Larry Basirico of Elon College in North Carolina urges
negotiating beforehand with your siblings and parents how you will
all handle a range of issues, from children's bedtimes to
between-meal snacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There tends to be more tension for parents on reunion
vacations, because each adult sibling is caught between the culture
of the family of origin and the culture of the new family you've
created, and that tension gets translated to the kids,'' he says.
Planning ahead may be a pain, he admits, but it reduces stress on
the vacation.
</P>
<P>
   More that where you are and what you do, it's your mellow affect
and spontaneity that children remember about vacation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're taking a walk on the beach and you tell a story about
how you used to paint shells when you were young, and the next
thing you know, you're going with the idea, picking shells and
buying paint. How often at home do you just drop everything and go
with an idea?'' asks Braun. ``That's what vacation is all about:
Less shoulds and more coulds.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of that is when you'll make discoveries about
your children, and when your children will make discoveries about
you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
VACATION TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Young children are prone to accidents when they are in new and
unfamiliar places, according to the American Academy of Pediatrics.
Be even more vigilant than you are at home about child-proofing and
safety precautions.
</P>
<P>
   --Before going away, talk about what will stay the same and what
will change: ``Bedtime will be later, but you still have to brush
your teeth; you can have snacks between meals, but ice cream only
once a day.'' Also be clear about vacation rules that differ from
rules at home. Two good ones: ``Always tell an adult if you want to
leave our group'' (for instance, on the beach); ``We have to hold
hands at the airport and in any crowded place.''
</P>
<P>
   --Parent educator Linda Braun thinks of the beach as therapeutic
for kids: The wide-open expanse and natural boundaries give them a
sense of independence because they don't feel under constant adult
scrutiny. Sand and water play allows for large and small motor
development, and they get to try out new social skills if they make
new playmates.
</P>
<P>
   --When a child brings a friend along, it changes family
dynamics. Allow for some time alone, just the family.
</P>
<P>
   --Build time into every day for physical activity. If you're
traveling by car, don't just make pit stops for the restroom, but
also to do jumping jacks together or play a game of tag.
</P>
<P>
   --A child who melts down over something really small, especially
an older child for whom such behavior is out of character, is
telling you, ``I can't take this new routine.'' When he's calm,
talk about it: ``Even though we're having fun, sometimes I miss the
way our house feels, even the way it smells. Do you?'' That alone
can make him feel less out of control.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
AFTERTHOUGHT: Recommended: ``What Stories Does My Son Need? A guide
to books and movies that build character in boys'' by Michael
Gurian (Tarcher/Putnam). It covers preschool through high school.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz's e-mail address is meltz(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
