<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-NEXABIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXABIT FOUNDER LEAVES LUCENT TO CREATE NEW STARTUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barely one year after selling his start-up Internet router
company to Lucent Technologies for $900 million, the founder of
Nexabit Networks has bailed out of Lucent _ and started a new
company directly across the street from the one he sold in
Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   With former Nexabit Networks employees seeing their Lucent stock
options mature this week, some industry insiders are predicting a
mass defection of employees to the new company, Axiowave Networks
Inc., set up by Nexabit founder Mukesh Chatter.
</P>
<P>
   To many people outside the telecommunications industry, the
situation could look like a case of ingratitude or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But in today's world of Internet and telecom start-ups, it is
almost standard practice for entrepreneurial company founders and
executives to leave soon after they sell their small companies for
big money. The key is not to go into such a similar line of
business they can get sued.
</P>
<P>
   Sycamore Networks in Chelmsford, Sonus Networks in Westford, and
Convergent Networks in Lowell are three examples of Massachusetts
start-ups founded or led by people who had already sold telecom
start-ups for lavish sums to Lucent or Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company gets acquired, if you have someone who was the
CEO, and now they're general manager of an operating group, it's
hard to expect them to stay on longer than they have agreed to,''
said Chris Baldwin, a partner with Charles River Ventures who knows
several people involved in the Nexabit-Axiowave situation.
</P>
<P>
   What is unclear is whether Chatter's setting up his new company
right across Nickerson Road from Nexabit was a provocative swipe at
Lucent _ or, as some people familiar with the story speculate _
merely a case of finding office space in the superheated Interstate
495 realty market near his home.
</P>
<P>
   Chatter did not return phone calls Wednesday, and a company
receptionist would not identify the name of a spokesman to talk to.
Axiowave has taken enough space to hire several dozen employees but
has only a handful now.
</P>
<P>
   Axiowave's other founder, Raymond Stata, the legendary former
chief executive officer of Analog Devices, who was also founder and
chairman of Nexabit Networks, was out of the office and unreachable
by phone Wednesday, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry sources said there were reports of friction between
Chatter and Lucent officials over the merits of Internet protocol
versus so-called ATM routing for moving data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish Mukesh a lot of luck in his new endeavor,'' said Lucy
Graziano, a Lucent spokeswoman. She said officials there were
unfamiliar with what Axiowave plans to do, and thus had no comment
on whether Chatter might face any legal action or efforts to block
him from hiring Lucent employees.
</P>
<P>
   One wrinkle to the story, elements of which were first reported
Wednesday by online networking newsletter Light Reading, is that
many Lucent employees have been frequent visitors to Axiowave over
the last several weeks _ to use its showers after games of
parking-lot basketball.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of newly stock-option-enriched Nexabit employees
fleeing Lucent, Graziano said, ``We have a very, very competitive
compensation package. We'll do the right things by our key
employees to keep them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because some employee is vested on a Monday doesn't mean
they leave on a Tuesday,'' Graziano said.
</P>
<P>
   Axiowave is in what is called ``stealth mode,'' refusing to say
what it plans to make or do or, beyond some top names, who works
there.
</P>
<P>
   Two people familiar with the company said Axiowave appears to be
pursuing an all-optical switching device that would use light,
rather than pulses of electricity, to move huge piles of data at
blazing speeds.
</P>
<P>
   Even in advanced fiber-optic networks, light pulses today are
generally converted back to electricity and then back to light to
move data from point to point, which can create bottlenecks in
thousand-lane data highways.
</P>
<P>
   In the most basic terms Axiowave might produce a box that does
the same thing as a Nexabit router, just potentially much faster.
But the difference in the technologies probably means Axiowave may
not directly compete with Lucent's Nexabit products, industry
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawsuits filed by companies against departing employees who
start new businesses are common, including a bitter fight between
Web consulting firm Cambridge Technology Partners Inc. against
founder James K. Sims, who set up Gen3 Partners Inc. in Boston
after leaving Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Lucent made its $900 million bid for Nexabit last
June, the company was developing _ but had yet to sell _ what is
called a terabit router, a device that can move a trillion bits of
data per second. Nexabit was one of six Bay State start-ups Lucent
bought last year for a total $24 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been persistent chatter in the industry that the
device does not work as well as billed, Lucent last November
reported a Nexabit router had moved data in normal network usage at
a then-record speed of 10 gigabits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Lucent announced its first customer for the
Nexabit-originated NX64000 device, VCities of Dallas, which is
using the terabit routers to help Internet companies and phone
companies sell new high-speed services. Graziano said several other
companies are testing the device.
</P>
<P>
   Other founders of Axiowave include Subhash C. Agrawal, a
software industry veteran, and Dan Vitti, a former Lucent vice
president of manufacturing planning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
