<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CYC-TOUR-RULES-BOS &LR;      07-20 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-RULES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNOFFICIAL RULES GOVERN TOUR TIMEOUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland _ On paper, the Tour de France waits for
no one.
</P>
<P>
   Every July, almost 200 cyclists bolt around the countryside in a
separate race each day to try and accumulate the lowest time in
three weeks of competition.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour does wait sometimes, though. The group has to stop for
barricaded railroad crossings, the cyclists skid to a stop for
crashes, and they are forced to pause when a local group is staging
a protest.
</P>
<P>
   But what about the most necessary, albeit unspoken, break _ the
bathroom break?
</P>
<P>
   It might seem appalling that a cyclist who is counting seconds
would sacrifice minutes for the so-called natural break. But after
a morning of coffee, cereal, pasta, omelettes, and several bottles
of water on top of six hours on a bike, what break could be any
more natural?
</P>
<P>
   It was brought to the forefront last week when Laurent Jalabert
said he was miffed when he was wearing the leaders' yellow jersey,
pulled off the road for a ``natural break,'' and the group kept
going at high speed.
</P>
<P>
   Tour courtesy, after all, says that the racers don't take
advantage of a fellow rider taking a break, said Paul Sherwen, a
veteran of seven Tours who now does commentary for European
television, ESPN, and ABC.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwen explained that some riders take the break while they're
still on their bike _ the racing suit is usually one piece and made
of Spandex, so we'll leave that to the imagination. Others dismount
their bike and go to the side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   The former is supposed to be done out of public view, or away
from a town according to the international cycling union, which can
be difficult in a race like the Tour where virtually every mile of
roadside is lined with people.
</P>
<P>
   It is definitely problematic, Sherwen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys can take a natural break on their bike, but I never
could. I had to stop,'' he said. ``Normally, you see a guy go up to
the front, so everybody knows the guy is leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   So the group doesn't speed away, unless they're looking for
payback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a guy, 11 or 12 years ago, who was a real pig,''
Sherwen said, saying that the rider would attack when the group
slowed down for a crash or at the feeding area, where the riders
are handed sacks of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``So once he stopped at the side of the road to go to the
toilet, and he put his bike down, and a guy rode along, picked up
his bike, and dumped it in a ditch. I can't remember his name, but
it was hilarious.''
</P>
<P>
   C'est le Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other rules that are not listed in the official race book:
</P>
<P>
   One is to let a rider move to the front of the pack when the
race goes through his hometown. Usually it's someone who's way down
in the overall standings, so he has a chance to look like a hero
when he rides by his cheering relatives.
</P>
<P>
   But again, some riders take advantage of the courtesy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, once a rider rode in front, went to the side of the
road to hug his parents, then got back on his bike and stayed in
front, where he bolted ahead of the pack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do something like that, if you go out to greet the
family, and you don't sit up (to slow down) when you get back, you
get a bad name for yourself overnight, and you always have a black
mark against you,'' Sherwen said. ``And you'll never be able to do
it ever again, nobody would ever let you.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are rules that the regulation book spells out:
</P>
<P>
   Taking water from fans is OK, taking glass bottles is not.
</P>
<P>
   Being sprayed by the spectators is all right; bring sprayed by
the manager in your team car is not.
</P>
<P>
   Getting pats on the back is OK; getting pushed uphill is not. It
might be unwanted, but if a Tour referee sees it, he can issue a
time penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Racers can _ and do gladly _ accept newpapers from fans on the
top of a mountain as the cyclists get ready for the cold descent,
when they reach speeds of 50 to 60 miles per hour. The cyclists
stuff the papers under their jerseys, then toss them aside when
they reach the bottom of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, perhaps the most unspoken part of the Tour can be the
power that one rider holds over the pack. Fans may not see it, but
the riders feel it. The Tour hasn't seen one in recent years, but
the event used to be so dominated by a racer that he was considered
the official leader. It's someone who controls the pack as much as
a Larry Bird or Michael Jordan could be in charge of their
basketball team. But how can that be, if there are almost 200
cyclists, all riding for different teams?
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I rode in all the Tours Bernard Hinault rode, and
he was the patron, he was the boss,'' said Sherwen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wanted the stage to go slow, the stage went slow. Not
because he had a bad day, but he though about the whole peleton, he
thought about everyone finishing the race. But he did it
forcefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherwen recalled that Hinault was in a crash during 1985 and
broke his nose. He managed to finish the race, but word got around
that he was injured, so the pack tried to take advantage of it the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when we got to the first climb, all these Colombians and
Spaniards were hammering and attacking up the road,'' Sherwen said.
``Hinualt got all his team to the front, and he rode hard the whole
rest of the race. It was like saying, `OK, boys, I might have a
broken nose, but I'm still the boss.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hinault won his fifth Tour that year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
