<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 13:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BISHOP-B     07-20 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BISHOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP HAS PLENTY TO OFFER IN RESERVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He wants to become at least the Patriots No.
2 quarterback, backup vice president of Patriots quarterbacks, a
heartbeat away from the presidency. His expectations are now more
realistic than they were last year at this time when he had visions
of stepping onto the field and never leaving it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bishop knows he will not unseat Drew Bledsoe, but he
wants to be in position to be active every Sunday, a step up from
his role of emergency third quarterback last season.
</P>
<P>
   With veteran John Friesz starting the season in Bill Belichick's
doghouse and with Friesz's contract kicking in for another season
if he plays this year, there's a distinct possibility Bishop could
at least be the relief pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely put myself in that situation by improving
everyday in practice and making the right reads. I have no control
over it, but I'm making strides toward doing that. I can step up
and be that extra player,''said Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop always seems to garner a lot of attention. Quarterback's
do in general, but on a team that has a superstar quarterback who's
a pocket passer, the opposite of that is often appealing especially
in times when Bledsoe is struggling or in times when the offensive
line is protecting well. Afterall, here's a guy who can run, squirm
out of harms way and make something big happen in the process with
his legs and his arm. There's still that image of last pre-season
when Bishop captured the imagination of his fans with a few
extraordinary athletic feats on the field, dodging would-be
tacklers and making something positive out of something negative.
</P>
<P>
   Listen, he wasn't the second coming of Brett Favre, completing
17 of 34 passes for 299 yards and three touchdowns including a
47-yard pass to Sean Morey, but theyt were a very exciting 34
passes.
</P>
<P>
   Once the season started, Bishop never saw the football field
except for practice.
</P>
<P>
   In an 8-8 season, that didn't seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a perfect season, Bishop would never see the playing field
because it would mean Bledsoe was being an All-Pro and leading the
Patriots to the playoffs. But after a 6-2 start, it crumbled all
around Bledsoe. The talk shows were heating up with impassioned
pleas to play Bishop. Pete Carroll's staff would never let it
happen. The staff was already on thin ice, it would certainly never
want to be responsible for giving a rookie quarterback a chance to
play over the established Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   So Bishop sat and sat and sat. For a kid who had always been the
center of attention it was difficult. He began talking of going to
the Cleveland Indians' training site in Winter Haven, Fla. and
resuming his baseball career. he balked at going to NFL Europe to
get playing experience in a place like Barcelona where he would
have been an instant star.
</P>
<P>
   When the new regime took over, offensive coordinator Charlie
Weis met with Bishop and thought it best he stay with the team in
the offseason to learn a new system feeling it might be too
confusing for Bishop to work the system in Barcelona and then have
to learn another one in New England.
</P>
<P>
   There's always been talk of getting Bishop's athleticism into a
game in a ``Slash'' role, but evidently that won't materialize.
Weis said that Bishop would learn to play quarterback, comparing
him a lot to former Patriot Ray Lucas, who emerged as a good
quarterback for the Jets last season after being used as a
defensive back, a receiver and a special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Lucas and Bishop is that Bishop has
always been a quarterback while Lucas played quarterback at Rutgers
and then was switched to defensive back by the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the Patriots have told Bishop that if Bledsoe
hits a wall during a game or in a certain situation, Bishop may be
called upon to run a play or two. In practice he's looked
especially good in goal line situations where he has the option to
run. But Wednesday he also showed off his arm strength nailing
Shockmain Davis, a free-agent rookie receiver from Angelo State
down the middle of the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new offensive coordinator has some things we've worked on
in practice where I could help the team out. If Drew's winning I'm
going to be happy but if we're losing it could be a different story
and I have to be ready to get my chance,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Always confident, it appears now that Bishop is showing he can
be more than just an athlete playing quarterback. Now he feels like
a quarterback who can do athletic things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I have a better understanding of the offense. I know
what's going on. I'm getting the ball to the right receiver at the
right time. I use practice as a game situation. I envision myself
in the game and I try to carry out the play like it is a game
situation. I think that's helped me. That's why I think it was a
good move to stay here rather than go to Europe. If I had gone to
Europe I'd be a few days behind, days that I wouldn't have been
here learning everything about the offense,'' Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of him, however, would have liked to try the ``Slash''
routine for a while and see if it could work, but ``I'm not
disappointed. I feel I can play quarterback in this league. If they
tried to experiment with something I'd give 110 percent. Right now
just I'll just stick as a quarterback. If I can help the team later
in the season I'll do what ever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is never far away from Bishop's thoughts, either.
Recently, a major league scout who watched Bishop play at Blinn
(Texas) Jr. College a few years ago said Bishop has superb athletic
tools in terms of speed, arm strength and potential power given
he's 6-2, 215 pounds. But the scout said, ``He's so raw it would
take him four or five years to get out of the minors. He'd have to
show he could hit consistently and it seems he had trouble hitting
a curveball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Bishop still plays catch with teammates and plays
in pickup softball games. Last summer he used to take rips in the
batting cage. He has a few teammates who played college baseball
including Kevin Faulk, Patrick Pass, and Tom Brady so it's always
the subject of conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if could get established in this league, I'd think about
pursuing baseball again. I haven't ruled it out completely, but now
I'm just concentrating on playing football and being a
quarterback,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun of watching Bishop is imagining what he could
become. So many times in sports great athletes get into the wrong
situation and never live up to their dreams or their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop doesn't want to be one of those which is why when he
steps on the field in Canton, Ohio on July 31st against the 49ers,
Bishop wants to show a nationally televised audience why he was
24-0 in two seasons at Blinn and 22-3 in two seasons at Kansas
State.
</P>
<P>
   And why all Michael Bishop ever does is win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
