<HEADER>
A7690 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-WOM-WEBB-BOS &LR;      07-20 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOM-WEBB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARRIE WEBB FEELS PATIENCE CAN BRING A VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ Hundreds of boys and girls, not to mention men
and women, pulled their shirts and sweaters _ yes, sweaters in July
_ tight against the chill wind blowing from the north, waiting for
The Merit Club's most famous member to finish his duty inside the
press tent.
</P>
<P>
   In time, Michael Jordan wound up his conference before a packed
media horde and rushed out, being led to safety with a quick ride
on a golf cart. Behind him, much as the Pied Piper, hundreds of
youths snaked after Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, perhaps the world's best woman golfer,
Australia's Karrie Webb, sat in the same seat Jordan had vacated
only moments earlier. This time, there were only a handful of media
people and, when Webb was done, a smaller handful of fans was
waiting outside for Webb's autograph.
</P>
<P>
   The small media crowd is easily, if frustratingly, explained. In
sheer idiocy of scheduling, the United States Golf Association
scheduled its 55th US Women's Open Championship the same week as
the men's British Open and virtually all of America's golf media
are across the Atlantic in Scotland, waiting for Tiger Woods to
attack St. Andrews, the birthplace of golf. Few are here in the far
northern (and very affluent) suburbs of Chicago to watch the women.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, like many of the other women, was irked that the spotlight
on the women has been dimmed by the conflict of the Women's Open
with the British Open. ``Obviously,'' said the Aussie, ``we'd all
prefer to have the week all to ourselves as far as the attention
goes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the spotlight, dim as it is, once again clearly is on Webb
who, despite her brillance, has yet to win a US Open. Lack of
patience, said the Aussie, has led to her downfall in four tries at
the women's biggest tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the spotlight, dim as it is, also is clearly on women's
golf. It is still Nancy Lopez, who played three holes with Jordan
on Tuesday, drawing the crowds although Lopez is a decade past her
prime, just as it still is American Juli Inkster, the 40-year-old
mother of two and defending US Open champion who, even Inkster
concedes, is the heroine of ``working moms'' throughout America.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster, as likable and accomplished as any golfer, pointedly
pined for an American girl to step forward and seize women's golf
much as Woods did the same on the men's side three years ago. ``I'd
like to see a good young American come up and play well,'' said
Inkster.
</P>
<P>
   Only then perhaps, Inkster went on, would the average American
sports fan catch on to the excellent golf played by the women. ``A
lot of people out there,'' Inkster wryly noted, ``still think we
hit it 210 yards off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   That up-and-coming American golfer, except perhaps for
23-year-old Kelli Kuehne, is still not visible on the horizon. And,
even with the fiery rivalry between Webb and the 29-year-old Swede,
Annika Sorenstam, that should _ but doesn't _ catch many eyes,
average sports fans aren't soon going to catch on that the women
indeed hit it much farther than 210 yards off the tee.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there will be a drama building among the three women
given the best chance to win this Open, Inkster, the red-hot
Sorenstam, who twice has won the Open and has won four of her last
six tournaments and Webb, who won four of the first five
tournaments on the 2000 Women's Tour but hasn't won since taking
the Nabisco Dinah Shore (by 10 strokes) seven tournaments ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenstam's victory last weekend in the Japan Airlines Big Apple
Classic in New York increased her earnings for the year to
$985,580, nudging by the $963,742 earned by Webb. The two women are
that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I can't do anything with the way Annika has been
playing,'' said Webb, when asked about the rivalry. ``She has
played great, especially in the last couple of months. But I've
just got to keep doing my own thing and just concentrate on my own
game, which is what I've done for 4 1/2 years now. I can't do
anything more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Well . . . except for winning an Open.
</P>
<P>
   Webb has done virtually everything but win the US Open. In her
rookie year of 1996, she won $1,002,000, the most ever won by a
rookie. Twice she has boasted the lowest scoring average on the
LPGA Tour, and last year whe won the Rolex Player of the Year
trophy. Yet, she has been able to finish in the US Open top five
only once (fourth in 1997), and she finished seventh last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's eluded me four times now,'' Webb said, playing on the
word ``eluded.'' And the reason why the Open has ``eluded'' her,
she went on, has been her impatience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can lose my patience,'' said the Australian, whose hometown
in Queensland is the same as Greg Norman's. ``Not necessarily on
the first day, or on the second day, and last time, I got to my
third day before losing my patience. I think when I first played in
the US Open, I lost it on my first day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to define ``patience,'' Webb replied with a golfer's true
lament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just get very . . . I go so long with holding things in,''
Webb explained. ``And then just one bad break, one bad swing and I
just . . . I just lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb believes that her ``patience'' is improving, but she notes
a fine distinction between having patience in a regular tour event
and having patience in a major. ``And that's what you have to work
on,'' she said, ``and just try and make the best of it you know,
especially in a major. But I feel as every year goes by, I'm a
little less hard on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   She finally has learned, she said, that in an Open with its deep
rough and slick greens ``that birdies are not going to come as
often as they do on other courses.'' Even more, she said, she has
learned that after a bogey she can't follow her natural instincts
``and say on the next tee, `Alright, I'm going to get it straight
back.' That's because at a US Open you can't always get it straight
back, but you might get it on the next hole, two holes later or six
holes later.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the season, Webb did everything right, winning
four of her first five tournaments. And when asked to explain the
difference between her golf game then and her game now, Webb gave
an indirect compliment to Woods while saying it is impossible to
win week after week in tournament golf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know myself that you just can't continue, although there is
one person out there who proves my theory wrong right now,'' said
Webb. ``But you just can't continue to win week in and week out.
You know, it's tiring.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Jordan handicapped which of the women would do
better on the golf course he knows so well. In between ducking
question after question about the sad plight of his old team, the
Bulls, Jordan said The Merit Course will be a tough test. His best
score here ``was a 69, but that was three years ago when I didn't
have a job.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan narrowed his selections to two _ ``Webb, but I would not
rule out Juli Inskter. This is a putter's course; if she can get
that putter straight, then she can shoot some low numbers. I would
pick Juli right now.''
</P>
<P>
   But this course ``is what drives me nuts about golf,'' Jordan
went on, paraphrasing Webb's lack of patience. ``When you think
you've got your game, you don't have your game,'' said the
basketball great. Jordan recalled his baseball days ``when one of
the players told me about golf. You've got to play your foul balls
in golf.''
</P>
<P>
   As Karrie Webb now knows too well.
</P>
<P>
   Those ``foul balls'' must be played.
</P>
<P>
   But patiently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
