</P>
<P>
   BUSH-VEEP (Washington) _ When Texas Gov. George Bush picks his
vice presidential running mate, no one will be watching more
closely than Vice President Al Gore, whose selection of a
Democratic vice presidential nominee next month could be influenced
by what Bush does. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITIES-ACT (Washington) _ Fifty-four million people with
disabilities are celebrating the transformation of America into a
place where they can ride on buses and eat in restaurants 10 years
after enactment of a law aimed at helping them. But advocates say
the fight to change attitudes continues. We look at the progress
and the remaining problems since the Americans with Disabilities
Act was signed into law July 26, 1990, by President George Bush. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   HEPATITUS-DANGERS (Washington)_ Hepatitis C, an infectious
disease that can hide undetected in a person for decades slowly
destroying the liver, is emerging as one of the country's top
health care concerns, both in terms in loss of life and stress on
the economy. BY ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-ADVISER (Washington) _ The trail that led Peter Swire to
the White House as President Clinton's chief adviser on privacy
matters began in the 1970s when he worked the computers at his
family's furniture stores in Albany, N.Y. There amid the recliners
and living room sets, he was inspired when his father, Bill Swire,
charged headlong into the computer era. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
