<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-DSL-MOVIES-HNS &LR;      07-20 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DSL-MOVIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SBC TO OFFER MOVIES OVER HIGH-SPEED INTERNET LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SANFORD NOWLIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ SBC Communications Inc. is gearing up to give its
DSL subscribers fast access not just to the Internet but to movies
and games.
</P>
<P>
   SBC, the San Antonio-based parent of the Southwestern Bell
telephone company, said it would test a new service unveiled
Wednesday by entertainment giant Blockbuster Inc. and Enron Corp.,
an energy company, that allows customers to order movies, games and
other entertainment via high-speed Internet lines known as DSL, or
digital subscriber lines.
</P>
<P>
   The service, called video-on-demand, will allow customers to
order a movie to view on their television or computer, but unlike a
conventional pay-per-view movie, they can start it when they want
and pause or rewind as they would a videocassette.
</P>
<P>
   SBC will offer the service over its DSL lines to about 5,000
customers in two or three cities by year's end, officials said. The
company wants ultimately to be able to offer it to all its
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of SBC's aggressive efforts to bring broadband to
the masses,'' said Jason Few, SBC's vice president of broadband
services. ``There's no question that video-on-demand and other
services we plan to offer will expand our DSL market beyond just
computer users.''
</P>
<P>
   SBC has not yet selected its test markets, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Blockbuster, the top video rental chain, will
provide programming for the new service, and Houston-based Enron
will deliver it via a nationwide fiber-optic network it has
developed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to SBC, the two companies have signed up other DSL
providers, including Verizon (the company formed by the merger of
Bell Atlantic and GTE Corp.) and Qwest Communications, to
participate in the test.
</P>
<P>
   They need the help of carriers such as SBC and Verizon to
deliver their service from Enron's network into homes. DSL lines,
which allow access to the Internet at blazing speeds, are needed to
handle the large amount of data necessary to transmit video.
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster and Enron, which agreed to work together for 20
years on the video-on-demand project, want to make their service
available across the United States and internationally some time
next year.
</P>
<P>
   SBC increasingly gets its revenue from data and Internet
services rather than traditional phone service. The company
recently earmarked $6 billion to roll out DSL to 80 percent of its
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Like other major telecom carriers, SBC wants to provide
customers a full range of phone, Internet and video services on one
monthly bill. It last year added another video component to the mix
when it agreed to resell DirecTV satellite service.
</P>
<P>
   Cable television companies are gearing up to offer their own
video-on-demand services. Time Warner, for example, is testing such
a service in Austin and expects to roll it out here next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Blockbuster-Enron venture, however, is the first major
attempt to offer such a service over DSL lines.
</P>
<P>
   The technical difficulties of such a large project may prove
daunting for the two companies, both of which are newcomers to the
broadcasting business, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's done this before on the scale they're talking
about,'' said Jim Penhune, an analyst with Yankee Group in Boston.
``It will be a significant challenge to get the number of customers
installed that they're talking about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1417EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
