<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7702 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-MONET-MUSEUM-HNS &LR;      07-20 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONET-MUSEUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MONET FANS HAVE ANOTHER MUSEUM TO VISIT IN PARIS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ANTONIA KAPLAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Admirers of Claude Monet have a new mecca to visit here,
a jewel of a museum showcasing the world's largest collection of
the master's work.
</P>
<P>
   The elegant building, now called the Marmottan-Claude Monet
Museum, is one of Paris' best-kept secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked away in a residential neighborhood on the city's west
side near the Bois de Boulogne, it used to be called the Marmottan
Museum. But after extensive renovation, it reopened in April with
its new name, its greatly expanded gallery space and its entire
Monet collection on display.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, it had held much of the Impressionist painter's art
in storage.
</P>
<P>
   The Monet collection boasts 100 oils and 37 other works _
pastels, caricatures and pen and ink drawings. It includes some of
the artist's most famous paintings: ``Impression of Sunrise,''
``Houses of Parliament,'' a ``Rouen Cathedral'' and many of the
``Water Lilies'' that he painted in his gardens during the 43 years
that he lived in Giverny, north of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Monet, who died in 1926 at the age of 86, is perhaps the best
known of the Impressionists. A water lily painting recently sold
for about $21 million at a Christie's auction.
</P>
<P>
   Monet inadvertently gave the Impressionist movement its name. He
included his ``Impression of Sunrise,'' with its ball of red rising
out of the blue mist at the port of Le Havre, France, in an exhibit
here in 1874. It stood out among paintings by such artists as
Pierre Auguste Renoir, Paul Cezanne, Camille Pissaro, Edgar Degas,
Alfred Sisley and Berthe Morisot.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Leroy, a leading critic at the time, looked around and
decided that the artists there _ the whole lot of them _ were
incompetent. He spotted Monet's title with the word ``impression''
and ridiculed the group's idea of using the play of light and color
to capture momentary scenes. Monet and the others, Leroy wrote,
were capable only of giving impressions and not of painting real
pictures. He entitled his scornful critique ``The Impressionists.''
</P>
<P>
   In its three-year renovation, the museum scooped out space under
its garden to create additional viewing areas. One is a magnificent
circular gallery where, hung all around it, are fine
representatives of the collection's 45 water-lily paintings,
donated by Monet's son Michel.
</P>
<P>
   The museum was originally a hunting lodge, purchased in 1882 by
Jules Marmottan and turned into a private residence by his son, art
collector Paul Marmottan. When he died in 1932, he bequeathed the
residence and its collections, including one of 19th century
furniture and sculpture, to the French Academy of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The mansion also displays works of other artists including
Monet's friends Renoir, Pissaro, Morisot, Sisley, Edouard Manet and
Paul Gauguin.
</P>
<P>
   Overseeing the renovation was Arnaud d'Hauterives, a 67-year-old
painter who was the museum's director for 12 years before he
retired this spring to concentrate on his work as permanent
secretary of the prestigious fine arts academy.
</P>
<P>
   D'Hauterives, who for years had an apartment at the museum,
said, ``I will miss having breakfast with Monet, but my job here is
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, located at No. 2 rue Louis-Boilly, is open every day
except Monday from 10 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. Individual tickets cost 40
francs, about $7.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
