<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-JOURNAL-PATRIOT-0721-     07-20 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-PATRIOT-0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: MOVIE, THE PATRIOT, MAKING IT TOUGH(ER) TO BE AN
AMERICAN IN BRITAIN
 &HT;    With photo mug of Roughton.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International, (k) Commentary and (l) Lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST HORSLEY, England _ My 6-year-old son made an American flag
for the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   OK, it had a dozen or so stars and not exactly the right number
of stripes _ but he drew it from a faint memory distorted by the
cartoonish American flags we see on everything here from blue jeans
to popcorn bags. We're talking about a little boy who probably has
never heard the ``Star Spangled Banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, he wanted to display his paper flag in front of our house.
I was touched, but I couldn't bring myself to stick it outside. I
placed it on another place of honor: the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   This is partly because it was gray, rainy and about 55 degrees
on the Fourth here, which would have made short work of the paper
flag. But it was more than that.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't want to draw attention to the fact that this very
English house in this very English neighborhood was full of
Americans. I think they all already know our secret because we
smile at strangers and leave at our curb 10 bags of garbage each
week to their two (wasteful American consumerism, packaged food,
disposable everything, etc.). Then there's the steady scent of
charring meat drifting from our backyard, clear evidence of
Americans trying to simulate summer in this country of eternal
February.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I'm no Anglophile. I'm proud of being an
American. In fact, I'm not sure I knew I was an American until I
moved to England. I had always thought myself a Texan or Atlantan
or at least a Southerner _ but never a nationality. You almost have
to be set among other people to see how they see you before you
feel part of a distinct tribe.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that stupid Mel Gibson movie. Even before it
opened here last weekend, the British press had been apoplectic
about The Patriot, which depicts the English _ or at least a few
English soldiers _ as pathological, murdering fops.
</P>
<P>
   It's a movie starring Australians directed by a German depicting
events that never happened in America.
</P>
<P>
   This follows of a series of American-inspired insults, including
Dan Rather's boorish proclamation that beneath the charming green
English facade lurks a violence-ridden society with crime rates on
par with the United States. (I think they were most offended that
this wasn't Dan's lead item.)
</P>
<P>
   While it's troubling that crime is on the rise in England, the
comparison is absurd. If you live in America, the odds that you
will be shot to death are 60 times higher than in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood remains the worst offender. First, there was Saving
Private Ryan, which, in the hyper-sensitive minds of some British
commentators, neglected to note that anybody but Americans and
Germans showed up on D-Day.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the movie U-571 has Americans _ not Brits _
capturing the Enigma machine from the Germans, thus allowing the
Allies to decode enemy communications. And even the quasi-British
production Chicken Run, has a bunch of silly British hens
overshadowed by the suave, if roguish American rooster. (Mel Gibson
again. Is this a trend?)
</P>
<P>
   There is a feeling among Britons that American films are
stealing their history _ which is pretty much all they have left.
They are proud that they resisted tyrants such as Napoleon and
Hitler. (I'm waiting for Hollywood to produce a movie with Mel
Gibson as a revenge-minded American kicking butt at Waterloo.)
</P>
<P>
   You look around here and cannot escape that this was once the
center of a vast empire. But there is no British Empire anymore. In
fact, there's barely a Britain.
</P>
<P>
   So, I feel for the Brits, and I'm mortified by the noisy and
never-ending success story that is the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The other night my wife Melinda and I watched a dazzling display
of fireworks with some friends, both English and American. At the
end of the splendid show, the American woman piped in, ``You think
that was fireworks? You should see the Fourth of July back home.''
Our English friends _ who love America _ smiled politely, but I
cringed. As a Southerner, I've heard enough ``you should see''
comments from Yankees for a lifetime and know better than to
inflict this obnoxiousness on others.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Melinda and I finally went to see the
dreaded movie.
</P>
<P>
   It was worse than I could have imagined. Mel Gibson and two
little boys armed with flintlocks dropped 20 British troops _
apparently not trained to find cover _ with less effort than I
expended as a youth blasting confused and unarmed quail.
</P>
<P>
   In the climactic scene, Gibson's character finds a wooden
flagpole, lethal weapon enough to whack a few of the king's
soldiers armed only with muskets, swords and bayonets.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, many Brits seem to take this in stride. Some
writers even said they wouldn't mind that their ancestors are cast
as ``baddies,'' so long as the film is entertaining. They are
offended more by the movie's shoddiness than by its insults to
their national pride.
</P>
<P>
   After the agony of watching the movie, I asked a nice older
couple from Farnham, a village outside London, what they thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very powerful film,'' said the husband, Mike Wheeler,
with a laugh. ``I ducked when that cannon ball went rolling across
the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor his wife Jackie was troubled by the depiction of
the English soldiers. They dismiss the sociopathic behavior of the
really bad English officer as predictable behavior by the
upper-classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were aristocrats, weren't they,'' Jackie Wheeler
explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were as bad as anybody else in war,'' said her husband.
``Who can argue with history?''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.thepatriot.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
