<HEADER>
A7712 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKNOTES20-COX     07-20 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rowling rules Times' kids best sellers
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times launches its children's best-seller list
Sunday, and to no one's surprise, the top four spots are occupied
by J.K. Rowling novels, including the just-released ``Harry Potter
and the Goblet of Fire'' at No. 1. Following in No. 5 and 6 are
``Backstreet Boys: The Official Book'' by Andre Csillag and ``Oh,
the Places You'll Go!'' by Dr. Seuss.
</P>
<P>
   The Times' book review editor, Charles McGrath, says the new
list was created to clear some room on the adult list. But if the
Times editors thought that kicking Harry Potter off the adult
fiction list would make room for more literary works, they were
mistaken. Only one, ``The Bluest Eye'' by Toni Morrison, crept into
the top 10. Others making the list were ``Omerta'' by Mario Puzo
(No. 5) and ``The Fighting Agents'' by W.E.B. Griffin (No. 7).
Instead of Potter, the top three books on the adult list are ``The
House on Hope Street'' by Danielle Steel, ``Cradle and All'' by
James Patterson and ``Heartbreaker'' by Julie Garwood.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Scary stuff: Get out your pruning shears. The first shoots of
Stephen King's online novel-in-progress, ``The Plant,'' will begin
climbing through the Web (www.stephenking.com) Monday. The
epistolary novel is set in the early 1980s and is ``sort of funny
and at the same time pretty gruesome (think `Christine'),'' King
notes on his Web site. The novel will be presented in segments
ranging from 5,000 to 7,000 words at $1 each on the honor system.
King says he doesn't mind if readers make copies of the
installments after they pay, but if they don't pay, he will stop
offering chapters. If it works, he adds, ``My friends, we have a
chance to become Big Publishing's worst nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  After the storm: What does a 35-year-old free-lance writer
tackle next when his first book, ``The Perfect Storm,'' sells more
than 1.5 million copies? Apparently, anything he wants. Sebastian
Junger tells National Geographic Adventure magazine that some
publishers have even offered him blank contracts. ``I just told my
agent I won't be interested for years.'' Meanwhile, he has opened
the Half King, a restaurant and bar on Tenth Avenue and 23rd Street
in Manhattan where literary readings will be held. And this
September he's going to Afghanistan to report on the extremist
Taliban government.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In the works: Winston Groom (``Forrest Gump'') returns to
print this fall with ``The Crimson Tide: An Illustrated History of
Football at the University of Alabama'' (Alabama Press, $39.95).
Other contributors include announcer Keith Jackson and authors Gay
Talese, Willie Morris and Howell Raines. The press is also
reissuing Raines' debut novel, ``Whiskey Man,'' about a boy in
Depression-era Alabama. ... Salon.com has sold a collection of its
pieces to Villard for a book to be published in October. ``Salon's
Wanderlust: Real-Life Tales of Adventure and Romance'' will include
essays by Isabel Allende and Jan Morris.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Check out the New York Times' Children's
Best Sellers: www.nytimes.com/books/00/07/23/bsp/bestchildren.html
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
