<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7713 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-PRIVACY-ADVISER-$ADV2     07-20 1475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-ADVISER-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHITE HOUSE PRIVACY ADVISER IS A COMPUTER WIZZARD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For Release Sunday, July 23)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The trail that led Peter Swire to the White House
as President Clinton's chief adviser on privacy matters began when
he worked the computers at his family's furniture stores in Albany,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   There amid the dining room and living room sets, he was inspired
when his father, Bill Swire, charged headlong into the computer era
in the 1970s. The elder Swire, whom his son described as a
``pioneer'' in the business uses of computers, developed a system
for tracking furniture inventory, sales and accounts that he
marketed nationwide through IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``By today's standards (computers) were primitive, but they
could keep customer records much more accurately, and create
reports so management could make better decisions,'' said Swire,
42, in an interview at his office in the ornate Old Executive
Office Building next to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   From such modest roots flowered a lifelong interest in the
social policy implications of the age of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   At Princeton University, where he graduated in 1980, his
undergraduate thesis was on information technology and how it
affected legal and economic thought.
</P>
<P>
   As a law student at Yale and then as a judicial clerk, legal
practitioner and law school professor, Swire formulated the issue
as a series of questions. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   __ How do you maintain privacy in an era where computer
technology makes it increasingly easy for prying eyes _ including
those of the government _ to keep tabs on what you buy, your
health, and who you talk to?
</P>
<P>
   __ Where do you draw the line between the legitimate needs of
business and government, and the Constitution's guarantee that
people shall ``be secure in their persons, houses, papers and
effects''?
</P>
<P>
   Swire has brought such questions into the White House as the
government's overall coordinator on privacy issues. Since becoming
Clinton's chief counselor for privacy in March 1999, he has tackled
a host of thorny privacy issues, most of them relating to computers
and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He's worked on these issues:
</P>
<P>
   __ Privacy of personal health information. Rules promulgated by
President Clinton last year will limit the release of sensitive
health records for non-medical purposes unless patients give their
consent. Such information would no longer be forwarded to lenders
or employers who might use it for credit or job-related decisions.
The rules are expected to be finalized later this summer and put
into effect two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   __ Genetic discrimination. Clinton issued an executive order
last February barring the federal government from using genetic
information in hiring and promotion decisions. Such information at
times has been used to analyze a worker's likelihood of contracting
diseases or passing on birth defects. Clinton is supporting
legislation to outlaw genetic discrimination in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   __ Financial privacy. Clinton last year signed legislation
allowing banks to get involved with the insurance and securities
industries, but not before lawmakers beefed up the law's privacy
guarantees. Under this law, banks and other financial institutions
are not permitted to divulge personal information to outside
entities without a customer's consent.
</P>
<P>
   It takes effect next year.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the thorniest problem on Swire's plate is the effort of
federal law enforcement to beef up its ability to monitor private
computer transactions, including e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have effective law enforcement tools to stop cyber
crime, but you also want to strongly protect privacy and civil
liberties on the Internet,'' he said. ``So the job is to come up
with proposals that do both of those.''
</P>
<P>
   The task is not a simple one. News reports this month about the
FBI's Carnivore system _ an electronic eavesdropping device used to
ferret out the investigative ``meat'' in vast quantities of data _
have drawn heated complaints from privacy advocates.
</P>
<P>
   Swire said the White House was not aware of Carnivore prior to
news accounts this month detailing it. But, he added, the
administration's answer to privacy concerns about Carnivore is to
push legislation that would require agents to obtain warrants for
monitoring the content of e-mails and other computer
communications. It would elevate computers to the level of
telephones in terms of access by law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Under current law, agents investigating who a suspect is
e-mailing or instant-messaging need only certify to a judge that
the information is necessary for a criminal investigation. It's the
same standard that applies to agents seeking a telephone ``pen
register'' _ a record of who a suspect is calling and getting calls
from.
</P>
<P>
   But the new White House proposal would elevate this standard for
so-called ``trap-and-trace'' orders significantly, for both
telephones and computers. Under the White House proposal, a judge
would issue such an order only after making an independent factual
finding of whether the agent had shown sufficient justification to
approve the monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two ways in which our proposal would, in fact, set
standards for how Carnivore would operate,'' he said, adding that
the FBI system technically complies with all current law. Privacy
advocates criticized the proposal as too little, too late, adding
that its chances of passing Congress are virtually nil with only
six months left to go in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, overall, the administration's privacy goal is ``to get
the information age right,'' Swire said. ``There are all these
fantastic possibilities for the information age, but not every
possible flow of information is a good flow. So while it might be
technically feasible for my neighbor or my boss to know every
detail of my medical file or every purchase I make, that doesn't
mean we want it to happen in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington Swire plays a coordinating role, making sure
government agencies such as the Justice Department and the Health
and Human Services Department are on the same page when it comes to
privacy. His office staff consists of another lawyer, a staff
assistant and an intern. As part of the Clinton administration,
Swire's personal views take a back seat to defending the
president's policies. Because he does not have Senate confirmation,
the White House does not permit him to testify before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``With those constraints, he has been a remarkably effective
voice on privacy,'' said James X. Dempsey, senior counsel for the
Washington-based Center for Democracy and Technology, which
monitors privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   Although some privacy advocates have suggested Swire occupies a
figurehead position, ``that's not accurate,'' said Janlori Goldman,
director of the Health Privacy Project at Georgetown University
Medical Center. ``He's helped the agencies _ Health and Human
Services, the Justice Department, the Labor Department _ to come
together and talk to each other. He brings a lot of substance to
help people find common ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Swire got in on the ground floor of computer privacy. He first
wrote about the Internet in 1992, ``which is pretty early by most
standards,'' he said. ``In the first paragraph, I had to define the
word `cyberspace.'''
</P>
<P>
   His writings on privacy, including co-authorship of a book
``None of Your Business: World Data Flows, Electronic Commerce and
the European Privacy Directive,'' led to a job feeler from Esther
Dyson, a prominent figure in the Internet world with close ties to
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Swire took leave from his post as law professor at Ohio State
University in Columbus, Ohio, to take the White House job. After
Clinton leaves office next year, he expects to return with his
wife, Anne, and their two sons, Nathan and Jesse, to Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Swire grew up in Menands, N.Y., outside Albany and graduated
from Albany Academy in 1976. His mother, Stephanie, was a radio
personality in Albany in the 1970s, hosting the Stevi Swire Show, a
local talk show on WQBK-AM.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were involved in ``reform politics'' in Albany, but
were not hardcore Democratic Party activists. Swire's road to the
White House was less one of political connections than policy
convictions, born of his days in the furniture store computer room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the American people want the administration to be
balanced in its approach to privacy,'' Swire said. ``We want a
strong economy, but we also want strong protection of privacy. It
would be a shame if either of those values got left by the
wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
