<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-20 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREERS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUILDING A NEST EGG MEANS SAVING EARLY, OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A recent survey by Hewitt Associates underlines
just how clueless a lot of workers are about money, and how little
Generation Xers have learned from the mistakes of baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt's survey found that more than two-thirds of people who
changed jobs in 1999 cashed out their 401(k) plans, rather than
either trying to stay in the plan or roll the money over into an
individual retirement account. Among those under 30, the cash-out
rate was 78 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These are not people who were starving. Only about one out of
six of them was even using the money to pay bills. But a lot of
people just don't learn the nuances of money and investing until
it's too late _ if they ever learn them at all.
</P>
<P>
   If I had to pick one skill that all workers should develop, it
would be money management. You don't have to sell out or become
obsessed with every dollar, but you ought to understand how to get
the most out of your paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Money lets people in their late 30s and 40s think about starting
their own businesses or taking wonderful vacations or retiring
early, while those who don't handle it well are looking at another
30 years on the same treadmill. If you have money, you can put your
energy into pursuing a dream; if you don't have money, you can put
too much energy into avoiding a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Let's talk a little cash:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nothing is certain except debt and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst habits young workers get into is to spend more
than they earn, somehow hoping that the credit card fairy will make
all their debts vanish. It's almost always a sucker bet, one that
can leave you in a financial hole for years.
</P>
<P>
   If you're young and any kind of a decent worker, you ought to be
getting steady raises. Take the extra money and pay down the debt
until it disappears. Otherwise, you're building your career and
financial future on quicksand.
</P>
<P>
   Good workplace habits have a way of paying huge dividends later
in life. Learning to live within your means is one of the best
habits you can get into.
</P>
<P>
   _ Start saving early.
</P>
<P>
   If you put $50,000 in a retirement account by the time you're 30
and earn 10 percent a year on it, your account will be worth more
than $1.5 million by the time you're 65 _ even if you never save
another penny. But if you wait until you're 40 to save that
$50,000, it won't even be worth $600,000 by age 65.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. That 10 years of waiting could cost you more than
$900,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ A penny saved is worth more than a penny earned.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose you have to pay $115 a month for parking, but then your
employer gives you a free parking place. That's like a $115 a month
raise, right?
</P>
<P>
   No. It's a lot better. It's more like a $200 raise. Remember: If
you get a $200 raise, you'll probably lose about $85 of it to
federal and state income taxes, Social Security and Medicare,
leaving you with that $115 to pay for parking.
</P>
<P>
   There are all sorts of ways you can get more money to spend
without actually getting a raise. Programs allow employers to pay
pretax dollars for things like parking, mass transit, health care
and child care. Before you push for a raise, think about whether
things like health club memberships or expense-account meals would
be more valuable to you.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget telecommuting, too. Or, if you're truly a
cash-oriented soul, an employer match to your 401(k) contribution.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take stock.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you decide that you're not suited for it, you owe it to
yourself to learn how to invest in the stock market. The Internet
has made a lot more information available to individual investors
than there used to be.
</P>
<P>
   What a lot of those people in the Hewitt survey probably never
learned is that having money in retirement accounts gives you a
great opportunity to buy and sell stocks, because you don't have to
pay taxes each time you make a capital gain. The money isn't taxed
until you start withdrawing it _ if it's ever taxed at all (certain
IRAs have tax-free distributions).
</P>
<P>
   But they took it out early, meaning not only that they are no
longer investors, but that they will have to pay a 10 percent
penalty to the Internal Revenue Service for withdrawing the cash
before they reached retirement age. Maybe someday they'll realize
that their penalty has turned out to be a lot more than 10 percent,
but by then it will be too late.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
