<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7733 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HARRIS-HN     07-20 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-HARRIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COWBOYS' JACKIE HARRIS IS SLIMMED DOWN AND ANXIOUS TO PLAY AT
TIGHT END 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRENT ZWERNEMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ In a sea _ really, more like a mirage in
the 100-degree heat _ of dropped passes in the Cowboys' morning
practice, No. 88 stepped in and saved the moment, or at least more
hand-wringing from the Dallas coaching staff on the second day of
training camp.
</P>
<P>
   No. 88 being new tight end Jackie Harris, who snagged the number
in the wake of Michael Irvin's retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has some skills to get himself open,'' Cowboys coach Dave
Campo said. ``You saw it today as an outside receiver when he
caught a fade on one of our linebackers. We feel like we have a
special guy there.''
</P>
<P>
   One who can shed weight if needed. Harris dropped from 260 to
247 pounds in the off-season at the coaches' request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want him thin, but not too thin,'' offensive coordinator
Jack Reilly said. ``We wanted him thinner for the receiving-type
things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The fade route being one of them.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys signed Harris from Tennessee as 272-pound David
LaFleur's backup, but Harris may see more playing time because of
his increased mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the starter; he's the bigger body,'' said Harris of
LaFleur, downplaying such a suggestion. ``I've trimmed up a little
bit to become more of a `movement guy. From here, I've just got to
find a way to make the coach decide that he needs to get me in the
game as often as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   LaFleur's numbers have gradually increased over three seasons _
18, 20 and 35 catches _ but the coaches are hopeful Harris can
provide a quicker threat across the middle, an area lacking since
Jay Novacek's 1996 retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to be able to go out and really work the safeties,
and beat the linebackers if you get the matchups you like,'' said
Harris, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Harris is in his 11th NFL season. He spent the past two years
with Tennessee, where he collected 26 catches for 297 yards on the
Titans' march to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his first four seasons with Green Bay and his next four
in Tampa Bay before signing with Tennessee. His most productive
season came in '95, when he caught 62 passes for 751 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Harris also offers the young guys on the team more than a
decade's worth of training camp experience: ``It can't get any
worse than this,'' he said of playing football in triple digits on
the thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   He said a nice respite is catching passes from Troy Aikman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in some offenses where you get open and the guy
doesn't see you, but I was running down the sidelines at one of the
mini-camps, and all of the sudden the ball was right on top of
me,'' Harris said. ``The guy sees the field so well, if you get
open, you better be prepared to catch the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris dropped the weight for just such an opportunity _ to move
faster and jump higher in catching passes _ but he said he wouldn't
want to get any lighter, because of matchup problems with defensive
ends.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates seem to admire the slimmed-down Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie is moving nicely and he's seizing the opportunity,''
fellow receiver James McKnight said. ``And I think he knows, OK,
we've got a chance to go all the way here, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
