<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER: BE A TRAVEL GROUP LEADER  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color slide included.) 
 By ADELE MALOTT 
 Condensed from The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Many travel companies now offer their budget-conscious and
entrepreneurial customers a way to save money on their trips _
sometimes as much as the full price of an airline ticket or the
entire cost of a tour.
 &HT;    The secret? Become a group travel leader. As the name implies,
group travel leaders earn their savings by recruiting friends,
neighbors or people they know from church groups or service clubs
to travel together.
 &HT;    Some mature travelers are so adept at organizing groups that it
becomes something of a part-time business in which they develop
various travel clubs and produce newsletters.
 &HT;    Robert Rogers of Eureka Springs, Ark., started out hoping to
earn travel credits as a ``vacation ambassador'' for Grand Circle
Travel, (800) 597-2452. GCT ambassadors earn a $100 credit for each
of the first four travelers he or she recruits in a calendar year.
Starting with the fifth traveler, credits accumulate at a rate of
$150 per person. The credits can be cashed in for any future trip
offered by GCT.
 &HT;    Rogers' first encounter with Grand Circle occurred two years ago
when he took an all-inclusive trip to the Costa Del Sol. Rogers was
so impressed with the itinerary on that particular tour that he
recommended it to some of his friends, describing it as a ``totally
relaxing'' experience. His anecdotes about the days he spent on the
Mediterranean coast were enough to convince his friends to sign up.
He then made bookings for them.
 &HT;    Rogers was so successful with his inaugural referrals that when
the list grew to 12 friends, GCT designated him a group leader _ a
notch up from vacation ambassador _ earning him a complimentary
trip.
 &HT;    Like Rogers, Bob Jones of Coldchester, Conn., was able to
stretch his travel dollar by also becoming a group leader. After
retiring in 1994 from his job as branch manager of the American
Automobile Association, Jones refused to slow down. ``I am just too
active to do nothing,'' he said. That's when he began asking
friends if they wanted to start a travel club.
 &HT;    After about 75 percent of those he asked said, ``Yes,'' Jones
started organizing cruises for a local travel agency. It wasn't
long before he branched out, coordinating groups for GCT. His first
trip for GCT was to Mexico's Copper Canyon.
 &HT;    
 THE MORE, THE MERRIER  
 &HT;    The larger groups help pay Jones' travel expenses and provide a
way for him to include extras, such as renting a motor coach for
the group to ride together to the New York airport.
 &HT;    ``But once we were in New York, I didn't have to do a thing,''
he says. ``We had our own coach and guide. He handled every
detail.''
 &HT;    Jones says that organizing a travel group can incur some costs,
depending on the amount of energy one wishes to invest in
recruiting participants. For example, Jones opted to personally
mail out brochures. He also took care of receiving each traveler's
deposit and forwarding it to GCT. But, he says, ``After that, Grand
Circle took over ... I didn't even have to count the luggage or the
people _ not once.''
 &HT;    As Jones points out, ``Anyone who is outgoing should be able to
do this.'' He has even gone so far as to hold social gatherings at
his home, where he shows a travel film describing an upcoming
destination and serves coffee and snacks. ``Then it all seems to
happen by itself,'' he says.
 &HT;    Jones has also been a group leader with other travel companies,
including Brendan Tours, Holland America and TWA.
 &HT;    Marion Lothian of Lakehurst, N.J., thinks it's her attention to
detail that makes her trips extra special. In fact, she admits that
her desire for everything to ``be just right'' is the main reason
why she chooses to serve as the intermediary for each participant.
That means getting each deposit, collecting the rest of the
payment, organizing a bus to the airport and allocating tips for
baggage handlers and guides.
 &HT;    ``I want to take care of everything so they don't have to stick
their hands in their pockets for anything,'' she says.
 &HT;    Just before each trip, Lothian briefs her travelers so they know
what to wear, how to handle the money in the country they will
visit and what to do with their passports and visas. When the trip
is concluded, Lothian does her book work and IRS paperwork.
 &HT;    Lothian has worked with Vantage Deluxe World Travel, (800)
634-2180; Collette, (888) 344-5578; and GCT. She even developed her
own travel club in her community of 3,500 and serves as club
president. This past spring she organized tours to Scandinavia and
Spain.
 &HT;    
 WITH THE PERKS COMES WORK  
 &HT;    Lothian suggests that anyone who is thinking about becoming a
group travel leader should have a nice personality as well as ``a
strong sense of right and wrong and how to handle situations while
keeping their cool.
 &HT;    ``If they don't want to do the preparation or book work, they
shouldn't get involved because it is work and responsibility,'' she
adds.
 &HT;    Many travel brochures now spell out the details of group-travel
credits or comps. For example, Vantage Deluxe World Travel provides
a free trip, double occupancy, to group leaders for each group of
10 they recruit _ even if the leader doesn't travel with the group.
 &HT;    Immersia Travel, (800) 207-5454, offers a $1,000 savings for a
``group travel planner'' who gathers five travelers for a trip. A
complimentary trip is earned when the planner gathers 10 people.
For groups of 14 or more, the planner gets both a complimentary
trip and a $100-per-person rebate.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Readers are invited to submit questions and comments to Adele
Malott, c/o The New York Times Syndicate, 122 East 42nd St., 14th
Floor, New York, N.Y. 10168. Send Adele a postcard from your trip
with ideas, questions and information on the bargains you find for
seniors.
 &HT;    Questions may also be sent to Adele by electronic mail. The
address is MatureTrav(at)aol.com. (For (AT) use the symbol on your
keyboard.)
 &HT;    Adele Malott is the publisher of THE MATURE TRAVELER: Travel
Bonanzas for 49ers-Plus, a newsletter for mature travelers.
 &HT;    
 c.2000 The Mature Traveler Newsletter 
