<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-ROLLOUT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     APPLE THINKS OUTSIDE THE CUBE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALAN T. SARACEVIC  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Steve Jobs has a new toy, and it looks like a
toaster.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's triumphant chief executive, addressing the faithful at
the Macworld conference in New York on Wednesday, introduced a bevy
of new products, but it was the 8-inch Power Mac G4 Cube that
captured everyone's attention.
</P>
<P>
   The G4 Cube is basically a small computer with a crystal-clear
enclosure. It is less than one-fourth the size of most computers,
yet houses a 450 MHz PowerPC G4 processor that can make more than 1
billion calculations per second, according to Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``The G4 Cube is simply the coolest computer ever,'' Jobs said.
``An entirely new class of computer, it marries the
Pentium-crushing performance of the Power Mac G4 with the
miniaturization, silent operation and elegant desktop design of the
iMac. It is an amazing engineering and design feat, and we're
thrilled to finally unveil it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among its other specs, the Cube includes 64 MB of memory,
expandable to 1.5 GB; 20 GB of storage, configurable up to 40 GB; a
slot-loading DVD drive; two FireWire ports; two USB ports; and a
56K V.90 modem.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes with Apple's new optical mouse, which works on any
surface, and a pair of Apple designed Harman Kardon speakers.
</P>
<P>
   All for the not-so-low price of $1,799, not including a monitor.
A 500 MHz Cube will also go on sale in August priced at $2,299.
</P>
<P>
   Among other announcements, Jobs unveiled a new line of
PowerMacs, the business version of the popular iMac computer that
has revitalized Apple's once-sagging fortunes. Since its
introduction three years ago, Apple has sold 3.7 million iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to keep that momentum going, Jobs unveiled four new iMacs
in four new colors: dark blue, emerald, deep red and white. The new
price points are $799, $999, $1,299 and $1,499.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs also gave an update on Apple's new operating system, called
OS X. It will be available to consumers in 2001, he said, although
he didn't get much more specific.
</P>
<P>
   Apple's new PowerMacs are the first to run on two computer
chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first personal computer in history to come with a
dual processing standard,'' Jobs told the group.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Gore, editor in chief of Macworld magazine, was impressed
with the scope of Apple's announcements, but said the depth left a
little to be desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cube is the big news,'' Gore said. ``There was a lot of
fire-eating and so-forth on stage, and it was the largest number of
products ever introduced at one show. They were all interesting,
but they're not the kind of products that will change the way we
live.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Cube, Gore marveled at its engineering.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing about the Cube is something they
didn't talk about,'' he said. ``This is the world's first totally
digital computer. There's not a single analog switch on the whole
thing. Essentially, it's the poster child for digital
convergence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
