<HEADER>
A7761 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-CHUCK21-COX     07-20 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CHUCK21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Chuck &AMP; Buck' stalks laughs, but trips up in an insufferable
tale
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' goes from whimsical to wince-inducing early on
and never recovers. Written by and starring Mike White as an
emotionally arrested 27-year-old, the movie starts off as an
off-kilter character study. With its wry tone and candy-pop
soundtrack, it's like something by Todd Solondz (``Happiness'').
Then it becomes insufferable.
</P>
<P>
   In this would-be comedy of discomfort, White plays Buck, still
living at home with his mother, his bedroom cluttered with toys.
When Mom dies, Buck's best childhood pal, Chuck, flies in from the
West Coast for the funeral. Only now he goes by Charlie (played by
the handsome but wooden Chris Weitz), he works as a music industry
executive and he's engaged to Carlyn (Beth Colt).
</P>
<P>
   Buck barely seems to notice these changes, or chooses to ignore
them. He invites the couple to spend the night. When they decline,
he withdraws some of his inheritance from the bank, packs his toys
into the Mercedes station wagon and moves to Los Angeles to stalk
his old pal.
</P>
<P>
   He stakes out Charlie's office building, hoping for a glimpse of
him. He calls at all hours. He swings by unannounced at the home
Charlie and Carlyn share.
</P>
<P>
   As Buck becomes more intrusive, Carlyn offers to give him her
therapist's number. You can't help thinking she'd be wiser dialing
the police and getting a restraining order. It's a little hard to
understand writer-actor White's fascination with this character.
He's the childishly creepy kind of guy whose cellar you
instinctively don't want to visit, more serial-killer-in-training
than unlikely romantic hero.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's voice of reason belongs to Beverly (the
scene-stealing Lupe Ontiveros), a community theater manager who
takes Buck under her wing, agreeing to direct the naive play he's
written about his friendship with Chuck. Reading the script,
Beverly says, ``I think you have something weird about women. I
think you have something weird about men.'' Yep.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't figured out the cause of Buck's attraction to
Charlie and don't want to know, stop reading here. Watching the
movie, it becomes obvious pretty early that Buck's motivation is
sexual; he's fixated on the experimental sex games he and Chuck
played together as kids. In its blithely oblivious way, the movie
winds up equating homosexuality with emotional immaturity. Here's a
movie Dr. Laura would like.
</P>
<P>
   As Beverly puts it, describing Buck's play, ``It's like a
homoerotic misogynist love story.'' That sums up the movie pretty
well, too. But it winds up with an implausible ending that
simultaneously feels both too pat and unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   One of the buzzed-about movies at this year's Sundance Film
Festival, ``Chuck &AMP; Buck'' has its fans and defenders. But to me, a
stalker just isn't funny, even if he acts harmless and sucks on
Tootsie Pops all the time. Actually, that makes him even scarier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck &AMP; Buck''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mike White, Chris Weitz and Lupe Ontiveros. Rated R for
sexuality and profanity. 1 hour, 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A would-be comedy about an emotionally immature
stalker.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murrits for hours doing nothing. ``Club'' has a creepiness
that plays like a Kafka story told in the stop-motion animation
style of Jan Svankmajer (``Alice'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartoon Noir'' begins with Pedro Serrazina's lovely ``The
Story of the Cat and the Moon'' (Portugal, five minutes), the
simply illustrated, black-and-white tale of a feline who lives on
rooftops to be close to his changeable lover.
</P>
<P>
   The second-shortest entry, Julie Zammarchi's ``Ape'' (USA, six
minutes) is an energetic, quasi-sick joke about a husband and wife
who bicker over their nightly meal, a freshly killed and cooked
simian. Piotr Dumala's ``Gentle Spirit'' (Poland, 10 minutes) is a
visually impressive, gloomy meditation about another troubled
couple. They're portrayed in shadowed tableaux, the images infused
with a hallucinatory, macabre style like a visual equivalent of
Edgar Allan Poe.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Vester's ``Abductees'' (United Kingdom, 12 minutes) is a
fascinating blend of myriad types of animation and film clips,
accompanying the recorded testimony of people who claim to have
been abducted by aliens, describing their experience. The short
manages to fluctuate from comic to creepy all the way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartoon Noir'' ends with Suzan Pitt's truly unpredictable
``Joy Street'' (USA, 24 minutes). An anxious woman waiting for some
unknown thing or person in her apartment sinks deeper toward
despair, until she is rescued by an ashtray ornament, a sort of
mouse-monkey figure, come to life. The exuberance (and occasional
eeriness) of the animation complements a story line that's as
inventive as it is inexplicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cartoon Noir''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   An animation anthology. Unrated but contains mature images and
themes. 1 hour, 21 minutes. Through Thursday. $3, $5 after 6 p.m.
Cinefest (Georgia State University).
</P>
<P>
   404-651-2463.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A dark, moody and satisfying collection.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
