<HEADER>
A7764 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DEAD-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      07-20 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAD-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DEAD' COMES ALIVE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Practically all of the news about ``James Joyce's The Dead'' is
good, and that is surely a relief.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the notices out of New York have been glowing, but it's
nevertheless impossible to approach this audaciously conceived
production _ the nerve, after all, of turning the greatest short
story in the English language into a Broadway musical _ without the
bias that it had better prove its worthiness every stomping Irish
step of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there is a stumble or two, primarily in the
misplacement of a few key story elements, the musical achieves such
lyrical warmth and touching sentiment that even the most
indoctrinated Joyceans will have to admit sheer enjoyment can be a
fine substitute for literary rigor.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the stage ``Dead'' is even on the same dimensional
Emerald Isle as something like ``Riverdance.'' To be blunt, it
radiates authenticity. Director Richard Nelson's musical is
scrupulously faithful to the story's concerns with universality and
isolation, constancy and change, camaraderie and the impossibility
of truly knowing the most loved of intimates.
</P>
<P>
   The songs, which were composed by Shaun Davey with lyrics by him
and Nelson, share a common delicate beauty though each is inspired
by a wide range of distinct influences, from regional airs to grand
opera, lullabies, music hall romps, Joyce's own prose and, in the
case of the defiantly energetic showstopper ``Wake the Dead,''
Celtic rhythms primordial enough to scare any Lord of the Dance
right out of his sequins.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the show's greatest triumph is the way it brings the
story's take on melancholy tinged Irish hospitality to glowing
life. For the longest time, we feel like honored guests at the
music-loving Morkan ladies' annual Christmastime party, somewhere
around 100 years ago. On a simple, utile stage that converts
effortlessly from Edwardian parlor to dining, bed and hotel rooms,
the elderly sisters Julia (Sally Ann Howe, who pivots from losing
to grasping at life with exquisite timing) and Kate (Marni Nixon,
who sang for Audrey Hepburn in the ``My Fair Lady'' movie) and
their niece Mary Jane (Donna Lynne Champlin) host a cheerful
evening of singing and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's staging enhances the participatory illusion by
literally having his players turn their backs on the audience and
sing to their fellow actors. And a cordial lot they are: lovable
lush Freddy Malins (the remarkably elastic Stephen Spinella) and
his disapproving old mum (Patricia Kilgarriff); provocative,
patriotic young Molly Ivers (Alice Ripley); the teasingly reluctant
tenor Bartell D'Arcy (John Kelly), who when he finally gives full
voice reveals what it takes to make angels cry; and others, all
well met.
</P>
<P>
   But most importantly, there's that happily complacent couple,
Gabriel and Gretta Conroy. He is played by Stephen Bogardus, she by
Faith Prince, both delightful singers and actors of arresting
presence. Bogardus serves as an occasional narrator as well as
Gabriel, which is fine since his inner life is ``The Dead's''
beating heart.
</P>
<P>
   But lost in the translation from story to stage is the
foreshadowing of Gabriel's self-doubt, and this noticeably takes
away from the devastating impact when he realizes that the party in
his head is as irretrievably over as the one recently concluded at
his aunts'.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an epiphany as sad and transcendent as Gabriel's can
only have its greatest effect in literature, where readers can
invest the words with the imaginative weight of their
interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   However, what cannot be done in print that ``James Joyce's The
Dead'' does magnificently is transport us to a place where shared
song expresses all that needs to be considered for those gossamer
moments until the music ends. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
What: ``James Joyce's The Dead.'' &QL; 
Where: Ahmanson Theatre, 135 North Grand Avenue, Downtown L.A. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays, 2 p.m. Saturdays and Sundays,
through Sept. 3. Call for exceptions and additional show times. &QL; 
How much: $25-$70. Call (213) 628-2772. &QL;
</P>
