<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7767 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-LOSER21-COX     07-20 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LOSER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collegiate `Loser' barely makes the grade
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Loser'' had all the makings of being a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Writer/director Amy Heckerling had already strutted her comedic
stuff with the high school spoofs ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High''
and ``Clueless.'' Her latest, a college relationship comedy, stars
Jason Biggs (fresh off last year's boisterous high school sexual
romp ``American Pie''), Mena Suvari (part of the ``Pie'' ensemble
who scored big as Kevin Spacey's object of desire in the
Oscar-winning ``American Beauty'') and Greg Kinnear (an Oscar
nominee for ``As Good as It Gets'').
</P>
<P>
   Even with all that going for it, ``Loser'' turns out to be a
fairly apt title.
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly a bore.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs plays Paul, a full-scholarship student fresh from a small
Midwestern town who arrives in New York with full-blown naivete.
Stumbling about campus (there are plenty of pratfalls to secure
this guy's place as a hapless outsider), he meets Dora (Suvari), a
bright, Gothic-style American beauty who's doing one stupid thing:
She's sleeping with the college's uppity, self-absorbed English lit
professor (Kinnear).
</P>
<P>
   Will Paul and Dora ever get together? Sure, but it'll sometimes
feel like an eternity getting there.
</P>
<P>
   First, Paul's got to be mistreated by his roommates, a trio of
slobs whose main activity is drugging the drinks of unsuspecting
females. And Dora's got to have her self-esteem shredded to bits by
the professor.
</P>
<P>
   These two are indeed clueless.
</P>
<P>
   Heckerling's film has enough decent jokes and subtlety. As
Paul's dad, Dan Aykroyd delivers in deadpan manner advice to make
it in the big, big world: ``Interested is interesting.'' And Paul's
throwaway clothes to wear when he's run out of clean things
includes a Sarah McLachlan T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the film's cuteness lingers way too long. When a
little kitty is saved, for instance, Suvari is allowed to purr
``aw'' to the point of viewer frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Biggs nor Suvari kick this thing into gear like Sean
Penn did ``Fast Times'' and Alicia Silverstone did ``Clueless.''
</P>
<P>
   The actors don't get much help from Heckerling, either. She's
too busy throwing in musical interludes, showing her actors
shoppnding Biggs i a park (to Simon and Garfunkel's ``Scarborough
Fair,'' no less).
</P>
<P>
   No way is this ``The Graduate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Loser''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jason Biggs and Mena Suvari. Directed by Amy
Heckerling. Rated PG-13 for sexual relationships, drug use and some
profanity. 1 hour, 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It's a bust.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
