<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 14:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7773 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0721-COX     07-20 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roadside advisories that once entertained now go splat
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOMEWHERE IN THE WEST _ ``But it was a blue spruce.''
</P>
<P>
   This was my wife, pining to no one in particular. I was
listening but my ear was of no comfort to her.
</P>
<P>
   We'd just driven by a gorgeous stand of mountain evergreens. Her
entreaty to the back-seat boys to observe it in wonder had met
towering indifference.
</P>
<P>
   As had ``look _ Pike's Peak.'' As had ``look at Denver's
skyline.'' If the advisories were met with looks at all, that was a
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout our trip, only rare appeals succeeded in drawing
attention: ``Look, a volcanic cone'' (our middle-schooler looked,
apparently thinking he'd see lava spewing); ``Look, Britney
Spears.'' (He didn't appreciate being tricked.)
</P>
<P>
   Ah, for the days when Mom and Dad were merry tour guides and two
young passengers clung to our every word.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cow on Daddy's side,'' would evoke a robust confirmation, and
echo, from an attentive 8-year-old and 3-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil wells on Mommy's side,'' we'd say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil wells on Mommy's side,'' they'd say. ``Choo-choo on
Daddy's side,'' we'd say, followed by the back-seat repeat.
</P>
<P>
   They were seasoned travelers from the start, and robust. The
oldest, for instance, was known to joyously count the white dashes
rocketing under our wheels. Now, that's a dedicated and attentive
traveler. And now?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil well on Daddy's side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Um, yes, we've seen one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Choo-choo train on Mommy's side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes. That would be a vehicle to transport goods, commonly on a
track parallel to many highways.''
</P>
<P>
   KNOW-IT-ALLS IN GEOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when multiple oil wells spotted up ahead could
be embellished into a herd of two-legged cooties on the high
plains. Now for passengers ages 17 and almost 13, oil wells are
just _ things that pump oil.
</P>
<P>
   This matter-of-factness was most frustrating a year ago when we
went on a long trip through Big Bend and the stunning canyonlands
of Arizona and Utah. Repeatedly, seeking to elicit ``oohs'' and
``ahhs,'' I was rebuffed. Indeed, I was mocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look over there,'' I'd say to the boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, Dad? Have you spotted another `precipitous geologic
formation'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look over there,'' I'd say a few miles down the road at
another red-rock wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, that's `precipitous,' `` someone in braces would crack.
</P>
<P>
   THRILL IS GONE?
</P>
<P>
   I know the boys will look back fondly at these rides on endless
highway, the sights and family exchanges. Right now it appears all
they appreciate is the next convenience store, where one will shop
for a magazine to help blot out any vistas down the road and the
other will seek to numb his mind with mood-altering bubble gum.
</P>
<P>
   Then they'll get back in the car and ignore everything we say.
</P>
<P>
   Wait until they have kids of their own. Wait until a cow
wallowing in mud and horseflies along the road becomes a slow-down
family event. And it will, for the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, their parents can only plead to acts of reflex when
announcing, ``Cows on Dad's side,'' knowing full well the
announcement likely will be ridiculed.
</P>
<P>
   After being ignored at several scenic junctures trying to stir
up interest one day on the road, my wife spotted a herd of exotic
animals that would have caused a stir on vacations past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Llamas on mommy's side, if anyone gives a flip.''
</P>
<P>
   To which from the back came, ``That would be possible only if we
had a flip to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
