A7781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-20 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Friday, July
21.
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO-FESTIVAL (New York) _ It often seems these days that no
aspect of our private and communal lives is shielded from the
patient, prying lens of the video camera. From amateur pornography
to security surveillance loops, from home movies of weddings,
childbirths and family reunions to C-Span and ``Big Brother,''
video records and shapes what we know of reality. So, what kind of
shape are we in, anyway? One place to look for an answer might be
at the New York Video Festival, which opens tonight and runs at the
Walter Reade theater at Lincoln Center through next Wednesday. By
Carol Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ART-EXHIBITS (Undated) _ The fresh crop of shows in museums
outside New York City this summer include several about artists
prominent around the same time: ``Calder in Connecticut'' at the
Wadsworth Athenaeum, Philip Guston at Yale and Frank O'Hara at the
Parrish in Southampton on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INNOCENT-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ In an exuberant celebration
of Russian playwright Alexander Ostrovsky's vision that also offers
a master class in acting, the Vakhtangov Theater of Moscow is
presenting ``Innocent as Charged'' as part of the Lincoln Center
Festival. By Wilborn Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   BOLSHOI-BALLET-REVIEW (New York) _ Review of the Bolshoi
Ballet's performance of Balanchine's ``Symphony in C.'' By Anna
Kisselgoff.
</P>
<P>
   BE-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Review of April Smith's ``Be the
One.'' By Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   ALICE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Andre Techine's new film, ``Alice
and Martin,'' like his earlier masterpieces ``Ma Saison Preferee''
and the scandalously underrated ``Wild Reeds,'' is full of gorgeous
photography, swift, elegant editing and meticulously composed
scenes. By A.O. Scott.
</P>
<P>
