<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7785 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-NINERS-NORTON-HNS     07-20 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-NORTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ERS' NORTON SAYS HIS TEAM DOESN'T INTIMIDATE FOES LIKE THE
OLD DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BRUCE ADAMS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Ken Norton Jr. is quick to put a handle on
this year's 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a bitter team,'' he said, referring to ``the
embarrassment'' of last year's 4-12 record and the preseason
predictions the team could do even worse this year. ``We're not
accepting all the talk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Norton was speaking Wednesday after the first full-squad
practice at training camp at the University of Pacific. He is in
his 14th camp, and this one really is different.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since he's been with the 49ers, the defense
will undergo more than just a tune-up. There will be changes
throughout the lineup _ moves that will probably involve a number
of rookies. The defense, after being ranked worst in the league
last year, is one of the biggest issues in camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's a matter of truly coaching, truly learning and coming
together as a team,'' Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Norton has always been a vocal leader on defense. This year
he'll be doing even more on the field. He is moving to the ``Mike``
linebacker spot, a position where he'll be expected to do more in
the way of disrupting blockers and be in line to make more tackles
_ even though he's led his team in tackles eight years in a row.
Winfred Tubbs will move to Norton's old ``plugger'' position, where
he'll line up behind one of the inside defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The move will put Norton closer to rookie Julian Peterson, the
49ers' unsigned first-round pick expected to start at Lee Woodall's
old spot on the outside. Norton will serve as an on-field coach for
the rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be more of an influence to the entire team,'' he
said of his new spot. ``Now it's a matter of understanding both
sides of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the heralded Peterson, Norton said, ``Obviously we wanted
a guy in there who didn't have a drop-off (from Woodall).''
</P>
<P>
   He also is anxious for Peterson to get in camp. ``I'm hoping
they really take care of business with him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson should be joined by other inexperienced players in the
secondary, and at times along the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real challenge to help these young guys,'' Norton said.
``It's not very often you have a chance to come to a pro team and
play so early.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled his own rookie season with the Dallas Cowboys. ``I
was lucky enough to come to a veteran team and learn the ways of
the game,'' he said. ``I'm not going to mention any names because
it will show my age.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton is 33 and one of the few remaining veterans on the 49ers.
He says he doesn't dwell on his own longevity, even though more and
more of his old teammates are gone. ``I really don't think about
that much,'' he said. ``I enjoy playing the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That enjoyment is apparent. Norton is perhaps the most
demonstrative player on the team. That won't change even though
he's taking on the role of elder.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, my outlook doesn't change,'' he said. ``I'm going to
be as vocal as I've always been. It always comes naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton was jovial after practice until someone asked how it felt
going into a camp when the 49ers were not going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never come to training camp without that expectation,`` he
said, putting a face on his image of the 49ers as a bitter team.
``I still have that expectation. . . . That's why they play the
game in this league. No one knows. It doesn't look good, but . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton did acknowledge that it will be a tough season, noting
that the 49ers would no longer be winning many games by
intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   Appropriately enough, for the son of a former heavyweight boxing
champion, he compared the old 49ers to the old Mike Tyson _ both,
he noted, often won by intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you win before you fight the game,'' he said. ``It's
not like that anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
