<SLUG> BC-KASHMIR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourism's prosperity a memory among Kashmiris
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is the time of year when Kashmir should be teeming with
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, they flocked to the lush Himalayan valley of apple
orchards and majestic poplar trees and skied the snow-tipped peaks
surrounding it.
</P>
<P>
   Indians came here to escape much of the subcontinent's stifling
summer heat; foreigners traveled for miles to marvel at the beauty
of land and history. They stayed in hotels lining The Boulevard,
Srinagar's wide avenue circling the legendary Dal Lake, or in the
thousands of intricately carved wooden houseboats bearing such
names as Young Monalisa, Blue Moon or Paradise.
</P>
<P>
   But paradise in Kashmir has since been lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kashmir was India's No. 1 tourist spot until 1989, when urban
terrorism started rearing its ugly head,'' said Ronjon Lahiri,
assistant director for the Government of India Tourist Office in
New York. ``Suddenly, Kashmir was wiped off the map. Just like
that, it was devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   South Asia's top tourist destination is now one of its most
violent battlegrounds: The 11-year-old Islamic insurgency in
India's northernmost state, known as Jammu and Kashmir, has left
50,000 dead. The militants say they are fighting for ``azadi,'' or
freedom, from predominantly Hindu India, under whose thumb they
feel persecuted. Some even want to become a part of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In response, India has deployed massive numbers of troops in
Kashmir to protect territory it has fought to keep in three armed
conflicts with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   There are few Kashmiris who have not felt the economic impact of
the war on a region dependent on tourist money _ almost 20 percent
of the state's gross domestic product originates in tourism. So for
the staffs at the 366 hotels and guesthouses, the owners of 1,089
houseboats, the agents at 147 travel outlets and the operators of
2,350 shikaras (boat-taxis) as well as the countless handicraft
artisans and pashmina shawl weavers, the decline in tourism has
been difficult to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business used to be so good that even in the middle of winter,
when it is so cold here, we had tourists in our houseboats,'' said
Mohammad Shera, whose family has owned a Dal Lake houseboat for
generations. ``Now it is zero.''
</P>
<P>
   Shera spends his days waiting with other houseboat owners at the
owners' union in central Srinagar, opposite the Tourist Reception
Center, hoping to lure a visitor or two.
</P>
<P>
   Mazoor Mahmood Ghasi is in the same predicament. Out of
desperation, the 32-year-old college graduate abandoned the family
houseboat business when there was no food left in his kitchen. His
father-in-law sold his houseboat and Ghasi purchased instead an
auto-rickshaw, an open three-wheeled vehicle that is a common and
cheap mode of transport in Srinagar, as it is in most Indian
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to wear good clothes. We had clean faces,'' Ghasi
said. ``Now look at us. We look like beggars on the street. Our
families are starving. I have studied economics in college and now
I am driving an auto.''
</P>
<P>
   For people like Ghasi and Shera, there was a glimmer of hope
last year after a government-sponsored campaign to revive tourism
attracted a decent number of visitors. But their hopes were quickly
dashed when a two-month conflict between India and Pakistan broke
out in May atop the peaks in Kargil. An airline hijacking last
December involving Kashmiri separatists caused a further scare.
</P>
<P>
   Still, at the start of this year's tourist season _ which
typically runs from April to October _ the government tried once
again to jump-start things by offering 30 percent discounts on
travel and lodging and by launching several marketing campaigns.
Optimistic state tourism officials said they hoped to attract
270,000 tourists to Kashmir this year. That is far less than half
of the record 700,000 tourists who set foot in Kashmir in 1988, the
year before the insurgency began.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer, the violence appears to be surging again as a
variety of factors continues to diminish prospects for a peaceful
compromise to ``the Kashmir problem.'' Among them is the Indian
government's rejection of the Kashmiri legislature's request for
political autonomy and a reported increase in deaths of Kashmiris
detained by the Indian army.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a militant hurled a grenade at a military bunker in
Srinagar, injuring a dozen people. The day before, two people were
killed near the Tourist Reception Center. A few weeks ago, a
terrorist bomb hidden in a fruit cart exploded along the banks of
Dal Lake and shattered all the windows of the Welcome Hotel, one of
Srinagar's most popular tourist residences. Many of the other
hotels have long been occupied by special units of the Indian army.
And just this week, police reported the killings of three Buddhist
monks and the abduction of a German tourist.
</P>
<P>
   These are only some of the violent incidents that have marred
the 2000 tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   ``God knows what will happen here,'' said Bashir Ahmed, who
transports people across Dal Lake on his shikara. Ahmed said he
recalls having as many as three to four customers a day. ``Now I am
lucky to have five customers who will ride my shikara in a whole
month. There is nothing left here.''
</P>
