<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7815 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-20 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PRIESTLY VIEWS OF ABORTION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Priests for Life, a group of Catholic clerics,
has launched a countrywide ad campaign to convince voters to
support candidates solely on the basis of their position on
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The national director of the group, the Rev. Frank A. Pavone,
says the campaign is aimed not only at anti-abortion voters but at
pro-choice voters and candidates who might change their mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the public to understand abortion as it is, as an act
of violence,'' Pavone told the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   With all due respect, the public might think twice about
accepting 6,000 Roman Catholic priests' version of ``abortion as it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Priests for Life reflects the Catholic hierarchy's dug-in,
intractable stance on abortion, which is an extension of its
dug-in, intractable stance on birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Both have root systems that run deep into _ and feed off of _
ancient (and not-so ancient) church misogyny, superstition and
contradictory reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   In his superb new book, ``Papal Sin: Structures of Deceit,''
Pulitzer Prize-winning author Gary Wills provides a detailed (and
depressing) look at that root system.
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the system is a perpetual disconnect between
church leaders and the whole of female reality. When it comes to
women _ be it their sexuality, reproductive capabilities or their
general value as human beings _ the authoritative Catholic Church
often has been the worst place to go for a valid account of the
subject ``as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, as Wills describes, this is the same church that
taught and made policy for centuries on Aristotle's notion of
``natural'' male superiority. As St. Thomas Aquinas argued in the
13th century:
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of nature's own operation, a woman is inferior and a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Females were considered inferior for a variety of reasons,
ranging from Eve's role in the allegory of The Fall to women's
``unclean'' menstrual cycles and their supposed sexual
insatiability.
</P>
<P>
   Albert the Great, who as Aquinas' teacher helped sow
intellectual seeds in the future saint's brain, posited an
imaginative theory of female inferiority:
</P>
<P>
   ``The woman contains more liquid than the man, and it is a
property of liquid to take things up easily and to hold onto them
poorly. Liquids are easily moved, hence women are inconstant . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   So impressively argued were these and other bizarre ideas of
``natural'' law, that the Catholic hierarchy developed its truly
perverse _ but long-standing _ position on sex itself: That it was
a sin unless its aim was procreation.
</P>
<P>
   How perverse did things get?
</P>
<P>
   Aquinas (again) believed that any position of sexual intercourse
other than the man on top was ``unnatural'' and thus a sin. Worse,
he wrote that INCEST was less of a sin than contraception because,
with incest, there was an unimpeded opportunity for procreation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the 13th century anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic hierarchy STILL teaches and preaches that it is
against God's natural law to prevent procreation while engaging in
sexual intercourse.
</P>
<P>
   And, as Wills observes:
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vatican has some of the same problems with abortion that
it has with contraception. Neither is mentioned in either Jewish
scripture or the New Testament _ you would think it might have been
condemned if it held such a high place on the list of crimes as
modern religious leaders give it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since there is no revealed teaching on the matter, the
argument against abortion must be made from natural reason, and
that brings it within the Vatican conception of natural law that
has been discredited with regard to contraception.''
</P>
<P>
   A practicing Catholic who is devoted to his church, not its
hierarchy, Wills spends an entire chapter examining the Vatican's
unenlightened, hypocritical and theologically unsound position on
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a fetus is ``a person'' or _ ``as the Vatican
teaches, every fertilized human ovum contains a human soul . . .
and baptism is needed for a soul freed from original sin to enter
heaven'' _ why doesn't the church insist on baptizing fetuses?
</P>
<P>
   And if abortion is ``murder,'' why make an exception because the
mother's life is in danger?
</P>
<P>
   If one takes this popular anti-abortion argument to its logical
end, Wills notes, there can be no exception:
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fetus and the mother have equal status as persons, the
natural and not the inflicted death should be preferred.''
</P>
<P>
   None of which is to say that Gary Wills presumes to tell the
public how to ``understand abortion as it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It is merely to say that abortion is a profound issue, and _
especially for women _ much more complex than ``an act of
violence.'' Even Catholic voters need to know there are
perspectives on the issue that reflect its complexity more
accurately than the view of 6,000 men who have vowed to toe the
company line.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
