<SLUG> BC-IVOR-WALL-STREET-ON-TELEVISION-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION GETS BULLISH ON WALL STREET 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Tom Everett
Scott in a scene from ``The $treet'' and George Newbern in a scene
from ``Bull.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Back in l987, Michael Douglas clinched a Best Actor Oscar when,
in Oliver Stone's ``Wall Street,'' he assumed the role of rapacious
financier Gordon Gekko and told the movie-going world that ``Greed
is good.''
 &HT;    Now, 13 years later, television finally seems to have gotten the
message.
 &HT;    In the next few weeks two cable networks _ Turner Network
Television and the FX network _ will launch new, hour-long dramas
set in the adrenaline-fueled world of high finance.
 &HT;    Turner's ``Bull,'' debuting at 10 p.m. on Aug. 15, is about a
bunch of young hotshots from Wall Street who break away from their
long-established company to set up a new enterprise. It stars an
ensemble cast of mostly unknown young actors, plus a few familiar
faces _ Stanley Tucci as a financial shark and Donald Moffatt as
the patriarch of their old firm, known as ``The Kaiser.''
 &HT;    Fox's ``The $treet'' _ penned by writer/producer Darren Star,
who created ``Melrose Place,'' ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and ``Sex
and the City'' _ has an ensemble cast seemingly more concerned with
the bedroom than the boardroom.
 &HT;    Again, the show is cast primarily with unknowns playing a group
of ``boy's club'' stock traders who run the offices of the
venerable Balmont Stevens Inc.
 &HT;    On the big screen, of course, Hollywood has flirted with high
finance as far back as the 1950s, with films such as ``Executive
Suite'' (l954) and ``The Man in the Gray Flannel Suit'' (l956).
``Wall Street'' offered an intriguing insider's look into the world
of mergers-and-acquisitions, while HBO's ``Barbarians at the Gate''
(l993) was a harsh but hilarious look at the takeover practices of
blue-chip American companies.
 &HT;    Other big-business-themed movies include ``Bonfire of the
Vanities'' (l990), ``The Hudsucker Proxy'' (l994) and this year's
``Boiler Room,'' which chronicled the life of a broker (Giovanni
Ribisi) peddling his investment wares from a back-room telephone.
 &HT;    This year's ``American Psycho'' hits some kind of new high in
having Christian Bale blend 1980s decadence with good,
old-fashioned gore, while the updated ``Hamlet'' sets the dirty
deeds at Elsinore in New York, with the no-longer-prince (Ethan
Hawke) vying with his uncle for control of the Denmark Corporation.
 &HT;    Now you can have all the vicious, no-holds-barred tumult of Wall
Street in your own living room. But in ``The $treet,'' which will
air Wednesdays at 9 p.m., the real action isn't on the trading
floor _ it starts only after the closing bell sounds, as we get an
intimate peek into the private lives of these dealers and the women
and men they love.
 &HT;    For example, the opening scene finds one of the young traders,
looking more like a male model than a financial wizard, rolling
around in bed with his nubile fiancee, his attention torn between
her and the stock-exchange figures flashing on their bedroom
television screen.
 &HT;    Star is unapologetic about his show's emphasis on copulation
over capitalization.
 &HT;    ``Sex and money are both powerful motivators,'' he says.
 &HT;    Showing a visitor around the cavernous Stage 29 at the Warner
Bros. studios in Burbank, Calif. _ remade into the high-tech,
razzle-dazzle offices of HSD Capital, headquarters for ``Bull's''
young entrepreneurs _ writer/producer/creator Michael Chernuchin,
best known for ``L.A. Law,'' says he spent more than a decade
peddling his idea to the major television networks, without
success.
 &HT;    ``Every time I pitched the idea,'' he recalls, ``the networks
told me that nobody cares about people that make money, because
it's too elite a world. But something has happened in the last
couple of years _ the stock market has become a national pastime
and, thanks to the Internet, everybody is in the market. Nearly 60
percent of all Americans own stock.
 &HT;    ``It's no longer just for the Gordon Gekkos of the world who
understand the street,'' Chernuchin says. ``It's an open book _
anybody can get involved.''
 &HT;    The dialogue in ``Bull'' is so jammed with financial jargon that
Turner has provided the media with a four-page ``cheat sheet'' of
financial lingo, from ``bull market'' and ``blue chip'' _ no prizes
for knowing those _ to esoterica such as ``churning'' (excessive
trading of a client's account in order to increase the broker's
commissions) and ``fallen angel'' (bonds that are heavily
downgraded).
 &HT;    Nonetheless, Chernuchin doesn't think that ``Bull'' risks being
too sophisticated for its audience.
 &HT;    ``In the early days of `NYPD Blue,' when David Caruso and Dennis
Franz were talking about `DD5s,' nobody knew what they were,'' he
says. ``But by episode 5, everyone knew. The same with `E.R.' _
they still use phrases I haven't a clue about.
 &HT;    ``On `Law and Order' I think I helped explain the law to
America,'' he concludes, ``and we're going try and do that in
`Bull,' using real terms and real business deals.
 &HT;    ``I give people credit _ they'll catch on.''
 &HT;    Chernuchin, who wrote more than 100 scripts for ``L.A. Law'' and
is himself a lawyer, says he's following the news in The Wall
Street Journal and won't hesitate to take advantage of
up-to-the-minute plot lines such as Mafia involvement in
overinflating penny stocks or stock-market crashes.
 &HT;    It may seem risky to have two Wall Street-themed shows launching
simultaneously, but Chernuchin laughs off the idea of any challenge
from ``The $treet.''
 &HT;    ``I think the shows are very different,'' he says. ``We're going
for a more sophisticated audience. Darren Star is a great writer,
and he does what he does _ it's the `Beverly Hills 90210'/`Melrose
Place,' who's-sleeping-with-whom type of show. And we're not doing
that. With this stuff, you can also learn.''
 &HT;    The current stock-market boom make both shows very timely, but
Chernuchin insists that his is more than simply an opportunistic
tie-in to the new world of stock options, IPOs and overnight
millionaires.
 &HT;    ``It's about the entrepreneurial spirit in America that made the
country great,'' he says. ``We're trying to do the history of
America through the eyes of these six young people. So I hope that
even people who don't like Wall Street will tune in to our show.''
 &HT;    In the pilot episode of ``Bull,'' Tucci appears as Hunter Lasky,
a coldhearted financial wizard who tells the new bucks: ``I learned
a long time ago that America is not about Mom, baseball or apple
pie _ America's about ownership.''
 &HT;    Chernuchin agrees.
 &HT;    ``I'm from a family of entrepreneurs,'' he says, ``and I think
that theme comes across in my writing and the way I look at the
world. The premise of our show is these people leaving a big firm
and starting on their own. It happens all the time, in every
field.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The $treet,'' consult the Fox
Broadcasting Web site at www.fox.com. For further information on
``Bull,'' consult the official Web site at
www.tnt.turner.com/series/bull. And don't forget to visit The New
York Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate
for information on Hollywood Stars and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
