<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7832 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-20 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN HORSES COULD ROAM THE HEAVENS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., France, China)  By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Scythians, the fierce nomadic tribes of Central Asia that
swept as far west as the Danube from the eighth to the fourth
century B.C., did not limit themselves to plundering Europe.
Skilled horsemen, they rampaged across ancient Eurasia as far east
as China. ``Their country is the back of a horse,'' Herodotus
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese did not like what was happening. ``The Chinese
finally realized that those who controlled the cavalry controlled
the world,'' said Jim Lally, a Manhattan dealer in Chinese art.
``It was a whole new technology.'' So they formed their own mounted
cavalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important Chinese appropriation from its nomadic
neighbors was horseback riding and mounted warfare,'' said Bill
Cooke, director of the International Museum of the Horse at the
Kentucky Horse Park in Lexington, Ky. So, Cooke said, ``to explore
the significance of the horse in the unification of China and in
the exchange of culture with the Western world along the Silk
Road,'' he organized ``Imperial China: The Art of the Horse in
Chinese History.'' The exhibition runs through Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Four years in the planning, it is one of the largest shows of
Chinese artifacts ever seen in the United States. It includes more
than 350 artifacts valued at $100 million, with terra cotta tomb
sculptures, a reconstructed chariot with its original bronze
fittings from about 200 B.C., horses in carved jade, gilded bronze
and porcelain, and colorful scroll paintings.
</P>
<P>
   By 307 BC, Bill Cooke said, King Wu Ling of the state of Zhao,
near the present-day northern border of China, issued an imperial
decree that soldiers stop wearing their long robes and adopt
nomadic dress so they could ride astride in battle just like their
enemies. The soldiers protected their homeland, and before long the
horse became an object of great affection in Chinese culture.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the horse has had a special place in China's social,
religious, economic and military life ever since the Chinese
domesticated it for meat, milk and hides about 3000 B.C.
``Throughout China's long and storied past, no animal has impacted
its history as greatly as the horse,'' Cooke said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese believed the ``heavenly horse,'' like the dragon,
was capable of flight, even of carrying his rider to the ``home of
the immortals'' in the next world. The noble horse inspired ancient
philosophers, poets, writers and artists.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Chinese were not the first to ride horses, they are
credited with perfecting two of the most significant inventions in
terms of world history: the harness and the stirrup, which
ultimately became as important as China's two other fabled
creations, paper and gunpowder.
</P>
<P>
   In the exhibition are some of the earliest life-size sculptures
of Chinese horses and their riders. Excavated from a tomb in
Shaanxi province in 1977, a cavalryman and his horse are part of
the terra cotta army commissioned for the tombs of the Qin dynasty
(221 to 207 B.C.). The unglazed horse is saddled up, with studs and
tassel decorating his saddle. His master leads him by the reins.
The cavalryman wears a tight cap, a short robe, an armored vest,
tight trousers and boots. The duo is among 116 cavalrymen and
horses discovered in the same excavation.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the Han dynasty (206 B.C. to A.D. 220), Chinese
emperors realized the need to import horses of superior stock to
beat back the barbarians' ever more daring raids. ``China's very
survival relied on its equestrian prowess,'' Cooke writes.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining better horses by importing them was not easy, however.
In the second century B.C., Emperor Han Wudi sent an expedition to
Turkmenistan (then called Ferghana) to buy that region's prized
Akhal-Teke, an ancient Eurasian breed of desert horse that was
tall, fast, strong and required little food or water. (It is
thought to be the forerunner of the English thoroughbred.) The
Chinese called them ``horse of heaven'' or the ``thousand-li'' _
that is, a horse that could run 1,000 li _ a li is about a third of
a mile _ without tiring.
</P>
<P>
   The ruler of Ferghana refused to sell his horses and killed the
envoys. The emperor decided to take the horses by force. He sent
6,000 cavalrymen and 20,000 soldiers to Ferghana. The campaign was
a disaster. Half the force died in the mountains and deserts en
route; the rest were badly defeated in battle. They straggled home
two years later, only to face a furious emperor.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, the emperor decided to send yet a larger army. As
Cooke explained, this expeditionary force of 60,000 soldiers and
30,000 horses went West with a herd of 100,000 cattle to sustain
them.
</P>
<P>
   After a 40-day siege of Ferghana, the Chinese collected 3,000
horses, 2,000 of which perished on the return journey. It turned
out that only 50 of the captured horses were of the prized breed.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the subjugation of Ferghana persuaded other tribes
to cooperate with the Han rulers, ultimately resulting in the
opening of the Silk Road. Thereafter, the Chinese traded silk and
tea for horses.
</P>
<P>
   The artistic depictions of horses most associated with China are
the magnificent terra cotta horses of the Tang dynasty (A.D. 618 to
907), which remain treasured works of art in the West today.(The
record price for one is $6.1 million at Sotheby's London in
December 1989.)
</P>
<P>
   To the Tang, the horse was not only a military necessity but
also a status symbol. The Tang used horses for battle, hunting,
dressage and polo. Women were allowed to ride. One particularly
charming figure in the show is a painted female tomb figure on
horseback. She sports a wide-brimmed black hat and a red flowered
jacket. Her yellow horse has a red mane and red spots like a modern
appaloosa.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the Chinese, who were a sedentary civilization, the horse
was a source of joy and pleasure,'' Lally said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about another Tang horse with a female rider in the
exhibition, this one glazed in rare blue as well as green and gold,
Lally said: ``The flying-hooves stance is unusual. These horses are
from the great artistic center Xian, which was to Tang China what
Paris was to Napoleonic France.'' Xian is near the site of the
terra cotta army.
</P>
<P>
   Torkom Demirjian, director of the Ariadne Galleries in
Manhattan, pointed out the quality of the Chinese bronze horse
trappings in the show. Demirjian sells some Tang horses, but he is
a specialist in Scythian and Thraco-Scythian objects, including
horse trappings. He noted the similarities, saying, ``The Chinese
had extensive relations with these nomadic peoples long before we
think they did.'' He is so impressed with the workmanship of his
gold Scythian horse and chariot trappings that he is taking them to
Paris to sell at the Biennale des Antiquaires in September.
</P>
<P>
   Cooke said 80,000 people had visited the Kentucky exhibition
since it opened on May 1. He said arrangements with Chinese
officials have been problem-free from the start. When he first went
to China to discuss doing a show, he was introduced to Zhang Ting
Hao, director general of the Administrative Bureau of Museums and
Archaeological Data of Shaanxi province, at a banquet. He told
Zhang his ideas, and Zhang replied that he had written his master's
thesis on the role of the horse in Chinese history. ``That was
it,'' Cooke recalled. ``In 24 hours, we went from an idea to a
10,000-square-foot installation.`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
