<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT     07-20 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO: HOW GROSS-OUT GOT THAT WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They wouldn't deign to in a million years, but those who deplore
the adolescent vulgarity in films like ``Scary Movie'' might want
to sit in on a commentary track done for the recent DVD of
``Kentucky Fried Movie'' (1977) from Anchor Bay. The important
thing (only thing) to keep in mind is that John Landis made the
film, really nothing more than a string of gags, the same year he
made ``National Lampoon's `Animal House,''' the gross-out classic
usually cited as a harbinger of the current mess.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Animal House' was a hugely successful film, with 50 or 60
imitators,'' Landis said the other day. ``There was another one
this year: `Road Trip.''' Early signs of the genre are apparent in
``Kentucky Fried Movie.'' A man with a solid sense of humor about
himself and his work, Landis said he had agreed to the commentary
only after Anchor Bay invited his collaborators, the writers Jim
Abrahams, Jerry Zucker and David Zucker and the producer Robert K.
Weiss, to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``Kentucky Fried'' could be plugged in about anywhere
today: reclaimed oil extracted from teen-agers' faces; Dino the
Gorilla, who throws a King Kong-sized tantrum when it is suggested
that he is impotent; fly zipping, nose picking, posterior
scratching, excrement smearing. ``Now's a good time to pull the
plug on that machine that's been keeping your daughter alive all
these months,'' a woman advises in one of the skits.
</P>
<P>
   Landis was 27 at the time, and today he and his colleagues watch
it all with a mix of hilarity and consternation. The Zuckers,
participants in many another piece of silly business, from
``Airplane!'' to the ``Naked Gun'' movies, were an earlier version
of the Farrelly brothers, makers of ``There's Something About
Mary'' and the current ``Me, Myself and Irene.'' Together, they
prod each other's memories, reacting in astonishment at some of the
bits.
</P>
<P>
   Landis, sounding serious, said the man in the gorilla suit had
gone on to win five Academy Awards. All the extras are either
somebody's cousin or the Zuckers, who fill in everywhere. Jerry
Zucker is thrown through a wall by the gorilla. ``This guy actually
went on to do porno,'' Landis said about one actor. There is plenty
of sex in ``Kentucky Fried Movie,'' and of the variety present
movie raters would be none too pleased with. ``That would get an
NC-17 now,'' Landis exclaims during an explicit shower scene. For
some reason, the video carries an R rating.
</P>
<P>
   On the disc the director says that when he went to make the
movie, he was thrown out of every studio, so he did what everybody
did: ``Look for a real estate guy with disposable income.'' In an
interview he made two basic observations about outrageous comedy.
First, the movie business follows the money, which is as
advantageous after ``There's Something About Mary'' as it was after
``Animal House.'' Second, it's not the joke, but the audience's
perception of who is telling the joke.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Python, for example, got away with a lot because of its
perceived intellect and sophistication. `` `Mary' is a complicated
case,'' he said. ``I think it ultimately worked because of Cameron
Diaz. If she wasn't in the movie, it wouldn't have.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW VIDEO RELEASES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   `THE BEACH'
</P>
<P>
   An American tourist named Richard (Leonardo DiCaprio) alights in
Thailand, where he knocks down jiggers of snake blood and persuades
two French contemporaries (Virginie Ledoyen and Guillaume Canet) to
help him find the perfect beach. On the way they narrowly escape
being machine-gunned by marijuana farmers before encountering a pod
of like-minded Western hedonists living communally in ``paradise.''
But while Danny Boyle's film has surface tension, Elvis Mitchell
wrote in The New York Times, ``all of DiCaprio's charisma and the
director's savvy are used to divert us from the fact that there's
not much going on.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2000. Fox. $107.37; DVD, $34.98. 120 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: July 25.
</P>
<P>
   `DROWNING MONA'
</P>
<P>
   No one in the tiny upstate New York town of Verplanck is overly
upset when Mona Dearly (Bette Midler) is sent to her demise in a
brakeless Yugo. As nasty as her name is ridiculous, Mona drew blood
every time she opened her mouth, so the real mystery around her
death is why anybody cares enough to find out who killed her. That
assignment falls to Chief Wyatt Rash (Danny DeVito), seemingly the
only reasonable person around. ``The real victims here are the
characters, who've been impaled on their own Herculean pursuit of
bad taste'' (Mitchell). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 95 minutes.
Closed captioned. R. Release date: July 15.
</P>
<P>
   `WHAT PLANET ARE YOU FROM?'
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the paranoid creeps he has played on television
and as a stand-up comic, Gary Shandling plays a man who would
simply like to impregnate a woman so he can take the child back to
his home planet. At a meeting of Alcoholics Anonymous, he comes
across Susan (Annette Bening), a freaked-out real estate agent who
becomes the emotional center of the film. As one of the writers of
Mike Nichols' film, Shandling gives himself plenty of space to work
the room, which leads to riffs about aliens, spirituality and other
topics. He may have become a fine actor over the years, ``but he's
finnicky and brittle here'' (Mitchell). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2000. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD, $24.95. 104 minutes.
Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   `RIDE WITH THE DEVIL'
</P>
<P>
   The Civil War era has never looked quite the way it does in Ang
Lee's chilly, dramatically skimpy epic about a group of
pro-Southern bushwhackers waging war along the Kansas-Missouri
border. Far from ``Gone With the Wind,'' austere farmhouses and
primitive frontier towns are better suited to an anthropological
study. The story focuses on two of the bushwhackers (Tobey Maguire
and Skeet Ulrich) and leads to a stunning re-creation of the
guerrilla raid on Lawrence, Kan., led by William Clarke Quantrill,
but the meditative quality and attention to detail ``keep the story
at a distance'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   2000. Universal. $99.36: DVD, $24.98. 138 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   `THE INDIAN TOMB'
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Lang didn't get around to directing a film of the same
title until 1959. Almost 40 years earlier, he co-wrote Joe May's
silent epic about the Maharajah of Eschnapur, who loses his wife to
a dashing British officer and determines to destroy him and
imprison her forever in a magnificent tomb he will have built
expressly for the purpose. Bring on the tigers, cobras, 3,000
extras (all filmed on May's 50-acre movie lot in Germany) and
Conrad Veidt as the vengeful, sadistic potentate. 1921. $79.95.
Information: (800) 551-8304.
</P>
<P>
   `IDENTIFICATION OF A WOMAN'
</P>
<P>
   It may not be one of Michelangelo Antonioni's best, but
Antonioni is Antonioni and the movie is available for the first
time on video. Tomas Milian stars as an actor caught between two
women (Daniela Silverio and Christine Boisson). The actors aren't
bad, but ``there are still a number of red herrings drying in the
sun when the film ends,'' Vincent Canby wrote in The New York
Times. 1982. $79.95. 131 minutes. Italian with English subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   `QUIET DAYS IN HOLLYWOOD'
</P>
<P>
   Here's an early look at Hilary Swank before all the ruckus over
``Boys Don't Cry,'' for which she won the Oscar as best actress.
Josef Rusnak's film presents seven unconnected vignettes about a
tawdry Hollywood world of gangsters, teen-age runaways and assorted
would-be's and hangers-on. 1995. $89.95. 95 minutes. R.
</P>
</TEXT>
