<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7840 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-20 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AMERICA'S FICKLE-FINGERED DRIVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Maybe it's a good thing evolution is slow and
can't keep up with technology. Otherwise humans would be evolving
into land octopuses.
</P>
<P>
   We'd be driving our cars using one hand to dial a cell phone,
another hand for personal grooming, two hands to fiddle with the
global positioning system and the stereo, two hands to type e-mail
and two more hands to handle the Whopper, fries and Coke.
</P>
<P>
   We'd still be holding the wheel with our knees.
</P>
<P>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration reported
Tuesday that 4,000 accidents a year are caused by distracted
drivers, and American industry is constantly inventing new sources
of distraction to add to the inside of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   You can get satellite global positioning systems to tell you the
exact latitude and longitude of your car, even if you can't tell
when you're crossing the yellow line.
</P>
<P>
   You can get on-board computers, perfect for e-mailing accident
reports to your insurance company.
</P>
<P>
   You can get TVs for the back seat, which is awash in the
distraction department. The kids will be a lot quieter, except when
they say, ``There's nothing good on. Are we there yet?''
</P>
<P>
   God forbid they tune into Ricki Lake, and you start trying to
figure out what kind of freaks she has on.
</P>
<P>
   While the number of electronic options is increasing, most
Americans still can't drive and talk on the phone at the same time,
much less dial a number. You can always tell when someone is
dialing because the car slows dramatically and drifts right or
left, depending on which hand is doing the dialing.
</P>
<P>
   Now Americans are being given more electronics than the average
Boeing 747, and they don't have to pass any tests to use all this
stuff. Driving inspectors are still making drivers weave around
orange cones, when they should be seeing if drivers can make
restaurant reservations at 55 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The only hope is that cell phones cause brain cancer, and it
gets them before they get us.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the NHTSA urged drivers not to talk on cell
phones or surf the Internet. That's a little like standing in the
surf and trying to keep the tide from coming in, especially since
the safety agency has no legal powers.
</P>
<P>
   A vehicle safety expert for the auto industry suggested that
automakers might start looking into high-tech solutions for
high-tech distractions, like putting calls on hold if automatic
sensors detect complicated traffic situations.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, they should put cars on hold in those situations.
</P>
<P>
   These are the same auto industry guys who didn't want to give us
seat belts because they cost too much. Now they say they can equip
cars like A-6 bombers, with defensive countermeasures to detect
approaching drunken drivers and little old ladies stepping into
crosswalks.
</P>
<P>
   Cars are already loaded with offense electronic systems, very
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   As if the high-tech threats aren't enough on the road, some of
the biggest threats involve the lowest-tech system of all _ the
ingestion of food.
</P>
<P>
   The food industry is putting all its technological genius into
encouraging us to eat, drink and drive at the same time _ while
dialing and keyboarding with the other hand, of course.
</P>
<P>
   American society has sunk so low that 7-Eleven has begun selling
macaroni and cheese on a push-up stick.
</P>
<P>
   The sociological rationale for one-handed meals and cell phones
is that Americans lead high-pressure lives, in which they have to
stay wired to the world at all times, and don't have time to sit
down to real meals.
</P>
<P>
   This is not life. Technology was supposed to make our lives
easier and more pleasurable, and now we're prisoners in a world
science-fiction writers never could imagine.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the cars of the future were supposed to drive us
automatically from place to place _ no hands required, no BMW
phonies on phones coming up fast behind.
</P>
<P>
   Food of the future was supposed to come out of squeeze tubes,
but no one thought it would be macaroni and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Forget mac-on-a-stick. Why don't they install in-car
naso-gastric feeding tubes, and then we'll be really wired.
</P>
<P>
   Does that come in nacho?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
