<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: CALDER'S EAGLE LANDS IN SEATTLE; EXPANSIONS IN HARTFORD
AND DENVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Texas, Wash., Colo., Conn., Britain, Germany, Japan)   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALDER'S `EAGLE' LANDS IN SEATTLE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For a year, ``Eagle,'' a monumental sculpture by Alexander
Calder, has stood in front of the Philadelphia Museum of Art. Now
the 39-foot-high biomorphic steel structure is heading to Seattle,
where it is to become the centerpiece of a sculpture park scheduled
to open in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Art Museum announced this week that it had acquired
the Calder for its new Olympic Sculpture Park, a six-acre site
downtown. The sculpture, which experts say cost more than $10
million, was purchased with a donation by Jon and Mary Shirley,
Seattle collectors, to the museum's acquisition fund.
</P>
<P>
   People close to the deal said Thomas Gibson, a London dealer,
represented the Shirleys on behalf of the museum. He declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   One mystery is the name of the seller, a group of investors
whose identity is being withheld by the Seattle museum.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, ``Eagle'' was owned by the Fort Worth
National Bank and stood in front of its headquarters in Texas. It
was bought by Loutex, the Fort Worth real estate development
company that bought the bank's building. Loutex sold it to the
investors' group several years ago. In April 1999, it left Texas
after unsuccessful efforts to find a buyer who would keep it in
Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was anybody willing to buy it for Philadelphia. ``The Calder
was lent to the city of Philadelphia through the Calder
Foundation,'' said Anne d'Harnoncourt, director of the Philadelphia
Museum of Art. ``It would have been great if a donor had acquired
it and given it to the museum, but that didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   R.C. Rower, a grandson of the artist and the director of the
Calder Foundation, said the reason might have been that ``everyone
there knows the foundation is going to be bringing large-scale
works to Philadelphia.'' A Calder Museum is planned for a site
across the Benjamin Franklin Parkway right across from the Rodin
Museum. ``We hope to have chosen the architect by early August,''
Rower said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eagle,'' made in 1971, two years before the artist died, is to
arrive in Seattle in the fall. ``We're working to find a temporary
location until the park opens,'' said Mimi Gates, director of the
Seattle Art Museum. The Calder is the first piece earmarked for the
sculpture park.
</P>
<P>
   A BIGGER ATHENAEUM
</P>
<P>
   The Wadsworth Athenaeum in Hartford, Conn., is embarking on its
first expansion in 30 years. The oldest art museum in the United
States, it occupies five contiguous buildings constructed over 125
years. The expansion will improve circulation and connections
between the existing buildings and add a new building to house at
least part of the permanent collections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many objects have been languishing in our storerooms,''
said Elizabeth Mankin Kornhauser, the acting director. ``As our
attendance has increased, it has become more and more been
difficult to accommodate visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum has hired Fox &AMP; Fowle, New York architects best know
for the new Conde Nast building at 4 Times Square, to become what
the Athenaeum calls its ``executive architects.'' It has also asked
the artist Maya Lin to create an environmental artwork for the
museum's Main Street exterior. Lin's project is being financed in
part by a $2.5 million grant from the state of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be exploring the merger of art, architecture and
landscape, the ambiguity of what's outside and what's inside,'' Lin
said. But, she added, ``it is still too early to discuss more
specifics, other than to say that I'd like to see art from inside a
museum come outside.'' Some ideas she is considering include
creating outdoor roomlike spaces for art, perhaps using video
artists to invent lighting and commissioning site-specific pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason Lin's plans are not fully formed is that the
museum has launched an international search for for a design
architect, to be chosen by October, to design a new building and
help renovate and reorganize some of the existing structures.
</P>
<P>
   EXPANSION IN DENVER
</P>
<P>
   After an intensive six-month search, the Denver Art Museum has
selected Daniel Libeskind to design its $62.5 million expansion.
Libeskind, born in Poland and now based in Berlin, has designed a
spiral extension for the Victoria and Albert Museum in London and a
new home for the Jewish Museum in San Francisco. He is to create a
new 146,000-square-foot building, the Denver museum's first major
expansion since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   When completed in 2004, it will nearly double the size of the
museum, creating new space for special exhibitions and for its
departments of modern and contemporary art and architecture, along
with its design and graphics departments. The addition will also
include education and multimedia programming and spaces for public
events.
</P>
<P>
   The main building, a 28-sided two-tower structure completed in
1971, was designed by the Italian architect Gio Ponti, who died in
1979. The expansion will use an open area across the street. It
will include a 1,000-car garage and a connection to the existing
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time talking to different architects,'' said
Louis Sharp, the museum director. ``We developed a list of 40
architects and narrowed it down to 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The finalists _ Libeskind, Thom Mayne of Santa Monica, Calif.,
and Arata Isozaki of Tokyo _ each gave a public lecture and a
daylong workshop, which were shown on cable television.
</P>
<P>
   When the Victoria and Albert Museum released the design for its
extension, neighbors and preservationists opposed the radical glass
structure, which resembles a series of tumbling boxes set between
two ornate Victorian palaces. Still, Louis said he did not think
Libeskind was too racy for Denver. ``This is a young city,'' he
said. ``We're prepared and excited to be stepping out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
