<HEADLINE>
&HT;        GORE AND BUSH VISIONS OF SPACE PROGRAM EMERGE
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, July 20 - Space exploration may be the final
frontier of the 2000 presidential contest: Mars missions and the
rocket industry have been subjects relatively untouched by either
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet advisors to Vice President Al Gore and George W. Bush,
outlining the presumed nominees' visions for space at a Capitol
Hill event yesterday, said both candidates are developing a space
agenda. Both candidates appear to share the goal of putting humans
on Mars and investing in a sluggish aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
   The event -- coinciding with the 31st anniversary of the Apollo
11 moon landing -- was billed as the first public discussion of
space policy under the next administration. The event was attended
by space industry officials and was held by the nonpartisan group
Women in Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Walker, a former Pennsylvania congressman and now a
consultant to Bush -- the all-but-named Republican nominee -- said
voters should expect a ``new direction'' for the space program
under a Bush presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Bush would provide the ``boldness and leadership that assures
American dominance in a new millennium,'' Walker said. Walker
criticized the Clinton-Gore administration for NASA's flat budget
in recent years. ``At best they have ignored space and at worst
they have used it as a political tool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said although the Texas governor was still fine-tuning a
space agenda, its would likely entail several key principles,
including tying the space program to military ends and spurring
commercial investment. Bush has voiced strong support for building
a space-based national missile defense, a plan also supported to
varying degrees by Gore and President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush would look to give humans a ``permanent
presence on the Moon and on Mars,'' Walker said. ``I do believe a
Bush administration would aggressively pursue policies to take us
back to the Moon and on to Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   Adviser Steven O. Palmer said Gore also would back NASA's Mars
program, whose future is uncertain after the loss of two probes at
the Red Planet last year. ``The question of human exploration of
Mars is not if, but when,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Gore's experience on space issues, Palmer said Gore would
make ``wise investments'' in the aerospace industry, and support
``pushing the envelope'' in science, technology, and space
exploration. Gore supports reducing the cost of space launches by
offering tax-free bonds and loan guarantees, and reforming export
control laws that restrict companies from selling technology
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a friend, an ally, and a leader in this community,''
Palmer said. ``After his election, his door will be open to all of
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer said the vice president stands by the $60 billion
national missile defense system, which has come under intense
criticism, especially after a recent test failure. ``However, he's
unwilling to move ahead unless the technology will work, it's
affordable, and it will not disturb world peace,'' Palmer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
