<HEADER>
A7870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-TRIXIE0721-COX     07-20 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TRIXIE0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Trick's on you. At the end, you'll want your money back.
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Squint hard and you can almost see what Emily
Watson had in mind when she got involved in the painfully unfunny
``screwball film noir,'' ``Trixie.''
</P>
<P>
   After stunning performances in such sober social dramas as
``Angela's Ashes'' and ``Cradle Will Rock,'' you'd yearn to break
out into a brazenly comic role too. And it sort of made sense for
her to place her trust in director Alan Rudolph, the resolutely
offbeat filmmaker who has given affectionate showcases to actresses
from Geraldine Chaplin (''Remember My Name'') to Genevieve Bujold
(''Choose Me'') to Julie Christie (''Afterglow'').
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remains that ``Trixie'' is an embarrassment for all
concerned, as leaden and vacant a comedy as you are likely to see
all year. Or rather, as you are likely to pass on seeing.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph has a quirky storyteller's touch and an affection for
actors, but when he miscalculates, the results can be excruciating.
Ask those fans who saw his previous effort, the incoherent
adaptation of Kurt Vonnegut's ``Breakfast of Champions.''
</P>
<P>
   His latest is a strained send-up of private detective tales, the
adventures of gum-chewing, language-mangling Trixie Zurbo (Watson),
a department store security guard who yearns for some genuine
undercover work. She gets hired for graveyard shift surveillance at
a two-bit casino and stumbles onto a murder case involving a sex
scandal, an incriminating videotape and a cheesy, patently corrupt
state senator (Nick Nolte).
</P>
<P>
   In the lighting fixtures of life, Trixie is one dim bulb, a fact
that is bluntly underscored by her habit of talking in
metaphor-mixing malaprops. She goes around saying things like
``Fish or get off the pot'' and ``Grab the bull by the tail and
look him in the eye.'' What begins as an endearing,
character-revealing habit quickly grows annoying. With everything
Trixie utters sounding like Yogi Berra-isms, the joke soon
evaporates and calls attention to the artificiality of Rudolph's
script.
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, her way with words proves contagious, at least with
bumbling lothario Dermot Mulroney and with Nolte's Sen. Avery.
Actually, Avery has his own style of windy palaver that almost
suggests an intentional theme of miscommunication, but is probably
just Nolte being indulged as he improvises politico-speak. Either
way, the irritating dialogue is sheer brilliance compared with
``Trixie's'' plot, which also feels made up on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   It has something to do with an alcohol-soaked party girl (Lesley
Ann Warren, bumping and grinding her career to a screeching halt)
who falls or is pushed out a motel window to her death. Also along
to muddy matters is a would-be movie star (Brittany Murphy) who
carries multiple ID cards with varying birth years and an
ill-at-ease Nathan Lane as a casino lounge entertainer who wiles
away his life doing bad impersonations of the likes of Anthony
Newley and Humphrey Bogart.
</P>
<P>
   All of this might have been stirred into a tasty
tongue-in-cheek, Raymond Chandler-esque stew, as Rudolph's mentor
(and ``Trixie's'' producer) Robert Altman managed with 1973's ``The
Long Goodbye.'' Instead, the comedy deflates and two hours in the
dark have never felt so long.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is gamely devoted to her character and while she is
straitjacketed by the role's one dimension, there are moments that
hint at the comedian within her. Nor does Nolte rise above the
writing, though you sense him pressing hard to please.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trixie'' should have gone straight to video, or perhaps the
studio's vault. If you go to see it, check the theater's refund
policy on the way in.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
