<HEADER>
A7871 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-STEELYDAN-FORMULA0721     07-20 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEELYDAN-FORMULA0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '70s duo tries to `Do it Again,' differently
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Call it the Steely Dan formula: a little
soul, a little substance, a little satire. And, of course, all that
jazz.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the '70s and early '80s, it was a sound that defined
a creative pop ideal. Even though the duo _ guitarist Walter
Becker, now 50, and keyboardist Donald Fagen, 52 _ had its share of
hits (''Reeling in the Years,'' ``Do it Again,'' ``Peg,'' ``Rikki
Don't Lose That Number''), this wasn't exactly music for the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   It still isn't. Witness Steely Dan's first new album in 20
years, ``Two Against Nature,'' a nine-song compilation that covers
such topics as incest and murder, with the occasional romantic
ballad thrown in. It's all accompanied by a jazzy beat, clever horn
arrangements and sly, shifting harmonies. Like much of Steely Dan's
work, it occupies a place somewhere between sinister and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the members of the duo say they've ever thought
consciously about their sound. It just, well, evolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started making records, and by the third record, we
developed a style that included all the things we liked,'' says
Fagen, speaking by phone from the same tour that will bring the duo
to the MARS Music Amphitheatre on Tuesday. ``At this point, we
still don't try to go for that, but it just shakes out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is good news for dedicated Dan fans, who haven't been able
to get their hands on any new material since 1980's ``Gaucho.''
Unlike most rock splits, this wasn't the result of some scandal or
blowup. The band, which was rounded out by some of the best studio
musicians from that era, had already given up touring in the
mid-'70s, claiming it wasn't the best vehicle for promoting its
finely crafted music. By the early '80s, Becker and Fagen were
simply burned out altogether. But they did stay friends _ Becker
produced Fagen's 1993 solo album, ``Kamakiriad ``_ and in the
mid-'90s, they regrouped and hit the road.
</P>
<P>
   An album was the logical next step, lest Becker and Fagen resign
themselves to being labeled a nostalgia act. ``We're just glad we
have new material,'' says Fagen.
</P>
<P>
   And some material it is. Take your pick of shady and strange
characters _ the album is full of them. There's the vagabond who
returns home, only to find his kid cousin is suddenly a sexy,
mature woman (''Cousin Dupree''). There's the failed novelist who
now spends his directionless days toiling at a bookstore (''What a
Shame About Me''). And there are women of every age and every shade
of moral character.
</P>
<P>
   While many of the songs are written in an elusive poetic style,
there's clearly something going on. ``I think underachievement is a
kind of theme,'' Fagen says of the album. Not unlike Dylan's ``Time
Out of Mind `` album, this is rock from a middle-aged man's
perspective. The difference, of course, is that Becker and Fagen
temper their wisdom with dark humor. Who else can get away with
writing a song about incest _ and make it pure fun?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a sense of humor about it, you can almost get away
with anything,'' says Fagen. ``It's sort of a way of looking at
life itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Musically, Fagen says the group hasn't bothered to update its
sound _ there are no nods to hip-hop, no pretense of being popular:
``I don't think at this point some kind of incredible innovation is
going to happen. . . . That would be dishonest.'' But he does note
that ``there's a lot of harmonic stuff we haven't tried before,''
and Becker's guitar playing has ``become much more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His guitar style dominates the record and gives it a unity
that maybe the other albums didn't have,'' Fagen adds. But if
there's a musician who steals the show, it's saxophonist Chris
Potter, whose solo on ``West of Hollywood,'' the album's
concluding, eight-minute song, turns it into an instant jazz-rock
classic.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, radio doesn't play eight-minute songs, so don't
expect to hear ``West of Hollywood `` on Top 40 anytime soon. These
are much different times than the early '70s, when Becker and
Fagen, two literame out with something in the next couple of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
