<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-INNOCENT-THEATER-REVI     07-20 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INNOCENT-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INNOCENT AS CHARGED': SHE LEFT TOWN A WRECK, BUT CAME BACK A
STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: production notes at end of review)  
 By WILBORN HAMPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the Russian playwright Alexander Ostrovsky, all
the world was quite literally the stage, and a life in the theater
was the only honest life worth pursuing. In an exuberant
celebration of Ostrovsky's vision that also offers a master class
in acting, the Vakhtangov Theater of Moscow is presenting
``Innocent as Charged'' through this weekend as part of the Lincoln
Center Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Ostrovsky was a forerunner of what would become a revolution in
the theater. If it was Chekhov's ax that finally brought down the
cherry orchard that was 19th-century Russia, it was Ostrovsky who
honed it with dozens of plays that satirized the landed gentry and
provincial bureaucrats. Although immensely popular in his day (a
statue of him stands outside the Maly Theater in St. Petersburg),
he frequently ran afoul of the czar's censors. He was one of the
favorites of the Communist authorities during the Soviet years,
which may explain why he was seldom performed in the West.
</P>
<P>
   New York audiences unfamiliar with Ostrovsky could ask for no
better introduction than the splendidly acted and visually opulent
production from the Vakhtangov that at times takes on an almost
circus atmosphere as characters move in and out of the audience,
wander on and off stage and interrupt dialogue with snatches of
song or even, in one delightful scene, a can-can line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Innocent as Charged,'' which is played in Russian and
simultaneously translated via headphones, is an old-fashioned
melodrama in structure and theme. Seventeen years separate the
first act (in which a young unwed mother is jilted by the father
and told that her 3-year-old child has died) and the next three
acts. During the intermission that follows, the woman moves away,
changes her name and becomes a famous actress. When the audience
returns, it finds her appearing in the same town from which she
fled, a star of the Russian stage. Naturally, the child had not
died, and is now a leading actor with the local theater company.
</P>
<P>
   Mother and son, of course, eventually reunite. But it is not the
story _ dramatic and sentimental as the denouement may be _ that
earns Ostrovsky his reputation as a precursor of the modern
theater. The strength of his plays, and the fascination of the
Vakhtangov's fine staging, is in the playwright's concentration on
character development, even in the secondary roles, and the flow of
action interspersed with songs that the director Pyotr Fomenko has
given this production.
</P>
<P>
   A behind-the-scenes story to the Vakhtangov's visit was
Fomenko's refusal to join the company here, saying he was too busy
with a new production in Russia and he thought the actors needed
more rehearsal time. He need not have worried. This production has
been a huge hit in Moscow, and it is easy to see why. The play
features a cast of 13, and there is not a weak link in it. The
lessons of Konstantin Stanislavsky are alive and well in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene, the famous actress (the character of Yelena
Ivanovna Kruchinina, given a fine performance by Yuliya Borisova)
explains to her ardent admirer (Nil Dudukin, superbly played by
Yuri Yakovlev) how she manages to so accurately portray night after
night the agony of a mother who has lost her child. It is quite
simple: she, too, had lost a child, and she calls on that
experience in recreating her role. Like Hamlet's instructions to
the players, Ostrovsky's actress is giving advice that Stanislavsky
would expand on in developing his method of acting that would
dominate 20th-century theater.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the actors uses small gestures or even a simply prop to
build an indelible character. Yevgeny Kniazev, who is an
irresistible free spirit as Grigory Neznamov, the grown lost son of
the famous actress, enters with a pool cue stick and a long purple
scarf that becomes part of his persona. For Mikhail Uliyanov, who
plays Grigory's fellow actor and older sidekick, it is an old coat,
hat and a decanter of vodka. And Lyudmila Maksakova, who is a
joyous bundle of raw seductive energy as Nina Pavlovna Korinkina,
the leading lady in the provincial acting troupe, uses a
long-stemmed carnation to create a femme fatale.
</P>
<P>
   Although the simultaneous translation via headphones (in which
one person renders all the roles) is as spiritless as a United
Nations Security Council debate, Ostrovsky's humor can still filter
through (as when Dudukin, presenting a gift of caviar to Yelena,
observes ``You must eat something.'') However, one noticed that
those in the audience not needing to rely on the translation were
laughing more than those of us who were.
</P>
<P>
   The Vakhtangov production is spectacular to look at. Whoever
paved the way for the troupe to bring its wardrobe deserves a vote
of thanks. The costumes by Olga Ahmatovakaya are stunning _ richly
textured silk gowns, smartly cut suits and top hats and wonderfully
tattered rags. And Tatyana Selvinskaya's sets _ crocheted doilies,
an old Victrola, a samovar _ are like time travel to 19th-century
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the inconvenience of moving between two venues (the
opening act is played on a postage-stamp stage _ to give the feel
of a cramped apartment, no doubt _ with the spectators sitting on
bleacher-like benches) and the fire-drill atmosphere of a general
admission audience elbowing its way to unreserved seats for the
second act (played in a sort of hotel ballroom atmosphere), just
watching the Vakhtangov actors is a treat for which anyone who
loves the theater should be grateful.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `INNOCENT AS CHARGED'
</P>
<P>
   By Alexander Ostrovsky; directed by Pyotr Fomenko; sets by
Tatyana Selvinskaya; costumes by Olga Ahmatovakaya; lighting by
Vladimir Amelin. Performed in Russian with simultaneous English
translation via headsets. The Vakhtangov Theater, the State
Academic Theater of Russia, presented by the Lincoln Center
Festival 2000. At Fordham University Theater, Pope Auditorium, West
60th Street at Columbus Avenue, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Yuliya Borisova (Yelena Ivanovna Kruchinina), Lyudmila
Maksakova (Nina Pavlovna Korinkina), Yuri Yakovlev (Nil Stratonych
Dudukin), Vyacheslav Shalevich (Grigory Lvovich Murov), Yevgeny
Kniazev (Grigory Neznamov), Victor Zozouline (Petya Milovzorov),
Mikhail Uliyanov (Shmaga), Inna Alabina and Alla Kazanskaya
(Arkhipovana Gatchikha Arina), Anatoly Menchtchikov (Ivan), Yelena
Sotnikova (Lyubov Ivanovna Otradina), Nonna Grishaeva (Taisa
Ilyinishna Shelavina), Yuri Kraskov (Grigory Lvovich Murov) and
Olga Gavriliouk (Annushka).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
