<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7874 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-LILEKS-WEB-SECURITY-N     07-20 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LILEKS-WEB-SECURITY-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLIGHTLY RIGHT, SLIGHTLY WRONG IN INTERNET SECURITY DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Tuesday, July 20, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By JAMES LILEKS  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bravo: The Clinton administration wants to give e-mail the same
protections enjoyed by phone conversations. No longer can the feds
read your e-mail as they please; they'll have to wake up a judge at
3 a.m., get him to sign a warrant, and then read your mail while
the judge totters back to bed.
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder how many judges wake up every morning
thinking, ``I had that strange dream where I signed a piece of
paper again.''
</P>
<P>
   But this isn't the only online issue being decided nowadays.
There's Carnivore, DeCSS and the notion of criminal linking. Sounds
geeky and irrelevant, sure -- but these issues affect everything
from the right of artists to control their work to the government's
ability to read Grandma's mail. It's the biggest intellectual
cluster-headache in the history of intellectual property;
everyone's slightly right and slightly wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Take the FBI's Carnivore device. It consumes all incoming and
outcoming e-mail to an Internet service provider, sifting for data
that might pertain to ongoing criminal investigations. It's like an
anti-Mafia automated phone tapper that listens to every
conversation in New Jersey and sets off a bell when it hears the
phrase ``horse head inna bed.'' Effective? Sure -- and gassing
everyone in New York and taking their prints while they're
unconscious would help law enforcement assemble a useful database
for identifying criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, Carnivore would catch criminals. Might even
catch a few terrorists too stupid to use encryption. It's the old
trade-off -- freedom vs. security. On one hand it's a frightening
device, but on the other hand it's heartening: Only in America do
we learn that these devices are being considered.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if they're telling us about Carnivore, it's probably
to take away attention from Omnivore, which has been capturing
every keystroke we've made since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Next issue: copyright. Emmanuel Goldstein, a k a Eric Corley,
publisher of the hacker zine 2600 and Webmaster of 2600.org, went
to court in mid-July. He's being sued by every movie company on the
planet. Background: Linux users wanted to watch DVDs on their
machines -- not because it's a good way to watch movies, but
because everyone else could do it. (A good excuse -- for a
5-year-old.) So a Norwegian teen named Jan Johansen cracked the
code and handed out a program called DeCSS to thwart the encryption
scheme. Some used the program for piracy, and the studios feared a
real yo-ho-ho fest of movie thievery.
</P>
<P>
   For good reason. Now a pirate can e-mail a movie to his DVD
sweatshop in Shanghai and get a jump on the legitimate
distributors. No one knows exactly how artists can profit from this
new model -- perhaps in the future we'll all pay an entertainment
utility bill, charged by the bit for our music, literature and
movie downloads.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, consider the problem of the illegal link. A
link is a few bytes of code that allow someone to leap off one Web
page and land on another. It's an exit sign -- and should someone
be held liable for an exit sign? Of course not. What if it leads to
an unguarded bank vault with piles of money? If someone uses your
exit to go someplace and commit a crime, are you guilty? Probably
not. But what if you build the exit and send out fliers announcing
``Free Entrance to Unguarded Bank Vault''?
</P>
<P>
   You can what-if this to death, so let's cut to the chase: You
can't criminalize links. This would be akin to banning ``Mein
Kampf'' and forbidding World War II histories to even acknowledge
its existence. Major news sites link to many external sites, and
they always remind us that they don't endorse these sites. If
someone can be held liable for linking, then the big media
companies will think twice before linking. Then the casual user
will think twice. The link is the essence of the Web. Stifle the
idea of the link, and the Web shrivels, dies and turns into
hermetically sealed channels with no interaction. TV, in other
words. Verdict: Hackers must prevail on this point.
</P>
<P>
   Emmanuel Goldstein, of course, was the name of a political
critic in George Orwell's ''1984.'' The real Mr. Goldstein was
brought to trial at the same time that TV premiered ``Big
Brother,'' a show about people who have willingly given up their
freedom and privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Willingly. At least Orwell thought we'd put up a struggle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
