<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7876 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-VEEP-$ADV23-HNS &LR;      07-20 1355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-VEEP-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH'S VP CHOICE COULD INFLUENCE GORE'S PICK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 23)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ No one will be more closely watching Republican
George W. Bush's choice of a running mate this week than Democrat
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor's selection promises to shape the political
landscape for the fall campaign by freeing Gore to choose a
conventional Democratic running mate or forcing him to match any
bold Republican selection with a dramatic choice of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the most important decision that Bush makes
before the election,'' says Larry Sabato, a political scientist at
the University of Virginia. ``Gore's choice of a running mate is
going to be determined by what Bush does.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Nelson, a presidential scholar at Rhodes College in
Memphis, Tenn., who authored `''A Heartbeat Away'' on vice
presidential selection and succession, says Bush could throw Gore
on the defensive by choosing a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bush wants to do something bold and path breaking, the best
move on the board would be to pick Elizabeth Dole,'' says Nelson,
citing the former Republican Cabinet officer and ex-Red Cross
president who withdrew from the GOP presidential race last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``By choosing a woman, Bush would put Gore in a bind in terms of
having to come up with a `diversity pick' of his own,'' said
Nelson. ``It would be very hard for Gore to just pick another white
male.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollster John Zogby, president of the Zogby International based
in Utica, N.Y., says Bush has already overcome Democrats'
traditional edge among women voters. Bush stands almost even with
Gore among women _ 43 percent to 44 percent. By contrast, President
Clinton enjoyed a 16 percentage point edge among women voters in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's choice of Dole or New Jersey Gov. Christine Todd Whitman
might prompt Gore to give greater consideration to prominent women
Democrats, such as Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., or Maryland Lt.
Gov. Kathleen Kennedy-Townsend, daughter of the late Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is expected to announce his running mate after the
Republican convention wraps up on Aug. 3 with Bush's acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   The only woman ever chosen to run on a national ticket was then-
Rep. Geraldine Ferraro, D-N.Y., selected by Democrat Walter Mondale
to join the Democratic ticket in 1984 in a failed effort to
sidetrack Ronald Reagan's quest for a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Griffin, a political scientist and sociologist at
Vanderbilt University, says Bush's selection will signal whether
the two-term governor envisions building a victory coalition upon
hotly contested constituencies such as women, union members, Roman
Catholics and minorities _ or whether the Texan plays it safe by
choosing a trusted, reliable running mate who will cement ties with
traditional Republican loyalists such as evangelical Christians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look behind his choice and you'll see his political
strategy,'' Griffin says.
</P>
<P>
   Bush faces a unique personal challenge with his selection as
well: He has to demonstrate that he can avoid the kind of misstep
that put a cloud over his father's nomination as the Republican
presidential candidate in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Then-Vice President George H.W. Bush saw his moment of triumph
extinguished from the unanticipated controversy that erupted over
his surprise selection of then-Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle's use of family connections to win a coveted spot in the
Indiana National Guard during the Vietnam war became the focus of
the convention rather than Bush's own vision for the nation
following the two-term presidency of Republican Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush rebounded from the setback to win 54 percent of the popular
vote and 426 electoral votes in the November election, crushing
Democrat Michael Dukakis, then governor of Massachusetts. Quayle
proved such a chronic embarrassment to GOP fortunes that year that
his campaign handlers shielded him from the news media and limited
his campaign activities.
</P>
<P>
   President Bush resisted advice from some GOP advisers in 1992
that he should dump Quayle from the ticket. Instead, Bush and
Quayle went down to defeat at the hands of the all-southern ``Baby
Boom'' ticket of Clinton, then governor of Arkansas, and Gore, then
a senator from neighboring Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush is banking that extensive screening of his
prospective running mates by Dick Cheney, a widely respected former
defense secretary and one-time White House chief of staff will
avert any unforeseen embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   As Sabato put it: ``We're going to see this week whether the
Bush family has a gene that causes them to blow the choice of
running mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who cites loyalty as one of his highest priorities, said
last week that he will choose a running mate who ``can do the job,
wants the job and is willing to work'' for him as president. Bush
added: ``You want somebody who's not going to hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also is weighing the prospective running mates'
home states, gender and race.
</P>
<P>
   Bush planned to showcase his choice during a five-day, six-state
barnstorming campaign through swing states that haven't voted
Republican since 1988, before arriving at the GOP convention in
Philadelphia on Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Latest nationwide polls show that voters rarely are persuaded by
a candidate's choice of running mate. A USA Today-CNN survey last
week found that 88 percent of the respondents said they had never
voted for a candidate because of the choice of running mate and 89
percent said they had never voted against a candidate because of
the choice of running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush prepared for his decision with frequent consultations with
Cheney by phone and in person; face-to-face meetings with
prospective running mates and carefully phrased favorable comments
about potential partners designed in part to bolster their standing
in their home states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would honor requests not to be considered for the
post made by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a popular defeated rival,
and former Joint Chiefs of Staff chairman, Gen. Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Bush faced bold choices that would underscore his bid for
moderate voters, such as Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge; New Jersey
Gov. Christine Todd Whitman; New York Gov. George Pataki; and Sens.
Fred Thompson and Bill Frist, both Republicans from Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Other prospects offered Bush the chance to bolster ties with
conservative Republicans, such as Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.;
Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating; and House Budget Committee Chairman
John Kasich, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the choice, history shows that vice presidential
nominees get a hefty boost toward the presidency despite
disparaging assessments such as Vice President John Adams's
dismissal of the post as ``the most insignificant office'' ever
``contrived'' by man. Vice President John Nance Gardner, who served
during the Great Depression, said the assignment ``wasn't worth a
bucket of warm'' liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Such notorious quips came before President Franklin D. Roosevelt
wrested the selection from party elders in 1940, setting the stage
for party nominees to make personal choices with whom they could
forge the kind of seamless partnership that emerged between
President Clinton and Gore during the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The post has proven an important stepping stone into the Oval
Office even though only four vice presidents in American history
have succeeded directly to the presidency _ Adams in 1796, Thomas
Jefferson in 1800, Martin Van Buren in 1836 and George H.W. Bush in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the 12 vice presidents since World War II, including
Gore, have subsequently captured their party's nomination for
president. Five of the 10 post-war presidents had served previously
as vice president. Including Truman, Lyndon Johnson, Richard Nixon,
Gerald Ford and Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart &LR; hearstdc.com )
</P>
