r e BC-TREK-BRIAN-DOWNEY-IN-     07-20 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-BRIAN-DOWNEY-IN-LEXX-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWEEDLE NOT-SO-DUMB: BRIAN DOWNEY ON `LEXX' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Brian Downey
in a scene from ``Lexx.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    The joys of ``Lexx'' are unending for Brian Downey.
 &HT;    ``I've been chained, wrapped in plastic, covered in a gigantic
condom, strapped to a cross and immersed in freezing water in
Namibia,'' says Downey, who co-stars in the envelope-stretching
series, which on Aug. 18 will kick off its second season on Sci-Fi
Channel. ``Apart from glue on the penis, I don't know what else
they can do to me.''
 &HT;    Surely the sadistic chaps who write ``Lexx'' will think of
something, because they seem to love torturing poor Stanley Tweedle
(Downey). For those who don't follow ``Lexx'' regularly, the show
follows the offbeat, decidedly unheroic adventures of Xev (Xenia
Seeberg), a love slave coveted by Stanley, and Kai (Michael
McManus), an ageless corpse _ and, of course, 790 (Jeffrey
Hirshfield), a robot who also worships Xev. And they all trek
through space on the Lexx, a sentient ship that resembles a
colossal insect.
 &HT;    Season two will differ from last year in ways both subtle and
pronounced. Now that Seeberg has established herself as Xev, the
actress will sport blonde tresses rather than red, and her outfits
will be toned down just a tad.
 &HT;    Venturing beyond its sound stages in Halifax, Nova Scotia,
``Lexx'' will benefit visually from location shooting in Germany
and Namibia.
 &HT;    In terms of tone, look for the often-wacky humor of the past to
give way to a slightly serious feel, meaning more dramatics and
deeper relationships between the core characters. And, rather than
feature stand-alone episodes, this year's 13 episodes of ``Lexx''
will play out as so many parts of one overall story.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot of big changes,'' Downey says by telephone
from his home in Newfoundland. ``At the end of your season one, we
didn't know what to do and went into suspended animation. We took
our chances and just flew out into space.
 &HT;    ``The opening of season two, `Fire and Water,' is us floating
through space and you see that we've encountered two planets, Fire
and Water,'' he says. ``One is all water and one is the most
horrific desert planet you could ever imagine. We are boarded by
people from the Fire planet who are very, very nasty.
 &HT;    ``They wake me up first and I have no idea who they are, no idea
where we are,'' Downey says. ``All we know is that right now, as
usual with `Lexx,' we are in trouble.
 &HT;    ``During the episode we find out that we've been in suspended
animation for 4,000 years,'' continues Downey, who's portrayed
Tweedle since 1995, when ``Lexx'' debuted as a quartet of
television movies. ``So the episodes that follow will be about how
we extricate ourselves from this particular problem, how we deal
with the new characters'' _ among them Fire's fiery leader, Prince,
played by Nigel Bennet of ``Forever Knight'' fame _ ``and how we
deal with the new adventures each of the regulars go through.''
 &HT;    Future episodes will include ``May,'' in which Stanley falls in
love, and ``Boomtown,'' in which he indulges in more sex than he
can possibly handle. ``The Key'' will bring Stanley dangerously
close to scoring with Xev.
 &HT;    Considering the show's popularity overseas, more ``Lexx'' seems
likely, even if the ratings don't ultimately warrant a third season
on Sci-Fi Channel. Right now, though, Downey is simply enjoying the
moment and the show itself.
 &HT;    ``I totally understand that `Lexx' is not everybody's cup of
tea, and it never was intended to be that,'' he says. ``We weren't
trying to be the next `Star Trek.' We weren't in competition with
anyone.
 &HT;    ``The whole intention was to do something that was different,''
Downey says. ``We said, `We don't know for sure if this is going to
work, but we're going to have fun doing it and we're going to make
that read on screen.'
 &HT;    ``That's exactly what we've done, and I give audiences all over
the world credit for being hungry for something new and something
that is a bit innovative.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Lexx,'' consult the official
Web site at www.lexx.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Web site at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on Inside Trek and Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
