<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple's New Computer Goes Back to Square One
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steve Jobs officially unveiled the new PowerMac G4
Cube at Mac World Expo on Wednesday. But even before his speech,
Mac fans, never shy in their ardor, couldn't contain themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Cube _ the nickname that enthusiasts immediately gave the
new computer _is a 450-megahertz computer encased in an 8-inch
cube. About one-quarter the size of the G4 computer that is
currently on the market, the Cube sits in a clear plastic display
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow'' was the exclamation of choice among Mac fans at the
Javits center in New York, as people pushed and shoved one another
to grab for posters that had been placed, unannounced, in an
unmarked corner of the Apple booth. They had been intended for
distribution after the keynote address by Jobs, Apple's chief
executive. But before he finished, no posters were left.
</P>
<P>
   The G4 Cube has 64 megabytes of memory, ports for USB and
FireWire connections and a DVD player that opens through a slot on
the top. It comes with a keyboard, speakers and an optical mouse,
but it doesn't include one part that is typically required in
computers of that speed: a fan. Engineers have designed the machine
with an air channel in the middle so the processors can be kept
cool without any fan noise.
</P>
<P>
   The Cube also comes with another feature: with a push of a
button, a handle pops up from the belly of the machine, enabling
users to pull it out of its plastic case and add or subtract parts
at will.
</P>
<P>
   It will go on sale in August for $1,799; a 500-megahertz version
will also be available, for $2,299, exclusively through the
company's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   Software Can Turn Notes Into Audio or Video Bookmarks
</P>
<P>
   Note takers, take note: Software is now available for those who
are tired of having to fast-forward through audio or video
recordings in hope of finding that one significant moment they
jotted down in their digital notepads.
</P>
<P>
   The software, called Souvenir, is designed for students,
reporters, lawyers, conference attendees and anyone else who takes
notes while recording interviews or lectures. The technology works
by issuing a time stamp each time a note is taken and using those
time stamps to create links between the jotted words and the
digital recording. When users review the notes later, they only
need to click on the words to pull up the corresponding video or
audio clip.
</P>
<P>
   The software, which is available for free downloading until this
fall at www.i-recall.com, requires that notes be taken on a digital
device like a personal computer or handheld organizer and that the
audio or visual recording must be digital, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA GUERNSEY
</P>
<P>
   British Columbia Decides To Restrict Some Videogames
</P>
<P>
   A week after it restricted sales of the Soldier of Fortune
computer game to adults, the Canadian province of British Columbia
announced that it will review and rate all electronic games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not talking about censorship here,'' said Andrew Petter,
the attorney general. ``The goal is to give parents better
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a complaint from a parent, the provincial director of
film classification, Mary-Louise McCausland, issued a decision on
July 11 classifying Soldier of Fortune as an ``adult motion
picture.''
</P>
<P>
   The adult classification, similar to an X rating under film
industry guidelines in the United States, means that rentals or
sales of the game to anyone under 18 is prohibited. Stores that
want to carry the title must obtain a special license and stock it
separately from other games.
</P>
<P>
   In her decision, McCausland found the game's violence to be
realistic, brutal and ``exploitative.'' Activision, the game's
distributor, declined to comment on the rating.
</P>
<P>
   Like many computer games, Soldier of Fortune was voluntarily
rated by the Entertainment Software Rating Board, a U.S.-based,
industry-backed group. But Petter said that his government wants
its own ratings system that reflects ``made-in-B.C. values.'' He
also said that minors would still be able to purchase games like
Soldier of Fortune online. ``The goal is not to hermetically seal
the province of British Columbia.''
</P>
<P>
   _ IAN AUSTEN
</P>
