<HEADLINE>
`WEST WING,' `SPRANOS' LEAD EMMY PACK IN NOMINATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ This time, Emmy mostly got it right.
</P>
<P>
   Kvetching by TV critics about oversights and howlingly bad
choices is a tradition almost as venerable as the Emmy Awards
themselves. But that proved hard _ though certainly not impossible
_ to do as the Academy of Television Arts &AMP; Sciences announced a
slate of nominations that generally separated wheat from chaff and
opened the door wider for newer shows.
</P>
<P>
   Gratifying choices abounded, along with, inevitably, a few
puzzling omissions. The two best-written dramas on television,
NBC's freshman ``The West Wing'' and HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' led
the pack with 18 nominations, rivaled in the dramatic category only
by the 10 nominations picked up by ABC's Boston-based ``The
Practice.'' Meanwhile, two increasingly formulaic dramas, ABC's
``NYPD Blue'' and Fox's ``The X-Files,'' deservedly did not make
the cut.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the academy sensibly spurned Fox's ``Ally McBeal,''
which won for best comedy last year but has since gone downhill
with startling speed, and bestowed 11 nominations on ``Will &AMP;
Grace,'' whose head-snapping repartee made it perhaps the funniest
show on TV in its second season. Another audacious sophomore show,
HBO's ``Sex and the City,'' snagged nine nominations, which is sure
to encourage rival networks now churning out copycat versions.
</P>
<P>
   The only breakout new comedy of the 1999-2000 season, Fox's
``Malcolm in the Middle,'' inexplicably did not garner a nomination
as best comedy. However, in a heartening turn of events, skilled
stage, screen, and TV veteran Jane Kaczmarek was nominated as best
actress in a comedy for her role as Malcolm's fierce but loving
mom. ``It's very sweet, happening at this time in my life,'' the
40-something Kaczmarek said Thursday in an interview here.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczmarek said, though, that she was disappointed the show
itself was not nominated _ ``Sometimes, they make comedies pay
their dues'' _ and that her husband, Bradley Whitford, was not
nominated for his portrayal of White House aide Josh Lyman in ``The
West Wing.'' Declared Kaczmarek with a laugh: ``How could they be
so smart to nominate me and so stupid not to nominate him?''
</P>
<P>
   Among the five ``West Wing'' cast members who did get nominated
for ``The West Wing'' was Richard Schiff, who wears a perpetual
poker face as chief of staff Toby Ziegler. In an interview in Los
Angeles Wednesday night, Schiff did crack a smile occasionally but
frowned as he worried that the show's strong ensemble cast might
``cancel each other out'' in the Emmy competition. ``Any award we
get is a compliment to the group,'' he insisted, and to creator
Aaron Sorkin, who he said ``tells wonderful stories'' while
offering ``optimistic, positive examples of what public servants
can bring to our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   The day must have been tinged with bittersweet feelings for
writer-producer Sorkin. On the one hand, there was the triumphant
showing of ``The West Wing,'' a show that has exploded the myth
that politics and politicians cannot make for engrossing drama. On
the other hand, the academy was no kinder to Sorkin's brilliant
``Sports Night'' than Nielsen viewers were. The low-rated, recently
canceled ABC dramedy and its superb cast got stiffed in all the
main categories as ``Sports Night'' earned a mere handful of
nominations in technical categories.
</P>
<P>
   Writer-producer David E. Kelley (``Ally McBeal,'' ``The
Practice'') must have had similarly mixed feelings as he weighed
Emmy's snub of ``Ally'' against its embrace of ``The Practice,''
last year's winner for best drama.
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy Awards will be announced on Sept. 10 in a ceremony to
be broadcast on ABC. Herewith, a few kudos, caveats, and general
observations about the nominations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gone but not forgotten were the late Nancy Marchand, nominated
for her chilling mob matriarch, Livia, in ``The Sopranos,'' and
Michael J. Fox, nominated as best actor in a comedy for his role in
a show he has just left, ABC's ``Spin City.'' Gone and virtually
forgotten was NBC's canceled ``Freaks and Geeks,'' quite possibly
the best new show of last season _ not that anyone inhabiting
Nielsen households noticed. ``Freaks and Geeks'' got a meager two
nominations.
</P>
<P>
   _ The good news is that the entire cast of CBS's ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' and NBC's ``Will &AMP; Grace'' won nominations. The bad
news is that so did John Lithgow, for his relentless hamminess in
NBC's ``Third Rock from the Sun,'' despite his own eye-rolling
surprise at winning last year.
</P>
<P>
   _ HBO continues to build on the momentum generated by ``The
Sopranos,'' while the WB network, all the rage a year or two ago
with its teen-angst dramas, continues to fade. NBC got 97
nominations, HBO earned 86 (including 10 for ``RKO 281,'' its fine
film about the making of ``Citizen Kane''), followed by ABC with
64, CBS with 41, UPN with seven, and the WB with a lowly five. When
UPN gets more Emmy nominations than you, trouble has officially
arrived. And the academy continued to turn a cold shoulder to the
WB's best show, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' PBS, meanwhile, got
only 12 nominations (including one for ``New York,'' a Ric Burns
documentary coproduced by WGBH-TV in Boston), three fewer than last
year and only one ahead of the Discovery Channel.
</P>
<P>
   _ The academy showed a definite preference for movie stars when
it came to choosing nominees in the miniseries category. For
instance, while HBO's gritty and groundbreaking ``The Corner'' was
nominated for best miniseries, star Khandi Alexander was ignored in
favor of Sally Field, Holly Hunter, Judy Davis, Halle Berry, and
Gena Rowlands. Some of the male nominees in the category _ Jack
Lemmon, William H. Macy, Beau Bridges _ are best known for their
film work.
</P>
</TEXT>
