<HEADER>
A7895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-DALEY21-COX     07-20 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-DALEY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A TOUGH CHICAGO POL BEGINNING A TOUGH JOB AT GORE CAMPAIGN
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ A small mirrored disco ball twirls almost
unnoticed from the ceiling of Vice President Al Gore's campaign
headquarters, a whimsical touch seemingly out of place as his staff
begins the serious task of taking on George W. Bush in the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   From the disco ball above the scores of newly arrived volunteers
and workers hangs a small sign: ``GRITS.'' It stands for ``Gore
Rocks In The South.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, though, it is a no-nonsense Chicago pol who is
rocking this part of the South these days: political fixer William
Daley, a son of the legendary Mayor Richard Daley, who officially
took over as chairman of the Gore presidential campaign this week.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's arrival, as much as the political calendar _ the
election is less than four months away _ has quickened the pace of
the campaign, giving it an edge and a focus that has been largely
missing since Gore dispatched challenger Bill Bradley in the
Democratic primaries last spring.
</P>
<P>
   And with national polls showing Gore in a virtual tie with Bush
after months of trailing the soon-to-be Republican nominee, the
campaign is fun again for the vice president's supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feel the excitement again, and he is a big part of
it,'' campaign communications chief Mark Fabiani said of Daley
during a tour of the campaign headquarters this week.
</P>
<P>
   Daley agreed last month to leave his job as President Clinton's
commerce secretary to take over for Tony Coelho, who was forced to
resign as campaign chairman because of health problems. His first
full day on the job was Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But where Coelho was ``Tony'' to the headquarters staff, Daley,
known to his family and friends as ``Billy,'' is ``the Chairman.''
And where Coelho, a Californian, donned cowboy boots and jeans upon
arriving in Music City, Daley has yet to be seen in the
headquarters in anything other than a dark business suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my uniform,'' Daley chuckled during an interview this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is not unlike the vice president himself who, no matter
how he tries to change his stripes, seems most comfortable in a
blue suit, white shirt and red tie.
</P>
<P>
   Daley understands that the South is a bit more laid back than
his home town of Chicago, at least in its style and manner. But he
also understands that there is nothing laid back about the politics
of the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never lived in the South before, but I worked in Jimmy
Carter's campaign,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the 51-year-old Daley has worked in every Democratic
presidential campaign since he accompanied his father to the 1960
convention in Los Angeles and met John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   But for what he doesn't understand about the South, he turns to
Donna Brazile, the campaign manager and a native of Louisiana, who
learned grassroots presidential politics in the presidential
campaigns of Carter and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main goal here is winning the election (for Gore),'' he
added. ``I think I understand a little bit about politics, and you
win elections by pounding away and connecting with the American
people. I think that's what's beginning to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Daley's arrival in Nashville coincides with a more aggressive
campaign style from Gore, one in which he tries to skewer Bush with
his own record as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Daley's takeover of the Gore campaign also coincides with new
national polls suggesting that the vice president has pulled even
with Bush after months of trailing the Texas governor, sometimes by
double digits.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Daley dismisses the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, for months now, there's been a perception, at least in
Washington, that the campaign was going well,'' he said. ``But you
could get out of Washington and see that most Americans just
weren't paying that much attention to the presidential campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   All that is about to change, though, as both parties prepare for
the nominating conventions that will usher in the final phase of
the presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Daley's time is being spent on Gore's vice presidential
selection, on convention preparations _ most notably negotiating
time slots for Bradley and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, on
Gore's post-convention trip down the Mississippi River, and the
three presidential debates scheduled for October.
</P>
<P>
   The day-to-day task of ministering to the Democratic Party's
powerful constituency groups, such as organized labor and women,
falls to Brazile, just as it did when Coelho was chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donna and I work well together,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   But Daley has also brought with him a core of assistants from
the Department of Commerce. And he has cleared the way for longtime
party operative Tad Devine to handle getting out the campaign's
basic ``prosperity and progress'' message.
</P>
<P>
   Brazile's office in the Gore headquarters sits next to Daley's.
But Brazile's outspokenness _ she once suggested that the
Republican Party uses former Joint Chiefs of Staff Chairman Colin
Powell and Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma as window dressing on racial
issues _ has occasionally gotten her in hot water. Consequently, it
is Daley who speaks for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm notable, not quotable,'' said Brazile.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.algore2000.com
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
