<HEADER>
A7899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIES-WHAT0721-COX     07-20 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-WHAT0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spooky Hitchcock homage `Lies Beneath' unravels at the end
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Gus Van Sant tried his hand at it. Brian De
Palma has practically built a career on it. So why shouldn't Robert
Zemeckis take a crack at making a thriller in the style of Alfred
Hitchcock?
</P>
<P>
   No one understood the psychology and mechanics of suspense quite
like Hitchcock, yet for much of ``What Lies Beneath `` _ a creepy
little yarn of guilt, gullibility and ghosts _ the Oscar-winning
director of ``Forrest Gump'' concocts a reasonable facsimile of the
British master's handiwork. Then, when stuck for a sufficiently
violent wrap-up to appease today's more bloodthirsty moviegoers,
Zemeckis settles for the pumped-up improbabilities of ``Fatal
Attraction `` crossed with the ``Cape Fear'' remake.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad. The first three-quarters of this movie are so
entertaining, if hardly original, that what lies afterward is a
genuine disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   If you've seen the overly explicit trailers for ``What Lies
Beneath,'' you know that Claire Spencer (Michelle Pfeiffer, an
ideal blond Hitchcock heroine) will believe she is seeing ghosts,
specifically the spirit of one of her genetics professor husband
Norman's (Harrison Ford) former students. But first, as an homage
to ``Rear Window,'' Claire becomes obsessively convinced that their
new next-door neighbor on a picturesque Vermont lake has killed his
wife. This is merely a subplot, but it gets us doubting Claire and
questioning our own perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Claire's daughter has just gone off to college and her
post-parting funk leads her to pour out her feelings and suspicions
to a psychiatrist. She could be heading for a mental breakdown, but
what explains the way her front door keeps opening by itself, the
frequent power outages, the water that refills in her bathtub and
the reflection of a face in that water?
</P>
<P>
   First-time screenwriter Clark Gregg will eventually let him
down, but Zemeckis knows how to build an air of creepiness that
gets an audience delighting in the dread of what may pop out at
them. Even in the most static of scenes, he keeps his camera on the
prowl, circling around, exploring the background in a way that
suggests something or someone lurks beyond the picture frame. It's
cheap suspense, but enormously effective.
</P>
<P>
   Claire may not have seen ``The Sixth Sense,'' but she has seen
detective movies, so when she learns _ awfully conveniently _ that
her ghost is a still-missing, presumably dead female student, she
launches her own investigation. She visits the girl's mother,
swipes a lock of the girl's hair and conducts a seance, complete
with Ouija board. The girl is roused from the dead to visit Claire,
inhabit her body and try to settle a score with Norman.
</P>
<P>
   From that point, it seems that no hackneyed plot device is
beneath ``What Lies Beneath.'' Claire finds a box of incriminating
evidence submerged just off her dock, other clues leap out at her
in a nearby village, and she is nearly drowned in her bathtub. She
then has to make a mad dash from a killer in her home and race away
in her truck, only to then stumble upon the body of the dead
student. You may find it hard to decide whether to scream or
giggle.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison and Pfeiffer remain enjoyable to watch, even as the
movie careens out of control. This movie is beneath each of them,
but it is preferable to their previous efforts _ ``Random Hearts''
and ``The Story of Us.'' Harrison is his usual jut-jawed, scowling
screen persona, while Pfeiffer gets more interesting acting
opportunities, as paranoid Claire and later as the seductive
student who possesses her.
</P>
<P>
   Movie buffs can spend their time spotting the references to
earlier thrillers. Suffice it to say that ``What Lies Beneath''
will probably not do for bathtubs what ``Psycho'' did for showers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
