<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-POKEMON0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This crudely animated cartoon is an exercise in exploitation
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ You would have thought one Pokemon movie
would be enough punishment for parents.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not. The forces behind this fad in all its forms _
video game, TV series and trading cards _ have made a sequel to
last year's debut Pokemon flick. It's as if they're trying to cash
in before Pokemon becomes another relic to add to the trash heap of
kiddie culture. Remember how hot those Beanie Babies once were?
</P>
<P>
   So here we have ``Pokemon the Movie 2000.'' In a way, this kind
of picture is review-proof. Children will want to see it regardless
of what their elders say _ and they'll stick with it even as Mom
and Dad snore into their popcorn. (My advice: Get an extra-large
Coke _ you'll need the caffeine.) But in a summer that's given us
such a brilliant kid-friendly picture as ``Chicken Run,'' you have
to ask: Why settle for less?
</P>
<P>
   And this is about as little entertainment as you can expect from
a children's flick, as exemplified by the crude animation.
</P>
<P>
   The premise is the usual good-vs.-evil shebang. Meet Jirarudan,
the bad guy: He collects rare Pokemon _ miniature monsters of
varying sizes, shapes and characters. His ultimate goal is to
capture Lugia, a mysterious Pokemon who lives in the sea and serves
as a sort of high-powered water-district manager, controlling the
flow of the currents. To get to Lugia, Jirarudan must first bag
three other, birdlike Pokemon, who represent the forces of fire,
lightning and ice. But the good guys stand in his way, namely young
Pokemon trainer Ash Ketchum and his sidekick, Pikachu. Expect lots
of raging battles over sea and land.
</P>
<P>
   Does it make any sense? Not to me; but then again, I'm not a
corporate exec looking to sell kids more Pokemon trading cards.
That, of course, is the real goal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   or Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
