u i BC-CHINA-SECT-520&AMP;ADD-NY     07-20 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECT-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALUN GONG MEMBERS CONTINUE PROTESTS ONE YEAR AFTER GROUP WAS
BANNED 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The police and Falun Gong followers played a grim game
in Tiananmen Square Thursday, with lean young cadets dashing across
the vast open space to snatch down ochre banners briefly unfurled
by middle-aged members of the banned spiritual discipline.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens, perhaps hundreds, of the group's followers have been
taken into custody in the past few days as the protests increase to
mark the first anniversary of the government's crackdown on the
spiritual movement that swept the country in the late 1990s,
gathering millions of adherents. The arrests and a pervasive
anti-Falun Gong propaganda campaign may have shrunk the group's
numbers, but also hardened the will of those followers who remain.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, exhortations by Falun Gong's exiled leader, Li
Hongzhi, have become increasingly urgent in recent weeks, praising
followers who ``defend the practice'' and warning destruction for
those ``evil beings'' who stand in its way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wicked and evil will soon be eliminated, the vile ones in
the human world will receive due retribution, and sins will no
longer be allowed to continue,'' he wrote in a message recently
posted on the group's official Web site. ``Disciples are waiting to
reach consummation, and I can wait no more.''
</P>
<P>
   Li founded Falun Gong in the early 1990s, developing a series of
yoga-like exercises based on the Chinese practice of qigong, the
discipline of breathing control and meditation intended to channel
the body's qi, or vital life force, to various ends.
</P>
<P>
   His message of personal salvation from a morally degenerating
world struck a chord with millions of Chinese who were
disillusioned with the spiritual vacuum created by the collapse of
the country's communist ideology and rampant corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But the Chinese government grew increasingly uneasy with Li's
growing popularity, and in early 1998 he left under pressure to
live in the United States. He owns a home in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   China began arresting adherents of the sect a year ago, and it
is still at it. Despite well-publicized prison terms of up to 18
years for the most active followers and reports of torture and
death among believers who have been detained, Falun Gong adherents
continue to arrive at Tiananmen Square, China's symbolic center and
most public space, to bear fleeting witness to their faith.
</P>
<P>
   The protests appear futile amid the crowds of tourists from
across China that fill the square each day. So huge is the square
that the small bands of protesters, usually only a handful in
number, attract little attention in the few seconds that it takes
for the plainclothes police spread among the crowds to subdue them.
The protesters rarely manage to raise a banner long enough for
anyone to read one, and they are quickly whisked away in the
blue-and-white police vans that cruise around the square for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Because China's state-run media rarely mention the protests, few
Chinese are even aware that they are happening.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``What was that?'' asked a woman, after a dozen young policemen
dragged down a yellow banner and bundled several Falun Gong
followers into a van that arrived within seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some troublemaker,'' replied a man beside her.
</P>
<P>
   The periodic scuffles, occasionally over elderly men or women
sitting in the lotus position and raising their arms in the opening
gesture of Falun Gong's meditative exercises, gave a bizarre edge
Thursday to the square's otherwise festive atmosphere. Tour groups
marched around behind guides bearing pennants and children flew
colorful kites. Occasionally, bystanders gathered to watch dumbly
as the police pummeled a resistant protester. At one point,
uniformed police officers could be seen punching a man who was in
one of their vans.
</P>
<P>
   Falun Gong activists abroad have grown increasingly
sophisticated in their efforts to reach people inside China and
keep the movement alive.
</P>
<P>
   Its members have established an expanding network of Internet
sites that occasionally circumvent China's efforts to block access.
And the group has even begun daily Chinese-language broadcasts into
China, though the broadcasts were jammed soon after they began this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The group's message has taken on an increasingly apocalyptic
cast as China's effort to exterminate the movement grinds down its
numbers. Earlier this week, a message on Falun Gong's main web site
reported that Li has been locked for nine months in a battle with
evil forces that have damaged his body and turned his hair gray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fellow cultivators, let us strive forward diligently and
courageously,'' the message said. ``Let us cherish the repeated
opportunities that Master, through tremendous sacrifice, has
created for us to advance towards Consummation!''
</P>
<P>
   Li's writings do not elucidate the meaning of ``consummation,''
but the message suggested that it refers to a transcendent event of
the sort promised by many religions, old and new. ``That humankind
has made it to the year 2000 is not to give humankind prosperity,
and even less is it to allow humankind to continue creating karma
for their own selfish interests,'' the message said.
</P>
<P>
   It is that sort of talk that most worries Beijing's leaders.
China has a history of milenarian movements that have led to tens
of millions of deaths and marked the end to some dynastic
governments. Invisible as the Falun Gong protests are to most
Chinese, they represent the most coordinated and sustained
challenge to Communist Party rule since the pro-democracy movement
of 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cult will not voluntarily step down from the historical
stage,'' said an editorial in Thursday's People's Daily, the
party's official mouthpiece.
</P>
<P>
   The fight against Falun Gong, it said, will be a ``long-lasting,
complicated and acute struggle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
