<HEADER>
A7906 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     07-20 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBUMS OF THE WEEK FEATURE ELECTRONIC TIBETAN WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANN POWERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   YUNGCHEN LHAMO: ``Coming Home''
</P>
<P>
   and
</P>
<P>
   LAMA GYURME with JEAN-PHILLIPE RYKIEL: ``Rain of Blessings:
Vajra Chants'' (Real World).
</P>
<P>
   Unfamiliar faiths can be easier to accept when expressed in
foreign tongues. The chant-based sacred music of Tibet has helped
stimulate American interest in both that country's religion and in
its struggle against Chinese dominance.
</P>
<P>
   New albums by the expatriates Yungchen Lamo and Lama Gyurme ,
communicate Tibetan wisdom _ and defiance _ within soothing New Age
electronica.
</P>
<P>
   Yungchen Lhamo's music is political as well as spiritual. On
``Coming Home,'' she spans artistic borders, aided by the renowned
producer Hector Zazou. At times she sounds like Sarah McLachlan or
a Hong Kong pop star. Zazou's settings for her high, melancholy
voice incorporate electric guitar, violin, cello and a sample of a
Tuvan throat singer. Yet whether singing in English or wordlessly
shouting, Lhamo keeps her focus on the essentially Tibetan themes
of compassion and liberation.
</P>
<P>
   Lama Gyurme is a monk, and on his second collaboration with the
French pianist Jean-Philippe Rykiel, he focuses on Vajra style
devotional chanting. Rykiel surrounds Gyurme's appealingly homely
voice with organ, violin and keyboards, creating a hymnlike tone.
Less overtly political than Lhamo, Gyurme still eloquently argues
for the preservation of Tibet, in a form flexible enough to appeal
to the West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
