<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7907 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-GOP-PLATFORM-NEWHOUSE     07-20 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-PLATFORM-NEWHOUSE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIDE TURNS IN FAVOR OF GOP'S TAX CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
Thursday, July 20, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded nytimes.com.) 
 By BRENT HUNSBERGER  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Republicans had a tough time last year selling their tax-cut
package: The public didn't seem interested, Democrats scored points
deriding it as welfare for the rich and, at nearly $800 billion
over 10 years, even some party regulars worried that it sucked up
too much of the projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, Republicans have easily pushed two
major tax cut bills through the House and the Senate and even
managed to convince a few Democrats to come along for the ride.
With their presidential convention just 10 days away, the GOP
leadership is rushing along another tax-relief measure, all but
daring President Clinton to veto it.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans owe their newfound success to good timing and
political strategy, according to analysts and lawmakers. Tax cuts
are always popular on Capitol Hill during an election year, and
rosy federal budget projections have made tax cuts especially hard
to resist. Meanwhile, the Republican leadership decision to
dismantle last year's mega-package and instead offer tax cuts in
smaller, targeted bills has made tax relief this year even more
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, nine Senate Democrats voted for the Republican-backed
estate and gift tax repeal and on Tuesday eight voted with the GOP
to partially eliminate a tax on married couples. Both proposals
were elements in the GOP package last year that was savaged by
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all has to do with packaging,'' said Marshall Wittman of
the conservative Heritage Foundation. ``Last year, the Republicans
tried to sell a huge, eye-glazing package. Now they've broken it
down into items everyone can identify with: death and marriage.
It's put it in comprehensible terms to the average voter.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., is credited with
repackaging the Republicans' $792 billion, catch-all tax cut. The
targeted bills have allowed Republicans to push big-ticket tax
relief without appearing fiscally irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the GOP last year were openly uncomfortable with their
own party's mega-tax-cut package, fearing that it would undermine
efforts to pay down the debt. This year's tax cuts aren't cheap:
The marriage penalty relief would cost $248 billion over the next
10 years and the estate tax repeal would cost $105 billion through
2010 and $750 billion in the decade after that. The bite-sized
portions, however, appear easier to swallow, and growing budget
surplus projections make them go down even more smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   Last week the Congressional Budget Office predicted that the
non-Social Security budget surplus will reach $100 billion in 2001,
three times larger than earlier projections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tax cuts in the face of large budget surpluses have a
presumption in their favor,'' said Henry Aaron, a Brookings
Institute economic analyst. ``With a bigger budget surplus, it's
easier to find things to spend it on.''
</P>
<P>
   The piecemeal approach has forced Democrats to risk going on
record as opposing specific tax-relief measures popular with
voters. While polls showed last year that voters had no appetite
for a massive tax cut, individual items -- especially the marriage
penalty relief -- are very popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any Democrat in a marginal (political) situation, especially
in a conservative region, has to be very careful when it comes to
voting against a repeal of taxes on death and marriage,'' said
Wittman of the Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a vote against the tax cuts could easily be turned
into 30-second attack ads during a campaign featuring ``a wedding
ceremony or the grim reaper putting a tax on you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's stuff people can relate to,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly on the defensive, Democrats are feeling the pressure.
Earlier this week Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers held an
unusual conference call with reporters to attack the Republican
bills as giveaways to the rich. He said that when fully phased in,
the measures would provide a tax break to the wealthiest 1 percent
of the population 84 times larger than for the average family.
</P>
<P>
   From the White House, press secretary Joe Lockhart charged that
the Republicans are less interested in tax relief than in scoring
political points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made it very clear that they want to get bills done,
timed to their convention, so they'll have something to talk about
at their convention,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has vowed to veto both bills.
</P>
<P>
   Even more tax-relief is on the table. On Wednesday, the House
Ways and Means Committee passed a bill designed to repeal a tax on
Social Security benefits for couples making more than $44,000 a
year. The bill would effectively roll back a 1993 Clinton
administration policy that taxed 85 percent of those benefits as a
means of shoring up Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic leaders complained that, once again, the Republicans
are trying to give relief to the best-off taxpayers at the expense
of safety-net social programs. They also said that at $44 billion
over five years, the proposed tax cut is sizable.
</P>
<P>
   But already Republicans are sharpening their rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flawed concept that a Social Security check from the
government arrive with a bill from the IRS attached,'' Rep. J.C.
Watts, R-Okla., said about the tax.
</P>
<P>
   With healthy surpluses and congressional elections approaching,
the Social Security tax cut may be another one that Democrats will
find hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to be taken up on the House floor next
week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
