<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7910 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0721-COX     07-20 1943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Not exactly the old San Antone
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore took on George W. Bush on his home ground today, in San
Antonio, accusing him of cutting taxes for special interests
instead of helping families that lack health care. Texas, he said,
``should be a state where it's just as easy to raise a child as it
is to set up an oil rig.'' Gore paid a glancing tribute to Bush's
political strengths at home and his ``warm and engaging
personality.'' But then he said pointedly that the presidency ``is
more than just a popularity contest.'' Gore's discussion with
invited guests took place at the Seven Oaks Resort and Conference
Center, a venue not exactly in keeping with the message but the
only one campaign aides said they could find on short notice.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST RULE: DO NO HARM
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush says he is getting close to a decision on his
running mate and suggests one political priority: ``You want
somebody who's not going to hurt you.'' Twelve days before the
opening of the national convention, Bush told reporters at an
impromptu news conference in Austin: ``I will make up my mind
soon.'' A number of Republicans are urging him to sit on his lead
in polls and make a ``safe'' pick, giving greater weight to a
candidate's potential to do harm than his prospects for bolstering
the ticket. Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating and even Dick Cheney _ head
of Bush's search _ reportedly are the latest favorites of the
take-no-chances crowd.
</P>
<P>
   IF CLINTON WERE DOING THE PICKING
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has been steering clear of the vice
presidental selection process, but the New York Times reports that
he has told friends and associates that two of his favorite choices
for Al Gore's running mate are ex- Majority Leader George Mitchell
of Maine and Sen. Bob Graham of Florida, both of whom he considered
picking eight years ago. Gore himself, speaking in Cedar Rapids,
Iowa, said he wants a vice president who would be much like himself
_ someone who has helped ``carry the heavy load that sometimes is
pretty crushing for a president.''
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY SET FOR PRIME TIME
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, the only Democratic rival to Al Gore during the
primary season, will play a major role at the Democratic convention
with a 15-to-20 minute speech during prime time on the second
night, Aug. 15. The ex-New Jersey senator campaigned with Gore for
the first time last Thursday, endorsing him in Green Bay, Wis., and
is slated to campaign for Democrats at all levels this fall.
</P>
<P>
   THEY CAN WAIT FOR THE RERUNS
</P>
<P>
   About four in 10 Americans say they have made no plans to watch
any of the national political conventions, says a poll on public
interest in the presidential elections. That's about double the
percentage who made that claim four years ago. In the poll from the
Vanishing Voter project, 43 percent said they don't plan to watch
the upcoming GOP convention, and almost that many, 38 percent, said
they have no plans to watch the Democratic convention in
mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   CONSTITUTIONAL RIGHT TO BEAR CHECKS
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay (R-Texas) argued today for the
abolition of all limits on campaign contributions, and urged
Republicans tommittee chairman. McCain reported raising $924,606
through June 30. He's already contributed $11,000 to Republican
congressional candidates, and spent about half the money raised on
travel, staff and events that have helped him maintain his
visibility on the political landscape.
</P>
<P>
   AND THAT'S ALL SHE WANTS TO SAY
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton said she was done talking about allegations that
she used an obscenity-laced, anti-Semitic slur during a heated
discussion with a campaign aide to Bill Clinton in Arkansas 26
years ago. ``I've said all I'm going to say about this. It wasn't
true, it didn't happen and I'm not going to allow it to distract
from the real issues of this campaign,'' she told a news conference
in Albany, N.Y., where she picked up the Senate endorsement of the
2.5 million-member state AFL-CIO.
</P>
<P>
   WOULD YOU SAY HE DOESN'T LIKE HER?
</P>
<P>
   The head of the New York state Republican Party accused Hillary
Clinton of being ``an angry woman'' driven by ``blind political
ambition'' and said voters should reject her bid for the Senate in
part because ``she didn't send Chelsea to school here.'' In a copy
of a fund-raising letter obtained today by The Associated Press,
William Powers said the first lady has ``been at the front and
center of every Clinton-Gore scandal, and this has been the most
seedy, shameless and corrupt administration in American history.''
It was the second harsh letter from Powers to surface in a week. In
the first, he called Clinton ``cold-blooded and hotheaded'' and
denounced her as a ``shrill and scheming person.''
</P>
<P>
   TALK IS GOOD _ MONEY'S BETTER
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Hillary Clinton should be running for senator of
Hollywood. She has a star-studded donor list, including Robert De
Niro, Robin Williams, Tom Cruise and Nicole Kidman. She's also
popular with small-screen performers, particularly two talk show
hosts. The New York Post reports that nice talker Rosie O'Donnell
has coughed up $10,000 for Clinton's various campaign funds, with
trashy talker Jerry Springer matching that amount dollar for
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   THERE ARE 50 STATES, REMEMBER?
</P>
<P>
   The Green Party's Ralph Nader thinks Al Gore and George W. Bush
should pay a call to each and every state of the union. ``What
about dropping the poll-driven travel schedule at least on the
first round of campaigning and treat all citizens of the United
States equally by visiting all the states?'' Nader wrote in a
letter to Gore and Bush. He had some specific spots in mind, too:
For Bush, Alaska and the site of the Exxon Valdez oil spill; for
Gore, Hawaii, to reassure island citizens that President Clinton's
recent executive order affecting the coral reefs is more than just
talk.
</P>
<P>
   THIS WEEK'S FUND-RAISING CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   Commerce Secretary-designate Norman Mineta received several
contributions in 1992 arranged by a convicted Democratic
fund-raiser who later acknowledged she reimbursed the donors,
according to congressional investigators' documents. The
investigators, however, said there's no evidence Mineta knew of the
scheme by fund-raiser Nora Lum to funnel $4,250 to his House
campaign through straw donors. Only $2,250 of the donations
actually reached Mineta's campaign treasury, according to Federal
Election Commission records.
</P>
<P>
   THIS TIME AROUND, THEY'LL AT LEAST TALK
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin Gov. Tommy Thompson, who chairs the Republican
Platform Committee, assured GOP pro-choice advocates that their
views will get a full airing next week when the committee meets
before the party's national convention begins. After a closed-door
meeting that Thompson held with several pro-choice groups, Susan
Cullman, co-chair of the Republican Pro-Choice Coalition, said,
``What was newsworthy to us is that we continue to have a dialogue.
... In 1996 and 1992, no one would return our calls. So this is a
plus.''
</P>
<P>
   BRING ON THE AUDITORS
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party said it will double-check the names of
thousands of people who received ballots in the party's mail-in
primary. Party leaders are investigating whether front-runner Pat
Buchanan broke rules by having ballots sent to supporters who
didn't ask for them, and they have threatened to disqualify him if
he doesn't comply with the audit. Buchanan's sole challenger for
the Reform nomination, physicist John Hagelin, had previously
offered to audit the lists of more than 500,000 names himself, but
party leaders decided to hire an outside accounting firm. The
party's convention is in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   NOD GOES TO FIRST AMENDMENT
</P>
<P>
   Activists who have set their sights on the Democratic convention
scored a victory when a federal judge said Los Angeles officials
must give protesters better access to the convention site. U.S.
District Judge Gary Feess agreed with the American Civil Liberties
Union, which sued the city and police department. The suit claimed
a wide buffer zone officials planned to establish around the
convention site _ the downtown Staples Center _ would violate
protesters' constitutional rights by keeping them too far from
delegates. ``When it's convenience versus the First Amendment,
convenience loses every time,'' Feess said.
</P>
<P>
   LABOR BACKS OFF PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   Labor leaders have closed ranks around Al Gore and distanced
themselves from protests planned for the Democratic convention,
suggesting that the streets will be far less mobbed than some had
feared or hoped. Demonstrations against global trade policies in
Seattle last year included thousands of union members who, along
with environmentalists and students, had a clear objective to shut
down the World Trade Organization summit and force the WTO to
consider labor and environmental standards when setting new trade
roles.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO KEEP THINGS UNDER WRAPS
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia police are making final arrangements this week for
the Republican convention, including opening overflow prison cells
in the suburbs or at the shuttered site of a 1970 prison riot for
the hundreds of demonstrators who could be arrested. Police
officials scheduled two meetings with protest groups to try to
smooth concerns over violence and vandalism during demonstrations.
As many as 20,000 protesters are expected to be in town.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT MATTERS MOST
</P>
<P>
   What do voters pine for in their presidential candidate? A
Princeton Survey found that 39 percent said the candidate's
``positions on the issues'' ranks first, followed by character,
experience, intelligence, party affiliation, and choice of vice
president. But what issues matter? The economy gets top billing
from 21 percent of those surveyed, followed by health care,
education, Social Security, taxes, abortion, foreign policy, the
environment, and Supreme Court nominations.
</P>
<P>
   NO DICE IN PHILLY
</P>
<P>
   A Las Vegas-style casino night that was to be the Nevada
Republican Party's biggest fund-raiser at the convention in
Philadelphia ran into trouble. It turns out gambling is illegal in
Pennsylvania _ even if it's with fake money and chips. Pennsylvania
Attorney General Mike Fisher advised the Nevada delegation to that
effect, and as a result, GOP leaders have decided to scrap the
event they had hoped would bring in as much as $100,000 to help
elect Republicans in Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   LOYALTY IS A FLEETING THING
</P>
<P>
   On the campaign trail this spring in New Jersey, Democratic
Senate candidate Jon Corzine repeatedly implored whoever was
listening to support Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey for governor
next year. His comment at a Democratic Party confab in Atlantic
City in early May was typical: ``You can make certain Jim McGreevey
is that governosh, every day is Thanksgiving. This from a
Washington Post reporter: ``In the last five hours, we have
consumed mashed potatoes, baked ziti, grilled chicken, beef
brisket, chicken soup, cauliflower, broccoli, crab-stuffed
mushrooms, shrimp and steak kebabs, pizza, chicken Caesar salad,
cookies and pastries, cheese and crackers, rolls, ice cream and
candy bars. At the moment, we are swarming around a table with egg
rolls and vegetables left over from a fund-raising event.''
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
