<HEADER>
A7911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CENSUS-SURVEY21-COX     07-20 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-SURVEY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ANNUAL SURVEY COULD EASE CENSUS BURDENS, OFFICIALS SAY
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau believes it has a better way.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the controversy over privacy concerns and the 2000 census,
officials told Congress on Thursday that a rolling annual survey
should replace the once-a-decade long form of detailed questions.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in the Internet also should make the next census seem
less obtrusive, said Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt.
</P>
<P>
   By 2010, officials envision that most people may be able to
securely file their census information via the World Wide Web or by
using a simple mail-back postcard. The Internet was available to
census-filers this year, but was not publicized or made a central
part of the agency's data-gathering effort.
</P>
<P>
   The government must still conduct a head count every 10 years,
as mandated by the Constitution, to apportion seats in Congress.
But it is asking Congress to fund an ongoing survey of roughly 3
million households a year, beginning in 2003, to learn details
about the population.
</P>
<P>
   The new method, known as the American Community Survey (ACS),
would provide the government with better and more timely
information with less intrusion in the lives of Americans, Prewitt
told a House subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best solution is to radically simplify the census by
eliminating the long form,'' Prewitt said. He called the ACS, which
is being tested on a limited scale, ``the single most important
innovation'' in federal data-gathering over the past 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   The ACS has been in the works for years as a better scientific
means of surveying America. Prewitt said the cost of the new
program would not exceed current spending for the 2000 census,
roughly $6.8 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans in March received the basic, eight-question short
form. The 53-question long form, delivered to one in six U.S.
households, became the target of talk-show hosts, Internet chat
sites and Republican Party leaders who said that some of the
questions were intrusive.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Americans complained that the long form asked
sensitive questions about such things as income and health. Some
who received it refused to return the form, saying they did not
trust the government to keep their answers confidential.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I think most of us here today support eliminating the
long form, is the American Community Survey the answer? I'm not
sure,'' said Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., chairman of the House
subcommittee on the census.
</P>
<P>
   The new survey would ask virtually the same questions as the
long form over years and provide the Census Bureau with an annual
sample of the state of America, rather than the current 10-year
snapshot.
</P>
<P>
   As a more subtle form of polling, it would not become a
once-a-decade lightening rod for public indignation against the
federal government, census officials suggested.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga., questioned whether ``this
additional information is absolutely necessary to fulfill the
constitutional purpose of the census.'' He has introduced a bill
that would remove federal penalties for failure to answer census
questions unrelated to apportionment.
</P>
<P>
   Questions asked on the long form are approved by Congress and
are intended to gather data called for by laws or administrative
rulings. Prewitt said about 400 current federal laws require
collecting the data asked for by the long form and another 35 bills
pending before Congress would add new questions.
</P>
<P>
   The information collected is used to apportion congressional
seats, to draw new congressional districts within the states, and
to equitably distribute about $200 billion in federal spending.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials also said that the ACS would be more efficient
because the information would be collected by staff professionals
rather than the tens of thousands part-time, temporary workers the
Census Bureau hires every 10 as part of the demonstration, ACS
forms were sent to about 700,000 households in 1,203 counties,
including virtually all U.S. counties with populations exceeding
250,000. Census researchers want to use the information to compare
it to the regular 2000 Census as a means of testing the ACS method.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.census.gov
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
