<HEADER>
A7914 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-GARCIA-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      07-20 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FINE DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. Times are PST.) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Nickelodeon's ``The Brothers Garcia'' laudably refuses to allow its
social significance _ it's the first TV comedy completely written,
directed and produced by and starring Latinos _ to weigh heavily
upon its souffle-light premise and tone. Reminiscent of ``The
Wonder Years,'' the series features John Leguizamo whimsically
narrating the story of the Garcias, a freshly scrubbed San Antonio
family embracing its ethnic heritage while wading through the
detritus of pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Larry (Alvin Alvarez), the youngest, is the kid providing
Leguizamo's perspective; his twin sister Lorena (Vaneza Leza
Pitynski), is a drama queen addicted to tattling and telenovelas.
Larry's older brothers are Carlos (Jeffrey Licon), a smart schemer,
and George (Bobby Gonzales), who thinks he's ready to try their
pop's special ultra-hot salsa, even though it's rumored to be
capable of melting through the hood of a car. Mom Sonia (Ada Maris)
is a hairdresser and bingo junkie; Dad Ray (Carlos La Camara)
teaches history and has a fondness for wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   In tonight's debut, the kids wrangle enough money for tickets to
see their favorite wrestler grapple live, though Sonia thinks Larry
might be more edified (or at least less influenced by violence) by
a trip to the Bingo parlor. Some of the comic bits are undeveloped
or just don't work, and the show's writers feel obligated to tack
on messages _ Leguizamo declares at the end of the episode, apropos
of nothing, ``Dad took his responsibilities to heart and Mm taught
us to do the same.'' But the performers are uniformly appealing,
and the humor is sold deftly and gracefully, rather than with the
sledgehammer approach some of Nickelodeon's _ not to mention the
networks' _ sitcoms prefer. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``The Brothers Garcia.'' &QL; 
What: Family comedy focusing on a close-knit Latino household. &QL; 
The stars: Alvin Alvarez, Bobby Gonzalez, Jeffrey Licon, Vaneza
Leza Pitynski, Ada Maris, Carlos La Camara. &QL; 
Where: Nickelodeon. &QL; 
When: 8:30 p.m. Sundays. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7916 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LOSER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     07-20 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOSER-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOSER': AMY HECKERLING'S ROMANTIC COMEDY, PROMISING AT START,
COMES UP SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen-age romantic comedies, a staple of every movie season, are
often treated with contempt and condescension, not least by the
people who make them, who seem to believe that young audiences will
swallow a hackneyed, slapdash piece of work as long as there are
cute actors and a good soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Forgettable, virtually interchangeable movies like ``She's All
That,'' ``Whatever It Takes'' and the nondance parts of ``Center
Stage'' operate on the disastrous assumption that since young love
is trivial, stories about it can be flimsy and second-hand. But
movies about adolescent longing (as distinct, for the sake of
argument, from adolescent lust) are the culture's last vital link
to the great studio comedies of the 1930s. If this proposition
seems laughable, that's because, owing to the cynicism and laziness
of filmmakers and production executives, the genre has been bled
dry of its innocence, its charm and its essential seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Heckerling has been among the few exceptions to this sorry
rule. She is responsible not only for ``Clueless'' (1996), a Jane
Austen adaptation superior in wit and insight to anything the
Merchant-Ivory gang could ever hope to perpetrate, but also, along
with Cameron Crowe, for ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High,'' one of
the touchstones of modern youth culture, still notable for its
intelligence and realism. If Heckerling's new movie, ``Loser,''
which she wrote and directed, falls short of the high standards set
by her earlier work, it is at least smarter and more probing than,
say, ``Boys and Girls,'' the summer's other college love story.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Biggs, who plays Freddie Prinze Jr.'s comic sidekick in
``Boys and Girls,'' shows up here as the title character, an
earnest young man named Paul from upstate New York who goes to the
big city as a scholarship student at an unnamed university. (It
looks a lot like New York University.) The first in his family to
go to college, Paul worries to his father (Dan Aykroyd) that he
won't fit in with the sarcastic sophisticates of the big city.
``You've seen that Seinfeld show,'' he explains. ``It's like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact it's a good deal worse. Paul's diffidence and decency
make him an immediate target for the cruelty of his roommates,
three spoiled, foppish rich boys played, with verve, conviction and
the most garish wardrobe ever assembled in the service of
heterosexual villainy, by Thomas Sadoski, Zak Orth and Jimmi
Simpson. Their blithe sadism, which the academic system colludes
with, connects ``Loser'' to the great John Hughes comedies of the
mid-1980s, which concealed live wires of class antagonism within
the insulating fluff of senior-prom anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Paul, expelled from the dorm, is living in an animal
shelter with caged cats and dogs who seem better cared for than he
is. His companion in misery, the unwitting soul mate without which
no romantic plot can flourish, is Dora Diamond, played by Mena
Suvari, who set middle America's middle-aged male hearts aflutter
in ``American Beauty.'' Suvari, no longer iconically blond and now
permitted room to exercise her own warm comic talents, is well
matched with the handsome, unassuming Biggs. They're attractive
without being offensively cute, and their characters manage to be
genuinely nice without seeming bland or phony.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of phony, Dora is mixed up with a smug, predatory
literature professor (Greg Kinnear) who holds her in his sway like,
as Elaine once said on ``Seinfeld,'' some kind of Svenjolly.
Kinnear's role smacks of anti-intellectualism, but his supercilious
portrayal of wasted intelligence and gilded self-satisfaction hits
its mark pretty well; the Modern Language Association might
consider organizing a protest. The professor treats Dora like a
play-thing, but both Kinnear and Suvari are subtle enough actors so
that the relationship is appallingly believable.
</P>
<P>
   As Paul and Dora endure cruelty and humiliation at the hands of
people who hurt them for no other reason than that they have the
power, ``Loser'' pushes its honesty almost to the point of
grimness. Just as ``Fast Times'' stared unflinchingly at the
underside of sexual awakening (in ways that no movie today would
dare), so ``Loser'' glimpses a dark world of date-rape, drugs,
binge drinking and general dishonesty behind the bright facade of
college life.
</P>
<P>
   Heckerling manages to balance this dark satirical tone with a
lively lightheartedness. Funny cameos from David Spade and Andy
Dick (who is making a specialty of weirdo-behind-a-desk roles)
help, as does the film's buoyant affection for clothes, music and
its Manhattan locations.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, ``Loser'' disappoints. Too many narrative
possibilities are thrown away, so it never reaches the critical
mass of desperate complication that would ensure a satisfying comic
pay-off at the end. Paul is a little too unambiguously good, and
the reward for his goodness seems to come too quickly. The last
half-hour feels forced and thrown together, as if a first-rate
comedy full of incident, intelligence and surprise had been nipped
in the bud, or edited away. But if ``Loser'' fails to revive the
fortunes of the teen romance, it at least makes a brave and sincere
effort.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LOSER'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Amy Heckerling; director of photography,
Rob Hahn; edited by Debra Chiate; music by David Kitay; production
designer, Steven Jordan; produced by Heckerling and Twink Caplan;
released by Columbia Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jason Biggs (Paul Tannek), Mena Suvari (Dora Diamond),
Greg Kinnear (Prof. Edward Alcott), Dan Aykroyd ( Tannek), Thomas
Sadoski (Chris), Zak Orth (Adam) and Jimmi Simpson (Noah).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 93 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1707EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
