<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIMINALS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRIMINAL LOVERS': MIX OF FAIRY TALE AND DOCUDRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Francois Ozon's new film, ``Criminal Lovers,'' is such an
amalgam of fairy tales, old movies and tabloid stories that it
never develops a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the world's chicest term paper, quoting from ``Night
of the Hunter,'' ``Bonnie and Clyde,'' ``Gun Crazy,'' ``They Live
by Night'' and true crime stories told through the eyes of Larry
Clark (the director of ``Kids''), sharing his fixation on the
hairless chests of teen-age boys. (Some will note resemblances to
``The Blair Witch Project,'' but ``Criminal Lovers,'' which opens
Friday at the Quad Cinema, was completed first.)
</P>
<P>
   The two central figures are trapped in a world of violence and
strangled lust. Alice (Natacha Regnier) persuades Luc (Jeremie
Renier) to kill Said (Salim Kechiouche), one of their high school
classmates somewhere in France. Alice says Said first ridiculed and
then raped her.
</P>
<P>
   Luc, still struggling with his own sexuality, fatally stabs Said
after Alice lures their prey into an extracurricular tryst in the
boys' locker room. These early scenes have a drab documentary
style. Alice toys with Luc from the outset: His eyes are almost
spinning like pinwheels on his withdrawn, impassive face. Ozon
photographs Renier as a naif, making the boy's long, sad face the
emblem of innocence fighting to remain intact throughout the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   Luc and Alice flee the scene of their crime and stumble through
the forest, lost and frightened, only to find themselves trapped in
the woodland cabin of a wild-eyed, bearded man who sticks them in a
hole under his house. The story of Hansel and Gretel is the primary
reference here, with Luc being the object of desire of both Alice
and the heavy-browed Woodsman (Miki Manojlovic), who tells Luc he
likes his boys fattened and his girls thin before he eats them.
</P>
<P>
   There is a perverse brazenness in Ozon, as his earlier feature,
``See the Sea,'' made clear. His corrosive deadpan shows up when he
chooses to emphasize the setting, lingering on the oppressive
verdant beauty of the forest as his murderous Hansel and Gretel run
and run and run. At times, the film's mordant absurdity plays with
poetry, but of the most self-conscious brand.
</P>
<P>
   Ozon, who also wrote the screenplay, plays with violence and sex
throughout the film. Luc gazes longingly at whatever it is he can't
have, and he seems to be equally attracted to Alice and Said. His
feelings aside, though, ``Criminal Lovers'' is a terribly cold
movie, very good at drawing attention to its sources but not
involving on even the simple level of fairy tales, with their
capacity for dwelling on native fears. Ozon's fantasy is
sterling-silver-plated and cool to the touch, so the direction
feels like nothing more than a form of gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   His intelligence shines through, but at the expense of the
characters. By the time Alice and Luc fall into each other's arms
and have a bout of soul-cleansing sex while forest animals gambol
about their naked bodies _ a smarter-than-the-average-bear riff on
Disney nature films _ the whole thing feels like a cool-breeze
exercise, with the film giving a detached running commentary on its
own content. It's one of those cases where the director trips over
his own brains; he's too smart for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `CRIMINAL LOVERS`
</P>
<P>
   Written (in French, with English subtitles) and directed by
Francois Ozon; director of photography, Pierre Stoeber; edited by
Dominique Petrot; music by Philippe Rombi; production designer,
Arnaud de Moleron; produced by Marc Missonnier and Olivier Delbosc;
released by Strand Releasing.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Natacha Regnier (Alice), Jeremie Renier (Luc), Miki
Manojlovic (the Woodsman), Salim Kechiouche (Said) and Yasmine
Belmadi (Karim).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 90 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
