<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7943 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-INTERNET-AVIATION21-C     07-20 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AVIATION21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIRLINES' WEB SITE FOR TICKETS COULD BE ABUSED, CRITICS WARN
 &HT;    With INTERNET-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Shopping on line for an airline ticket will become
simpler and cheaper once the nation's biggest carriers start
selling tickets through a jointly sponsored Web site this fall, the
companies insist.
</P>
<P>
   But critics warned Thursday at a Senate hearing that the joint
venture, called Orbitz, will quickly become a ``platform for
collusion'' to steer customers away from independent travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   The launch of Orbitz this fall will ``eliminate or severely
curtail the competition from existing online travel agencies,''
said Mark Silbergeld, co-director of the Washington office of
Consumers Union, a nationwide consumer advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   A senior official of the U.S. Department of Transportation (DOT)
agreed that Orbitz has the potential to harm consumers, but said
certain regulations could head off problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orbitz could potentially benefit consumers and airlines by
providing a wider range of fare options, bias-free displays, and
reduced booking fees,'' DOT Inspector General Kenneth Mead said.
``But red flags raised by competitive issues, such as airlines
potentially restricting their lowest fares exclusively to Orbitz,
must first be resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Mead suggested that the government insist that airlines disclose
their lowest fares to all travel agents so that consumers could get
the same information no matter where they go to find it.
</P>
<P>
   The Orbitz hearing was requested by Senate Commerce Committee
Chairman John McCain, who said he was concerned because of the
industry's history of using computerized reservation systems to try
to stifle competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be foolish of us to ignore our past experience'' and
assume that major airlines won't use the Internet to shift business
to themselves and their joint-venture travel agency, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Orbitz is backed by the nation's five largest carriers: Delta
Air Lines, United Airlines, Continental Airlines, American Airlines
and Northwest Airlines. Thirty other airlines have agreed to join
as affiliates. But some carriers, including Southwest Airlines,
oppose the joint operation.
</P>
<P>
   Orbitz Chairman and CEO Jeff Katz said his company will use a
newly developed search engine that can find more and better fares
for customers by using multiple servers, rather than mainframe
computers. At the same time, Orbitz will help participating
airlines by drastically reducing their ticket distribution costs.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, a carrier pays a commission to the travel agent
who books the ticket. But with Orbitz acting as the travel agent,
the airlines the will, in essence, be paying commissions to
themselves _ a move that will hold hold costs down for consumers,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, airlines have been trying to get travelers to buy
tickets from the carriers' own Web sites. But Web surfers have
preferred to seek out independent sites, such as Expedia, owned by
Microsoft Corp., and Travelocity, owned by Sabre Holdings Corp., to
compare fares. Nearly half of the roughly $7 billion spent on
online travel last year went to those two agents.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that airlines will offer their lowest fares only on the
Orbitz site, the American Society of Travel Agents has filed a
complaint with the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said he was skeptical about Orbitz,
given that it is owned by the same airlines that frequently have
failed to live up to pledges to improve customer service. ``Given
the pattern of anti-consumer activity by the airlines, we need to
determine the minimum safeguards'' to protect consumers before
Orbitz gets started, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Department of Transportation: www.dot.gov
</P>
<P>
   Senate Commerce Committee: www.senate.gov/(tilde)commerce
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
