<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BENEATH-FILM-REVIEW-N     07-20 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BENEATH-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT LIES BENEATH': DESPITE ZEMECKIS' SHOCKS, RESULTING `BENEATH'
IS SCHLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By ELVIS MITCHELL  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before moving on to more stately affairs (``Forrest Gump'' and
``Contact''), Robert Zemeckis was accomplished at good
old-fashioned unclean fun, so it should come as no surprise that he
has directed the new thriller ``What Lies Beneath.''
</P>
<P>
   At the start, he zaps us with quick, glib scares, just to show
he still knows how, but his heart isn't in this kind of material
anymore. His reflexes are a little slow.
</P>
<P>
   Zemeckis and his former partner, Bob Gale, honed their skills
working on the hammy shock series ``Kolchak, the Night Stalker,'' a
creature-of-the-week television show from the late 1970s that
inspired ``The X Files.'' But those days of zip and wanton mockery
are long behind Zemeckis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Lies Beneath'' is as implausibly chilling as any ``X
Files'' episode. By the last 10 minutes (this movie is two hours
and 10 minutes long), your interest will have long vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The film takes its time in laying out the story of high-strung
Claire (Michelle Pfeiffer), who is dissolving into hysteria on a
regular basis. Her daughter (Katherine Towne) has just gone off to
college. And Claire is still recovering from the trauma of a car
accident of a year before, when she was behind the wheel. Then her
house starts showing signs of being haunted. Her husband, Norman
(Harrison Ford), is a driven research scientist who's never home to
offer any emotional support.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer plays the kind of damaged-goods housewife with too much
time on her hands that is one of the few horror-genre cliches
``Scary Movie'' didn't get around to making fun of. On the other
hand, ``Scary Movie'' understood the virtues of brevity. Pfeiffer
stops walking on eggshells about an hour into the movie and shows
that she's capable of breaking a few eggs. By this time, the
audience knows she is possessed by the spirit of a woman (Amber
Valletta) with whom Norman had an affair, and she drops onto him
from the ceiling for hot-blooded clinches.
</P>
<P>
   Between the shameless shocks, and with the help of about a third
of Pfeiffer's performance, ``Beneath'' clicks. The movie is too
similar to one of its climaxes, which involves Claire's fighting
off the effects of a drug that causes paralysis: the film stumbles
around in a stupor, trying to bring its eyes down from the top of
its head and wake up before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   Zemeckis has all the externals down cold. He uses long takes and
occasionally tosses off a firecracker of a surprise at the end of a
scene. There are ominous breezes through the house as a cello saws
away on the soundtrack. Diana Scarwid packs her own good time as
Claire's fun-loving New Age flake of a pal; her jaundiced squint
and hoarse croak of a laugh indicate she would know how to have fun
in a haunted house.
</P>
<P>
   Ford shambles through this picture like the real terror, the
Creature Without a Pulse. He, too, has the superficial details down
to a science, using his voice like a cozy cotton blanket to drop
over Pfeiffer's shoulders. The only surprise in this picture is its
audacious torpor; the trailer gives away everything but the price
of the large popcorn and Diet Coke special.
</P>
<P>
   At this point in his career, Ford knows he needs to try
something new, and very early in the film he shows more loose charm
than he did in ``Six Days, Seven Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Zemeckis, too, wanted to test his skills; he squeezed this movie
in during a break from shooting ``Castaway,'' with Tom Hanks.
</P>
<P>
   The big climax could be right out of ``Tales From the Crypt'' (
Zemeckis served as an executive producer for the cable series based
on the 1950s horror comics). Or, for that matter, from ``Kolchak,
the Night Stalker.'' It's openly schlocky. Mostly, ``What Lies
Beneath'' glazes over faster than a Krispy Kreme doughnut, and
neither is very flavorful after sitting around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `WHAT LIES BENEATH'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Zemeckis; written by Clark Gregg, based on a
story by Sarah Kernochan and Gregg; director of photography, Don
Burgess; edited by Arthur Schmidt; music by Alan Silvestri;
production designers, Rick Carter and Jim Teegarden; produced by
Steve Starkey, Zemeckis and Jack Rapke; released by DreamWorks.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Michelle Pfeiffer (Claire Spencer), Harrison Ford (Norman
Spencer), Diana Scarwid (Jody), Joe Morton (Dr. Drayton), James
Remar (Warren Feur), Miranda Otto (Mary Feur), Wendy Crewson
(Elena), Ray Baker (Dr. Stan Powell), Amber Valletta (Madison
Elizabeth Frank) and Katherine Towne (Caitlin Spencer).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 130 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
</TEXT>
