<HEADER>
A7954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-OSTEOPOROSIS0721-COX     07-20 1322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTEOPOROSIS0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When your bones betray you
 &HT;    By Carolyn Susman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The falling seemed interminable. Like Alice down the
rabbit hole.
</P>
<P>
   But the landing was hard, and Anita Stillman had no doubt that
she had broken her left hip.
</P>
<P>
   At nearly 79, this active woman was participating in a breast
cancer seminar at Boca Raton Community Hospital when her weakened
bones betrayed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sitting at the end of the table. I was getting up to get
a cold drink and somebody had put a pocketbook underneath,'' she
recalls, gesturing under her sofa to indicate how the errant object
had obstructed her path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught my right foot in it and I went flying, and . . .
believe me, as I came down, I could hear my doctor saying, `Your
left hip has nothing very much left there.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I hit, I knew I cracked it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing very much left there. Words that had caused the
grandmother to cringe when she had heard them only three days
before.
</P>
<P>
   The diagnosis: osteoporosis, a thinning of the bones that will
cause half the women over 50 to experience a fracture in their
lifetimes. And one in eight men over 50, as well, according to the
National Osteoporosis Foundation, (www.nof.org).
</P>
<P>
   Peak bone mass is reached in the 20s and 30s, so exercise and
calcium are extremely important then to build up strong bone mass.
At least 1,000 milligrams of calcium daily is advised. When bone
loss begins, as it will, in the 40s for women and in the 50s for
men, increased calcium is recommended _ about 1,200 milligrams a
day average _ along with continued exercise, moderate alcohol, and
no smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The message going out today is: Osteoporosis is both a
preventable and treatable disease.
</P>
<P>
   Stillman had very little bone density left when she fell, but
that was the second time she had gotten a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people her age, she thought that broken bones were a
consequence of aging and had tried and discarded treatment three
years earlier when the drug she was taking to build her bone mass,
Fosamax, gave her heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she didn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis? That hurt, and resulted in replacement of both her
knees.
</P>
<P>
   But osteoporosis is a silent disease that rarely alerts those
who have it.
</P>
<P>
   Stillman did have an indication, though, that all wasn't well.
</P>
<P>
   Her posture had deteriorated _ ``My children noticed I was
stooped, and my husband kept saying, `Stand up!' '' _ and she had
lost an inch in height, both signs of bone deterioration. Yet, she
didn't follow through on treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't doing it consistently,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't suffer with osteoporosis. When I took my first (bone
density) test, I was surprised at the results. If it doesn't hurt,
you don't fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   FOCUSING ON CANCER INSTEAD
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem appears to be that women are more afraid of
cancer than of osteoporosis, even though the risk of a hip fracture
equals the combined risk of developing breast, ovarian and uterine
cancer, the National Osteoporosis Foundation advises.
</P>
<P>
   And 20 percent of those with hip fractures _ men and women _ are
dead within a year because of conditions like pneumonia that can
develop when people are bedridden with fractures.
</P>
<P>
   Some women are afraid, also, of Fosamax, the often prescribed
medication, which can cause intestinal problems or ulcers in the
esophagus if not taken correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon R. Sullivan of Greenaces is one of those. Even though her
mother had osteoporosis, and she herself had a bone density test
that showed she was losing bone mass, Sullivan quit taking the drug
four years ago after a four-month trial.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't that the drug disagreed with her, it's that she had
read about its possible risks _ which occur infrequently if
instructions are followed, according to the American Medical
Association _ and didn't want to take that chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there's got to be a better way.''
</P>
<P>
   Her doctor showed her pictures of her weakened bones; he argued
with her to continue to take some medication. Eventually, she lied
and told him she was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who wanted to listen to him? I think he really truly believes
that I should and I didn't want to.''
</P>
<P>
   She knows that medical tests showed Fosamax _ first introduced
in 1995 _ builds healthy bone at the spine and hip, but she prefers
to try a regimen of diet, exercise, and vitamins that is
recommended to prevent bone weakening.
</P>
<P>
   At 66, she walks 4 miles every other day, alternating with yoga
exercises followed by weight lifting. She also takes 1,200
milligrams of calcium plus vitamin D daily. (Doctors generally
recommend 1,500 milligrams daily for postmenopausal women not on
hormone replacement therapy.)
</P>
<P>
   And she eats lots of high-calcium foods.
</P>
<P>
   When she went back for her follow-up bone density test two years
after her initial exam, her condition was the same. She hadn't lost
bone density, but she hadn't gained any, either.
</P>
<P>
   Even though there are other drugs that can be used for
osteoporosis, Sullivan is sticking with her routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the alternative method is far better for me. Not only
am I strengthening my bones by lifting weights, I'm eating foods
that have a lot more antioxidants in them. And I have lost a good
30 pounds!''
</P>
<P>
   She's scheduled to take another test this year (Medicare pays
for bone density tests every two years for people at risk) but
still hasn't decided whether she'd switch to drugs if her bones are
thinning further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking very positively at this point,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICATION CRUCIAL FOR SOME
</P>
<P>
   Doctors warn that waiting can be a dangerous game, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in the early, early stages (of bone loss), chances
are you'd benefit from going on prophylactic care and not waiting
and seeing,'' said Dr. Richard Levine, an internist, who
specializes in geriatrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you're downright osteoporotic, you should find a
medicine that works. Or watch your step!''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mark Ettinger, medical director of the Clinical Research
Center of South Florida in Stuart and Lake Worth, agrees that there
should be no doubt about taking medication if a patient already has
osteoporosis.
</P>
<P>
   But there might be room for experimenting, such as Sullivan is
doing, if the patient is only mildly affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how low (in bone density) she is. If she's not
dangerously low, and maintaining (bone), fine. She needs to be
monitored on an ongoing basis. That's different from a woman going
down (in bone density) or already osteoporotic with a high risk of
fracture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no magic number at which fracture risk increases. It's
an ever increasing continuum of risk. There are rapid and slow bone
losers. There is no one-size-fits-all treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he emphasizes, ``cleaning up lifestyles and taking calcium
pills are not enough for many women. An adequate diet and exercise
will certainly slow the rate of bone loss, but for some women it's
not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   CHANGES IN MOBILITY, ACTIVITIES
</P>
<P>
   Anita Stillman knows that truth.
</P>
<P>
   Since her fall, she has been using a nasal spray, Miacalcin, to
help retard bone loss, and is taking calcium and vitamin D daily.
</P>
<P>
   Her lifestyle, however, has been severely affected by her fall.
She has to use a walker and painkillers to get through her day, and
she no longer can dash out the door on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   She gazes at the ceiling fan she used to stand on a ladder to
clean and shakes her head, no. That's a task she won't try again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a most debilitating thing. I must alter my lifestyle
because I know my bones are thin. I'll do my best to build them up
because I am aware of what is wrong. Once you know you have it, if
a person has any kind of intelligence, they have to know it doesn't
go away. Don't wait till you fall.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
