<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7956 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IDENTITY-THEFT-0721-C     07-20 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IDENTITY-THEFT-0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMITTEE ADDS VOICE TO COMPLAINTS ABOUT ``IDENTITY THEFT''
 &HT;    By Rob O'Dell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House subcommittee unanimously approved a bill
that would protect Americans from identity theft _ primarily the
misuse of Social Security numbers _ by restricting how those
numbers can be used.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed the Social Security subcommittee by a
voice vote Thursday, would restrict the use of Social Security
numbers in both the public and private sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Identity theft is the fastest growing financial crime in the
nation, affecting an estimated 500,000 to 700,000 Americans each
year,'' said subcommittee Chairman E. Clay Shaw, R-Fla., the bill's
sponsor. ``Today, we've taken another significant step toward
protecting Americans from this devastating crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security was created to help Americans enjoy their
golden years, not spend their days trying to restore their good
name.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would prohibit the sale of Social Security numbers by
private industries or any government agency _ at the local, state
or federal level. It also would prohibit third parties from
offering services to obtain Social Security numbers, such as
advertising agencies offering services to stores to obtain the
names and Social Security numbers of prospective clients.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, Social Security numbers also would be
prohibited from appearing on driver's licenses, motor vehicle
registration, or other identification-related records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year alone, the number of Americans who reported misuse
of their number increased 233 percent,'' Shaw said. ``Social
Security numbers were once a form of financial security, and they
have now become a tool for potential financial ruin.''
</P>
<P>
   The new legislation would deter businesses from refusing service
if a person declines to provide their Social Security number by
making them liable under the Unfair Trade Practice Law. It would
not be a blanket restriction on all uses of Social Security numbers
but would simply ban sales of the numbers, Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Social Security numbers were first introduced, their
purpose was to keep track of worker's earnings so benefits could be
calculated when the worker retired,'' Shaw said. ``But today,
Social Security numbers have become the gateway for crooked con
artists to raid your bank accounts, max out your credit cards, and
literally steal your identity.''
</P>
<P>
   House action on the bill is expected in September, said a
spokeswoman for Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Rep. E. Clay Shaw: www.house.gov/shaw
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
