<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-CHRISTIANS-07     07-20 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-CHRISTIANS-0721-1STLD- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in19th graf, adds 'Archbishop' title before 'Pietro Sambi'
 &HT;    CHRISTIAN LEADERS DON'T WANT TO BE FORGOTTEN IN JERUSALEM TALKS
 &HT;    (600&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    EDs: With list of Christian holy sites attached at end of story.
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0721.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ He is a Christian living near the place where Jesus
was crucified, but Palestinian Jack Mardin still feels like some
people do not recognize his place here.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think there are Jews and Muslims and there are no
Christians here,'' said the 25-year-old Mardin (pronounced,
Mar-DEEN''). ``The Holy Sepulcher is our church. Our patriarchs are
here. We have lots of churches.''
</P>
<P>
   His patriarchs may feel the same way.
</P>
<P>
   This week, local leaders of the three major local Christian
denominations wrote a letter to U.S., Israeli and Palestinian
leaders asking for a place at the Camp David peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trust you will not forget or overlook our age-long presence
here,'' stated the letter from the patriarchs of the Greek
Orthodox, Roman Catholic and Armenian Orthodox churches.
</P>
<P>
   The letter asks that Christian communities not be divided and
for guarantees that holy sites will remain open to all the faiths.
</P>
<P>
   The status of Jerusalem, ruled by Israel but claimed in part by
the Palestinians, is said to be a major sticking point in the
10-day-old summit talks at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians are asking for sovereignty primarily over the parts
of Jerusalem that they populate, which were captured by Israel in
the 1967 war. Israelis say that Jerusalem has been the center of
Judaism for 3,000 years and cannot be shared.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has been painted in largely terms of Muslims vs.
Jews. Focus is on who will rule over the Western Wall, sacred to
Jews, and the Haram esh-Sharif complex, sacred to Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   In the battle for world opinion, Israeli leaders repeatedly
state that Jerusalem is not as important for Muslims as it is for
Jews. It is, they say, the ``heart of Judaism.'' Christians are
rarely.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Jerusalem's place in Christianity, Jerusalem Mayor
Ehud Olmert said recently, ``It is a lung for Moslems and a lung
for Christians and a heart for Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jerusalem is the site of Jesus' crucifixion and
resurrection. The place where he prayed in Gethsemane and where his
mother, Mary, lived. It is also home to about 10,000 Christians.
Most of them are Palestinians and some are Armenian.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem's Christian sites are also the destination of hundreds
of thousands of Christian pilgrims from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, pilgrims lined up in the Church of the Holy Sepulcher,
the cavernous collection of chapels where Catholics and Orthodox
Christians believe Jesus was crucified.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Swehla, a 22-year-old pilgrim from Modesto, Calif., said he
was keeping track of the Camp David talks but does not expect them
to affect the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will really make a difference,'' he said,
standing in the line to see Jesus' tomb. ``No one will do anything
to it. It's too historic.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, few expect any major changes in the holy sites soon.
Modern history has seen generally open access under Israel. The
Palestinian Authority built Christian confidence by sinking
millions of aid dollars into improving conditions around the
birthplace of Jesus in Bethlehem, under their control.
</P>
<P>
   But, before the modern age, the Holy Land saw churches,
synagogues and mosques ransacked as rulers of the different
religions held sway. Even the Church of the Holy Sepulcher has been
destroyed more than once since it was first built in the Fourth
Century.
</P>
<P>
   ``History has shown that whoever has the political power tends
to favor his own,'' said Archbishop Pietro Sambi, the Vatican
representative to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The letter from the patriarchs was similar to other
pronouncements that Christian leaders have made during
negotiations, said Palestinian analyst Mahdi Abdul-Hadi.
</P>
<P>
   It stated that they oppose a proposal reportedly being discussed
at Camp David in which Israel would retain control of the Jewish
and Armenian areas in the Old City. The Palestinians would get
control of the Christian and Muslim areas.
</P>
<P>
   The church leaders said the Armenians are Christians and should
not be divided from the other Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The letter also asked for ``international guarantees'' that
Christians will have open access to Christian sites. It also asked
that Christians be allowed to continue to develop their
communities, which have shrunk dramatically in proportion to the
Jewish and Muslim populations.
</P>
<P>
   Wadie Abunassar, spokesman for the authors of the letter, said
they did not intend to meddle in politics or favor either side in
the negotiations but to protect Christian interests.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a major Protestant group has taken a pro-Israel
stand. The International Christian Embassy in Jerusalem has for
more than a year circulated a petition commending Israeli control
of holy sites in Jerusalem and throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
   The ICEJ organizes trips and activities in Israel primarily for
evangelical churches around the world and has consistently sided
with Israel in its bid to hold onto occupied areas.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   -----------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   JERUSALEM'S CHRISTIAN HOLY SITES
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is home to many Christian holy sites based on the
traditional _ though not always confirmed _ locations of events
described in the Bible. Here are some, listed by location:
</P>
<P>
   OLD CITY
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Church of the Holy Sepulcher: Orthodox Christian and Catholic
site of Jesus' crucifixion and resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Via Dolorosa/Stations of the Cross: Path where Jesus is
believed to have walked bearing the cross.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Anne's Church: Believed by some to be the site of the home
of Mary and her parents, and where Jesus cured an ill man.
</P>
<P>
   EAST JERUSALEM:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden Tomb: Protestant site of the crucifixion and
resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Garden of Gethsemane: Mount of Olives site where Jesus prayed.
</P>
<P>
   WEST JERUSALEM:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Cenacle: Traditional site of the Last Supper.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Monastery of the Cross: Traditional site of the tree used to
make the crucifixion cross.
</P>
<P>
   Source: The Holy Land, by Jerome Murphy O'Connor; Jerusalem:
Illustrated History Atlas, by Martin Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
