<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7959 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-LOSER-SPI &LR;      07-20 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LOSER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING LEADS MAKE `LOSER' A WORTHWHILE DIVERSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amy Heckerling kicked off the modern wave of teen revisions of
the classics with ``Clueless,'' her high-school twist on Jane
Austen's ``Emma.'' Her new college romance, ``Loser,'' is inspired
by, of all things, Billy Wilder's classic film ``The Apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Transplanted from corporate culture to a university setting,
it's an amiable little comedy with a pair of bright young leads
propping up a film with little dramatic heft.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Biggs, the ``American Pie'' pastry lover, is the eponymous
loser Paul, a sweet, small-town doofus who leaves his Midwest home
for New York University. Paul is the lump in the melting pot, a
clumsy, culturally clueless kid in a dorky hunting cap and haircut
out of the Jazz Age dropped into a dorm with three preening rich
snots who are in college to party, score chicks and party some
more.
</P>
<P>
   Dora (Mena Suvari, the rose petal princess from ``American
Beauty''), dressed in thrift-store punk fashions and coifed in a
carefully chaotic nest of hair, looks the gloomy goth chick but is
really a bubbly, bright girl selling herself short in crummy jobs
and a demeaning affair with their patronizing European history
teacher, Professor Alcott (Greg Kinnear).
</P>
<P>
   The romantic complications of ``The Apartment'' arrive when
Paul, already smitten with Dora, arrives home to find her passed
out in his bathroom. His treacherous former roomies have been using
his off-campus digs to stage drug-fueled parties and slipped her a
mickey, leaving her in a bad way.
</P>
<P>
   Oily Alcott will have nothing to do with her, and Paul becomes
her nurse, best friend and heartsick suitor.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs strikes a balance between awkward, out-of-place flailing
and nice guy sincerity and naivete , and Suvari is delightfully
animated as a struggling city girl. Though they never really spark
as a romantic couple, their easy, relaxed performances make their
scenes together great fun, and Heckerling never lets the picture
slip into doofus humor.
</P>
<P>
   But the film never comes alive. Kinnear is almost too good as a
smarmy, stuck on himself jerk, and the three elitist fashion
stooges quickly devolve into vicious miscreants. Such cartoonish
characters offer little weight to the quandaries offered in this
obvious morality play.
</P>
<P>
   And for a college romantic comedy, it's completely lacking in
the campus culture. It's up to Biggs and Suvari to shore up the
piece. Their charm can't overcome the underbaked drama, but they're
fun to spend time with. Sometimes that's good enough.
</P>
<P>
   LOSER
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR/WRITER: Amy Heckerling
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Jason Biggs, Mena Suvari, Greg Kinnear, Zak Orth, Tom
Sadoski, Jimmi Simpson
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 105 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for language and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0258 </DOCNO>
