</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ GALVESTON, Texas _ My first impression of
Galveston was literally a blur. I was 14 years old and there on a
Scout trip. Being terribly nearsighted and full of teen-age
stupidity, I wore my glasses into the surf so I would be able to
see if I was about to be bit by a jellyfish, or worse, a shark.
(Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel) EMBARGOED for Sunday. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MCNEELY-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Wait. You
actually think the Texas comptroller _ a partisan elected official
_ would trot out revenue statistics with an eye to politics? Next
you'll say Santa Claus is my mom and dad. Well, not to suggest the
recent revenue estimate by Republican Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander isn't accurate. But suffice it to say that Rylander and
her Democratic predecessors know how to use the revenue estimate as
a political tool. (McNeely, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ SOMEWHERE IN THE WEST _ ``But it
was a blue spruce.'' This was my wife, pining to no one in
particular. I was listening but my ear was of no comfort to her.
We'd just driven by a gorgeous stand of mountain evergreens. Her
entreaty to the back-seat boys to observe it in wonder had met
towering indifference. (John Young is opinion page editor of the
Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED.
</P>
