<P>
   WESTNILE _CDC announces that 26 infected birds (more than they
said at the ocnference this week) have been found this summer in
the NY region, where intensive surveillance is going on. The agency
issues guidelines for dealing with WN in problematic areas: check
dead birds, kill mosquitos with whatever spraying is necessary,
wear insect repellant and protective clothing. Checking to see how
much of this people should be doing in Georgia and other Southern
states where WN hasn't arrived yet but is forecast to. (McKenna,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   OSTEOPOROSIS _ Two women share their struggles with
osteoporosis. We talk to a woman in her 70s who broke her hip as a
result of osteoporosis. The good news: the silent disease is
treatable and preventable. (Susman, Palm Beach Post) 40. WITH ART.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JUNK-DNA _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Researchers at UT and Duke have
figured out a way to harness junk DNA and turn it into a vehicle
that can be used in gene therapy and genetic engineering. The
implications are monumental. The potential applications range from
using the process to cure cancer and AIDS; alter genes to protect
people from biological warfare; and genetically engineer a better
crop of wine and cheese. Human trials on using junk DNA in HIV
patients are about a year or two away. (Roser, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
