<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, July 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The record-setting heat that has plagued parts of the Southeast
for most of July will abate Friday and Saturday as a front drifts
south through the Gulf states. The front will be the focus for
clusters of thunderstorms for the next several days. The strongest
storms Friday will be from eastern Oklahoma to the western
Tennessee Valley. Scattered thundershowers will also occur near the
front in the Carolinas and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Unseasonably cool air will cover a large area from the upper
Middle West to the Northeast. A front marking a new surge of the
cool air will be preceded by a broken band of thundershowers near
the central and northern Appalachians. Behind the front, abundant
clouds and sprinkles will occur in the chilly air around the Great
Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, heat will expand as high pressure promotes ample
sun.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HAWAIIAN TROPICS
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the tropical ocean south of Hawaii gave birth to the
first tropical depression of the central Pacific hurricane season.
Should the depression, which is 700 miles south of the island
chain, strengthen, it would be named Alika. Tropical storms and
hurricanes that form in the Pacific between 140 degrees west
longitude and the international dateline are given Hawaiian names
and are monitored by the Central Pacific Hurricane Center in
Honolulu. Hurricanes that form farther east in the Pacific have a
separate set of names and are tracked by the Tropical Prediction
Center in Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
