<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7966 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DOCTORS-BIOTERROR-NYT     07-20 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-BIOTERROR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN NATIONAL SECURITY BECOMES A MEDICAL ISSUE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 By STEPHEN L. COHEN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    In an October broadcast eerily reminiscent of Orson Welles' 1938
radio thriller, ``The War of the Worlds,'' ABC News broke a
horrific story to a startled television audience: terrorists had
unleashed deadly biological weapons on an unsuspecting American
city. Undetected by subway commuters braving the evening rush hour,
the attackers had tossed bottles of anthrax spores onto the train
tracks, releasing lethal bacteria in an invisible cloud. Within a
week, 50,000 people would be dead.
 &HT;    It was every civic leader's worst nightmare, and one of the
greatest disasters in U.S. history. But it never happened. Like
Orson Welles' apocalyptic tale of alien assault, it was a fictional
account, and like the 1938 radio broadcast, it triggered its share
of controversy.
 &HT;    Though ABC made it clear that it was presenting a fictional
scenario, some viewers lambasted the network, complaining that it
was encouraging potential terrorists to act. Others accused the
network of unnecessary theatrics that could only promote fear and
confusion.
 &HT;    But was the broadcast accurate? Do Americans really face the
specter of a biological Armageddon?
 &HT;    According to Defense Secretary William Cohen, the prospect of a
catastrophic attack is all too real. In a recent statement, he
described how contagion could spread dramatically in the aftermath
of a biological attack, with doctors offering little relief and
hospitals becoming warehouses for the dead and dying. He concluded:
``This is not hyperbole -- it is reality.''
 &HT;    Others are more sanguine. Robert Burnham of the FBI's domestic
terrorism unit considers the risk of a biological attack to be
relatively low, though he says that the FBI is genuinely concerned
about a loophole in federal law that makes the possession of
bioweapons like anthrax perfectly legal, regardless of whether one
has a legitimate reason to possess such material. This loophole
complicated the prosecution of Larry Wayne Harris in 1995 for the
possession of the agent that causes bubonic plague.
 &HT;    Dr. D. A. Henderson, Director of the Center for Civilian
Biodefense Studies at Johns Hopkins University, believes that the
threat of bioterrorism has heightened in recent years, and that
dissident groups have both the motivation and the ability to deploy
some of the most dangerous pathogens as weapons against the U.S.
population.
 &HT;    He dismisses the widely held view that the scientific expertise
required to produce and disperse lethal organisms is only within
the reach of the most sophisticated laboratories.
 &HT;    ``Recipes for making biological weapons are available on the
Internet,'' he explains, ``and even groups with modest finances and
basic training in biology and engineering could develop an
effective weapon at little cost.''
 &HT;    The Japanese cult Aum Shinrikyo is best known for its 1995 sarin
gas attack on the Tokyo subway system, but we now know that the
group also planned to use biological weapons like anthrax against
U.S. forces in Japan. The cult's arsenal included large amounts of
nutrient media, botulinum toxin, anthrax cultures, and drone
aircraft equipped with spray tanks. Members of the group even
traveled to Zaire in 1992 to obtain samples of Ebola virus for
weapons development.
 &HT;    Henderson cites two familiar microbes -- smallpox and anthrax --
as the most formidable threats to the public. Anthrax, with a
fatality rate of 80 to 90 percent, could cause thousands of
casualties, paralyzing an entire city. Smallpox is also a killer of
unimaginable proportions: in the 20th century alone, it has killed
500 million people.
 &HT;    Unlike anthrax, smallpox is a highly communicable disease, which
means that it could spread like wildfire through the population.
And since routine smallpox vaccination in the U.S. was halted in
1972, as much as 90 percent of the population lacks smallpox
immunity. This means that a major city could quickly be swamped
with cases of a disease in which one out of three people will die.
 &HT;    It would not take many cases to overwhelm the medical system.
The Center for Civilian Biodefense Studies reports that even if
only 50 people were initially infected, it could lead to a
nationwide epidemic with thousands of fatalities. Cities, moreover,
lack the isolation facilities needed to prevent further spread of
the contagion.
 &HT;    In Washington, D.C., for example, there are only about 100
hospital beds that could provide proper isolation of infected
patients. Making matters worse, smallpox vaccine reserves would
rapidly be depleted. The U.S. currently has about 15 million doses
on hand, but it is estimated that only about half of these doses
are usable. If more vaccine were needed, it would take up to a year
to produce it, since there is presently no manufacturing capacity
for the product.
 &HT;    All of this points to a serious gap in the nation's preparedness
to address the biological weapons threat, despite the Clinton
administration's efforts to increase spending over the past two
years to fight terrorism. According to medical experts, the problem
may be one of priorities as well as financial resources.
 &HT;    In recent testimony before Congress, Dr. Tara O'Toole of the
Johns Hopkins University School of Public Health reported that
domestic preparedness programs have focused primarily on the threat
posed by conventional explosives or chemical weapons. Yet medical
experts maintain that biological terrorism is more likely than ever
before, and far more threatening than either explosives or
chemicals. While the worst effects of a chemical or explosive
attack are soon over, the devastation following a smallpox or
anthrax outbreak would continue for days, weeks or even months as
new cases continued to arise.
 &HT;    An effective response would require significant medical
resources, but for fiscal year 2000, the Department of Health and
Human Services is requesting just $230 million out of a total
anti-terrorism budget of $10 billion. This represents less than 3%
of the total budget, and health professionals contend that it is
emblematic of the administration's lack of attention to the
bioweapons threat.
 &HT;    O'Toole addressed the issue of biological preparedness in her
House testimony. She explained that few American cities have
practiced responding to an attack that employs biological weapons,
and that even when bioterrorism scenarios are considered,
clinicians, hospital leaders and public health experts are
frequently excluded from the training and exercises sponsored by
federal agencies.
 &HT;    She also stressed that the government urgently needs to expand
its efforts to develop national pharmaceutical and vaccine
stockpiles and to improve disease surveillance systems.
 &HT;    Dr. Michael Osterholm, a former Minnesota state epidemiologist
and an authority on bioterrorism, is even blunter in his
assessment: ``We have a substantial national response to terrorism
-- the problem is they forgot to include a meaningful biological
component in their plans.''
 &HT;    
