<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEN-SOURCE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEN SOURCE SHARES WEB SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB NORBERG   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTEREY, Calif. _ Perl, Apache, Sendmail and Bind are not
household names, say, like Microsoft. Unless the house is filled
with techies whose lives revolve around building interactive Web
sites for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But those little-known technologies increasingly are the
infrastructure of the Internet and are part of a growing worldwide
``open source'' movement in which software code is shared freely
among techies.
</P>
<P>
   Without those programs, no one could surf the Internet for
advice on buying a new car or plan a Hawaii vacation, send e-mail
to a stock broker, buy a book or sell an antique desk at auction.
</P>
<P>
   It was those technologies _ and the far-flung community of
programmers that developed them _ that were on display this week at
O'Reilly &AMP; Associates' second annual Open Source Conference,
drawing 1,800 Web developers, programmers and systems
administrators from 24 countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this worldwide development community that is
invisible to the general public, just as what they create is
invisible to the public,'' said Sara Winge, spokeswoman for
O'Reilly, based in Sebastopol. ``And yet what they have created,
the Internet, is the greatest technological impact to come along in
a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference began four years ago as a classroom program of
tutorials for Perl, the computer programming that connects Internet
servers to other computer programs and makes the Web interactive.
</P>
<P>
   It evolved into an open source conference coinciding with the
strengthening of the open source movement, which believes that
software, programming and innovation are best served when the
source code is open and available on the Internet, allowing anyone
to work on it, and not closed and proprietary, such as software
produced by Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Open source is a process, not a product,'' said Tim O'Reilly,
O'Reilly &AMP; Associates' founder and president.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Behlendorf, who co-founded Collab.Net with O'Reilly to run
open source projects for corporations, said an open source project
could involve 50,000 programmers worldwide adding a bit of code,
and current estimates are 5 million to 10 million open source
programmers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real innovation happens in the universities and by people
hacking at home on their own, and open source nurtures that,''
Behlendorf said.
</P>
<P>
   Open source has developed into a community with an almost
cultlike following.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly said an open source conference was a natural follow-up
to his company's best-selling Perl book, a textbook on programming
Perl scripts to connect Web servers to other computers, which allow
Web sites to become interactive and also perform functions. Perl,
for instance, allows a stock quote page to link to news stories or
searches Web sites for key phrases of text.
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly's book publishing business, which caters to developers
and programmers, sold $15 million in Perl books since its first
publication in 1992. Company revenues are about $60 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Without the open source movement, the Internet never would have
succeeded, O'Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet service providers use Apache software for their
servers, e-mail uses Sendmail, Perl links Web servers to other
programs, like databases, and Linux operating systems are used in
Web publishing and system administration.
</P>
<P>
   All of those programs are open source.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was all this important technology, and it was all
underground,'' O'Reilly said, adding that his company's ``sweet
spot was documenting all that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which costs as much as $1,000 to attend,
includes four days of tutorials in those subjects. Chuck Burwell of
San Francisco, a systems administrator for Wells Fargo Bank,
attended for sessions on Sendmail.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can find the information at other places, but it is not as
centralized,'' Burwell said. ``We use several open source tools.
Sendmail is the biggest one. Our entire e-mail system is based on
Sendmail.''
</P>
<P>
   Perl programmer Jason Maxham of Alexa, an Amazon.com subsidiary
in San Francisco, was interested in the tutorial classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great place to learn,'' Maxham said. ``The courses
are taught by the best and the brightest in the world of Perl.''
</P>
<P>
   Shane O'Donnell of OpenNMS.org, from Raleigh, N.C., used the
conference to meet developers face-to-face. His company has an open
source program that connects servers to networks for ISPs and large
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't the only conference, there are Linux conferences,
but it is the broadest format within the open source community,''
O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of The New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
