<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WWII-MEMORIAL21-COX     07-20 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-MEMORIAL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORLD WAR II MEMORIAL CLEARS NEXT-TO-LAST HURDLE TO APPROVAL
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Fine Arts Commission approved plans
Thursday for a World War II monument to be built on the National
Mall between the Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote came after six hours of emotional testimony.
Opponents argued that the memorial's granite arches and pillars
will spoil the open, sweeping vista of ``America's front yard.''
Supporters countered that the sunken design will not mar the view,
and that this ``hallowed ground'' is the appropriate site to
remember the most significant event of 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The approval leaves only one more bureaucratic hurdle before
construction can begin. Final approval of the design is needed next
month from the National Capital Planning Commission, which has
already given a preliminary okay. Ground-breaking for the $100
million monument is scheduled for Veterans Day in November. and
dedication for Memorial Day in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   With World War II veterans dying at a rate of 1,000 a day,
supporters said there is some urgency in getting started. The war
ended 55 years ago, and the average age of its veterans is 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost 10 million of the 16 million men and women who
served in uniform. There are less than 6 million of us left,'' said
former Sen. Bob Dole, chairman of the National World War II
Monument Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is taking longer to build the memorial than it took to
fight the war,'' said Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, author of the
legislation authorizing the memorial. Congress voted its approval
in 1993, and President Clinton dedicated the site two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Kaptur began the effort at the urging of Roger Durbin, a
constituent and World War II veteran who had visited Washington and
was dismayed to find no memorial to the epic struggle waged and won
by what Tom Brokaw has termed ``the Greatest Generation'' of
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, Roger passed away earlier this year,'' Kaptur told the
commission.
</P>
<P>
   Years of debate have improved the memorial design, but ``there
comes a point'' when action must replace talk, said Sen. Daniel
Inouye, D-Hawaii. ``We have reached that point,'' said Inouye, who,
like Dole, was partially disabled by his World War II wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the right site. We have the right design. What we do
not have is a lot of time,'' said Luther Smith, who served with the
Tuskegee Airmen, an African American unit, before being taken
prisoner after his plane was shot down over Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But dozens of opponents marched to a microphone and told the
arts commission that ``it's not too late'' to move the memorial to
another spot.
</P>
<P>
   The site is wrong. with the memorial imposing itself upon the
majestic open space between the Washington Monument and Lincoln
Memorial, said Judy Scott Feldman, an architectural historian
leading the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The World War II Memorial would encircle the existing Rainbow
Pool, an integral part of the Lincoln Memorial, she said. Her
group, the National Coalition to Save Our Mall, may file suit to
stop the project, citing a National Park Service report that they
say confirms this connection between the Rainbow Pool and the
Lincoln Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two cannot be severed without destroying the whole,'' said
Eleanor Holmes Norton, the non-voting congressional delegate of the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference before the commission meeting, Norton said
the memorial should be located in the Constitution Gardens, a few
hundred yards north of the proposed site. If the memorial is built
as planned, she said, ``our generation will be blamed'' for
``obstructing'' and ``defacing'' the National Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial features two semi-circles of 56 stone pillars with
bronze wreaths, representing the number of U.S. states and
territories during the war. The pillars surround a 7.4-acre sunken
plaza and fountains in what is now the Rainbow Pool. On the north
and south entrances are 41-foot triumphal arches that designers say
will stand under taller elm trees that already line nearby paths.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of criticism, the original design was altered so the
vista was not obstructed, said Fredrich St. Florian, the architect.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial will be ``sensitive to its setting'' and
``respectful of its neighbors,'' he told the commission, and it
will convey the message that democracy triumphed over tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.wwiimemorial.com
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
