<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DOCTORS-SPOUSE2S-BOS &LR;      07-20 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-SPOUSE2S-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL COMMUNITY SEES DOMESTIC MURDER CASES AS BIZARRE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (In third graf, corrects that it's Dr. Kartell's estranged wife's
lover who was shot.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD AND RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ One practiced plastic surgery in upscale Andover. The
others were affiliated with two renowned Harvard teaching
hospitals. Each, authorities say, ended his career as a healer in a
burst of deadly violence.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 48 hours, three Boston-area physicians have appeared
in court facing murder charges, a macabre coincidence that is
prompting some local doctors to ponder their special responsibility
to remain gentle under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dr. James Kartell of Andover received a five- to
eight-year prison term for shooting his estranged wife's lover to
death inside the Methuen hospital where Kartell had long practiced.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the defense continued to present its case in the
trial of Dr. Dirk K. Greineder, who headed the allergy department
at Brigham and Women's Hospital until he was accused last fall of
bludgeoning his wife to death in a Wellesley park.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Dr. Richard Sharpe, a Gloucester dermatologist
affiliated with Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center, was arraigned
on charges that he shot his estranged wife to death Friday in her
Wenham home. Greineder and Sharpe have pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the state Board of Medicine expressed concern over
the trio of murder cases. They suspended Sharpe's license Wednesday
_ as they did previously with Greineder's and Kartell's _ and said
they would redouble efforts to reach out to troubled physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Board's Physician Health and Compliance Unit works closely
with the (Massachusetts Medical Society) to ensure doctors in need
of support receive assistance and supervision,'' said board member
Dr. Peter Madras.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors interviewed stressed that they see the three killings
mainly as a bizarre coincidence, not as a sign that doctors have
somehow become prone to homicide. But they said that in the days
since the Sharpe case erupted, it has been a hot topic in some
medical circles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any colleague that I've seen that I
haven't had the conversation, `Can you believe this?' '' said Dr.
Kenneth Arndt, who until March headed the dermatology department at
Beth Israel Deaconess and was Sharpe's adviser during his Harvard
residency. ``Every place I am, people know him or have known him.''
</P>
<P>
   At Massachusetts General Hospital, where Sharpe completed a
fellowship, several doctors said Wednesday that they were working
too hard to consider the issue, and some had not heard of the
murders. But one resident wearing blue scrubs, who refused to give
his name, said the news about Sharpe had disturbed him and made him
think about doctors' need to stay calm at the most stressful times.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to think a doctor could've found another way of
resolving the conflict, which is what we're taught all the time in
dealing with patients,'' the resident, in his mid-30s, said as he
grabbed a snack from a hot dog cart near the hospital. ``You'd like
to think we're . . . maybe better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stephen J. Bergman has considered himself ``a spokesman for
humane medical training'' since his 1978 novel ``The House of
God,'' based on his residency at Beth Israel, became a cult classic
among medical trainees. He said Wednesday that he pays special
attention to murders by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm especially interested in where we go wrong, how we lose
our humanity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two sensational murders that have become part of popular culture
involved doctors accused of killing their wives _ Sam H. Sheppard
and Jeffrey R. MacDonald.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman said that while murder accusations are extreme cases,
the recent ones made him feel angry that the medical profession is
not better at quickly detecting emotional and drug abuse problems.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe may have abused prescription drugs, his wife's lawyer has
said, and Greineder, authorities said, had turned to prostitutes
and online pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a self-centered, achievement-oriented, competitive
perspective, that can be rewarded in destructive ways by medical
schools and medical training programs and the medical profession,''
Bergman said.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that all of the accused are more than 40 years old, he
said that self-centered view ``can take you only so far in your
life . . . and then something's gotta give.'' Bergman, a
psychiatrist, added that middle-aged doctors have a high incidence
of depression, substance abuse, and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Medical Association, doctors are more
likely to become the victims of homicide than to commit it. There
is no evidence that doctors are more or less prone to commit murder
than people in other professions, says the AMA.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Massachusetts Medical Society, Dr. Virginia
T. Latham, found a different message in the killings: Domestic
violence affects all professions, including doctors, and
``transcends socioeconomic levels.'' She said the society is trying
to stress that point to its membership, and sent guidelines on
detecting domestic abuse to all doctors in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Sharpe had several businesses built around cosmetic
surgery such as liposuction and that Kartell was a plastic surgeon,
area plastic surgeons said that they are under particular pressure
because they work on people's faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like an entertainer who is on stage,'' said Dr.
Joel Feldman, a private-practice plastic surgeon in Cambridge.
``There is the sense that your work is all out there for people to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he added, that is no reason to kill.
</P>
<P>
   The changing nature of medicine with its stress on efficiency is
a burden on many doctors, said Dr. Richard Corlin, a Santa Monica,
Calif.-based gastroenterologist who is president-elect of the AMA.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what you have in Boston,'' he said, ``is a tragic and
bizarre coincidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
