<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0721-1     07-20 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-0721-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: in 24th graf, corrects 'Friday' to read 'Thursday'; in
final graf, corrects 'we get ... ' to read 'he gets ...' in quote
 &HT;    FOR MIDEAST SUMMIT, CLINTON SHOWS 'IT AIN'T OVER 'TIL IT'S
OVER': Leaves Talks On Life Support In His Absence
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-CHRISTIANS-0721.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ Midnight loomed over the cloud-shrouded Catoctin
Mountains, framing the portrait of gloom that hung with the weight
of lost hope within the green clapboard walls of the Laurel lodge.
</P>
<P>
   For nine days and nights here Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators had argued and reasoned, fulminated and fumed, hoping
to resolve the dense web of dispute at the core of half a century
of enmity and war in the wounded heart of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Their talks, though, had failed. Their bags were packed for the
long journey home, and there seemed nothing left now but to bid
each other a farewell tinged in sorrow for what might have been, a
mournful wake for the dreams of peace they had dared to share over
strong coffee and simple meals in the days when that vision lay
just over the horizon of their common gaze.
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby cabin, though, the body was still breathing. The
high-stakes peace summit, already officially declared dead, was
actually on diplomatic life support, sustained by a frenzy of
jawboning, cajoling and finally arm-twisting by at least one person
unwilling to let the talks die.
</P>
<P>
   With his black armored limousine waiting to ferry him from his
secluded retreat near here to the White House 70 miles away,
President Clinton pushed, nagged and let his temper flare in a
last-ditch effort to keep Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat from leaving Camp David with no
peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Through a five-hour diplomatic rollercoaster ride, Clinton
shuttled between Arafat and Barak, who had not met directly in four
days, while the badly listing summit teetered on the brink of
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   By 10:30 (ET) Wednesday night, Clinton appeared to give up.
</P>
<P>
   He ordered his spokesman, Joe Lockhart, to announce to reporters
gathered in this hamlet five miles from Camp David that the
high-stakes talks had collapsed in failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summit has come to a conclusion without reaching an
agreement,'' Lockhart said, sending the international press corps
galloping off like digital age town criers to announce to the world
that the negotiations had failed.
</P>
<P>
   In the Camp David darkness, U.S. Secret Service agents scrambled
to shoehorn Secretary of State Madeleine Albright's limousine into
the waiting presidential motorcade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prepare for POTUS movement,'' an agent's voice crackled over
the scanner, using the White House acronym for President of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcade stayed put, though. Albright, Clinton, his
National Security Adviser Samuel Berger and his top Mideast Envoy
Dennis Ross remained in contact with Arafat and Barak and their
negotiating teams.
</P>
<P>
   By midnight, the faltering peace summit had been resuscitated.
Arafat and Barak agreed to extend their negotiations for at least
three more days, while the president journeys to Japan and returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all thought it was over,'' Clinton said an hour later,
speaking to reporters holed up at the temporary press center set up
at Thurmont Elementary School. ``And then we discovered that nobody
wanted to quit. Nobody wanted to give up.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the high-drama diplomacy, aides insist, was a
president determined, after seven years of trying, not to let the
chance for securing a peace accord slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There, in the president's mind, was an opportunity, and an
opportunity to be seized,'' Lockhart told reporters early Thursday
morning, an hour or so after Barak and Arafat agreed to go into
overtime at a Camp David summit originally scheduled to have ended
by Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say the president used every ounce of his power of
persuasion that he had available to him,'' Lockhart said, ``and
then some that he didn't know he had.''
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton triumphed in holding the talks together, he remained
far from securing a peace accord. He warned clearly, moreover, that
none was guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing in the fact that they're staying here that
magically makes this easier,'' Lockhart said. ``It's not easy, and
there's nothing that can make it easy.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 2 a.m. (ET) Thursday when Clinton returned to the White
House. Less than three hours later he was gone, boarding Air Force
One with his daughter, Chelsea, for the 15-hour flight to Okinawa,
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   There, Clinton is to meet Friday and Saturday with his
counterparts from the so-called Group of Eight industrial
democratic powers _ the United States, Canada, France, Italy,
Japan, Germany and Britain plus Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the agenda will be Clinton's assessment of the prospects
for Mideast peace _ and his pleas for G-8 economic and security aid
to support an agreement, should one be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll remind the leaders of the G-8 both what's at stake and
discuss in some format how countries within the G-8 can help this
process eventually,'' said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's absence, Albright met separately Thursday with
Arafat and Barak, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher told
reporters Thursday, as negotiating teams from both sides held talks
focused on such core issues as the question of Palestinian
statehood, the future of Jerusalem, the fate of Jewish settlers and
Palestinian refugees and territorial and security matters.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear how much longer the Camp David talks might
continue. That assessment, said Boucher, would be made by Clinton
upon his expected return late Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think that unlimited time should be spent on this,''
Boucher said. ``It is a matter of making decisions and working on
the issues so decisions can be made.''
</P>
<P>
   Albright's chief task, until the president's return, will be to
try to clarify those areas where both sides remain apart and to
consolidate, where possible, issues on which they've made progress
toward agreement since the talks began July 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will continue to try to close the gaps and move forward on
the issues,'' Boucher said. ``She is here to carry the ball forward
so that the president can assess our progress when he gets back.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
