<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRITE FILM `BENEATH' EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C-  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Zemeckis (``Forrest Gump'') is usually such a reliable
filmmaker that you really have to wonder how he managed to
criminally misuse the marquee dream team of Harrison Ford and
Michelle Pfeiffer and turn out a summer thriller as predictable and
hackneyed as ``What Lies Beneath.''
</P>
<P>
   He's quoted all over the media as saying he wanted to make a
``pure suspense movie,'' ``something really terrifying and
mysterious'' _ ``perhaps the kind of film Hitchcock would have made
in his day, but using the modern technology of today to help tell
the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, though the film winks at Hitchcock's ``Suspicion'' and
``Rear Window,'' it's actually a ghost story _ and one that seems
to have been hastily rewritten at the last minute to be the kind of
somber, low-tech variety of the genre that was the rage of last
summer's box office.
</P>
<P>
   It opens well, the production values are very strong and there's
a goose bump or two raised in the first act. But it soon collapses
into a plodding patchwork of scenes from other, better movies and a
climax so melodramatic that it drew hoots of laughter at last
week's Seattle preview.
</P>
<P>
   The story is about the Spencers, a seemingly perfect couple who
live in a lakeside Victorian mansion in an idyllic Vermont town:
Claire (Pfeiffer), a fortyish, ex-classical musician recovering
from some undisclosed recent trauma; and her second husband, Norman
(Ford), a workaholic genetics professor (Ford).
</P>
<P>
   When their only daughter goes off to college, Claire not only
suffers the empty-nest syndrome in a big way, she begins hearing
voices and seeing strange visions, and soon concludes that a young
woman neighbor has been murdered and _ as in ``The Sixth Sense''
and ``Stir of Echoes'' _ the ghost is trying to tell her something.
</P>
<P>
   Truly, this is a bad script. It's out for suspense with a
capital ``S,'' but since there's absolutely no surprises in it, the
audience is always two steps ahead of the game. It's also clear
from the get-go just who the real villain is _ indeed, it's even
spelled out for us right there on the film's poster.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't help that the movie is a grueling two-hours and 10
minutes long or that Zemeckis' narrative pacing is way off, or that
he overdoses the audience with so many clumsy false scares _ things
menacingly jumping out that turn out to be the family dog or some
other innocuous nothing _ that we're soon completely immune to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer tries valiantly but she's helpless under the
circumstances. Ford doesn't seem to be trying at all, and is
surprisingly charmless and dull. He may be the biggest movie star
of the last 25 years, but after last fall's ``Random Hearts'' and
this clunker, he may be in need of some serious career advice.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT LIES BENEATH
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTOR: Robert Zemeckis
</P>
<P>
   WRITER: Clark Gregg
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Harrison Ford, Michelle Pfeiffer, Miranda Otto, Diana
Scarwid, James Remar
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 130 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: PG-13 for domestic and occult violence
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0268 </DOCNO>
