<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-20 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHO IS FRANK KEATING? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Texas Gov. George W. Bush picks Oklahoma Gov.
Frank Keating as his running mate _ which insiders suggest Bush is
inclined to do _ the country will be confronted with a very
conservative, Southern-dominated Republican ticket.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, Keating's great charm is that he is a long-time chum
who could be depended on to be loyal and supportive. He is not a
Bush clone, but their views are similar.
</P>
<P>
   Keating,56, is an anti-union, anti-abortion Catholic in good
standing with the party's religious right activists.
</P>
<P>
   He took the conservative Heritage Foundation here by storm on
Thursday, packing the think tank's auditorium with ideological
allies and curious members of the media. His official purpose was
to discuss his campaign to reduce Oklahoma's high divorce rate.
Most of his audience simply wanted to have a close look at an
obscure, small-state governor who might be thrust into national
prominence any minute now.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't duck the big ``veep'' question, admitting that all the
speculation was flattering. He joked about waiting for the magic
phone call from Bush, wondering aloud if it would come.
</P>
<P>
   And he observed wryly that one unexpected consequence of all the
speculation was that his son recently called from college and
``treated me reverently _ that has never happened before in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Keating lavishly praised Bush, promising to ``do anything he
wants'' even if there is no Bush-Keating ticket. ``It may be that I
will be serving ice tea at some reception,'' he quipped.
</P>
<P>
   The slim, white-haired Keating is an attractive personality with
an easy-going manner not unlike Bush's own. He won a reputation for
calm leadership with his sympathetic, reassuring response to the
1995 Oklahoma City bombing in which 168 people died.
</P>
<P>
   But his views are so conservative that his presence on the
ticket would be a downer if Bush intends to reach out to
independents and turn a moderate face to the electorate in
November. Furthermore, as a fellow governor, Keating lacks the
legislative and foreign policy experience that a senator could
bring to the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The issues that matter to Oklahoma have little resonance in the
industrial Midwest, the bustling West Coast or the liberal
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Keating stands with the religious right not only against
abortion but also on the contentious issues of school prayer and
the teaching of evolution.
</P>
<P>
   When the Supreme Court said student-led prayers broadcast over a
loudspeaker system at a football game were an unconstitutional
breach of the traditional wall between church and state, Keating
accused the high bench of violating the Constitution instead of
upholding it.
</P>
<P>
   When Oklahoma's State Textbook Committee demanded that all
biology textbooks bear a disclaimer saying that evolution is
``unproven'' and a ``controversial theory,'' Keating applauded. He
described this official snub of all the scientific evidence that
confirms the human evolutionary process as ``thoughtful.'' For good
measure, he added irresponsibly that he didn't think he was
descended from a baboon.
</P>
<P>
   When he got into a fight over pay levels with the state's
unionized teachers, he was asked his solution for dealing with
them. ``Homicide,'' he snapped. (He later claimed it was just a
joke, but the teachers were not amused.)
</P>
<P>
   His elevation to the national Republican ticket might galvanize
not only teachers' groups but other unions as well. Many labor
leaders already prefer Vice President Al Gore, but the members are
not uniformly enthusiastic. Wait until they learn that Keating
regularly pushes for a state right-to-work law, which the unions
hate. Such laws prohibit employers from requiring a worker to join
a union in order to obtain or hold a job.
</P>
<P>
   Keating has not had his way on right-to-work because the
Oklahoma legislature is not always prepared to do his bidding.
Asked his opinion of the state's lawmakers earlier this year, he
replied, ``The legislature has yet to get religion. That's to be
expected, since two-thirds of them are Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   He tried later to explain that he didn't mean Democrats are
godless heathens but merely that they are politically
unenlightened. The fact he made the crack at the religion-based
Oral Roberts University in Tulsa, Okla., however, tends to undercut
his sanitized revision.
</P>
<P>
   In short, adding Keating to the ticket might make Bush feel
comfortable but it wouldn't do much toward winning the election.
The only Republican who would do that remains Sen. John McCain of
Arizona, and Bush does not seem to have the courage to cope with an
independent star who could outshine him.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-G8-OKINAWA-(TRIMS)-NY     07-20 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-OKINAWA-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
G8 MEETING FOCUSES THE WORLD'S EYES ON OKINAWA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGO, Japan _ Of the many locations Japan considered for the
annual summit meeting of the world's largest industrialized
nations, this resort town in the country's southernmost island,
Okinawa, seemed a most dubious choice.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawa, a backwater province plagued by a tragic past, lacked
the infrastructure and know-how needed to mount an international
event of such magnitude. Relations between Tokyo and the erstwhile
island kingdom have never been good, and the islanders have long
demanded the removal of the U.S. military bases that constrict
their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
   But the late Japanese Prime Minister Keichi Obuchi, who died
suddenly of a stroke in May, insisted on staging the summit meeting
here, hoping to bolster Okinawa's weak economy and make some amends
for decades of abuse and neglect of the island by Japan and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   With the summit meeting opening Friday, many Japanese officials
and their U.S. counterparts are now regretting Obuchi's
well-intentioned choice, and are fretting about the potential for
mishap and mayhem in what is ostensibly a sun-drenched paradise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you can say that we are all on pins and needles,''
said a Japanese official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``Although we feel ready for the summit, there is a sinking feeling
in our stomachs that it will either go off without a hitch or there
could be great chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   To the unknowing eye, Okinawa is a haven: a sub-tropical slice
of striking beauty, rich in coral reefs, lush forests, pristine
beaches and blue-green waters.
</P>
<P>
   But trouble lurks not far beneath this shimmering surface. The
recent arrest of a U.S. Marine accused of molesting a sleeping
Okinawan schoolgirl has heightened outrage among islanders who have
vowed to disrupt the summit meeting with massive demonstrations.
About 27,000 angry people formed a human chain Thursday around
Kadena Air Base to protest the presence of U.S. troops on the
island _ a major embarrassment to the decorous host nation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is the first U.S. president to visit Okinawa
since it reverted back to Japan from the U.S. military in 1972. On
Friday, the president is scheduled to make a major speech at the
peace monument on this island, which at the end of World War II was
the scene of a fierce battle between the United States and Japanese
troops. Nearly one-third of Okinawa's population was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese security forces, which have deployed 22,000 officers
from across the country to Okinawa, are bracing for a possible
repeat of the violence that erupted during international trade
meetings in the United States in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   And summit meeting organizers have expressed fear that Okinawa,
Japan's poorest and least-developed prefecture, cannot handle the
onslaught of the thousands of foreigners who are expected to attend
the conference. Forecasts of nightmare traffic jams, power
failures, overbooked hotels, faulty telephone lines and seasonal
typhoons abound.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Before Japan annexed Okinawa in the early 1600s, the island was
the seat of the Ryukyu Kingdom, which was closely linked to China
and had diplomatic and trade ties with Korea and Southeast Asia.
Because of their multicultural links, Okinawans have their own art
forms, dialect, cuisine and way of life that are distinct from the
homogeneity elsewhere in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the door to Asia for Japan,'' said Ryu Yamazaki, the
foreign ministry spokesman. ``We wanted to introduce the world to
this unique culture which is part of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Japan has been host to past meetings of the G8 nations, but in
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawa is the largest of the small islands that make up the
prefecture, which has a population of 1.2 million people and is
home to about two-thirds of the 45,000 U.S. military personnel in
Japan. Okinawans maintain that they bear an unfair burden because
their island is less than 1 percent of Japan's total area but
contains 75 percent of the U.S. military facilities in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The island also has its share of social problems. Okinawa's
unemployment rate is twice the national average. It has Japan's
lowest household savings rate and lowest per capita income, and the
country's highest teenage pregnancy and divorce rates.
</P>
<P>
   One reason to bring the meeting here was to convince islanders
to accept a much-disputed plan to construct a new U.S. Marine Corps
helicopter base off the coast of Nago. The new heliport will
replace the Futenma Air Station, which is set to be returned to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   While Okinawans welcomed the closing of the old air station,
which was a major nuisance to local residents, they are adamantly
opposed to allowing the United States to build a new military base.
But the allure of hosting the international summit meeting, with
its economic benefits, was seen as the major factor that persuaded
local Okinawan officials to accept the relocation plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``One cannot deny the political benefits of putting the summit
in Okinawa,'' said Yukio Okmoto, a former foreign ministry
official, who served as an adviser to past Japanese governments on
the Okinawa issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, the main reason was to bring a new era of thinking to
the Okinawa mentality,'' Okmoto said. ``Okinawa has been shackled
by past history and unable to move forward like the rest of Japan.
Mr. Obuchi thought the summit would be a very important turning
point in the island's history.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many Okinawans have mixed feelings about the summit meeting:
They are delighted that the conference will focus worldwide
attention on them and their culture, but worried that the summit
meeting will be seen as a quick fix for their long-standing
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although the islanders' dislike of the U.S. military bases is
clear, many expressed great pride that the three-day conference has
come to town.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the summit, Okinawa will no longer be a question on
`Jeopardy,''' Takada said. ``The world will know us.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the island, government offices, businesses, private homes
and taxi cabs are displaying the flags of the eight nations whose
leaders are attending the summit meeting. The central government
has spent hundreds of millions of dollars to construct new
conference halls, widen roads, refurbish parks and install new
telephone lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great thing for world leaders to come here and learn
about the Okinawan reality,'' said Yashikazu Tamaki, an Okinawan
assemblymen. ``It's good for Okinawan children because it will give
them a sense of pride and encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I am worried that leaders like President Clinton will come
to Okinawa and make a speech thanking Okinawans for accepting the
military bases,'' Tamaki said. ``That would be like rubbing salt
into the wounds of Okinawans, because the reality is we don't want
the bases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
