<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7994 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-GORE-PROFILE-SPI &LR;      07-20 2009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-PROFILE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AL GORE EAGER TO SHARE HIS VISION WITH OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN BAY, Wis. _ Even by the elastic standards politicians use
to measure success, July 13 was an exceptionally good day for Al
Gore. In fact, it was as close to perfect as Gore had experienced
since launching his candidacy for president 13 months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley, who challenged Gore for the Democratic nomination,
had just enthusiastically endorsed him in front of 1,000
sign-waving, high-decibel supporters at a picturesque old amusement
park on the shore of Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement was news, and the visuals were good, earning
Gore a prominent place on that night's network news. The weather
was sunny and warm. Voters nationwide saw Gore in literally the
best possible light.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in a long time, there was a sense of momentum
surrounding Gore and his campaign, an unmistakable optimism that
the campaign _ and the candidate _ were finally hitting their
stride.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as he rode back to Green Bay's airport in his black
limousine, the 52-year-old vice president was surprisingly subdued,
refusing to give in to the exhilaration that surrounded him, even
when asked a softball question about the endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large number of voters respect his judgment and have an
interest in his thoughts and recommendations,'' Gore said of
Bradley. ``So I think it is a very big endorsement that will help
quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the candidate who is famous for keeping his emotions
in check was playing true to form. And in so doing, Gore
highlighted one of the biggest barriers between him and his goal of
being the next president of the United States. Voters, even
stalwart Democrats, have a hard time getting excited about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a lot of voters, Gore is not inspiring; he's wooden,''
said Don Balmer, a professor of political science at Lewis &AMP; Clark
College in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released last week by the independent Pew Research Center
confirmed Balmer's assessment and exposed Gore's dilemma as he
heads toward the Democratic National Convention next month and the
crucial weeks that follow.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that while voters in general are lethargic about
the race, Gore's Republican rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, ``has
an enthusiasm edge over Gore ... particularly within his own party
base.''
</P>
<P>
   It drives Rep. Norm Dicks crazy. Dicks, D-Wash., is one of
Gore's closest friends and has spent enough time with him to see a
side that Gore shields from public view. If only Gore would loosen
up, Dicks says, life would be so much easier for him.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't, and Dicks is at a loss to explain why. ``That's
one of the biggest mysteries I've ever encountered. The guy who I
played basketball with in the gym or sat on the floor with and
chitchatted is a guy with a lot of energy, a lot of personality and
a good sense of humor. He's very witty and quick.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gore would not concede that people find him
difficult to like. ``Even if it were true, it wouldn't be a matter
of great concern,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because so few people are really focused on the election right
now and where I'm personally involved (to the public), they know me
as vice president, but they don't really know me as a person or as
a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job over the next 3{ months includes introducing myself and
telling them very clearly what my vision for the future of the
country is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for Gore is the lingering questions about his
role in raising money during the 1996 campaign. The Justice
Department and the FBI have recommended that a special prosecutor
be appointed to investigate allegations of illegality, but Attorney
General Janet Reno has declined to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the attention is focused on a 1996 event Gore attended
at a Buddhist temple where campaign contributions were collected.
Republicans in Congress also have called for a special prosecutor
to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also has been linked to 37 ``coffees'' at the White House
that investigators believed were improper fund-raisers. Gore has
told investigators he attended 25 of the events but insists nothing
improper took place.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were not fund-raisers,'' he said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet
The Press.'' ``That's the simple point. And again, this has all
been investigated many times, and I put out the entire transcript
(of his questioning by investigators) of that voluntarily,
completely and fully, so that people can make up their own minds
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a region in the country where the vice president
should be doing well, it is the Northwest, where his experience and
his liberal-to-moderate views on the environment, education, health
care and other issues resonate. Yet a recent poll had him behind by
5 points in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is Gore's natural cautiousness. On issues
important to Washington, such as the preservation of salmon and the
future of Microsoft, he offers answers that only raise more
questions.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Gore had to say in the interview about preserving
salmon and the potential for tearing down four large dams along the
Snake River _ an issue on which there is no middle ground:
</P>
<P>
   ``I have pledged that I would bring together all of the affected
and interested parties, build a science-based consensus in the
Northwest on the best approach to secure the future of salmon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Extinction is not an option. Nor is massive economic
dislocation. But with a consensus approach that brings all of the
parties together, I'm confident we can develop a solution that
works for all parties.''
</P>
<P>
   On the question of Microsoft's future and the government's
anti-trust case against the software maker, Gore offered even less.
``I don't comment on ongoing legal proceedings. It would be
improper of me.''
</P>
<P>
   On other issues important to Washington state, such as trade,
Gore's stance is virtually the same as Bush's. Both support
expanding trade to China and opening markets overseas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Gore is having problems in Oregon and Washington
is indicative of some large problems with his campaign,'' said Tim
Hibbitts, an independent pollster in Portland. ``Why isn't Gore
winning big'' in the Northwest? Hibbitts wonders. ``He's not that
unpleasant an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his aides are trying to figure it out, too. Polls show
that voters agree with his positions on such issues as education,
crime, Social Security, the economy and health care more than they
do with the positions taken by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Still other polls show that people are feeling good about the
direction the nation is headed, about the economy and the future.
Yet Gore reaps little benefit from those good feelings, even though
as vice president he had prominent roles in formulating policy.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that Gore is prepared for the job. He has been
vice president for eight years and before that he was a U.S.
senator and a congressman. He served five months in Vietnam as an
Army journalist, going to the front lines ``with an M-16 and a
pencil,'' Gore likes to say.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting into politics, he was a newspaper reporter in
Nashville, Tenn. He spent a year of study at a divinity school
before winning a seat in Congress in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being born in Carthage, Tenn., Gore is more a creature
of Washington, D.C.'s power alleys than of the South. His father,
Albert Gore Sr., was a U.S. senator from 1953 through 1970. He
attended one of the capital's most elite prep schools and received
a degree in government with honors from Harvard University in 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Gore credits his father with nurturing his political instincts
and ideology. The elder Gore was notable for being one of the
South's few liberals. He supported civil rights and opposed the
Vietnam War. Those views ultimately brought him down.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore Jr. formally announced his candidacy, his speech
included a loving tribute to his father, who died in 1998, and to
his father's last campaign, in 1970. ``His last election was lost _
but his conscience won,'' Gore said. ``He taught me all my life
that that was what really counted. I miss my dad, but I know he's
here in spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Less public influences are his wife, Tipper, and his oldest
daughter, Karenna Gore Schiff. Gore often seeks their advice
regarding the campaign. Of Tipper, he told USA Today, ``I really
trust her judgment a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   A trained psychologist and former newspaper photographer, the
51-year-old Tipper Gore has been called the ``principal power
center in Gore's world'' and plays a major, if quiet, role in many
of Gore's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   They have been married for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Karenna Gore Schiff, at 26 the oldest of Gore's four children,
reaches out to young voters as part of her campaign duties. As for
her political instincts, her father says she has ``nearly perfect
pitch,'' which gives her comments extra weight within the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She also is the mother of Al and Tipper's only grandchild, a boy
born on July 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first go-round for Gore in presidential
politics. In 1988, he won more than 3 million votes in seven states
before dropping out of the race for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is familiar with Washington state. He has visited 15 times
since the 1996 election. Last summer, he and his son, Albert,
climbed Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., said having a president with such a
deep understanding of the state is important. ``I'll know that a
year from now if I have a problem with apples in central Washington
I can call a president who gets it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If Gore comes across as guarded, he doesn't shy away from a
political fight. He battered Bradley so aggressively in the
primaries that Bradley called Gore ``dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   He has relentlessly attacks Bush as being a pawn of the gun
lobby, ``big oil'' and the wealthiest of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he thought Bush was compassionate, as the Republican
claims, Gore said, ``I don't really know him personally, so I can't
comment on his personal attributes. I don't think the policies he's
followed tend to be compassionate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly not toward the children who have to go without
health insurance in larger numbers in Texas than in any of our
other 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly not for those who are breathing in the worst air
pollution in any state because of sweetheart deals with the big oil
companies. ... I could go on, but I think you get the picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he chose a life of public service, Gore became
animated for the first time in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``A life of public service? Oh, my gosh. I talked to a woman two
days ago who is blind because of diabetes she got 10 years ago. I
want to raise the amount of research funding to speed the finding
of a cure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman is a senior citizen, and she talked about the
prescription drug bill. She was really near desperation because she
couldn't afford to pay for her prescription and still have enough
money to buy food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Passing a prescription drug benefit and getting that woman the
health care she deserves would make any kind work and sacrifice
worthwhile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and his senior advisers are hoping that people will be
swayed not by Bush's easy backslapping but by Gore's experience,
his strong Democratic credentials and most of all, his promise for
``a fresh start, a new president who has the willingness to fight
for the working people; and serve the people instead of the
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about me,'' Gore said in the interview. ``It's not
about George W. Bush. It's about the future of America. It's about
the American people and I have great confidence in the judgment of
the American people. ``I strongly believe that the positions that I
have had ... for almost a quarter of a century now are far more in
tune with what the American people want than the views on the other
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
