<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DISCERNING SCOTS STUDY TIGER'S GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Out near the ninth green of the Old
Course, an elderly Scot suddenly shook his head and asked, ``Why
are there so many people?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tiger Woods,'' he was told, ``is in the next group.''
</P>
<P>
   But because the 24-year-old U.S. Open champion had made eight
quiet pars, all those people following him had not made much noise.
The Scots never do. Tom Weiskopf, who won the 1973 British Open at
Troon, once assumed his blind shot at a Scottish course would be
close to the hole, but when he and Jack Nicklaus arrived at the
green, his ball was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here it is,'' Nicklaus finally said. ``In the cup.''
</P>
<P>
   On his way off the green, Weiskopf looked over at the gallery of
Scots and asked, ``Did anyone see the ball go in?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes,'' he was told.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why didn't you clap?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a practice round.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Woods shot a 5-under 67 in Thursday's opening round of
the 126th British Open, the Scots were equally discerning. It was
as if they were examining a new high-tech timepiece to learn what
makes it tick.
</P>
<P>
   Some stopped at the concession stands to munch fish and chips,
chicken and chips, burgers, sausages and sandwiches while drinking
soda (``That's one fifty, love,'' the counter lady said) and
McEwan's Export ale, advertised as ``the perfect round.'' But
mostly they were quietly studying the golfer in the black cap, gray
shirt, black vest, black slacks and black shoes who has changed the
game that Scottish pros brought to America a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the Scots were studying how Woods would adapt his
power to the nuances of seaside-links golf, especially at the Old
Course, with its steep-walled bunkers. But Thursday, he was never
in a bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, as Woods' pitching wedge spun to within 12 feet on the
352-yard ninth hole, the applause was firmer. When he made the putt
for his first birdie, he was accorded a quick burst of applause
that resembled the weather _ sunny and warm. ``All right, Tiger,''
someone even yelled.
</P>
<P>
   If he had made that birdie at the Masters, the roar would have
shaken Augusta National's cathedral pines.
</P>
<P>
   If he had made that birdie at the recent U.S. Open at Pebble
Beach, the roar would have rolled across Carmel Bay like the surf.
</P>
<P>
   At the Old Course at St. Andrews Thursday, the only roar was
when Royal Air Force fighter jets took off from the Leuchers air
base across the Firth of Tay.
</P>
<P>
   But even without U.S. sound effects, that first birdie seemed to
energize Tiger Woods. On his way to the 10th tee, he had a quicker
spring in his step. He hadn't used his driver since the sixth tee
but now he crushed a tee shot that rolled across the hard, fast
fairway to within a few yards of the huge green on the 379-yard
hole and prompted an ``ooooh'' from the gallery. And when his
50-yard putt stopped about 10 feet from the cup, he earned a burst
of applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``They understood and appreciated that it was a good putt,'' he
said later. ``They know.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scots also seemed to know that Woods was on the move now.
After a par at the 174-yard 11th, he birdied the 314-yard 12th with
a driver and two putts. Counting his par at the 175-yard eighth, he
suddenly had five consecutive 3s.
</P>
<P>
   After another 300-yard drive on the 14th, he surveyed the Hell
Bunker where Jack Nicklaus took five to get out en route to a 10 in
the 1995 Open and where an U.S. tourist once turned to his Scottish
caddie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I carry that Hell Bunker?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt it, sir. It probably weighs 20 tons.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods carried those 20 tons. He pounded a 3-wood onto the green
and two-putted for another birdie. At the 456-yard 15th, a driver
and a 9-iron to 10 feet of the hole created his fifth birdie. But
with people peering out of the windows of the Old Course Hotel, a
pulled 3-wood off the tee on the 17th, the dreaded ``Road Hole,''
preceded his best shot of the round _ a slashed 160-yard escape
from the heather.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to hit it hard with my right hand, then again
hold on with my left,'' he explained later. ``You have to open up
the face because you know the grass is not going to grab the
clubhead, it's going to grab the shaft. That's the trick to it. You
need to hit it hard and hold on so you don't flip it. It was a
delicate balance I was trying to find.''
</P>
<P>
   When his ball soared to just short of the green, and then he
putted to within a foot to save par, the Scots understood and
appreciated what he had done. They even applauded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
