<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7996 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BUSH-PROFILE-SPI &LR;      07-20 2027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-PROFILE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEORGE W. BUSH A MAN `AT EASE WITH HIMSELF' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY   
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ As a senator's grandson, son of a president and
the Republicans' soon-to-be nominee for the White House, George W.
Bush comes from an American political dynasty that extends the
velvet glove but knows how to use a fist of steel.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor bills himself as a ``compassionate
conservative'' who promises education policies that will leave no
child behind, just as his father, George Bush, spoke of ``a kinder,
gentler America'' in 1988 and pledged to be the ``education
president.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes basic Republican principles and adds a soft edge to
them,'' said Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., chairwoman of this year's
Bush campaign in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But George W. Bush also delights in being seen as a tough guy
and recalling what happened to those who underestimated him. ``In
1994 I was diminished,'' he said in a recent interview here,
referring to the campaign in which incumbent Texas Gov. Ann
Richards dubbed him ``shrub.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been living with the name `George Bush' all my life, I'm
proud of it,'' added Bush. He unseated the popular Richards.
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old Texas governor comes from a line of Connecticut
Yankees transplanted to the Oil Patch. The Bushes have long put
emphasis on personal generosity, proper behavior and public
service. But they also fight to win and rarely forget a slight.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush was given the nickname ``Junior'' behind his back
when serving as a sometime political troubleshooter in his father's
campaigns and presidential administration. He was the
enforcer-gatekeeper who briefly shut off Newsweek magazine's access
after it ran a campaign profile with the cover headline ``Fighting
the Wimp Factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 1992 campaign, he performed an unpleasant deed that
his father could not bring himself to do _ telling the abrasive
White House chief of staff, John Sununu, it was time to quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he enjoyed playing the role of enforcer,'' said Molly
Ivins, the populist Texas newspaper columnist and co-author of an
unflattering biography of George W.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Bush took no prisoners in his 1988 quest for the
White House, depicting Bob Dole as a tax-raiser and blaming Michael
Dukakis for crimes committed by furloughed Massachusetts convict
Willie Horton. Four years earlier, after a debate with Democratic
vice presidential nominee Geraldine Ferraro, he boasted that he
``kicked a little ass last night.''
</P>
<P>
   His son turned around the race for this year's Republican
nomination in the South Carolina primary by unleashing leaders of
the Religious Right who conducted a highly negative, personal
campaign against John McCain. The Arizona senator had beaten Bush
in the lead New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a tough competitor, by the way,'' Bush said. ``That's what
the primaries showed, that I could take a punch and come back.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one political difference between father and son. Vice
president Bush abandoned the Pacific Northwest late in 1988 and
again in the '92 campaign. He drew such raucous protests that at
one point aides nicknamed Portland ``the Beirut of America'' after
anarchists overturned trash cans and burned a U.S. flag outside a
hotel where he was speaking.
</P>
<P>
   But his son is targeting Washington and Oregon, pledging in
particular that he will resume the logging of ``a reasonable amount
of board feet'' out of national forests in the Northwest and that
he will not try to restore salmon runs by breaching four dams on
the lower Snake River.
</P>
<P>
   ``My point is, we can have both salmon runs and hydroelectric
energy by having salmon-friendly turbines,'' Bush said. He has
discussed Northwest issues to the point where, after answering
questions from donors at a recent fund-raiser here, he quipped:
``Quite a policy wonk, aren't I?''
</P>
<P>
   It's music to the ears of GOP Sen. Slade Gorton, who faces a
tough re-election race and wants to roll back Clinton
administration environmental policies. ``Between Jennifer (Dunn)
and me, we will have an excellent ear in the White House,'' Gorton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is a person very much at ease with people more
intellectual than he,'' Gorton added. ``He listens, he absorbs
ideas, and then he makes up his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   That view is not universally shared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extent to which (Bush) has never thought about many things
is awesome,'' Ivins joked. She said Bush depends heavily on an
``iron triangle'' of advisers _ campaign chief Karl Rove,
communications director Karen Hughes (who ghost-wrote Bush's
autobiography) and an old Midland, Texas, friend named Don Evans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is promising he would bring to the White House a targeted,
somewhat minimalist agenda, following a pattern he established
after entering the Texas governor's office in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will spend my capital on entitlement (Social Security and
Medicare) reform, tax cuts, education and restoring our military
strength,'' he said. ``American presidents can't be all things to
all people and get anything done. The American people understand
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the agenda is domestic, in contrast to his father, who
was most comfortable dealing with foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, in fairness to his father, he had no experience at
the state level. Governor Bush has had to deal with these issues,''
said Craig Berkman, a Portland venture capitalist and fund-raiser
in the presidential campaigns of both father and son.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush has caused the greatest stir with his plan to overhaul
and partially privatize Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   He would allow workers to invest a portion of their payroll
taxes in personal retirement accounts. They would get to choose
among a diversified set of stock and bond portfolios. After
retirement, investors would be required to convert some of their
accounts into securities that pay regular benefits, like Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promised to make deep cuts in America's nuclear weapons
arsenal and to remove some U.S. intercontinental ballistic missiles
from what he recently called ``hair-trigger'' alert status.
</P>
<P>
   But he would also spend billions to put in place a missile
defense system far more ambitious than the one the Clinton
administration is pondering. It would aim to protect not just the
United States, but also Europe, Israel and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is straightforward on education. He would give local school
districts far more latitude over how federal education dollars are
spent. But he would require tests to prove that ``we are seeing
results,'' particularly on reading and mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   Citing Texas as example, however, critics fear that Bush as
president would withhold funding from other important issues, such
as air and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   As governor, ``he has never made the environment a priority. ...
He thinks business and industry will do the right thing on the
environment in keeping with his laissez faire attitude on
government,'' said Ken Kramer, director of the Lone Star chapter of
the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Houston overtook Los Angeles as the nation's
smoggiest city. The nation's oil and petrochemical capital
registered 52 days when ground-level ozone, the main ingredient in
smog, exceeded the national health standard's maximum.
</P>
<P>
   Bush bristles at talk of pollution in his state's largest city.
``Houston, Texas, is a booming town,'' he said. ``It's an auto
town. What's not reported is that a Clinton appointee to EPA says
air quality in Texas has improved over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If things are so lousy, why did I get 70 percent of the vote''
in his 1998 re-election race? he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did sign legislation last year that will require utilities
``grandfathered'' out of the state's clean air act to install
state-of-the-art pollution control equipment by 2003. The bill was
stronger than proposed by Bush, who originally asked Exxon and
Marathon Oil executives to ``develop the concept of a voluntary
program to permit grandfathered facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, Pat Ford of Save Our Wild Salmon questions
Bush's understanding of the ``salmon-friendly turbines'' that will
supposedly solve the salmon crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an anecdotal recovery plan,'' Ford said. ``The turbines
will kill fewer fish. That's all. They will also cost almost as
much as removing the dams. You are talking on the order of $20
million per turbine, with more than 50 turbines.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office in Austin reflects its occupant. A pair of
glass-paneled wooden cabinets contain Bush's collection of 250
baseballs, autographed by ballplayers and other figures. Bush
bought a small share of the Texas Rangers in 1989 for $606,000 and
was designated by fellow owners as the public face of the
franchise. The Rangers prospered in the field, and the city of
Arlington built the team a $190 million stadium (of which the
Rangers paid about $50 million). In 1998 the governor sold his
share of the Rangers for $14.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Behind his desk, a framed picture shows toddler George W. Bush
with his parents and grandparents, Connecticut Sen. Prescott Bush
and Dorothy Walker Bush, at the Midland airport.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the office is an 1830s painting of Texas'
founder, Sam Houston, depicted in a toga and captioned, ``Sam
Houston as Marius Among the Ruins of Carthage.'' Houston was down
on his luck when artist Washington Cooper painted him. Bush tells
visitors that he keeps the painting as a reminder of what drink can
do to even an outstanding public figure.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has talked in general terms of his ``young and
irresponsible years,'' while declining to give the press any fodder
on the rumors of past drug use that have popped up since his first
gubernatorial campaign in 1994. His staff is extremely sensitive
about a biography, ``First Son,'' published late last year by Bill
Minutaglio, a writer with The Dallas Morning News. It depicts Bush
as a Yale student in the 1960s, a party boy oblivious to the social
ferment of the times.
</P>
<P>
   Bush quit drinking 14 years ago under the quiet, firm influence
of his wife, Laura. A former librarian, she calls him ``Bushy'' and
is known as a calming influence on a man nicknamed by friends
``Bombastic Bushkin'' after a Johnny Carson character.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appears to be, as Gorton put it after a visit to Austin,
``very much at ease with himself.'' Asked how he would keep from
getting an exalted view of himself in the White House, Bush
replied: ``The answer is based on the internal soul of the person
running.''
</P>
<P>
   The presumed GOP nominee is a reborn Christian, an advocate of
what he calls ``faith-based programs'' in which churches help ease
the impact of welfare cuts. The elder Bush is an active
Episcopalian; his son has followed Laura into the Methodist church.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is not an orator. He has inherited his father's habit of
mangling words. He once referred to the people of Greece as
``Grecians.'' In the interview, he talked about how a death penalty
case ``had full analyzation'' but had inspired ``emotionality.''
</P>
<P>
   But he can wax eloquent on faith, as in a recent speech at the
Simon Wiesenthal Center in Los Angeles. ``For all its flaws, I
believe our nation is chosen by God and commissioned by history to
be a model to the world of justice and inclusion and diversity
without division,'' Bush declared.
</P>
<P>
   This is, however, the same politician who opposed legislation to
ban the execution of mentally retarded defendants and vetoed a bill
to require appointment of legal counsel within 20 days for people
who cannot afford a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a Talk magazine interview, Bush mocked Karla Faye Tucker, the
first woman executed in Texas in more than a century, as she
unsuccessfully pleaded for clemency. He imitated her, whimpering,
``Please don't kill me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he opposed legislation setting down criteria in
considerations of clemency for death row inmates, Bush saw it as
entirely consistent with his philosophy, saying: ``Government's
role is not to try to judge heart. That's up to somebody higher, a
higher authority than government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
