<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7997 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-HNS &LR;      07-20 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-SCHOOLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CHARTER SCHOOLS FARE NO BETTER THAN TRADITIONAL ONES ON STATE
TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JULIAN GUTHRIE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Statewide test scores released this week show
charter schools in the San Francisco Bay area generally doing no
better than traditional public schools at improving student
performance.
</P>
<P>
   A comparison of second-grade reading, math, language and
spelling scores of the region's charter schools with second-grade
statewide averages shows charter schools faring slightly better in
reading and math and slightly worse in writing and spelling.
</P>
<P>
   Of 16 Bay-area charter schools that tested second-graders in
reading, scores at nine schools were higher and seven were lower
than the statewide reading average.
</P>
<P>
   Of 17 charter schools that reported second-grade math scores,
nine were higher and eight lower than the statewide math average.
In spelling, scores at 10 schools were lower and seven were higher.
In language, scores at nine schools were lower and eight higher.
</P>
<P>
   The results come at a time when charter schools are embraced as
a panacea for public education and are opening at the rate of 10
per month. With about 85,000 children in 263 schools, California
boasts the nation's largest charter school enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you talk about charter schools being the magic bullet,
what these scores tell us is that we're not seeing stark
differences between charters and traditional public schools,'' said
Luis Huerta, a research associate at Policy Analysis for California
Education and co-author of the forthcoming book ``Inside Charter
Schools.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You see half gains and half losses, with charter schools
scoring comparably to traditional schools,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The scores for 4.3 million students in nearly 8,000 schools were
released Monday by the California Department of Education. In its
third year, the multiple-choice Stanford 9 exam is given to
students in grades 2 through 11. In the exam, a score of 50 is the
national average.
</P>
<P>
   The scores for charter schools in Alameda, Contra Costa, Marin,
Napa, San Francisco, San Mateo, Solano and Sonoma counties show
general teaching strengths and weaknesses by academic subject. They
also reveal extreme inconsistencies from grade to grade and subject
to subject within schools.
</P>
<P>
   A few examples of Bay-area charter schools where grades vary
from subject to subject include:
</P>
<P>
   _ At Novato Unified Charter in Marin County, only 18 percent of
second-graders scored at or above the national average in reading.
In spelling, kids did even worse: 14 percent met or surpassed the
national average. In math and language, the same second-grade class
performed better. Sixty-eight percent scored at or above the
national average in math; 45 percent were at the national average
in language.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Cali Calmecac Charter in Windsor in Sonoma County, 27
percent of second-graders read at or above the national average,
compared with 66 percent in math, 45 percent in language and 14
percent in spelling.
</P>
<P>
   _ At Creative Arts Charter in San Francisco, 79 percent of
second-graders met or exceeded the national average in reading,
compared with 33 percent in math, 19 percent in language and 13
percent in spelling.
</P>
<P>
   _ At the Edison Charter Academy, also in San Francisco, 39
percent of second-graders read at or above the national average,
compared with 58 percent in math, 18 percent in language and 34
percent in spelling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inconsistencies are important to look at,'' Huerta said.
``Many charters try to break away from the norm. These are usually
organizational differences, but there are also curricular
differences. Some of those differences may explain the
inconsistencies in test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a contradiction here,'' Huerta said, ``in that charter
schools are given local freedom and innovation to create something
new. But, at the same time, they're bound by this state test, which
is very standardized and may not fit the mission or objectives of a
charter school.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are publicly funded, but free from many state
and local regulations. Proponents say such schools offer parents
more choices and give educators the freedom to innovate. These
innovations may be picked up by traditional public schools,
proponents say.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco school board member Dan Kelly has said charter
schools aren't the cure for what ails public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Academically, charter schools haven't been particularly
innovative or striking as a group,'' Kelly said. ``The biggest
difference is that charters have autonomy from the school district.
That may be good, it may be poor. They have great opportunity to
succeed _ or to fail, in a big way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
