<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7999 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      07-20 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE SILVER SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Now it can be told: Hugh Jackman used to walk around
the house with steel blades protruding from his knuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day in my living room, I'd just walk around with those
claws, to get used to them,'' Jackman said. ``I've got scars on one
leg, punctures straight through the cheek, on my forehead. I'm a
bit clumsy. I'm lucky I didn't tell them that when I auditioned.''
</P>
<P>
   The process by which one of the thousands of aspiring young
actors from all over the world first breaks out of the Hollywood
pack and then somehow rises to stardom is difficult to handicap.
Every year a dozen or so fresh names are offered up as the next hot
things and given the big push by the major studios and the top
publicity firms, and nine times out of 10, they fall short of the
golden ring. But every now and then, something clicks, and at the
moment something seems to be clicking for Hugh Jackman.
</P>
<P>
   Jackman, 32, is an affable and accomplished Australian actor
with a background in musical theater. His performance as Wolverine,
the central character in ``X-Men,'' has transformed him from
another face in the ensemble to a name above the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I thought when I read the script was, `Get me
to a gym,''' Jackman said. ``It's pretty physical. We worked a lot
on the movement style of Wolverine, and I studied some martial
arts. I watched a lot of Mike Tyson fights, especially his early
fights. There's something about his style, the animal rage, that
seemed right for Wolverine.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who are not ``X-Men''-literate, the story is set in
the near future, when the next stage in human evolution has begun.
Every now and then, mutants are born with weird, often
uncontrollable powers. Non-mutants hate and fear them and want to
destroy them or, worse, regulate them.
</P>
<P>
   Wolverine has the ability to heal himself almost instantly. In
addition, sometime in his past (he can't remember) someone operated
on him and implanted a steel skeleton that causes razor-sharp
blades to protrude from his hands whenever someone ticks him off.
</P>
<P>
   So he's a little tense. Tread carefully.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Jackman is in New York, beginning work on a new
film, ``Animal Husbandry,'' opposite Ashley Judd, another recent
example of a young star bursting through the ranks. It's a romantic
comedy. ``No hair, no claws,'' Jackman said.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he would take a little time this week, though, to go
to one of the theaters in Manhattan showing ``X-Men'' and watch it
with a paying audience. ``I want to hear them cheering,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AN EVOLVING CAREER
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Reitman has become almost the grand old man of comedy in
Hollywood. It seems as if it was only a couple of weeks ago that he
was hanging out with the Ghostbusters. And now, after a three-year
hiatus from directing, during which he got his new production
company, Montecito Films, off the ground, Reitman is going back
behind the camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evolution'' will be a grand-scale, special-effects comedy _
his old ``Ghostbusters'' stomping ground _ with a story that
contains echoes of ``X-Men,'' about a fresh burst in evolution that
leads to the sudden appearance of strange creatures. But no one is
watching Mike Tyson fights to prepare for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we want to design new creatures that make sense and
aren't just silly, like a head with a hand sticking out of it, but
something that makes some cognitive sense,'' Reitman said.
</P>
<P>
   He's just about to send the script to actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for any major movie stars or comedy stars,
just really funny people who will make the story work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And with luck, ``Evolution'' will be in theaters by mid- or late
2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people sometimes get carried away with special
effects,'' Reitman said. ``The key to this movie will be that, in
the end, it's a comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   NORMAL IN HOLLYWOOD
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Paradis set a bottle of water to one side and leaned
forward, her hands clasped between her thighs, as if she were
chilly: ``It's great to be here in Los Angeles because I can just
be normal here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Normal is an interesting concept for the serious and earnest
Paradis, a model turned pop singer turned actress who stars in
Patrice Leconte's ``Girl on the Bridge.'' Paradis, 28, was a
teen-ager when a chance encounter at a recording studio in France
resulted in her first record, ``Joe le Taxi,'' which became a huge
bubble-gum hit all over Europe in the late 1980s. In 1989, she won
a Cesar, the French equivalent of the Oscar, for her supporting
role in ``White Wedding,'' playing a troubled teen-ager who seduces
and destroys the teacher who tried to help her. And she has been a
regular face in television and magazine advertisements. Together,
they have brought a celebrity that does not always make her
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In France, I don't know, it's the look on people's faces,''
she said. ``Being looked at, being pointed at, being talked about
when you are only an inch away. Here I can feel like a human
being.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Paradis can do that here, in the United States, is
that until now her celebrity has not crossed the Atlantic, at least
with anything like the intensity it enjoys in Europe. That's fine
with her, she said. She needs a place to be normal.
</P>
<P>
   She was sitting around a chipped, weathered dining table in a
side room at the Chateau Marmont Hotel on the Sunset Strip. She was
in town to conclude some mixing work on her latest album, to be
released in Europe later this year, to promote ``Girl on the
Bridge,'' which has a limited U.S. premiere in New York and a few
other cities next July 28, and just to hang around.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is one of the three cities where Paradis and her
husband, the actor Johnny Depp, maintain residences. (Paris and New
York are the others.) They have a 14-month-old daughter, Lily-Rose
Melody, and she said they were expecting another baby in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In the film Paradis plays Adele, another young and troubled
woman. This one is stopped from hurling herself off a bridge by a
circus knife-thrower who recruits his assistants from the ranks of
the suicidal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not as pure and smart as Adele is,'' Paradis said. ``When
I read the part, there was not one word that I wanted to change.''
</P>
<P>
   What did stop her, at least for a moment, was that the film
opens with Adele delivering an eight-page monologue directly into
the camera. But in the end, she took a deep breath, focused and,
with the help of Leconte, with whom she also worked on the 1998
``Half a Chance,'' she nailed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I must be honest,'' Paradis said. ``I was so afraid.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
