<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOM-OF-BRIDE-BOOK-REV     07-20 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOM-OF-BRIDE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOTHER OF THE BRIDE': A MARTYR TO MATRIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: publication notes at end of review)  
 By BEN STEELMAN   
 The Morning Star, Wilmington, N.C.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thanks to Spencer Tracy and Steve Martin, the plight of the
father of the bride has been amply documented. But what about Mom?
</P>
<P>
   Joan Bennett and even Diane Keaton, for Pete's sake, seemed to
take it all so calmly, totally in control at all times.
</P>
<P>
   According to certified m.o.b. Ilene Beckerman, don't believe it
for a minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``To tell you the truth,'' she writes, ``childbirth was easier
than being the mother of the bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, put another way, ``My mother-of-the-bride story begins with
the conception of my daughter, which took about five seconds;
briefly covers my pregnancy, which took the usual nine months; and
ends with the planning of my daughter's wedding, which took a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckerman, a sometime resident of New Jersey, didn't begin
writing until she was past 60 but made up for lost time fast. In
``Love, Loss and What I Wore'' (Algonquin Books, 1995), she told
the entire story of her life based on her favorite clothes, from
her Brownie uniform to the Diane von Furstenberg wrap. In ``Mother
of the Bride,'' subtitled ``The Dream, the Reality, The Search for
a Perfect Dress,'' she writes epigrammatically, in a style that
falls somewhere between Erma Bombeck and Dorothy Parker.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do five girls _ one short, one tall, one buxom, one flat,
one who gave birth a month ago _ have in common?'' she asks. ``A
bridesmaid's dress they all hate.''
</P>
<P>
   She illustrates her work as well, in a style that falls
somewhere between Dilbert's Scott Adams and The New Yorker's Roz
Chast.
</P>
<P>
   Her observations are prickly yet pointed, as in the hunt for the
ideal m.o.b. dress: ``I finally found something. It showed a little
cleavage. I learned a long time ago, if you show a little cleavage,
nobody ever looks anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   She also quickly discovers the principle that Mothers of Brides
can do nothing right, except open their checkbooks and shut their
mouths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how to act with my daughter anymore. I had to
watch my words. I had to watch my tone of voice. Once she was
inside my body. Now I was getting under her skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, sibling rivalry rears its ugly head: `` `If I have to
spend one more minute talking about her wedding,' I heard her
sister say, `I'll tell the whole world she used to pick her nose
and eat it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And between everything else, such as the Great Shower Debate,
Mom can't help wondering what happened to adorable little girl she
once knew, ``how she stood on a kitchen chair and sang all the
words to every song in the third-grade play but was too shy to even
move her lips onstage.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a good dessert souffle, ``Mother of the Bride'' is light,
frothy, tart enough not to be too syrupy-sweet and so delicate,
it's a marvel it didn't fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   And it is absolutely on key. My wife, who's marrying off her own
daughter in December, swears that every word is true.
</P>
<P>
   Wedding season is almost over, but there's still time to buy
this little gem as a thank-you present for the unsung heroine of
every summer nuptial.
</P>
<P>
   After all, as Ilene Beckerman points out, nobody will ever love
you as much as your mother. Nobody. Not even your dog. And to a
95-year-old woman, her 70-year-old daughter will always be her
baby.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MOTHER OF THE BRIDE'
</P>
<P>
   By Illene Beckerman
</P>
<P>
   Chapel Hill: Algonquin Books
</P>
<P>
   $17.95
</P>
<P>
   (The Morning Star in Wilmington, N.C., is part of The New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
