<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0282 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; tth-z
u l BC-CLIMBING-RAINIER-SPI &LR;      07-20 1721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLIMBING-RAINIER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIMBING RAINIER TAKES GOOD TRAINING, GUIDES AND LUCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY E. NEVALA  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ I grew up in southern Michigan, where the highest
elevation within 40 miles of my home was the top floor of a
downtown parking garage. Mountain climbing never made my athletic
resume, and after relocating to Seattle I considered the Cascade
Range just a pretty backdrop for cycling and snowshoeing.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in March, when I paused before an American Lung
Association poster featuring a smiling woman gripping an ice ax
near the top of Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   The adventure of climbing one of the highest peaks in the United
States intrigued me. I talked to Rainier climbers, read books on
the topic, then nervously began training to take part in the
Washington Lung Association's annual fund-raiser, Climb for Clean
Air.
</P>
<P>
   My rookie jitters diminished when I discovered that our route
from Paradise, the mountain's most popular base-to-summit
trailhead, was not technical. Although the climb requires ropes,
crampons, ice axes and helmets above 10,000 feet, it does not
involve scaling rocks and cliffs.
</P>
<P>
   Most described the two-day, round-trip climb as a long, steady
march.
</P>
<P>
   ``Climbing Mount Rainier is a lot like climbing stairs,'' said
famed Rainier guide Lou Whittaker. His guide outfit, Rainier
Mountaineering Inc., begins the ascent at Paradise at 5,400 feet
and includes a lengthy evening rest stop at Camp Muir at 10,000
feet before a midnight attempt on the 14,411-foot summit.
</P>
<P>
   The early start for the top ensures a cold, firm climbing
surface, reducing the risk of rock- and icefall and allowing for a
timely descent. The group returns to Paradise the same day as the
summit attempt.
</P>
<P>
   To train I upped my aerobic activity. Weekdays I swam, cycled
and jogged, and on weekends I hiked Mount Si near North Bend. As
the climb date approached, before work each day I threw on a pack
stuffed with a water-filled milk carton and an eight-pound
``Encyclopedia of Mammals'' and trudged up and down Queen Anne
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Twice I drove to Paradise for practice hikes to Camp Muir. My
cousin's 21-pound baby boy even helped with workouts, riding in a
backpack koala-style to the top of Tiger Mountain outside Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   While guides direct climbers' every move on the mountain, this
risky sport requires safety training. A month before my climb, I
spent a Saturday with the RMI guides at Paradise to learn ice-ax
handling and rope-team etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   I wanted to avoid the label ``dope on a rope.''
</P>
<P>
   We practiced self-arrest, purposely hurtling our bodies down the
slope headfirst and upside down, then stopping falls with our axes
and kicking our plastic boot toes into the snow for bracing.
</P>
<P>
   The guides emphasized two tips for a successful climb: a type of
walking called the rest step, and pressure breathing.
</P>
<P>
   To learn the rest step, one guide suggested we ``walk like a
stork.'' The front foot quickly steps forward, while the straight
back leg pauses and holds the body weight, allowing skeletal
support. Repeated again and again and those restful pauses add up.
</P>
<P>
   Combining the rest step with pressure breathing _ normal
inhaling followed by hard, whoooshing exhaling that rids the lungs
of excess carbon dioxide _ has helped thousands of climbers to
mountain summits much higher than Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Another trick is to consume plenty of water and food. Eating at
altitude doesn't always appeal, since many climbers' stomachs start
to hula. So RMI guides emphasize favorite foods over healthier
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're certainly not going to gain weight on this climb,''
they said. ``Bring whatever you will put in your mouth and
swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   And so I carried phad thai noodles, pretzels, chocolate energy
bars, Fig Newtons and M&AMP;Ms tucked in 30 pounds of gear when I
departed Paradise on a sunny Thursday morning with 23 teammates and
six RMI guides.
</P>
<P>
   We switchbacked in shorts and T-shirts single file for the first
couple of miles. After skirting crumbly rocks at Pebble Creek, we
hiked straight up the Muir Snowfield, a giant white mat of treeless
landscape. After each hour of hiking, we stopped for a 15-minute
break to eat, drink, adjust clothing layers and apply sunblock.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived at Camp Muir at 10,000 feet in five hours, thrilled
by the sight of the modest A-frame ranger hut, boxy bunkhouse,
stone cookhouse and three outhouses. A dinner of spaghetti, red
sauce and corn revived us. After eating, RMI guide Brent Okita
detailed the terrain and weather conditions for the summit attempt,
then shooed us to bed at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Light sleepers found no mercy from snoring, stinky, restless
climbers as we lay in cozy bundles within the bunkhouse's plywood
shell. Most climbers were wide-eyed when Okita gave the wake-up
call at 12:20 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Good-natured chaos followed in the college-dorm-size room as 24
climbers scrambled out of sleeping bags, layered their clothing,
cinched plastic boots and adjusted harnesses and helmets. I gulped
hot peach oatmeal before retrieving my pack outside.
</P>
<P>
   My hands shook as I reloaded snacks, fleece shirts and a
Gore-Tex jacket. It was nerves, not cold. The climbing conditions
were ideal, with the temperature around 30 degrees and only a
gentle swirl of wind.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Okita announced the climbing teams, guide-led
groups of five and six people mixed and matched according to
strength and ability. Before roping to my team, I swapped my
climbing poles for an ice ax and laced on crampons _ metal spikes
attached to boots to give traction on the glaciers.
</P>
<P>
   Guides double-checked our harnesses and headlamps and we were
the first RMI team to walk away from Camp Muir at 1:54 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   A glittering quilt of stars draped the sky and my stress eased
as I breathed the cool air. I relaxed my white-knuckled hold on my
section of rope _ our guide, my five teammates and I were each
separated by 30 feet. The trail ahead resembled a miniature
highway, the path brightened by headlamps from independent climbers
who started even earlier.
</P>
<P>
   After 30 minutes of gentle hills over ice-crusted snow, we hit
Cathedral Gap, a nasty, steep outcropping of loose dirt and
fist-size volcanic rock. We spent 40 minutes picking through when,
at 11,000 feet, I snagged my crampon. I stumbled, my right knee and
shin crunching on sharp rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get up, we have to go,'' called Okita from his lead position.
With 200 Rainier summits notched on his climbing belt, he knew this
route. And I knew he wasn't kidding. Rockfall was a danger here.
</P>
<P>
   We hustled another 200 feet to our first rest stop. I palmed my
knee and felt the swell beneath my climbing pants. With a triathlon
and several bicycle trips scheduled _ in addition to a 9,000-foot
descent _ I needed a healthy leg.
</P>
<P>
   Shocked and disappointed, I knew my summit would have to come
another day.
</P>
<P>
   As a pink and orange sunrise lit craggy Little Tahoma, I turned
back with a guide and another climber suffering from altitude
sickness. My teammates walked on to complete what many later called
the most difficult physical challenge of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   For the next five hours they rested only three more times as
they steadily gained another 3,000 feet in elevation. They crossed
a 100-foot deep crevasse via a horizontal ladder and battled colder
winds, thinner air and steeper slopes.
</P>
<P>
   One rope team dodged a boulder rolling down the mountainside.
</P>
<P>
   Altitude sickness stopped two more climbers. Others suffered
through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so pumped to get there. Nothing was going to turn me
around,'' said Carter Woollen, a Seattle architect. ``The
adrenaline was just going.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue Web writer Carry Porter called the last 300 yards to
the snow-swept summit the most difficult.
</P>
<P>
   At the top many climbers hugged and slapped hands. Some cried.
While many dropped their packs and bodies on the mountain's crater
rim, a dozen walked another quarter-mile across the flat crater
floor to the true summit, Columbia Crest, a small snowy knoll at
14,411 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was calm, the air was crystal clear and we had a fantastic
sunrise,'' Porter said. ``You could see mountains in Oregon.''
</P>
<P>
   One hour and dozens of snapshots later, the group reversed
course. At noon, three hours after departing the summit, they
arrived at Camp Muir rubber-legged but smiling, snacking on Oreos
and honeydew melon before a two-hour descent to hot showers and a
celebration dinner at the Paradise Inn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the hardest thing I've ever done. My calves and quads
are just shredded,'' said Laura Downey, who works in a retail
garden center at Pike Place Market. ``I've run two marathons, done
the STP (Seattle to Portland bicycle ride), and multiple
half-marathons. They are easy money, in comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   But was it worth it?
</P>
<P>
   Concluded Downey: ``Absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   CLIMBING MOUNT RAINIER
</P>
<P>
   Reaching Rainier's 14,411-foot summit requires a vertical
elevation gain of more than 9,000 feet over a distance of eight or
more miles. While most routes are not technical, climbers must be
in excellent physical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Many climbers go with a guide service offering one-day climbing
instruction, two-day summit climbs, five-day climbing seminars and
private climbs. Summer is the most popular time to climb, although
trips go year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Gearheads rejoice: There is plenty of required equipment,
including ice axes, crampons, ski poles, helmets, down jackets,
sleeping bags and boots. Most equipment can be rented locally.
</P>
<P>
   GUIDE SERVICES
</P>
<P>
   Alpine Ascents International: 206-378-1927,
www.alpineascents.com
</P>
<P>
   American Alpine Institute: 360-671-1505, www.aai.cc
</P>
<P>
   Cascade Alpine Guides and Adventures: 206-706-1587,
www.cascadealpine.com
</P>
<P>
   Mount Rainier Alpine Guides: 360-825-3773
</P>
<P>
   Rainier Mountaineering Inc.: 360-569-2227 (summer) or
253-627-2227 (winter) , www.rmiguides.com
</P>
<P>
   RMI and the American Lung Association Climb for Clean Air:
206-441-5100, www.alaw.org/climb.html
</P>
<P>
   INDEPENDENT CLIMBING TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   Summit attempts on your own require excellent mountaineering
skills and a permit available at park ranger stations. Contact
Mount Rainier National Park: 360-569-2211 or
www.nps.gov/mora/climb/climb.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
