<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8010 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BOOK-SHAKESPEARE-$ADV     07-20 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SHAKESPEARE-$ADV23-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLINGS AND ARROWS OF FORTUNE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By FRED ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Power Plays: Shakespeare's Lessons in Leadership and
Management'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, 2000), John O. Whitney and Tina
Packer honor their subject with a pleasurable and instructive book.
They give us an engaging testament on practicality and morality in
business, richly illuminated by instances from Shakespeare, all
expertly dissected. A reader whose memories of Shakespeare's magic
are lost in cobwebs can expect a treat.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney, lover of Shakespeare and senior professor at the
Columbia Business School, provides the business wisdom. An expert
on saving troubled companies, he writes with the assurance of a
half-century in business. The book has lots of cases (Did James
Robinson get the heave-ho at American Express because, like Richard
II, he neglected his realm?), but the professor is most cogent in
holding his own experiences up to Shakespeare's mirror.
</P>
<P>
   A wise old bird, he instructs as often from mistakes as from
accomplishments. At times a chief executive, at other times No. 2,
he has absorbed the ways and means and machinations of command.
</P>
<P>
   The reader hears a lot about Pathmark Supermarkets, where
Whitney, installed as chief operating officer, led a notably
successful turnaround three decades ago. As the applause rolled in,
he was sure he had a lock on the chief executive's chair. In fact,
people had knives out for him, an outsider and an unwelcome savior.
``I was foolish _ and blind, to boot,'' he writes on reflection. It
was an outcome worthy of ``Henry IV.''
</P>
<P>
   At his elbow as he writes is Packer, once of the Royal
Shakespeare Company, who came to this country to present
Shakespeare as it should be presented. She is founder and chief
executive of Shakespeare &AMP; Company, a thriving theater in Lenox,
Mass. She and the professor are a congenial pair. He has exulted in
Shakespeare all his adult life; her creation has become a sizable
business.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney writes most of the book. Packer periodically steps on
stage to add a creative dramatist's understanding of what it is to
act or how actors rise above self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   She also offers some fresh thinking on Shakespeare's women and
power. She admires the Rosalind of ``As You Like It,''
free-spirited and independent, much preferring her over the
tormented Ophelia of ``Hamlet''; but Packer is taken with the
cunning Cleopatra. In an epilogue, Packer finds a new set of
corporate values in Shakespeare's late plays, based on redemption
and collaboration, not bloodshed and deceit.
</P>
<P>
   But the magnetic voice here is Shakespeare's. He ``plumbed more
deeply into the problems of leadership than anyone before him and
most who came after.'' On leadership and power, Whitney finds gold
in the kingship plays and the great tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamlet'' provides a contrasting backdrop for an admiring
sketch of Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com, whose focus, decisiveness and
fleetness of foot compare so starkly with the breast-beating
vacillation of the Prince of Denmark. (``Hamlet cannot lead,
manage, or follow.'')
</P>
<P>
   The authors take three topics in order _ power, persuasion,
values _ and a good book gets even better when it gets to values.
Anyone who mines Shakespeare for insights on power can't miss, and
this discussion doesn't. The section on persuasion offers, as the
model inspirational speech, Henry V's immortal call to arms on the
eve of Agincourt, with the English outnumbered five to one. It
reminds us how masterfully the young king played the theme of honor
until the woefully discouraging odds became a rallying point.
</P>
<P>
   We few, we happy few, we band of brothers.
</P>
<P>
   For he today that sheds his blood with me
</P>
<P>
   Shall be my brother. . . .
</P>
<P>
   To turn a hostile crowd, what example could trump Mark Antony's
oration at Caesar's funeral?
</P>
<P>
   . . . the noble Brutus
</P>
<P>
   Hath told you Caesar was ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   If it were so, it was a grievous fault,
</P>
<P>
   And grievously hath Caesar answer'd it.
</P>
<P>
   Polonius, the foolish old man in ``Hamlet,'' was given to
fatuous declarations:
</P>
<P>
   To thine ownself be true,
</P>
<P>
   And it must follow as the night the day
</P>
<P>
   Thou canst not be false to any man.
</P>
<P>
   The aphorism is ``patently absurd,'' Whitney declares, given
that interests are at least as likely to clash as coincide, and he
sets off on an exploration of how Man Alone squares with Man in
Society. His musings take him to Frank Sinatra (``I did it my
way'') as well as Ralph Waldo Emerson. Eventually he decides that
the best of religion and law, checked by the free market, provides
the most hopeful reconciliation. Happily, he notes that Shakespeare
_ a wealthy, worldly man as well as playwright _ was at home in a
market-driven society.
</P>
<P>
   Whitney has a soft spot for Sir John Falstaff, the quick-witted,
carousing reprobate who instructed Prince Hal in the true nature of
his domain. But when Hal became King Henry V, he stunned Jack
Falstaff by banishing him summarily. Was his fate just?
</P>
<P>
   Falstaff becomes the opportunity to talk about business'
distaste for the inspired oddball. The professor has his share of
maverick blood; in his turnaround days, he once made a point by
publicly torching the company-policy manual. It tickled him to play
host to a visiting chief executive in the company cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   So he accepts Falstaff's fall from favor, but most reluctantly:
``I would have fired him for his actions, not his thoughts.''
Falstaff takes bribes, flops in battle, commits highway robbery.
``Banish the Jack Falstaff of `Henry IV,' yes, but banish him with
love, care and caution.''
</P>
<P>
   The professor sets tough moral standards. ``Deceit is at the
center of all of Shakespeare's tragedies,'' he writes, adding that
it is not unknown in business. Iago deceives Othello. Richard III
deceives almost everyone. Cassius seduces Brutus into the plot to
kill Caesar.
</P>
<P>
   So is it ethical in business, Whitney asks, when one has decided
to leave a company and start one's own, to furtively recruit
colleagues to come along? Deceit always harms, he answers, if only
the deceit of self. ``Is deception acceptable if it harms no one?
By now, we realize that this is an oxymoron,'' he says. But the
world cannot live without deception, he concedes: ``Shakespeare,
the great philosopher, and life itself make us confront it. When is
it justified? When is it not?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
