<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8013 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-EARNS-BOS &LR;      07-20 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON SLIDE IN SALES CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. posted income from continuing operations of $95
million for the three months ended July 2, a 68 percent decline
from a year earlier, as the company continued to suffer from
slowing sales of missiles and delays in aircraft deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   The results were in line with analysts' expectations, however,
and a rising order backlog suggests the Lexington, Mass. company's
financial slide may have bottomed out.
</P>
<P>
   Including businesses it has since divested, Raytheon reported
net income of $49 million, down from $290 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for the quarter fell 10 percent to $4.13 billion, from
$4.57 billion a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But the company didn't revise its outlook downward any further
and said its backlog stood at a record $25.6 billion, a relatively
successful report given past troubles at the country's
third-largest defense contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in a while things haven't been the
same, or worse (than expected),'' said an SG Cowen analyst, Cai von
Rumohr. ``This was something of a turn.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters and analysts, Raytheon chief
executive Daniel Burnham said company leaders were ``not prepared
to say all our issues are behind us, but we feel we've taken
another step'' toward recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial had expected
income from continuing operations of 27 cents a share, a penny less
than Raytheon reported.
</P>
<P>
   The company's widely traded Class B shares rose $2.50 to close
at $23.4375 in New York Stock Exchange trading. The financial
results were announced yesteday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Shares reached a high of $74.9375 last July, then fell sharply
after Burnham disclosed slowing overseas missile sales and
difficulty integrating various defense businesses that Raytheon
began buying in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The problems prompted Burnham to shuffle managers, lay off more
employees, and sell an engineering unit he had hoped to salvage.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of that Cambridge, Mass. division, Raytheon Engineers &AMP;
Constructors, to Morrison Knudsen Corp. of Boise, Idaho, was
completed last month, resulting in a $46 million loss for the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say Raytheon is also considering the sale of its
civil-aircraft division. That unit, in Wichita, Kan., saw operating
income decline 49 percent to $35 million, despite higher sales,
because of price competition and rising computer-system costs.
</P>
<P>
   Operating income also declined, compared to a year earlier, at
Raytheon's missile-making Electronic Systems unit, its command,
control, communications and information-systems unit, and its
commercial electroncis business.
</P>
<P>
   Divestitures could help Raytheon pay down debt from its
acquisition campaign. Debt stood at $10.5 billion on July 2, up
from $9.9 billion a year earlier. Net debt, or debt minus cash, was
$10.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's chief financial officer, Frank Caine, said the
company will pay down net debt to at least $9.2 billion by
December.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon's order backlog of $25.6 billion was 20 percent more
than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also hopes to benefit from increased spending on
missile-defense programs, both for the Navy and for the Pentagon's
National Missile Defense effort. A test of the latter flopped
earlier this month when a rocket failed to deliver a
Raytheon-produced antimissile device to the target.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Burnham noted many in Congress still support the
projects. ``The general political mood is in strong support of
missile defense, and therefore we're bullish, whether (defenses
are) sea-based or land-based,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such programs would produce about $700 million in revenue for
the company this year and more than $3.5 billion in revenue through
2005, Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Willian Fiala, analyst for Edward Jones, said the results could
be the start of a rebound for Raytheon. ``It appears the worst is
over, but they still have a long way to get back on track,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is the backlog, but it will take time for them
to get through a lot of their operating issues,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
