<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMSTRONG EASES BACK WITH 5-MINUTE LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREIBURG, Germany _ An hour before Thursday's stage in the Tour
de France, Lance Armstrong was where he usually is prerace _
sequestered in the RV near the US Postal Service team's designated
area.
</P>
<P>
   So it's doubtful Armstrong saw much of Lake Leman in Lausanne,
Switzerland, Thursday's starting point, until he rolled out of
town.
</P>
<P>
   And it's just as doubtful Armstrong's fans saw much of him.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several Americans hoping to catch a glimpse of
Armstrong merely saw a flash of yellow as the race leader left the
van to sign in for the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream is to get his autograph,'' said Caryn Dahm, who was
leaning over a metal barricade with Christy Tanis. They looked more
like they were outside the studio of the ``Today'' show than at a
bike race as they held up a sign that read ``Iowa Loves Lance.''
Both live near Lausanne, where their husbands work, but Dahm is
from New Hampston, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Next to them was John Green, from Philadelphia, clad in a gray
T-shirt with an American flag on it, and holding a Wheaties cereal
box featuring Armstrong's picture.
</P>
<P>
   They wouldn't get an autograph, but his fans at least would get
the satisfaction of seeing Armstrong retain the yellow jersey at
the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The 148-mile leg _ the third longest in the Tour _ headed north
from Lausanne over rolling hills to Germany. The course was lined
with an estimated 1.5 million people, many wearing pink Deutsche
Telekom hats. They were not only honoring the German-based team,
but native Jan Ullrich, who won the Tour in 1997 and currently is
in second place.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the fifth visit to Germany in the 87-year history of
the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Five riders broke from the pack early but none were contenders
in the overall standings, so the rest didn't bother to chase them.
With 40 miles to go, the gap was more than 16 minutes, and the pack
could only roll their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Italy's Salvatore Commesso and Alexandre Vinokourov of
Kazakhstan left the leaders with less than 20 miles to go and
played a cat-and-mouse game as they rode into town. Neither wanted
to give the other control, and both slammed on their brakes at the
final turn. Commesso edged Vinokourov in the final sprint,
finishing in 6 hours 8 minutes 15 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Three others finished just more than a minute later, but most of
the pack, including Armstrong, cruised in 15 minutes after the
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go easy or go hard, and it's never easy,'' Armstrong said.
And easy or not, Armstrong said pedaling for almost 150 miles is
not his idea of a good race, for either riders or spectators.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's good for the race or the drama and the
aggression of the race to have stages of 250 kilometers,'' he said.
``Yes, there was a breakaway today, but with a race that's 250
kilometers in one direction with a headwind the whole way, you're
just never going to see a dramatic race in those conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   With three days of racing left, Armstrong's lead over Ullrich is
more than five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong took umbridge when asked what he thinks his chances
are in Friday's time trial, his forte.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I thought I won all three time trials last year,'' he
snapped. ``I'm starting the race planning on winning.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
