<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-GILLETTE-EARNS-BOS &LR;      07-20 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GILLETTE-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLETTE TO KEEP BRAUN PRODUCT LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Saying it plans to hang on to all of its Braun product
lines, Gillette Co. reported Thursday strong second-quarter sales
for blades, razors, and its Braun electric shavers and small
household appliances.
</P>
<P>
   But Gillette also reported declining or flat sales for its
Duracell batteries and its Oral-B oral-care products.
</P>
<P>
   Total quarterly sales rose 2 percent to $2.25 billion. Net
income from continuing operations rose 2 percent to $296 million,
or 28 cents a share, matching Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Gillette warned that sales growth in the quarter might
be affected by the euro's decline. Foreign curreny issues are one
reason why Gillette's momentum has slowed recently.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the adverse effects of exchange and the divestiture of
its White Rain hair-care line, second-quarter sales were up 8
percent, Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with these results,'' said vice president Eric
A. Kraus, who noted that, on an earnings-per-share basis, net
income from continuing operations rose 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As for a possible sale of its ailing stationery business to
Newell Rubbermaid Inc., Gillette would only say Thursday that
negotiations, first announced last month, are continuing.
</P>
<P>
   While second-quarter razor sales and profits rose 8 percent and
7 percent respectively, Duracell sales fell 3 percent, and profits
declined 19 percent. It was the second straight quarter that
Duracell has reported a sales decline.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gillette officials, Duracell's performance has been
``clouded'' by short-term issues such as ``aggressive competitive
activity.'' Duracell's long-term outlook remains bright, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Gillette said it would consider selling its
stationery lines and the household-appliance portion of its Braun
product line so it could focus on its core businesses.
</P>
<P>
   After conducting a strategic review of its Braun business,
Gillette said Thursday it will keep the product line intact.
</P>
<P>
   Braun sales rose 11 percent in the second quarter, and its
profits more than doubled, Gillette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to make progress, reflecting the success of our
new products and the improving economic conditions in developing
markets,'' said Gillette chairman and chief executive Michael C.
Hawley. ``We look for further progress in the second half of 2000,
based on strong fundamentals in our core categories.''
</P>
<P>
   One investor expressed displeasure with Gillette's decision to
keep the Braun division intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braun has been one disappointment after another,'' Northstar
Group president Henry Asher told Bloomberg News. ``I can't
understand why they wouldn't sell it, unless they didn't get an
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillette issued results before the New York markets closed. On
the New York Stock Exchange, shares fell $1 to $32.3125.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
