<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, July 21. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-SURVEY (Washington) _ Despite the overwhelming
confidence displayed by Gov. George W. Bush's campaign, the
presidential election stands as a very close contest. An analysis
of polls state by state, along with interviews with Republican and
Democratic strategists in the campaigns and around the country. By
Adam Clymer and Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ After a five-year climb, the number of
legal claims filed against New York City that accuse police
officers of using excessive force or other misconduct has dropped
sharply, according to statistics kept by the city comptroller's
office. By Kevin Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ On the events Wednesday night
that saved the peace talks at Camp David, plus Thursday's
developments. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRIDE (Houston) _ For months, Vice President Al Gore and
other national Democrats have depicted George W. Bush's Texas as a
problem-plagued state. Pollution? Gore says Texas is the most
polluted state in America. Poverty? Gore says that too many of
Texas' people are poor and that the state does too little for them.
Not surprisingly, Texans, a prideful lot willing to overlook a few
bad statistics, have taken offense. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEUTRINOS (Undated) _ What many physicists believe to be the
last and most elusive member of nature's most ghostly family of
particles, neutrinos, has been detected at the Fermi National
Accelerator Laboratory near Chicago. By James Glanz.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-INDICTMENTS (Undated) _ A federal grand jury Thursday
indicted two former Salt Lake City Olympics bid officials on
charges of conspiracy and interstate travel in aid of racketeering
for their alleged roles in paying $1 million to help win the 2002
Winter Games. By Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-TESTING (Undated) _ As genetic testing becomes available
for a growing array of health conditions, those who choose to learn
their own genetic risks, and the health professionals who treat
them, are facing increasingly difficult decisions about how _ and
if _ to share the results with family members who carry some of the
genes. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
</TEXT>
