<HEADLINE>
FORMER IRISH LEADER HAUGHEY TO TESTIFY IN CORRUPTION SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN _ James Joyce once observed that it would be impossible
to walk across Dublin without passing a pub. Were Joyce alive
today, he might suggest it is impossible to walk across Dublin
without passing a crooked politician.
</P>
<P>
   These are normally the dog days of summer in Ireland, when
Dubliners step outside the doors of their ornate pubs, drinks in
hand, to enjoy conversation and the light that lingers well past 10
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the summer of scandal in Ireland, and Friday the
nation's former prime minister, Charles J. Haughey, is scheduled to
take the witness stand in one of the myriad tribunals probing
corruption throughout Ireland's political, judicial, and business
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin O'Connor couldn't have dreamed up Charlie Haughey. In
O'Connor's epic novel, ``The Last Hurrah,'' the protagonist Frank
Skeffington, a thinly-veiled James Michael Curley, Boston's
legendary and corrupt mayor, was portrayed as a duplicitous,
vainglorious, class-baiting thief.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to using his position to enrich himself, even
fictional rogues like Frank Skeffington pale in comparison to
Charlie Haughey.
</P>
<P>
   According to prior testimony, Haughey solicited more than $12
million in bribes while he was prime minister, mostly from property
developers. Calculating how much money Haughey got from his
government salary and how much he spent on his lavish lifestyle,
prosecutors say privately Haughey took at least three times that
amount from just about anyone who wanted to do business in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, during an investigation into influence-peddling
that spawned the tribunal that Haughey will appear before, Haughey
stunned the nation when he admitted he had received a $2 million
donation from a supermarket magnate in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey insisted he did nothing wrong, did no favors for the
money, and blamed any transgressions on his former financial
manager and close friend, Des Traynor, who is now, conveniently for
Haughey, dead.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying the arrogance that some find endearing and others
consider outrageous, Haughey denied the millions he took from
businessmen looking for influence funded his lavish lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have a lavish lifestyle,'' he told the tribunal
counsel, Denis McCullough. ``My work was my lifestyle and when I
was in office I worked every day, all day. There was no room for
any sort of an extravagant lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Haughey, who served as prime minister for three terms during the
1980s and 1990s, operated like a dictator of a banana republic,
sipping rare wines while much of his country wallowed in poverty
and hundreds of thousands of young people were forced to emigrate
to find work. He shamelessly shook down businessmen then spent the
ill-gotten gains on fine art, rich food, and assorted luxuries.
</P>
<P>
   He used $50,000 in bribes on tailored Charvet shirts from Paris.
He bought an island off the Irish coast so he could vacation in
privacy. He lined the walls of his 200-year-old, $30-million home
on a 300-acre estate north of Dublin with millions of dollars of
art.
</P>
<P>
   Lording over the most socially conservative country in Europe,
he carried on a torrid affair with a gossip columnist who regaled
the nation with tales about how ``Sweetie,'' as she called Haughey,
would lavish her with good meals and better sex.
</P>
<P>
   Haughey's venality was breathtaking. When his longtime friend
and deputy prime minister Brian Lenihan contracted an ultimately
fatal illness that required treatment in the United States, Haughey
hit up businessmen for more than $300,000 to offset the medical
bills, then allegedly pocketed most of the cash.
</P>
<P>
   While Haughey was the undisputed king of Irish sleaze, he was
not alone. Influence-peddling was rampant, according to testimony
presented to various tribunals. Even the current prime minister,
Bertie Ahern, widely hailed by President Clinton for his
stewardship of the peace process in Northern Ireland, has been
implicated.
</P>
<P>
   In April a businessman said he gave Ahern $75,000 in a hotel
parking lot in 1989. Ahern publicly denied it, but has admitted
signing blank checks for Haughey when Ahern was in charge of his
Fianna Fail's party finances.
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to condemn Haughey, Ahern has sought to distance
himself from his old mentor. Many political commentators in Dublin
say it is only a matter of time before Ahern's coalition government
collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Irish people are alternately amused and appalled by the
revelations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything and everyone was for sale. It's almost more
pathetic than scandalous,'' says Frank McDonald, author of the
recently published book, ``The Construction of Dublin.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said most Irish politicians do not take corruption
seriously, nor, he says, do most Irish people, though that could be
changing. A recent poll by the Sunday Tribune newspaper found that
for the first time ever, a majority of Irish people said that
corruption is the biggest issue facing the nation. Two-thirds of
those polled said they do not believe Ahern is cooperating fully
with the tribunals.
</P>
<P>
   Critics like McDonald say the politicians are hoping that the
sheer length and complexity of the tribunals will bore the public
into apathy rather than rouse their anger to demand systemic
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never in the 78-year history of the state has anyone been
imprisoned for political corruption. That almost beggars belief,''
said McDonald. ``Irish people have long been in denial about
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is impossible to ignore any longer, so ubiquitous are the
tribunals investigating influence-peddling in political, legal, and
business circles.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Manning, who besides being an Irish senator is a
professor of political science at University College Dublin, said
Ireland's prosperity has indirectly exposed its underbelly. Only
the United States produces more software than Ireland. And while
the growing popularity of computers and the Internet has turned
Ireland from one of Europe's poorest countries to one of its
richest in fewer than 10 years, it has also allowed prosecutors to
document influence-peddling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electronic money trail changed everything,'' said Manning.
``The ability to use electronic bank statements, to trace phone
calls, this gave the investigators the ability to catch people in
lies. Only recently have Irish people realized how deep the
corruption goes. It had been drip, drip, drip. Now people are
saying we've got to get rid of this lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The question today is not whether Haughey was corrupt, but
whether he should go to jail. Last month, a judge postponed
Haughey's trial on charges of lying to a previous tribunal, arguing
that deputy prime minister Mary Harney's suggestion to jail Haughey
made it impossible for him to get a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
   Irish people are divided on whether the 75-year-old Haughey, who
is in failing health, should go to prison. Manning isn't sure.
McDonald said until crooked politicians are put in jail, Ireland
will not begin to control corruption.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities between Haughey and Boston's rogue mayor, James
Michael Curley, are striking. The Irish newspapers are calling
Haughey's appearance Friday his ``Last Hurrah.'' After federal
prosecutors finished with him, Curley died broke and broken.
Prosecutors would like to do the same to Haughey.
</P>
<P>
   Both politicians were helped at the ballot box rather than hurt
by their roguish behavior. Both had an extraordinary sense of
entitlement, and made their names by helping the poor and elderly.
Haughey's defenders cite policies that helped the disadvantaged as
a mitigating factor when trying to put his corruption in context.
</P>
<P>
   When he takes the stand at Dublin Castle, Haughey will face a
stark choice. He can either name those who forked over a fortune to
him or face the prospect of being forced to pay for the cost of the
tribunal. Prosecutors say they have spent about $10 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he is forced to pay, it is doubtful that Haughey
will end up the pauper that Curley was after his last hurrah.
Haughey's personal fortune is estimated at about $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   Few people here, meanwhile, expect Haughey to cough up names.
Nothing and no one is more reviled in Ireland than an informer.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Haughey, his friends say, may have been a thief, but
he's no informer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
