u i BC-JERUSALEM-CLERGY-BOS &LR;      07-20 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERUSALEM-CLERGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN CLERGY DECRY LACK OF PRESENCE AT CAMP DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The heads of Jerusalem's three largest Christian
denominations expressed concern in a letter published Thursday that
their interests were not being represented at the Camp David talks,
and requested that representatives of the churches be permitted to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trust you will not forget or overlook our agelong presence
here,'' stated the letter, which was signed by Greek Orthodox
Patriarch Diodoros I, Latin Catholic Patriarch Michel Sabbah, and
Armenian Orthodox Patriarch Torkom II.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rich tapestry of this land is made even richer and more
precious with this continuous Christian life, witness, and presence
alongside the two other Abrahamic traditions of Judaism and
Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was addressed to Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, and President Clinton, and
excerpts were published in the respected Israeli newspaper Haaretz.
</P>
<P>
   One of the proposals that has reportedly been considered at Camp
David is a division of the Old City, with the Palestinian Authority
taking administrative control of the Muslim and Christian quarters
and Israel maintaining control of the Jewish and Armenian quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Christian community _ who represent approximately
140,000 Christians in Israel, the Palestinian-controlled West Bank,
and Jerusalem _ strongly oppose separating the Armenian and
Christian quarters, saying that they are ``inseparable and firmly
united by the same faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Hassassian, the Palestinian Authority's high commissioner
for church affairs and an adviser to the Palestinian negotiating
team, said, ``We are conveying a message that they cannot rule out
the Christians.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem is holy to the three monotheistic faiths, Judaism,
Christianity, and Islam. The Western Wall is the holiest site in
Judaism, the Dome of the Rock and Al-Aksa mosque complex is
generally considered the third holiest shrine in Islam after Mecca
and Medina, and the Holy Sepulchre is one of the most sacred sites
in Christendom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of religion in the negotiations is not an
imperative one, and should not be a divisive one,'' Hassassian
said. ``But the Israelis have made some attempt to downplay the
religious dimension of the other two faiths. That is wrong, and a
reminder is needed that this is a city sacred not only to Jews and
Muslims, but to Christians as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hassassian said he did not expect the request for
representatives of the churches to attend Camp David to be
accepted. But he added that he felt it was important for the church
leaders to state their concerns during the negotiations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1855EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8033 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT &LR;      07-20 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McENROE WON'T BE PLAYING DOUBLES FOR U.S.  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTANDER, Spain _ It wasn't quite mutiny, as much it was an
example of U.S. democracy. Collectively, delicately, John McEnroe's
players let it be known that they preferred him on the sideline,
where a Davis Cup captain belongs.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe took that attitudinal proclamation from a team meeting
Wednesday night and Thursday officially junked his tentative plan
to play doubles Saturday, as a 41-year-old antique whose last Davis
Cup competition was in 1992. Minutes before Thursday afternoon's
draw, he removed himself from the four-man U.S. roster that will
begin play Friday as a heavy underdog to Spain in the Cup
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   An unsightly blister in the middle of his left hand and some
soreness in his left arm from three days of practice hadn't
convinced McEnroe to lay down his racquet. The tenor of the team
meeting, however, made it clear to him that his players,
undecorated as they might be, thought it was unfair for McEnroe to
nominate himself, given the clay court surface that was likely to
exploit his fitness and age.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that John is not head and shoulders above any of
us in his caliber as a doubles player right now,'' said Todd
Martin, the senior U.S. player and de facto diplomat.``His
knowledge of the game is better, and to have him on the sidelines,
telling us what we're doing right and wrong, I think will help the
doubles team quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, designated as the No. 1 singles player, will play Albert
Costa in Friday's first singles match, before Jan-Michael Gambill
meets Alex Corretja. It was after Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi
withdrew their commitment to play the semifinal that McEnroe named
himself to the team. Thursday, he said, it was, in large part, a
strategic maneuver in the event Agassi changed his mind, which he
had heard was a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Yet since he assumed the captain's job last summer, the idea of
playing doubles had been bouncing softly around McEnroe's head like
one of his legendary touch volleys. When he didn't name an active
doubles player to this team last week, he seemed to be setting the
stage for himself, though he admitted he was not playing well on
the practice court.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know me _ I wanted to play, but these guys talked me out
of it,'' McEnroe said. ``They wanted a chance at glory, so now they
have to step up and show them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They'' _ Chris Woodruff and Vince Spadea _ are ranked No. 188
and 864, respectively, in doubles. The Spaniards don't have
accomplished doubles players either, and their team of Corretja and
Juan Balcells is in itself little more than a marriage of
necessity. Doubles, McEnroe said, is the one match here this
weekend that he has been counting on winning, no matter who played.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, then, was less about results and form than it was
about whose team this was, in the absence of the U.S. stars.
Players such as Woodruff and Spadea understand they are not and
never will be what McEnroe was, but they argued that they are
active professionals, in the prime of their careers and they,
unlike Sampras and Agassi, made the effort to return to Europe
after the clay and grass-court seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, everybody in the world knows that he's the best
doubles player of all time,'' Gambill said of McEnroe. ``That goes
without saying. But it's not like because he's not out there we
can't win. We pretty much discussed it. It wasn't really like we
said, `John, you can't play.'''
</P>
<P>
   According to McEnroe, it was more what wasn't said: something
along the lines of ``John, please play.''
</P>
<P>
   Only Gambill at any point during the week, McEnroe said,
expressed enthusiasm over the possibility of playing doubles with
him. Martin and even Woodruff made it plain that while McEnroe's
second serve may be good enough for seniors' events, the Spaniards
were likely to treat it like batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had considered playing despite his players'
sentiments, McEnroe said: ``I'd feel a little awkward. Maybe I've
gotten a little soft in my old age. So far I've led democratically.
I haven't led dictatorially.'' He admitted that the ``the focus had
gotten off track,'' and that he was uncomfortable with the notion
that he was ``riding in on a horse to save the Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the doubles will be moot unless the
Americans can avoid being ground down by Corretja and Costa in
singles. The Spanish captain, Javier Duarte, raised some eyebrows
by choosing Costa as his second singles player instead of Juan
Carlos Ferrero, one of the hottest young clay court players in the
world. Ferrero is ranked 13th. Costa is 16th. Corretja is ranked
seventh. Martin is ranked 29th, while Gambill is 37th.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, they should win,'' he said. ``But Spain has been
underachieving for 20 years in Davis Cup. I've just been surprised
that they haven't been able to get over the hump and have choked so
many times.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, McEnroe picked up and was off to Bilbao, an hour's
drive, to hit the Guggenheim Museum. He didn't have to practice.
There are benefits to being 41, and done.
</P>
</TEXT>
