<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8036 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-BELLSOUTH0721-COX     07-20 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth exceeds forecasts with another record quarter
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth Corp. on Thursday turned in yet another
record quarter, with a 39.9 percent increase in earnings and
revenue up 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   During the three months ended June 30, the Atlanta-based
regional telecommunications company reported $1.1 billion in
earnings, or 56 cents per share, compared with $786 million, or 41
cents a share, during the same quarter a year ago. Those results
beat a consensus of analysts' estimates by a penny a share as
revenue hit $6.8 billion during the quarter, compared with $6.1
billion in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most important is the top-line growth,'' said Isaiah
Harris, vice president for finance. ``I am not sure there are a lot
of surprises. We have delivered fairly consistent results.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth was fueled largely by data services, wireless and
international units.
</P>
<P>
   Data services to businesses, including providing high-speed
lines and hosting Web sites, grew 27 percent to $869 million during
the quarter. Meanwhile, BellSouth's premier means of delivering
high-speed data _ digital subscriber lines and fiber _ now have
74,000 customers, compared with 49,000 three months earlier and
30,000 at the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   By quarter's end, about 788,000 customers were using BellSouth's
Internet unit.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from the company's wireless operations in the United
States, which are mostly limited to the Southeast, surged 17
percent to $877 million during the quarter. The company now has 5.9
million customers paying an average of $54 a month, up from a
monthly average of $51 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has announced an alliance with SBC Communications that
will merge the two companies' wireless units, creating a new
company to be based in Atlanta. An offering from the combined
company is expected by late this year.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth's international business grew to $834 million during
the quarter, up nearly 18 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company this year has expanded its reach in Colombia and
Brazil, the largest market in Latin America. BellSouth's
international interests at quarter's end accounted for 7.6 million
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The company's core business _ local phone service in the
Southeast _ still accounts for the majority of BellSouth revenue
and has kept growing, albeit more modestly than wireless or data.
</P>
<P>
   Land line communications, including fees for connecting to
BellSouth's network, accounted for $4.6 billion in revenue, roughly
two-thirds of BellSouth's total. Local service alone brought in
$2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company workforce grew again last quarter as the company
again began to approach the size it had reached a decade ago before
starting years of painful cuts. BellSouth completed the quarter
with 99,027 employees, up 4,029 from a year before, with most of
the hiring coming in service and sales to handle growing wireless
and data businesses.
</P>
<P>
   However, the company earlier this year announced cuts of 2,100
jobs in an effort to reduce corporate staff. ``There is actually a
negative hidden beneath the surface,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth peaked in 1990 with 103,152 workers, then reached its
lowest ebb in 1997 with about 81,100.
</P>
<P>
   But solid performance quarter after quarter doesn't always reap
a Wall Street reward. Like other large telecom companies, BellSouth
has been receiving a cool investor reception. Analysts have
variously blamed that on Internet fever _ the shifting of billions
of investment dollars to ``new economy'' companies _ and investor
fear of an acquisition that will dilute holdings.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth shares did get a bounce in the spring with the
announcement that the company plans a tracking stock for its Latin
American unit, but then the telecom tide went out again. In the
past 52 weeks, BellSouth has traded as high as $53.50 and as low as
$34.94.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said the company needs to shrug off the market malaise.
``Our only reponse is to continue to deliver growth and to tell our
story. We believe that over time, the stock will reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth stock on Thursday dropped $2.13, closing at $39.44.
</P>
<P>
   Among others reporting earnings was BellSouth partner SBC, which
said second-quarter profit was flat, but _ like BellSouth _ higher
than Wall Street expectations by a penny per share. San
Antonio-based SBC's revenue was up 10 percent to $13.2 billion.
Earnings were $1.92 billion, or 56 cents per share, only slightly
higher than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   SBC doubled the number of customers for its DSL service and
after being permitted into long-distance in Texas signed up 150,000
customers in eight days. SBC added 537,000 wireless customers
during the quarter, while wireless revenues climbed 30.6 percent to
$1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
