<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sprint suitor strays, but earnings rise
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sprint reported better-than-expected profit Thursday,
even as a potential suitor seemed to be turning its attention
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas-based Sprint, the nation's fourth-largest wireless
carrier and third-largest long-distance company, reported quarterly
earnings of $926 million, up 13 percent from the same period a year
ago. Excluding a one-time gain, that represents 67 cents per share
_ about 20 percent better than the second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has been seen as an alluring marriage candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anteing up for its wireless business, Sprint PCS, is a good
way for long-term investors to own a piece of greatness,'' wrote
Morningstar.com's Todd P. Bernier on Thursday. ``The company's
showing in the June quarter, announced today, was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Sprint's deal to be acquired by Mississippi-based
WorldCom was blocked last month by regulators. Speculation then had
Sprint being purchased by Deutsche Telekom, and the two were
reportedly talking. Then several dozen U.S. senators objected,
citing DT's majority ownership by the German government.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom seemed then to shift its attentions. While the
company is reportedly in a host of different negotiations, its
priority seems to be VoiceStream. DT has reportedly offered more
than $200 a share _ or about $53 billion _ for the wireless
carrier, and a deal would make a Deutsche bid for Sprint and its
wireless network unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The VoiceStream pricing is right, wrote analyst Walter Piecyk of
PaineWebber. ``While competitive bids are possible, we believe this
is a price that management would accept.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would leave the field open to ... whom?
</P>
<P>
   Only a few players are big enough to bid for the company.
BellSouth, which bid against WorldCom for Sprint in October, has
thus far expressed no interest in renewing the chase. A
BellSouth-Sprint merger would still bump against a continued ban on
BellSouth offering long-distance. Moreover, since the fall,
BellSouth has announced an alliance of its wireless operations with
those of SBC Commu- nications.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint stock fell $2.44 Thursday to $42.56 a share. The tracking
stock for its wireless unit rose 52 cents to $64.38.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
