u i BC-AFRICA-G8-650&AMP;ADD-NYT     07-20 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-G8-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERS OF DEVELOPING COUNTRIES BRING VOICE OF THE POOR TO G-8
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ With leaders of the world's industrialized countries
gathering in Japan for their annual meeting, a handful of major
Third World nations took center stage Thursday and lambasted the
richest nations on behalf of the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Tokyo on the eve of the summit meeting,
which is being held on Japan's southern island of Okinawa, leaders
of South Africa, Nigeria and Algeria _ three of Africa's largest
countries _ said the world's seven leading economic powers, plus
Russia, had been too slow to act on debt relief and other issues
vital to economic growth in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no longer a question of what we should do,'' said
Nigeria's president, Olusegun Obasanjo. ``We all know what we
should do. The question is do we have the political will.''
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was sponsored by Jubilee 2000, a coalition
of charities calling for debt relief for the poor. Obasanjo is head
of the so-called Group of 77, a political coalition of
underdeveloped countries, and is also head of the movement of
nonaligned nations. .
</P>
<P>
   The comments by Obasanjo _ and similarly spirited remarks made
by the South African leader, Thabo Mbeki, and the Algerian
president, Abdelaziz Bouteflika _ were among the rare contretemps
in a minutely planned diplomatic ballet as delegations from the
leading industrial nations _ the United States, Britain, Italy,
Canada, France, Germany and Japan _ joined delegates from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo and his African peers accused the world's
industrialized powers of selfish shortsightedness in their dealings
with the Third World. Heavy debt-servicing demands in developing
countries prevent spending on vital services like health care and
education.
</P>
<P>
   The anger of the Third World presidents was underscored by
reports that the industrialized nations would act to speed debt
relief for Russia during the three-day Okinawa meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki said that in addition to debt issues, representatives of
rich and poor nations at a meeting Thursday discussed increasing
foreign direct investment in Africa, Africa's access to foreign
markets and the transfer of information technology and
biotechnology to Africa, among other things. ``It is a range of
things that are interrelated, and it is important that the G-8,
when they address these questions, address all of these
questions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The African leaders were not met separately by the Japanese
prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, as they had requested, but instead
were included at a dinner Thursday night with leading officials of
the seven industrialized nations and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Third World leaders also met with leaders of several
international technology giants, including Sony Corp. and Cisco
Systems.
</P>
<P>
   After the talks, the U.S. treasury secretary, Lawrence Summers,
who was standing in for President Clinton _ who was arrived late
because of the Israeli-Palestinian talks at Camp David, Md. _ said
that significant ground had been covered during the evening
meeting. Among the proposals agreed upon were expanding debt relief
programs beyond the poorest, most-heavily indebted countries that
had previously been eligible. It was also agreed that the next
round of World Trade Organization talks would be devoted to the
problems of poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a somewhat skeptical note, Mbeki said the Third World
must await the outcome of the summit meeting before gauging how
determined the rich nations are to provide more meaningful
assistance for solving the problems of poverty and disease. ``The
question of what they will say, that can only come at the end of
the Okinawa meeting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the summit meeting last year, the world's richest nations
announced with great fanfare a $100 billion debt relief package for
40 of the world's poorest countries. But almost none of the money
called for under the program has been disbursed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Clinton administration narrowly averted embarrassment over
this issue when the House of Representatives voted only last week
to finance Clinton's request for Washington's $262 million share in
providing debt relief.
</P>
<P>
   Again this year, the industrialized nations are promising a
number of major initiatives at their summit meeting, and the plans
are as sweeping as they have ever been.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting has been billed as the Information Summit, and has
set as one of its goals reducing the so-called digital divide _ or
access to the Internet and other information technology _ between
rich and poor countries.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has pledged to donate $15 billion over the next five years
to help poor countries increase Internet access and develop
information technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Major goals have also been announced in health care. The leaders
of the industrialized nations have reportedly agreed on setting a
target of 25 percent for reducing AIDS infection among 15 to 24
year olds in the Third World by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 35 million people are living with AIDS worldwide, and
70 percent of the victims are in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has pledged $3 billion to battle AIDS and tropical
diseases like malaria in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also announced an AIDS initiative this week for 24
African countries that will provide them with $1 billion in loans
annually to pay for medicine and other treatment to fight AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
