u f BC-UPS0721-COX     07-20 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UPS0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Market share up, UPS profit soars 18%
 &HT;    By Dave Hirschman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rising domestic and international shipments fueled an
18 percent jump in profit at United Parcel Service Corp. during the
three months that ended June 30, the company reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   UPS earned $695 million, or 60 cents a share, in its second
quarter on revenue of $7.3 billion. The Sandy Springs-based
transportation giant earned $588 million, or 52 cents a share, on
revenue of $6.6 billion during the same period last year, excluding
one-time charges. The company's performance was in line with Wall
Street expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, we're pleased by the company's growth
across all segments,'' said Jim Kelly, UPS chairman and chief
executive. ``Customers are rewarding us for superior service and
the industry's broadest product portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS daily package volume averaged 13.2 million units in the
quarter, up 6.7 percent from 12.4 million in the same period last
year. Domestic volume rose 6 percent with premium-priced,
next-morning shipments growing 9.9 percent. International volume
rose 15.3 percent, with U.S. exports surging 23 percent.
</P>
<P>
   UPS also announced Thursday that it will impose a 1.25 percent
fuel surcharge beginning Aug. 7 to make up for recent price spikes.
Fuel typically accounts for about 3 percent of the company's total
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Satish Jindel, transportation analyst at SJ Consulting, said UPS
is gaining market share from rivals FedEx Corp., Airborne Express
and the U.S. Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growth in this sector is not evenly spread,'' Jindel said.
``UPS is taking business away from the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   UPS ``non-package revenue'' from ancillary businesses such as
insurance, logistics and finance rocketed to $371 million during
the quarter, up 70 percent from $218 million a year ago. Robert
Clanin, chief financial officer at UPS, said large start-up costs
will keep the logistics division from being immediately profitable,
however.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're investing heavily in logistics,'' Clanin said. ``We
anticipate it will take a year or more for logistics to become
fully profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rosy outlook, UPS shares fell $1.69 to $59.56
because the company failed to surpass analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Meeting expectations doesn't get you a pat on the back,''
Clanin said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
