<HEADER>
A8040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT &LR;      07-20 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOUR-DE-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG SPRINT HELPS ITALIAN STEAL STAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREIBURG, Germany _ Five low-ranked but aggressive riders jumped
away early Thursday in the Tour de France, built a lead of nearly
28 minutes through the gingerbread villages of Switzerland and held
more than half of it at the finish before enormous crowds in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   It was the type of exciting day that often develops toward the
end of a Tour when the stage is monstrously long and the leaders
have their eyes on another day _ a long individual time trial
Friday _ and are content to let lesser lights shine.
</P>
<P>
   The shiniest was Salvatore Commesso, an Italian with Saeco, who
won a sprint finish against Alexander Vinokourov, a Kazakh with
Deutsche Telekom, a German team.
</P>
<P>
   Commesso finished first by half a bicycle length in 6 hours 8
minutes 15 seconds for the 246.5-kilometer (153-mile) 18th of 21
stages. Commesso's speed of 40 kilometers an hour (a shade under 25
mph) brought him home 15:40 ahead of the main pack.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong, who complained afterward about the length of
the stage and the fact that an even longer one is scheduled
Saturday, a day before the finish in Paris, continued in the
leader's yellow jersey with an unchanged edge of 5:37 in overall
elapsed time over Jan Ullrich.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Julich could have been, should have been, in the breakaway
group, but wasn't. He is low-ranked _ 49th place, one hour 37
minutes 40 seconds behind his former teammate and longtime rival,
Armstrong. But Julich, 28, an American who rides for the Credit
Agricole team from France and finished third in the 1998 Tour, is
not aggressive these days.
</P>
<P>
   A strong climber who has worn the king of the mountains jersey
in other races, Julich has been limping home in the gruppetto, the
Italian word for the group of riders who work together far behind
in the mountains to make sure they all finish within the time
needed to avoid disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the Tour de France through different eyes,'' Julich
said. ``It's kind of a humbling experience.''
</P>
<P>
   His troubles in this Tour began on the first day in the
Pyrenees, the climb to the Hautacam peak on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power just wasn't there in the legs in the mountains,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Julich finished nearly 13 minutes behind the winner, snuffing
his hopes of standing on the three-step victory podium when the
race ends in Paris on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized it was over,'' he said, ``and it's kind of
difficult to pick up the pieces after that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
