u l BC-DEALER0720-COX     07-20 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEALER0720-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Career as a Las Vegas blackjack dealer hard way to make an easy
living
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ She's standing at a blackjack table at The Mirage
Hotel, expertly dealing the cards and chatting with patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Her name tag reads ``Nancy'' and ``Dayton, Ohio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They want customers to know where we're from because it's an
icebreaker,'' explains Nancy Potasky Stein, who's been a Las Vegas
dealer 16 years. ``It gives them a chance to say they're also from
Dayton or Columbus or Cincinnati.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in tuxedo shirt and bow tie, short black skirt and
teal-and-black vest decorated with a palm-tree design, Stein has
worked her way up to the top of a profession she calls fun and
exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a hard way to make an easy living,'' Stein says. ``I like
it because it's a people job.''
</P>
<P>
   That's obvious on this particular morning as a patron steers her
wheelchair up to Stein's table.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know my mother passed away,'' the woman confides as Stein
begins to deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a local who always came in with her mother,'' says Stein
later. ``I knew right away when I didn't see her mother that
something was wrong. I have a lot of repeat customers; you get to
know their whole life stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Her clients come from around the world and speak a variety of
languages. Her workplace is one of the strip's most elaborate
hotels, housing novelties ranging from Siegfried and Roy's gorgeous
snow-white leopards and white tigers to a ``live volcano'' that
erupts every half hour.
</P>
<P>
   On her way to work, she passes live dolphins and sharks, a
tropical rain forest, palm trees and loads of orchids.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as glamorous as it might appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``You stand on your feet all day and sometimes you have to put
up with obnoxious people,'' Stein says. ``But, overall, people are
basically nice _they're out having a good time, they're on
vacation, they're relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   So how did a local girl end up cutting the chips in Las Vegas?
</P>
<P>
   It all started when her dad opened an auto painting shop in Las
Vegas and his daughter began accompanying him to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I might want to be a dealer,'' said Stein, then 24,
who had attended the University of Tampa and always worshipped the
sun. ``I had never picked up a deck of cards in my life!
</P>
<P>
   ``My father had a friend who had a dealers' school and he said
you could earn a good living,'' she remembers. Today, according to
Stein, dealers earn between $20,000 and $80,000, primarily in tips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually paid just minimum wage,'' Stein explains,
adding that dealers prefer the type of tip in which the player
makes a bet for the dealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dealer might average between $120-$160 a day in tips plus
their salary,'' says Stein, who deals in two areas _ a low limit
$5,000 pit and a high limit ($5,000-$10,000) pit on weekends. Stein
works six hours a day, with 20 -minute breaks each hour.
</P>
<P>
   Employee cafeterias provide another perk: Casino employees eat
whatever they like free of charge when they're on duty. There are
also complimentary tickets to shows to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who has always dealt blackjack_ the nation's most popular
casino game _ says dealing isn't as easy as it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You practice by pitching cards into a hat for hours,'' she
says. ``You learn to deal out of a shoe, how to cut the chips, what
the payoffs are.''
</P>
<P>
   Though dealing had traditionally been a man's profession, by the
time Stein attended dealers' school, women were dealing as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was all by myself, scared but excited,'' she recalls.
``Everyone said I'd be back in Dayton in six months.''
</P>
<P>
   After completing the course, neophyte dealers get their feet wet
by working at downtown casinos as apprentices, then move to the
strip.
</P>
<P>
   Stein practiced at El Cortez, then went to the Horseshoe .
</P>
<P>
   ``Every casino has a different costume,'' says Stein. ``At the
Horseshoe, we wore jeans and a bolero and cowboy boots.'' She
worked her way up to the Golden Nugget, the old MGM, then moved to
the prestigious Mirage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you're interviewed by the casino manager, other
times you are auditioned _ they watch you deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein suffered a temporary setback at the age of 30 when she was
diagnosed with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a fighter,'' she says. ``I kept my apartment here but
went back to Dayton for the chemo and radiation.''
</P>
<P>
   She credits her dad with encouraging her to become a dealer when
she expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll earn a good living and meet a nice Jewish boy,'' he
assured her.
</P>
<P>
   Both predictions have come true. At 43, Stein met and married
Howard Stein, a pit boss at the Bellagio hotel. It was a first
marriage for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to get married but I was very picky,'' says
Stein.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Stein says his wife is an excellent dealer who's lots of
fun, always upbeat and brings out the best in others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of dealers out here who are stone-faced and
don't talk, and you might as well go to a machine!'' he says.
``When you gamble most people lose money because that's what Las
Vegas is built on. People aren't exactly happy when they lose but
the hurt isn't so bad when you're with Nancy because you're having
fun. She gets everybody involved _ the people at the table are all
interacting with one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein says Las Vegas has changed dramatically since she arrived
20 years ago. Then, she says, the town was known for cheap
all-you-can-eat buffets; today, gourmet restaurants abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all the concerts come here now,'' Stein says. ``Las Vegas
is a good value for a vacation and now people bring their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite Las Vegas acts currently include ``O,'' a Cirque du
Soleil show performed on a stage of water at the Bellagio;
impersonator Danny Gans, who performs at The Mirage, and
``Mystere,'' another Cirque show at Treasure Island.
</P>
<P>
   Any gambling advice?
</P>
<P>
   ``Come knowing that gambling is for entertainment only,'' she
advises. ``Come to have a good time. Pick up a strategy card if
you're a novice ... it will tell you when to split, when to double
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``And don't spend more than you can afford to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Contact Meredith Moss at meredithmoss(at)coxohio.com or at
225-2440.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
