<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-VOTERS-SUBURBMOMS23-C     07-20 1556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTERS-SUBURBMOMS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WOMEN'S VOTE UP FOR GRABS THIS YEAR, TO GORE'S DISMAY
 &HT;    1100&AMP;add. With VOTERS-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories for release Sunday, July 23.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Va. _ Shielded by a shade tree from the midday sun,
Nancy Luciani sits in a trim municipal park as her son and a gaggle
of other 6-year-olds chase a ball across a grassy field. Nearby are
all the trappings of life in the 'burbs: the jogging strollers, the
minivans, the fellow parents waiting to ferry their kids to their
next summer activity.
</P>
<P>
   Luciani is a 36-year-old mom watching her kid play soccer. But
do not call her a ``soccer mom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The soccer-mom term is so derogatory. It suggests that all
women think and feel the same way,'' says Luciani, a former
corporate systems analyst and now full-time mother of three from
Oakton, Va., a suburb of Washington. ``Women care about a lot of
different things.''
</P>
<P>
   And to be sure, Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush
of Texas care a lot about women _ and their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, soccer moms gained almost mythical stature among
campaign operatives and political commentators as a coveted swing
voting bloc that would re-elect President Clinton or give
Republican Bob Dole a fighting chance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, as they had in '92, a majority of women voters handed
Bill Clinton a decisive victory, demonstrating their traditional
preference for the Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the neck-and-neck 2000 presidential campaign is a
different story. According to polls, Bush is cutting into the
conventional Democratic advantage with women, the very voters Gore
must have if he expects to win in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real clear that younger women, mothers, married women,
are key battleground groups,'' said pollster Andrew Kohut, director
of the Pew Research Center for the People and the Press.
</P>
<P>
   The tenor of the campaign illustrates just how hard Bush and
Gore are trying to appeal to the bloc _ each touting proposals for
education, children, health care and community values.
</P>
<P>
   But women voters are no monolith.
</P>
<P>
   Working women naturally are interested in the economy,
fair-labor issues and women's rights. Working moms care about those
things too, plus day-care and family leave. Stay-at-home mothers
pay attention to education and family values. For many but not most
women, abortion is a make-or-break issue, depending on which side
of the issue they are on.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer moms, suburb moms, mall moms _ by any other name, this
target group is mainly young, mainly white and mainly living in
suburbs and small towns. They represent anywhere between 5 and 20
percent of the electorate, pollsters say.
</P>
<P>
   What makes this group of women so important as a voting bloc are
men.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic-Republican gender gap exists because men
abandoned the Democratic party during the Reagan era in the 1980s
and, to a greater extent, in the midterm elections of 1994 that
elected a Republican Congress. Since early 1999, surveys show that
Bush has consistently drawn greater support from men compared to
Gore, leading by an average of 20 percentage points in recent
polls.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in the battle for women, the stakes are greatest for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he holds what several recent polls describe as only a
slight lead among all women, and in some surveys he lags among
married women. A Pew Research Center poll in late June found Gore
trailing Bush among mothers, 45 percent to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, women have been a core constituency for the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the presidency from Bush's father in 1992, Clinton
garnered 45 percent of the women's vote, compared to 37 percent for
the elder Bush. In 1996, Clinton doubled his victory margin to 16
percentage points, beating Dole among women voters 54 percent to 38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why is Gore losing some of them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is smart. He's talking about issues that women do care
about _ education, children's health, Social Security. He speaks
with a more credible voice on these issues than previous Republican
candidates have,'' said Anna Greenberg, a pollster at Harvard
University's John F. Kennedy School of Government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important for Al Gore to shore up the traditional base,
and the base includes important blocs of Democratic and independent
women voters,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But some pollsters and political analysts detect a potentially
more troublesome factor for Gore. Many women voters, when gauging
qualities such as character and trust, view him negatively.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys show Bush out-polling Gore on character
evaluations and leadership qualities. Gore's poll numbers dipped in
June amid news reports that Justice Department officials had
recommended that an independent counsel probe the vice president's
1996 campaign finance activities.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Browning, a high-school teacher and 41-year-old mother
of three in Vienna, Va., voted for Clinton in 1992 and in 1996 and
considers herself a solid Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But she does not like Gore, and cannot bring herself to support
Bush. Instead, she'll vote for third-party candidate and consumer
advocate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want authenticity. Someone who seems genuine and not
sculpted by some marketing specialist,'' she said. ``I just don't
trust him (Gore) because he seems so contradictory depending on the
audience he's talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   In his campaigns for governor in Texas, Bush proved popular with
women voters. Running against a woman, Democratic incumbent Ann
Richards in 1994, Bush split the women's vote. In 1998, Bush won
re-election with 65 percent of the women's vote.
</P>
<P>
   Touting his ``compassionate conservatism,'' Bush thus far has
commanded the presidential campaign agenda and prevented Gore from
stressing the kinds of issues most appealing to women, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has fashioned himself as ``the low-risk change,'' said
Thomas Mann, a scholar of government and politics at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research center.
</P>
<P>
   Voters detect few differences between the candidates on bedrock
issues like health care and education. That has given Bush an edge
in appealing to both women and men as the anti-Washington candidate
by focusing ``on changing the way we conduct politics,'' Mann said
</P>
<P>
   Yet many pollsters and political scholars dismiss the notion
that Gore has been tainted directly by President Clinton and the
scandals that plagued his administration, most notably the affair
with Monica Lewinsky that led to Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore and the Democrats may suffer a credibility problem when
campaigning on family values _ issues such as community, parenting
and morals that women in particular rank high among their
priorities, said analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To some extent, Clinton has given the Republicans those issues
and made it difficult for the Democrats to talk about them,''
Greenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll in March asked women what factor is most important
in their vote this year. They were evenly split, with 47 percent
naming an issue or issues and 47 percent citing character and
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Luciani, the soccer mom who detests the label, ranks the
character of the candidate and issues involving the economy,
education and family values high on her list. A self-described
independent voter, she says Gore was never an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't know anything about him, if he were starting from
zero, I would consider him,'' she said. ``But knowing about him and
his connections to the Clinton administration, I'd say 'no.' ``
</P>
<P>
   At the Republican nominating convention, convening July 31 in
Philadelphia, the podium with be filled with ample evidence of the
GOP strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Day One: The candidate's wife, Laura Bush, and former Gen. Colin
Powell will address issues of health care, education and Bush's
``leave no child behind'' theme. Day Two: former presidential
candidate Elizabeth Dole and GOP adviser Condoleeza Rice will
emphasize America's place in the world. Day Three: a focus on small
business, a traditional Republican theme and one that plays to a
current trend _ about half of all new small businesses are run by
women.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise in Los Angeles in mid-August, Gore and the Democrats
will stress the important issues separating him and Bush: gun
control, abortion rights and the party's traditional role as a
defender of equal rights.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts point out that, with four months remaining until the
election, much about the character of the race can and probably
will change. Many voters, women and men, have yet to focus on the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, women appear much more likely than in the past to
consider the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in '96 the soccer moms, or what that meant, was
baloney,'' said the pollster Kohut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those younger married women or young mothers were always for
Clinton, not for Dole. They thought Dole was out on another planet,
and they couldn't relate to him. But younger women are having a
real hard time choosing between Bush and Gore in a way that they
didn't have four years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles W. Holmes's e-mail address is chuckh(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
