<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-ART-NYT &LR;      07-20 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS SOAR AS INVESTORS INTERPRET GREENSPAN OPTIMISTICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also GREENSPAN-ECON)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Are investors looking at Alan Greenspan through
rose-colored glasses?
</P>
<P>
   They may have done just that Thursday, focusing on all the
positives of the testimony by the Federal Reserve chairman before
the Senate Banking Committee and sending stock and bond prices
sharply higher and interest rates lower. The Nasdaq composite index
jumped 3.2 percent. The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 1.4
percent, led by a 12 percent surge in IBM after it reported strong
second-quarter profits late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   What investors and analysts saw, to their surprise, was
Greenspan offering encouragement for the view that the central bank
would be able to slow economic growth enough to contain inflation,
without risking a recession and, possibly, without any more
interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``What has captured the markets' attention here is that
Greenspan has raised the possibility that the Fed is done,'' said
Louis Crandall, chief economist at R.H. Wrightson &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Berner, chief U.S. economist at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, said the Fed's aggressive stance of last spring had
mellowed. ``The tone is one of a Fed that is going to be in a
watchful, waiting mode, but doesn't see any catalyst for acting,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But investors may be too optimistic, and this could trip up
markets in the days ahead, when the euphoria created by a mellow
Alan Greenspan wears off.
</P>
<P>
   First, even some Wall Street analysts who were surprised by
Greenspan's optimism still say more Fed rate increases will be
needed in the future to finally slow economic growth to a
manageable, noninflationary pace.
</P>
<P>
   While the chances of a rate increase in late August, when Fed
policy makers next meet, are diminishing, Richard Berner, chief
U.S. economist at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, expects at least one
more rate rise before the central bank is finished.
</P>
<P>
   But there may be an even bigger problem lurking for investors if
Greenspan's remarks bring a lot of bulls back to the stock and bond
markets. Strong rallies in both markets, on the belief that the
worst of a yearlong series of Fed increases is over, could make
slowing economic growth much more difficult and require more
increases than now anticipated. Stocks rising to new highs could
set off a burst of consumer spending _ through what is known as the
wealth effect _ of the kind that has reignited economic growth in
the last several years. Declining interest rates will help spur
both businesses and consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were to rally 15 percent or 20 percent from here, that
would negate some of the Fed's tightening pressure,'' Berner said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this threat to a successful slowdown, or soft
landing, ``most of us didn't expect him to be this
market-friendly,'' Crandall said. ``This was the surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan also warned that a soft landing for the economy is not
assured. But that message seemed to be drowned out Thursday by the
market applause for Greenspan's unexpected optimism.
</P>
<P>
   In the stock market, the Nasdaq index jumped 128.93 points, to
4,184.56, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 13.61
points, or 0.9 percent, to 1,495.57. The Dow rose 147.79 points, to
10,843.87. IBM, which had announced a 12 percent earnings increase,
accounted for half the Dow's rise. IBM rallied in after-hours
trading on Wednesday, but that did not show up in the Dow until
Thursday, when the stock rose $12.84, to $117.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices were higher as yields, which move in
the opposite direction, fell. The yield on the Treasury's 10-year
note fell to 6 percent, from 6.15 percent Wednesday, while the
price rose 1 3/32, to 103 19/32. The yield on the 10-year note has
been fighting to get back below 6 percent for five weeks. The yield
on the 30-year bond fell to 5.81 percent from 5.91 percent
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One key monitor of concern about Fed rate increases did ease
Thursday. The yield fell on the futures contracts on the federal
funds rate, the central bank's short-term interest rate target, for
August, October, November and December.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony on monetary policy, Greenspan pointed out
several factors restraining consumer spending, including rising
consumer debt, rising oil and gasoline prices and the flat
performance of the stock market so far this year. And he said that
this consumer slowdown, if it continued, might be enough to bring
economic growth down to the noninflationary pace Fed officials
want. That is somewhere around 3.5 percent, well below the 6
percent pace of last year's fourth quarter and this year's first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should this favorable outcome prevail,'' he said, ``the
immediate threat to our prosperity from growing imbalances in our
economy would abate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan also warned that it was too early to declare
victory. ``It is much too soon,'' he said, ``to conclude that these
concerns are behind us. We cannot yet be sure that slower expansion
of domestic final demand, at a pace more in line with potential
supply, will persist.''
</P>
<P>
   In past years, the economy has reaccelerated after slowing in
the second quarter, a fact that Greenspan mentioned. The next key
economic report is the Employment Cost Index, which measures worker
compensation and is one of the Fed's favorite inflation barometers.
It will be released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The next several days ought to indicate if investors have gotten
Fed-happy. The stock and bond markets have often responded nicely
on the day some positive news is released, only to settle back
after investors realize that they _ and the Fed _ still need to see
more positive data before they know they are out of the woods. But
if investors conclude too early that they are out of the woods,
their optimism, and the rallies it creates, may put them back in
again.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
