<P>
   Business Day Front Page of The New York Times, Friday, July 21.
</P>
<P>
   (Lede story)
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Lucent Technologies Inc. said
Thursday that its financial results would fall short of
expectations for the next two quarters, at least in part because
the company has been caught off guard by slower demand for
traditional communications systems and the rising importance of
newer technologies. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   (Dual top display)
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-ECON (Washington) _ Federal Reserve chairman Alan
Greenspan told the Senate Banking Committee Thursday that the
economy may be slowing in response to the highest interest rates in
nearly a decade, but he also suggested that the central bank could
not rule out additional rate increases this year. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Are investors looking at Alan Greenspan
through rose-colored glasses? They may have done just that
Thursday, focusing on all the positives of the testimony by the
Federal Reserve chairman before the Senate Banking Committee and
sending stock and bond prices sharply higher and interest rates
lower. The Nasdaq composite index jumped 3.2 percent. The Dow Jones
industrial average climbed 1.4 percent, led by a 12 percent surge
in IBM after it reported strong second-quarter profits late
Wednesday. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
