A8070 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-FILM-POKEMON-SPI &LR;      07-20 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-POKEMON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE IS LESS IN HO-HUM, MORALISTIC `POKEMON 2000' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C   
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never having been a part of the Pokemon phenomenon or craze, I
was curious to experience its seemingly endless appeal to kids for
myself. The concept of Pokemon's Nintendo sensibility providing any
sort of catharsis seemed nebulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon the Movie 2000'' is actually two films _ ``Pikachu's
Rescue Adventure'' followed by ``The Power of One.'' The press
notes say this is a sequel to last fall's hit, ``Pokemon The First
Movie,'' and the kids at a recent preview screening clamored for
their seats and appeared eager to revel in Pokemon magic.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the fad is beginning to wear thin. The theater
wasn't even full, and the young audience was contained and quiet
throughout, which can either be interpreted as a good _ or bad _
sign.
</P>
<P>
   To a neophyte, ``Pokemon the Movie 2000'' is a decidedly mixed
bag. The films introduce six new Pokemon along with returning human
counterparts, including Pokemon trainer Ash Ketchum. But audiences
must sit through ``Pikachu's Rescue Adventure,'' a 22-minute short,
before the main attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pikachu's Rescue Adventure'' chronicles the difficulties the
Pokemon face when a storm threatens their peaceful existence. It's
an immediately forgettable effort with little to distinguish it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Power of One'' is decidedly better. It has a cohesive
storyline and is imbued with some semblance of mythology and
Pokemon lore. It mixes creatures similar to Stravinsky's ``The
Firebird'' with a quest to rebalance nature after a greedy
collector attempts to throw that balance off-kilter. The legend
foretells that a ``chosen one'' will come after three Pokemon
legends _ the creatures that embody ice, fire and lightning _
``wreak destruction upon the world in which they clash.'' This
havoc will force the ultimate Pokemon named Lugia, who lives deep
in the sea, to surface and face capture.
</P>
<P>
   If this doom comes to pass, the Earth ``shall turn to ash,''
which refers to Ash Ketchum himself, and the boy must muster the
courage to help ward off impending destruction.
</P>
<P>
   This is certainly a metaphysical premise that may be too
sophisticated for smaller kids, but at least it attempts to create
some sense of the natural world and the chaos that human greed can
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it may just be the Pokemon chatter, which is
indistinguishable, that kids like so much. Due to its
nonsensicalness, kids can find any meaning they wish. It just may
be that ``Pokemon the Movie 2000'' will fare better with older kids
and adults, while smaller children will be bored by the lack of
Pokemon action and might prefer good old-fashioned fun over a
higher-minded moral.
</P>
<P>
   POKEMON THE MOVIE 2000
</P>
<P>
   DIRECTORS: Kunihiko Yuyama, Michael Haigney
</P>
<P>
   WRITERS: Norman J. Grossfeld, Michael Haigney, Takeshi Shudo
</P>
<P>
   VOICES: Veronica Taylor, Rachel Lillis, Eric Stuart, Ikue Otani
</P>
<P>
   RUNNING TIME: 103 minutes
</P>
<P>
   RATING: G
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
