A8077 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      07-20 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELS IN LEAD AFTER FIRST ROUND OF BRITISH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Ernie Els opened his eyes Thursday
morning, turned on the television in his hotel room and got an
immediate wake-up call. He saw players with early tee times
pummeling The Old Course at St. Andrews with birdies. He saw Tiger
Woods make a back-nine surge and charge his way onto the leader
board.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Els reached the driving range to prepare for his
afternoon round, the pressure was inescapable. Either he would join
the leaders with a strong opening round at the British Open, or he
would face an early deficit that might be too large to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Els did more than join the leaders. He passed them. Shooting an
opening-round 6-under 66, including a rare birdie on the No. 17
Road Hole, one of the world's toughest par 4s, Els held a
one-stroke lead over Woods and Steve Flesch after Thursday's first
round.
</P>
<P>
   Both Woods and Flesch shot 67s, while seven players were tied at
68 just two strokes off the lead: Tom Lehman, the 1996 British Open
champion; Scott Dunlap and Ian Garbutt of England; Sergio Garcia of
Spain; Padraig Harrington of Ireland; Shigeki Maruyama of Japan,
and Dennis Paulson of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Several players who expected to contend virtually eliminated
themselves with poor rounds. Hal Sutton shot 75, Nick Price and
John Daly both shot 76, and defending champion Paul Lawrie shot 78.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty of the 151 players in the field shot under par, as
afternoon temperatures were in the 70s, and there was not enough
wind to seriously affect ball flight or club selection. At times,
it felt more like San Diego than St. Andrews. If conditions remain
that way, it will be difficult for Woods or anyone else to run
away, because many players will continue to shoot under par.
</P>
<P>
   Remember last year's British Open at Carnoustie, Scotland, when
the winning score was 6 over ? This will be a far different
championship if the weather remains calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is firm and fast, but if you are playing well, the
course is there for the taking,'' said Lehman.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting precise and powerful drives that gave him great angles
into the greens, Els took the lead with the cool and calculating
style that has made him a two-time U.S. Open champion (1994 and
1997). He entered the tournament with momentum, winning last week's
Standard Life Loch Lomond Invitational in Scotland, and he has
played strong golf the entire year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Els has been overshadowed and outplayed by Woods, just like
everyone else in golf. When Woods won the U.S. Open by a
record-setting 15 strokes last month, it was Els who tied for
second with Miguel Angel Jimenez. When Vijay Singh won the Masters
in April, Els finished second. And when Woods opened the year with
a thrilling victory at the Mercedes Championships, he had to beat
Els in a riveting battle that lasted until the second hole of
sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   If Els were to finish second this weekend, he would become the
first player in history to finish second in three consecutive
majors. But finishing second is not what Els is about. With people
looking for the latest rival for Woods, Els may be playing well
enough to assume that role shortly, perhaps this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's quite a few players that can step up and be the rival,
whatever you want to call it,'' Els said. ``If I play well, I'm
probably going to play with Tiger sometime this week. He plays at
that level just about every week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to think about it too much. Tiger is a
good friend of mine and he's one heck of a player. Whoever wins
this week is probably the next rival of Tiger Woods, if it's not
him.''
</P>
<P>
   If Woods wins, he will become the youngest player in history, at
age 24, to win the career Grand Slam. For Woods, it was important
to avoid an early deficit that would force him to play catch-up,
and Thursday's strong start put him in excellent position. After
dominating last month's U.S. Open at Pebble Beach, Woods entered
this tournament as the overwhelming favorite. Yet Woods will gladly
settle for any victory, whether it's by 15 strokes or one stroke.
And Thursday, he took the first step toward that mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened at the U.S. Open, you have to put it
behind you,'' said Woods, after a bogey-free round that included a
furious flurry _ five birdies in a seven-hole stretch beginning
with a 12-foot birdie putt on No. 9, and ending with a 10-foot
birdie putt on No. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he had never played St. Andrews in more favorable
conditions. ``I don't think I've ever played any links golf like
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Els overtook Woods with a strong start, making four birdies
and just one bogey on the front nine. Then playing into the wind on
the back nine, Els added birdies on No. 10, No. 12, and No. 14,
followed by his final birdie on No. 17, which was world class. How
difficult is the par-4, 455-yard No. 17 at St. Andrews? There were
four birdies there Thursday, 70 bogeys, 21 double-bogeys and seven
scores worse than double-bogey.
</P>
<P>
   But Els had one of the four birdies. The tee shot at No 17 is
unnerving, forcing players to hit over a portion of the Old Course
Hotel into a fairway which they cannot see. Players chose their
line on the tee shot by using a sign that sits against the wall of
the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the word ``course', and you go over the letter
U,'' said Els. ``That's the exact line.''
</P>
<P>
   That works if you are as good as Els. After hitting a perfect
tee shot at No. 17, Els hit a gorgeous 6-iron from 183 yards that
landed six feet from the pin. The gallery in the stands adjacent to
the 17th green roared, then Els made the putt to take the lead. And
Els almost birdied No. 18 as well, missing a 12-foot birdie
attempt, before a tap-in par ended his day.
</P>
<P>
   Early in his career, Els was not a big fan of St. Andrews. He
had begun to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple of blind shots, but if you start getting your
lines right off the tees, the golf course becomes a little more
fun,'' he said. ``As to where it ranks as my favorite courses?
Let's see after this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1927EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ACCOUNTING-NORRIS-COL     07-20 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-NORRIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: PUZZLING INVESTORS WITH ACCOUNTING MYSTERIES IS POOR
PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Analyzing financial reports can resemble detective work.
Sometimes a certain fact is crucial; sometimes it is irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   One such fact is the trend in accounts receivable, the measure
of how much customers owe but haven't yet paid. A surge may
indicate that the company is having disputes with its customers
over how much they owe, or that customers are having problems
paying their bills. Or, it may reflect a more liberal credit policy
that is bolstering sales and profits. Either way, it is something
that American investors are used to being able to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   But what does it mean if a company leaps through accounting
hoops and comes up with a way to avoid disclosing what is happening
to accounts receivable, as well as other facts normally disclosed
on a routine basis?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question confronting investors in Modis Professional
Services, a company that used to be a hot stock when it was called
Accustaff. Modis was created in the early 1990s as a ``roll up,'' a
company that merged dozens of temporary help firms to create a
national operation.
</P>
<P>
   Investors believed then that such combines somehow created
synergies that made the whole more valuable than the sum of its
parts. Now, roll-ups are out of fashion and Modis' stock price is
down 78 percent from its 1998 high. Modis is trying to get with the
current fashion. It has sold some operations and plans to cut what
is left into two pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The largest segment, the information technology division,
provides about two-thirds of Modis' revenues. But Modis says that
is the business being spun off to shareholders. So it treats it as
a discontinued operation, and its latest quarterly report gives no
details about its balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   That is, to put it mildly, ridiculous. Not only is the division
by far the largest part of Modis, but it is not being discontinued
so far as the shareholders are concerned. They will continue to own
it when the spin-off is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Modis' lack of disclosure does, however, comply with the minimum
requirements of the current accounting rules. The Financial
Accounting Standards Board last week proposed a new rule that would
require complete disclosures in such cases, but that rule won't
take effect for some time. Still, even though the current rule
allows such treatment, nothing in it keeps Modis from telling its
shareholders what is happening to the balance sheet of its largest
operation. It just chooses not to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Modis is run by accountants. Its chief executive, Derek Dewan,
and its chief financial officer, Michael Abney, are both former
managing partners of the Jacksonville, Fla., office of Coopers &AMP;
Lybrand. I wondered whether they thought that it was fair to
investors to conceal such information. But the company's general
counsel, after being told what I wanted to ask them about, called
back to say they felt it would be improper to discuss such subjects
while the spin-off was being planned.
</P>
<P>
   So we return to the question. What does it mean? I don't know.
The fact that revenues at the information technology division fell
14 percent in the first quarter _ Modis did disclose that _ is not
good news. But the fact that Dewan bought stock at $10.25 a share
in April, or 25 percent more than the current price of $8.1875, is
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   It's an interesting mystery. But that is just the point. It
shouldn't be a mystery at all. Before executives with access to
such routine information make more trades, they should let the
other shareholders in on the facts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
