<HEADER>
A8083 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELL0721-COX     07-20 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell promises greater profits to come
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Michael Dell isn't bashful about getting
involved in Washington politics when technology policies are
concerned, but he prefers the role of confidant, not candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, an adviser to and fundraiser for Republican presidential
hopeful George W. Bush, said Thursday that he wouldn't trade the
chief executive's office for a cabinet seat.
</P>
<P>
   When Dell was asked the question by a shareholder at the
company's annual meeting, he deferred to his wife, Susan, who
shouted a decisive ``no'' from the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Although many Dell shareholders wondered about the company's
stock price, which has been locked stubbornly in the $40 to $50
range since splitting in March 1999, most praised the company and
its namesake chief executive. The stock was up $1.44 Thursday,
closing at $52.81 per share.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in five years, Dell didn't have a stock split
to announce to shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   But he had plenty to say, noting that the company's $136.6
billion market capitalization _ the total value of its shares
outstanding _ was greater than that of rivals Compaq Computer
Corp., Gateway Inc. and Apple Computer Inc. combined.
</P>
<P>
   But Dell didn't dwell long on past success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just getting started,'' Dell told shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   He proceeded to lay out a vision in which Dell would ride the
Internet to greater revenue and profits in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   The company is banking heavily on higher-profit servers and
storage products, which are at the heart of corporate computer
networks as well as Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Dell plans to capture a large part of the spending on products
that make up the Internet infrastructure _ a market it expects to
grow 200 percent annually to about $370 billion in just three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also plans to use its reputation as an e-commerce
heavyweight to sell expertise in various new services, such as
Web-site hosting and consulting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell.com is one of largest, if not the largest, online
business in the world, doing $40 to $50 million a day in sales,''
Dell said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell _ whose unofficial mantra for nearly a decade has been
liquidity, profitability and growth _ said with pride that ``unlike
Amazon, our online business is profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell's comments Thursday didn't provide the same warm, fuzzy
feeling as a stock split, but sufficed for many shareholders, such
as Lee Weislow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, this thing was like a party, the stock was
splitting,'' she said. ``For a while, I felt maybe I should sell
the stock. But I'm glad I didn't. It's still a stock you need to
own _ like GE.''
</P>
<P>
   Two shareholders asked Dell about its purchase last year of
ConvergeNet, a small data-storage technology company, for $340
million.
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, an analyst with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray,
previously had questioned whether the deal would yield any useful
products. Others have since echoed his claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made too big a jump,'' John McArthur, a storage analyst
for research firm International Data Corp., said this week. ``I
don't know anybody who was positive on the ConvergeNet acquisition.
You didn't have to talk to too many people before you ran into some
ex-ConvergeNet folks who said: 'That's nice, but (the technology)
doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had one of the new products on display outside the
meeting hall and said it will begin shipping test versions to some
customers in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't believe everything you read because it's not necessarily
accurate,'' Dell said. ``You're going to see from Dell over the
next few quarters an array of products from this team.''
</P>
<P>
   And Vice Chairman Jim Vanderslice defended the technology,
saying it works and will offer significant cost and performance
advantages to the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be the first time someone has written something
about us that's negative, and it wouldn't be the first time it was
wrong,'' Dell said. ``I don't think this game is over at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
