u f BC-ING-AETNA0721-COX     07-20 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ING-AETNA0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dutch firm sees Aetna deal gains
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ING Group NV's $7.7 billion acquisition of Aetna
Inc.'s financial service and international units may turn into more
business for the Dutch firm's American headquarters in the Atlanta
area, an ING executive said.
</P>
<P>
   The 600-employee operations can expect some growth as ING
doubles its U.S. business and triples its Latin American business
through the deal announced Thursday, said Keith Gubbay, executive
vice president for ING Americas.
</P>
<P>
   But like other units, ING's local corporate and investment
management offices could also feel some pressure as ING seeks to
squeeze $200 million in reduced expenses or additional revenues
from the combined entities in five years, Gubbay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect a lot of that will come from the revenue side,''
said Gubbay, adding that the acquisition will combine companies
with few overlapping businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be some expense consolidation,'' he said, ``but I
think it will be measured.''
</P>
<P>
   The long-anticipated ING-Aetna deal along with ING's acquisition
of ReliaStar three months ago puts the finishing touch to its
recent goal to rank among the 10-largest insurance firms in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ING said it will pay $5 billion in cash, mostly from company
funds, and assume $2.7 billion in debt to acquire Aetna's financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   The company will grow to 50 million customers from about 30
million now. Such growth and scale of operations is ``absolutely
essential to maintain the lead in today's financial services
markets,'' said ING Chairman Ewald Kist.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Aetna's international businesses will transform
ING into the top international insurance company in Latin America,
with more than 13 million customers, and the second-largest in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ING said it will combine part of the Aetna Financial Services
and Aetna International units into its ING Americas headquarters in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta office employs about 100 people each in its
investment management and corporate staffs in Atlanta, and about
400 in its life insurance unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta office has ``a very small regional staff responsible
for Latin America,'' said Gubbay.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
