<HEADER>
A8087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM-FCC-     07-20 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEUTSCHE-TELEKOM-FCC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEUTSCHE TELEKOM BUYOUT OF ANY U.S. COMPANY FACES HARD SCRUTINY,
FCC WARNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairman of the Federal Communications
Commission said Thursday that because Deutsche Telekom is
controlled by the German government, any offers it makes to buy an
American telephone company would face heavy regulatory scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In response to concerns raised by many Democratic and Republican
lawmakers, William Kennard, the FCC chairman, said that a merger
involving foreign government-controlled providers like Deutsche
Telekom raised important national security and competition
questions that would require close examination.
</P>
<P>
   For months, senior executives of Deutsche Telekom have been
exploring the possibility of a major expansion into the United
States. The company has made an offer to acquire the VoiceStream
Wireless Corp. for about $53 billion in cash and stock. Deutsche
Telekom has also made an unsuccessful run at acquiring Qwest
Communications International of Denver, and there has been
speculation that it could try to make another bid for the company
or others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, as you do, that the Commission's approach must
promote competition and maintain a secure telecommunication system
for our national security,'' Kennard wrote in a letter larded with
carefully-worded caveats.
</P>
<P>
   The letter replied to earlier correspondences sent by 30
Democratic and Republican lawmakers led by Sen. Ernest Hollings of
South Carolina, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Commerce
Committee. The lawmakers, including Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., and his Democratic counterpart, Sen. Tom Daschle of
South Dakota, have moved to adopt legislation curtailing any deal.
They have raised objections because Deutsche Telekom is 57 percent
owned by the German government.
</P>
<P>
   At Hollings' urging, the lawmakers attached a provision to a
Senate appropriations bill this week that would have the effect of
prohibiting the FCC from approving any American license transfers
to Deutsche Telekom for a year. The measure is now pending on the
floor of the Senate. Hollings has also introduced separate
legislation that has gained the support of many top Democrats and
Republicans that would permanently bar a deal.
</P>
<P>
   But other senators, including John McCain, the Arizona
Republican who heads the Commerce Committee, have raised concerns
that efforts by the government to block a deal could lead to
retaliation against American companies doing business abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it would be easy to envision new foreign restrictions
on U.S. programming, satellite launches and the like, foreign
governments' retaliation would not necessarily be confined to the
telecom sector,'' McCain said in a letter to colleagues this week.
``Any foreign market in which American companies are vigorous
participants could be fair game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennard's letter does not suggest that he is predisposed to
outright rejection of such a deal. But it portends the prospect of
a lengthy regulatory battle should Deutsche Telekom complete an
acquisition of an American company.
</P>
<P>
   Because regulators might need more than a year to examine any
proposed deals, the outcome of a review is impossible to predict,
since it is not even clear who would have the final say. Kennard's
term is set to end next July and the next president might appoint a
new chairman even sooner.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, any deal would be scrutinized by the office of the
U.S. trade representative, which would have to weigh whether trade
agreements might be violated by any attempt by the U.S. government
to block the merger.
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to allay growing concerns in Congress, Deutsche
Telekom has recently attempted to recruit some leading lobbyists
here, but has not been entirely successful. Several lobbyists said
they had turned the company down, in part because they represent
American telephone companies with competing interests. Among the
lobbying firms who recently spurned the German company is Quinn
Gillespie &AMP; Associates. Jack Quinn, the former White House counsel
who heads the firm, said last week that it was recently approached
but turned down Deutsche Telekom because it already does work for
two large regional telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings said in a recent interview that he is not opposed to
foreign investment in the United States, and in fact, has worked
hard to get foreign companies to open manufacturing plants in South
Carolina. But he said that at a time when the U.S. government is
moving to deregulate the telecommunications industry and foster
competition, it would be both inappropriate and unfair for American
companies to have to compete against a foreign government able to
subsidize the operations of its telecommunications business.
</P>
<P>
   Hollings has also taken his case beyond the FCC. He said that
last week he personally pressed John Podesta, the White House chief
of staff, to take steps to block any deal involving a foreign
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he would study it,'' Hollings said. The White House
has not taken a position on the matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
