<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8088 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      07-20 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE INVADES BUSH COUNTRY TO HIGHLIGHT HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MATT FLORES  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Flanked by San Antonio families he said epitomize
the problems with Texas' health care system, Vice President Al Gore
on Thursday attacked George W. Bush for his budgetary priorities,
saying the Texas governor placed more emphasis on tax cuts for the
rich than on medical needs of the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in Texas, faced with the largest surplus ever, Governor
Bush chose a different set of priorities,'' Gore, the Democratic
presidential hopeful, told a news conference. ``Instead of
addressing some serious problems involving families and children
who don't have health insurance, the governor made his top priority
_ the first bill he signed _ a large tax cut for special
interests.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed to the Lone Star State's record 1999 surplus of $6.4
billion, then said the state now faces a budget shortfall of up to
$750 million. He attributed the turnaround to Bush, whom he blamed
for putting too much emphasis on saving money to make room for a
$1.7 billion tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's comments drew a sharp response from Bush's
presidential campaign, which accused Gore of blatantly distorting
Texas budget figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Texas, taxes are low, the surplus is large, and spending on
education and health are up. The only shortfall to be found is in
Al Gore's credibility,'' Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer said, adding
that state Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander earlier in the day
released figures showing Texas with a $1.4 billion surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander herself took exception to Gore's figures, saying: ``The
only partisan politics that is being played is being played by Al
Gore. When he starts questioning our financial credibility in the
state of Texas, I am going to continue to set the record
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democrats have been particularly critical of Bush because
of a projection of more than $600 million in cost overruns in
Medicaid and prison expenses. Gore's San Antonio visit was hastily
added to the vice president's campaign itinerary after news of the
overruns starting appearing in newspaper headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's staff finalized his appearance at about 5 a.m. Thursday,
said Maria Meyer, a campaign official in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush, the presumed Republican presidential nominee,
maintains a double-digit lead over Gore in Texas, the two are in a
statistical dead heat in some national polls.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore the theme of his 30-minute speech, Gore pointed to
recent statistics that rank Texas second in the nation for number
of children living in poverty. He also said 1.4 million of the
nation's 11 million uninsured children reside in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing his remarks, Gore began a discussion with local
residents, including health care providers and mothers of uninsured
children who highlighted problems in obtaining adequate medical
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore charged that Bush fought efforts to expand health care
coverage to 220,000 low-income Texas children in the last
legislative session, and said 600,000 other children eligible for
Medicaid have not been enrolled because of cumbersome
administrative procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also noted the state could lose $449 million in federal
funding for the Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) because
it did not begin enrolling children in the program until May.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really wanted to address that problem, one way to do it
would have been to take that large surplus last year and address
the problem,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jeff Wentworth, a San Antonio Republican who stood
outside the Seven Oaks Conference Center and handed out handbills
denying Gore's remarks, reminded reporters that the last state
budget passed overwhelmingly by a Democrat-controlled state House.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say we ignored everything else to give tax cuts is
ludicrous,'' Wentworth said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Gore made an unexpected visit to the
Northeast YMCA Children's Greenhouse, where toddlers and
pre-schoolers were eating tacos.
</P>
<P>
   Gore made himself at home, sitting down with the children and
firing off questions: What were they having for lunch? Who was
going swimming that afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   Four-year-old Peyton Pyle wiggled his way to the front. Richard
Rodriguez, 4, who was wearing what appeared to be a Tyrannosaurus
Rex on his red T-shirt, corrected the vice president at one point.
``It's not a dinosaur. It's a crocodile,'' Richard informed him.
</P>
<P>
   During the 20-minute visit, Gore also performed, balancing a
broom on his nose and forehead. The children also had a chance to
question the vice president.
</P>
</TEXT>
