<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUR-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE GROUPS SUE SCOUR.COM FOR AIDING `THEFT' OF MUSIC, MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using strong rhetoric reminiscent of a public advocacy campaign,
trade groups representing the major movie studios and record labels
filed a copyright infringement lawsuit Thursday against Scour.com,
an Internet company that offers a file-swapping service similar to
the controversial Napster program.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a simple case of theft,'' said Jack Valenti, president
of the Motion Picture Association of America, which along with the
Recording Industry Association of America is suing Scour.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the case as a moral crusade involving ``what is right
and what is wrong,'' Valenti added, ``We need to reinstate... the
once assumed social contract that says, `Stealing is wrong.' You
don't raise your children to steal.''
</P>
<P>
   The case, filed in a Manhattan federal court, is the latest of
several suits initiated by the recording industry against Internet
companies including Napster and MP3.com. But it marks the first
time the movie trade group has joined forces with the music
business. Like the Napster case, the new suit alleges that Scour is
responsible for mass distribution and duplication of copyrighted
materials including music and videos.
</P>
<P>
   Scour.com, backed by Hollywood mogul and former top Disney
executive Michael Ovitz, offers an online search engine for music
and video files; like Napster, its Scour Exchange program enables
users to locate and download bootleg movie files as well as music
files.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Top Five Video Searches'' on the site Thursday included
the recently released summer blockbusters ``X-Men,'' ``Gladiator''
and ``Mission Impossible II.'' Unlike music files, however, movie
files can take hours to download, the system is hard to use, and
their quality is grossly inferior to seeing a movie at a theater or
on a legal videotape.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement released Thursday, the Beverly Hills-based Scour
claimed it was surprised by the lawsuit. Scour said it is
negotiating licensing rights with entertainment giants Sony, Warner
and BMG, and has license agreements with Miramax and Hollywood
Records; all of those companies are plaintiffs in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scour has always positioned itself as a cooperative,
responsible and legally compliant partner within the entertainment
community, and is working hand-in-hand with record labels, film
studios and other entertainment companies to deliver licensed
entertainment content to the Scour consumer,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, the former Hollywood superagent, is known as a tough
negotiator who got his clients lucrative deals from the movie
studios. He had no comment about the suit. ``We don't comment on
litigation filed against third parties,'' said Mike Burns, a
spokesperson for Ovitz' firm, CKE Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the entertainment industry painted the case as a
battle to change public perception about the legality of
downloading free music and movies.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the Pew Internet Project found that 13 million
people, or 14 percent of all Internet users, have downloaded free
music files from the Internet and that only 2 percent of online
users, fewer than 2 million people, have paid to download music.
</P>
<P>
   Programs like Napster and Scour Exchange create ``the impression
to users around the world that creative property has no value,''
said Carey Sherman, the RIAA's executive vice president and chief
counsel. The suit asks for damages of up to $150,000 per song or
movie downloaded from the Scour system.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to change the public perception is a deliberate
strategy on the part of the plaintiffs, but it is not likely to
work, said William Fisher, a Harvard Law School professor who
specializes in intellectual property.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are correct that once these technologies take hold it is
going to be hard to get the next generation of consumers to pay for
this stuff,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   The most relevant case is the 1984 decision in the Sony Betamax
case, in which the Supreme Court ruled that VCR manufacturers do
not violate copyright law when consumers record programs for home
viewing. By the time the case reached the Supreme Court, home
recording was a common practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher added that the heated rhetoric used in the case can be
misleading, since intellectual property is limited by duration and
by the fair use doctrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those things are obscured by this rhetoric of
shoplifting, stealing and theft, and the insistence that
intellectual property is no different than any other form of
property,'' Fisher said. ``They are hoping that intellectual
property rights will be perceived as real property rights, but I
think they will probably fail in that aspiration.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recording industry has prevailed in the courts in its
case against MP3.com, which settled financially with some of the
companies that sued it. Its case against Napster continues next
week at a hearing set for Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
