<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNACO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARNINGS AT WARNACO, MAKER OF CALVIN KLEIN JEANS, PLUMMET AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every time it appears that the Warnaco Group, the maker of
Calvin Klein jeans and underwear, has hit bottom, another shoe
drops.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Thursday that it would miss earnings
estimates by a wide margin, the third time it has done so this
year. Warnaco said operating earnings for fiscal 2000 will be 26
cents to 36 cents a share, almost $1.50 less than the average
estimate among analysts polled by First Call/Thomson Financial.
Last year, the company earned $1.90 a share. The company said there
would be a ``commensurate'' but unspecified reduction in
second-quarter net income to be announced in August.
</P>
<P>
   Distressed investors sent Warnaco's stock down $1.8125 a share
to an all-time low of $4.9375. It is now down nearly 60 percent
this year, and off 89 percent from its high of $44 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Stock analysts said that Warnaco's management team had already
lost its credibility on Wall Street and that they were not
surprised that the company's results were so far off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are analyzing the company as a distressed stock,'' said
Mathew Hershberg, who follows the company for S&AMP;P Equity Group,
adding that the manufacturer is in increasingly dire straits.
</P>
<P>
   The news put more pressure on Warnaco's already embattled chief
executive, Linda Wachner. When Warnaco announced a disappointing
quarter in May, Leon Cooperman, who owns almost 7 percent of
Warnaco privately and through his money management firm Omega
Advisors, sent a scathing letter to Warnaco's board of directors
blaming Wachner for the company's problems. So far, Wachner's board
has remained steadfastly loyal, but investor frustration, as
demonstrated by the plunging stock, is increasing.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Wachner cited a ``difficult business environment
affecting the apparel industry in general'' to explain the
company's shortfalls and asserted that Warnaco has ``more than
adequate cash flow to support our businesses.'' She was unavailable
for futher comment.
</P>
<P>
   Warnaco blamed part of its financial woes on ``negative
publicity'' surrounding a legal battle with its largest licensor,
Calvin Klein. In May, Calvin Klein Inc. sued to break its licensing
agreement with Warnaco on the grounds that the manufacturer had
tarnished the designer's trademark by producing substandard
merchandise and was distributing it through unauthorized stores
like warehouse clubs. Warnaco has countersued Klein and his
company, citing defamation and breach of good faith, and is asking
for $1 billion in damages.
</P>
<P>
   A Warnaco spokesman said that the company now anticipated a $120
million decline in revenue this year related to the Calvin Klein
publicity problems.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the earnings warning, Warnaco said Thursday that it
had refinanced debt that was coming due later this summer. The
agreements with Warnaco's creditors will extend the maturity dates
of its $500 million trade credit and $600 million bridge loan until
August 2002. The company would not disclose the terms of the
financing. But the Warnaco spokesman said that the additional
interest costs for this year alone would be $30 million, accounting
for much of the estimated earnings decline.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced it would take a $60 million after-tax
charge in connection with closing its distribution centers in
Europe and reducing its worldwide work force by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many questions about the strength of Warnaco's core
business remain unanswered, at least until the company reports its
full second-quarter results on Aug. 4. It cited softening consumer
appetite for its sportswear as part of the reason for its earnings
drop, but it was unclear which of its many brands were weak.
</P>
<P>
   Wachner had said previously that she was counting on the Speedo
and ABS by Allen Schwartz brands to provide the company with
dynamic top-line growth, and numbers for those businesses were not
made available Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With the stock plunging, Warnaco may come under increasing
pressure to take the company private or to strike a deal with one
of its many suitors, most notably the VF Corp., the maker of Lee,
which is particularly interested in adding an upscale jeans brand
like Calvin Klein.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
