<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BERTELSMANN-MUSIC-NYT     07-20 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERTELSMANN-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMANY'S BERTELSMANN BUYS CDNOW FOR $117 MILLION TO EXPAND
E-COMMERCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bertelsmann AG, the German media conglomerate, will buy CDNow
Inc., the struggling online music retailer, for $117 million in
cash, Bertelsmann said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, worth $3 for each CDNow share, will give Bertelsmann a
recognized brand in online music sales as it attempts to expand its
electronic commerce business. For CDNow, the merger ends the
company's extensive search for a partner, which intensified in
March after a merger deal with Columbia House fell through.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow, which went public in February 1998 at $16 a share, has
stumbled in the face of increasing competition, losing $119 million
last year. Its stock, which reached a high of $35.50 a share in
April 1998, closed at $2.875 a share Wednesday, the day before the
merger was announced. The stock closed at $2.92 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a savior for CDNow,'' said Aram Sinnreich, an analyst
with Jupiter Communications in New York. ``It was clear it was in
dire straits and couldn't continue doing business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   The CDNow service, which allows visitors to download music as
well as purchase tracks and CDs, was founded by twin brothers Jason
and Matthew Olim in 1994 and was an instant hit among music fans
and technology aficionados. But the site quickly lost market share
when Amazon and national music chains began selling CDs online.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its struggles, however, CDNow has managed to amass the
single largest database of qualified online music buyers, Sinnreich
said. For that reason, the acquisition instantly puts Bertelsmann,
which is based in Gutersloh, Germany, at the top of the online
music business. ``It gives them exactly what they haven't been able
to get through their own music properties, a large database of
customers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Eierhoff, a Bertelsmann board member, called the merger an
``excellent fit'' with both the company's online and traditional
music assets, not only because of CDNow's music content but because
of its strength in new digital downloading technologies.
</P>
<P>
   CDNow, whose headquarters are in Fort Washington, Pa., will
continue its current operations after the merger, the companies
said, becoming Bertelsmann's primary online music sales effort
under the leadership of Andreas Schmidt, former chief executive of
AOL Europe and current president and CEO of Bertelsmann's new
e-Commerce Group. GetMusic, an online music service that is the
result of a venture between Bertelsmann's BMG Entertainment and
Universal Music Group, will be featured on the CDNow Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Schmidt said that, among other things,
the acquisition of CDNow gives Bertelsmann a huge boost in the
emerging market for electronic music distribution, a hotly
contested subject that has pitted musicians and record companies
against Internet companies developing distribution technologies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to turn CDNow into a music commerce play and expand it
internationally, while we expand the brand onto other platforms,
like mobile and broadband,'' Schmidt said. ``Clearly, all music
content will be in digital form from here on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann's acquisition of CDNow is the latest in a recent
series of deals, which include an alliance with America Online to
distribute Bertelsmann's brands over AOL, and a separate
distribution deal with Terra Lycos.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
