<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8104 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f BC-FARNBOROUGH-SPI &LR;      07-20 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARNBOROUGH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING ANGLING TO STAY IN SPOTLIGHT AT FARNBOROUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When the world's aerospace industry gathers at the
Farnborough International air show outside of London next week,
much of the buzz will be about the Airbus A3XX super jumbo, which
could see its first firm orders.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing is planning a big show, too. And airline and
government customers won't be the only ones likely to find the
display compelling. Investors and the company's employees should
keep an eye on Farnborough.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its hot pace of commercial airplane sales this year,
Boeing will announce several billion in orders _ including a flurry
of demand for its ne super long-range 777X jets, the 777-300X and
the 777-200X.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing could announce orders for as many as two dozen of the
jets, the sources said. Such an order would be worth $4 billion to
$5 billion, based on list prices.
</P>
<P>
   And that doesn't count a possible order from International Lease
Finance Corp. for more than a dozen 777s on which negotiations
continue.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of the air show.
</P>
<P>
   Though both manufacturers deny it, Boeing and Airbus ask some of
their customers to save order announcements for either the Paris or
Farnborough air shows, which are held in alternating years. They
are the world's biggest air shows.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Paris Air Show, International Lease said it would
buy 50 next generation 737s and take options on 50 more. But it
took much of 1999 before the sales agreement was actually signed
for the first 50 planes.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Boeing is placing more importance this year
on the air show.
</P>
<P>
   Importantly, this will be Boeing Chairman Phil Condit's first
appearance at either of the big European shows since 1992, shortly
after he was named Boeing's president.
</P>
<P>
   At past shows, Boeing and Airbus staged dueling media events on
the opening day. Top executives gave presentations and answered
questions.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Farnborough show will be different.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus will hold its big media event Monday, opening day.
</P>
<P>
   Condit will not follow with the Boeing briefing until Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning Monday morning, Boeing will be conducting daily
informational briefings on products from the Super Hornet and Joint
Strike Fighter to the 747X stretch. The stretched version of the
747 could be launched within a year, depending on customer demand.
It would carry about 100 more passengers than the 416-seat 747-400.
</P>
<P>
   The company may be hoping to offset some of the attention likely
to be given to the probably star of the show, Airbus Industrie's
proposed new super-jumbo airplane, the A3XX. The huge jetliner is
seen as the first real challenge to Boeing's dominance of the jumbo
jet market with the 747.
</P>
<P>
   Though Boeing has not yet reached the stage where it is ready to
announce firm orders for its new jumbo jet _ a derivitive of the
747, Airbus may announce the first firm orders for the A3XX at
Farnborough.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus received permission just last month from its board to
begin offering the plane for sale. The first firm order for the
A3XX is expected to come from Emirates, which is one of several
airlines to publicly say they will buy the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   But even if there is no A3XX order announcement, the Europeans
are likely to capture a lot of attention because of a new aerospace
giant on the scene _ EADS, short for European Aeronautic Defense
and Space Co.
</P>
<P>
   EADS became the world's third largest aerospace entity behind
Boeing and Lockheed Martin earlier this month with the merger of
Germany's Daimler-Chrysler Aerospace (Dasa), France's Aerospatiale
Matra and Spain's Casa. Together, they own 80 percent of Airbus.
The UK's BAE Systems owns the remaining 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus itself is undergoing a dramatic transformation into a
single corporation to better compete against Boeing. Since its
creation in 1970, Airbus has operated an a consortium of European
aerospace companies. So EADS and a new Airbus will take center
stage on the opening day of the air show, against the backdrop of
the A3XX.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing will not have to wait for Condit's briefing Wednesday to
make its own noise at the show. The company has scheduled an event
for Tuesday, the second day, to ``honor'' customers for its 777X
jets.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing announced the launch of the two new versions of its
planes in February. They are targeted for Asian airlines looking
for 21st-century widebody jets that have the range to fly more than
300 passengers non-stop between Asia and the United States. The
301-seat 777-200X will be able to fly up to 10,100 miles before
refueling, and the 359-seat 777-300X will be able to fly up to
8,314 miles.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Boeing has only announced firm 777X orders from Japan
Airlines and from Taiwan's EVA Airways Corp. Sources said as many
as five or six more customers will be announced at Farnborough,
possibly as early as Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It could be the start of a very good week for Boeing. But one
that will exhaust its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an amazing experience,'' Condit said in an interview last
week when asked about air shows. ``You get almost no sleep. You eat
way too much. And you end the week totally, completed exhausted.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit said he would like to see one air show held every four
years, just like the Olympics. Cities would bid for the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would all go and it would be one heck of an event,'' Condit
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Airshows were conceived when the technology rate was much
higher,'' he said. ``There were new programs every year. There were
always new things to see. That isn't the world we are in, either on
the defense side or the civil side.''
</P>
<P>
   The Farnborough show will showcase the competition among
manurfacturers, all right. But, like most shows of the current age,
this one is less about competing new technologies than the
years-old race between Boeing and Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   And that's about market share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
