u v BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      07-20 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, July 21. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-SURVEY (Washington) _ Despite the confidence displayed
by Gov. George W. Bush's campaign, the presidential election stands
as a very competitive contest. An analysis of opinion polls state
by state, along with interviews with Republican and Democratic
strategists in the campaigns and around the country, found enough
crucial states that are so competitive that midsummer events and
the fall debates could overturn the current standings in state
after state. By Adam Clymer and Richard L. Berke. (We plan to move
the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo NYT15 and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Top center: 2-column reefer photo to CLINTON-G8; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Thurmont, Md.) _ With President Clinton's
departure for Japan, the energy drained from the
Israeli-Palestinian peace summit as the exhausted delegations slept
late and then worked with the U.S. team to determine how to move
beyond the impasse and the mutual accusations of bad faith. By
Deborah Sontag. (Scheduled to move by 8:45 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.) 1,800 words.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   GENETIC-TESTING (Undated) _ As genetic testing becomes available
for a growing array of health conditions, those who choose to learn
their own genetic risks, and the health professionals who treat
them, are facing increasingly difficult decisions about how and
whether to share the results with family members who carry some of
the genes. By Tamar Lewin. (The story has moved in ``a'' news
file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRIDE (Houston) _ For months, Vice President Al Gore and
other national Democrats have depicted George W. Bush's Texas as a
problem-plagued state. Pollution? Gore says Texas is the most
polluted state in America. Poverty? Gore says that too many of
Texas' people are poor and that the state does too little for them.
Not surprisingly, Texans, a prideful lot who take a brighter view
of things, are offended. By Jim Yardley. (Scheduled to move by 8
p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE (New York) _ After a five-year climb, the number of
legal claims filed against New York City that accuse police
officers of using excessive force or other misconduct has dropped
sharply, according to statistics kept by the city comptroller's
office. By Kevin Flynn. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a''
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   3-column New York day photo.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-INDICTMENTS (Undated) _ A federal grand jury indicts two
former Salt Lake City Olympics officials on charges of conspiracy
and interstate travel in aid of racketeering for their alleged
roles in paying $1 million to help win the 2002 Winter Games. By
Jere Longman. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEUTRINOS (Undated) _ What many physicists consider to be
one of the last pieces of the puzzle that explains the structure of
matter has been detected at the Fermi National Accelerator
Laboratory near Chicago. A team of international scientists are
expected to announce that they have detected what is considered to
be the most elusive member of nature's most ghostly family of
particles, the tau neutrino. By James Glanz. (Scheduled to move by
8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN-ECON (Washington) _ Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan says
there is not yet enough evidence to conclude that the economy has
slowed to a non-inflationary pace, and he leaves the door open to
further interest rate increases as soon as next month. By Richard
W. Stevenson. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN-IQ (Undated) _ Addressing a longstanding debate among
scientists over how much of the brain is activated to perform a
difficult task like taking an IQ test, researchers have found that
a surprisingly small and specific region of gray matter may be the
brain's master problem solver. By Natalie Angier. (Scheduled to
move by 8:15 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   GENETICS-PROTEST (Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y.) _ Vandals mowed down
a cornfield last week that the late geneticist Barbara McClintock
started in the 1940s to do the Nobel-winning research that laid the
groundwork for today's genome work. Officials at the Cold Spring
Harbor Lab see it as part of a disturbing outbreak of
``eco-terrorism'' around the country _ about 30 incidents of
vandalism and arson that have been kept quiet because scientists
don't want to encourage copycat attacks. By Michael Cooper.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.) 1,300 words.
</P>
