u s BC-CYC-TOUR-NOTES0721-CO     07-20 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-NOTES0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Special guests
 &HT;    By Suzanne Halliburton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb, one of Lance Armstrong's main sponsors,
has picked up the tab for nine cancer survivors to take in the
final five stages of the Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers created the chemotherapy drugs that successfully
treated Armstrong's advanced testicular cancer four years ago. The
company's relationship with Armstrong also has evolved during the
past year into the company's sponsorship of the U.S. Postal Service
team.
</P>
<P>
   John Kouten, a Bristol-Myers spokesman, said the company
received numerous VIP passes for the Tour as part of its
sponsorship of the Postal team. Rather than giving the passes to
corporate executives, the company within the past eight weeks
selected nine people who have some connection to Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong will sign the Charter of Paris Against Cancer Sunday
night after his now expected Tour victory. The charter was started
at the World Summitt Against Cancer in Paris on Feb. 4. Armstrong's
signature will be among more than 100 other international leaders
and celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody can sign the document, which calls for expanded
commitment to cancer, by logging onto www.CharterAgainstCancer.org.
</P>
<P>
   TOO MANY PEOPLE
</P>
<P>
   Local police estimated that up to 1.5 million people watched
Thursday's stage between Lausanne, Switzerland and Freiburg,
Germany. That would make the crowd the largest to watch a
non-mountain stage since the Tour visited Valkenbourg, Holland in
1992. In fact, the mayor of Valkenbourg was in Freiburg on Thursday
trying to talk Tour officials into bringing another stage back to
his city.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour typically draws about 11 million spectators each year.
Another 2 million fans in France watch the Tour coverage each day
on television. The coverage is not interrupted by commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular Tour stages are the ones in the mountains,
where people camp out days in advance to get a good viewing spot.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELOGUE
</P>
<P>
   The Freiburg Cathedral is probably the most prominent landmark
in this 1,000-year-old town that once was part of France and
Austria. The cathedral is more than 700 years old, with its tower
going up almost 400 feet. It is called locally the ``Unser Liben
Frowen Bauw,'' which in German means ``Building of the Blessed
Virgin.'' It was one of the few churches of its kind built in the
Middle Ages. One historian described it as the most beautiful
cathedral of its kind in all Christendom.
</P>
<P>
   The cathedral survived the intense bombing Freiburg received in
World War I. The city also was the site of accidental bombing by
German troops in 1940, in which 57 locals were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
