<SLUG> BC-DELTA-EARNINGS0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta's record volume yields $1 billion profit
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Packed planes offset higher fuel costs to lift Delta
Air Lines' fourth-quarter profit 3 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta-based carrier also finished its fiscal year, which
ended June 30, with a third consecutive annual profit of about $1
billion. It boarded a record 117 million passengers for the year,
more than any other airline in the world, although it remains
third-biggest as measured by revenue passenger miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamental demand for air travel is really terrific,'' said
Chairman and Chief Executive Leo Mullin, who has led Delta since
1997. ``Obviously everybody is seeing it in crowded airplanes, but
that translates into financial performance.''
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance on CNBC, Mullin also said the government has
failed to deliver on promised improvements in the air traffic
control system, producing more weather-related delays this summer
in some parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we're in for a tough summer. Our delays are up
quite substantially, particularly in the Northeast,'' he said.
Unusually dry weather in the Southeast has spared Delta's Atlanta
hub somewhat, although delays in the Northeast affect the whole
system.
</P>
<P>
   For its fourth quarter, Delta posted net income of $376 million,
or $2.86 a share, excluding one-time items, compared with $364
million, or $2.40 per share a year earlier. The results top the
First Call consensus analysts' forecast of $2.72 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue for the quarter increased to $4.47 billion vs. $3.92
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of a gallon of jet fuel rose to 60 cents from
51 cents a year earlier, a 17.6 percent jump. Operating profit
margin for the quarter slipped to 15.4 percent from 16.2 percent,
as unit costs rose 4.9 percent to 9.38 cents per available
seat-mile.
</P>
<P>
   Delta has been hurt less than other airlines by higher fuel
costs, as it negotiated ``hedging'' contracts prior to the runup in
oil prices. Those contracts begin lapsing later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Delta had a non-cash gain of $228 million related to stock
holdings in Internet seat-seller Priceline.com. It took an $86
million charge for an early retirement offer taken by 2,500
employees. With those items, quarterly profit was $460 million, or
$3.51 a share.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year, Delta posted a $1.02 billion profit
excluding special items, vs. $1.08 billion a year earlier.
Operating profit margin dipped to 11.7 percent, from 12.7 percent a
year earlier as unit costs rose 2 percent to 9.07 cents per
available seat-mile.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers posted better-than-expected quarterly earnings
earlier this week, although a warning from United about weaker
third-quarter results sent airline stocks skidding Wednesday. Delta
shares regained some of the loss Thursday, rising 25 cents Thursday
to $53.88.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
