<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMYS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `West Wing' vs. mob as Emmy tries to sharpen edge
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer and Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the summer of ``Survivor,'' Thursday's Emmy nominations
looked back on a television season in which not a single rat was
consumed in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   For the scorekeepers, freshman drama ``The West Wing'' and HBO's
``The Sopranos'' led all nominees with 18 each. HBO's movie ``RKO
218,'' about Orson Welles, had 13 nominations, ABC's musical
``Annie'' got 12, and HBO's ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge'' and
NBC sitcom ``Will &AMP; Grace'' had 11 each.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had the most nominations with 97 followed by HBO (86), ABC
(64), CBS (41) and Fox (26).
</P>
<P>
   ``Ally McBeal,'' which won best comedy last year, wasn't even
nominated this year. Shut out of major categories: ``The X-Files''
(once a favorite) and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (as always).
</P>
<P>
   We don't have a vote, but following are some thoughts on who
should win and who will win this year's Emmys. (Editor's note: our
critics had different thoughts in some categories, so their names
and comments accompany those picks.)
</P>
<P>
   Also, handicapping the winners this year is more difficult than
in the past. The Emmys are changing the voting process, a result of
building criticism over safe, repeat choices (Dennis Franz of
``NYPD Blue'' recently, and before that, Candice Bergen for
``Murphy Brown''), and last year's selection of ``The Practice''
over ``The Sopranos,'' which many called a travesty.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Emmy relied on volunteer members of the National
Academy of Television Arts and Sciences to screen submitted videos
at a hotel over a weekend. A frequent criticism was that only the
retired and unemployed members had time to do this and edgier shows
lost out.
</P>
<P>
   This year, volunteers will screen videos at home on their own
time. The academy says this will increase the pool of voters and
possibly yield more daring winners, but some wonder if members will
just vote for their favorite shows and skip the viewing.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find out beginning at 8 p.m. Sept. 10 on ABC with host
Garry Shandling. For now, our picks:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Best drama.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``ER'' (NBC); ``Law &AMP; Order'' (NBC); ``The Practice''
(ABC); ``The Sopranos'' (HBO); ``The West Wing'' (NBC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: Emmy likes the center stripe in the road.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Jubera says ``The West Wing''; Kloer picks ``The
Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Both pick ``The West Wing:'' Says Jubera: Once in
a while, Emmy gets one right. Kloer thinks it is
</P>
<P>
   just the kind of solid, middle-brow drama that gets Emmy's seal.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Best comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS); ``Frasier'' (NBC);
``Friends'' (NBC); ``Sex and the City'' (HBO); ``Will &AMP; Grace''
(NBC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: There's still laughs left in the ol' sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (Jubera); ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' (Kloer).
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Both say ``Everybody Loves Raymond.'' Jubera: Is
asking Emmy to get two right asking too much? Probably. Kloer: Its
popularity and (belated) Emmy recognition seem to be tracking
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Drama lead actor.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Dennis Franz, ``NYPD Blue'' (ABC); James Gandolfini,
``The Sopranos'' (HBO); Jerry Orbach, ``Law &AMP; Order'' (NBC); Martin
Sheen, ``The West Wing'' (NBC); Sam Waterston, ``Law &AMP; Order''
(NBC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: Emmy acknowledges a range of actors, from the
exquisitely pedestrian (Orbach) to the subtly melodramatic (Franz)
to the exquisitely subtle (Gandolfini).
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Sheen _ perfectly presidential (Jubera).
Gandolfini _ So good, he's scary; so scary, he's good (Kloer).
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Both say Sheen _ unless Emmy makes up to
Gandolfini for blowing it last year.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Drama lead actress.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Lorraine Bracco, ``The Sopranos'' (HBO); Amy
Brenneman, ``Judging Amy'' (CBS); Edie Falco, ``The Sopranos''
(HBO); Julianna Margulies, ``ER'' (NBC); Sela Ward, ``Once and
Again'' (ABC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: Not a dewy-eyed starlet in the bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: All of them (Jubera). Falco (Kloer).
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Jubera says Brenneman _ she's judge and jury.
Kloer: Ward _ female voters want to be her, male voters just want
her.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Comedy lead actor.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Michael J. Fox, ``Spin City'' (ABC); Kelsey Grammer,
``Frasier'' (NBC); John Lithgow, ``3rd Rock from the Sun'' (NBC);
Eric McCormack, ``Will &AMP; Grace'' (NBC); Ray Romano, ``Everybody
Loves Raymond'' (CBS).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: Comedy's not dead. But it's hurting.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Fox, for all the right sentimental reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Fox _ bet the house on it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Comedy lead actress.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Jenna Elfman, ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' (ABC); Patricia
Heaton, ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS); Jane Kaczmarek,
``Malcolm in the Middle'' (Fox); Debra Messing, ``Will &AMP; Grace''
(NBC); Sarah Jessica Parker, ``Sex and the City'' (HBO).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: The future of comedy is here.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Kaczmarek, the new anti-Donna Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Elfman. The new Queen of Comedy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Drama supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Michael Badalucco, ``The Practice'' (ABC); Dominic
Chianese, ``The Sopranos'' (HBO); Steve Harris, ``The Practice''
(ABC); Richard Schiff, ``The West Wing'' (NBC); John Spencer, ``The
West Wing'' (NBC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: You can get a nod without being close to a
household name.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Chianese, Schiff, Spencer or Harris. (Jubera).
Schiff, whose Toby is the moral center of ``West Wing.'' (Kloer)
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Jubera says Badalucco: It wouldn't be the Emmys
without blowing at least one category. Kloer: Schiff.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Drama supporting actress.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Stockard Channing, ``The West Wing'' (NBC); Tyne Daly,
``Judging Amy'' (CBS); Allison Janney, ``The West Wing'' (NBC);
Nancy Marchand, ``The Sopranos'' (HBO); Holland Taylor, ``The
Practice'' (ABC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: They're even older than the best actress
nominees
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Janney, the most sympathetic press secretary in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: The late Marchand, in fitting tribute.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Category: Comedy supporting actor.
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Peter Boyle, ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS); Brad
Garrett, ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS); Sean Hayes, ``Will &AMP;
Grace'' (NBC); Peter MacNicol, ``Alley McBeal'' (Fox); David Hyde
Pierce, ``Frasier'' (NBC).
</P>
<P>
   What they mean: Everybody loves ``Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Hayes (Jubera). Garrett, for a memorable season
(KloeUse By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
