<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When it comes to shoes, the sky's the limit
 &HT;    By Erin Coyle
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta women, like women everywhere, can't have enough shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Take, as a possible example, Atlanta's former chief investment
officer, Theresa Stanford. Federal prosecutors said Wednesday that
in a kickback scheme involving her husband's company, she received
a credit card and charged $30,000 in shoes over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to believe any woman would need so many? Remember Imelda
Marcos?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have 150 pairs of shoes. I just love shoes,'' says
Carylon Brown, 58, of Atlanta. She generally buys one or two pairs
every two months for $75-$100 each, although she's already bought
three pairs in July. And she has several that still have price tags
on them.
</P>
<P>
   But $30,000 in four years? It's possible.
</P>
<P>
   A good pair at Bob Ellis Shoes, an upscale store in Phipps
Plaza, costs anywhere from $200 to $400, says Jim Whitlow, vice
president. Really high fashion shoes can go for more than $2,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have customers that buy 20 to 30 to 40 pairs of shoes a
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Erna Martino of Atlanta just laughs when she's asked how many
shoes she owns. She says you never ask a woman that.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmm. Has anyone told the federal prosecutor that?
</P>
<P>
   Erin Coyle writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
