<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roundup of weekend TV options
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dateline NBC'' (9 p.m. on NBC) _ Correspondent Sara James
anchors an hourlong show on the aftermath of the Columbine High
School shooting, focusing on student Craig Scott and his family,
and how they have dealt with what happened.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sound Affects'' (10 p.m. on VH1) _ In the premiere of this
VH1 series, everyday folks talk about how a rock song or singer
inspired them to overcome adversity. I once played Cheap Trick's
``Surrender'' 28 times in a row in a small apartment but instead of
overcoming adversity, I created it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dennis Miller Live'' (11:30 p.m. on HBO) Kevin Bacon is the
guest, which instantly elevates Miller to a major player in the
``Six Degrees of ...'' game.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Hollywood Dream Jobs'' (3 p.m. on E!) _ For every guy who
gets to be part of Leo DiCaprio's posse, there's some poor schlub
who has to shave Tom Arnold's back.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ice'' (1998, 8 p.m. on ABC)_ Last Saturday, ABC's movie was
about a hole in the ozone that caused unbearable heat. This week
it's a movie about a new Ice Age, starring Grant Show (``Melrose
Place'') and Eva Larue (La Who?) Callahan. Somebody's been reading
their Robert Frost (``Some say the world will end in fire/ Some say
in ice'').
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Anne of Green Gables: The Continuing Story'' (9 p.m. on
WGTV) _ The final part of this beloved family-oriented trilogy
makes its PBS debut, returning Megan Follows to the role of Anne
Shirley, now an adult during the World War I era. It concludes July
30.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Strong Medicine'' (9 p.m. on Lifetime) _ Janine Turner,
still best known as bush pilot Maggie on ``Northern Exposure,''
returns to series TV. She looks startlingly different here, with
long dark hair and a more sculpted face. Anyway, she plays a
well-heeled Philadelphia surgeon who's dragged into helping at a
struggling women's clinic run by Dr. Delgado (Rosa Blasi). Whoopi
Goldberg, who co-produces this new series, guest-stars in the pilot
as the all-knowing medicine woman who brings them together.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ellen DeGeneres: The Beginning'' (10 p.m. on HBO) _ Yup,
she's on HBO. DeGeneres goes back to her stand-up roots with an
hourlong routine that she honed all over the country in recent
months, including a stop at Atlanta's Symphony Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``There's Something About Mary'' (8 tonight on HBO) _ OK,
maybe it didn't deserve to win an Oscar for best picture. But
surely it should have at least been nominated for best makeup, for
Chris Elliott's hideous case of progressive hives. 118m.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Next Karate Kid'' (1994, 9 p.m. Saturday on the Disney
Channel) _ Five years before she was the toast of the film industry
for ``Boys Don't Cry,'' young Hilary Swank first came to attention
as the female replacement for Ralph Macchio in the ``Karate Kid''
franchise. She kicks some major, uh, you know. 104m.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Brothers Garcia'' (8:30 p.m. Sunday on Nickelodeon).
</P>
<P>
   With the broadcast networks continuing to treat Latino
characters with all the open-armed welcome of a Pat Buchanan rally,
Nickelodeon comes along with this snappy little comedy that gets it
all right.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brothers Garcia'' is no mere sop to diversity, it's an
amusing comedy (with no laugh track!) that has the makings of a
``Malcolm in the Middle.'' Like ``Malcolm,'' it's about a large,
wacky family, told from the point of view of one young son, in this
case 11-year-old Larry, looking back as an adult (with narration by
John Leguizamo, a la Daniel Stern's voice-overs in ``The Wonder
Years'').
</P>
<P>
   The ethnic ``angle'' is present, but not emphasized very much
(in the pilot, we never learn the Garcias' specific heritage).
There's a reference to Dad's super-duper salsa (cut to stock
footage of an atomic bomb when the jar is opened) and such, but
``Garcia'' is accessible to families of any heritage, and enjoyable
enough that parents will actually want to watch this new Nick treat
with their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Worst Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Getting Away With Murder: The JonBenet Ramsey Story''
</P>
<P>
   (9 tonight on Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Getting away with murder is what Fox is doing, re-running this
February sweeps piece of horse-hockey. Not even up to the standards
of a ``real'' docudrama, this rancid little show presents two
``detectives'' named Detective Guilty and Inspector Innocent, with
theories as to how Ramsey's parents did or did not kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
