<HEADER>
A8113 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-WESTNILE21-COX     07-20 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WESTNILE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Killer virus under surveillance
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention on Thursday
published explicit guidelines for areas where birds infected with
the West Nile virus are found.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, that includes only the greater New York area,
where the imported African virus surfaced last summer, sickening at
least 62 people and killing seven. So far this summer, 26 infected
birds _ 21 crows, four blue jays and a hawk _ have been found in
five counties in New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   West Nile has not yet appeared in Georgia _ the furthest south
that an infected bird has been discovered was a crow found dead in
Maryland last fall _ but public-health authorities predict that it
will inevitably arrive via birds flying south on migratory
pathways.
</P>
<P>
   The virus, which was never seen in the U.S. before August 1999,
is transmitted by mosquitos from the infected birds to horses and
humans. In a small percentage of cases, the virus causes a
potentially fatal swelling of the brain and spinal cord for which
there is no known treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Areas where the virus has been found should take these steps,
the CDC said:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Intensify surveillance and tracking of the virus through
programs including mosquito trapping, analyzing dead birds, and
maintaining ``sentinel flocks'' of chickens whose blood is checked
periodically for the virus.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reinforce publicly funded mosquito-control efforts, including
killing mosquito larvae and ground spraying for adult mosquitos
within two miles of any area where infected birds or mosquitos are
found.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Consider spraying insecticides from the air in areas where
transmission of West Nile to humans is confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Educate the public about the need to eliminate standing water
(which mosquitos use for breeding) near homes, and advise the
public to use insect repellents and protective clothing in areas
where the virus has been found.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia has already received CDC funding to set up a West Nile
surveillance program; the Division of Public Health has urged
residents to contact local health departments if they find birds
for whose death there is no obvious explanation (such as a
collision with a building).
</P>
<P>
   Though West Nile has not been found here, ``It is always
appropriate to look around your home to see if there are good
breeding sites for mosquitos present, such as stagnant water in
puddles or unused pools, or water in discarded tires,'' said Dr.
Stephen Ostroff, associate director of CDC's National Center for
Infectious Diseases and federal coordinator of the anti-West Nile
campaign. ``It is prudent for people to remove any standing water
to prevent mosquitos from breeding. And should they want to further
reduce their risk, it is appropriate for them to wear insect
repellents and protective clothing outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
