A8114 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ISRAEL-     07-20 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS TAKE NEGOTIATIONS ROLLER COASTER IN STRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (with MIDEAST-TALKS) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ For a moment early Thursday morning, when she heard
the announcement that the Camp David talks had ended with no
agreement, Gaby Bar-Zakai breathed easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt relieved,'' recalled Bar-Zakai, who lives in Maaleh
Adumim, a sprawling Israeli suburb of Jerusalem in the West Bank.
``I was very concerned that if the talks didn't break up, the
Israeli concessions would be total.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the news that the talks would continue after all, and
Bar-Zakai seesawed back to reality. By Thursday night she was more
sober.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was clear to me that things would swing back and forth,''
she said as she savored a warm summer evening with friends at a
sidewalk cafe in downtown Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm skeptical,'' she said, ``because I don't think the
Palestinians are ripe for a comprehensive agreement. But I think
there will be a partial accord, because both sides have no other
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day after the last-minute reversal at Camp David,
Israelis kept a watchful eye on developments, but they were not
holding their breath.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to the ups and downs of negotiations with the
Palestinians after years of tortuous talks, people seemed unruffled
by the latest cliff-hanger, as they tried to get on with ordinary
lives in extraordinary times.
</P>
<P>
   Everything seemed the same Thursday in Jerusalem, but it was
not. For the first time, an Israeli prime minister had negotiated
with the Palestinians on the future of the city, which Israel has
always claimed as its indivisible capital _ and it was going over
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are apathetic; they're too busy with their daily
lives,'' said Avi Mizrahi, 23, as he sat on a park bench with a
friend. He allowed that he was no fan of Prime Minister Ehud Barak,
who was ``just doing everything to earn a place in the history
books, without a coalition or proper support.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barak's efforts seem to have the quiet support of many
liberal Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting their views, the newspaper Haaretz said: ``Barak
should be congratulated for his readiness to smash the taboo on
negotiations over Jerusalem. The Camp David summit 2000 will be
recorded as the first occasion in which Israelis and Palestinians
tried to touch the dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   Meron Benvenisti, an expert on the Palestinian-Israeli conflict,
wrote in Haaretz that ``the very fact that the taboo has been
broken and Israel is holding a discussion on Jerusalem that means
division of the city'' is ``an act from which there can be no
return.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk shows were dominated by discussions on solutions for
Jerusalem, and some callers from the city said they supported plans
to put Arab neighborhoods under Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Long-repeated assertions by Israeli politicians that Jerusalem
would remain Israel's united and eternal capital seemed to be
giving way to a more pragmatic public debate about the city's
future.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing the shift, Ariel Sharon, the leader of the opposition
Likud Party, accused Barak on Thursday of giving up too much,
creating ``impossible starting lines for any future negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak had ``already given Arafat a deposit, and we will have to
work hard to erase the withdrawal lines drawn by Barak on the map
at Camp David,'' Sharon said. ``These will be the starting lines
for the next Palestinian demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Natan Sharansky, who left Barak's cabinet in protest over the
summit meeting, sent a letter to the prime minister, urging him to
submit any agreement on Jerusalem for approval by Jewish leaders,
as well as by Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a tent near Barak's office, Sharansky is advocating
formation of a broad government that would include opposition
parties, in order to reach a wide consensus on peace moves.
</P>
<P>
   Founders of the Jewish settlement movement have set up their own
tent nearby, where they are holding a hunger strike for the
duration of the summit meeting. Thursday scores of settlers swayed
there in prayer on a religious fast day that carried added
significance for them.
</P>
<P>
   The fast commemorates the breaching of the walls of Jerusalem
before the destruction of the first Jewish temple by the
Babylonians in 587 B.C. and the second temple by the Romans in A.D.
70. Barak's plans for the city, the settlers assert, are tantamount
to another destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
