<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8117 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-BRAIN-IQ-ART-770(     07-20 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BRAIN-IQ-ART-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS REPORT FINDING THE BRAIN'S `POWER CENTER' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England, Colo., N.J., Mass., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NATALIE ANGIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Addressing a longstanding debate among scientists over how much
of the brain is activated to perform a difficult task like taking
an IQ test, researchers have found that a surprisingly small and
specific region of gray matter may be the brain's master problem
solver.
</P>
<P>
   The results suggest that the venerable ``seat of human
intelligence'' is less of a throne in dimensions than a footstool.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Duncan of the Cognition and Brain Science Unit of the
Medical Research Council in Cambridge, England, and his colleagues
are reporting their results in Friday's issue of the journal
Science. In their research, the team conducted brain scans of
people who were asked to solve diverse IQ-type questions, including
spatial problems that required looking at four geometric images on
a display monitor and trying to figure out which did not fit with
the others. They were also assigned verbal tasks that involved
finding patterns to complex sequences of letters.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists wondered whether large areas of the brain would
light up on their scans as the subjects sweated and figuratively
gnawed on their No. 2 pencils, or whether a limited locus of the
brain would prove to be the intellect's central headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, the same confined region was activated whether
the subjects were tackling verbal or spatial problems. The region
in question, called the lateral prefrontal cortex, comes in pairs,
one for each hemisphere of the brain. It is somewhat above the
outer edge of the eyebrow, and corresponds roughly to where someone
would rest his head in the palm of the hand when cogitating or
daydreaming.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same region of the brain that previous neuroimaging
studies had shown to be important for solving novel tasks, keeping
many things in mind at once, and screening out irrelevant
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing here seems to be a global work space for
organizing and coordinating information and carrying it back to
other parts of the brain as needed,'' Duncan said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   It is the relative performance of this cerebral work space, he
said, that intelligence tests appear to measure, and that
determines how deft a person is at solving a broad array range of
cognitive problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are blessed with a work space that functions very,
very well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he and his colleagues see this region of the brain as so
crucial to high-level thinking that they boldly titled their report
``A Neural Basis for General Intelligence.'' But their neuroimaging
studies do not answer incendiary questions like whether current
standardized tests ``really'' measure intelligence, or are
culturally or otherwise biased. Nor does the research say anything
about whether the performance of the lateral prefrontal cortex is
largely innate or is heavily influenced by learning and experience.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan and his co-workers have yet to see if there are
detectable differences in the response of the lateral prefrontal
cortex in people who tend to score high on standardized tests
compared with those who do not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a misinterpretation of this paper to say, `There's
a genius spot in the brain,' '' said Dr. Marie T. Banich, a
cognitive neuroscientist at the University of Colorado in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert J. Sternberg, a psychologist at Yale who wrote a
``Perspectives'' essay to accompany the new study, said in an
interview: ``This is a very narrow view of intelligence. Many
psychologists are obsessed with IQ-type tests, but such tests don't
tell you who is going to be successful in life and who isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out in his Perspectives piece that Vice President Al
Gore, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and former Sen. Bill Bradley all
scored just middling-well on the verbal portion of the College
Boards, yet all, he said, would be considered exceptionally
successful Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Many neuroscientists said they were impressed with the Duncan
study.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an intriguing study,'' said Dr. Jonathan D. Cohen, a
professor of psychology and director of the Center for the Study of
Brain, Mind and Behavior at Princeton. ``Duncan asks the question,
is there some kind of underlying common mechanism that is
`intelligence,' or is intelligence a fractionable set of cognitive
processes that differ according to different skills, domains, or
talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he found was very similar brain areas were engaged in
what appear to be very different problem-solving tasks,'' Cohen
said. ``This draws our attention to a relatively well-defined area
over the vast expanse of the brain.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Duncan's research specifically tested two hoary and competing
hypotheses of general intelligence by two British psychologists.
One, formulated by Charles Spearman in the early 1900s, proposed
that there was a general factor, dubbed the ``g-factor,'' that
allowed a person to perform well in a diverse array of cognitive
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, Godfrey Thomson suggested that any difficult
cognitive task required the contribution of multiple
``information-processors'' in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   The Duncan team tested 60 participants ages 29 to 51 on a range
of tasks, some requiring intensive problem-solving skills _ the IQ
test questions _ and others simpler in nature.
</P>
<P>
   As they worked, the subjects' brains were scanned with positron
emission tomography, or PET scan devices. Such scanning technology
is considered an older method of neuroimaging than the now
fashionable fast magnetic resonance imaging technique, but Duncan
said that the studies were begun before the advent of fast MRI, and
that their future research, including efforts to detect differences
in the lateral prefrontal cortex between high-IQ and low-IQ
subjects, will be based on MRI scans. Neural scans measure relative
blood flow in the brain, an indication of how vigorously a region
is being recruited into action.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan admitted that he anticipated the Spearman hypothesis
would be borne out by neural imaging, and that therefore he was not
terribly surprised by his results.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say I was prejudiced,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the spatial problems, the lateral prefrontal
cortex was activated in both hemispheres of the brain, whereas for
verbal problems, only the left kicked in. Scientists cannot say
whether this reflects the fact that verbal ability is thought to be
mostly left-hemispheric in nature, or because the average person
has an easier time thinking verbally than spatially and therefore
needs to use only half the cortical energy to attack the verbal
challenge. Additionally, the spatial problems recruited some spots
of the brain thought to be involved in visual analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Neuroscientists said the most striking result was the activation
of the same patch of the left hemisphere lateral prefrontal cortex
for both verbal and spatial tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most important is that you see very nice convergence in
this area for two different types of problems,'' said Banich.
</P>
<P>
   The results lend weight to the idea that the brain is modular in
its construction, built of various regions or loci that carry out
highly specialized functions, like recognizing faces or large
landmarks in the environment, or categorizing apples, bananas and
grapes as fruits. At the same time, the lateral prefrontal cortex
appears to be a master integrator of tasks and input _ a cognitive
lumper rather than a splitter, as it were.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lateral prefrontal cortex is a region that receives a lot
of converging information, both external and internal,'' said Dr.
Earl K. Miller, a professor of neuroscience at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology. ``It's the most well-connected part of the
brain. If there is going to be a general mechanism for
intelligence, you'd expect it to be in a region where a lot of
information converges.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuroscientists also emphasize that, despite its modularity, the
brain is extremely plastic and dynamic.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to think of intelligence as static, and the
g-factor as something fixed and immutable,'' said Dr. William T.
Greenough, a neuroscientist at the University of Illinois in
Urbana-Champaign. But his research with rats has shown that putting
them in a stimulus-rich environment improves their performance on
all sorts of tests that might be thought of as the rodent
equivalent of the College Boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brain is very responsive to experience,'' Greenough said.
``It is an ever-changing place.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
