<HEADLINE>
LEADERS' DECISION TO STAY SEEN AS A COMPLIMENT TO CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ The first sign of unfolding drama flashed across
a police scanner. ``Prepare for POTUS movement,'' warned a Secret
Service agent at Camp David just after 10 p.m., using shorthand to
say the President of the United States was on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcade was up and running. President Clinton was leaving
for Japan. By 10:30 p.m., US officials informed the Middle East
leaders in their cabins, and within half an hour it was broadcast
around the world: Despite nine days of intensive negotiations, the
peace summit called to end more than a half-century of conflict had
fallen apart.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden turnabout that followed stunned even veterans of the
tumultous politics of the Middle East. Yet early Thursday, as
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat took the remarkable step of remaining at Camp David in
Clinton's absence, it appeared the two men had reached the same
conclusion at once: Going home empty-handed would be worse than
staying put.
</P>
<P>
   And in a brief one-hour window, as Clinton changed clothes and
packed, Arafat and Barak made a last-minute decision that could yet
decide the course of the Middle East peace process. To many
involved, it was not only a relief but also a surprise, capping a
chaotic day of brinkmanship and verbal crossfire that included
Barak packing his bags and announcing he was storming out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must admit, this is like riding a rollercoaster,'' Israeli
Immigration Minister Yuli Tamir said Thursday. ``Every minute is
different from the last.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides, under intense domestic pressures not to cede too
much, had made progress on certain issues during more than a week
and a half of meetings. In particular, officials said they had
found common ground on two of the four core issues at stake: How to
handle some 3 million Palestinian refugees and their descendents,
and the return of some portion of the West Bank that Israel
captured in the 1967 Six-Day War.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton's departure loomed late Wednesday, they were
reportedly deadlocked on the most explosive subject, control over
the holy city of Jerusalem, and even a ``last push'' from Clinton
could not bring the leaders closer to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   While Israeli delegates packed their bags and loaded them onto
trucks, Clinton shuttled between the two camps for three to five
hours, using ``every ounce of his power of persuasion that he had
available, and then some that he didn't know he had'' to persuade
the leaders to reach an agreement, White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart said. Clinton ultimately gave up at around 9 p.m.,
retreating to his own cabin as negotiators stayed on to complete a
final round of talks with Barak and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates bid each other farewell over dinner, one US official
said.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher called his wife and
said he'd be home by midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton changed into a dark suit and a blue tie, preparing to
drive to the White House to announce that talks had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luggage was loaded. The motorcade was assembled in front of
the President's cabin,'' Lockhart said. ``We were ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was still a lingering possibility. According to US
officials, the decision for Arafat and Barak to stay was not
initiated by either side, nor the result of harsh arm-twisting by
Clinton in the 11th hour. Lockhart said ``the notion of staying had
been kicked around throughout the evening,'' implying the idea came
from both Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't march into a room and say, `Here, we've got an
idea, let's try this,' '' Lockhart said. ``Conversations continued.
And in the period in which we were preparing to leave I think
there, in the President's mind, was an opportunity and an
opportunity to be seized.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamir, the Israeli Cabinet minister, who has been in Washington
over the past week, said the decision on the Israeli side came not
out of a belief that any progress had been made, or because of any
sign that Arafat might make concessions. Instead, it was ``really
out of respect and deep appreciation for what Clinton had done in
order to convene the summit and negotiate a peace agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a decision on the part of the Israeli delegation to
give it another chance,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although both leaders could gain support among hard-liners by
standing firm in their positions, Barak had said all along he would
remain at Camp David for up to two weeks to reach a real
compromise, and Arafat indicated he would consider staying longer
at the beginning of the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are all staying at Camp David. I don't know for how long,
but we are hopeful they would reach agreement,'' Hassan
Abdel-Rahman, the Palestine Liberation Organization's
representative in Washington, told Reuters. ``As long as there are
negotiations, there is hope to clinch a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to return on Sunday night from Japan, where
he is attending the G-8 summit of industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, as the atmosphere relaxed at Camp David, US
Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright Thursday took charge of
the talks, holding meetings with negotiating teams all day.
Boucher, the State Department spokesman, said ``the same pattern
and intensity will be maintained'' during Clinton's absence,
although several officials said they expected the teams to now work
at a somewhat slower pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is looking to put together, as much as we can, the
positions of the parties and see how we can move all the issues
forward,'' he said. ``So the determination is there. . . . She's
here to carry the ball forward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
