<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS FEEL THEY GAVE ONE AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thursday's visitors to Yankee Stadium would be
forgiven if the baseball game passed unnoticed, if they were
distracted by the parade of soft snow-white clouds outlined in
blue. Midsummer felt like early fall, incredibly.
</P>
<P>
   But the ballgame passed by the New York Yankees, as well. One
moment they had a comfortable lead and their pitcher was
dominating. Soon they were in their clubhouse, puzzled, trying to
understand how they lost to the Detroit Tigers, 5-3. It is a
recurring theme for the Yankees, who have repeatedly failed to
break away from other contenders in the mediocre American League
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like our pockets were picked,'' said Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager.
</P>
<P>
   Being the object of theft is a passive act. The Yankees played
an active role in this defeat, their 41st in 90 games this year; it
should have never, ever come to that.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (43-49) is without Tony Clark and Juan Gonzalez _ both
sluggers are on the disabled list _ and the Tigers are playing
mostly with journeymen. They came to New York on a 36-hour road
trip, a poor team that could be taken out easily. Roger Clemens
struck out 11 Tigers over eight innings on Wednesday and won by
9-1, and Thursday David Justice and Jorge Posada ripped home runs
in the second inning to give the Yankees and Andy Pettitte (9-6) a
3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees flubbed a scoring chance in the fifth inning, when
they had runners at first and second and one out, and could not add
anything. Still, their advantage was three runs, Pettitte's
fastball had sizzle _ he was on the way to striking out 10 batters
_ and there was nothing to suggest the Yankees might lose this
game.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte walked Damion Easley, the Tigers' leadoff hitter, to
open the sixth inning, a mild problem that became something of a
crisis when Pettitte threw two pitches out of the strike zone to
the next hitter, Shane Halter, who had drawn exactly five walks
this season. Posada, the Yankees' catcher, jogged to the mound,
where he was joined by Mel Stottlemyre, the pitching coach. But
Pettitte was panicking a bit, overthrowing, trying too hard. He
walked Halter. He had a three-run lead in the sixth, and he walked
two batters to start an inning. He felt himself overstriding, felt
his mechanics falling apart, ``and I just didn't make the
adjustment,'' Pettitte said.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Higginson hit a ground-ball single, driving home one run,
before Pettitte struck out Dean Palmer and Wendell Magee; just one
more out, and the Yankees would survive with a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Deivi Cruz singled to left, where Felix Jose _ making his
third start of the season _ charged the ball. ``I was trying to
throw the guy out at home, and I didn't have a chance,'' Jose said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than glove the ball and throw home, Jose fumbled Cruz's
hit, then hurled the ball toward home plate, rather than second
base. Halter scored on the hit, Higginson took third on Jose's
error, and Cruz rambled into second on the poorly directed throw.
Two runs in, two runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte tried jamming Juan Encarnacion with a cut fastball but
missed his target _ the ball was too far over the plate _ and
Encarnacion laced a single through the middle, two runs scored. As
the inning ended, one batter later, Pettitte removed his hat, wiped
his brow and spat on the ground disgustedly.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no reprieve. Chuck Knoblauch doubled leading off
the seventh, and following that hit, Derek Jeter tried to roll the
ball to the right side of the field _ and hit a soft, harmless
lineout instead, failing to advance the runner. Knoblauch never
made it past third. The Yankees had runners at first and second and
one out in the ninth and Paul O'Neill smacked a hard grounder off
Detroit's closer, Todd Jones, but right to the second baseman,
Easley, who started a game-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill ran through the bag, turned and headed for the Yankees'
dugout on the first-base side of the field, head down, the
realization of defeat sinking in. ``This is a game that you've got
to win,'' Pettitte said. ``The two walks led to it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Neill: ``This is a game where you look back and you'll
think we definitely should have won.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill and Tino Martinez and others spoke positively of the
current direction of the team. It has four victories in the last
six games, 11 victories in the last 16 games. The Yankees are in
first place in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the perfect lineup continues, even after the
acquisitions of Justice and the left-handed pitcher Denny Neagle.
The Yankees' front office is seeking a right-handed power hitter to
bat eighth and play left field _ those are the specifications _ and
might swap a top prospect in return. The current craving is for
another big hitter, the thinking being that if only they could get
another star, perhaps that will put them over the top. Or perhaps
the players already in pinstripes must start performing
consistently. Perhaps they need to win games like the game they
gave away Thursday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
