<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CAN'T IGNORE EVERETT'S NEED FOR HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the record, the official press box over/under was 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to take the Rod Beck route and call it five a
bump, that's fine, but 10 games simply seemed to be the minimum
number of lost games Judge Frank Robinson could assign to Carl
Everett for his tempestuous outburst at Fenway Park last Saturday
afternoon. Only one person I talked to thought there was even a
(itals)chance(unitals) the punishment would be anything less, while
just about everyone believed anything in excess of 15 would be
punishing the Red Sox themselves to excess. Most people accurately
predicted that Robinson would make it 10, and so he has. As for the
appeal process, who knows? Anything can happen, of course, but it
would be wise to assume that when all the harrumphing and all the
legal wrangling is complete Carl Everett will wind up being sat
down for 10 games _ whenevah.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Carl is fortunate his fate wasn't in the hands of
Judge Ryan. I would have given him at least 20. I might have
entertained 30.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who saw this thing (except, of course, his agent) knows
that the 10 games were a no-brainer. He (itals)did(unitals)
head-butt umpire Ron Kulpa, not once, but twice. He did continue to
act like a fool, long after the fact. But the big thing was that no
one can go around even thinking about head-butting an umpire.
</P>
<P>
   The problem I have with a 10-game suspension is that Carl
Everett is a multiple offender who must be made aware of a
zero-tolerance approach for the future. I'm not sure that this
10-game suspension will send that messsage, especially since there
is no evidence that the Boston Red Sox as an organization have any
intention of addressing Carl Everett's core problem, which is a
propensity for excessive outrage, no matter how small, or even in
two interesting cases, how nonexistent the provocation.
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, the most telling aspect of last Saturday's
incident was the reaction of Mets right fielder Derek Bell, who
came running in from his position to intercede, a direct violation
of all known baseball etiquette. He did so because, alone among all
people in Boston last Saturday, he truly (itals)knew(unitals) Carl
Everett, and he feared the worst. Derek Bell has been a friend of
Everett's since the age of 8. He has seen his buddy in good times
and in bad. He came running in from right field because he believed
in his heart of hearts that Everett was capable of committing an
act that would end his baseball career, right then and there, and
that could conceivably lead to his incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   Bell indicated he feared his friend of two decades might get
into ``serious, serious, serious trouble.'' That is why he was
willing to risk the wrath of his teammates by involving himself
with the actions of an opposing player toward the umpire, something
that would ordinarily have amused them, more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what Carl Everett is capable of doing? Any
professional athlete who would go into a swearing fit at the
expense of a fellow airline passenger who had placed a briefcase on
his suit coat (a simple ``Excuse me, but I wish you wouldn't do
that'' would suffice) and who would overreact with another
profanity-laden outburst to a thoroughly innocuous item in a
baseball game story in which he was accurately quoted as saying ``I
have nothing to say'' is, if not mentally unstable, frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who doesn't think there is cause for worry with this man
should dig out last Sunday's Globe (July 16) and scour Gordon
Edes's wonderfully researched story on the turbulent life and times
of one Carl Everett. When you've finished wading through the data,
you have the answer to the question, ``Why is such a talented
player now with his fifth organization?''
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Red Sox are now liable for $30 million worth of
Carl Everett, and given that they will be very happy to pay that
money if he continues to play baseball the way he has this season
for the next four campaigns, the issue now is ensuring that he is
in a position to play approximately 140-150 games a year between
now and 2005. What would you say are the odds of him doing this?
I'd say that as things stand there is a better chance of him going
off on somebody in a road rage incident, or throwing a bat at a
pitcher he feels has violated his turf, than there is of him
proceeding peacefully through a seven-month baseball season. The
fact is it doesn't take much to turn Carl Everett, Great
Ballplayer, into Carl Everett, Menace To Society.
</P>
<P>
   We know already that he has learned nothing from this affair,
given that his initial reaction to the suspension was to blame the
media for making this an issue.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is Dan Duquette's move. This incident has brought out the
worst in Jimy Williams, whose apparent position is that he's still
available for me to write his name in the lineup, so
(itals)what(unitals) anger issue? You'd hope that the
ever-inscrutable GM, Amherst grad that he is, would identify
Everett's problem in a long-term context and take steps to get him
the professional help he obviously needs, simply to cover his own
executive butt.
</P>
<P>
   But I long ago conceded that Dan Duquette marches to his own
unique drummer. On more than one occasion he has given strong
indications that he believes this game is played with baseball
robots, not actual men who breathe and feel. (It doesn't help in
this particular matter that his greatest creation, the shortstop,
really (itals)is(unitals) the closest thing to a factory-ordered
baseball machine in the game today.)
</P>
<P>
   It is beyond dispute that the Red Sox need Everett in their
lineup. It is likewise beyond dispute that, absent a strong
preemptive strike on their part, this will not be the last time
they'll be sitting around awaiting Judge Robinson's decision in the
wake of an irrational Everett blowup.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox are very lucky he will only be out for 10
games. If they don't address this situation, the next suspension
will be much longer. That is an ultra-mortal lock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
ryan(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
