<HEADER>
A8125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-450     07-20 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-POLITICS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PARLIAMENT, SHARED BY GOVERNING PARTY AND OPPOSITION, OPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ The cameras flashed, the crowds cheered and
the bitter rivals strode in side by side. One month after this
country's momentous elections, Parliament officially opened
Thursday with the governing party forced to share space and power
with a formidable opposition for the first time in more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   But as the foreign affairs minister, Stan Mudenge, marched
alongside Evelyn Masaiti, a teacher who was attacked by supporters
of Mudenge's party during the harsh and bloody campaign, he bowed
graciously to the new reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He greeted me,'' marveled Masaiti, who braved the political
violence to win a seat for the opposition. ``He said, `How are
you?' He said he was lucky to be standing near me because the
cameras would all concentrate on the man next to such a smartly
dressed woman. And I just laughed.''
</P>
<P>
   With nervous glances and awkward handshakes, President Robert
Mugabe's ZANU-PF party formally ceded its near total monopoly on
power Thursday. And as the opposition party members took their
seats in the chamber, thousands of flag-waving, singing supporters
danced in the streets and welcomed a new, raucous era of
multi-party democracy.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, a single opposition party _ the Movement for
Democratic Change _ now controls 57 seats in the 150-member
Parliament, a share large enough to block Mugabe's party from
unilaterally changing the constitution. The ZANU-PF, which won 62
seats, had controlled all but three seats since the late 1980s.
Mugabe also appoints 30 members of the Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   As the president entered Parliament Thursday afternoon and saw
the new faces in the chamber that his party had overwhelmingly
dominated for two decades, he clearly knew the political landscape
here had dramatically shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results of the elections are here, fully reflected in this
significantly changed composition of this august house,'' Mugabe
said Thursday in a markedly conciliatory speech to the new
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``To you, all honorable members, I say congratulations while
expressing the fervent hope that you will shoulder your weighty
responsibilities in this house with dignity, a sense of
responsibility and seriousness of purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The government maintains its majority in Parliament, but the
political realignment is still unprecedented here. And as cannons
boomed and fighter jets whizzed over the capital, thousands of
people flocked to see the spectacle with their own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took off from work; I had to see it for myself,'' said
Theresa Macheche, 18, a manicurist. ``We voted for change. We are
fed up. Now we finally have a mixed Parliament with different
parties.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his speech, Mugabe promised to address some of the concerns
of the disenchanted urban electorate. He promised to focus on the
ailing economy and move quickly to withdraw thousands of soldiers
from the civil war in Congo, as well as step up the pace of land
redistribution to poor black farmers, an issue that appeals to his
rural support base.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have also tempered their fiery statements
against the white minority and black supporters of the Movement for
Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   And last Saturday, Mugabe announced the formation of a new
Cabinet that has been widely praised across the political spectrum.
The key ministries of finance and industry, for instance, are now
run by Simba Makoni and Nkosana Moyo respectively, two highly
regarded businessmen who have sometimes been at odds with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   That move was a critical first step in the effort to woo back
Western donors, who have withdrawn desperately needed financial
assistance from Zimbabwe, saying the economy is severely
mismanaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inclusion of private-sector business leaders to head the
key economic ministries is in itself a powerful signal that this is
the time for fundamental change,'' said Kumbirai Katsande,
president of the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries.
</P>
<P>
   But two Western officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said financial rescue will not come soon. They fear the new
ministers will lack the political clout to make painful, but
critical economic decisions. And they point to the government's
continuing threats to seize white-owned land without compensation
as a continuing source of concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there is likely to be no change at all to the
system of management and the style of leadership,'' said John
Makumbe, a political analyst at the University of Zimbabwe and a
frequent government critic.
</P>
<P>
   But the political shift is nothing short of extraordinary for
many opposition legislators who are still learning parliamentary
rules and how to wend their way through a building most had only
seen on television. They are teachers, lawyers, students and
businessmen who feel bewildered by government budgets and
committees. And some are scrambling to find money to rent offices
or print business cards.
</P>
<P>
   Masaiti, 35, whose car was burned in the political violence that
swept the country before the elections, had to squeeze into a
public bus to make the four-hour journey from her rural district in
Mutasa for the opening of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the new legislators took their oaths of office in a
festive ceremony marked by dueling chants. ``Zimbabwe's
independence was won through bloodshed!'' chorused the ZANU-PF
members.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition members shouted back, startling their opponents into
silence. ``ZANU-PF is rotten!'' they cried.
</P>
<P>
   But their jubilation faded as they promptly lost their first
battle over the choice of the new speaker of Parliament. The
governing party closed ranks and selected its preferred candidate,
reminding the downcast opposition of the limits of their newfound
power.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Moyo, the chief of information in Mugabe's office, said
Movement for Democratic Change members must learn to work with the
majority or risk becoming ``noisemakers not lawmakers.'' And some
opposition legislators admit that they will be repeatedly
outnumbered unless they find allies across the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Masaiti says she is undeterred by challenge. She said she got
into politics because she was tired of struggling to feed her
family. And Thursday morning, on her big day, when she looked at
her reflection in the mirror, she finally believed she had made it.
``That woman,'' she said she told herself, ``is an M.P.''
</P>
<P>
   And by 9 a.m., hours before the opening ceremony, the new M.P.,
or member of parliament, was already at work, meeting with women's
groups and taking careful notes in her tiny spiral notebook.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying they want development, roads, schools,
irrigation, health facilities,'' she said, as she rushed off to her
next meeting. ``I know it won't be easy. I just promise I will try
my best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
