<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8126 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-DISABILITIES-ACT-$ADV     07-20 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITIES-ACT-$ADV23-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DISABILITY LAW CELEBRATED BUT ADVOCATES SAY WORK REMAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, July 23)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ten years ago Michael Smith, an accountant with the
Ohio state government in Cincinnati, couldn't get into many
buildings, eat in many restaurants or navigate many hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Smith found barriers everywhere because he has used a wheelchair
since a 1972 car accident left him paralyzed from the waist down.
</P>
<P>
   Now, thanks to the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA), which
former President George Bush signed July 26, 1990, a lot of the
barriers have fallen.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says, ``Before the law, there was a large part of everyday
life that was out of reach for me. It's still a challenge being
disabled, but at least now, I feel like the world isn't working
against me.''
</P>
<P>
   This week the nation's 54 million people with disabilities are
celebrating the transformation of America into a place where they
can ride buses, use bathrooms in public buildings and reach
drinking fountains _ all because of the ADA, which was aimed at
giving them access to places previously off limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It quite literally is a different world today for people with
disabilities,'' says Helena Berger, chief operating officer of
American Association of People with Disabilities, a
Washington-based advocacy group. ``The physical changes in
America's buildings and transportation have been tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger says the ADA helped make people aware that people with
disabilities were being discriminated against.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, most businesses just didn't think about people
with disabilities or about the fact that their restaurant or store
was completely inaccessible to the disabled,'' she says. ``Now,
most people think about these things, which makes all the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1990, hundreds of technical rules devised to implement the
law have brought ramps, wider aisles, lower counters and drinking
fountains, automatic doors, special elevators, more accessible
restrooms, listening devices and wheelchair lifts.
</P>
<P>
   To mark the anniversary, the AAPD is sponsoring a 24-city torch
relay. The torch was lit June 7 at the grave of Martin Luther King
Jr. in Atlanta and will arrive in Washington on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``By beginning the relay at Dr. King's grave, we wanted to show
people that our struggle, like his, is about equality,'' Berger
says.
</P>
<P>
   She and other advocates argue that the struggle for equal rights
continues, particularly in the area of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Fiedler, chairman of the Washington-based Disability Rights
Council, says economic independence remains the ultimate goal for
people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movement is maturing,'' he says. ``Now it's about jobs,
careers and participating in our society.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a survey conducted by the National Organization on
Disability here and the New York-based Harris Poll, 56 percent of
people with disabilities who are able to work currently hold full-
or part-times jobs compared with 80 percent of those without
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released last week, also showed a significant income
gap between people with and without disabilities. Twenty-nine
percent of those with disabilities live in households with incomes
of $15,000 or less. Ten percent of people without disabilities live
in such households. Conversely, 16 percent of people with
disabilities live in households with $50,000 or more annual income.
But 39 percent of those without disabilities live in such
households.
</P>
<P>
   Berger says that the high unemployment numbers stem from an
entrenched prejudice against people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to put in a ramp or widen a hallway,'' she
says. ``It's another thing hire a person with a disability to come
into your office every day and to really be around that person.''
</P>
<P>
   She says that removing the ``mental barriers'' faced by people
with disabilities could take decades. ``These stereotypes die hard,
and no legislation can change attitudes overnight,'' she adds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she says, disability groups must turn to the courts
to ensure that employers comply with the ADA.
</P>
<P>
   But as disability groups push to open doors, businesses are
complaining that the burdens placed on them have become too great.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Eide, a spokesman for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce,
charges that predatory lawyers are seeking to enrich themselves
more than help people with disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   He cites the case of a California woman, who claims a plaintiff
sued her and 19 other restaurant owners after driving up and down
streets targeting everyone whose parking signs for the disabled
were not visible from the road.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grover of the National Restaurant Association, who
oversees the industry's compliance with the ADA, says, ``There is a
simmering anger among some disability-rights groups who just want
to drag people into court. And there is opportunistic behavior
among some attorneys who see this as a way to make some money.''
Grover argues that ``the ADA was designed for access, not to put
money in the pockets of lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce and the restaurant association are
supporting a bill, recently introduced by Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla.,
that would give businesses 90 days to comply with the ADA after a
complaint has been lodged. Foley says retailers in Florida and
California are being harassed by what he calls ``drive-by
lawsuits'' initiated by lawyers who find ADA violations and seek
out people with disabilities to complain about them.
</P>
<P>
   But Berger argues that business owners have had 10 years to
comply with the ADA. ``The guidelines are clear and have been
around for a decade, so why do they need an extra 90 days?'' she
asks.
</P>
<P>
   Berger says the ADA should not be weakened. ``We've come a long
way in a short time, but we still have far to go, and we're going
to need all the help we can get,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
