<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8128 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-TEXAS0721-COX     07-20 0629
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-TEXAS0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GBy Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George Bush has always touted his record of
working with Texas Democrats, even basking in the endorsement of
the late Lt. Gov Bob Bullock, a Democratic icon who died last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the spotlight of a presidential campaign _ usually with
a nudge from the Democratic National Committee and the Al Gore
campaign _ is trying to recast the governor's role with the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mario Gallegos Jr., D-Houston, has appeared on CNN
twice and MSNBC, attended a press conference in Chicago and
accompanied Gore in San Antonio on Thursday _ and that's just this
week. Earlier this month, Sen. Gonzalo Barrientos, D-Austin, and
State Rep. Senfronia Thompson, D-Houston, had press conferences on
Bush's record at the National Council of La Raza in California and
the NAACP national convention in Baltimore, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Bush's selling points has been it's hard to find a
(Texas) Democrat to criticize him,'' said University of Texas
political professor Bruce Buchanan. ``By highlighting a few of them
cuts Bush down a little.''
</P>
<P>
   The DNC underwrites the out-of-state travel and the Gore
campaign encourages out-of-state reporters to interview the handful
of Texas Democratic officials willing to criticize the popular
governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they need a Latino from Texas, they call me or Gonzalo
(Barrientos),'' Gallegos said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   By taking the fight to Bush in his home state, Buchanan said
Gore is trying to hammer both ends of the governor's compassionate
conservatism. While Gore questions the health of state finances
after Bush's property tax cut, Buchanan said the Democrat also
raises again the state's traditionally low national rankings in
health care and other social spending.
</P>
<P>
   Using Texas Democrats in the message also helps, Buchanan said,
although it runs counter to Texas tradition of bipartisanship in
the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Gallegos and Barrientos said they are only telling
the truth _ Democrats had to push Bush to give more children health
insurance, expand kindergarten and raise teacher salaries. In
typical legislative trade-off, they said Bush's got his property
tax cut despite misgivings by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Few elected Democrats have been willing to tackle Bush head-on
in the presidential campaign. Buchanan said a lot of Democrats in
the pro-business coalition that runs the Legislature like Bush and
supported the budget Gore is criticizing. Others seeking
re-election _ from Speaker Pete Laney and on down the ballot _
don't want to make Bush a campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Texas chauvinism also helps the governor. State Rep. Garnet
Coleman, D-Houston, said he was swamped with calls from national
reporters when he was quoted in his hometown newspaper saying
Bush's tax cut will make it harder for Texas to make ends meet next
year. He said he got a lot of reaction from his colleagues who fear
criticizing Bush is seen as criticizing Texas _ and the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts you in a tough spot if your loyalty to Texas is
equated with loyalty to Bush,'' he said. ``It is not my desire to
be an on-going spokesperson for the Gore campaign. My priority is
to help my constituents.''
</P>
<P>
   Molly Beth Malcolm, Texas Democratic Party chairwoman, said
Democratic officials will follow their own political instincts in
addressing Bush's record. She urged voters to remember one thing:
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush is not Texas. When we criticize his record, we are
not criticizing our state.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
