<HEADER>
A8129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-COVERDELL-ROLE0721-CO     07-20 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COVERDELL-ROLE0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coverdell's death leaves projects aplenty in limbo
 &HT;    By Melanie Eversley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At a get-together at a Washington think tank this
week, officials from Mexico walked up to Roger Noriega, a Capitol
Hill staffer, shook his hand, and lamented what a blow this week's
tragedy would be to their cause.
</P>
<P>
   The news was that Georgia's senior senator, Republican Paul
Coverdell, had died unexpectedly the day before, following a stroke
and surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, who in Washington would help them push for democracy in
Mexico and throughout the Caribbean, the officials wondered. They
shared their grief with Noriega, who worked with Coverdell on the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a number of people came up to me and said, 'Oh my God.
This is terrible,' '' said Noriega, the senior professional staff
member for the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coverdell felt the Americas were special and different and
that we needed to work together more,'' Noriega continued. ``There
were people who recognized that the guy really cared. A lot of
people were worried about the vacuum it might leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is not just Coverdell's drive to crush the drug trade and
nurture democracy in Latin America that has hit a snag.
</P>
<P>
   There were his plans to probe unusual travel activities among
members of the Small Business Administration, the federal agency
charged with making loans and offering training to small
businesses. There was his upcoming role as National Caucus Team
co-chair for the Republican National Convention starting July 31 in
Philadelphia. There, Coverdell's job would have been to speak with
reporters when Texas Gov. George W. Bush, his friend and the
presumptive Republican nominee for president, could not. There also
was Coverdell's work with the leaders of America's Fortune 500
companies to ensure that the Senate passed a bill granting
permanent, normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it is all left hanging.
</P>
<P>
   The people who make up the nuts and bolts of Washington _ the
lobbyists, consultants, policy analysts and others _ described
Coverdell as one of those driven people whose mind was always on
the 10 things he still needed to do, and whose respect was so
sweeping that he affected every project working its way through the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a single activity that leadership was pushing
that didn't involve Sen. Coverdell,'' John Czwartacki, spokesman
for Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.), said. Though
Coverdell had given up his seat on the Senate Foreign Affairs
Committee to fill a vacancy on the Senate Finance Committee, he
remained involved in Caribbean affairs, Noriega said.
</P>
<P>
   And as secretary of the Senate Republican Conference, it was
Coverdell's job to negotiate legislation strategy with The Business
Roundtable, a Washington-based association of the heads of the
country's largest companies. Just last Thursday, Coverdell met with
the group to bandy about strategy to get the Senate to approve the
China trade bill, which passed the U.S. House in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting was actually a wonderful example of the senator in
that he was absolutely honest about the chances coming up. He was a
wonderful political handicapper,'' Johanna Schneider, roundtable
spokeswoman, said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the group is waiting to see whom Lott names as a new point
person on the issue, Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   Coverdell also was making progress getting answers for concerns
he had about the day-to-day operations of the Small Business
Administration, Emilia DiSanto, majority staff director for the
Senate Small Business Committee, said. Coverdell, a committee
member, had just begun looking into allegations about unusual trips
taken by SBA employees. On Thursday, he was to help run the first
of a series of hearings that would have followed a new method of
monitoring SBA operations, DiSanto said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you, Senator Coverdell was excited about this
hearing,'' she said. She hopes his concerns about travel among SBA
workers will find a new home too. ``We're hopeful that another one
of the senators picks up interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
