<HEADER>
A8135 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS &LR;      07-20 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELS TAKES EARLY, 1-SHOT, LEAD OVER WOODS, FLESCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ They call it the luck of the draw and
professional golfers understand that it comes with the job. They
don't ask for sympathy, just that good and bad fortunes share equal
time.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els got the slate wiped clear Thursday, which is why he
was able to vault to a one-shot lead over Tiger Woods and Steve
Flesch in the first round of the 129th British Open at sun-baked
St. Andrews. Admittedly in a struggle with his confidence of late,
Els offset bogeys on both par 3s with eight birdies _ the last of
which came at the near-impossible Road Hole, the par-4 17th _ in a
6-under-par 66 effort that silenced some efficient work put in by
Woods earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Low scores were the order of business on a course that continues
to play harder and faster than anything these gentlemen have
experienced. Obviously, the golfers have adjusted, because 50 of
them posted red numbers. A seven-player group at 68 included former
champ Tom Lehman and 20-year-old Sergio Garcia, and at 69 there
were 15 players, ranging from the red-hot Notah Begay to Ireland's
beloved Christy O'Connor Jr., at 52 enjoying perhaps his last
go-round in this championship.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Westwood, Darren Clarke, Nick Faldo, David Duval, and Fred
Couples were among 14 who posted 70s, and Colin Montgomerie logged
in with 10 others at 71.
</P>
<P>
   None of them, it seems, was anxious to see Woods run from view,
a sentiment that was expressed quite well by Els.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see Tiger at 5-under and you have not even started your
round,'' said the two-time US Open champ, whose trip began after
Woods had finished. ``You know you have your work cut out for
you.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knew he had been here before, just a month ago in the US
Open. Woods had sizzled to a 5-under 65, carving up Pebble Beach in
benign weather conditions, when Els journeyed off the first tee and
into cold, foggy, windy weather. ``I was 1-under par playing the
11th,'' said Els, ``and then it was called off.''
</P>
<P>
   The morning re-start proved difficult, Els finished with a 74,
inherited a nine-shot deficit, and became just one of 155 punching
bags for Woods's 15-shot victory.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching early Round 1 action in his hotel room
Thursday, the gracious South African with the sweet swing
discovered that the golf gods were smiling on him and the other
late starters. ``For once,'' he said, ``I got fortunate with my
draw.''
</P>
<P>
   The afternoon weather was virtually a carbon copy of what Woods
and the morning crew had faced, and it made the ever-present smile
on Els's face even wider. The front nine was practically all
downwind and when he turned for the demanding home stretch, Els
discovered that the wind had settled down.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to take advantage of that,'' said Els, who has four
Top 10s in nine British Open starts.
</P>
<P>
   Advantage, Els, with a frontside power surge which can deliver
to the same area code as Woods. At the 397-yard third, Els drove it
close to the green, pitched to 15 feet, and got to 1-under. He
reached the 568-yard, par-5 fifth in two and made birdie, then
drove the 412-yard sixth hole and got to 3-under.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he was having fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day like this, you can shoot anything,'' said Els, who
drilled a 2-iron at the 388-yard seventh, then pitched to 20 feet
for birdie No. 4 and suddenly the bogey-free round Woods had
scripted wasn't as impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Woods thought it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a few loose shots here and there,'' said Woods, who
started the round as if he were out merely to work on his
lag-putting. Without a good birdie chance in his first eight holes,
Woods was two-putting from across greens at every step and staring
at a hefty deficit because Begay was pushing deep into the red.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was an 18-hole tournament, I would have been in
trouble,'' said Woods. ``Since there's 72 of them, I had a long way
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Five shots behind Begay through eight holes, Woods ripped off
five birdies in a seven-hole stretch, highlighted by his own power
supply. He drove it to the fringe on the 379-yard 10th, onto the
green at the 314-yard 12th, then reached the 581-yard 14th in two.
After Begay (he got to 7-under when he chipped in for an eagle-2 at
the 12th) had fallen from the top spot with a triple-bogey, bogey
finish, Woods saved par with a shot only he can hit _ a wedge out
of impossible heather down the left side of No. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to open up the face because you know the grass is not
going to grab the club head, it's going to grab the shaft,'' said
Woods, who muscled his ball to the front of the green, then
navigated the two putts for par.
</P>
<P>
   Impressive, but Els did him better in the afternoon, making one
of the four birdies yielded by that demanding 17th. ``I hit some
pretty awesome drives today, but that must be the shot of the day
(for me),'' said Els of his 6-iron from 184 yards that set up his
final birdie of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Though Flesch (seven birdies, two bogeys) also had put up a 66
to share second and a flock of marquee names had great afternoons,
Els faced questions about only one lurking presence, Woods.
Fortunately, he is used to it, though he's more like The Big
Un-Easy when the tired subject comes up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I play good enough, I'm probably going to play with
him,'' said Els, who was trying to enjoy his 65. ``So let's leave
it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite true _ at least not for Round 2, because Els goes out
early, Woods tees off late. The luck of the draw has another chance
to get involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
