<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8136 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-BRITISH-ELS21-COX     07-20 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BRITISH-ELS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Els is one shot up on Tiger
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. ANDREWS, Scotland _ Ernie Els has been saying golf needs
someone to take on Tiger Woods. Someone like, say, him.
</P>
<P>
   Els positioned himself for another run at Woods with a
six-under-par 66 Thursday to take the first-round lead in the 129th
British Open. Els led Woods and Steve Flesch by a shot on a day
when a lack of wind made the Old Course a pushover.
</P>
<P>
   Els has had perhaps the best view of Woods' dominance this year,
losing in a brilliant playoff with Woods at the Mercedes
Championships. Moreover, Els is coming off consecutive runner-up
finishes in the past two majors, though he was a distant 15 shots
back in last month's U.S. Open at Pebble Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Els was more content to let his clubs do the talking Thursday
when asked about whether he can be the man to take on Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I play good enough, I can play with him,'' Els said.
``Let's just leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed on the subject, Els got testy and said: ``I just shot
66, guys. Let's talk about me. Get on the phone with Tiger if you
want to talk about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Alrighty.
</P>
<P>
   Els' best statement came on the devilish 17th hole when he hit a
6-iron from 184 yards to 8 feet. He made the putt to take the lead
on a hole that yielded just four birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who can become the youngest player (24) to complete the
career grand slam with a victory here, didn't make much noise early
as he struggled for pars on the first eight holes. But almost on
command, he had five birdies in a seven-hole stretch to do all the
day's damage.
</P>
<P>
   That's how dominant Woods has become: Even when he doesn't have
a so-called ``A game,'' he finds himself within a shot of the lead
at a major. Not that Woods was worried, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long championship,'' he said. ``Seventy-two holes. If
it was an 18-hole tournament, I would have been in trouble. Any
time you start a major with eight straight pars, I don't care what
major that is, I'll take that start.''
</P>
<P>
   Flesch is trying to become just the second left-hander to win a
major (the other was Palm Beach Gardens resident Bob Charles, who
won the 1967 British Open). But Flesch was more impressed with the
company he was keeping Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're around him (Woods), you know something is going
right,'' Flesch said. ``But you can't worry about him. If you do
that, you're going to make bogeys so fast you're going to be home
watching everyone else play.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven players tied for fourth, two shots back, constituted
quite an eclectic group. They were Sergio Garcia, who was supposed
to be Woods' chief rival after he finished second in last year's
PGA Championship; fellow Ryder Cuppers Tom Lehman and Padraig
Harrington; rising Japanese star Shigeki Maruyama; first-round
Masters leader Dennis Paulson; Florida native Scott Dunlap; and a
player Woods had never heard of _ Ian Garbutt.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's 68 was noteworthy because it represented a 21-shot
improvement over the 89 he shot in last year's British Open at
Carnoustie. The Spaniard added an 83 to finish at the bottom of the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be something to go from last to first, wouldn't
it?'' Garcia said. ``Twenty-one shots isn't that big of a
difference, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Garbutt was the lone player to get to seven under (after 12
holes), but he bogeyed three of his final six holes. Still, that
was an unexpected showing for the 28-year-old Englishman who has
made just eight-of-20 cuts on the PGA European Tour this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a funny year for me because I'm normally
consistent,'' Garbutt said. ``But it was nice to look up on the
leader board and see I was on top of names like Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   The day's other big development regarded the rare combination of
little wind and warm, sunny skies at St. Andrews. That enabled 50
players to break par and the field to average 73.0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather was the big story today,'' Lehman said. ``The
course played as easy as it's going to play. She doesn't have much
of a defense without the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, Flesch and Garcia were the only players among the top 10
who played Thursday afternoon, which should bode well for them when
they go out this morning. But sooner or later, Els knows he'll have
to deal with a force as irresistible as the weather if he wants to
add another major to his two U.S. Open titles.
</P>
<P>
   Els wasn't about to guarantee a victory, but he's confident he
won't need binoculars to find Woods by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he beats me by 15 from now,'' Els said, ``there should be
an inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
