<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STRONG-MEDICINE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STRONG MEDICINE' IS NOT THE CURE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use after Sat., July 22, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below.) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
``Strong Medicine'' offers awfully diluted drama.
</P>
<P>
   Janine Turner stars as Dr. Dana Stowe, a driven but cold cancer
researcher at a prestigious Philadelphia hospital. Rosa Blasi plays
Dr. Luisa Delgado, who runs a struggling women's free clinic in the
city's inner city. Stowe thinks Delgado cuts too many corners in
her practice of medicine; Delgado finds Stowe's research antiseptic
and impersonal.
</P>
<P>
   So guess who's gonna have to work together? Tonight's pilot
takes its time setting up its premise. In the meantime, it concerns
itself with Delgado's run-ins with a homeless woman and an abusive
couple and their son, as well as Stowe's insistence that a woman at
risk for ovarian cancer take preventive measures, when all the
woman wants is to have a child.
</P>
<P>
   It's all melodrama of the sort we've seen on ``ER'' or any other
recent medical drama. Hollywood Square Whoopi Goldberg, one of the
show's executive producers, appears as a kindly doctor in a
glorified cameo reminiscent of the easy paycheck she picked up for
her nothing role in ``Girl, Interrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Strong Medicine's'' premise isn't fatally flawed, but it is
awfully familiar, and other dramatic elements will no doubt need to
be added to maintain viewer interest.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QL; 
The show: ``Strong Medicine.'' &QL; 
What: Drama about dissimilar doctors working together for a women's
free clinic. &QL; 
The stars: Janine Turner, Rosa Blasi, Whoopi Goldberg. &QL; 
Where: Lifetime. &QL; 
When: 9 p.m. Sundays.
</P>
</TEXT>
