<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors like Greenspan's softer stance
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The U.S. economy appears headed for a soft landing,
but it's not there yet, and still higher interest rates may be
needed to contain inflation, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soft landing'' is the term analysts apply to the Fed's goal of
slowing the economy from the 4 percent-plus annual rate of the last
four years to less than 3 percent, without a recession and while
holding inflation at bay.
</P>
<P>
   That's the logic behind the Fed's policy of raising its
short-term federal funds rate by a total of 1.75 percent since June
1999 to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Recent economic reports suggest that these rate increases have
begun to slow the economy, and Greenspan agreed in his semiannual
testimony before the Senate Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``growth in household spending has slowed noticeably
this spring from the unusually rapid pace observed late in 1999 and
early this year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time,'' he cautioned, ``inflation has picked
up _ even the core measures that do not include energy prices
directly.'' Despite his caution, Greenspan's comments were
considerably less threatening than they were in his February
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Investors took that to mean the Fed's string of rate hikes is
nearing an end, if not over, igniting a buying rally that sent all
major stock market averages higher. Investor spirits also were
buoyed by stronger-than-expected IBM earnings and a rally in
financial and other rate-sensitive stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenspan sounded considerably less grumpy than we and most
investors had been expecting,'' Dain Rauscher senior economist
Vincent Boberski told Bloomberg News.
</P>
<P>
   But Bank One chief economist Diane Swonk said Greenspan ``left
himself completely open for (another rate hike in) August and
beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared testimony, Greenspan attributed the economic
slowing to a combination of factors: the spring stock market
correction, the ``rising debt burden of households,'' higher oil
prices and the fact that Americans may have bought all the houses,
new cars and other big-ticket items they need for now.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that ``even without the rise in interest rates, an
eventual leveling out or some tapering off of purchases of durable
goods and construction of single-family housing would be
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan reiterated his thesis that the economy's unexpected
strength comes from business investment in computers and
productivity-enhancing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate problem, he said, is that consumer demand for
goods and services _ fueled, in large part, by stock market wealth
_ has expanded faster than the economy's ability to produce those
goods and services, threatening inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The principal risk is that America's strong economy has created
a tight labor market that threatens to produce wage inflation if
businesses are forced to raise wages to attract the workers they
need. So far that hasn't happened, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan said the outlook for the economy this year is ``a
little stronger'' than anticipated in his February forecast. He
said it is likely to expand at a 4 percent to 4.5 percent annual
rate despite slower second-half growth.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 2001 growth rate is expected to moderate to 3.25
percent to 3.75 percent, with the unemployment rate likely staying
close to 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's markets, the technology-loaded Nasdaq composite
jumped about 3 percent to pace the trading, while the blue-chip Dow
Jones industrial average rose 1.5 percent and the broader S&AMP;P 500
about 1 percent. Treasury yields also dipped as optimistic bond
traders cheered Greenspan's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
