<SLUG> BC-RAC-OAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET STATUS EYES THE TOP FILLY SPOT
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Triple Tiara, New York's version of the Triple Crown for
fillies, reaches a climax at Belmont Park Saturday with the
$300,000 Coaching Club American Oaks at a 1 1/2 miles. For Secret
Status, the race presents a chance to clinch her claim to be
recognized as the nation's leading 3-year-old filly.
</P>
<P>
   Secret Status drew the outside post position Thursday when
entries were filed for the Oaks, but that seemed to be no problem
for a filly with her record, especially in a short field of seven.
She comes into the Oaks with six victories in 10 starts, and she
has run in the money nine times.
</P>
<P>
   She leaped to the head of this year's class by winning the
Kentucky Oaks at Churchill Downs by 6 3/4 lengths, and the Mother
Goose Stakes at Belmont, the second jewel of the Triple Tiara, by a
neck over Jostle, who will break from the No. 5 slot in Saturday's
running.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had some things to overcome in the Oaks, and she did,''
said Neil Howard, who trains Secret Status for her owner, Will
Farish. ``I think she settles a lot better around two turns. It's
been a maturity thing with her. The breeding says she should get
better with time.''
</P>
<P>
   Secret Status comes with stars in her breeding: She is a
daughter of A.P. Indy and a granddaughter of Seattle Slew and
Alydar. She also comes with a star jockey in the saddle: Pat Day,
who is riding her for the sixth straight time. Day also rode
Commendable in the Belmont Stakes at a 1 1/2 miles last month,
staying close to the pace before charging to the front to win in
the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Pat riding,'' Howard said, ``you always feel like you
have an edge. My only concern, as with every other trainer, is
whether your horse can get a mile and a half. She's got the
pedigree to do it, but until she actually does it, the jury is
still out.''
</P>
<P>
   Secret Status did not run in the first race in the Triple Tiara
series, the Acorn, which was won by Finder's Fee. Winning two of
the three races should be good enough to propel her toward the
Alabama at Saratoga on Aug. 19. But few fillies in this country
have been asked to run a 1 1/2 miles, so the Oaks is a major
hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   In the Mother Goose, Secret Status got into a duel down the
stretch with Jostle, who had spun six furlongs in a snappy 1:09
4/5. And Jostle, owned by Fox Hill Farms, won three stakes last
year as a juvenile and the Black-Eyed Susan this year. In the
Mother Goose, she gamely tried to withstand the late rush by Secret
Status, who prevailed by the length of her neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Mother Goose was her best race,'' said John
Servis, who trains Jostle. ``She never got a breather. When Secret
Status ran up to her, she dug in. She had every opportunity to
chuck it, and she didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Secret Status and Jostle, the field for the Oaks
includes John Peace's Sound of the West on the rail; Zoftig, who
lost the Ashland by a nose; Polly Jo, a New York-bred filly; Miss
Chief, a turf runner for Bill Mott and Jerry Bailey, and Resort,
trained by Shug McGaughey.
</P>
<P>
   The Coaching Club American Oaks will be run on the next-to-last
day of the Belmont meeting. Racing ends on Sunday before switching
north for the annual summertime season at Saratoga, starting next
Wednesday and continuing through Labor Day, Sept. 4. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
