<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BNSF-MERGER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BNSF, CANADIAN NATIONAL OFFICIALLY JUNK MERGER PLANS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By DAN PILLER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Burlington Northern Santa Fe and Canadian
National railroads officially scrapped plans for a $5.8 billion
merger on Thursday, saying regulatory delays of more than two years
are not worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the two railroads said their decision was
predicated on concern for stockholders, who have seen the value of
their shares drop since the merger was proposed last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``BNSF and CN are shareholder-driven organizations,'' said
Robert Krebs, chairman of Fort Worth-based BNSF. ``We have
concluded that it is not in the best interests of our shareholders
to assume the risks of waiting up to 2 1/2 years for a decision by
regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   The merger would have created a 50,000-mile railroad system
connecting BNSF's network in the western U.S. with Canadian
National's system extending from Chicago to Halifax on the Atlantic
Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes a week after a federal appeals court in
Washington, D.C., upheld a 15-month moratorium on merger
applications imposed in March by the U.S. Surface Transportation
Board.
</P>
<P>
   When that ruling was released, analysts speculated that the deal
was dead. Because mergers take 18 months by law to be decided by
regulators, the delay in filing a merger plan until next summer
would push back the effective date of any merger approval into late
2002.
</P>
<P>
   CN chairman Paul Tellier said from company headquarters in
Montreal that ``the delay and uncertainty caused by the moratorium
and proposed rulemaking made it impossible for us to continue with
our combination efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies stressed on Thursday that they won't have to pay
breakup fees because ``the companies have mutually agreed to unwind
their transaction.'' The original agreement called for payments of
$350 million by BNSF and $150 million by CN if either pulled out of
the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate headquarters for the newly merged North American
Railways would have been located in Montreal, but the operations
center would have remained in Fort Worth. Matthew Rose, BNSF
president, would have become chief operating officer of the new
entity. Rose was named on Thursday to the BNSF board.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs said earlier this year that he would likely retire after
the merger was completed. The BNSF chairman was not available for
comment beyond his written statement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The merger had attracted widespread opposition from rival
railroads and shipping groups. The STB said it needed more time to
study all railroad mergers in light of serious service problems
following the last two mergers, the combination of Union Pacific
and Southern Pacific in 1997 and the collaborative breakup of
Conrail last year by Norfolk Southern and CSX.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors had gotten scared of these big mergers because of
the previous problems,'' said Tom Burnett of Merger Insight, a New
York-based investment firm that follows major mergers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regulators had made it clear that this was a merger
proposal that was going down the wrong track,'' Burnett added.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's announcement, following a BNSF board meeting, was
made after the stock markets had closed. BNSF shares closed at
$24.75 a share, down 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs had contended that because the 1995 merger of Burlington
Northern and Santa Fe which created BNSF had gone relatively
smoothly, his company deserved the chance to enter another merger.
</P>
<P>
   The two railroads had sued the STB in federal court, arguing
that the moratorium violated federal laws requiring prompt action
on mergers. But in a two-to-one decision last Friday, a federal
appeals court upheld the STB's right to impose a moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Rival railroads warned that approval of the BNSF-CN merger would
touch off other big mergers that would reduce competition. And
major shippers joined the opposition, led by chemical manufacturers
who were hurt badly by traffic tieups after the Union
Pacific-Southern Pacific merger.
</P>
<P>
   BNSF did not enter into the CN merger out of financial
necessity. The company earned $238 million on revenues of $2.19
billion last year. The company is the nation's largest hauler of
coal and grain, and has greatly expanded its trailer-on-flatcar, or
intermodal, service in recent years. BNSF also is a major hauler of
new automobiles, with many of them shipped through its operation at
Alliance Airport north of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
