<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-JUNK-DNA21-COX     07-20 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUNK-DNA21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT scholars develop use for junk genes
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _Researchers at the University of Texas have
turned seemingly useless, or junk, DNA into a gene-delivery vehicle
that might one day be used in gene therapy and genetic engineering.
</P>
<P>
   If the scientists succeed in making their discovery work in
humans, the implications could be enormous. The process could be
used to knock out AIDS, cancer and other diseases. The military
could use it to protect soldiers from biological weapons. And wine
producers could tap into the technique to engineer a better grape.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a novel way of manipulating DNA ... in a way that hasn't
been done before,'' said UT professor Alan Lambowitz, director of
UT's Institute for Cellular and Molecular Biology and a lead
researcher in the discovery being published today in the journal
Science.
</P>
<P>
   The work comes as scientists finish mapping the human genome _
the 3 billion base pairs of DNA and the 80,000 to 100,000 genes
that make human beings what they are. Though scientists now know
the locations of most genes, the genes' functions are largely
unknown. Lambowitz and his colleagues said they expect their work
to produce a greater understanding of how genes work.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle they discovered could be used to turn off a bad
gene, such as a cancer-causing gene, or to introduce a helpful one,
such as a tumor-suppressing gene, into the body, Lambowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   But manipulating genes also is controversial. That's partly
because the same kind of genetic manipulation that could cure
diseases could also cause them.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can always turn technology around to be destructive,''
said Marlene Belfort, director of genetics at the Wadsworth Center
at the New York State Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, the research is an important first step that
could lead to potentially life-saving therapies. ``I think it's
lovely,'' said Belfort, a member of the prestigious National
Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   There are obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists have not yet proven that their pioneering
procedure will work with human chromosomes. That might take another
year to demonstrate, Lambowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has a lot of potential,'' said Dr. HaigKazazian,
chairman of the genetics department at the University of
Pennsylvania School of Medicine. But ``don't blow it up too much,''
he cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early, Kazazian said, to predict what might happen.
</P>
<P>
   Lambowitz is cautious but optimistic. He already has created a
company to commercialize the technology and has five patents.
Others are pending. He shares the existing patents with other
inventors and Ohio State University, where he worked before coming
to UT in 1997. UT will share in the new patents.
</P>
<P>
   Two of Lambowitz's graduate students, Michael Karberg and Huatao
Guo, who recently earned his doctorate, also authored the Science
paper, as did Duke researchers Meredith Long, J.P. Jones III and
Bruce Sullenger.
</P>
<P>
   What they describe in the Science article is a method to convert
junk DNA from bacteria in the laboratory into a vehicle that can be
used to introduce genes or disrupt specific genes in human cells.
The cells in the experiment are outside the body, floating in a
culture dish. The researchers used the same procedure to target DNA
_ the material in cells that have the genetic instructions for
making living organisms _ in bacteria they wanted to manipulate.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, scientists could not steer genes, which are pieces of
DNA, to a specific site. Other procedures for introducing genetic
material into cells did not work well because the vehicles insert
randomly and can be dangerous if they disrupt the wrong genes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``magic bullets,'' as Karberg called them, are group II
introns, or junk DNA, found in bacterial cells.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think group II introns are ancestors to human introns,''
Guo said.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of the DNA in humans is believed to be junk,
Lambowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For gene therapy or genetic engineering, what you're trying to
do is create an organism with a specific gene function,'' Lambowitz
said. ``You also can insert something into a harmful gene or virus,
causing it not to function.''
</P>
<P>
   If the scientists succeed in making the process work with human
chromosomes in the lab, they will move to human trials. Lambowitz
and his colleagues will work on HIV, the virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to remove T-cells from HIV patients, put the cells in
a laboratory dish, modify them so they are resistant to the virus
and reintroduce the cells into the body. That would produce a
healthy population of T-cells, the ones that get wiped out by HIV.
If it works, the HIV should not develop into full-blown,
potentially deadly AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has a reasonable shot of working, but it hasn't worked
yet,'' Lambowitz said. ``I don't want to encourage someone that
there will be a cure for AIDS in two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Lambowitz has been working on some form of the research since
1993, while he was still a professor at Ohio State. The concept of
targeting genes with junk DNA was born in 1997, and the
possibilities of what could be done have escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just limited to humans,'' Karberg said. ``We can
work with people's pets, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
