<HEADER>
A8153 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-775(2TA     07-20 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOTH SIDES TAKE DAY TO CATCH THEIR BREATHS AND REASSESS POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THURMONT, Md. _ With President Clinton's departure for Japan,
the energy drained from the Israeli-Palestinin peace summit on
Thursday as the exhausted delegations slept late and then worked
with the American team to determine how to move beyond the impasse
and the mutual accusations of bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   Squirreled away in their cabins in the woods, the Israelis and
the Palestinians tried to recover from the roller-coaster drama of
late Wednesday night when, within the span of an hour and a half,
the summit died and was reborn.
</P>
<P>
   After teetering on the edge of a collapsed peace process, and
contemplating an uncertain future with the potential for renewed
violence, they voluntarily returned on Thursday afternoon to the
same stumbling blocks, the same frustrations, the same elusive
prospects for a final accord.
</P>
<P>
   The Israelis said that they remained at Camp David, unpacking
their bags and reclaiming their golf carts, only because Clinton
had asked that they stay until his return on Sunday or Monday.
``When the president asks, you can't say no,'' a senior Israeli
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Israeli official said that the president made the
request after the White House announced that the talks were over.
He said the Israelis believed that the announcement at 11 p.m. on
Wednesday night was a gambit meant to provoke some eleventh-hour
decision-making. And when no decisions were provoked, the Israeli
said, Clinton decided to prolong the summit.
</P>
<P>
   American officials contest this account, saying that Prime
Minister Ehud Barak of Israel took the initiative and, facing a
return home empty-handed, asked that the negotiations continue.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also said that Shlomo Ben Ami, a popular Labor Party
politician and an effective negotiator, helped talk Barak into
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, however, Israeli officials said on Thursday, on the
10th day of the summit, that they did not see anything left to
discuss. They said they were awaiting answers from the
Palestinians, who, they claim, have hedged their responses to
American compromise proposals on most issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is now in Arafat's court,'' Yitzhak Herzog, the
Israeli Cabinet secretary, said in an interview referring to the
Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat. ``My uncle Abba Eban once said
the Palestinians never miss a chance to miss a chance, and I hope
and pray for all our children that they don't miss this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials denied the Israelis' interpretation of
where things stood, saying the Israelis were simply trying to
portray themselves as flexible and the other side as intransigent.
It was the Israelis who wanted to leave, they said, and they wh
wanted to remain so as to leave no stone unturned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be held responsible for the failure of the
talks,'' said Samir Ghousheh, a member of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's executive committee. ``If we hang tough, it will
become clear that it is the Israeli side that is insincere.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Palestinians believe that the Americans are permanently
biased toward Israel, even if Clinton himself has diligently
nurtured a relationship with Mr. Arafat, and they contend that the
summit is inherently built to disfavor them.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, they say, has the ultimate power to say no, but, after
seven years of building an international consensus for a
Palestinian state, he wants to reserve that power so as not to
endanger what he has created.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried about the failure of the summit,'' said
Sulaiman al-Najjab, a member of the PLO executive committee. ``We
are worried, too, about the bias of the United States. Any failure
will be as a result of such bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of pressuring Israel to respect international
resolutions, they are pressuring us to make more concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``So far, the American and Israeli proposals haven't
met our expectations, but we must keep trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Israeli television, reflecting its delegation's line, reported
that the Israeli delegates would be ``resting'' until Clinton
returns from the Group of Eight meeting in Japan to try to persuade
the parties to end their 52 years of bitter conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said the delegations would do more than
rest; they would return to the tables to tackle once more the
division of the West Bank, the future of Jewish settlements, the
fate of Palestinian refugees and the thorniest issue, the status of
Jerusalem. Indeed, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright held long
meetings with both leaders on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Day 10, and the success is that they're still
talking,'' Richard Boucher, the State Department spokesman, said on
Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, the peace camp and the members of the silent majority
that supports peace voiced relief that Barak had decided to stay at
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Rightist leaders expressed anxiety about the concessions that
Barak seemed prepared to make turning over Palestinian
neighborhoods in Jerusalem to Palestinian control, for instance, as
well as any that might go even further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barak has set a dangerous precedent,'' Ariel Sharon, leader of
the Likud Party, said in a television interview. ``We'll have to
work hard to reverse the decisions he made in the last nine days.''
</P>
<P>
   In the West Bank, a number of Palestinians said they were
relieved that the talks were continuing because they fear a
disintegration of the region into chaos and violence.
</P>
<P>
   And several analysts in the Arab world said that while they were
heartened that substantive talks had taken place, they believed
that the stumbling blocks _ particularly, the disagreement over
Jerusalem _ might be insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that the outcome of this summit is zero,'' Abdel
Barri Utwan, editor of a London-based Arabic newspaper, said in an
interview on al-Jazeera satellite television. ``They wouldn't keep
going for nine days if there was no understanding. Maybe there are
some unresolved details on Jerusalem. Nevertheless, these details
have the power to destroy the negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat reportedly told the Americans that he does not believe
that he has a formal mandate from the Arab and Muslim world to
recognize the Israeli annexation of East Jerusalem and cede
sovereignty forever. That kind of recognition is what Israel is
seeking, in exchange for giving the Palestinians control over
Palestinian neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat has to worry not only about his constituency at home,
but his constituency in the Arab world as a whole,'' said a senior
Western diplomat in Cairo.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid what is seeming like an irresolvable issue and a
potential deal-breaker, the Americans have crafted a draft
agreement that leaves the issue to the side but still pronounces an
end to the conflict, diplomats say.
</P>
<P>
   But both the Israelis and the Palestinians are extremely
reluctant to back a partial deal.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the news blackout, it is impossible to know precisely
what is on the table. But, at its core, analysts and diplomats in
contact with the parties believe that an accord would establish a
demilitarized Palestinian state on about 90 to 95 percent of the
West Bank, with the rest being annexed to Israel. The territory
would be transferred gradually to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian officials acknowledge that Barak has gradually
agreed to give more and more land, from a starting point of 50
percent of the West Bank. But they say it is hard to talk about
land without talking about Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials argue that the Palestinians should not reject
what the Israelis consider a generous offer that goes beyond what
any politician who comes after Barak would be prepared to make. A
rightist politician, they say, would never contemplate it, and
those doves who are Barak's political rivals do not have the his
security credentials, as a career general.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to think history will judge the Palestinians harshly if
they miss the Barak moment,'' said David Makovsky, a senior fellow
at the Washington Institute for Near East Policy who has chronicled
the peace effort for the last decade. ``I don't think they'll find
a more accommodating Israeli leader, or one with equal clout. I
think he's Israel's DeGaulle and this is the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   An American official, however, said that a letter Barak sent to
Clinton on Wednesday revealed an imperiousness that would serve to
rally the Arab world around Arafat. In the letter, Barak said that
the Palestinians were negotiating in bad faith.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
