<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8156 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-TECH-HOTEL0721-COX     07-20 1694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-HOTEL0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hotels catering to tech-savvy travelers
 &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When Bass Hotels &AMP; Resorts Inc. purchased the
partly renovated Stephen F. Austin Hotel in January, the company
made sure of one thing: that the 1924 building be wired and fitted
with the latest communication technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The historic hotel at Seventh Street and Congress Avenue
reopened in May as the most technologically advanced among the
company's 41 upscale Inter-Continental hotels in the Western
Hemisphere. All guest rooms and four meeting rooms boast T1
high-speed Internet connections _ the standard in large
corporations, about 90 times faster than 56K modem _ and 250
direct-dial telephone numbers are rotated among the 189 rooms. Each
room is equipped with three telephones that provide voice and data
options. Guests can review charges and check out on the 29-inch
televisions in the rooms. Even the mini-bar is high tech: Infrared
sensors and pressure switches send messages down to the front desk
when an item is removed, and the guest is automatically charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to have an impact in a high-tech city, we have to
come with the best technology,'' says Manrique Rodriguez, general
manager of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   But in reality, the Stephen F. Austin had no choice: To compete
for the tech-savvy business traveler visiting Austin, a hotel must
offer more than a pants press in the rooms and free shuttle service
to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of hotels, Austin is the most wired city in the
nation,'' says Brett Stewart, the co-founder and CEO of
Austin-based Wayport Inc., one of the leading Internet service
providers for hotels across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, at least 14 hotels advertise high-speed Internet access
in all guest rooms, and several others plan to offer the service in
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the nation is quickly catching on. In a report
released this week by technology market research firm Cahners
In-Stat Group, 48.2 percent of more than 300 hotels surveyed
nationwide said they plan to install high-speed Internet access in
all rooms over the next year. Another 34.1 percent said they plan
to offer it within two years. That's compared to just five percent,
or about 1,400 hotels, that offer high-speed access today.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts predict that in three to four years, fast
Internet access will be found even in roadside motels.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like the Four Seasons Hotel Austin and the Driskill Hotel,
have upped the ante. They offer fast wireless Internet access in
public areas _ the lobby, the bar, the restaurant, many of the
conference rooms, and at the Four Seasons, even the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The Four Seasons, as a test case for Wayport, was the first
hotel in the world to have a wireless Internet network, in 1997.
But only now do some guests come equipped with wireless Ethernet
cards that allow them to use the service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's way cool,'' says Richard Paine, advanced computing
technologist for The Boeing Co. in Seattle, who attended a meeting
at The Four Seasons three weeks ago where nearly all of the 225
attendees used the wireless network. ``This makes it much more
convenient because you're connected all the time. You don't have to
wait until you get to your room.''
</P>
<P>
   Paine said he used the connection during the conference,
sponsored by communications technology consortium The Open Group,
to log into Boeing's secure internal Web site and to check
corporate sites to verify information during presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Paine, who spends about half his time traveling around the
country and to Europe and Asia on business, said it was the first
time he used wireless Internet in a hotel.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the latest technology offered in hotels was voice
mail. Now, at the Driskill, for example, WebTV with a wireless
keyboard is available for $9.95 a day. ``It's almost as if you're
outdated as soon as you put it in,'' Britt Meylan, conference
services director at the hotel, says of new technology. That's why
the hotel, midway through a major renovation last year, decided to
wire half the building with Category 7 cable, the latest in
high-speed networking, but more than the hotel needs for its
current T1 connections.
</P>
<P>
   NO LONGER 'LAGGARDS IN TECHNOLOGY' Technology is rapidly
changing the experience of staying in a hotel. A hotel in
Vancouver, British Columbia, features a remote bedside console that
can adjust the lighting and room temperature, illuminate the ``Do
Not Disturb'' sign and, in some rooms, open and close the window
drapes. Other hotels are testing new frequent traveler ID cards
that would serve as keycards and provide personalized access to a
WebTV unit. An upscale hotel set to open in New York next month is
secretly working out the kinks of a plan that would eliminate the
front desk and instead equip bell hops with Palm Pilots to check in
guests.
</P>
<P>
   This frenzy for the latest in high-tech is remarkable for
hoteliers, who ``historically have been laggards in technology,''
says John Paul Nichols, executive vice president for the hotel
division of Cendant Corp. The corporation is in the process of
wiring all 6,400 of its hotels _ eight brands that include Super 8,
Travel Lodge, Howard Johnson and Wingate Inn _ for high-speed
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The adoption rate in the industry is exploding and a lot of
that is driven by the explosion of the Internet,'' Nichols says.
``If you've got it in your house, you've got it in work . . . you
better darn well have it in your hotel room.''
</P>
<P>
   Even landmark hotels like the 114-year-old Driskill Hotel in
Austin are finding that a historic renovation alone won't attract
customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want to stay in old hotels,'' says Jeff Trigger,
managing director of the Driskill. ``They love history and a sense
of place, but they want the modern world and all the amenities that
brings.''
</P>
<P>
   The Victorian hotel, however, presents technology in subtle
ways. In many cases, it's hard to tell it's even there. LCD
projectors are hidden in ceiling molding in the conference rooms
and, in one meeting room, a faux fireplace with a gilded-framed
mirror rolls to the side to make room for a pull-down screen for
PowerPoint presentations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our business, we're constantly balancing the high-tech and
the high-touch world,'' Trigger said. ``Guests expect high-tech.
(But) we don't want that sort of in-your-face way of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD AGAIN, AND AGAIN Travelers like Dexter Henderson,
director of product introduction and deployment at Austin-based
Tivoli Systems Inc. have come to expect fast Internet connections
on the road. Henderson, who is away from the office for 10 days
every month, only stays at hotels with broadband access. He doesn't
have a wireless Ethernet card _ which costs about $200 _ but
figures it's only a matter of time. He uses the Internet in hotels
to load up different elements for multimedia presentations. ``You
can actually get a lot accomplished on the road,'' Henderson says.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more business is conducted over the Internet,
workers say without fast and ubiquitous access on the road, they
fall behind. The number of people who access the Internet while
traveling increased 190 percent over three years, to 85 million in
1999 from 29 million in 1996, according to a February report of the
Travel Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Gorman, director of wireless programs at the Menlo Park,
Calif., office of The Open Group, lives on the Internet and
wireless networks when he is on the road, which is most of the
time. In Europe, where he has been traveling the past two weeks, he
is constantly connected by cellular phone. And in many places,
notably Scandinavia, he can connect to his company e-mail account
on his laptop through his cell phone. That sort of service will
slowly arrive to the United States, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will revolutionize travel,'' he said over his cell phone
during a cab ride to London Heathrow Airport, where he was catching
a plane to France.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Gorman settles for wireless access on his
laptop at the few hotels that offer the service and at some
airports, like Austin-Bergstrom International Airport, which last
month became the first airport in the nation to offer the service
in all public areas. Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport
launched wireless service last week. Wayport installed wireless
Internet in those airports and is a big reason why Austin is one of
the most wired _ and wireless _ cities in the nation. The company
recently signed a contract to provide wireless service in Katz's
Deli &AMP; Bar and is courting other local eateries.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, chief executive at Wayport, sees a vast market for
wireless Internet in what he calls ``high-loiter retail,'' like
coffeehouses and bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, his biggest focus is hotels. Since the middle of
last year, Wayport has installed or has been contracted to install
high-speed Internet access in nearly 600 hotels. This month, the
company says it plans to install high-speed Internet access in 125
hotels, the most of any month.
</P>
<P>
   As hotels become bastions of high-tech, some in the industry are
left wondering if all of this technology will one day make hotels
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dominguez, director of sales and marketing at the
Sheraton Austin, has received rave reviews for the hotel's new
business conference center, wired for high-speed Internet access
and capable of hosting any kind of high-tech meeting. A local
company, Shield Networks LLC, is setting up a broadband Webcasting
service for future meetings. Anyone with the proper pass code could
log into a meeting and watch it on a computer from anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   While Dominguez predicts it will be a popular feature, he
admits, ``that's actually frightening as a hotelier. Because if you
don't need to go to the meeting, people are going to stop
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little far-fetched right now, but I can see it
happening,'' he says of virtual meetings. ``Why travel if you can
sit at home?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
