u f BC-MEXICO-ECON-NYT &LR;      07-20 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSPIRED BY VICENTE FOX, EX-WORLD BANK OFFICER HELPS STEER MEXICO'S
FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Few economists put their faith in pipe dreams,
much less the visions of politicians looking toward higher office.
But Luis Ernesto Derbez _ a World Bank manager who had served in
Africa, Asia and Central America _ said he let his emotions take
the lead when he decided to join the improbable quest of Vicente
Fox for the Mexican presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Derbez was living in Washington when he
received the invitation from Fox. He had met Fox, then a state
governor and a prominent aspirant for his center-right party's
presidential nomination, a year earlier while guest teaching at the
Technological Institute of Higher Studies in Monterrey. The
meeting, Derbez said, left him inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vision that Vicente Fox proposed, of what needed to be
done in Mexico, of the changes that he thought needed to be carried
out, was a vision that at the time sounded like a dream, but it was
a great necessity for the country,'' Derbez said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a decision that was part emotional and part rational,''
he said about joining the Fox campaign. ``It was professionally
rational in that it meant working with someone like Vicente Fox.
And emotional because he really was a person that stirred my
enthusiasm.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, Fox stirred the nation when he became the first
candidate in 71 years to wrest the presidency from the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party. Earlier this week, Fox announced
the leaders of his transition team _ 18 men and two women
responsible for seeking out the best ideas, programs and people for
his administration, which will take office on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Derbez was named co-chairman of the economic committee with
Eduardo Sojo, an economist and a former student. But members of the
transition team say that to the president-elect, the 53-year-old
Derbez ranks first among equals.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Derbez said, he served as a kind of movie
director _ working behind the scenes with a brain trust of hundreds
to develop ideas for government reform and then turning them into
themes for campaign speeches. Since Fox's triumph, Derbez has been
more prominent in public.
</P>
<P>
   He has held Wall Street teleconferences and meetings with
reporters as part of the president-elect's effort to signal a new
openness in government. He has helped calm concerns that Mexico, as
in 1994, could plunge into an election-year financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and his advisers promise to increase economic growth to 7
percent midway through the six-year presidential term and to create
1.4 million jobs a year. Derbez and Sojo, who has a master's degree
from the University of Pennsylvania, will work with the current
administration of President Ernesto Zedillo on next year's budget
with the aim of increasing spending on education and small-business
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Derbez himself is the product of a small family business _ his
parents ran a clothing factory that employed 20 workers. A husband
and father of three, he earned a master's degree in economics at
the University of Oregon and a doctorate in industrial organization
at Iowa State University.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the Fox campaign in 1997, he had worked 14 years
managing economic adjustment programs for the World Bank, served as
an independent consultant to the Inter-American Development Bank
and was a visiting professor at the Johns Hopkins School of
Advanced International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   Derbez said he had been looking for years for some kind of work
to bring him back to Mexico, but had not been inspired or intrigued
until he met Fox. Upon joining the president-elect, Derbez began
seeking out the best Mexican minds, at home and abroad, for advice
on how to manage the next government.
</P>
<P>
   This is an approach, he said, that the Fox administration hopes
to incorporate into its regular activity, allowing smart and
talented Mexicans living abroad to serve as advisers to government
agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Derbez said that the creation of such advisory groups, along
with giving Mexicans abroad the right to vote in elections, are
some of the steps the new team hopes to take to inspire Mexican
expatriates. ``There are people that send us messages, that want to
participate,'' he said, ``and so the challenge right now is to
gather the information and to organize some kind of programs with
them.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there are rough and politically sensitive
conversations headed Derbez's way. Among some of the new
government's plans are wide-ranging fiscal changes to help raise
money for increased social spending in areas like education and
health care. The changes would include an end of some corporate tax
exemptions and the imposing of taxes on food and medicine. The Fox
advisers will also explore opening the electric power and
petrochemical industries to private investment.
</P>
<P>
   Previous privatization attempts in those industries have failed,
largely because of strong union opposition to the sale of
businesses related to oil. Since Fox's election, the union stance
has hardened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever controls petrochemicals, controls the oil,'' said
Victor Garcia, a spokesman for the Mexican oil workers union.
``Whoever controls oil, controls the economy. Whoever controls the
economy, controls politics. And whoever controls politics controls
the country. That is why we will not support privatizing
petrochemicals. It puts our sovereignty at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Derbez has had experience in navigating politically sensitive
matters. As a division chief in West Africa for the World Bank from
1992 to 1994, he supervised negotiations between France and 14
former colonies regarding the devaluation of their currency, the
CFA franc. The currency's value was cut in half overnight, causing
outrage among many Africans.
</P>
<P>
   Derbez managed the storm, satisfying all sides, his boss at the
World Bank in those years, Olivier Lafourcade, said. ``It was one
of the most delicate and highly complicated issues we had ever
dealt with at the bank,'' said Lafourcade, who is now director of
the World Bank office in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he plans to handle opposition to Fox's plans, Derbez
invoked that same spirit. ``What cannot be done is to make abrupt
decisions and impose them from above,'' he said. ``And what must be
done is conversing with all the groups affected, to learn their
point of view and their worries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
