<HEADER>
A8162 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f BC-AIR-EARNINGS-TEX     07-20 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-EARNINGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES POST LARGE PROFITS FOR QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
 By DAN REED 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ |Delta and Northwest airlines on Thursday
capped a three-day period in which the nation's nine largest
airlines reported a whopping $1.7 billion quarterly profit by
capitalizing on record passenger demand to more than offset a 50
percent jump in fuel prices.
</P>
<P>
   Of the nine, only US Airways and America West Airlines failed to
exceed analysts' profit estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Delta topped United and American airlines with a June quarter
profit of $460 million. In the same period a year ago, the company
earned $364 million.
</P>
<P>
   Delta outperformed United and American even after excluding its
own one-time accounting charges. Delta earned $376 million in the
quarter, excluding unusual items. Meanwhile, before adjusting for
one-time accounting items, United parent UAL Corp. earned $370
million and American parent AMR Corp. earned $321 million.
</P>
<P>
   Each share of Delta stock earned $3.51 in the quarter, compared
with $2.40 per share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Northwest also exceeded analysts's expectation of a 98
cent-per-share quarterly profit by earning a net profit of $115
million, or $1.26 per fully diluted share in the quarter ended June
30. Revenues rose 12.7 percent to $2.9 billion. Through the first
six months of the year, Northwest earned $118 million, or $1.29 per
share. The company's six-month revenues rose 12.7 percent to $5.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the positive earnings report, Northwest shares lost
$1.4375 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange, where they
closed at $33.25. Delta stock, however, gained 25 cents to close at
$53.875 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Like all of their rivals, both Delta and Northwest reported
unprecedented levels of demand. Delta recorded a record 77.5
percent load factor for the quarter, while Northwest filled an
average of 79.7 percent of its seats, its all-time highest
quarterly load factor.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
