<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore, Bush trade jabs in Texas
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight and Jena Heath
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO They stood 90 miles apart and took turns swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore flew into San Antonio Thursday to accuse
Gov. George W. Bush of squandering a state budget surplus by
favoring the oil industry and special interests with $1.7 billion
in tax breaks even as he resisted paying for health insurance for
poor children. Two hours later, Bush emerged from the governor's
mansion to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that Gov. Bush is a popular and well-liked
governor here, and I want to give him some credit on that score,''
Gore said. ``I think he has a warm and engaging personality. But,
you know, the presidency is more than just a popularity contest. It
involves whether or not you're willing to fight for what's right,
whether or not you're willing to spend some popularity to do
difficult, hard things.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore called Texas, ``a wonderful state,'' but said it should
also be ``a state where it 's just as easy to raise a child as it
is to set up an oil rig.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush defended his record, saying he cut taxes ``in a fiscally
responsible way,'' and that the state now has a $1.4 billion
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Vice President Gore to claim otherwise for his own
political purposes is a travesty,'' Bush said. ``He should be
ashamed. Texas doesn't need the vice president to lecture us on
balanced budgets.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore continued pounding Bush's two terms as governor, saying the
state leads the nation in industrial pollution, ranks second in
child poverty, third in deaths from asthma and last for women with
health insurance. And he sliced at Bush's efforts to attract Latino
voters, saying that half the children in Texas without health
insurance are Latino.
</P>
<P>
   The two went mano -a -mano as the Bush campaign unveiled three
new campaign advertisements slated for the key swing states of
Ohio, Pennsylvania, Florida and Washington in the days leading up
to the Republican National Convention, which begins July 31 in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's was the toughest direct criticism Bush's legislative
record has had in years here _ even if few Texas Democrats showed
up Thursday to help Gore make his point. State Sen. Mario Gallegos,
D-Houston; and state Reps. Carlos Uresti and Ruth Jones McClendon,
both San Antonio Democrats, appeared with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has spent almost two weeks attacking Bush for
pushing through a $1.7 billion tax cut last year after news reports
that cost overruns in the Medicaid and prison programs have left
the state budget $610 million short.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Republican state Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander held a press conference to say that the state now has a
$1.4 billion surplus _ more than enough to cover the shortfall and
a rosier projection than the $1.1 billion she unveiled five days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said there is ``a rush by the governor's political allies
to try to put a gloss on it. And the governor told one of the
newspapers represented here last week that he hopes to not to be
around to have to deal with it next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing with Bush, campaign spokeswoman Karen Hughes said Bush
was joking when he made the remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, his sense of humor, other people don't always
understand it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that every state budget is balanced.
</P>
<P>
   `` I'm proud that under my leadership, working with Republicans
and Democrats, Texas has increased spending for education,
increased spending for health care, built and funded prisons and
cut taxes by record amounts,'' he said. ``And we still have a large
surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes offered to sit down with Gore to explain the state's
budget numbers, an offer the Gore camp declined.
</P>
<P>
   ```She's no Alan Greenspan; she's a Republican partisan,'' Gore
spokesman Chris Lehane said, adding that Gore preferred to talk to
``real families in this state who have been impacted by (Bush's)
wrong-headed decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Dick Armey, (R-Irving) also got into the act.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just another example of Al Gore not wanting to let the
facts get in the way of making a good argument,'' Armey said in an
e-mail sent to political reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, amid a plunge in oil prices that made it more costly
to operate numerous low-producing wells than to shut them down,
Bush strongly backed a temporary suspension of the severance on oil
and gas production. He gave the bill emergency status, and it was
the first measure he signed into law during the session. The tax
breaks were capped at $45 million.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, legislators pushed to expand the Children's
Health Insurance Program, a federal-state effort to help low-income
families who make too much money to get Medicaid coverage but not
enough to afford insurance coverage on their own. Democratic
lawmakers wanted to set the threshold for families to qualify at
200 percent of the federal poverty level; the governor's office
favored 150 percent. In the end, the Legislature approved the 200
percent cap and Bush agreed.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writer Gary Susswein contributed to
this report, which also includes material from the Associated
Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
