<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-SPINOFF0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin center part of Lucent spinoff
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Lucent Technologies Inc., the big maker of
communications equipment, said Thursday it will spin off its $4
billion microelectronics business, which includes a promising chip
development center in Austin formerly known as Agere Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoff, which also includes Lucent's business for
developing components used in high-speed optical networks, is
expected to take place in the first quarter of next year. The new
company, which is still unnamed, plans to offer 20 percent of its
shares in an initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dividing Lucent in order to accelerate growth,'' said
Richard McGinn, chairman and chief executive of Lucent, which is
based in Murray Hill, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Lucent said it would spin off another part of its
business devoted to corporate networking equipment later this year.
That business, which Lucent named Avaya, has not been spun off yet.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent made the announcement at the same time it released its
second-quarter financial results. Net income was $1 billion, or 30
cents a share, on revenue of $8.7 billion. Net income was up 30
percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Investors pushed the stock downward Thursday when management
forecast that the company's growth will slow in the second half of
this year. The stock closed down $10.06 a share, or 15.6 percent,
at $54.44 in New York Stock Exchange trading.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's operations in Austin develops high-speed communications
processing chips.
</P>
<P>
   A top manager locally said the spinoff will help the chip
business. ``It's definitely good news,'' said Eric Rothfus,
director of the Austin business unit. ``Here in Austin we will
expand more aggressively what we do. This gives us the opportunity
to recruit more people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, which acquired Agere Inc. in April for more than $400
million in stock, employs more than140 people in Austin and expects
to expand to 180 by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, based in Allentown, Pa., will have 16,000
workers, including a share of the famed Bell Laboratories research
center. It will concentrate on chips for wireless and wireline
communications equipment, going up against rivals such as Motorola
Inc., Texas Instruments Inc. and Conexant Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent was the world's 16th largest semiconductor maker in 1999
with sales of $3.3 billion, up 18 percent from the year before. The
company said it had $4 billion in sales in the past four quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a force to be reckoned with,'' said analyst Will
Strauss with Forward Concepts of Tempe, Ariz. ``And now they are
let loose on the world.'' Cutting its ties from Lucent should help
the spinoff win more sales with equipment makers that formerly were
reluctant to do business with a major competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The communications components business will now be given the
opportunity to achieve its full potential as it becomes freed from
the strategic conflict if faced as part of Lucent,'' McGinn said.
``And Lucent will now be totally focused on the largest network
buildout in history, a $225 billion market opportunity this year.
We will be able to streamline our operations, increase investments
in the market for broadband and wireless Internet infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
