<P>
   ART ADV: Graphics and photos are being sent, as indicated below,
to NYT Graphics and Photos subscribers. Clients needing
retransmission or information, or nonsubscribers seeking to arrange
individual purchase, should call (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAGE ONE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVESTING-GREENBERG-BUFFETT (Undated) _ One plays the hayseed,
the other the New York tough guy, but Warren E. Buffett of Omaha
and Maurice R. Greenberg of Manhattan _ have a lot in common. Each
has built an empire that has delivered tremendous value to
shareholders. Greenberg, 75, and Buffett, nearly 70, are giants in
the same game. Though both Buffet's Berkshire Hathaway and
Greenberg's American International Group have other operations,
each is mainly in the insurance business. ``We think alike,''
Buffett said recently. ``If you showed us 10 deals, we would
probably come to pretty similar conclusions on most of them.'' That
makes all the more extraordinary this fact: For 10 years,
Greenberg's company has been the better bet for investors. By
Joseph B. Treaster.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphics.
</P>
<P>
   PESYSTEMS-HUNKAPILLER-GENOME (Foster City, Calif.) _ PE
Biosystems has emerged as the leading supplier of equipment to the
exploding genomics industry. The company controls at least 70
percent of the market for gene sequencers. It is the leading
supplier of equipment used for one of the fundamental processes in
biotechnology, the amplification and detection of DNA by polymerase
chain reaction. It is in the early lead for machines used to
analyze proteins. Competitors often refer to PE as the Microsoft of
genomics equipment, for its commanding position and its aggressive
tactics. If PE is the Microsoft, then Dr. Michael J. Hunkapiller is
the Bill Gates, a nerd at heart, who has transformed himself into a
respected, shrewd and tough businessman. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INVESTING-CHARTING (Undated) _ For years finance professors have
held chartists in contempt. The problem has been one of translating
chartists' visual pattern recognition into the mathematics on which
academics rely, according to a new study, in which the authors, all
academics, gauge which charting techniques work. After defining the
chart patterns mathematically, the researchers back-tested the
patterns' predictive prowess for 750 stocks over 35 years ending in
1996. One of their findings is that the patterns predict the future
direction of Nasdaq stocks better than they do exchange-listed
issues. By Mark Hurlbert.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-REITS (Undated) _ It might not be realistic to expect a
Real Estate Investment Trust to be the next Cisco Systems, but a
significant new law is leading some money managers to suggest that
investors look to REIT's as technology plays. They point to REIT's
that are either actively investing in technology to improve
businesses, or that cater to the real estate needs of e-commerce
companies. These companies are poised to benefit from the federal
REIT Modernization Act of 1999, which, in January, will allow
REIT's to offer services like landscaping, parcel delivery, and
telecommunications _ to tenants and other parties. The new law is
``probably the biggest development in the REIT industry since 1986,
when REIT's were permitted to both own and manage real estate,''
says Anthony R. Davis, an analyst at UBS Warburg Dillon Read. By
Sana Siwolop.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-WHITCOMB (Undated) _ Roland P. Whitcomb, the lead manager
of the $799.1 million First American Technology &UR;  &LR; fund, says that in
a technology cycle, value investors get confused by the high
valuation of the stocks, because they underestimate the coming
innovation. Growth investors often have trouble selling, because
they take the growth rate and project it forward, he says. Whitcomb
gives each new technology cycle time to run, an inisght that has
helped the fund return 66.6 percent a year for the three years that
ended July 14, compared with 53.8 percent for its technology peers.
By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   INVEST-Q&AMP;A-BRONSON (Undated) _ Gail Bronson, a senior analyst
for IPO Monitor, and a Silicon Valley venture capitalist, is
interviewed about the new issue market. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS-MUTUAL-FUNDS (Undated) _ Last year the mutual fund
industry discovered the Internet; this year the buzz word is
``wireless.'' Four funds focused on wireless investing have opened
this year, and regulatory paperwork has been filed for a fifth
offering from Fidelity Investments. Further, the telecommunications
fund sector _ previously the best way to play wireless stocks _ has
seen its offerings swell from 10 at the end of 1998 to about 25
funds that are either open or in the pipeline. By Danny Hakim.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL COMMENTARY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Financial column. Subject tk.
</P>
<P>
   WATCH (Undated) Weekly Wall Street commentary. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL INVESTING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-COST (Undated) _ In 1999, a family with pretax income
of more than $61,900 and one child can expect some serious sticker
shock. It will cost an average of $290,000 to raise that child
through age 17, with the heaviest expenses _ $85,000 _ during the
teen years, the Agriculture Department says. By James Schembari.
</P>
<P>
   CELLPHONE-NUISANCES (Undated) _ Stories abound about annoying
cell phone usuage in public places, but this report by Lawrence Van
Gelder has some of the funniest. One New Jersey man recalls a scene
in a restaurant after a diner, talking loudly on a cell phone,
finally said, ``Goodbye.'' The New Jersey man also said,
``Goodbye.'' This was followed by a chorus of ``goodbyes'' from
around the restaurant and then ``a wave of laughter.'' Then there's
the New York announcer who asked theatergoers to turn off cell
phones and beepers. He was interrupted by his own beeper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BOARD-DIRECTORS (Undated) _ The average length of tenure on
corporate boards is dropping and turnover is rising. More seats are
going to outside directors. and chief executives are joining fewer
boards. The changes also mean that there are more opportunities
than before to become a director for the first time. This story
gives specific steps ambitious executives can take to improve their
chances. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   FRIDGE-CHINA (QINGDAO, China) _ The Haier Group has become
China's largest appliance maker, with sales of $3.2 billion last
year. It is also one of China's largest exporters, selling $1.4
billion of products in 160 countries. Earlier this year, Haier
opened a $30 million refrigerator factory in Camden, S.C. Why make
fridges in South Carolina when China is so much cheaper? Zhang
Ruimin, Haier's chief executive, said he wants to learn to compete
with General Electric and Whirlpool on their home turf. Thinking
like that is why Zhang is being identified with one of America's
best chief executives, Jack Welch of GE. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-SHAKESPEARE-POWER (Undated) _ ``Power Plays: Shakespeare's
Lessons in Leadership and Management,'' by John O. Whitney and Tina
Packer is a testament on practicality and morality in business,
illuminated by instances from Shakespeare. ``Hamlet'' provides a
backdrop for an admiring sketch of Jeff Bezos of Amazon.com, whose
focus, decisiveness and fleetness is compared with the vacillation
of Hamlet, how could neither lead nor follow. Falstaff becomes the
opportunity to talk about business' distaste for the inspired
oddball. The book notes that Shakespeare _ a wealthy, worldly man _
was at home in a market-driven society. By Fred Andrews. (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   BIKE-POST-OFFICE (Undated) _ Cheering on professional cyclists,
Gail Sonnenberg has one thing in mind: increasing sales at the U.S.
Postal Service. As senior vice president of sales, Sonnenberg began
overseeing the Postal Service's cycling-team sponsorship in 1997
just as Lance Armstrong emerged from his bout with cancer to join
the squad. Last year, the team with its uniforms emblazoned with
the Postal Service logo was the first American squad to win the
Tour de France, a morale raiser at the post office. It also brought
the post office $10 million in revenues from other sponsors, she
said, and the association with Armstrong brings glamour to an
otherwise bland brand. By Greg Winter.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AUTOS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-PTCRUISER (Undated) _ The 2001 PT Cruiser,
DaimlerChrysler's category-defying minivan-sedan, owes much to the
'37 Plymouth, the late '30s Ford sedans with a 1950 Chevy Panel van
and a little Willys Overland thrown in. But Dan Niel, reviewing the
vehicle, says its charismatic retro design camouflages a supremely
efficient box-on-wheels. The PT won't tempt hot-rodders, but on
balance, he says, complaints are few and compliments abound. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
