<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8175 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-TEXAS-PRIDE-755(2TAKE     07-20 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-PRIDE-755(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXANS RESENT GORE'S CRITICISMS OF THEIR STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ For months, Vice President Al Gore and other national
Democrats have depicted George W. Bush's Texas as all but a Third
World country. Pollution? Gore says Texas is the most polluted
state in America. Poverty? Gore says that too many of Texas' people
are poor and that the state does too little for them.
</P>
<P>
   Gore even came to Texas on Thursday to continue his criticisms,
questioning Bush's handling of the state budget and his priorities
as governor. Lagging schools, children without health insurance,
pockets of disease _ Gore's ever-expanding list of Texas woes
leaves out mosquitoes and big hair, but it does go on.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Texans, a prideful lot who take a brighter
view of things, are offended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas isn't nearly as backward and Third World as the Gore
campaign would make us out,'' protested Michael Levy, the publisher
of Texas Monthly magazine. ``I personally am starting to get
offended.''
</P>
<P>
   There has always been a divergence between the view others hold
of Texas and the view Texans hold of themselves, with cliches
abounding in both. But the crucible of a presidential campaign
seems to have exacerbated the gap and pricked at the old
resentments of many Texans, who believe that most outsiders have
never understood the state and never will.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just jealous,'' said Phyllis K. Griggs, the mayor pro
tem of McAllen. ``Texas is bigger than life. People feel they can
make fun of it. Have you ever heard anybody make fun of, say,
Nebraska?''
</P>
<P>
   Last week Levy and four other Texans, none of them unfamiliar
with politics or publicity, declared themselves the Proud of Texas
Committee. They wrote to Gore, pledging to defend the honor of
their state against his ``misrepresentations.'' In another era,
that might have involved pistols; in modern Texas, a news release
sufficed. (The release neglected to mention, however, that four of
the committee's five members are campaign contributors to Bush, a
fact Democratic officials happily pointed out.)
</P>
<P>
   The Proud committee has pledged to rebut political attacks on
Texas, and it had better get busy. Earlier this month the
Democratic National Committee, ever helpful in an election year,
issued a travel advisory warning that visitors entering the state
should check their immunization shots. Why? Because below-average
immunization rates in Houston and elsewhere made Texas ``ripe for
epidemic'' _ a playful political swipe that angered local health
officials. Bush campaign officials pointed out that Houston's
mayor, Lee Brown, is a Democrat and a Gore supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Or consider the e-mail message that flashed onto the computer
screens of political reporters across the country in May: ``Texas:
most manure in America.'' Not exactly the makings of a state
slogan, but a report issued by the Sierra Club and Consumers Union
showed that farms in Texas generated more animal waste than those
in any other state. ``We're definitely No. 1 in No. 2,'' said
Reggie James, the director of Consumers Union in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning across the country, Gore regularly blames Bush for
statistics that show Texas leads the nation in many pollution
categories, has one of the highest numbers of children lacking
health insurance and still lags in many national education
rankings. In recent days, with state spending overruns causing
headlines here, Gore has denounced Texas' fiscal ``mess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Governor Bush ran America the way he has run the state of
Texas, our prosperity would vanish and our progress would be
blocked,'' Gore said in San Antonio on Thursday at a meeting with
parents of children who lack health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his staff have aggressively contested Gore's attacks,
accusing him of misrepresenting some facts and taking others out of
context. They say that pollution has declined during the five and a
half years of the Bush administration, a very debatable contention,
and that the state is doing more to insure poor children. They
point out national studies showing educational gains in the state
and fiercely rebut Gore's fiscal criticism, noting that the state
on Thursday announced a budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Others rising to the defense of Texas point to the large number
of immigrants, legal and illegal, coming across the Mexican border,
an influx that often skews state poverty statistics even as cities
like Austin, Dallas and Houston are booming.
</P>
<P>
   They note, too, that Texas has traditionally been a low-tax,
low-service state; outsiders may disapprove of that philosophy,
they say, but that is a separate debate.
</P>
<P>
   Gore does have some admirers in Texas, and they maintain that
regardless of any bruised feelings, the criticism is unavoidable
and necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to have your own family point out that you have
an ugly house, it's another to have someone else say it,'' said Jim
Hightower, a liberal Democrat and former state agriculture
commissioner who now writes books and is host of a radio talk show.
``But there it is. It seems to me that we're not in a very good
position to whine about what Gore is saying.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore, of course, is not indulging in some radical new political
tactic. In fact, his role model could well be Bush's father. In
1988, Vice President George Bush toured Boston Harbor to harangue
his Democratic opponent, Gov. Michael S. Dukakis of Massachusetts,
about pollution.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1992, when the elder Bush, as president, belittled Bill
Clinton's Arkansas as a ``small state,'' Ross Perot, the Reform
Party's nominee and himself a Texan, found the theme hard to
resist. ``I could say that I ran a small grocery store on the
corner,'' Perot offered as an analogy. ``Therefore I extrapolate
that into the fact that I could run Wal-Mart. That's not true.''
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that Texas is a big place; the debate is over
what sort of place it is. Insiders and outsiders have always had a
different take. The old stereotype of cowboys and wildcatters is
badly dated; modern Texas, with more than 20 million people, is
characterized by urban sprawl and increasingly populated by
computer processors, lawyers and office workers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless many Texans still hold dear the self-image that Ann
W. Richards spoke of several years ago when, as governor, she
dedicated an enormous roadside statue of one of the state's icons,
Sam Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is now, as he was then, the image of a Texan,'' she said,
``the image we all believe of ourselves: courageous, strong,
ambitious, shrewd, eccentric, sentimental and just a little too
rowdy for his own good.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of grandeur and of a larger destiny does not always
translate to visitors. Some outsiders never seem to get past the
hot weather. The Chicago Tribune once described Houston as ``a hot,
humid, swampy, colorless flatland metropolis that may already be
beyond physical or social redemption.'' In 1994, for the pro
basketball finals between the New York Knicks and the Houston
Rockets, The New York Post dispatched a sports columnist to offer
its own account of the nation's fourth-largest city. ``This Place
Is a Hellhole,'' the Post headline concluded.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Other affronts are subtler. Gregory Curtis, who recently stepped
down as editor of Texas Monthly, recalls that guests at a cocktail
party in New York seemed genuinely surprised that he had bought his
tailored suits in Texas. Curtis used one of his final columns
before leaving the magazine to excoriate the national media,
especially The New York Times, accusing them of portraying Bush and
Texas unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a suspicion, at least _ or certainly some kind of
discontent _ between the East and Texas,'' Curtis said in an
interview. ``There is an assumption that things in Texas are bad
and backward and on and on. You find yourself being held
accountable for the presumptions of the way that Texas is.''
</P>
<P>
   T.R. Fehrenbach, an author who is an authority on Texas history,
sees an eternal tension between Texans and anyone trying to tell
them what to do. ``I don't think Easterners understand the
territoriality of the native Texan,'' Fehrenbach said. ``This isn't
new. It goes back to before the Civil War. We are always being
pressured by outsiders to get more like them.''
</P>
<P>
   The outside criticism has in recent weeks spurred a modest tizzy
in the state media, spilling from news accounts of the latest Gore
broadside to editorial musings about what it all means to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. George W. Bush has more than a presidential campaign at
stake,'' wrote William McKenzie of The Dallas Morning News in an
editorial last week. ``The idea of Texas itself also is at play in
his race for the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
