<HEADER>
A8177 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f C-COST-CHILDREN-$ADV23-N     07-20 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
STICKER SHOCK: RAISING ONE CHILD FOR 17 YEARS COSTS $290,000 
</HEADLINE>
 C-COST-CHILDREN-$ADV23-NYT   (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By JAMES SCHEMBARI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When my daughter, Marian, turned 13 in May, I asked her what she
wanted for this special birthday. ``Anything within reason,'' I
said. She thought about it a bit, then replied, ``I want to see a
show on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Then she asked if she could bring a couple of friends. She also
wondered if we could go out to dinner before the show. Finally,
shortly before the event, she told my wife that she really didn't
have anything appropriate to wear to a night on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Reason went out the window. By the time the evening was over,
the birthday party cost about $600. I suppose I should be happy
that she didn't ask for a pony.
</P>
<P>
   Marian has been a teen-ager for only a couple of months, but I
am already wondering what the next few years will be like. After
all, while children are undoubtedly expensive to raise, teen-agers
are the most expensive. Their clothing costs jump, as do their
costs for entertainment and, of course, food. Did I mention
birthday parties?
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, a family with pretax income of more than $61,900 will
spend an average of about $290,000 to raise an only child through
age 17, with the heaviest expenses _ $85,000 _ during the teen
years, the Agriculture Department says. And that money, of course,
just gets parents to the start of the horrific college years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, children have many benefits, but they are
expensive,'' said Mark Lino, an economist at the department.
``Teen-agers are the most expensive because they are very
food-intensive, and they have the highest transportation expenses.
These are the years they begin to drive. The average 16-year-old,
Lino said, consumed about $3,000 in food in 1999, compared with
about $2,320 for an 8-year-old. When it comes to clothing, he said,
parents spent almost $1,300 for the 16-year-old, versus $855 for
the 8-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Distler, 50, a high school teacher in Shawnee Mission,
Kan., said she was amazed at what she spends on her 16-year-old
daughter, Kate. ``I wasn't used to paying $60 for a pair of jeans
that looked like they were already worn out,'' Distler said. ``My
husband has sticker shock. We spend about $2,400 in clothes a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the hobbies. Another mom from Kansas, who asked
that her name not be used, said she had spent about $5,000 on
fencing lessons, equipment and trips for her 18-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take them shopping once a week and you get a little
outfit,'' this mom said. ``Then there's the video and DVD rentals,
about $15 a week. That adds up. We keep telling ourselves that we
would be rich if we hadn't had kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some weeks it can be overwhelming,'' she said. ``Like the
prom: that was a lot of money. You think it's not going to be a big
deal, and it snowballs.'' She said the total bill for prom night
was about $570.
</P>
<P>
   Karin Humbolt, the author of ``I Want to Be Rich: A Teen-ager's
Modem to Money'' (Reynolds Publishing, 1998), says there are ways
to mitigate the costs. For one, she said, parents should get their
teen-agers financially involved in the family. She said a child who
works or gets an allowance should be encouraged to chip in, maybe
by paying for entertainment expenses. The children should also
understand where the family's money is coming from and what it
takes to support them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they realize what it takes to get up day after
day, punch that time clock and deal with work,'' Humbolt said.
``Tell them how much it does cost to support the family. The child
will be able to relate to that, and understand why he won't be able
to afford that $100 pair of Nikes.''
</P>
<P>
   I think that is why my daughter understands that we're not
sending her to boarding school in Europe for the eighth grade. That
surprising request came soon after the Broadway trip. She wanted an
adventure, she said, and being an ``A'' student in Spanish, wanted
to immerse herself in another language.
</P>
<P>
   A commendable request, and I admire her maturity, but the school
she had picked out, in Switzerland, costs $35,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how people are doing it, because it's such a
struggle and it's so expensive to raise a teen-ager today,''
Humbolt said. ``Parents really have to plan. It takes a fortune and
six credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if Marian would settle for a pony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
