<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8180 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-ART-290&AMP;ADD     07-20 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-ART-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC REPORTS CLAIMS OF POLICE MISCONDUCT ARE DOWN SHARPLY IN PAST
YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a five-year climb, the number of legal claims
accusing New York City police officers of using excessive force or
other misconduct has dropped sharply, by 25 percent over the last
year, according to city statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction brings an abrupt end to a period, since 1995, when
the number of claims had grown and suggests officers may be showing
greater restraint on the streets in the aftermath of infamous
incidents like the police shooting of Amadou Diallo and the
station-house torture of Abner Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The decrease in legal claims coincides with two other downturns
that have been little noticed amid the sustained public outcry over
high-profile cases of police use of force: The number of police
shootings has declined, as have the n the number of complaints
submitted to the Civilian Complaint Review Board. Civilian
complaints have decreased by 14 percent over the past six months,
officials said, while police shootings last year were down to 31
from the 43 recorded in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when federal prosecutors are arguing that the Police
Department does such a poor job of curbing brutality that it may
require outside oversight, the city can be expected to tout these
decreases as clear evidence that its own reforms, however belated,
have begun to show results. Critics have other explanations: City
lawyers, they say, may have scared off complainants with tougher
negotiating positions, or perhaps the numbers are simply a fluke.
</P>
<P>
   But the decrease is striking: Legal claims against police
officers, which are a precursor to police brutality lawsuits,
declined to 1,766 claims for the 12-month period ending in June
compared with 2,386 filed for the one-year period that ended in
June 1999.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``This is a dramatic one-year reduction,'' said Comptroller Alan
Hevesi, whose office keeps track of all legal claims. ``If the
leadership of the Police Department focuses on the necessary
reforms, it could be the beginning of a meaningful and important
trend that would save the city enormous costs in lives, injuries
and dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials were quick to credit their innovations for the
reductions, citing improvements in training and reforms in the
disciplinary process that they said had rewired attitudes and made
officers more wary of misconduct. Two years ago, for example, the
department began integrity testing, in which undercover officers
pose as angry citizens in elaborate sting operations intended to
weed out officers with a propensity for violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is occurring is that police officers are much more
cognizant of their responsibility to act with courtesy,
professionalism and respect,'' Police Commissioner Howard Safir
said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics remained unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent years, New Yorkers have seen an historical spike in
police action claims,'' said Norman Siegel, executive director of
the New York Civil Liberties Union. ``In light of this history, we
should not jump to any quick conclusions based on one year of data
as to whether this means there is a decrease in police
misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   The drop in legal claims is significant by itself, but it is
particularly interesting in light of the reduction in misconduct
complaints filed with the civilian review board. In the past, when
civilian complaints have declined, critics said the downturn did
not constitute evidence of police restraint but of public mistrust
in the process. In many cases, they said, people mistreated by
police chose to bypass a complaint process they viewed as
ineffectual in favor of simply filing a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the number of legal claims filed each year has been
carefully scrutinized as a second barometer of public
dissatisfaction with the police. The claims, technically known as
notices of claim, must be filed with the comptroller's office. They
serve notice on the city that it is about to be sued by someone who
claims to have suffered as a result of police misconduct or error,
such as the failure to provide proper police protection. Most of
the cases are filed by people who say they were victims of police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, the number of claims alleging police misconduct or
mistakes has risen each year except one, 1998, when it dipped by 8
percent. Last year's total of 2,386 claims appears to have been the
highest number ever filed.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the 25 percent drop this year, Siegel said, the number
of claims is still higher than the 1,500 claims typically filed
annually a decade ago. But police officials said that comparison
was unfair because those numbers were recorded before the merger of
the transit and housing police into the Police Department, a 1994
event that added 7,000 officers to the force.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction this year in claims may present a budgetary bonus
for the city as well. Settling police misconduct cases in recent
years has become a major financial headache. Last year, the city
paid out a record $40 million to resolve claims and lawsuits in
police cases, up from $28 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Berger, a lawyer who monitored police misconduct cases for
the city and now represents plaintiffs in brutality cases, said
that he believes a large part of the decline in claims is
attributable to new strategies the city is employing to control
these settlement costs. In the past year or so, he said, city
lawyers have adopted a much tougher negotiating stance in
misconduct cases and are offering much smaller settlements. The
tactic, he said, has scared off some lawyers who in the past might
have taken on less sensational, less lucrative, but legitimate
misconduct cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not necessarily mean that those cases are not
arising,'' he said. ``It's just that my segment of the bar is
becoming more realistic.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Berger said one client he represented in 1998,
whose home had been mistakenly searched based on a faulty warrant,
received a $200,000 settlement. In a very similar case he has now,
Berger said, the city has offered only $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel S. Connolly, a lawyer who supervises the city's
litigation in police misconduct cases, said he agreed with Berger
that the city's negotiating stance is firmer these days. But he
said that stance does not dissuade people with legitimate claims
from suing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who get scared away,'' he said, ``are the people
who did not have meritorious claims to begin with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
