<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8183 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f C-CELLPHONE-NUISIANCES-$     07-20 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 C-CELLPHONE-NUISIANCES-$ADV23-NYT  
 (For release Sunday, July 23)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   Cell phones, mobile radios, faxes
and tiny digital assistants were supposed to make life better in
this brave new world of communications, . But sometimes, it seems,
they have only made it more of a trial.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I use e-mail and a fax machine and own a cell phone, but I
guess I'm not beeper-literate,'' writes Phyllis Spiegel of
Plainsboro, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls some unseasonably cold days in May, when she agreed
to stay in Princeton with children of some friends who were taking
a short trip to London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The noise started the very first night I tried to sleep in the
master bedroom _ the sound of what I could have sworn was a
foghorn, at regular short intervals without letup,'' she writes.
``I thought it might have been the heating system in the lovely old
house. The children had no idea. It was driving me nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sound continued for two more nights (and days). After the
second night, I moved into the den.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mystery was solved when my friends came home. It was a
beeper, put in a basket on top of a dresser among a bunch of papers
and other materials.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a mobile radio operator and as president of Pro-Tec Mobile
Communications, a wireless communications company in Casa Grande,
Ariz., Catherine E. Sutter has heard a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Her store of anecdotes about communications equipment doesn't
stop with the one about the fellow who, while installing a two-way
radio in a new John Deere tractor, drilled four perfect holes into
a $900 fuel tank. Or the one about the installer who forgot to bolt
down the front seat of a new truck after installing a radio
underneath _ when the customer flipped the seat forward to store
some papers, it went through the windshield.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter has this one to add: A married customer, partying with
the boys, met a woman in a local bar. ``Knowing he needed to buy
himself some more time as they drove off in his truck to the next
bar, he proceeded to call his wife from the truck phone, using the
hands-free speaker,'' Sutter writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the wife answered, he said he was still out with the
boys, and everyone was heading out to eat dinner and he would be
home later. Of course the wife complained, but she accepted his
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his drinking, he forgot to push the `end' button on
the phone. He then started romancing the girlfriend, suggesting a
hotel and complaining about his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``For over 20 minutes, the wife listened to their conversation,
never letting on that the hands-free speaker was still in the
active mode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Needless to say, the great benefits of cellular service caused
a divorce.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A day after Jay Leno complained on ``The Tonight Show'' about
the shouting of cell-phone users, Walter J. Hamilton, a retired
General Electric sales representative in New Milford, N.J., went
out to dinner with his wife, Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   In the restaurant, a cell phone rang, and a man answered and
started talking loudly enough to disturb the chef in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   When the man completed his call, he said, ``Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton then said, ``Goodbye,'' too, and a chorus of other
``goodbyes'' sounded from around the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``A wave of laughter followed,'' Hamilton writes, ``much to the
discomfort of the cell-phone user.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Rosenberg, a sales director at Snowball.com, an Internet
company in San Francisco, was sitting out a long delay at the Los
Angeles International Airport by immersing himself in a book when a
woman within 10 feet of him initiated a cell phone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next 10 minutes involuntarily listening to a
conversation about her date the previous night with a much older
man, and whether it made sense to see him again. Adding to his
torture was the woman's incessant use of ``anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   When the call ended, Rosenberg decided to speak up. ``Excuse me,
Miss,'' he said, ``but that was incredibly rude to subject us to
your personal conversation for such an extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   She shot back, ``My call is no different than two people having
a conversation next to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosenberg is now philosophical. ``What I learned through my
experience at LAX airport is that there are two sides to this
issue, much like smokers and nonsmokers. And each side is convinced
its perspective is correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of smokers, however, public-space etiquette has
forced them to be more considerate of those around them. The
message is that it's not wrong to smoke, but it is wrong to force
your smoke on others in shared public space.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, it may not be wrong to initiate a private cell phone
conversation while sitting in a public place, but from the looks of
it, it is inconsiderate.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   June Lazerus of Manhattan says she was starting to believe that
she had integrated the cell phone into her experiential vocabulary.
Like so many other people, she was past the point where she thought
people were talking to themselves on the street, in an elevator or
on a bus when, in fact, they were talking on cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me a long time to get to this point, and I admit to
some pride in having reached it,'' Lazerus says. ``Informed by my
new reality, I walked past a Starbucks a few days ago and barely
noted the young woman outside who was speaking to no one in
particular. I was halfway across the street before I realized my
mistake. She was not talking on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was asking politely for passers-by to help her out with
some change.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now for the last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Theatergoers are now accustomed to the pre-curtain instruction
from the management to turn off all cell phones and beepers. But
Geoffrey W. Jackson, a retired banker from Manhattan, says he was
attending a New York City Ballet performance at the New York State
Theater in Lincoln Center when he encountered a memorable version.
</P>
<P>
   ``The announcer's own beeper,'' he said, ``went off while he was
speaking.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
