<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0405 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8184 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LUCENT-EARNINGS-ART-N     07-20 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-EARNINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT SAYS EARNINGS WILL MISS EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies said Thursday that its financial results
would fall short of expectations for the next two quarters, at
least in part because the company had been caught off guard by
slower demand for traditional communications systems and the rising
importance of newer technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was the second major disappointment this year
for Lucent, North America's biggest maker of communications
equipment, and it sent the company's shares down about 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company attributed a previous warning about its results
largely to a failure to fully exploit surging demand for optical
communications gear, which transmits information using pulses of
light.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, that failure could be considered a one-time
mistake. But Thursday the company disclosed a deeper set of
problems, led by slowing demand for the company's core telephone
switches, a product line that has consistently made a big
contribution to Lucent's bottom line. In addition, sales of more
advanced systems have not picked up the revenue slack as quickly as
the company had expected, even as the new products generate smaller
profit margins than the old.
</P>
<P>
   The new chief financial officer of the company said Thursday
that many of the company's internal systems were antiquated and
that the company could take significant reorganization charges as
it attempts a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   And the chairman, Richard McGinn, said Thursday that significant
changes in Lucent's executive ranks could be announced by the end
of the month.
</P>
<P>
   But not everything is looking down at Lucent, which is based in
Murray Hill, N.J. For its third quarter, the company announced
earnings that slightly beat analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the unit that makes semiconductors and internal
components for optical systems is doing well, and the company said
Thursday that it would spin off that division as a separate
company. Lucent said it would sell up to 20 percent of the newly
independent operation to the public early next year and distribute
its remaining stake in the unit to Lucent's shareholders next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   That distribution could prove a windfall for Lucent's holders,
but Thursday provided anything but. The company's shares fell
$10.375, to $54.25, shaving more than $33 billion from Lucent's
market value.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a disappointment to us,'' McGinn said Thursday morning
in a conference call with financial analysts. ``This isn't in a
sense in keeping with the `contract' we have with our investors. No
one is more disappointed about this than I am, and I take this
personally. I'm accountable for what happened and for what we need
to do to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   The most visible part of Lucent's troubles is slowing demand for
traditional telephone switches and for the software that powers
those switches. Companies like Lucent usually made a lot of their
money by selling new software for features like Caller ID, call
waiting and three-way calling.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many communications carriers are placing more emphasis on
developing new data and Internet products than on developing new
voice features. And when they do introduce new voice features, they
are finding ways to do so without being locked into the proprietary
software traditionally sold by Lucent and its brethren.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lucent's new breed of optical and data communications
products are taking longer than expected to come to the market in
force. The company is also feeling pressure on its earnings because
of its cat-and-mouse relationship with some of its own customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like going to a car dealer at the end of the month,''
said Steven Levy, a communications equipment analyst at Lehman
Brothers. ``Customers behave the way you train them to behave. When
you're struggling to make a very aggressive sales target, the
customer might not be ready to buy a certain product, so you go to
them and say: `OK, I need to make my number so I'll give you better
terms, or I'll finance it, or I'll discount it.' That's one reason
why Lucent's gross margins have been disappointing for four
quarters in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent also said it lost a big chunk of a major overseas
contract but would not identify the customer. Some analysts
speculated that it was the Saudi Arabian communications monopoly,
while others suggested it was a Chinese communications company.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, underlying all the problems are internal systems
that Deborah Hopkins, who was named Lucent's chief financial
officer in April, describes as largely inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways we are probably still running with AT&AMP;T
processes,'' Hopkins said in an interview Thursday, referring to
Lucent's legacy as part of AT&AMP;T. ``We can now rethink how we do
everything. An example would be billing. Why isn't billing on the
Web? The more you can simplify billing, the easier it is to
collect. That goes to procurement. Why don't we use e-procurement
so we can minimize the layers of handoff and the number of people
involved?''
</P>
<P>
   To get back on track in its next fiscal year, the company will
probably announce a reorganization within the next few months.
``There could be a sizable charge, but there will be a payback and
a business case behind it,'' Hopkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkins said that one arena for structural change could be the
unit that serves big communications carriers. If that happens, one
prime candidate for reorganization would appear to be Patricia
Russo, an executive vice president who runs that group.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said Thursday that its earnings from continuing
operations in its fourth quarter, which ends in September, would
grow about 15 percent compared with figures in the period a year
earlier, leading analysts to say that the company would earn about
$1.10 a share this year. The consensus estimate by analysts polled
by First Call/Thomson Financial had been $1.27 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Lucent's other guidance, analysts said the company was
now projecting to earn about $1.32 a share for its 2001 fiscal
year. The consensus estimate had been $1.55.
</P>
<P>
   For the most recent quarter, Lucent Thursday reported revenue of
$8.7 billion, up 18 percent from $7.4 billion in the period a year
earlier. Including special charges, Lucent reported a loss of $301
million, or 9 cents a share, compared with a gain of $763 million,
or 24 cents a share, in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said it would have earned $1 billion, or 30 cents a
share, without the charges. Analysts had expected the company to
earn 29 cents a share on that basis, according to First Call.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
