<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8185 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-KENNY-QUITS0721-COX     07-20 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNY-QUITS0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `I've decided it's time to do something different. To stretch my
wings.'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kenny Leon, the artistic director and actor who
ignited a sputtering Alliance Theatre Company and moved it toward
the front rank of regional theaters in the 1990s, is stepping down.
</P>
<P>
   The 44-year-old Leon _ a rising star of the national theater
scene who has brought whites and blacks together over idealistic
plays _ dropped the bombshell announcement Thursday. He will leave
the Alliance at the end of the upcoming season, around June 30,
2001. The director seemed almost as stunned as his staffers by the
decision he had reached Tuesday night, while on a golfing vacation
in Pinehurst, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been an emotional day,'' Leon said. ``I decided it's
time to do something different. To stretch my wings. I'll finish
this season _ and I'm excited about it _ but then I have no idea
what I'll do. I have faith that when word gets around,
opportunities will present themselves. I hope theater will be at
the heart of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon, who next month opens his 11th season as artistic director,
leaves the Alliance with its national profile at an all-time high.
And its finances _ not his direct responsibility _ at a new low, $1
million in the red. The 32-year-old theater co-produced the 1998
tryout of ``Aida,'' the Disney hit musical on Broadway, and
premiered the nationally acclaimed Pearl Cleage's ``Blues for an
Alabama Sky'' and Alfred Uhry's ``The Last Night of Ballyhoo''
(winner of the 1997 Tony Award for best play).
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny's talent created an identity for that theater,'' said
Ben Cameron, executive director of Theatre Communications Group,
the New York-based service organization for regional theaters.
``But 11 years is a long time to run a theater these days. Kenny's
decision fits the pattern _ especially for younger directors _
feeling that they can't make the lifetime commitment of that
earlier generation of founding directors.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, although Leon never used the word ``burnout,'' the
syndrome lurked like a shadow over his words.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I gave the news to Debbie Shelton (Alliance board chair)
the other night, I felt like a great weight was lifted from me, and
yet I was saddened,'' said Leon, who grew up poor in rural Florida
and rose through the Atlanta theater scene after graduating from
Clark College in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Sounding a common refrain among those who have left similar
posts in recent years, Leon added, ``The administrative part of
this job is a big drain, it takes me away from the art that I love.
I would like to spend 60 percent of my life directing, and the
other 40 percent either acting, or producing new work, or getting
into independent films . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Leon gave what sounded like a weary laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, I'm going to need a job, man! Maybe McDonald's
has some openings.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone was more somber in the Alliance offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dumbfounded and haven't had time to digest this,'' said
board chair Shelton. ``Kenny has articulated so beautifully our
mission of bringing the community together. The growing diversity
of our audience (about 3-to-1, white to black) and our position on
the national stage is due to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Beauchamp Carr, vice president of the Woodruff Arts Center:
``Sometimes I feel a little amazed that we have managed to keep
Kenny here as long as we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Leon's announcement comes exactly 10 years after the Alliance
board's equally surprising choice of the director, who had no
administrative experience but had dazzled local audiences with his
talent as the theater's associate director. He remains one of just
two African-Americans to lead a flagship regional theater. The
timing of his departure is ironic, for Leon won his hard early
battles for black plays and players; the biracial ``Christmas
Carol'' is a perennial smash. Indeed, recently Leon's drifted
toward more crowd-pleasers on the main stage, though audience
numbers have been erratic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always a challenge to get people in seats _ it's the same
in New York or anywhere,'' Leon noted. ``Was the deficit a burden
on me? Not particularly. No one was pressuring me to do anything
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   `ONE OF THE LAST PLAYERS'
</P>
<P>
   With Leon's departure, the Atlanta talent drain becomes a
hemorrhage. Those making exits in recent months _ often for greener
cultural pastures _ have included Ned Rifkin of the High Museum of
Art, Chris Coleman of Actor's Express, Yoel Levi of the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra and Harriet Sanford of the Fulton County Arts
Council. Their common laments: not enough financial support,
audience apathy.
</P>
<P>
   Leon told the Journal-Constitution last November that he felt,
``I am one of the last players left on the team, and that's a scary
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The director then claimed to be staying put. Ken Bernhardt,
then-Alliance board chairman, said the specter of losing Leon
``scares the hell out of me,'' but that the director was ``morally
and contractually obligated to stay through the 2001-2002 season.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the ramifications of breaking that contract _
whether, for instance, his salary (believed to be around $100,000)
might now be open to renegotiation _ Leon said, ``I don't think
there will be a problem.'' Shelton said there has been no time to
consider that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Leon will be ``intimately involved in the national, or even
international, search for a successor,'' Shelton added, but would
not mention any candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not pushing the panic button,'' said Gus Stuhlreyer,
Alliance managing director. ``We have time for a smooth transition,
and with David Bell (associate director) and Rosemary Newcott
(children's theater director) on board, we're at no loss for
leadership. But there's no question Kenny is our inspirational _
not just artistic _ leader.''
</P>
<P>
   And Leon is at no loss for opportunity _ burger-flipping jokes
aside. He's a superb actor (1998's ``The Blood Knot'' at Theatrical
Outfit) with movie-star looks. He's in steady demand for freelance
directing at such leading regionals as the Goodman Theatre of
Chicago and New York's Joseph Papp Public Theatre.
</P>
<P>
   NO DEFINITE PLANS
</P>
<P>
   Following his collaboration on ``Aida,'' Disney hired Leon to
develop a basketball musical called ``Hoopz'' with Broadway
dancer-choreographer Savion Glover (``Bring in 'Da Noise . . .'').
Although the project was shelved, it sparked speculation that
Disney, film studios or commercial theater producers might be
dangling even bigger offers.
</P>
<P>
   Leon waved the rumors away.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's knocking on my door right now,'' he said. He added
that there were no overriding personal factors in his decision; no
children, for example, from his marriage to Carol Mitchell Leon,
which ended in divorce in 1998. Leon would like to keep ties to the
Alliance and Atlanta, but doubts that there will be enough local
opportunity to allow him to remain here after the close of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been praying and thinking for a long time to know what
kind of change I need in my life,'' Leon said. ``I hope in the next
year to have a clearer idea of what I was put on this planet to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
