<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Banged-up Mets vow to make a late push
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ To be fair about it, the New York Mets are a wounded
team, with three every-day players currently on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   They are finishing up the longest road trip of the season, an
11-game, 12-day voyage that has kept them away from Shea Stadium
since July 9.
</P>
<P>
   They also are in the year's most brutal segment of the schedule,
with 53 of 58 games coming against winning teams. Sixteen of those
dates pit New York against first-place clubs.
</P>
<P>
   So much for fairness. Now the question that is being asked in
two National League cities this weekend: When does the contending
start?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who open a weekend series at Turner Field tonight,
have never let the Braves out of arm's length, chasing them from
second place every day since June 8. They have gotten as close as
one game back, and have lagged as far back as 6 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   It is a long summer. But the Braves continue to brace themselves
for a rush, forecast before spring camp opened, that has yet to
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good,'' said Mets reserve third baseman Lenny
Harris. ``We're keeping the torch lit until we get healthy. And
then we push.''
</P>
<P>
   That Harris was speaking on behalf of the Mets explains some of
the situation. A five-team journeyman over his 13 seasons, Harris
is currently starting for Gold Glove third baseman Robin Ventura,
who is out with a bruised rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   Harris starts next to Melvin Mora, who is subbing for Gold Glove
shortstop Rey Ordonez, out for the year with a broken arm. Starting
behind them in center field is Jay Payton, who has taken starter
Darryl Hamilton's spot while he recovers from foot surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed starter Rick Reed just got off the DL, three weeks
after Andruw Jones broke his wrist with a line drive. The club has
had to call up seven players from Class AAA Norfolk in the past
month alone. The call for a deal for Cincinnati's Barry Larkin,
fanned by the New York tabloids, has taken on religious fervor.
</P>
<P>
   When last they met, the Mets split a four-game series with a
pair of stirring victories _ recall the seven-run comeback _ but
given the chance to seize a share of first place on July 2, New
York fell to Tom Glavine 10-2.
</P>
<P>
   Since that day, the Mets are 6-9, having won just one series in
five. Since the All-Star break, while the Braves have gone 6-1
through the first game of Thursday's doubleheader, New York has
managed a 4-4 record, the second-place deficit going from three
games at the break to 5 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend could tighten things back up. But to be fair about
it, the opposite could happen, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
