u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-20 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: CARLOS SUES
</P>
<P>
   The convicted murderer known as Carlos the Jackal is taking
France to the European Court of Human Rights for holding him in
solitary confinement for almost six years. The Venezuelan-born
ex-guerrilla, whose real name is Illich Ramirez Sanchez, was
sentenced to life in prison in 1997 for murdering three people. He
is accusing the French of using isolation as a torture tactic.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: IRAQI CHEMICALS RULED OUT
</P>
<P>
   The Ministry of Defense said a study had found no evidence that
Iraq used chemical weapons against British troops in the gulf war.
Many servicemen have suffered illnesses, sometimes called gulf war
syndrome, since the 1990-91 conflict, but British researchers
believe the cause was vaccines that troops were given rather than
exposure to chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: `DOCTOR DEATH' INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   Families of the victims of Dr. Harold Shipman, 54, convicted of
murdering 15 patients with heroin injections and suspected of
killing nearly 200, forced the government to hold a public inquiry.
Health Secretary Alan Milburn had sought a private session, saying
it would be quicker. But Lord Justice Kennedy of the High Court in
London said there were ``many powerful considerations in favor of
an open inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: INDIAN CANDIDATES
</P>
<P>
   Indians are planning to run candidates in parliamentary
elections, expected next spring. The move, either with a new First
Nations Party or with existing parties, comes after the rise of
Stockwell Day, leader of the right-wing Canadian Alliance, and
after the election of Matthew Coon Come, a confrontational Cree
leader, as national chief of the Assembly of First Nations. Indians
are believed to hold swing votes in 10 percent of the 301
parliamentary districts.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: BANK CHIEF QUITS
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Corta, the top administrative officer of Mexico's bank
rescue agency, said he would leave his post Sept. 1. He cited
personal reasons, but the resignation comes as the agency's work
has provoked a new battle over whether the government has protected
millionaires who committed fraud during the bailout that began in
1995, which has cost taxpayers nearly $100 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: GOVERNOR TELLS OF BUGGING
</P>
<P>
   The governor of Oaxaca, Jose Murat, from the ruling party known
as the PRI, said he had found hidden microphones in his office and
had ordered his own detectives to investigate, saying he had no
confidence in federal security agencies. His remarks seemed
directed at Interior Ministry officials, some of whom have been
active in a rival faction of the PRI, consumed by infighting since
its electoral defeat.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: PINOCHET MOVE
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has begun analyzing an appeal to decide if
Gen. Augusto Pinochet should lose his legislative immunity in order
to stand trial on charges that he ordered executions and torture.
The Court of Appeals decided last month to strip General Pinochet,
who is a senator for life under the Constitution written during his
regime, of his immunity. The Supreme Court is expected to rule next
month.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: LONELY INAUGURATION
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Hugo Banzer of Bolivia and Gustavo Noboa of Ecuador
are the only heads of state to have accepted invitations to attend
the July 28 inauguration of President Alberto Fujimori, who won a
recent election marred by charges of irregularities and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL, VENEZUELA: PLEA TO SWISS
</P>
<P>
   The two countries have asked the Swiss for help in finding
millions of dollars they say was embezzled by ex-officials. Swiss
officials said Venezuela is seeking money in three accounts
believed to be tied to Carlos Andres Perez, who was twice
president. Brazil wants legal aid in connection with a Geneva
account said to belong to a fugitive judge, Swiss officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: PRESIDENT JEERED
</P>
<P>
   Legislators jeered President Abdurrahman Wahid after he defied
attempts to question him about his leadership, including the firing
of two ministers. Wahid, the first president to be summoned before
Parliament, said that under the Constitution he was not accountable
to them. ``I came here today because of the consideration that we
are just building up real democracy in this country,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
