<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENTIAL ELECTION IS SHAPING UP AS VERY CLOSE IN KEY STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo _
NYT15 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER and RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the confidence displayed by Gov. George W.
Bush's campaign, the presidential election today stands as a very
competitive contest, with ample time and opportunity for either him
or Vice President Al Gore to surge ahead.
</P>
<P>
   At a first glance of the electoral map, Bush is leading in
enough states to assure him an electoral college victory. But in
many of those states, the governor's margin is quite slim.
Moreover, Election Day is more than three months off, and the
contest is entering a crucial phase where the choice of running
mates and the message the conventions deliver could define the
race.
</P>
<P>
   An analysis of opinion polls state by state, along with
interviews with Republican and Democratic strategists in the
campaigns and around the country, found enough crucial states that
are so competitive that those midsummer events, and the fall
debates to follow, could overturn the current standings in state
after state. Or they could solidify Bush's position.
</P>
<P>
   No dominant national issue is defining the race. So if the
contest remains relatively tight, the outcome in crucial states
could be decided by local considerations such as Republicans in the
Philadelphia suburbs deserting their party over abortion _ or by
Democrats in Michigan rallying to the Green Party banner of Ralph
Nader.
</P>
<P>
   For all the emphasis in the press on national polls, where Bush
has maintained long-standing but narrowing leads, both campaigns
are paying closer attention to the outlook in individual states,
because the goal for each side is to plot a path to collect the 270
electoral votes needed for victory.
</P>
<P>
   The state-by-state considerations are so vital that, to a large
degree, they are driving the campaigns' advertising budgets and the
candidates' travel schedules.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gore's top lieutenants held a conference call to
make important decisions about which states they should pump more
resources into _ or not. Gore campaign officials said they had
decided, for instance, not to spend as much in Illinois as they had
planned because they feel confident in Gore's prospects there.
</P>
<P>
   Just the same, one Bush campaign official said that Bush was
doing better than he expected in Arizona, Colorado and Montana and,
as a result, the campaign could scale back its spending in those
states.
</P>
<P>
   The state-by-state analysis shows that Gore is most potent along
the coasts, while Bush has an inland foundation in the South and
mountain states. That leaves the race to turn on several states in
the industrial Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Bush appears safe in 18 states with 140 electoral
votes, from Texas to Alaska to Virginia. Another 11 states,
including Florida, Michigan and Oregon _ with a combined 138
electoral votes _ seem to be leaning his way, though many of them
could easily change quickly. If all these states went for Bush, it
would give him 278 electoral votes, 8 more than needed for
election.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president looks safe in 8 states, from New York to
California to Hawaii, and the District of Columbia, with 134
electoral votes. Another 4 states, from Connecticut to Illinois,
with 39 electoral votes, appear to be leaning his way.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves 9 states, including such powers as Pennsylvania and
New Jersey, as tossups. Combined, they account for 87 electoral
votes.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, if Bush won all the states that are safe or
lean his way, with a total of 278 electoral votes, he could win
without taking any of the tossups. But while many more states are
leaning toward Bush, polls and politicians agree that in several
important states, the governor is barely ahead. It would not take a
shift of too many voters to deny him Ohio, Missouri and Florida,
and then his total would drop precipitously, to 221 electors.
</P>
<P>
   Neither campaign agrees with this analysis. The Bush camp still
insists that the governor is comfortably ahead. Karl Rove, Bush's
chief strategist, said in an interview that Gore had made some
progress in drawing support from Democrats who had been reluctant
to support him. But he said there was no sign that he was pulling
any support from Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some tightening, you bet, because he's bringing
the Democrats home,'' Rove said. ``But nationally, this race has
been essentially stuck at five or six points for the last four
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have also been encouraged that Nader has siphoned
some support from Gore in several states, and by Bush's strength in
some historical Democratic pockets, like Minnesota. The race there
is a toss-up.
</P>
<P>
   William M. Daley, chairman of the Gore campaign, disputed the
idea of even a tentative Bush advantage. ``I think it's basically a
dead heat, basically where it's been for months,'' Daley said.
``People aren't into it. There's a whole slew of states out there
because people aren't focused. Nothing has grabbed them yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the competitiveness came through in interviews in state
after state, where local party heads and strategists described
match-ups that they said were more competitive than in years.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Graber, the chairman of the Republican Party in
Wisconsin, marveled at polls in his state showing Bush slightly
ahead. ``There is a different energy and a different feel from what
we had four years ago,'' Graber said. ``We were written off very
early in the process. There was no money in this state. There was
no TV. It was really free ride for Clinton. That's not the case''
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Russell Feingold, D-Wis., agreed. He said the race in his
state _ where the last Republican to win was Ronald Reagan in 1984
_ was shaping up to be the most competitive in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be terribly close, and I think it could end up
being one of the two or three decisive states,'' he said.
``Everybody should fight like heck to win this state because it's
up for grabs.''
</P>
<P>
   The competitiveness of Wisconsin helped explain why that is one
of 26 states Bush has campaigned in since May. (He was there for
two days.)
</P>
<P>
   Candidates spend very little time in states they expect to lose.
Gore has popped up in Indiana, for example, not once since May, or
about as often as Bush has traveled to Massachusetts (once).
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes candidates take an occasional tactical foray designed
to befuddle the opposition. Gore traveled to Bush's home state of
Texas on Thursday not because he thinks he has a chance there but
to draw free national publicity as he condemned the governor's
record.
</P>
<P>
   And except if there is money to be collected, candidates do not
venture into states that they consider sure wins.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They campaign, in person and on television, in the states where
they think they lead or trail narrowly. For example, starting last
month, Gore began spending heavily on television ads aimed at 18
states: Arkansas, Delaware, Florida, Louisiana, Georgia,
Pennsylvania, Illinois, Kentucky, Iowa, Maine, Michigan, Missouri,
New Jersey, New Mexico, Ohio, Oregon, Washington and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Rove said the Gore commercials had no impact. ``There are now
seven states where we have polling that took place before their
advertising and polling that took place after,'' he said. ``And in
all seven of the states, we've held ground or moved up. The only
way it may have helped is to keep us from moving ahead.'' He said
the advertisements were ``based on a flawed assumption that people
are going to pay a lot of attention to advertising during the
summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, dean of the Annenberg School at the
University of Pennsylvania, disagrees with the Bush camp. She is
conducting the largest polling operation of the year, 100,000
interviews in key states night after night.
</P>
<P>
   She studied the eight states where Gore (through the financial
fig leaf of the Democratic National Committee) spent at least
$300,000 more than Bush (through the Republican National
Committee). Those states were Florida. Illinois, Louisiana,
Michigan, Missouri, Ohio, Oregon, and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, she found that Gore had gained 10 percentage points on
average in those states. ``He was closing substantially,'' she
said. ``It is reasonable to say the ads worked.''
</P>
<P>
   After months in which Bush seemed to have the advantage,
national polls made public this week showed the race closer than
previous surveys by the same organizations. Those national polls,
with their consistent methodology, provide a rough guidelines to
the contours of any presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's close now, and the movement mainly is on Gore's end,''
said John Zogby, an independent pollster.
</P>
<P>
   Yet experts say today's electoral snapshot should hardly be
considered definitive since the public really is not paying much
attention to the campaign in midsummer. Professor Thomas Patterson
of Harvard, a student of public involvement in politics, said his
surveys showed that if people are not given a name but only asked
if they have presidential choice, half say they do not.
</P>
<P>
   Other polls, which offer names, find the undecided numbers as
low as 10 percent. As for the numbers reflecting people's
preferences, Mr. Patterson said, ``I think they are soft.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Here is an analysis of the outlook in several important states:
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN: Leans Bush. He has campaigned hard in the state, and
almost all of Nader's support, 8 percent in one recent poll, is
coming out of Gore's base. Hostility from the auto workers and
teamsters are making it harder for the vice president to capitalize
on economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   MISSOURI: Leans Bush. This is always a swing state, and one that
has picked a presidential winner every time since 1960 Bush is
well-organized, and Gore has not solidified the union support that
is central to Democratic successes in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Leans Bush. But this is a wild card. Gov. Jeb Bush,
George W. Bush's brother, said in an interview he is determined not
to let his state slip through. ``I'm certainly not going to be
embarrassed and have the state go the other way,'' Jeb Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Al Cardenas, the state Republican chairman, said
he feared that Gore could pick Bob Graham, the popular senator from
the state, as his running mate, which would force a competition
there. ``If Graham gives him a couple of points in Florida, in a
tight race we obviously would have to work a little harder,'' said
Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   ILLINOIS: Leans Gore. Brad Goodrich, the Republican Party's
executive director, argues that Bush holds a slim lead and that
Gore's ads have had no effect. But Sen. Richard Durbin, a Democrat
and a potential running mate, said polling information he had
received from Gore headquarters showed the vice president now
leading by a few points. Mayor Richard M. Daley of Chicago is
expected to work hard for the Gore campaign now that his brother
William is in charge of it. He cannot do as much for Gore as the
legendary effort his father made for John F. Kennedy, but he still
matters politically.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO: Leans Bush. Polls in this state, which has a history of
close outcomes, have see-sawed. Robert Bennett, chairman of the
state Republican Party, said that while his candidate is ahead, it
is not by much. He is well aware that the dynamic could change as
the convention opens at the end of the month. ``We could have a
blow up at the convention of some sort,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But David Leland, the state Democratic chairman, said it was no
accident Gore has ventured to the state at least nine times since
the campaign began. ``We won't lose this race for lack of
attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY: Tossup. For most of the century, New Jersey has been
a close state in presidential campaigns _ and usually supports the
winner. Democrats say their only sure shot in the state would have
been if Sen. Bill Bradley had won the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA: Tossup. Gore is cutting into Republican strength
in the Philadelphia suburbs, while Bush is strong in the
southwestern mining counties, and has a strong state organization.
Bush would be strongly favored if he chose Gov. Tom Ridge to be his
running mate, but Sen. Arlen Specter fears the Texas governor could
lose support if it seems his only reason for rejecting Ridge is the
abortion issue.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON: Tossup. Gore got a boost this week when the Clinton
administration decided not to blow up a dam on the Lower Snake
River to improve the salmon habitat. The issue had been killing him
in Eastern Washington where farmers depend on hydroelectric power.
</P>
</TEXT>
