<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARNACO WARNS ON PROFIT AND INVESTORS PUNISH STOCK
</P>
<P>
   Warnaco, the maker of intimate apparel, said that it would miss
earnings estimates by a wide margin, the third time it has missed
projections in the last year. The company said operating earnings
for the 2000 fiscal year would be 26 to 36 cents a share, almost
$1.50 less than estimates. Irate investors sent Warnaco shares down
$1.8125, to $4.9375. They are now down nearly 60 percent this year,
and off 89 percent from their high of $44 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES ADDED TO MUSIC DISPUTE
</P>
<P>
   Expanding their legal attack on the exchange of copyrighted
works on the Internet, the motion picture and music industries sued
to shut down Scour.com, a venture backed by Michael Ovitz that the
industries contend permits not just free trading of copyrighted
music files but of movies. In invoking the film issue, the lawsuit
adds a wrinkle to a dispute that has focused largely on music.
</P>
<P>
   MERGER OF RAILROADS IS CALLED OFF
</P>
<P>
   The largest rail merger in North American history was formally
scrapped as the railroads involved _ Burlington Northern Santa Fe
and the Canadian National Railway _ complained about regulatory
interference and shippers remained convinced that they have not
seen the end of the consolidation that has so far left just a
handful of major freight railroads to serve the United States and
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   MECHANICS CAUSE TROUBLE FOR UNITED
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines, already reeling from the refusal of many of its
10,000 pilots to work overtime, is now facing similar difficulties
from its 15,000 mechanics, whose contract with the airline expired
on July 12.
</P>
<P>
   BERTELSMANN PLANS TO BUY CDNOW
</P>
<P>
   Bertelsmann, the German media conglomerate, will buy CDNow, the
struggling online music retailer, for $117 million in cash. The
deal will give Bertelsmann a recognized brand in online music sales
as it attempts to expand its electronic commerce business.
</P>
<P>
   A GUIDING HAND FOR MEXICO'S LEADER
</P>
<P>
   Luis Ernesto Derbez, a World Bank manager who had served in
Africa, Asia and Central America, has become a leading adviser to
Vicente Fox, the president-elect of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING CONSTRUCTION DECLINES 3 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Housing construction fell 3 percent in June, to its lowest level
in more than two years, responding to a string of interest rate
increases, government figures showed.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT DOUBLES AT AMERICA ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   America Online posted a 115 percent gain in fourth-quarter
profit, slightly beating the expectations of analysts, who said the
results were solid but contained few surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems reported profit that exceeded forecasts, lifted
by continued strong sales of servers that help power the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS FALL AT MATTEL AND HASBRO
</P>
<P>
   Mattel and Hasbro, two of the largest toymakers, said that
second-quarter profits fell as sales slowed and an increase in the
value of the dollar hurt earnings from overseas.
</P>
<P>
   GILLETTE POSTS 2.1 PERCENT GAIN IN PROFIT
</P>
<P>
   Gillette said that its second-quarter earnings rose 2.1 percent,
on increased sales of its Mach 3 blades. Its shares fell after the
company said it would retain its Braun unit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
