<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-JERUSALEM-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JERUSALEM ARABS LOOK EXPECTANTLY AND ANXIOUSLY TO CAMP DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also MIDEAST-TALKS, MIDEAST-TALKS-ISRAEL)  
(ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ On Thursday, Arab residents of East Jerusalem had
been following the reports from Camp David for 10 days with rising
anticipation _ and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 33 years, it appears, Israel has signaled
a willingness to give up some control of the Arab neighborhoods it
annexed here after the 1967 Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
   What that means in practical terms is still moot. But far from
being welcomed as a victory for Palestinian nationalism, the
development has roused fears in East Jerusalem of a compromise that
would fall short of Palestinian aspirations for full sovereignty,
while putting at risk their current jobs, social services and
access to Palestinian and Israeli areas alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very hard time, because people don't know what is
going to happen to them,'' said Ahmed Libekert, the Palestinian
manager of the largest Israeli-run public health clinic in East
Jerusalem. ``My staff keeps asking me. But we just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, liberal editorialists praised Prime Minister Ehud
Barak for ``smashing the taboo'' on discussing a redivision of
Jerusalem. But in East Jerusalem, home to 210,000 Arabs, the
Israeli offer was widely scorned, as Barak reportedly refused to
consider ceding any Arab neighborhoods to a Palestinian state,
offering only limited autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   For Palestinians, the demand for sovereignty in East Jerusalem
is practical as well as ideological. Barak's talk of ``high
fences'' between Israel and an independent Palestinian state has
aroused fears of an East Jerusalem severed from its West Bank
hinterland.
</P>
<P>
   There is also much quiet ambivalence about radical political and
economic change here.
</P>
<P>
   Since being involuntarily absorbed into Israel after the 1967
war, the residents of East Jerusalem have overwhelmingly refused to
opt for Israeli citizenship. But by Israeli law they are entitled
to the same benefits as other city residents.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Hanan, who would not give her last name, is a 38-year-old mother
of six and a regular visitor to Libekert's clinic. She lives in
Beit Hanina, one of the East Jerusalem neighborhoods Israel is said
to be willing to cede to Palestinian rule. She says she worries
about the possible loss of her Israeli health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Ramallah,'' she said, citing the biggest nearby
Palestinian-ruled city. ``There are no health services there like
here. There is no proper social welfare system. The Palestinian
Authority didn't prove itself in Ramallah, so we are afraid of what
they would do here.''
</P>
<P>
   Randa, a young mother of two whose husband suffers from mental
illness, quietly agreed. ``My husband gets treatment in an Israeli
hospital,'' she said. ``If he was in Ramallah, they would not have
been able to provide him with the proper care.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, most Arab residents of East Jerusalem look forward to the
day when they can fly their own flag, answer to their own courts
and even pay taxes to a country that they consider their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think that because of the few shekels I get from the
national insurance, I want to give up my homeland?'' said Khader
Jabsheh, 70, from Shufat, an Arab neighborhood that Israel annexed
after the 1967 war. ``The insurance I get is my right. It is not a
gift from Israel. I have been paying taxes for over 30 years, and I
am entitled to get some of this money back.''
</P>
<P>
   But economic problems are not the only reason some Jerusalem
Arabs have misgivings about Yasser Arafat and the Palestinian
Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Many East Jerusalem intellectuals and political activists,
fervid supporters of Palestinian independence though they may be,
have been openly critical of what they perceive to be the corrupt
and autocratic nature of Palestinian Authority rule.
</P>
<P>
   And some Christian Arabs were alarmed by reports this week that
Israel and the Muslim leader of the Palestinians were debating
control of Christian churches and residential districts in
Jerusalem's Old City. By one account, Arafat's negotiators were
pressing for the area around the Church of the Holy Sepulcher, but
were willing to concede to Israel the ancient Armenian Quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual joint statement, the three patriarchs of the major
Christian churches in Jerusalem lodged a protest against any such
division. They called for ``a system of international guarantees''
of access to the Old City holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Most concerns, though, are not spiritual or political, but
economic. Many here who adamantly favor a full transfer of
sovereignty to a Palestinian state say they expect that change to
bring financial hardships.
</P>
<P>
   Arab residents have long complained about the inequities between
municipal services and educational spending in East Jerusalem and
Jewish West Jerusalem. Now, with nearby towns in the West Bank
under Palestinian rule, the disparities between East Jerusalem and
much poorer Palestinian areas have also come into sobering focus.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ziad Abu Ziad, who oversees the Palestinian Authority's growing
operations in Jerusalem, notes that his department already runs 12
schools with about 15,000 students in East Jerusalem. By next year,
Palestinian officials say, they will control the administration and
curriculum of most schools in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Palestinians ``should copy the Israeli system'' and
put into effect a similar national health insurance plan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, said Ibrahim Shami, a patient at an Israeli
clinic here, Jerusalem Palestinians should be prepared for
sacrifices. ``We may lose services, but we will gain a homeland,
and this is more important than any loss,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
