<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-SOUTHFLORIDA0721-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'We're going to resurrect those glory days of yesteryear'
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI BEACH _ These days the only thing on the corner of Fifth
and Washington is a parking lot. So the closest thing to boxing
that happens here is a couple South Beach partiers squaring off for
an impromptu 3 a.m. bout.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a time when the boxing universe revolved around
this spot. Until the bulldozers came in 1993, this was the home of
the Fifth Street Gym. During its 42-year life, at least 30
champions, from Sugar Ray Robinson to Sugar Ray Leonard, worked out
here. Both Muhammad Ali and Sonny Liston trained here. Even the
Beatles once stopped by.
</P>
<P>
   Not that, even in its heyday, the gym was some sort of 1960s
Planet Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   It was on the second floor. No air-conditioning. Just big fans
stirring up the smell of sweat and rotting walls.
</P>
<P>
   A dive? Some might call it that. Others would say it was the
most beautiful place they ever saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I came here from north London seven years ago, the first
thing I did was make a beeline for the Fifth Street Gym,'' Trevor
Cedar says. ``You could feel the history.''
</P>
<P>
   Cedar, 34, is standing in the gym he opened two years ago at 715
Washington Ave., a couple blocks from the site of the Fifth Street
Gym. Sweat is pouring down his face, partly because he has just
finished moving some boxes and partly because the place doesn't
have air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   If that's not enough to bring back some of the old ``Guys and
Dolls'' ambience, the South Florida Boxing gym is on the second
floor, above the ``Vegas Cabaret.'' And to get to 7,000-square foot
former gymnastics studio, you enter a door on the ground floor and
walk through a hall with a giant mural on both sides. To your left,
a 10-foot Ali towers over you in a pose that instantly brings to
mind the famous photo from his upset of Liston in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   And where is Liston?
</P>
<P>
   On the right wall. Down by the ground. Lying on the canvas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to feel like you're entering the ring,'' Cedar
says. ``I wanted to bring back the feel of the Fifth Street Gym, of
that era.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Cedar hopes, is what will begin to happen Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly 20 years since South Florida's last major
title fight: Aaron Pryor vs. Alexis Arguello in the Orange Bowl on
Nov. 12, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   And although some will argue that the matchup Saturday night at
AmericanAirlines Arena _ Felix Trinidad defending his WBA
superwelterweight title against Mamadou Thiam _ is too much of a
mismatch to rate as a ``major'' title fight, there is little
question this is the biggest boxing event South Florida has held in
years.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether it is a blip on the screen or, as people
such as Cedar hope, the revival of the golden era of boxing in
South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never going to happen,'' said Steve Shepherd of West Palm
Beach's Spartan Boxing and Kickboxing.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Shepherd wouldn't like to see the top bouts return
to South Florida. He just believes that the current centers of the
boxing universe _ Las Vegas and Atlantic City _ have something to
offer that South Florida can't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The casinos,'' he says. ``They pay fight fees to bring the
shows there. They bring in the high-rollers. You can't compete with
that. ... But it will be good (for South Florida boxing) if Don
King can get something started here.''
</P>
<P>
   King, the promoter of the Saturday's bouts, insists that the
fights are only a taste of what is to come to South Florida _
including West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell the people of Palm Beach, that this is a precursor, a
harbinger so to speak,'' King said after a two-hour press
conference Thursday in downtown Miami. ``This is what will be
coming to Only in America Arena.''
</P>
<P>
   That, King says, is the tentative name for the former jai alai
front on 45th Street that he and his wife, Henrietta, paid $6.25
million for in June 1999. At the time, King, who owns a
14,000-square foot mansion in Manapalan, not only pledged to turn
the 300,000-square foot facility into a 10,000-seat venue that
would be like a ``miniature Madison Square Garden,'' he said it
could be done by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   By last October, Dutch Bliss, the Boca Raton-based contractor
handling the project, backed off that and said the arena more
likely would open by the end of 2000. Now, one year after the
purchase, some of King's associates predict it likely won't be
ready until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``The timetable is more or less in the hands of the county
fathers,'' King said. ``It has taken over a year of just going
through the due diligence. They've been very cooperative, very
supportive. But we move at a snail's pace up there.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, the commission voted to exempt King's project from rules
that would have required the widening of 45th Street. Several
county commissioners contacted this week said they are leaving it
up to King to set the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason for the lack of progress, the commissioners
and King say they believe the project will come to fruition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to resurrect those glory days of yesteryear,''
King said Thursday, the cadence and volume of his voice rising.
``We're going to bring sports and entertainment together. It's
going to be a marriage made in heaven, and it only can be presented
by Don King in Only in America Arena in West Palm Beach. So get
ready y'all.''
</P>
<P>
   There is reason for boxing fans to hope that this is more than
hot air from the man with the hot hair. In the last couple years,
some fights have been held in arenas that normally play host to
other sporting events. Madison Square Garden in New York. The
Staples Center in Los Angeles. Conseco Fieldhouse in Indianapolis.
The Fox Theater in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most refreshing trends in the sport is the number
of fights being held in arenas rather than casinos,'' said HBO vice
president of programming Kerry Davis, one of the sports
movers-and-shakers. ``And if this fight does well here, other
fights are going to gravitate to this market.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what Cedar, the transplanted Englishman who owns the
boxing gym in South Beach, hopes this fight will do. Help bring
more fights here. Maybe even help bring back memories of when this
place was the center of the boxing universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali ran down this street,'' he says, pointing at Washington
Avenue as if it is not a street but a shrine. ``I can't believe
they torn down the Fifth Street Gym. When that happened, you lost a
piece of American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
