<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN RE-EMERGES, AS POSSIBLE BUSH RUNNING MATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Months after John McCain adamantly closed the
door to accepting his party's vice presidential nomination, a
Republican close to the Arizona senator said Thursday that he would
take the No. 2 spot on the ticket if Gov. George W. Bush offered
it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's turnaround, which was described as reluctant, came as a
growing number of Republicans lobbied for him as the best possible
addition to the ticket. Some House Republicans, looking for help in
holding the House majority, were circulating a petition to Bush
saying he and the Arizona senator would make the best ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The senator signaled his willingness to be Bush's running mate
earlier this week in a telephone conversation with Pennsylvania
Gov. Tom Ridge, according to the Republican official close to
McCain. The officials said that Ridge telephoned McCain on Tuesday
to say that he felt he himself was no longer in the running for the
No. 2 slot and to urge McCain to put his name into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Despite McCain's new willingness to take the job, several
advisers to Bush were skeptical that the governor would consider
him. Karen P. Hughes, the governor's spokeswoman, said simply,
``Governor Bush has said all along that he takes Senator McCain at
his word that he does not wish to be considered for the vice
presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Reeves, Ridge's spokesman, said the governor spoke with
McCain by telephone this week. But he would not divulge the
contents of the conversation. He said their discussion was ``not an
unusual event _ they've known each other for 20 years.'' Reeves
described their talk as ``a private conservation between them''
that he could not discuss.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has long been considered an unlikely choice for Bush
because of the premium that the Texas governor places on loyalty
and the sometimes strained relations between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   The attention that focused on McCain today may have been nothing
more than the wishful thinking of his loyalists. It also reflected
the frenzy of speculation among political insiders about what Bush
will do.
</P>
<P>
   Still, McCain was among a number of politicians whose phone
numbers were collected Thursday by aides to Richard B. Cheney, the
former defense secretary who is heading Bush's search team, so that
the Bush campaign can let them know in the coming days of the Texas
governor's final decision.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was not the only one being promoted. Bill Powers, the
chairman of the New York Republican Party, announced at one point
in the day that ``good sources'' had indicated to him that Gov.
George Pataki of New York was on the short list. But Pataki's aides
said immediately that they did not have such information.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Ridge, other possible candidates include: Govs.
Frank Keating of Oklahoma and James Gilmore III of Virginia; Sens.
Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and Fred Thompson and Bill Frist of
Tennessee; and Rep. John Kascih of Ohio. Former Sen. John Danforth
of Missouri, who pulled himself out of the running more than a
month ago, is drawing renewed speculation as well.
</P>
<P>
   Keating on Thursday said he submitted information on his
finances and health to Cheney several weeks ago and has not heard
from him since. ``That's why I'm not holding my breath,'' he said.
But later, a Republican strategist close to Keating said that the
Oklahoma governor's office had also been asked to provide Cheney
with weekend phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans believe Cheney himself is a contender. Bush
himself was asked about Cheney several times Thursday and did not
answer.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden indications that McCain would agree to be vice
president if asked were part of a strange dance that has been going
on for months, and even Thursday the McCain camp was sending mixed
signals. A Republican who knows McCain well insisted that he still
hoped he would not actually be asked to become the No. 2. ``It's
not something he would prefer to happen,'' said a close associate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
