<HEADER>
A8201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-WWII-MEMORIAL-ART-NYT     07-20 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-MEMORIAL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL BACKS WORLD WAR II MEMORIAL ON MALL IN WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., Kan., Hawaii, Ohio, Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The old soldier, his voice cracking with emotion
and his battle-shattered right hand held against his chest, pleaded
with a federal panel Thursday to finally approve the first national
World War II memorial before all his aging comrades died.
</P>
<P>
   ``We earn a lot of titles in our lives,'' said the veteran, Bob
Dole, the Republican candidate for president in 1996 and longtime
senator from Kansas. ``The one that I am most proud of is
veteran.''
</P>
<P>
   He got his wish. The panel, the Commission of Fine Arts, voted
6-0 to approve the memorial on a spot between the Washington
Monument and the Lincoln Memorial on the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   There was emotion on both sides. Opponents of the memorial,
which is to cost $100 million by the time it is scheduled to open
on Memorial Day 2003, challenged its design and its location.
</P>
<P>
   The architecture, they contended, was of the style favored by
the forces defeated by the United States and its allies in World
War II. One critic, Judy Scott Feldman, chairwoman of the National
Coalition to Save Our Mall, complained that the design was
``imperial and triumphal'' and was ``unacceptably reminiscent of
Fascist and Nazi regimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Helen Fagin, who settled in the United States after
being liberated by U.S. soldiers in Poland and who serves on an
advisory board that endorsed the memorial, said that it was ``very
offensive, egregious and disingenuous'' to compare the design with
Nazi architecture.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics complained that its location blocked the grand
vista between the Washington and Lincoln monuments. John Graves, a
corporal in the war, said he represented veterans who wanted a
memorial, ``but not on that particular spot.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the members of the commission had their turn to
comment, all spoke in favor.
</P>
<P>
   The monument was designed by Friedrich St. Florian, an architect
in Providence, R.I. It is of stone and bronze, an oval pool flanked
on two sides by semicircles of 56 pillars, one for each U.S. state
and territory during the war, which ended in 1945. It has open
arches on the north and south sides, named Atlantic and Pacific,
for the two areas in which the war was fought.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, who lost an arm in the war, called
himself ``a small participant in that great war'' and urged the
commission to approve it.
</P>
<P>
   About 16.3 million Americans served in the war, and earlier this
year the Department of Veterans Services said 5.7 million veterans
were still alive, but dying at the rate of 1,000 a day, a factor
mentioned by many advocates who call for quick construction.
</P>
<P>
   F. Haydn Williams, who headed the panel that selected the site,
urged the commission to vote approval for ``the veterans for whom
the clock is ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   The session began with J. Carter Brown, chairman of the Fine
Arts Commission, foreshadowing the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be on the Mall and it has to be central,'' he said,
eliminating the opponents' argument against its location. He said
that St. Florian had addressed complaints about the design by
placing openings in the pillars and arches, creating what he called
more transparency.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Marcy Kaptur, D-Ohio, who introduced legislation calling
for construction of the monument, said the location was
``appropriate and historically coherent,'' coming between the
monument to the president who was the hero of the Revolutionary War
that created the nation and the memorial to the president who held
it together in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's action was the most important step in the approval
process. The last remaining hurdle is action by the National
Capital Planning Commission, but it generally follows the lead of
the arts commission on matters of aesthetics.
</P>
<P>
   One advocate was Luther H. Smith, of Villanova, Pa., who was one
of the Tuskegee airmen, the black aviators who had their own unit
in the segregated Army and downed 10 German aircraft in combat.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the surviving World War II veterans, he said,
is 80, and he added: ``We have the right site. We have the right
design. What we don't have is a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole spoke with the emotion of an old soldier when he mentioned
the sacrifices of his comrades but leavened with the irreverent
humor for which he was noted in public life.
</P>
<P>
   He ticked off the contributors to the project and then, glancing
out at the veterans in the audience, added that he had been
successful in getting donations from funeral homes. ``Probably not
a good thing to raise with this group,'' he acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   He paused and waited for the laughter to end before adding,
``Sort of a layaway plan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
