<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-HADDOCK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNADAY, HARVICK NOT YOUR NORMAL ROOKIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM HADDOCK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's safe to say the rookie class on the NASCAR Busch Series
this year is not your average class of drivers.
</P>
<P>
   At the head of this group is 42-year-old Busch Series rookie Ron
Hornaday Jr. of Palmdale, Calif., who Sunday at Nazareth Speedway
became the first rookie to win a race since Steve Park in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But even with his first career Busch win, Hornaday trails fellow
rookie Kevin Harvick in the Busch Series standings. Harvick is
fourth and has a 28-point lead over Hornaday, who is sixth. The
rookie-of-the-year race is even tighter, with Harvick having a
six-point lead over Hornaday.
</P>
<P>
   The way things are going, Harvick and Hornaday could be the
first pair of rookies to finish in the top 10 in points since
Johnny Benson and Dennis Setzer did it in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fortunate not to have these guys in my rookie class,''
said 1998 Busch Series Rookie of the Year Andy Santerre. ``But it's
fun to get to race with them now.''
</P>
<P>
   But ask Hornaday about his being in the hunt for
rookie-of-the-year honors and he doesn't get too excited. He has
his sights set on the Busch championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My big deal is to catch Jeff Green,'' Hornaday said. ``We're
not going to lay down and let him win any more.''
</P>
<P>
   With four wins, six poles and a 499-point lead in the standings,
Green has been the driver to catch this year on the Busch circuit.
And for one day, Hornaday and his Dale Earnhardt-owned NAPA Auto
Parts team did just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy for the NAPA team. They've been working their
guts out,'' Hornaday said.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching victory lane is nothing new for Hornaday. The two-time
NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series champ won a record 25 races in his
five years on that circuit. Before his Truck Series career, he has
been NASCAR Winston West and Saugus (Calif.) Speedway Late Model
champion. Even though Hornaday's career reaches back to the
bump-and-grind days of Late Model racing at Saugus, he says every
race on the Busch Series is a new experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like a rookie,'' Hornaday said. ``I go to places
and race on tracks I haven't been to before. And I'm learning every
time I'm racing.''
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Busch Series is NAPA Auto Care 250 at Pikes
Peak International Raceway on Saturday. Hornaday won at the
Colorado Springs, Colo., track in 1998 while with the Truck Series.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether having raced and won at Pikes Peak before
would help him this weekend, Hornaday said: ``If you asked me three
weeks ago, I would have said it wouldn't have helped at all. The
trucks and the Busch cars are totally different. But now I know I
can run the cars just like a truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty pumped up. And I'm going to drive the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   JR. ON THE HORIZON: Hornaday announced Tuesday that his son,
Ronnie, will be following in his father's footsteps by running a
limited NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series schedule, which will include
the Powerstroke 200 at Indianapolis Raceway Park on Aug. 3 and
possibly the California Speedway race in Fontana, Calif., to end
the season Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hornaday also said his son is preparing to run a full Truck
Series schedule in 2001 and is searching for sponsorship for a
team.
</P>
<P>
   TOP 10: Bill Sedgwick of Acton, Calif., driver of the Arrowhead
Mountain Spring Water Chevrolet, was sixth in the NASCAR Winston
West Coors Light 200 at Evergreen Speedway in Monroe, Wash., on
Sunday. Sedgwick, who is also sixth in the Winston West standings,
earned $3,590 for his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Brendan Gaughan, who drives the NAPA/Martin Senour Chevrolet,
won the race at Evergreen Speedway. It was his second victory of
the season. Gaughan and Bobby Dotter are the only drivers with two
wins this season on the Winston West Series.
</P>
<P>
   The next race on the Winston West schedule is the Home Depot 250
at Irwindale (Calif.) Speedway on Aug. 19. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8205 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WHAT-LIES-BENEATH-REV     07-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHAT-LIES-BENEATH-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-WHAT-LIES-BENEATH-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``WHAT LIES BENEATH'' WILL RAISE YOUR HAIR(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can always rank a horror movie by how high you jump during
its really scary parts.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath (enditalic)has just raised the
bar.
</P>
<P>
   This taut supernatural thriller is the scariest movie since
(beginitalic)Poltergeist(enditalic), building suspense throughout
with sly camera work and a creepy, claustrophobic feel. Michelle
Pfeiffer is brilliant in the leading role, elevating her already
formidable game to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer plays Claire, wife of Dr. Norman Spencer (Harrison
Ford), a respected researcher with a hidden past. But Claire begins
to learn the truth after she sees the wraithlike figure of a young
woman and hears mysterious sounds echo through the couple's
rambling two-story lake house.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just where this slam-bang ghost story starts. You'll
have to put your head on a swivel to keep up with the twists and
turns in this expertly constructed tale of distrust, betrayal and
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)What Lies Beneath (enditalic)also contains one of
the most terrifying sequences since the two priests entered the
bedroom in (beginitalic)The Exorcist(enditalic). The movie should
include one of those sensational warnings from the '50s: ``No one
will be admitted in the last 10 minutes of this film!'''
</P>
<P>
   Tellingly, the movie isn't that different from others of the
genre, except in its execution. You could have taken the same story
and filmed it with different actors and another director, and you
would have some sad (beginitalic)Amityville Horror
(enditalic)sequel.
</P>
<P>
   But director Robert Zemeckis ((beginitalic)Forrest Gump, Who
Framed Roger Rabbit) (enditalic)takes a simple horror story and
turns it into something special. He steers away from the
slasher-film formula, concentrating instead on Claire's
psychological deterioration during her ordeal, which is
particularly torturous because the ghost looks just like her.
</P>
<P>
   To keep us on our toes while Claire unravels, Zemeckis employs
well-worn cinematic devices: spooky mirrors, billowing steam and
those tight camera shots that have the whole audience yelling,
``Look out behind you!'' He pays homage to several Hitchcock films,
including (beginitalic)Rear Window (enditalic)and
(beginitalic)Psycho(enditalic), but that doesn't distract from or
interrupt the movie's flow.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, you start to get nervous anytime a character
walks into the house and flips on a light switch. There's just no
telling what will happen.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen all these moves before, but the camera work, pacing
and acting put this film on a higher plane. The story is quirky and
creative enough to keep the audience interested, even during the
setup.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actors - especially Diana Scarwid, who portrays
Claire's wisecracking best friend - play their roles with
enthusiastic vigor. Scarwid helps the movie maintain a wry sense of
humor, and Zemeckis uses that light tone to meticulously build
Pfeiffer's character throughout the first hour. When things start
to fall apart, the audience is clearly rooting for her.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeiffer, who is on the screen in almost every scene, deserves
plenty of credit for the movie's success, and perhaps even an Oscar
nomination. Her performance runs the gamut from silly to sultry,
from confused to terrified. She smoothly handles her transformation
from all-American mom to haunted woman.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the first hour, Ford is almost window dressing,
though there is clearly chemistry between Pfeiffer and him while
they cavort as a happily married couple. As Pfeiffer's paranoia
builds and strange things start happening, Ford's character plays a
more pivotal role.
</P>
<P>
   The final 30 minutes are as frightening as it gets. If you're
not scared, you're probably covering your eyes. As far as that
goes, I can hardly blame you.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Contact Muller at Bill.Muller(a)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
