<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0426 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-INCROWD-REVIEW-AZR &LR;      07-20 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INCROWD-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-INCROWD-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    ``THE IN CROWD'' SHOULD BE COUNTRY-LUBBED(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The posters for (beginitalic)The In Crowd (enditalic)are tagged
with the line: ``What would you do to get in?''
</P>
<P>
   After the first 45 minutes, you'll be asking: ``What can I do to
get out?''
</P>
<P>
   It's really not clear what they're trying to accomplish with
this movie, a poor man's (beginitalic)Cruel Intentions
(enditalic)without Sarah Michelle Gellar or even the slightest
shred of a script.
</P>
<P>
   The first half plays like an extended episode of
(beginitalic)Baywatch(enditalic), as we watch snobby
twentysomethings frolic on the beach and make catty remarks to each
other. They're led by Brittany (soap star Susan Ward), a poor
little rich girl who likes to manipulate her friends while she
romances the local tennis pro.
</P>
<P>
   If this doesn't sound familiar, I want to congratulate you for
escaping from the gulag.
</P>
<P>
   In the second half the movie turns dark, as Brittany clashes
with Adrien (Lori Heuring), a country club worker who has been just
been released from a mental hospital, where she suffered from
something called ``erotomania.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the movie's only claim on the erotic thriller genre,
since most of the film is neither erotic nor thrilling.
</P>
<P>
   Brittany has a dark secret, which we figure out in the first 20
minutes of the movie. She spends the rest of the time scheming
about this and that, but after awhile, we don't care anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The film also suffers from a bad case of (beginitalic)Chariots
of Fire (enditalic)syndrome: Many of the male characters look
alike, so it makes the silly plot that much harder to follow.
</P>
<P>
   And just when we think we'll escape, the movie gives us a
drawn-out ending, punishment perhaps, for trying to join
(beginitalic)The In Crowd(enditalic).
</P>
</TEXT>
