<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-YACHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAST GUARD CHECKED SEN. KENNEDY WHEN YACHT STRAYED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 361-foot Japanese schooner Kaiwo Maru was sailing
out of Boston Harbor on Sunday after its triumphant Tall Ships
visit when a 50-foot yacht crossed into its path.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiwo Maru sounded its horns in warning. The Coast Guard
rushed over to check the credentials of the wayward skipper.
</P>
<P>
   What they found was US Senator Edward M. Kennedy, an honored
guest of the Tall Ships pageant, piloting his yacht, the Mya, with
his wife Victoria. After a brief conversation, the Coast Guard
allowed Kennedy's boat to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard issued a statment saying Kennedy had not caused
a safety hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Coast guard approached several vessels to ensure that the
Tall Ships had a clear path on their arrival July 11 and their
departure July 16,'' the statement from the Boston-based First
Coast Guard district said. ``Senator Kennedy was aboard one of
those vessels. All vessels complied including Senator Kennedy and
moved to a safe area. At no time was there any threat to the safety
of the events.''
</P>
<P>
   As news of the senator's sailing zigzag raced over the Internet,
and media inquiries began trickling in, the senator's office noted
that Kennedy had received permission to join the Parade of Sail and
that he had cooperated with the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Japanese signal to the Mya came when he was moving out of
the way,'' said Will Keyser, Kennedy's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of Sail Boston 2000 said Thursday Kennedy was fully
credentialed to be in area where he was sailing and was displaying
the necessary Coast Guard flag.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's Washington office stressed that the senator had not
violated any Coast Guard rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``When approached by a Coast Guard vessel, the senator displayed
his Coast Guard-issued flag demonstrating he was part of the
festival,'' said Keyser. ``He was invited to continue to proceed.''
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Commander M.A. Cicalese, who was in charge of safety
and security for the event, told boston.com Thursday that Kennedy
had sailed into a restricted area under heavy fog. The Coast Guard
had ordered the ships to leave the harbor without sails, powered by
their engines, because of the fog.
</P>
<P>
   Cicalese, who was on the bridge of the USS John F. Kennedy at
the time of the incident, told boston.com the incident was under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Coast Guard statement said the incident is not part
of any investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, an avid sailor like many in his family, was
instrumental in bringing naval vessels that participated in Sail
Boston 2000, including the aircraft carrier that bears his late
brother's name, to the harbor.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, he was merely another sailor, who apparently
forgot one rule of life on the high seas _ and national politics:
Stay out of the way of the bigger boat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
