A8214 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-STUDIOS-WEB-LAWSUIT-N     07-20 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUDIOS-WEB-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIE AND RECORDING BUSINESSES SUE SCOUR.COM FOR INFRINGING
COPYRIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Expanding their legal attack on the exchange of
copyrighted works on the Internet, the motion picture and music
industries Thursday sued to shut down Scour.com, a venture the
industries say permits the free trading not just of music but of
movies, in some cases as soon as they open in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   In invoking the film issue, the lawsuit adds a wrinkle to a
story that has focused largely on music, in particular on the
embattled Napster service. It also puts the motion picture industry
at odds with one of its own stalwarts, given that Michael Ovitz,
the former Disney president and an agent who represents some of
Hollywood's biggest stars, owns 20 percent of Scour.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court in Manhattan,
more than 30 of the world's largest movie and record houses contend
that their copyrighted works are being freely exchanged by tens of
thousands of users of Scour.com, which is based in Los Angeles.
Started by several UCLA students, the site points users to
multimedia content on the Internet, including music and video,
serving in part like a focused search engine.
</P>
<P>
   But the site also includes a feature called Scour Exchange,
which allows users to trade music and movie files they keep on
their computers. In that way, the feature is like Napster, which
has been sued by the recording industry for permitting users to
exchange music files.
</P>
<P>
   Scour issued a statement expressing surprise at the lawsuit. It
said that it had been negotiating business agreements with the
record companies, and that it already had deals to present content
on its site from two plaintiffs in the case, Miramax and Hollywood
Records.
</P>
<P>
   The statement did not address the legal questions raised by the
suit. But in interviews earlier this year, company officials said
they should not be held accountable if some people use the service
to trade copyrighted material, an assertion also made by Napster.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials countered that the company was knowingly
permitting, even encouraging, the exchange of copyrighted
materials, and seeking to profit from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This lawsuit is about stealing,'' said Jack Valenti, president
of the Motion Picture Association of America. ``It's a harsh word,
but it's the only one that fits the definition.''
</P>
<P>
   More generally, the lawsuit underscores unresolved
copyright-infringement issues raised by the advent and growing
popularity of the Internet, which provides an unprecedented ability
to trade and copy data. The issue could face a crucial test next
week when a federal judge in San Francisco is scheduled to consider
whether to grant the Recording Industry Association of America's
request to shut down Napster.
</P>
<P>
   The Scour lawsuit does not say how many copyrighted works are
available on Scour Exchange, but says there are 1.8 million files
available through Scour, ``most of them unauthorized and infringing
copies.'' Industry officials said it was typical for 25,000 people
to be using the service at any given time. And documents filed with
the court said that some of the works traded freely were popular
music and first-run movies like ``Gladiator'' and ``Mission:
Impossible 2.''
</P>
<P>
   One additional twist in the case comes from the presence of
Ovitz, who read about Scour in the UCLA campus newspaper and bought
a stake in the company last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some industry analysts have said that Ovitz's stake in Scour is
a conflict of interest because his talent management agency,
Artists Management Group, represents some of the very artists whose
works are traded on Scour Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Hilary Rosen, president of the Recording Industry
Association of America, wrote a letter to Ovitz contending that
Scour was engaged in unlawful activities.
</P>
<P>
   A person close to Artists Management Group said Ovitz had grown
increasingly uncomfortable with his association with the company.
In June, Ovitz sent letters to Dan Rodrigues, the president of
Scour Exchange, and to the Scour board expressing concern about the
copyright implications.
</P>
<P>
   The person also said that Ovitz felt he was not in a position to
control the company's direction, and that Ovitz had hired an
investment banker to sell his stake. Officials from Scour declined
to comment on Ovitz's position. A spokesman for Artists Management
also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The position stands in contrast to statements made earlier by
officials from Artists Management Group. In May, James Ellis, the
agency's general counsel, said the company stood behind Scour
Exchange and the concept of file sharing. ``In the face of a
rapidly changing marketplace, Scour had to respond to maintain and
grow its audience and give them what they wanted,'' Ellis said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit against Scour does not specify the amount of damages
sought.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8215 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SEGA-PIRACY-BOS &LR;      07-20 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-PIRACY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA SAYS WEB SITES, AUCTIONS SHUT DOWN TO HALT PIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Music and movies aren't the only things being pirated and
distributed over the Internet these days.
</P>
<P>
   Video games are also big targets.
</P>
<P>
   Sega of America Thursday said it has shut down 60 Web sites and
125 auctions trafficking in pirated video games played on Sega's
Dreamcast console.
</P>
<P>
   Software pirating has existed for as long as software has been
around. What's new is the unprecendented ease brought by the
Internet for pirating and distributing software, leading to a crop
of new applications such as Napster for copying and sharing music,
and DivX, which can be used to duplicate movies.
</P>
<P>
   The gaming industry estimates that over $3 billion is lost every
year from piracy, a huge sum considering the industry itself pulled
in just $6.9 billion in 1999 from sales of both consoles and
software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Console makers earn a majority of their cash from licensing
software,'' said Michael Goodman, a senior analyst with the Yankee
Group. ``So piracy is literally a direct attack on their revenue
stream.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega, which is based in Japan and has operations in San
Francisco, is teaming up with other console makers and software
publishers to fight back. Their arsenal was considerably beefed up
when Congress this year passed the Digital Millennium Copyright
Act, which allowed copyright holders to go after Web sites and
Internet service providers that host sales of pirated software.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest broadside, Sega last week began issuing cease and
desist orders to five auction sites, including those hosted by
Yahoo!, eBay, Lycos, Excite and Amazon.com, according to Charles
Bellfield, Sega's spokesman. In addition, the company asked
Internet service providers to shut down Web sites that sell pirated
games, as well as companies hosting virtual hard drives that are
used by their customers for storing pirated games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those companies that do not comply will face both civil and
criminal prosecution by both federal and state authorities with
whom we are working with,'' said Bellfield.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, all the companies Sega has approached have cooperated,
according to Bellfield. Sega continues to issue cease and desist
orders daily, he said. The company, which said it loses millions of
dollars a year to piracy, is working with European officials and
negotiating with Asian law enforcement on its crusade.
</P>
<P>
   Last March, Sega teamed up with game-maker Nintendo and
Electronic Arts, a large game publisher, to file a lawsuit against
Yahoo! to prevent pirated games from being sold on Yahoo's Web
site. The case, filed in U.S. District Court in California, is
still pending.
</P>
<P>
   But game industry analysts question how successful companies
will be in stamping out illicit copying of digital products via
Napster, DivX or a simple $200 compact disk ``burner'' that can
duplicate CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a bigger picture of piracy,'' said P.J.
McNealy, analyst with the Gartner Group. ``As more things become
digital, they will become more portable and easier to exchange,
particularly over the Internet. Instances like this will continue
to crop up more often.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
