<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RACE18-COX     07-20 2348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    After 44 years, former Georgia teacher's stands by her remarks
on race
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - Colleen Wiggins hasn't said much about
it these 44 years. She'd rather not think about it, ever. But twice
now, her husband, Jim, has written to the newspapers and gotten
them to dredge it all up again.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because he's the one who was bitter for so long. And
maybe that's because it hurt him more, watching helplessly as she
went through all that.
</P>
<P>
   She is tempted to tell this fine man to hush-up once and for all
and throw away what's left of the old letters and crumbly news
clippings, except that she can't really be sure that what happened
to her in small-town Georgia in 1956 was really peculiar to that
place and time.
</P>
<P>
   So she takes the box out of the closet and spreads all of those
scraps across the sofa in their house, wondering aloud if some
other teacher, somewhere, someday will suffer as much for the
mistake of answering a student's question without stopping to think
about who might be offended by the answer.
</P>
<P>
   No one wrote down what she said that day in front of her
10th-grade world history class at the Bethesda School _ some of
what got back to her later was just plain crazy _ but she's sure of
this much: She said that she would continue teaching even if the
school took in black students.
</P>
<P>
   Then she said she would not stop her daughter from marrying a
black man.
</P>
<P>
   No matter that there were no black children living anywhere near
the school. No matter that her daughter wasn't yet 2. Colleen Marie
Wiggins, Southern by birth, minister's wife by choice and nobody's
idea of a liberal firebrand, knew right away that she was in for
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came home and said, `Jim, I think I opened my big mouth a
little too much today,''' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She'd opened it wide enough to lose her job. Wide enough that,
eventually, people all over the country knew what she said. The
furor did not die for a long time, until she was gone from that
town and that state and from the South.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than cultural dissonance that caused her now
tepid-sounding remarks to grate on so many people in then-rural
Bethesda and Lilburn and the other communities clustered around the
Gwinnett County seat of Lawrenceville, 20-or-so miles northeast of
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fear,'' she says. ``Fear of change.''
</P>
<P>
   Change, enormous and irreversible, was occurring throughout the
South when the Wigginses arrived in Georgia in 1955. Colleen, born
in North Carolina, and Jim, born in North Florida, could feel the
change in themselves after three years of Methodist missionary work
in Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up seeing water fountains at the bus station that said
`white' and `colored,''' Colleen says. ``And, of course, the white
people sat in the front of the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout her childhood, black people passed in silence,
standing in their own lines and disappearing through their own
doorways. She found no reason to challenge racial conventions
during her studies at all-white, all-girl Greensboro College in her
home state, where she got a teaching degree. From there, the
Methodist Church sent her to Kansas City for missionary training.
</P>
<P>
   That's where she became friendly with a black person for the
first time, a missionary student her age. She learned firsthand
that nothing awful would happen if they drank from the same
fountain or sat together on a bus.
</P>
<P>
   It's also where she met Jim, another missionary student. They
fell in love and finagled a common missionary assignment in Hawaii,
where they were married. ``In Hawaii, there were people of many
races,'' she says. ``They all came and went together. No one
thought anything of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Their three-year assignment ended just as Jim's brother was
leaving his job as student pastor at Bethesda Methodist Church. Jim
was invited to take his place. It was a job that would help support
Colleen and their daughter, Sandi, while he studied for a master's
degree in theology at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Bethesda wasn't really a town, ``just a couple of stores, a gas
station and the church,'' but it had a school. Grades one through
12, maybe 200 kids in all, with a pot-bellied stove in each
classroom. Although her degree was in religious education, Colleen
was hired to teach English, history, geography, typing.
</P>
<P>
   Her salary was $233 a month. Jim's was about $150. Together, the
two 26-year-olds earned enough to get by. They lived in the old
brick parsonage. They ate fresh vegetables and sausage and chicken
that their farmer-parishioners eagerly shared. ``It was a wonderful
community,'' Colleen says. ``Just wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   It was especially wonderful if you were white, which was true of
nearly everyone for miles around. There wasn't much need to worry
about separate fountains or waiting rooms. But people worried just
the same. Everyone was worried about Montgomery, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   A few months before Jim and Colleen moved to Bethesda, a black
bus rider named Rosa Parks was arrested in Montgomery because she
refused to move to the back. Other black people in Montgomery
reacted in a way white people could not understand, much less
abide: They quit riding buses.
</P>
<P>
   The Montgomery Bus Boycott was the talk of the South for nearly
a year. A lot of the talk in places like Bethesda was angry. Jim
and Colleen heard it but didn't say much. ``We were no longer
comfortable with the way we grew up, but we felt things had to
change slowly,'' Jim says. ``We weren't radical reformers.''
</P>
<P>
   Colleen got through most of the school year without trouble,
except for the one visit from Gertrude Stephens, a parent who
objected to a lesson about the United Nations. ``She wanted me to
teach Americanism, not about one world,'' Colleen says.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen might have avoided further controversy if it hadn't been
for a countywide, end-of-the-year essay contest. The theme: Is
interposition the answer to segregation?
</P>
<P>
   Most students found the question puzzling. They understood
segregation, and they understood why it was an issue. The Supreme
Court had ruled two years before in Brown vs. the Board of
Education that separate schools were unconstitutional. Then it
ordered Topeka, Kansas, to integrate its schools ``with all
deliberate speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia politicians were among the first and most enthusiastic
proponents of ``interposition'' as a way to avoid similar
consequences. It was a highfalutin but constitutionally cockeyed
theory that a state had the authority to ignore any federal ruling
it didn't like.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students couldn't figure out what it meant, so they
started asking teachers,'' Colleen says. ``Well, the other teachers
had sense enough to say, `Look it up,' even though there was no
information in our little library.''
</P>
<P>
   Not Colleen Wiggins. She didn't see the harm in helping kids
prepare for an essay contest sponsored by the county. One question
led to another. She was surprised that most of her students thought
integration might not be so bad. How could she keep quiet when one
asked what she thought? She does not remember who started all this
_ the names are a bit hazy now _ but one of the girls asked what
she'd do if black children were admitted to Bethesda School.
Colleen hesitated. ``My feelings were: Shall I say, `I'm not going
to answer?' Being young, I answered. I said I'd teach any
student.''
</P>
<P>
   Her students could not let such a remarkable statement pass.
More questions followed. The most pointed: What if your daughter
wanted to marry a black man? Colleen measured her words: ``I said
my daughter could marry whomever she pleases.'' She tried to
insulate herself with ``ifs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If'' she loves him. ``If'' that's what she really wants.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she knew what she'd done.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude then was what I call colonialism,'' she says.
``You are not bad to other races. You take care of them. But you
don't mix with them. When I said my daughter could marry a black
man, I might as well have said I wanted her to marry a black man.
That's what people heard.''
</P>
<P>
   She did her best to wrap up the discussion quickly. She hoped it
would end with the class bell. ``Don't go home and tell your
parents that I'm teaching integration,'' she said. But some did.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, her principal and two other friends came calling at
the Wiggins home. They said a group of parents wanted her fired.
The most insistent were G.W. and Gertrude Stephens. Colleen and Jim
decided to go straight to the Stephens' home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were very nice people,'' Colleen says. ``They said they'd
prayed over this. But she was adamant about what she believed in.''
</P>
<P>
   The school year was about to end, but not before the Stephenses
and others had asked for a formal investigation. The school board
held up Colleen's contract. A petition for her removal was signed
by 124 people.
</P>
<P>
   The petition noted that the state's loyalty oath required
teachers ``to refrain from directly or indirectly subscribing to or
teaching any theory of government or economics or of social
relations which is inconsistent with the fundamental principles of
patriotism and high ideals of Americanism.'' The petition charged
that she had lost the respect of students and parents ``due to her
advocacy and teaching of integration... ''
</P>
<P>
   ``What hurt was that these parents thought I was encouraging
students to go against them,'' she says. ``I would never do that.
But a student has a right to form an opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   The school board took statements throughout the summer. In
August, it concluded that she should be rehired. Colleen went back
to the Bethesda School for the fall term expecting her second child
and a more tranquil school year. That wasn't likely anywhere in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   When September arrived, black students attempted to enroll at
white schools in Texas, Kentucky, Tennessee and other states. The
National Guard had to hold back angry crowds. Many school districts
were determined to fight any change.
</P>
<P>
   In Gwinnett County, Ga., the school board found it could not
quickly dispose of the complaint against Colleen Wiggins. The
parents who wanted her fired took their complaint to the state,
which cut off its portion of her salary until the local board held
another hearing. The state's portion was nearly all of it: $225.
</P>
<P>
   The local trustees dipped into their own budget to keep paying
her. Colleen went on teaching, certain that the people who wanted
her to leave were a minority: More than 400 people signed a
petition in her favor. The parishioners at church raised $200 so
she could hire a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   But it was hard to find one who would take the case. ``It was
the hot political item,'' she says. Even people she knew well were
cautious. Most said nothing at all. ``The silence was the worst
part,'' Colleen says.
</P>
<P>
   A 3 1/2-hour hearing was held on Oct. 9, 1956. Again, the board
voted to keep Colleen. It was not the end of her ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings, the petition, the state's action all generated
more publicity. The stories jumped to papers far and wide,
including the New York Times. Someone even sent her a clipping from
Paraguay. Phone calls came day and night _ frightening, vulgar
calls. One bomb threat. A couple of crossed sticks burned on the
lawn. Hate mail came, too, mostly unsigned. She got plenty of
letters of support, but many of those were also unsigned, even
letters from the North.
</P>
<P>
   The note that made her angriest was presented in person. Before
the state would step aside, Colleen would have to sign an oath that
she did not believe in integration and would not advocate it
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got me,'' she says. ``I'd already agreed not to teach
integration in school. What right did anyone have to tell me what I
could or could not believe? I refused to sign it.''
</P>
<P>
   It took nearly all her strength to do that. She finally woke up
one November morning and couldn't get out of bed. ``I was paralyzed
by the stress,'' she says. Jim worried about her health. Both
worried about her pregnancy. Instead of the oath, Colleen signed a
letter of resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I'd made my impact,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even that didn't satisfy the state, which set a hearing to
revoke her license. James A. Mackay, the one lawyer willing to take
up Colleen's cause, was not surprised. ``Demagoguery is hard to
fight,'' says Mackay, now 81 and retired. ``But good teachers like
Colleen could not be intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   The state eventually backed down, but Colleen and Jim had
already decided to leave. He took a youth-director's job at a
church in California in the spring of 1957 and finished his
studies. They continued their church work with migrants in New York
and then moved to Eatonville, Fla., where Colleen got back to the
classroom as a Head Start teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen was hired to teach at Lincoln Elementary in Riviera
Beach, Fla., in 1968, when the county was in the throes of
integration. There were no white students in her class. The school
board's refusal to integrate in 1956 resulted in a federal
desegregation order that remained in force for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen, later an environmental science teacher at Palm Beach
Gardens High School, retired from teaching in 1991 but she hasn't
left the classroom entirely. She travels to schools throughout
South Florida with a butterfly exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   Her former lawyer, Mackay, was elected to Congress in 1964. The
following year, he bucked the Southern bloc to vote for the
landmark Voting Rights Act. He was defeated in the next election.
</P>
<P>
   Black students were eventually admitted to Bethesda School.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Stephens died in 1998. ``I wonder if she ever changed
her views, even just a little,'' Colleen says.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen, now 70, says the experience changed her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me a stronger person,'' she says. ``I think of the
people who supported me. How brave they were. It helped me believe
in the good of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian can be reached at dougkalajian(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
