<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-FLA-UNCANDIDATE-420&AMP;A     07-20 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-UNCANDIDATE-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA CANDIDATE HOUNDS PEOPLE TO VOTE _ FOR SOMEONE ELSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Like most candidates for public office, Douglas
Couvertier needed a clear, strong message, something that would cut
through the other candidates' talk about what they would do for the
voters, if elected.
</P>
<P>
   He needed a catchy slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please don't vote for me, please,'' seemed about right.
</P>
<P>
   Couvertier, whose name will be on the ballot Tuesday when voters
go to the polls to elect a city council for the newly formed town
of Southwest Ranches in Broward County, is running hard, and
running to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to civic leaders asking them not to vote for me,''
or provide other support in any way, said Couvertier. ``I've sent
out letters saying, `Please don't vote for me.' I've talked to
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood a real good chance of being elected,'' he said,
forlorn. ``In fact, my fear is I still stand a real good chance of
being elected.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, he said, he will resign from the council
without serving.
</P>
<P>
   It did not start that way, of course. He ran because he wanted
to help shape the future of the town, one of the last mostly rural
places in South Florida that is neither park land, nor under water
in the rainy season.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the 54-year-old Couvertier, a battalion chief
for the Miami-Dade Fire Department, was told by his boss that the
Miami-Dade County charter prohibits employees from holding elective
office.
</P>
<P>
   Under the charter, candidates must go on leave when they begin
campaigning, and must quit their job if they win. Couvertier could,
his superiors told him, lose a big part of his pension if he
resigned from the fire department now.
</P>
<P>
   He did not know the charter had such a provision, and it came to
his bosses' attention too late. He wanted to bow out, but was told
by election officials that it was too late to have his name removed
from the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   So he is campaigning fast and furious, as dedicated as anybody
who is trying to win, to derail his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   He has stopped short of name-calling and character
assassination, but there is no telling how low he may have to stoop
if things keep going the way they are going.
</P>
<P>
   He hears he is the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   With eight candidates seeking four at-large seats, he has a
50-50 chance at least, but early indications are that Couvertier, a
27-year veteran of the fire department and a popular figure in his
community of 7,000 to 9,000 people, has been pulling ahead.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Saturday, in what seemed like a good thing at the time, he
won the endorsement of The Miami Herald.
</P>
<P>
   His home bustles with anti-campaign activity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God you called,'' said a friend, Sara Horowitz, when
told it was The New York Times on the line. ``We're trying so
desperately not to get him elected.''
</P>
<P>
   With no budget for television advertising _ if he just had some
television money, he could blow himself right out of contention _
he must try other tactics.
</P>
<P>
   But it is tricky.
</P>
<P>
   He could post signs that read ``Vote for anybody but me,'' but
that could backfire. In the attention span of many voters, it might
be just enough information to trip their memories on election day
and cause them to vote for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe in this area,'' he said. ``I've lived here
for over 20 years and I love it here. I thought it was important
for my town for me to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But now is not the time.
</P>
<P>
   Couvertier is three years from retirement. If he is elected and
then resigns, he will probably be able to save his pension. But he
would prefer not to go through that bureaucratic ordeal, and not
have friends and neighbors elect him to a job that he immediately
rejects.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to quit the race came too late to just take him off
the ballot, said Jane Carroll, the Broward County elections
supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to correct them at this point,'' Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-four absentee ballots are already in. With Couvertier's
luck, he is probably already ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes me nervous,'' Horowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   For the other candidates, it seems like a lot of good votes
going to waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, first, I think Doug is a good candidate and it's a shame
that he has to back out,'' said Forest Blanton, 47, who is running
for the council.
</P>
<P>
   But politics is politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were more aggressive, I'd try to ask him to recommend me
to voters,'' Blanton said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Castillo, the Miami-Dade County assistant fire chief,
said Couvertier was not going to be disciplined for not taking a
leave because it was ``an honest mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' he said, ``everyone is chuckling.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though it appears that Couvertier will be able to reclaim
his job if he is elected, then resigns, he takes the election
seriously and does not want to have to say ``No thank you,'' if he
is unsuccessful in not winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only out now is to lose,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
