<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM F. WHYTE, 86; BOOK CHRONICLED BOSTON SLUM IN 1940S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TOM LONG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ William F. Whyte, a retired professor at Cornell
University and author of ``Street Corner Society,'' a seminal
sociological study of Italian-American street life in the North End
of Boston, died Sunday in Ithaca, N.Y. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street Corner Society'' was first published in 1943, when the
North End was a congested slum inhabited almost exclusively by
Italian immigrants and their families. Mr. Whyte took a
``hands-on'' approach to his research, living in the North End
while a fellow at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   His book is credited with changing the way Americans looked at
both urban poverty and Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, which was published in an expanded 50th anniversary
edition by the Chicago University Press in 1993, the North End is
referred to as ``Cornerville,'' a neighborhood of ``Eastern City''
where gangs of youths hung out on almost every street corner.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Whyte discovered that although the North End appeared
chaotic to outsiders, it had a strict social order built around
churches, social and political clubs, and corner gangs. North End
residents had solid family values and preserved a vigorous ethnic
culture. He learned that, while the neighborhood was very poor _
the unemployment rate was about 40 percent _ it was one of the
safest places in the city.
</P>
<P>
   During his stay he helped organize a 1939 protest march that
resulted in cleaner streets and improvements to the public
bathhouse. Because the boilers often broke down, the bathhouse
frequently had only cold water, a serious inconvenience in a
neighborhood where about 85 percent of the houses had no tubs or
showers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Whyte called his method ``participatory action research,''
and claimed he could maintain objectivity while sometimes nudging
his subject in the direction of reform.
</P>
<P>
   Some academics were not so sure. They called for more passive,
objective observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``His practice of social science was really aimed at social
reform and social change,'' said Davydd Greenwood, a professor of
anthropology at Cornell. ``He never accepted the notion that social
science should be a purely academic profession.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Street Corner Society'' was translated into Chinese, Japanese,
German, French, Italian, and Spanish. It has sold more than 270,000
copies.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Whyte was born in Springfield, Mass. He graduated from
Swarthmore College and earned a doctorate at the University of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948 he became one of the first professors at the new Cornell
University School of Industrial and Labor Relations.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Kathleen (King); two daughters, Joyce Wiza
of Manchester, N.H., and Lucy Whyte Ferguson of Taos, N.M.; two
sons, Martin K. of Silver Spring, Md., and John of Philadelphia; 12
grandchildren; and eight great-grandchildren
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
