u p BC-GORE-NYT     07-20 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE SEEKS TO DISCREDIT RIVAL IN HIS HOME STATE 
</HEADLINE>
 (See also TEXAS-PRIDE) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Vice President Al Gore blew into Gov. George W.
Bush's home territory on Thursday to try to undercut the governor's
popularity, suggesting that what he called Bush's skewed priorities
had made Texas a backwater where big oil interests are more
important than children's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this is a wonderful state,'' Gore said. ``But I think it
should be _ and I think most people agree _ it should be a state
where it's just as easy to raise a child as it is to set up an oil
rig.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also confronted head on the common assumption, backed up in
polls, that voters prefer Bush's personality, warning that the
presidency was not a ``popularity contest.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that Governor Bush is a popular and well-liked
governor here, and I want to give him some credit on that score,''
Gore told a hastily arranged forum of a dozen adults, including
Democratic state legislators, three single mothers and a few
squirming children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has a warm and engaging personality but, you know,
the presidency is more than just a popularity contest,'' Gore went
on. ``It involves whether or not you're willing to fight for what's
right, whether or not you're willing to spend popularity to do
difficult, hard things. And that's where you get to priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore diverted his campaign to Texas on Thursday to try to take
advantage of questions emerging about the state budget, which has
$610 million in cost overruns.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, which called Gore's visit a gimmick stunt,
said the vice president was raising more questions about his own
credibility than he was about the stewardship of Texas, accusing
him of distorting the budget situation.
</P>
<P>
   The state comptroller, a Republican and a supporter of Bush,
announced on Thursday that the state had $1.4 billion in cash on
hand, an amount more than necessary to cover any spending overruns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held a brief news conference at the governor's mansion on
Thursday afternoon and, when asked about Gore's visit, said, ``I
welcome him here.''
</P>
<P>
   But in his prepared remarks, Bush talked tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am disappointed that the vice president of all the United
States would come to one of those states and try to mislead people
about its budget,'' the statement said. ``Our Texas budget is
balanced and in the black. We have a surplus of $1.4 billion in the
bank. For Vice President Gore to claim otherwise for his own
political purposes is a travesty _ he should be ashamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett a spokesman for Bush, said Gore's chief distortion
was painting a $1.7 billion tax cut pushed by Bush and his allies
as a special break for the oil industry. Bartlett said that the oil
industry's share amounted to just $20 million, and that most of the
tax break had been applied to reducing school property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the central question was one of priorities. His press
secretary, Chris Lehane, said Bush's priorities ``raise questions
about whether he has what it takes to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   This was a theme that Gore had tried out earlier this spring but
dropped when advisers said it was too early to be so negative. It
still seemed the major risk on Thursday for Gore, which is why he
opened his remarks with a nod to Bush's congeniality, Gore backers
acknowledged. Still, Gore advisers said this would become a central
theme as the campaign developed.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides conceded that today's event was aimed chiefly at
voters beyond Texas, particularly swing voters, women and core
Democrats who may find the governor an appealing figure, but who
would be offended at what Gore tried to portray as Bush's disregard
for health care, children and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   One of Gore's most serious charges was that Texas had not only
favored oil companies and other special interests over health care
for children, but that it had deliberately made applying for
children's health insurance a cumbersome process, so the state
would have more money available for the oil companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a state finds ways to discourage families from signing up
for CHIP, the state saves money in its budget,'' Gore said, with a
personal testimonial from one of his guests to that effect. ``If
they create obstacles, and families get the idea they shouldn't
participate, the state can use the money for other things, like a
tax break for the oil companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, Bush's spokesman, said Gore was blurring the line
between Medicaid and CHIPS, the Children's Health Insurance
Program. He said that applications for the children's health
program were simple and could be mailed in. He said that contrary
to Gore's assertion, Texas is one of 12 states, not the only one,
that requires reapplication every six months for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   As for Gore's comments on Bush's personality, Bartlett said:
``This contest is going to be, Who do the American people trust
with their money and their priorities? And if we're going to base
this on the fiscal stewardship of Texas compared to the lack of Al
Gore's credibility, we relish the fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
