<HEADER>
A8229 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-MARRIAGE-TAX-NYT &LR;      07-20 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS REPUBLICANS ALTER `MARRIAGE TAX' PLAN, PRICE TAG RISES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., S.D.)  By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hoping to make it harder for President Clinton to veto a measure
they see as having tremendous political appeal, Republicans have
unveiled a new version of their tax cut for married couples, but
they promptly found themselves under fire for making the bill cost
$44 billion more overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their new version of the tax bill, which House
and Senate negotiators agreed to Wednesday night, did respond to
the White House's concerns by stripping out a provision in the
Senate bill that would have benefited only upper-income taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, the negotiators also decided to speed up
the timetable for putting the cuts into effect, a step that left
the bill with a 10-year cost of $292 billion. That a $44 billion
increase in the estimates over that time frame, handing the
administration more ammunition to assert that the bill is too
costly.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans had said on Wednesday that they hoped to defuse the
Democratic criticism by agreeing on a revised bill closer in cost
to the $180 billion, 10-year measure passed by the House than to
the $248 billion, 10-year plan approved by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, which had said it would veto even the
less-costly House version, promptly reiterated the veto threat, and
congressional Democrats joined in on the attack as well, portraying
the Republicans as more interested in scoring election-year
debating points than in passing compromise legislation that would
mean something to voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no better,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., the
minority leader. ``In fact, it's worse than the original version,
based on cost alone. I'm disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   The House quickly passed the revised bill on a 271-156 vote, and
the Senate was expected to give it final approval within a day or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that by stripping out a provision to benefit
couples earning $106,000 or more this year, they had responded to
criticism from Democrats that the measure was too tilted to the
wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   They said that the bill left plenty of money in the projected
federal budget surplus to deal with other needs like reducing the
national debt. And they challenged Clinton to make good on his
claim that he also favored the main goal of the bill, reducing the
marriage penalty, the quirk in the tax code that forces many
two-income couples to pay more in taxes than they would if they had
remained single.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason on earth that the president should veto
this bill,'' said House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to congressional leaders Thursday, Secretary of
the Treasury Lawrence H. Summers listed several.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together with other tax legislation passed by the Congress
this year,'' Summers said, ``it would threaten our fiscal
discipline and jeopardize our ability to strengthen Social Security
and Medicare, pay down the national debt, enact well targeted tax
cuts, provide a long-overdue voluntary Medicare prescription drug
benefit, and meet other pressing national priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The revised version of the bill would immediately double the
standard deduction for married couples filing jointly so that it
would be equal to twice the standard deduction for single filers.
The deduction now for couples filing jointly is 1.67 times the
deduction for single people.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would gradually expand the income level covered by
the 15 percent income tax bracket for married couples to twice the
level covered for single filers. The change would be phased in over
five years, starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also increase the earned income tax credit, a
rebate for low-income working families. But Democrats said the
revised bill would offer a smaller increase in the credit than the
version passed by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   With the revisions in the bill, the nonpartisan Joint Committee
on Taxation said, the tax would total $292 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But because of an arcane budget rule, the bill would expire in
five years, meaning that unless a future Congress acted to extend
them, the tax cuts would be canceled just as they were fully phased
in.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to make the best of the situation, Republicans said that
meant the bill's actual cost would be $90 billion, the size of the
tax cut over five years, not the $292 billion figure cited.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
