<HEADLINE>
THE NEWS ACCORDING TO OLBERMANN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They hired him 18 months ago to a multimillion-dollar contract
specifically to boost the credibility and exposure of their nightly
sports report. So why now will the execs at Fox Sports Net be
content with having poster boy Keith Olbermann on as a once-a-week
fixture?
</P>
<P>
   Because, Fox Sports chief David Hill says, this is ``an attempt
to redefine sports journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   And because, Hill adds, ``In TV, you gotta be like a shark _
move or else you'll die.''
</P>
<P>
   And because, those who need to speculate will say, Olbermann has
worn out his welcome already and this is a way to separate him from
the rest of the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's total crap,'' Hill responded Thursday during a
conference call during the announcement of what will be called
``The Keith Olbermann Evening News,'' a multifaceted, one-hour
sports news and interview show starting Sunday, Aug. 6, in the 10
p.m. time slot.
</P>
<P>
   The name, by the way, is meant to be silly and serious. Take
your pick.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Hill admits he wasn't totally happy with the way Fox
Sports News had been evolving, even with Olbermann's presence,
which is why ``NFL on Fox'' Sunday-morning show producer Scott
Ackerson was brought on board about four months ago to revamp it
into what's now called ``The National Sports Report.''
</P>
<P>
   With that part of the plan in place, Fox can afford to branch
Olbermann off into his own show, of which he'll also be executive
producer. It will also fill a void of Sunday-night sports TV
programming that has yet to be defined clearly in this information
age of knowing game results hours before the news shows come on.
</P>
<P>
   The approach will be to replace the usual ``National Sports
Report'' hour with Olbermann's sports-news segment, followed by
analysis, opinions, interviews and essays. One-stop shopping, kinda
like the old ``Nightly News'' shows the networks did in the '60s
and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound as arrogant and egotistical as I've ever been,
but this is the one show you should watch if you only watch one
sports show,'' Olbermann said. ``The idea is I don't think there's
one show anymore with everything so diffused. If you want
interviews, you watch Jim Rome or Gary Miller (on ESPN's `Up
Close'). If it's analysis, you wait for (HBO's) `Real Sports' or
(ESPN's) `Outside the Lines' or (Fox's) `Goin' Deep.' There's no
full-service operation anymore. At least one night a week, we have
the opportunity to do it. We can experiment and see if this is what
the people want.''
</P>
<P>
   It's another risk Fox is willing to take. The worst that could
happen is it doesn't appeal to the cerebral sports fan and
Olbermann returns to the schlock factory.
</P>
<P>
   And for Olbermann, it's a unique situation in which he'll be his
own boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given my career history, I can now submit my own resignation
to myself,'' he said. ``Finally, I can give myself hell.''
</P>
<P>
   MEANWHILE, BACK IN THE STUDIO: If the only form of baseball that
Mark Gubicza could be around in his post-big-league career was in
helping coach his 5-year-old son's tee-ball team at Northridge
(Calif.) Little League, that'd be fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   But then a TV opportunity was presented to Gubicza on a tee.
Could it be even better?
</P>
<P>
   In this case, sure, especially since it was a gig near the San
Fernando Valley home that he and wife Lisa have lived in since they
were married in 1986 and where they've had two daughters, now 8 and
2.
</P>
<P>
   Two years removed from a disappointing end to his 14-year
career, Gubicza says he has the best of both family and baseball
going in as a studio analyst this year with Fox's ``National Sports
Report'' news show and its ``Baseball Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation couldn't be better,'' said Gubicza, who turns
38 in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, my job should be as a real husband and father.
Playing for so long away from home was so much a burden on my wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV certainly wasn't anything I thought much about after
retirement. If anything, I thought I'd be coaching. But it feels
great to be back in the game, expressing opinions. It's like I'm
back in the clubhouse again _ and I get to go home afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   After a shoulder injury pretty much washed out his final year _
a 0-1 record in two horrific starts with the Angels in '97 after 13
seasons with Kansas City that included two All-Star appearances _
Gubicza was asked by the Royals if he'd like to be a roving
minor-league pitching instructor. He passed.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox gave him a tryout and he was about to sign,
but he found out he'd have to spend time at Triple-A Pawtucket. He
passed again.
</P>
<P>
   ESPN even called to see if he'd like to be on its ``Baseball
Tonight'' show, but that meant going back to Bristol, Conn. No
thanks.
</P>
<P>
   But when Fox Sports talent recruiter Hank Siegel asked him out
of the blue if he'd like to do an audition for the news show,
Gubicza gave it a try.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. Getting by on more than just good looks,
Gubicza has been able to convey his thoughts with relative ease. He
says he has no trouble making the transition from playing field to
TV studio, even with the fine line ex-athletes and former managers
(such as fellow Fox analysts Ron Darling, Steve Sax and Kevin
Kennedy) have to draw when discussing current players with whom
they have long-time relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've treated it as if I was a player in that regard,'' Gubicza
said. ``I didn't like it when people said things about my
character. If I had a bad outing, fine. As long as it's not a
character issue. I'm not going to roast someone for the pure
entertainment of it.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- Coverage of the Tour de France winds down to this weekend's
final stages, and should Lance Armstrong keep that yellow shirt on,
ESPN says it will do what a 24-hour all-sports network should do _
cut in live Sunday morning, even if it's only the last 10 minutes
of the race. That's projected to between 7:50 and 8:08 a.m. Pacific
Time. A live report on the start of the final stage will be
featured in ESPN's 6 a.m. ``SportsCenter.'' ESPN2's regularly
scheduled coverage Sunday will be at 4 p.m., and ESPN has a show
starting at midnight. ABC has delayed coverage Saturday to 5 p.m. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- Mike Lamb joins Jim Watson and John Jackson on Fox Sports Net
2's coverage of the CaliFlorida high school all-star football game
from the Rose Bowl (Saturday, 7 p.m. PDT) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- No surprise with all the flowing synergy featured in the new
movie ``Disney's The Kid,'' but stay around for the credits and
you'll discover that it was ESPN ``SportsCenter'' anchor Rich Eisen
who played the part of ``Stuart Scott'' and Stuart Scott who did
``Rich Eisen.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- Used to be a team could win a title and then sell a few caps,
T-shirts and bumper stickers to make the fans feel a part of it.
Today, it's videos, CDs and quick-to-print books that the diehards
are expected to buy into or else feel incomplete. And only the
``officially licensed'' material will do. The official Lakers
1999-2000 championship video was released this week, an hour-long
production put out by NBA Entertainment and USA Home Entertainment
that sells for $19.99. That in itself is a nice investment with
some very decent never-before-seen stuff. But add to that the
official CD of what's described as ``arena music and the most
memorable calls of the season,'' and there's another $17. Can't
exclude the official NBA Finals 2000 retrospective, called ``The
Big Title'' by Barry Rubinstein and Lyle Spencer. Goes for $19.95.
So, for about $57, that'll set you up in case all this stuff
somehow escapes your recent memory. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- Wanna watch live Sparky Anderson's induction into the Baseball
Hall of Fame on Sunday? You'll need ESPN Classic. That channel has
the honor of showing it live at 10:30 a.m. PDT, which Adelphia
cable system, serving Anderson's hometown of Thousand Oaks, Calif.,
does carry. For everyone else, it's wait until Monday at 4:30 p.m.
to watch it on ESPN2. Usually, either ESPN or ESPN2 finds a way to
squeeze this annual event into its Sunday lineup, but for this day,
the Davis Cup, Senior PGA, the Swaps Stakes from Hollywood Park and
its ``Sunday Night Baseball'' game take up ESPN, while ESPN2 has
the U.S. men's soccer match from Costa Rica live, the Tour De
France and then the Dodgers-Giants game. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
-- Boomer Esiason, added this week to CBS Radio coverage of
``Monday Night Football,'' somewhat apologized for the Al
Michaels-bashing that occurred upon his firing a few months back.
``Certainly when you get released from somewhere, you get down and
you're emotional about it,'' Esiason said. ``I'm over it. I've
always worn my feelings on my sleeve. It took me awhile (to get
over it). No one ever wants to be told they can't do a job that
they think they're good at.'' Keep telling yourself that, Boomer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tom Hoffarth can be reached at sptmediaaol.com or (818) 713-3661. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
