<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALLON USES DETOUR ON WAY TO LEAD
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL FIELDS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURNEE, Ill. _ Meg Mallon knows that the route to success in the
U.S. Women's Open traditionally demands few detours, but she made
an unusual one Thursday while taking the first-round lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon chose a maverick strategy on the 14th hole in an
otherwise textbook round at the Merit Club. The result was a
4-under 68, which gave her a one-stroke lead over Australians
Karrie Webb and Shani Waugh. Juli Inkster, the defending champion,
was another stroke back at 70. Annika Sorenstam, the LPGA's money
leader, was five strokes back at 73.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the Women's Open in 1991, Mallon purposely drove
her tee shot at the difficult 406-yard par 4 into the wrong
fairway. The drive, played well right into the adjacent 13th
fairway to avoid water and sand on the troublesome dogleg hole, set
up a 5-iron shot to the green from 170 yards and a two-putt par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that's a better way to play the hole,'' said Mallon,
who was encouraged by her caddie, John Killeen. ``The tee shot on
14 is very severe.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that during her practice rounds, ``I had hit it in the
water and in the bunker and I thought going over to the 13th
fairway was a better option.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dottie Pepper looks back on her opening 76, she might
agree. Pepper was cruising along at even par before driving two
balls into the water at No. 14 and making a quadruple-bogey 8.
</P>
<P>
   The wind picked up in the afternoon, providing tougher
conditions for afternoon starters. Mallon, Waugh and Inkster each
played in the morning. ``It was almost perfectly calm when we teed
off,'' said the 30-year-old Waugh. ``This course is tough enough
when it's calm.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallon's decision at the 14th hole startled fellow players and
U.S. Golf Association officials, who hadn't anticipated such a
maneuver. ``I guess creativity is the hallmark of U.S. Women's Open
champions,'' said Kendra Graham, the USGA director of women's
competitions. ``I think it's ingenious. It just shows there are
many ways to skin a cat.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of an infamous piece of USGA history, Graham attempted
to play down Mallon's line of play on No. 14. During the first
round of the men's 1979 U.S. Open at Inverness Club in Toledo,
Ohio, Lon Hinkle and five others took a shortcut from the eighth
tee down the 17th fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Before the start of the second round, the USGA hastily planted a
24-foot spruce to block the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remember the Hinkle tree,'' Graham said. ``I would not want
to do that at the U.S. Women's Open.''
</P>
<P>
   A five-person championship committee had planned to discuss the
issue Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Mallon, meanwhile, would love to repeat her first-round form.
She hit 16 greens in regulation and did not make a bogey. Just a
few days ago, she was struggling with her swing,
uncharacteristically hitting shots far off line.
</P>
<P>
   But sessions with her instructor, Mike McGetrick, restored her
rhythm and tempo. ``I had no transition at the top of my
backswing,'' Mallon said. ``Mike and I just went back to basics. We
had to work on drills just to get me back.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her Women's Open victory in 1991, the 37-year-old
Mallon was second in 1995 and tied for fifth place last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some very good finishes in the U.S. Open,'' she said.
``But I know how fickle it is _ a certain break here or a lucky
bounce there. It's my favorite event, and I'd love to win it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb, who played in the stronger afternoon winds, is looking for
her first Women's Open title. She had to take her right shoe and
sock off to play a recovery shot out of a water hazard on the
seventh hole, but saved par. Webb birdied two of the final three
holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all it was just a really solid round of golf,'' Webb
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
