<HEADLINE>
SIX STATES BEGIN TO SUE PHONE   GIANTS  &HT;     BY TODD WALLACK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO - California and five other states filed separate
lawsuits against Worldcom Thursday, accusing the long distance
giant of slamming, cramming and deceptive advertising.
<P>
   Several states also sued AT&AMP;T and Sprint for misleading
advertising Thursday. But California regulators said they zeroed in
on Worldcom, the nation's second-largest long distance telephone
company, because it received more complaints than any other major
long distance carrier. Top complaints included slamming, or
switching customers' service without permission, and cramming
unauthorized charges on customers' bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are providing a necessary service, but they are doing it
utilizing unfair business practices,'' charged California Attorney
General Bill Lockyer.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC received more than 3,500 complaints against Worldcom
last year, more than AT&AMP;T, even though AT&AMP;T has three to four times
as many customers. And PUC complaints against Worldcom climbed 136
percent from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   As first reported in Thursday's Chronicle, Lockyer teamed up
with the California Public Utilities Commission to deliver a
two-fisted punch against Worldcom, which mainly sells long distance
service under the MCI name. The complaint, filed in San Francisco
Superior Court, seeks $20 million in penalties and court-ordered
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom declined to comment on the suits. But consumer groups,
who have long &LR;  frequently complained that long distance companies
have received scant attention from state regulators, cheered the
announcements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is great news,'' said Tom Long, an attorney with the
Utility Reform Network in San Francisco. ``No one in this office
can recall the PUC going to state court to enforce consumer
protection laws. This is a breath of fresh air.''
</P>
<P>
   Maine, Minnesota, Missouri and New Jersey also sued Worldcom.
Idaho and Maine sued AT&AMP;T. Illinois sued Sprint. And Connecticut
sued all three. Attorneys general said they coordinated the action
to pool their resources and boost the impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is to let the industry know that we mean
business,'' said Leslie Sandberg, a spokeswoman for the Minnesota
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Worldcom has already been fined for slamming by New York state
regulators, and recently paid the U.S. government $3.5 million in
lieu of a fine for slamming. But Connecticut Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal said federal regulators haven't done enough to
address false advertising and other issues. ``The federal agencies
have simply not stepped up to the plate'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint could not be reached for comment. But AT&AMP;T said the suits
were unwarranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been our longstanding policy to provide customers with
clear and direct information,'' said AT&AMP;T spokesman Mark Siegel.
``To do anything else in a competitive marketplace simply wouldn't
make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   But the California complaint cites several examples of
misleading ads from Worldcom, such as the company's ``Five Cents
Everyday''cq &LR;  promotion.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint says the advertisements are deceptive because the
rates don't apply to weekdays between 7 a.m. and 7 p.m., or
in-state calls. In addition, customers always wind up paying more
than a nickel per minute when extra charges are considered.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to standard taxes and calling rates, Worldcom
charges a monthly fee of up to $4.95 per month, levies a $5 minimum
for calls and tacks on a ``carrier access charge'' of $1.46 per
month. In addition, Worldcom charges up to 7.2 percent more for a
``Federal Universal Service Fee,'' even though the federal
government doesn't require Worldcom to charge the fee.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal, the Connecticut attorney general, singled out the
Worldcom ads, which often feature basketball star Michael Jordan
and cartoon icon Bugs Bunny, as particularly egregious. He said
many of the key details only appear in tiny print, if at all, while
a ``flurry of activity is on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Customers deserve the truth as big and clear as a Michael
Jordan slam dunk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone companies aren't actually legally required to disclose
all the terms and conditions to consumers, so long as they include
them in government filings. But regulators say they aren't allowed
to mislead customers either.
</P>
<P>
   California regulators also slammed Worldcom for bragging that
its national directory service lets customers ``get any phone
listing in America,'' when the database is incomplete. And
regulators said it didn't adequately disclose all the rates and
restrictions for its 10-10-321 dial-around long-distance number.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, when customers call to complain or ask
questions, they often encounter rude customer service
representatives, who sometimes hang up on them or put them on hold
for more than an hour, the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at todd(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
