<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8255 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COOKING--TEAMWORK-SFC     07-20 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING--TEAMWORK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMELLS LIKE TEAM SPIRIT
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KELLY YAMANOUCHI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO - A few weeks ago, Bob Valeiko and 17 colleagues in
his sales group at America Online were sipping wine and commenting
on the chef's delicious sweet-corn soup with spicy rock shrimp.
<P>
   Also on the menu were pan-seared halibut fillets with asparagus,
lemon risotto, Caesar salad and chocolate souffle. It was more than
Valeiko could bear.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't necessarily Valeiko's love for risotto that sparked
his enthusiasm. The truth is that the AOL senior executive and his
colleagues found the dinner particularly satisfying because they
had prepared it themselves, under the watchful eye of a chef, as
part of an unusual team-building exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Halibut fillets? Chocolate souffle? Team building?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the organizers believe the event serves team-building
purposes quite well.
</P>
<P>
   Their reasoning: The old team-building standbys such as rock
climbing and group brainstorming put employees through a lot of
physical exertion, mental stretching and competition without making
them happier or more productive.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the thinking is that an exercise like preparing dinner
together could very well be the type of relaxed atmosphere that can
truly help employees develop better rapport and build trust.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly a new idea. Mary Risley has been doing it for two
decades at her San Francisco cooking school, Tante Marie.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, cooking classes have been tailored to serve corporate
team-building purposes in other culinary meccas such as New York
and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking classes are gaining currency these days, especially in
the Bay Area, where Silicon Valley companies are looking for ways
to give professionals on the fast track a break as well as a chance
to get to know their co-workers beyond their e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of cooking and eating a sumptuous meal with colleagues
fits in well with the frenetic but casual workplace attitude so
prevalent in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are living such fast-paced lives where they're driving
in SUVs down to the Silicon Valley, coming back late at night and
microwaving their food,'' Risley said. ``Somehow, cooking classes
are grounding them. It's closer to a former life, it's not high
tech.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of AOL, the company firmly believes that
team-building events can help those groups that are separated
geographically and communicate mainly through e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Employees in Valeiko's sales unit say the cooking class was a
much-needed break from their long, hectic workdays.
</P>
<P>
   After cocktails and an explanation from chef Charlie Vollmar,
they put on their aprons, rolled up their sleeves and split up into
teams.
</P>
<P>
   One group clustered around the counter preparing a Caesar salad,
while another started mincing shallots for the appetizer.
</P>
<P>
   While Valeiko helped with the main dish, some of his co-workers
started on the chocolate souffle.
</P>
<P>
   Vollmar worked next to each team, giving instructions and brief
lessons on how to cook the ``professional way,'' starting with a
lesson on how to properly dice an onion.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two hours later, the group sat at dinner tables they
had set themselves complete with fanned napkins as they waited
eagerly to serve their dishes and taste what their co-workers made.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Flanagan, a sales representative for AOL, said she has done
plenty of other team building with activities such as rope-obstacle
courses. For her, the cooking class was not only a chance to learn
something new and practical, but also more relaxing, especially
because it came at the end of the workweek.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies are making team building a regular quarterly or
monthly event. They also aren't shy about investing tidy sums in
the exercise because they have seen the return in improved employee
workplace performance.
</P>
<P>
   In case of Valeiko's group, AOL shelled out nearly $2,000 for
the cooking class and even flew Valeiko and another employee in
from New York for the occasion. By comparison, other team-building
programs such as ropes courses and rock climbing can cost more,
nearly $200 per person for a half-day event.
</P>
<P>
   Companies also use cooking classes to serve other purposes, such
as rewarding the efforts of a department or getting employees and
their clients together.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing companies finding very untraditional ways of
entertaining their troops or entertaining their clients,'' said
Vollmar, who runs Epicurean Exchange, a 1-year-old business he
started to teach cooking classes for companies.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking classes can be ``a low-risk way to interact with
people,'' noted Bain &AMP; Co. employee Karen Greve, who learned to
cook with her co-workers during a team-building session.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Susan Forster, who teaches a seminar series on team building
through the Advanced Management Institute in San Francisco, said
she hadn't heard of this use of the culinary arts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she noted that a cooking class could have the fundamental
criteria for a successful team-building exercise: planning,
coordinating and evaluating the results _ skills that can be
brought to the next project at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage of cooking is that it makes team members
accountable: ``The meal you create _ that's what you get, and
that's what you gotta eat,'' Forster said.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 organizations in the Bay Area offer cooking classes
for corporate team-building purposes. They charge anywhere between
$45 per person for a two-hour class to $400 for an all-day session.
For that price, the employees get to eat what they have prepared in
a formal dinner, complete with wine.
</P>
<P>
   The price may be well worth it in today's red-hot job market,
where companies seek ways to keep qualified professionals from
bolting to other companies.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the cooking classes come in. Instead of using team
building to push employees harder, they are trying to show
employees that they are appreciated by using cooking classes as a
reward for finishing a project, or for a much-deserved break.
</P>
<P>
   But in some corporate cooking classes, results are still
everything.
</P>
<P>
   It starts with choosing a recipe designed to foster teamwork.
For instance, preparing a complex dish with a number of steps _
like chocolate souffle with a creme anglaise _ requires each person
in the group to work toward a common goal, with the completion of
each step and successful timing essential to successful execution.
</P>
<P>
   There are many variations of the cooking team-building game. One
of the California Culinary Academy's team-building programs
dispenses with recipes and favors the use of a ``mystery basket,''
in which the group is supposed to cook a meal after being given raw
ingredients _ such as vegetables, proteins, herbs and spices.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the team members set the rules of the game. The
group might decide that it can only ask a certain number of
questions of the chef before deciding what ingredients will bring
out the best flavor, then attempt to relate the exercise to their
work.
</P>
<P>
   Team Cuisine, a San Francisco organization that runs cooking
classes for companies, starts with the group deciding what their
goals for the session will be. For example, the goal might be to
get the group to work more cohesively, ending the session with a
discussion about what the team members learned while preparing the
meal.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Connolly, who runs Team Cuisine, says he uses ``cooking as a
metaphor for learning'' and also incorporates motivational speaking
into the program.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate cooking sessions provide an opportunity for
employees to learn more about their work styles in a different
setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some that direct, some that take charge, some that
chop, some that observe,'' said AOL's Valeiko.
</P>
<P>
   Often a manager might find that work habits from the office pop
up in the kitchen, giving insight to employees' teamwork styles.
</P>
<P>
   A culinary lesson also has a practical element for
corporate-ladder climbers who don't have the time or the energy to
cook at the end of the day. In the AOL telesales department,
everyone is under 30, none is married and few know their way around
the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, one cooking class won't turn anyone into a gourmet
chef. For many, it doesn't even necessarily yield any immediate
results in terms of building better teams. Instead, it's just an
expensive way to socialize with co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all have jobs that we sit in our cubes and we're on the
phone much of the day,'' AOL's Flanagan said. ``We don't have a lot
of time to relax and get to know each other personally.''
</P>
<P>
   And Flanagan strongly believes that in the long term, the
camaraderie built during a day out of the office can help in the
workplace. ``It enables you to rely on other people and ask people
questions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another AOL sales representative, Brian Tu, summed up the best
part of the cooking class for himself: ``Having my manager serve me
dinner. That's always fun.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Yamanouchi at  &LR; kyamanouchi &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
