<HEADER>
A8257 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCH     07-20 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIPMAKERS ARE THE HEROES OF THE SECOND-QUARTER ALL-STAR TEAM  &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're midway through the second-quarter earnings reporting
season, and once again, the all-star roster is loaded with
companies from the technology team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, what's driving the economy is energy and technology,
the same as the first quarter,'' says Chuck Hill, research director
with First Call, one of two major earnings trackers.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the companies in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 have
reported second-quarter results and so far, tech earnings are
beating expectations by 9 percent, and are up 44 percent
year-over-year, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all is said and done, we expect tech earnings to be up 36
percent,'' says Hill. That's even better than tech's 33 percent
year-over-year gain in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chip and chip-equipment companies are leading the techs. In
fact, four of the companies reporting the 10 largest gains are in
this category.
</P>
<P>
   Semiconductor earnings are up 163 percent; First Call is
expecting 133 percent when final results are in.
</P>
<P>
   Chip-equipment earnings are up 250 percent, but only two
high-flying companies have reported. First Call expects a final
gain of 148 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the big energy companies won't report earnings until
next week, but they are likely to be gushers. The five that have
reported so far have shown a 272 percent increase; First Call is
anticipating a 129 percent gain in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Hill says the biggest surprise has been electric utilities.
``What had been one of the more predictable sectors is now one of
the more unpredictable ones, because of deregulation. With the
demand situation changing as well, we're getting a lot of erratic
patterns. You get into a period when there are shortages and prices
go sky high. These companies are learning to cope, and once it
settles out it won't be as erratic.''
</P>
<P>
   Software is another mixed bag, says Joseph Kalinowski, equity
strategist at IBES International, the other big earnings tracker.
</P>
<P>
   After Computer Associates and BMC announced they wouldn't meet
earnings expectations, he thought all software companies might
struggle. Instead, ``they're either coming in real strong or
missing the consensus,'' Kalinowski says.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of PENDER21 (107960 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``On average, software companies are beating estimates by 11.3
percent. The average company in the S&AMP;P is beating by only 3.5
percent,'' Kalinowski says.
</P>
<P>
   What's not doing so well? Consumer durables, consumer services,
finance and transportation are all showing less than 10 percent
year-over-year gains in earnings.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, second-quarter earnings will be strong, but not as
robust as the sizzling first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Year-over-year growth was 23.6 percent in first quarter. So
far this quarter, we're only at 16 percent,'' Hill says. But he
thinks next week's energy surge will drive the final average to 18
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, investors responded to first-quarter earnings by
dumping stocks. They were so terrified by Alan Greenspan's interest
rate increases that they barely noticed near-record earnings gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This quarter, we're in a tug of war between an
interest-rate-driven market and an earnings-driven market,'' Hill
says.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever we get a bit of news that indicates the economy may be
overheating _ like last week's inflation number _ the market
panics. On days when the economy seems benign, investors focus once
again on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   One highlight: Small companies are doing as well as large ones,
which is unusual this late in an economic cycle.
</P>
<P>
   With 22 percent of the little guys reporting, the average
earnings gain is 18 percent. ``They're going to be about the same
as the S&AMP;P 500 after underperforming for two years,'' Hill says.
``Next quarter, small-cap earnings ought to exceed big cap.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; STH  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; EARNINGS SUE-PRISES: Are all surprises created equal?
</P>
<P>
   Not according to Joseph Kalinowski, who publishes a little-known
but interesting statistic known as the SUE score.
</P>
<P>
   Short for ``standardized unanticipated earnings,'' it measures
not just the size but the significance of an earnings surprise.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of PENDER21 (107960 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  For example, suppose two companies are both expected to earn 10
cents per share. However, analysts expect company Company A to earn
5 cents to 15 cents, and Company B to earn 9 cents to 11 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies report 20 cents. Both have a 100 percent
surprise. But company A beat the most optimistic analysts by only a
nickel, whereas company B blew away almost all of the analysts by a
much wider margin. Company B's surprise was more significant,
according to Kalinowski.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the SUE score measures the number of standard
deviations the actual reported earnings differ from the surprise
mean estimate.
</P>
<P>
   A 10 percent surprise relative to a 1 percent range in estimates
yields a SUE score of 10. A 10 percent surprise relative to a 10
percent range in estimates yields a SUE score of 1. Kalinowski says
a SUE score greater than 1 or less than negative 1 is a
statistically significant earnings surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with big SUE-prises for the second quarter are listed
in the accompanying chart. I'll update the list when earnings
season is over.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's hard to find SUE scores unless you're a
client of IBES. The New York company plans to begin publishing some
SUE scores on its Web site ( &LR; www.ibes.com &LR; ) but hasn't done so yet.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender(AT)sfgate.com
</P>
