<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8258 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-COULTER--CHASE-SFCHRO     07-20 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COULTER--CHASE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULTER EXCITED BY CHASE  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO - David Coulter &UR;  &LR; says he's thinking about his new
job, not dwelling on the past.
<P>
   The former chief executive officer of Bank of America, in one of
his first interviews since he was named vice chairman and consumer
banking chief of New York's Chase Manhattan Corp., said he is
charged up about his new assignment.
</P>
<P>
   Coulter had little to say about the 1998 sale of BofA to North
Carolina's NationsBank and his subsequent ouster by Hugh McColl,
the combined banks' boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm working hard to look forward as opposed to looking
backward,'' Coulter stressed. ``I guess if I had to make a summary
statement, it's just that I tried to do the right thing, I tried to
do things that made sense for the shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   During and after his 21/2 &LR; - &LR; year &LR;   &LR; stint as BofA's CEO,
Coulter's local reputation rode a roller coaster. At first, he was
the man who pumped up BofA's morale and its stock with a
disciplined yet personable management style.
</P>
<P>
   After the takeover, as jobs disappeared and BofA's stock
tumbled, many saw him as a bumbler who had sold out his bank,
walking away with a golden parachute that gives him $5 million a
year for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In the banking world, however, the reviews were not so harsh.
Coulter was widely admired for his intellect, analytical abilities
and people skills, if not for his bargaining acumen. ``He's
obviously a very talented guy,'' said Tony Price, an executive
recruiter with the search firm Russell Reynolds Associates.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving BofA, Coulter weighed several options before last
year joining the Beacon Group, an investment banking and money
management boutique. Two months ago, Chase, the nation's No. 3
bank, bought Beacon. Coulter found himself huddled with William
Harrison, the bank's CEO, discussing job possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Coulter said at first he wasn't enthusiastic
about staying with Chase in a subordinate role. But, Coulter said,
Harrison charmed him and promised him broad authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked probably three or four times,'' Coulter said. ``I
believe that Bill is really trying hard to create a team at the top
that works together. In terms of how we structured what I was going
to be doing, ... he was very flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter said he also was won over by the chance to run the
retail operation of one of the nation's top financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is changing the rules for financial institutions,
Coulter noted. Banks are struggling to come up with the right
balance of online and brick-and-mortar services.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of COULTER2 (100409 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &UR;  &LR;  ``The retail business today ... is certainly in a period of
change,'' he said. ``The people who get this right, who figure this
out strategically ... if you can be on the leading edge of that
change, you'll feel some real accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison sweetened his offer by handing Coulter responsibilities
for Chase's international operations and putting the bank's online
business under his supervision. ``I had my chance to have my cake
and eat it a couple of times,'' Coulter quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Before he got the top job at BofA, Coulter had little experience
as a consumer banking manager. He spent most of his career in staff
jobs or running corporate or international operations. But the old
BofA had one of the nation's most extensive retail networks, and
Coulter took a crash course in the business when he became the
bank's leader.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving BofA, Coulter moved to Los Angeles. He retains
extensive ties in the Bay Area and sits on the board of such
institutions as PG&AMP;E Corp. and the San Francisco Art Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Though he and his wife, Susan, will move to New York, Coulter
expects to return frequently to the Bay Area, especially to promote
the business of Chase's San Francisco investment bank, Chase H&AMP;Q,
the former Hambrecht &AMP; Quist. Coulter was an H&AMP;Q director before
Chase bought it last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to try hard to stay involved with California,'' he
said. ``At some point in time, I'll probably end up (living) in
California.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulter doesn't seem to spend much time thinking about the
ironic twists in his professional life. (Harrison, his new boss,
like McColl, is a native of the Carolinas.)
</P>
<P>
   Coulter said his new job is simply something that came along:
``This may not have been what I was expecting to do a year ago, but
this looks like an interesting opportunity for me.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
