r f BC-SCOUR--SUED-SFCHRON &LR;      07-20 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOUR--SUED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD ATTACKS DIGITAL MOVIE PIRACY 
 &HT;     BY CARRIE KIRBY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ Joining the recording industry in its escalating
war against Internet copyright infringement, the Motion Picture
Association of America filed a copyright infringement suit Thursday
against Scour, a Web exchange where people trade downloads of
full-length movies.
<P>
   ``This lawsuit is about stealing,'' said Jack Valenti, head of
the association, which represents major movie studios including
Sony and Universal. ``There's a feeling spread among young people
that it's OK to take something that belongs to others, just because
technology makes it possible. (But) you don't raise your children
to steal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association of America, which joined the
motion picture group and the National Music Publishers Association
in the suit, has a similar case pending against San Mateo's
Napster, a file-sharing program that allows millions of users to
trade music files.
</P>
<P>
   Both suits want the sites to halt distribution of bootleg music
and video materials. Films traded on Scour Exchange include some
not yet released on video, such as ``The Patriot'' and ``X-Men.''
The exchange can also be used to trade songs and still images.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also seeks $150,000 in damages for each copyright
infringement or reimbursement for profits lost. About 1.5 million
files have been downloaded from the Scour Exchange since the
program was started in April, the company estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Scour, a Los Angeles Web company that bills itself as a search
engine for multimedia content, insisted it has complied with
federal copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Scour has a notice posted on its Web site that says it
is not responsible for materials its users share. If copyright
holders do complain, Scour will remove links to the materials in
question, the notice says.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Thursday, Scour President Dan Rodrigues said he
was surprised by the lawsuit, especially because the Web site has
partnerships with Miramax and Hollywood Records, both listed as
plaintiffs in the suit, and recently met with Sony, Warner and BMG.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Scour is nearly identical to the case against
Napster now in federal court, said Brian Mudge, an
intellectual-property-rights lawyer with New York's Kenyon and
Kenyon. He predicted that the industry groups will win both cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scour is likely to find themselves in as much hot water as
Napster found themselves,'' Mudge said. ``The courts will find that
copyright law exists in cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters Thursday, Valenti
characterized the Internet exchanges as rogue companies and that
helped rob individual artists, technicians and other entertainment
industry workers of their royalty payments.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Scour is backed by mogul Michael Ovitz, who briefly
served as the president of Walt Disney and now runs a talent agency
called the Artists Management Group, which represents some of the
very artists Scour is accused of robbing. AMG's clients include
actor Robin Williams and director Martin Scorsese.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Sheirer, a media and entertainment analyst with Forrester
Research, said Ovitz's involvement lends legitimacy to the
file-sharing concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even an industry insider thinks this is a great service. It's
not just a rebel site like Napster that views these kinds of
services as something consumers really want,'' Sheirer said.
</P>
<P>
   Valenti and other industry officials acknowledged that in order
to control property rights online in the long term, major
entertainment companies will have to find ways to use the Internet
for their own purposes, perhaps taking advantage of technologies
similar to those used by Napster and Scour.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time that we're in the courtroom, we're also in
the laboratory and in cyberspace,'' Valenti said. ``Our ultimate
goal is to open movies online.''
</P>
<P>
   Scour and Napster are not the only Internet sites where people
trade copyright materials. New sites pop up continually. Some, such
as music-trading network Gnutella, exist informally as
decentralized networks of individual users that would be difficult
to sue. As a result, analysts say halting all online trading of
movies and music may be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Forrester's Sheirer say the lawsuits are worthwhile
because the industry can use them to influence the public and
congressional perception of unauthorized file trading. The Senate
Judiciary Committee has heard from both sides of the debate in
recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Eight movie studios, including Disney and Time Warner, and 16
record companies were listed as plaintiffs in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
