<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-WOOD-PRODUCTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLYWOOD MAKER WILLAMETTE INDUSTRIES SETTLES POLLUTION CASE FOR
$93.2 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency and the Justice
Department announced Thursday that a plywood manufacturer with 13
factories in four states had agreed to a $93.2 million settlement
for air pollution violations, the largest settlement based on
pollution from factories.
</P>
<P>
   The accord means that the environmental agency has settled
pollution cases in the last few years with companies that make up
more than half the wood products industry. In a sector-by-sector
campaign to enforce the terms of the Clean Air Act, the agency has
also reached agreements with diesel engine manufacturers, but it is
still battling with refineries and with coal-burning power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement with Willamette Industries Inc., a plywood and
building materials manufacturer based in Portland, Ore., with
plants in Arkansas, Louisiana and South Carolina as well, follows
settlements with Louisiana-Pacific, Georgia-Pacific and
Weyerhaeuser; the government is still pursuing Boise-Cascade.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a civil penalty of $11.2 million, Willamette will
spend $8 million on environmental projects, and $74 million on new
pollution-control equipment, government officials said. Carol
Browner, the EPA administrator, said that the company had saved
money for years by not installing equipment to reduce emissions but
that with the settlement, ``the economic benefit has been captured
in the penalty, and then some.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Duane McDougall, the company's chief executive
officer, said the company had reached the agreement ``to resolve
certain historic air permit questions.'' Willamette will install
emission control equipment that is ``well beyond what is
required,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA says factories that emit pollutants into the air must
have permits to make changes in the plants. Browner said, ``These
guys didn't even say they needed a permit.''
</P>
<P>
   McDougall said that Willamette had consulted with state
authorities as it made changes to its factories over the years and
had been told that no permits were required, but that the
environmental agency had ``revisited these decisions based on a
revised interpretation of long-established standards and
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's defense is similar to the one still being raised
by electric utility companies that the agency last year accused of
not seeking permits for changes they had made to their plants.
</P>
<P>
   Willamette makes plywood and composite panels. The adhesives
used to bond sheets of plywood together, or form composites, give
off pollutants, volatile organic compounds, that react with
nitrogen compounds in sunlight to form smog.
</P>
<P>
   Under the settlement, the company will install equipment to
reduce emissions of the compounds, as well as cut emissions of
small particles and carbon monoxide. The company will spend money
to improve municipal sewer systems, acquire park land and build
ethanol fueling stations to encourage companies that own fleets of
vehicles to use clean fuel.
</P>
</TEXT>
