<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-INDICTMENTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SALT LAKE CITY OLYMPIC BID ORGANIZERS INDICTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (DELETES first sentence of 12th graf because it repeats first
sentence of 5th graf)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After rejecting plea deals in recent days, the two chief
organizers of Salt Lake City's bid to win the 2002 Winter Olympics
were indicted Thursday by a federal grand jury on charges of
conspiracy to commit bribery, fraud and racketeering related to the
vote-buying scandal that erupted in late 1998 and threatened the
future of the Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-count indictment alleges that Thomas Welch, 55, the
former president of the Salt Lake City bid committee, and David
Johnson, 41, the former vice president, paid $1 million to
improperly influence the votes of more than a dozen delegates of
the International Olympic Committee, which awards the host sites
for the Winter and Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   The two former officials also secretly paid an official of the
U.S. Olympic Committee to assist in Salt Lake City's bid, drew up a
series of bogus contracts, falsified books, records and other
documents to conceal their activities, and diverted $130,000 in bid
committee money for personal use, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Welch and Johnson became the fourth and fifth persons to be
prosecuted in the Salt Lake City scandal, and according to the
indictment were the ones most directly involved in the plan to win
votes through lavish spending and gift-giving to IOC delegates. A
series of revelations about the scandal in late 1998 and early in
1999 severely damaged the Olympics and the credibility of the IOC,
and threatened to topple the committee's president, Juan Antonio
Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   Ten delegates either resigned or were forced out in the wake of
the scandal. Late last year, acknowledging that the bid process had
become corrupted, the IOC instituted a policy that prohibits its
members from visiting cities seeking to host Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Welch and Johnson rejected a plea deal they described
as too sweeping in what they would have to admit to. Subsequent
efforts by their lawyers and prosecutors to reach a deal were
unavailing. In Thursday's indictment they were charged with one
count of conspiracy, five counts of mail fraud, five counts of wire
fraud and four counts of interstate travel in aid of racketeering.
Each charge carries a maximum of five years in prison and a fine of
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the charges have been reported previously in great
detail. The one new charge that has surfaced in recent days
concerned money that Welch and Johnson allegedly used for personal
purposes. Jet Set Sports, a New York-based ticket and travel agent,
acknowledged in a statement on Wednesday that it was cooperating
with federal authorities regarding $130,000 in a series of cash
payments that it made to the Salt Lake City bid officials in 1994
and 1995, before the 2002 Games were awarded. At the time, the
company was seeking to become an official Olympic sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   Max Wheeler, Johnson's attorney, had told reporters in Salt Lake
City that the company made the donations because it stood to make a
significant profit as an official Olympic travel broker, which it
later became. Wheeler said the money was spent on bid activities,
not personal enrichment. The indictment describes a series of cash
payments totaling $130,000 made by a potential Olympic sponsor to
Welch and Johnson at airports and hotels between August of 1994 and
May of 1995. The 2002 Games were awarded on June 16, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued through his Washington-based attorney,
Welch denied that he and Johnson had committed any wrongdoing.
Wheeler has said repeatedly that the two Olympic officials were
being made scapegoats for participating in what had become a common
practice among bid cities of providing exorbitant favors for
members of the IOC in order to secure their votes. Both men have
denied bribing any delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to assure everyone,'' Welch said in the statement,
``that David Johnson and I committed no crime. I took no pay from
the bid effort. I did not ask for or receive anything personally
from the (bid) committee or from anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   An independent ethics panel investigating Salt Lake City's bid
concluded that officials had given more than $1.2 million in cash
payments, scholarships, jobs, medical treatment, shopping sprees,
excessive travel and expensive baubles to IOC delegates and their
families. The panel pointed most of the blame at Welch and Johnson,
who, in turn, have said that there was widespread knowledge and
approval of their activities in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, it has been revealed that similar bidding practices
also occurred in Atlanta's securing of the 1996 Summer Olympics,
Nagano, Japan's hosting the 1998 Winter Games and Sydney,
Australia's bid to win the 2000 Summer Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 of the IOC's 114 delegates have been linked to various
bidding improprieties, both major and minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that we defrauded the bid committee or anybody else
is preposterous,'' Welch said in his statement. ``So is the charge
that we bribed anybody. But that does not change the fact that we
will be photographed and booked like common criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, who is Johnson's attorney, called the charges ``ill
advised'' and said they may ``jeopardize the effective presentation
of the Olympic Games.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both men seemed to rule out accepting any further plea offer
that might come from federal prosecutors. Current Salt Lake City
Olympic officials have expressed concern that the specter of a
trial will further cloud their efforts to prepare and continue to
raise sponsorship money for the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Welch said: ``We and our families must go through the agony of a
criminal trial on the eve of the Games because we did what we, and
many other people, thought was absolutely necessary and in keeping
with the ideals of the community. We will defend ourselves and we
will be acquitted, but no one can possibly understand the
heartbreak and disappointment I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   David Simmons, a Salt Lake City businessman, had pleaded guilty
to tax offenses related to an alleged sham telecommunications job
provided to Jung Hoon Kim, the son of a powerful IOC delegate from
South Korea named Kim Un-Yong. The son, known as John Kim, has been
indicted but has left the country and is considered a fugitive by
the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Alredo La Mont, formerly in charge of international relations
for the USOC, had also pleaded guilty to tax charges related to
payments he secretly received from the Salt Lake bid committee for
his effort as a consultant to help secure the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
