u f BC-AOL-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      07-20 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA ONLINE REGISTERS STRONG PROFIT FOR QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
  By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signaling that the problems of many Internet start-ups are not
hurting their larger cousins, America Online on Thursday reported
fiscal fourth-quarter earnings of $338 million, up 115 percent from
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   America Online, the world's biggest Internet company and one of
the few profitable ones, earned 13 cents a share, 2 cents more than
analysts had expected. But analysts, generally conservative in
their predictions, said the results were solid but contained few
surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't come in with any fireworks here, but they met
expectations,'' said Paul Noglows, an analyst with Chase H&AMP;Q.
</P>
<P>
   For the company's fiscal year, ended June 30, it earned $1.2
billion on sales of $6.9 billion, marking the first time an
Internet company has earned more than $1 billion in a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only four years ago after becoming the first Internet company
with $1 billion in annual revenue, we now post $1 billion in
profit,'' Steve Case, the chairman, boasted on a conference call
with investors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the well-publicized problems of many Internet companies,
most of which had been big advertisers on AOL's services, the
company's advertising and electronic commerce revenue increased by
95 percent to $609 million.
</P>
<P>
   Case played down any slowing in an interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of our advertising revenue comes from
companies like Coca-Cola, which have been around for a long time
and will be around forever,'' he said. ``The minority comes from
dot-com's, and of that, most come from well-funded companies.'' He
also noted that even the most troubled start-ups might well manage
to be taken over, as CDNow, an AOL client, was Thursday by
Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty clear that now they will be able to pay their
bills,'' Case said.
</P>
<P>
   Case added that he expected growth in advertising to remain
steady for the rest of the year and to pick up next year when the
company's acquisition of Time Warner Inc. was completed. He noted
that there was little overlap between the top advertisers at AOL
and Time Warner, creating the opportunity to sell more to existing
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Case dismissed statements by the Walt Disney Co. that it would
ask federal regulators to force the combined AOL and Time Warner to
spin off its cable systems or otherwise make sure that its content
was not given more favorable treatment on its distribution
networks. He said he agreed with statements by Gerald Levin, his
counterpart at Time Warner, calling Disney's move ``silly and
absurd.'' And he said he did not expect any problems completing the
acquisition by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts agreed. ``There has long been an issue about the cable
assets,'' Noglows said. ``But I don't see that as a deal breaker.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, America Online is continuing its unparalleled
growth. In the most recent quarter, subscription revenue increased
by 26 percent to $1.2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Even though spring is historically the slowest season for new
customers, the flagship service added 992,000 new subscriptions in
the quarter for 23.2 million members worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's CompuServe 2000 service, which is offered with rebates and
discounts to appeal to price-conscious customers, added 146,000
members in the quarter. After a loss of about 50,000 subscribers to
the company's older and more expensive CompuServe Classic service,
CompuServe's total membership worldwide membership rose to 2.8
million. Over the last year, CompuServe 2000 added 1.3 million new
subscriptions, but the classic service lost 500,000 subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The international versions of the AOL and CompuServe services
added a total of 200,000 subscribers in the quarter to reach 3.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   AOL said its expenses were up 25 percent to $1.5 billion for the
quarter. But it said that it benefited from sharp drops in the cost
of providing the telecommunications network, largely resulting from
regulatory changes.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting America Online's strong financial position, even in
contrast to the other large Internet companies, its cash position
increased by $1.9 billion over the last year to $3.9 billion at the
end of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that its backlog of commitments to advertise in
the future increased by $300 million in the quarter, to $3 billion,
twice the level of a year ago. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
