<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TO CAMPAIGN IN HOMETOWN; BUSH LEAD SLIPS IN OHIO 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY TO CAMPAIGN IN HOMETOWN
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey will campaign in his
hometown of Crystal City, Mo., on Saturday with Gov. Mel Carnahan,
a Democrat who is trying to unseat Sen. John Ashcroft, a one-term
Republican, in one of the year's hardest-fought congressional
races. The event will be part of a four-day, 22-stop train tour
across Missouri by Carnahan that is intended to recreate the 1948
whistle-stop tours around America by another Missourian, President
Harry S. Truman. Bradley will be campaigning for just the second
time since he dropped out of the Democratic presidential primaries
in March; last week, he endorsed Vice President Al Gore in
Wisconsin. Although Bradley lost the Missouri primary to Gore, he
remains wildly popular in Crystal City, where he kicked off his
campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH LEAD SLIPS IN OHIO
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush has lost some ground to Vice President Al
Gore in Ohio, considered a swing state in the fall election, a new
poll shows. The poll, released Thursday by the University of
Cincinnati's Institute for Policy Research, has Bush leading Gore
by four points in a two-candidate field, 49 percent to 45 percent,
and by six points, 47 percent to 41 percent, in a four-candidate
field that includes Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party and Ralph
Nader of the Green Party. In April, a poll by the institute gave
Bush a nine-point lead over Gore in a two-candidate race and an
eight-point lead when Buchanan and Nader were included. In both
polls the third-party candidates had 4 percent or less. The new
poll, which surveyed 537 likely voters from July 5-13 and has a
margin of sampling error of plus or minus four percentage points,
also found that roughly a third of Bush and Gore supporters might
switch their vote to another candidate before Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON WOULD FIND TOUGH FIGHT
</P>
<P>
   He has never given any real indication that he might try it, but
President Clinton would face a hard fight if he ran for the Senate
in his native Arkansas after leaving the White House, a new poll
shows. The Mason-Dixon poll, commissioned by The Arkansas
Democrat-Gazette, shows Clinton trailing Sen. Tim Hutchinson, a
Republican whose first term ends in 2002, 49 percent to 41 percent,
with 10 percent undecided. Clinton has laughed off but never denied
speculation that he might seek a Senate seat, as his wife, Hillary,
is doing in New York.The poll, conducted July 13-15 and covering
622 registered voters, has a margin of sampling error of plus or
minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   THE CONVENTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Billy GRAHAM'S SON DELIVERS BENEDICTION
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Graham, the eldest son of the Rev. Billy Graham and
also an evangelist, will deliver the benediction that closes the
first day of the Republican National Convention in Philadelphia on
July 31. Graham, who lives in North Carolina and is president of
Samaritan's Purse, a Christian relief organization, offered a
prayer at the 1996 Republican convention in San Diego. To attend
the convention, Graham will fly from an international evangelists'
conference in Amsterdam, which is being arranged by his father's
organization, the Billy Graham Evangelistic Association.
TODAY'S SCHEDULES
GEORGE W. BUSH _ No public events AL GORE _ Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
