<HEADER>
A8280 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-73     07-20 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-CAMPAIGN-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY ASSAILS LAZIO ON HOME LOAN VOTE
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Suggesting that her opponent cared more about wealthy
campaign donors than about constituents, Hillary Rodham Clinton
attacked Rep. Rick Lazio on Thursday for trying to kill legislation
in 1998 to expand a federal program that helps first-time home
buyers obtain mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton questioned why Lazio had objected to the legislation,
since it was intended to benefit people in more expensive areas,
including Lazio's district on Long Island, by raising the limit on
the size of mortgages guaranteed by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The program, run by the Federal Housing Administration, assists
first-time home buyers or those with shaky credit, who might
otherwise have difficulty in securing a mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had vigorously fought the legislation, saying at the time
that it was an unacceptable intrusion by government into private
industry. The program provides competition for private mortgage
insurance companies, which charge fees to guarantee mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, one of the most influential Republicans on housing
issues, and a few other senior Republicans were able to scale back
the measure before it passed. Less than a month later, Lazio
collected a total of $23,500 in contributions from six of the
largest private mortgage insurance companies in the nation. The
Lazio campaign said recently that the donations were not related to
the fight over the loan limit.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Clinton maintained that Lazio had betrayed his
constituents by opposing a higher loan limit and said that she
would have championed the proposal. ``His opposition meant that if
he had prevailed, fewer people in Long Island and in the rest of
New York would have been able to afford a home,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the donations to Lazio, which were reported in The
New York Times on Thursday, she said, ``We are going to have to let
New Yorkers reach their own conclusions about what that means.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Flood, a spokesman for the Lazio campaign, disparaged
Clinton's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has done more for affordable housing in New York than
Rick Lazio as chairman of the subcommittee on housing,'' Flood
said. ``He authored and led the fight for a number of landmark
public housing and affordable housing bills. He has an outstanding
record. The real question is, where has Hillary Clinton been and
what has she done for homeownership in New York?''
</P>
<P>
   The jousting over Lazio's record came as both campaigns
continued to feud over the contents of fund-raising solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   A new letter signed by the chairman of the Republican State
Committee, William Powers, says Clinton is an ``ambitious,
ruthless, scheming, calculating, manipulating woman,'' and later
refers to her as an ``angry woman whose political views are so far
to the left, she has left common sense behind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's been at the front and center of every Clinton-Gore
scandal and this has been the most seedy, shameless and corrupt
administration in American history,'' says the letter, which was
first disclosed Thursday by The Associated Press. Powers also
refers to Clinton's daughter, Chelsea, noting that Clinton did not
send Chelsea to school in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second strongly worded letter from the state party
attacking Clinton to surface this month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has long stirred passionate feelings across the
country, has been a powerful lure in fund-raising letters, with
Republicans across the nation invoking her name in an effort to
generate money from people who dislike her. Before he withdrew from
the Senate race, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York, Lazio's
predecessor as Senate candidate, set a fund-raising record in part
by tapping into this sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Albany, Powers said the language in the
letter was not anti-woman and was an accurate portrayal of
Clinton's character. He said he was not concerned that the letter
would backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a response to direct mail like we're getting
from her,'' Powers said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Howard Wolfson, attacked the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``While Rick Lazio smiles for the cameras in public, his
Republican allies quietly send out insult-filled letters behind
closed doors,'' Wolfson said in a statement. ``It's time for the
hypocrisy to stop. These negative letters signal that Rick Lazio
and the GOP have no intention of running a campaign on the
issues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After Giuliani withdrew from the Senate race in May, saying he
needed to concentrate on treatment of his prostate cancer, he
pledged to help Lazio. The Giuliani campaign now says it has
returned about $3 million to donors, with instructions to make it
easy for them to send the money to Lazio. It is not clear how many
have heeded the request.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce J. Teitelbaum, a senior political adviser to Giuliani,
said the campaign had $3.8 million left and added that Giuliani
advisers would be meeting with senior state Republicans in the
coming weeks to determine how Giuliani could use his political
operation to help Lazio and other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Teitelbaum said the campaign had already begun to use its list
of donors to assist local candidates. For example, the campaign has
culled the names of donors who live in Lazio's congressional
district and has given them to the Republican who is running to
succeed him, Joan Johnson, to aid her fund-raising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
