<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-EXPOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER GAME, ANOTHER INJURY: THIS TIME, METS LOSE ALFONZO
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The bases were loaded with two outs in the eighth
inning, and his team was trailing by three runs. Even so, Edgardo
Alfonzo knew he could not hit.
</P>
<P>
   When he came off the field after the bottom of the seventh,
Alfonzo, the New York Mets' All-Star second baseman, told manager
Bobby Valentine that he could not continue. Alfonzo has been
bothered all season by soreness in his right hip, and he had
crossed the threshold of tolerable pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you can play with pain, and you know when you
have to shut it down because you don't feel really good,'' Alfonzo
said. ``When you don't feel like you're 80 percent, it's a good
thing to come out of the game and give another guy the opportunity
to do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the other guy was Mark Johnson, who struck out
against the Montreal Expos' Dustin Hermanson, ending the inning and
the Mets' best chance of the day. The Mets lost to the Expos, 4-1,
and they have split the first eight games on this road trip heading
into the opener of a three-game series in Atlanta on Friday against
a Braves team that is now five games ahead of them in the NL East.
</P>
<P>
   After playing the last five games on unforgiving artificial
surfaces, Alfonzo aggravated the hip flexor on a single in the
fourth inning. He will receive treatment on the hip Friday, but
general manager Steve Phillips said he did not plan for Alfonzo to
visit a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo conceded that ``it's going to be a little tough'' to
play against the Braves on Friday, and Valentine said the soreness
would have to calm down considerably before he'd put Alfonzo in the
lineup. It stands to reason that the Mets, who have a rested
bullpen and are carrying 12 pitchers, will recall a position player
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They may do something more. Phillips watched the game from a
private box at Olympic Stadium, talking on the telephone most of
the time; yes, he said, he was speaking with other teams about
trades. The Mets may have a match with the Los Angeles Dodgers for
Darren Dreifort, a starting pitcher, or with the Cincinnati Reds
for shortstop Barry Larkin. Phillips is also trying to bolster the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets could play their leading division rival with first
baseman Todd Zeile as their only regular infielder who is not out
with an injury.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Rey Ordonez is out for the season with a broken arm,
and his replacement, Melvin Mora, is 3 for 26 since the All-Star
Game break. Third baseman Robin Ventura, who is on the disabled
list with a bruised rotator cuff, is halfway into the two-week
period the Mets believe he will be sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be sitting around waiting for a knight in shining
armor in a trade to rescue your team,'' said catcher Mike Piazza.
``If we go out and get a guy that can help us out, great, but we've
got to win with the core of guys that we have here now.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the lesser-heralded Mets have contributed lately, the
Mets without Alfonzo and Ventura are far less intimidating. There
are fewer hitters to pitch around.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one of the biggest contributors to us offensively,''
starter Mike Hampton, Thursday's losing pitcher, said of Alfonzo.
``Losing Robin is big enough, and having him out of your lineup
basically kills us. Besides Todd and Mike, those are the guys that,
if I was the opposing pitcher, those two guys ain't going to beat
me. I'd make the other guys beat me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to lose two of your best players. We need to do
something to get back to where we were and to get healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza pointed out that the Expos are not healthy, either, but
they overcame their injuries and won Thursday. Vladimir Guerrero,
the incomparable right fielder, was out with a strained right hip
flexor, and center fielder Rondell White was out with a strained
hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Chris Widger's bat did most of the damage off Hampton.
Widger homered to lead off the sixth, breaking a 1-1 tie, then
stroked a two-run double off the left-field wall in the seventh. In
his career, Widger is 8 for 12 off Hampton, whose record fell to
9-7.
</P>
<P>
   To Valentine, Hampton has not been quite as sharp since beating
the Yankees while pitching on three days' rest on July 9. Hampton
will get an extra day of rest when the Mets are off on Monday.
``I'm sure that day will do him a world of good,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton did not dispute that, but he brushed off the suggestion
that the short rest _ or the muscle cramp in his forearm that
forced him from the Yankees game after seven shutout innings _ has
affected him at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, maybe they're searching for answers because
we're losing games when I pitch,'' Hampton said. ``I'm fine. I
thought I had some of my best stuff of the year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
