u s BC-BBA-EVERETT-NYT &LR;      07-20 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-EVERETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT GIVEN A 10-GAME SUSPENSION
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Everett, one half of the heart of the Boston Red Sox
offense, was suspended for 10 games and fined $5,000 Thursday for
his encounter _ physical and verbal _ with an umpire in a game with
the New York Mets last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Everett postponed the suspension, which was to have begun
Thursday, by appealing the disciplinary action by Frank Robinson,
major league baseball's vice president for on-field operations.
Everett then went out and hit a two-run home run in the first
inning of the first game of a day-night doubleheader in Baltimore.
He finished 1 for 5 and struck out four times in Boston's 11-7
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the suspension, Robinson said he acted because of
the outfielder's excessive arguing, foul language and contact with
Ron Kulpa, the home plate umpire, who had told Everett he was
standing too close to home plate when he batted against the Mets in
a 6-4 Boston triumph.
</P>
<P>
   During his tirade, Everett bumped Kulpa with his chest, then
angrily slammed his helmet to the ground and struck the umpire in
the face with his face, sending Kulpa staggering backward.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox personnel had difficulty controlling and calming the
enraged Everett, who, when he finally reached the dugout, knocked
over a water container and tossed a bat onto the field, just
missing a teammate, Bret Saberhagen, in the process.
</P>
<P>
   With a .320 batting average and a team-leading 26 home runs and
74 runs batted in before Thursday night's second game, Everett will
leave a hole in the Red Sox lineup when he serves his suspension,
whether it's 10 games or a reduced number. He and Nomar Garciaparra
form the nucleus of the team's offense, and the Red Sox can ill
afford to lose him in their quest for a playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   Because Everett looked so out of control in his confrontation
with Kulpa, some people believed he would be hit with a longer
suspension. Robinson might have been inclined to make it longer,
but he wound up somewhat in the middle of the range of previous
suspensions for similar actions.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing on Everett's appeal, Players Association lawyers
will argue that both the length of the suspension and the fine are
excessive. Management lawyers will most likely use as Exhibit A the
case of Bill Madlock, who in a 1980 game shoved his glove into the
face of Umpire Jerry Crawford.
</P>
<P>
   Madlock was fined $5,000 and suspended for 15 days. After his
appeals were denied, the Pittsburgh Pirates third baseman served
the suspension from June 6 through June 19, missing 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Coleman of St. Louis, on the other hand, was fined $500
and suspended for seven games in 1990 after he cut Ed Montague's
nose with the bill of his batting helmet.
</P>
<P>
   The longest suspension for physical contact with an umpire is
believed to belong to Pete Rose, who as manager of the Cincinnati
Reds in 1988 was given 30 days for pushing Dave Pallone. A.
Bartlett Giamatti, then N.L. president, imposed the severe penalty
because, he said, Rose's action incited Riverfront Stadium fans,
who threw objects onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   Everett became incensed when Kulpa drew a line with his foot,
indicating the border of the batter's box at the side near home
plate. Everett stands closer to the plate than most batters, and
Kulpa felt he was closer than the six inches the rules stipulate
should separate the plate from the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Dennis Cook of the Mets was ejected from the
interleague game after he hit Everett with a pitch. Cook argued
that Everett was standing out of the batter's box.
</P>
<P>
   In Baltimore Thursday, Everett said the news media coverage of
his incident with the umpire ``tried to make me out to be a
monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say I didn't do the things people said I did,'' he
added. ``I could say some things that could ruffle some feathers,
but I'd rather keep that to myself until I state my case.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's contact with Kulpa's head has been described by some
as a headbutt, but Larry Reynolds, Everett's agent, said he looked
at a tape of the confrontation frame by frame and saw no such
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl's lips and nose touched the umpire,'' Reynolds said in a
telephone interview, ``but his forehead clearly never touched the
forehead of the umpire. There clearly was no headbutt.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone, Robinson declined to elaborate on his
decision, explaining that he will have to testify at the appeal
hearing before Paul Beeston, chief operating officer of Major
League Baseball. No date has been set for the hearing, but it most
likely won't be held until next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
