<HEADLINE>
STATE ENCOURAGES MORE SWIMMING IN A CLEANER HUDSON
</HEADLINE>
  By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ After years of cleaning up the garbage and
pollution that gave the Hudson River a bad name, New York State
officials are now trying to bring back public beaches and swimming
areas along its shores.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Environmental Conservation and the State
Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation have begun a
two-year study to develop state-operated public swimming beaches
along the Hudson from Manhattan to Columbia County, just south of
Albany. The $88,000 study is part of Gov. George Pataki's 1996
initiative, the Hudson River Estuary Action Plan, to protect the
river.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water quality in the Hudson River has improved
dramatically, particularly in the last decade,'' said Jennifer
Post, a DEC spokeswoman. ``Obviously, it's a big river and there
are some areas where tides or other conditions may make it
inappropriate to swim, but we believe there are many locations
where swimming is safe and should be encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Although swimmers have dipped into the Hudson River for as long
as anyone can remember, extensive pollution from raw sewage and
chemical runoffs in earlier decades have made it a less than
attractive option for most people. ``Swimming in the Hudson is a
longstanding activity, but people used to have to clear a path
before they could get in the water,'' said Cara Lee, environmental
director for Scenic Hudson, a nonprofit group that monitors the
river.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials and environmentalists say water quality has
steadily improved as a result of pollution controls adopted by
government agencies since the 1972 Clean Water Act, which required
that sewage be treated before being released into the river. State
research shows that most of the river is now safe for swimming,
Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Swimmers now have access to the Hudson from a handful of public
parks operated by local governments, including Croton Point Park in
Westchester County and Kingston Point Park in Ulster County. Other
swimmers enter the river from private property or boats.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the state sent out 2,500 questionnaires to businesses,
environmental organizations, government agencies and randomly
selected residents to solicit suggestions for more public swimming
sites. More than half of the forms have been returned, naming 50
locations from Manhattan to Troy.
</P>
<P>
   State officials met Thursday night at Bear Mountain State Park
in Rockland County to discuss the swimming study with local
residents. Another meeting has been scheduled for Tuesday in Greene
County, and officials will continue to take written comments until
Aug. 4. No decision has been made on how many swimming sites would
be developed, or how they would be paid for.
</P>
<P>
   Several environmentalists said Thursday that they welcomed the
state's efforts. ``If people are swimming at a place, the
government has to make sure the water there is clean enough,'' said
Cathy Drew, director of the River Project, a marine biology
monitoring station in Manhattan. ``The very best thing we can do
for the river is to jump in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
