<HEADLINE>
U.S. NUCLEAR AGENCY DELAYS REOPENING OF PLANT IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MATTHEW L. WALD with RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Nuclear Regulatory Commission Thursday said
that Con Edison was not ready to reopen the Indian Point 2 nuclear
reactor with its existing steam generators. The decision makes it
less likely that the plant will resume operations this summer and
more likely that consumers will see higher utility bills.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC, in a letter sent to plant managers Thursday, asked for
extensive further analysis of the steam generators, one of which
caused an accident that shut down the plant Feb. 15. The commission
staff said that the accuracy of the instrument for measuring flaws
in the tube walls had been determined by using a tube at another
reactor and that the tubes at Indian Point might differ.
</P>
<P>
   A Con Ed spokesman, Joseph P. Petta, said, ``Right now the
immediate focus is getting these answers to the NRC.'' But he said
the company might try to reduce the uncertainty by sealing off the
tubes most likely to leak, or that it might go ahead with replacing
the steam generators immediately, a step that would preclude
operation for months. ``We haven't ruled anything out,'' Petta
said.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said Con Ed could have saved its customers money by
replacing the generators months or even years ago. Loss of the
plant for the rest of the summer would also increase the risk of
the region's running short of power during the season when heat
waves can challenge the system's ability to produce enough
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seemingly, this is the opportunity for Con Ed to go ahead and
do the right thing and replace the steam generators, and not put
the public at any greater risk than they have to be,'' said James
P. Riccio, a nuclear expert at the Critical Mass Energy Project, a
nonprofit group founded by Ralph Nader that had petitioned the
regulatory commission to keep the plant shut. ``If they had
replaced the steam generators in February, they would be making
money hand over fist right now. Instead, they're paying it out hand
over fist.''
</P>
<P>
   After the February accident, the company inspected the steam
generators and asked for permission to run the plant for up to 10
months. But it also said it planned to shut down and replace the
steam generators in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   It now faces the prospect of buying replacement power through
the high-demand, high-cost weeks of late July through early
September, while it repairs the steam generators to the
satisfaction of the regulators or installs replacement generators
already at the plant site, in Buchanan, N.Y., on the east bank of
the Hudson River near Peekskill.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Costs are higher this summer because oil and natural gas, the
substitutes, are up in price. And because New York state has
deregulated its utilities, power costs now vary much more sharply
according to the time of year. Con Ed has sold off nearly all of
its own generators, and is seeking to sell Indian Point.
</P>
<P>
   The steam generators are giant heat exchangers. Indian Point 2
heats water in the nuclear core and then pumps it into the steam
generators, into thousands of thin-walled metal tubes. Outside the
tubes, clean, nonradioactive water is pumped in and boiled into
steam, which is used to spin a turbine, which turns a generator
that makes electricity. In February, one of the tubes leaked water
from the core, which is contaminated with radioactive material,
into the clean, non-radioactive steam. Con Ed said the release of
radiation was too small to be measured, but the plant has been shut
for analysis and repairs ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Steam generators are designed with extra tubes so bad ones can
be plugged. But that, too, could take days or weeks; the company
may simply decide to go ahead and replace the generators.
</P>
</TEXT>
