<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIL-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BURLINGTON NORTHERN AND CANADIAN NATIONAL RAILWAYS CALL OFF
MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The largest rail merger in North American history was formally
scrapped Thursday amid complaints about regulatory interference.
</P>
<P>
   The boards of the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Corp. and the
Canadian National Railway voted to end an agreement to combine the
two companies into one transcontinental system running from
Halifax, Nova Scotia, to the Mexican border and up to the Alaskan
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Executives of the two railroads said that the decision by the
Surface Transportation Board to hold up all mergers for 15 months
while new guidelines are issued had made going ahead with the plan
too risky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The delay and uncertainty caused by the STB's moratorium and
proposed rule-making made it impossible for us to continue with our
combination efforts,'' Paul Tellier, president of Canadian
National, said in a statement issued by both railroads.
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium is to last until June. Merger applications
typically take more than a year to be considered by the federal
regulatory board, which would mean that the two railroads would be
prohibited from merging for more than two years, a period they say
is too long.
</P>
<P>
   Tellier and his counterpart at Burlington Northern, Robert
Krebs, said they would work to better coordinate the operations of
the two carriers as fully as possible without a formal merger. They
said no break-up fees would be assessed because both companies had
decided to end the merger plan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, shippers said they remained convinced they had not
seen the end of the consolidation that has left just a handful of
major freight railroads to serve the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the termination of the Burlington Northern-Canadian
National proposal, shippers said they believe the major railroads
remain intent on mergering until there are just two major rail
systems left in North America. There are five major railroads
operating in the United States and two in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``The railroads have really showed their hands as far as what
they view the endgame being,'' said Diane Duff, executive director
of the Alliance for Rail Competition, which represents the coal and
chemical industries as well as other bulk shippers. ``Mergers seem
to be the only way they know how to `get efficiencies.'''
</P>
<P>
   Duff said American regulators now have a chance to ``make a sea
change in the way they've approached the rail industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Shippers have complained that the Surface Transportation Board
has favored the railroads and not always promoted real competition
adequately.
</P>
<P>
   The last few big rail mergers caused major service disruptions
that cost manufacturers and shippers millions of dollars in lost
business. Union Pacific and the Southern Pacific joined together in
1996, and last year the Norfolk Southern and the CSX each acquired
a portion of the Conrail system. Both deals resulted in bigger
railroads, but less competition, according to shippers.
</P>
<P>
   Shippers reacted angrily when Canadian National and Burlington
Northern announced their planned combination in December, and by
March the regulators called a halt to all mergers until new rules
could be drawn up. The two railroads thought that the board had
overstepped its authority, but their legal challenge was overturned
last week by a federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Surface Transportation Board said they have
already begun to receive comment from shippers and railroads on
what the new merger guidelines should look like.
</P>
<P>
   The issues to be covered include such basic ones as relieving
bottlenecks and providing access to terminal areas. A controversial
matter is expected to be the captive shippers, businesses on routes
served by only one rail line.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Speight, head of the distribution team at the American
Chemistry Council, an industry group, said the chemical producers
are particularly vulnerable to the lack of rail competition because
63 percent of the nation's chemical plants and warehouses are
already captive to a single railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something to make sure that future mergers
don't result in the same costly service problems that we
experienced in past mergers,'' Speight said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides trying to shape the new merger regulations, the chemical
industry will be lobbying Congress intensively to foster
competition in the rail industry when the moratorium ends, Speight
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board is scheduled to issue proposed
new merger regulations in the first week of October. After a period
of public comment, final regulations are to come out in June when
the moratorium has ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
