</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLA-CLEANUP-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASTE FROM OLD MINES LEAVES PILES OF PROBLEMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROSS MILLOY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PICHER, Okla. _ The problem is chat. Not the Internet variety or
the kind swapped over coffee at Rascal's Truck Stop on the highway
leading into this hardscrabble town of 1,800, but huge hills of
processed rock left after the lead and zinc mines closed in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The mounds of chat _ ground rock laced with lead and iron _ have
marked the skyline of Picher since miners began pulling minerals
from dozens of mine shafts here in 1891. When the mines played out
or were forced to close by cheaper foreign imports _ the last one
shut down in 1958 _ 175 million tons of chat was left behind,
creating a toxic moonscape encircling the town that federal
officials have been trying to clean up since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nearly a hundred chat piles near here, some of them
100 acres wide at the base and stretching 200 feet high,'' said
Philip Allen, the project manager for the Environmental Protection
Agency's Tar Creek Superfund Site remediation efforts here. ``It's
an enormous problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do the job right could cost hundreds of millions of dollars
and would probably take the rest of my career to finish,'' said
Allen, 42.
</P>
<P>
   Government efforts to do something about the chat piles began in
earnest after a 1993 study found that 34 percent of the children
tested in Picher had blood lead levels exceeding 10 micrograms per
deciliter _ considered by the Centers For Disease Control and
Prevention as the point at which there is a risk of brain or
nervous system damage.
</P>
<P>
   Some children in the area tested as high as 32 micrograms per
deciliter, said Dr. Bob Lynch, at the University of Oklahoma's
Health Sciences Center. ``If a kid is over 10, investigations get
launched. Anything over 40 requires medical intervention,'' Lynch
said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, threatened by financial shortages and an investigation
into accusations of price-gouging by one of the contractors
involved, the EPA is at least temporarily abandoning most of its
efforts here after spending $55 million over five years, $21
million of it to clean and replace the yards of 1,537 houses in
Picher.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the Oklahoma Legislature refused to appropriate $2.75
million in matching funds required to continue the program,
although about 700 sites still remained to be cleaned up, Allen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of demobilizing right now, and I expect
to be out of here by next week,'' he said. A skeleton crew of three
people, compared with a staff of 300 employees at its peak, will
remain until officials decide whether to continue the cleanup
effort next year.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 23, agents of the FBI raided the project's offices after
some former employees contended that the engineering contractor,
Morrison Knudsen, had overcharged the government.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said those accusations probably had an influence on the
Oklahoma legislators' decision not to finance the next phase of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   A Morrison Knudsen spokesman Thursday denied any wrongdoing on
the project, but declined to discuss the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Griffin, Oklahoma's secretary of the environment, said
Picher is within a 40-square-mile area designated as the nation's
highest-priority Superfund cleanup site.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to the chat, we have 2,000 abandoned mine shafts
and more than 300 miles of flooded underground tunnels in the area,
creating an extremely dangerous water quality and public safety
hazard,'' Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gov. Frank Keating appointed Griffin to head a task
force to deal with issues raised by the abandoned mines, including
the health effects of mine tailings, water quality, mine shaft
plugging and potential uses for chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a great road-building material when mixed with
asphalt,'' Griffin said. He estimates there is enough chat near
Picher to build a four-lane highway two times around the globe, and
that all of that chat would be worth about $500 million if it could
be sold.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately, Griffin said, 80 percent of the chat is on
Indian land, and the U.S. Bureau of Indian Affairs, which controls
ownership, has placed a moratorium on sale of the chat pending
further study of the health effects of using it in roads.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the herculean efforts of the government to clean up
their yards, most of the people living in the ramshackle cottages
and mobile homes of Picher remain skeptical of the chat's health
hazards and seem merely amused by the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty good job, but it's a big waste of money,''
said Theron Duggan, 33, who was an excavation crew manager for the
EPA, even cleaning up his own yard in the shadow of a towering chat
pile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played on those chat piles all my life, and I can't see
that it's affected me any,'' Duggan said.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than being grateful for the government's efforts, many
local residents complain about the quality of the federal agency's
work.
</P>
<P>
   Vance Reeves, 30, says the agency's workers killed four walnut
trees in his yard and dumped dirt on his porch.
</P>
<P>
   Steven McBride said the workers accidentally paved over part of
his yard while cleaning a parking lot next door. ``They done more
harm than betterment,'' McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Smith, 75, said that since the agency ``remediated'' her
property, water has collected in her yard after it rains, making it
hard to garden and drawing so many mosquitoes that she could not go
outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got too many workers that like to lean on their hoe
handles instead of doing things right,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
