<SLUG> BC-NY-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 NO WEST NILE VIRUS IN SOUTH CAROLINIAN'S DEATH IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 71-year-old man who died in Staten Island on
Wednesday was not infected with the West Nile virus, city officials
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The man, a visitor from South Carolina whose name has not been
released, was admitted to St. Vincent's Medical Center in Staten
Island on July 5 complaining of headache, fever and confusion _
symptoms sometimes associated with encephalitis, which can be
caused by West Nile. He died early Wednesday at the medical center.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue and blood samples from the man, who was found to have
encephalitis, were sent to the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta, as well as city laboratories, to be tested
for West Nile, largely because crows infected with the virus were
found on Staten Island this month. Although health officials said
they did not yet know why the man died, they said he could have
been sickened by any of several other viruses that cause
encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors around the city have been advised to send blood samples
of patients who have West Nile-like symptoms to the city for
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, West Nile virus sickened 62 people in the New York
region, killing 7. There have been no confirmed cases in humans
this year, but the discovery of the virus in mosquitoes and dead
birds again this year has prompted some municipalities to begin
spraying pesticide.
</P>
<P>
   The city sprayed two areas of Staten Island on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester County, north of New York City, officials planned
to spray four communities on Thursday night, beginning at 11:30:
North Castle, New Castle, Mount Pleasant and Pleasantville.
</P>
<P>
   The following 10 Westchester communities will be sprayed
starting midnight on Friday: New Rochelle, Eastchester, Tuckahoe,
Bronxville, part of Mamaroneck, Scarsdale, Mount Kisco, Pound
Ridge, Lewisboro and Bedford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
