<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0481 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-TALKS-NY     07-20 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OVERTIME AT CAMP DAVID 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 21:
</P>
<P>
   No one knows at this point whether the Camp David meetings will
eventually bring a Mideast peace agreement. This is the first time
Israeli and Palestinian leaders have tackled the most difficult
issues, like sovereignty over Jerusalem. But the fact that Israel's
prime minister, Ehud Barak, and the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, decided to stay on after President Clinton's departure for
Okinawa on Thursday morning is encouraging. Neither man wants to
walk away from the chance of ending a half-century of destructive
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Although a news blackout veils many details, the sharpest
divisions appear to be over Jerusalem. Barak, like all Israeli
leaders since 1967, has insisted that the city remain united and
under Israeli sovereignty. He is reportedly open to letting
Jerusalem's 200,000 Palestinians run their own civil affairs and
letting a Jerusalem suburb serve as a Palestinian capital. But
Arafat resists accepting permanent Israeli sovereignty over East
Jerusalem, something no Arab leader has been willing to concede. He
has left himself little room for flexibility by failing to prepare
Palestinians for any sort of compromise on the city. East
Jerusalem, which Israel captured from Jordan in the 1967 war, is
home to some of the holiest sites of Judaism, Christianity and
Islam.
</P>
<P>
   Deals are under discussion on all other issues, including
borders, the future of Jewish settlements and the return of
Palestinian refugees. But the Jerusalem impasse has blocked a
comprehensive accord, and neither leader wants to go home with a
partial agreement, leaving Jerusalem to resolve later. That would
oblige them to sell difficult compromises on other issues without a
final peace.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these obstacles, President Clinton has worked hard to
keep the talks going, persuading Barak and Arafat to stay after
both had written him letters saying they saw little hope of further
progress. Meetings are now scheduled to continue at least until
Clinton's return Sunday night. While he is away, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright will lead U.S. efforts to help the two sides
bridge their remaining differences.
</P>
<P>
   There is no easy way to reconcile the Israeli and Palestinian
positions on Jerusalem. But if Barak and Arafat believed that
Jerusalem was an insoluble problem, they would not have come to
Camp David. With enough creativity and courage, some way can still
be found to give each side enough to permit a comprehensive deal.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis and Palestinians feel passionately about Jerusalem, a
city that carries powerful religious and national symbolism. But
most people on both sides also yearn for peace. Barak and Arafat
still have time to work out a formula for Jerusalem and conclude
the historic peace agreement that is now within their reach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
