<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-G8-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ON OKINAWA FOR G-8 MEETING, ASSERTS U.S. REDUCING ITS
`FOOTPRINT' 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITOMAN CITY, Japan, _ President Clinton jumped from one delicate
matter to another Friday, after he arrived on the island of Okinawa
for an economic meeting of world leaders and immediately tried to
pacify residents fed up with the American military presence on the
island.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue to do what we can to reduce our footprint on
this island,'' Clinton said on Thursday morning at a seaside
memorial devoted to the more than 200,000 Japanese, Americans and
others who died in 1945 during the the Battle of Okinawa. ``We take
seriously our responsibility to be good neighbors, and it is
unacceptable to the United States when we do not meet the
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Before flying here, Clinton left the Middle East peace talks
unfinished and aides signaled on his arrival that he was eager to
return to Camp David. They said he might scale back his three-day
trip here for the annual meeting of the Group of 8.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton tried to reassure the Japanese, who have poured money
and attention into the meeting, that it was an important gathering
that merited his 14-hour trip. Clinton is to join the leaders of
Japan, Italy, Germany, France, Britain, Canada and Russia for a
series of closed-door meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit was the first for an American president to this
sliver of land since the United States returned Okinawa to Japan in
1972. Clinton arrived during a particular rocky time in relations
between Okinawans and the approximately 26,000 American troops
stationed on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Okinawans, who lived under U.S. occupation for 27 years, have
long complained that that they suffer from the military presence.
There are 37 U.S. military facilities in Okinawa, representing all
the services and taking up tens of thousands of acres. Recent
incidents involving wayward soldiers have added to local fury.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pointed out that the United States has begun
consolidating bases on Okinawa, a process that residents complain
has been far too slow. The president also emphasized the role
Okinawa has played in ensuring stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that the people of Okinawa did not ask to play this
role, hosting more than 50 percent of American forces in Japan on
less than 1 percent of its land mass,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In advance of the meeting, the U.S. military banned its
personnel from drinking alcohol or leaving their bases after
midnight, a curfew that followed a hit-and-run accident involving a
staff sergeant stationed at the Kadena Air Base.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, the highest-ranking U.S. military official in
Okinawa issued an apology after a marine was arrested on charges of
entering a house and molesting a 14-year-old girl who was sleeping
there.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit was reminiscent of an earlier stop by another
American president almost four decades ago. While the island was
still under U.S. control, President Dwight D. Eisenhower stopped
briefly in Okinawa on June 19, 1960, during a tour of Asia and
faced the same anger displayed for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Huge crowds of residents turned out to see Eisenhower, and 1,500
of them began a snake dance to protest the presence of American
troops and the failure to return the island to Japanese control.
</P>
<P>
   Eisenhower ignored the demonstrations in his remarks, calling
the American presence a ``splendid example of the mutual benefits
that result when people of good will work toward the common goal of
peace and friendship in freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke Friday morning from Cornerstone of Peace Park, a
memorial to the soldiers and civilians of Japanese, American and
Okinawan ancestry who died here.
</P>
<P>
   Carved into a granite wall on a seaside bluff, which Clinton
toured with the governor of Okinawa, Keichi Inamine, were the names
of 234,183 victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Battle of Okinawa was warfare at its most tragic,''
Clinton said. ``This monument built in its memory is humanity at
its most inspired. For here, no grief goes unrecognized. While most
monuments remember only those who have fallen from one side, this
memorial recognizes those from all sides, and those who took no
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke a few words of Japanese, quoting Sho Tai, an
ancient king from Okinawa who said, ``the time for war is ending,
and the time for peace is not far away.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he is to leave on Sunday afternoon, Clinton will also
address American troops at the Camp Foster Marine Base. Commanders
have selected 25 outstanding military personnel to appear with the
president and make the point that the Americans are here to
prevent, not cause, turmoil in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
