<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BRICK-ATTACK-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMELESS MAN HELD IN JULY 9 CONCRETE ATTACK ON YOUNG WOMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After an intensive 10-day search, a homeless man was
charged Thursday with using a chunk of concrete to fracture a young
woman's skull during a daytime attack in midtown Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Bently Louis Grant, 35, was charged with second-degree
attempted murder, first-degree assault and criminal possession of a
weapon, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant confessed after being picked up on Wednesday night by
three plainclothes officers who spotted him in the Park Slope
section of Brooklyn, said Police Commissioner Howard Safir at a
news conference at the 13th Precinct station house Thursday. Safir
said police had been looking for Grant, because a witness
identified him as the attacker in a photo line-up.
</P>
<P>
   A police official said that Grant did not give any motivation
for his actions in his confession.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest of Grant concludes a manhunt that began on July 9,
when Tiffany F. Goldberg, 25, was struck in the back of the head
with a chunk of concrete. The attack took place minutes after noon
on East 29th Street between Lexington Avenue and Park Avenue South,
shortly after Goldberg left the Marble Collegiate Reformed Church,
where she sings in the choir.
</P>
<P>
   She bled heavily from her skull and was taken to Bellevue
Hospital Center. She also suffered two chipped teeth and
lacerations when she fell face-first to the sidewalk. But Goldberg,
walked out the next day in high spirits, after saying that her
attacker was probably a ``struggling kid'' when he was a child.
</P>
<P>
   The attack quickly captured the public's attention, partly
because it echoed an assault in midtown last fall in which another
woman, Nicole Barrett, was smashed in her skull by a man wielding a
paving stone. Paris Drake, a street vendor, was arrested in that
case and charged with attempted murder. In both cases, the same
image of urban vulnerability resonated with the public and the news
media _ a college-educated woman attacked in broad daylight by a
man who roamed the streets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Neither woman was robbed, but police said witnesses saw Grant
reaching for Goldberg's handbag before swinging the concrete chunk.
</P>
<P>
   After the attack on Goldberg, police talked to witnesses and
circulated sketches of a man who resembled Grant. Two police
officers who were canvassing homeless people in the Murray Hill
section of Manhattan first came across Grant around noon on July
13, Safir said. They brought him into the 13th Precinct, questioned
him, took a Polaroid photograph and let him go because they did not
have any evidence to indicate he was the attacker.
</P>
<P>
   But soon afterward, a witness identified Grant from a photo
line-up. Copies of the photograph were given to officers throughout
the city. In the Polaroid, Grant wears a stained white T-shirt and
stares to the left of the camera with a haunted, faraway look.
</P>
<P>
   Three plainclothes officers were patrolling Park Slope in an
unmarked car on Wednesday evening when they saw Grant. He was
standing on the busy commercial strip of Seventh Avenue, at Carroll
Street, said Sgt. James Dodd, one of the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said he walked up to Grant and said, ``Hey Bently, how are
you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   The officer said Grant responded, ``How do you know me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know you from last year,'' Dodd said. ``What's your
last name?''
</P>
<P>
   When Grant told the officers his surname, they escorted him into
the car.
</P>
<P>
   A police official at the 13th Precinct said the questioning and
eventual confession ``took a lot of hours.'' A witness identified
Grant from a line-up, Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   Grant has no permanent address but frequented the Murray Hill
and Park Slope neighborhoods, said Chief Thomas Fahey, a police
spokesman. He said that a few homeless men had been brought in by
police and questioned during the 10-day search.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they did not know whether Grant had a history of
mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   Computerized records at the Department of Homeless Services show
that Grant spent the night of Feb. 1 in the Bellevue Men's Shelter
on First Avenue near East 30th Street, but left the next day. He
was one of more than 5,400 men in the city's shelter system that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys have this kind of lodging record,'' said Patrick
Markee, director of policy for the Coalition for the Homeless.
``One night in the winter or a handful of nights when it's cold,
but no regular contact with the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that 50 detectives worked on tracking down Goldberg's
assailant. The police offered a $10,000 reward for information in
the case. Although dozens of people are assaulted, robbed and shot
each week in New York, the police rarely expend the same amount of
manpower on tracking down those assailants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a high-profile case,'' Safir said about the use of
resources. ``It was a case that the public was concerned about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
