<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-HUFFINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUFFINS' TOP CHALLENGER IN THE DECATHLON TRIALS IS HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ind., Cal.)  By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ When he learned that Dan O'Brien had
withdrawn from the Olympic trials decathlon with a foot injury,
Chris Huffins thought someone was joking. O'Brien is the current
Olympic champion and the former world record-holder, the one
decathlete Huffins had never defeated. O'Brien has served as sort
of a mirror in which Huffins has measured his own reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe it,'' said Huffins, a native of Brooklyn who
will be an assistant track coach at Georgia Tech this fall. ``It's
like reading a book and you have the ending predicted and it's
really stupid and you think, `It's not supposed to end like
that.'''
</P>
<P>
   This was the year when Huffins, a two-time national champion,
figured he would finally defeat O'Brien, at the Olympic trials no
less. Huffins won a bronze medal at the 1999 world championships
and is expected to challenge for a medal in September at the 2000
Summer Games in Sydney, Australia. But O'Brien is gone from the
trials and Huffins' main competitor now is himself, not any
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The decathlon began Thursday night with Huffins' two strongest
events, the 100 meters and the long jump. Huffins holds the world
record for the decathlon 100, 10.22 seconds, set at the 1996
Olympic trials. His personal best in the long jump, 26 feet 5}
inches, is less than 2 inches shorter than the third-place finisher
leaped Monday night in the open long-jump final.
</P>
<P>
   Huffins held first place after three events Thursday night,
winning the 100 in 10.45 and the long jump at 25-10, and throwing
the shot put 47-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do my absolute best, I believe I will win,'' the
30-year-old Huffins said of the Olympic decathlon.
</P>
<P>
   However, his personal best of 8,694 points lags well behind the
world record of 8,994 points set by Tomas Dvorak of the Czech
Republic, who is the overwhelming Olympic favorite. Huffins'
weakness is related to his strength _ running. While he has a
sprinter's searing speed at 100 meters, and his personal best at
the nondecathlon event of 200 meters is 20.78 seconds, Huffins has
run 400 meters no faster than 48.05 and the 1,500 meters in 4
minutes 51.20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   This time in the metric mile is 17 seconds slower than O'Brien's
personal best and appears to have become a sort of psychological
hurdle for Huffins. He did not finish the decathlon at the 1997
world track championships in Athens or at an important meet in
Gotzis, Austria, earlier this year, skipping the 1,500 both times.
If Huffins is to challenge for a gold medal in Sydney, O'Brien
said, he must learn to convert his sprinter's speed to the longer
running events and to specific technical events such as the pole
vault, where his best is an ordinary 16-}, a foot shorter than
O'Brien's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just knowing that he can compete at that level and going
after the 400,'' O'Brien said of Huffins. ``He can run 21 flat in
the 200 and 48 in the quarter. That has never made sense to me. And
his pole-vault run is not what his long-jump run is. It should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Huffins said he has paid more attention to running
during training. He believes he is better prepared to deal with the
final exhausting meters of the 400, where, according to the world
record-holder Michael Johnson, ``your body is totally fatigued and
wants to flop all over the track.''
</P>
<P>
   Huffins said: ``All the components are there. In the quarter
mile, it's learning how to deal with the demons in the last
portion.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn,
Huffins never expected to become a decathlete. When he was 11, he
moved to Indianapolis to join his mother, Sandra Gay, who had
studied drama and education at Fordham University, and who wanted
her son to concentrate on his schoolwork, not athletics. Limited to
one sport, Huffins chose basketball over track and field.
</P>
<P>
   His mother later relented during her son's career at Cathedral
High in Indianapolis, and Huffins leaped 23-6{ in the long jump,
reached the state semifinals at 100 meters and earned a scholarship
to California-Berkeley, where he received a degree in the political
economies of industrial society.
</P>
<P>
   He first became intrigued by the decathlon in 1991, during a
redshirt season at Cal. Depending on what story is to be believed,
Huffins either bragged to coach Ed Miller, ``I can do that,'' or
took Miller's suggestion that training for a decathlon would aid
his sprinting, long jumping and triple jumping. ``That was a great
big farce, but I was young and dumb and it worked,'' Huffins said.
</P>
<P>
   He scored 7,531 points in his first decathlon, thought he was
awful but persisted after Miller encouraged him. His second
decathlon qualified him for the 1992 Olympic trials and his third
decathlon came at those infamous trials in New Orleans, where
O'Brien failed to clear a height in the pole vault. Unaware that
O'Brien was an Olympic favorite, Huffins said he made a friendly
bet with O'Brien that he could beat him in the long jump. He was
standing on a parallel runway when O'Brien missed on his third
attempt to clear a height in the pole vault, failing to qualify for
the Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea of that whole zoo of things going on around
me,'' Huffins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember telling myself, `I'm not going to do that''' _
fail to clear a height.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a successful pole vault, Huffins finished 15th at the
1992 trials, four places behind O'Brien. At the 1996 trials,
Huffins finished third. A month later, he took 10th at the Atlanta
Games, while O'Brien took the gold medal. Huffins later won two
national titles, but O'Brien did not compete because of injury. The
2000 Olympic trials would finally signal the changing of the
decathlon guard, Huffins believed. Then O'Brien withdrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was building to a crescendo and now it doesn't
happen,'' Huffins said. But, he added, the outcome will not be
altered, even if the competition has been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the victor is going to be any different than it
would have been in the first place,'' Huffins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000720.0487 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SENEGAL-NYT &LR;      07-20 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SENEGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: JUSTICE DENIED IN SENEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, July 21:
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago the Pinochet precedent spread to Africa when
Senegal decided to try the former dictator of Chad, Hissene Habre,
on charges of torture. It was the first time an African country had
brought human rights charges against another nation's head of
state, and it energized democracy activists _ and terrified other
former tyrants _ across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   But Senegalese courts have now dropped the charges after what
looks suspiciously like interference from the country's new
president. Chad's torture victims have appealed. Their plea should
be heard by a court independent of executive branch pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Habre ruled Chad for eight years with the backing of France and
the United States, which supported him as a counter to the Libyan
leader, Moammar Ghadafy. Habre's regime killed thousands of people,
and hundreds of thousands may have been tortured. He was overthrown
in 1990. Since then he has lived in Senegal.
</P>
<P>
   His comfortable exile was disturbed when he was arrested in
February, after a group of torture victims came to Senegal to
testify. Judge Demba Kandji's indictment was based on Senegal's
ratification of the Torture Convention, which obliges states to
prosecute or extradite alleged torturers no matter where the crimes
took place.
</P>
<P>
   In March, however, Abdoulaye Wade was elected president of
Senegal. Wade appointed Habre's attorney, Madicke Niang, as a
special adviser. President Wade also headed a panel that removed
Kandji from the case. The president of the Indicting Chamber, the
body that released Habre, was promoted while his chamber was
deliberating the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The chamber's decision that Senegal had no jurisdiction to
prosecute torture abroad is particularly disappointing because
Senegal enjoys one of Africa's most independent judiciaries. It was
the first nation to ratify the International Criminal Court, and
its lawyers hold prominent positions in judicial and human rights
organizations worldwide. If it tried Habre, Senegal could make a
signal contribution to human rights on a continent that has
suffered more than any other from murderous leaders and the absence
of the rule of law.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
