<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8420 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     07-20 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING WILL MISS ALLEN PAULSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Allen Paulson, the great thoroughbred
breeder and owner who died of cancer Wednesday night in La Jolla,
Calif., won major horse races all over the world and flew his
Gulfstream airplanes to round-the-globe records.
</P>
<P>
   To feel racing's loss, though, you needn't go any farther than
Hollywood Park. It was here that Paulson displayed the adventurous
spirit that distinguished him.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1995, Cigar had won eight races in a row, a streak that
had taken him to five tracks in as many Eastern states, and trainer
Bill Mott was understandably reluctant to ship the emerging
superstar to the Hollywood Gold Cup to take on the best of the
West. But Paulson rarely thought small. He wanted the Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar came to Hollywood Park and won the $1 million race by 3
lengths, with million-dollar race winners Tinners Way, Best Pal and
Concern giving chase. Cigar's winning streak would grow to a
record-tying 16, including a victory in the far-away Dubai World
Cup, before ending at Del Mar on his next California excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar became a modern racing legend _ and earned nearly $10
million _ for three reasons: his own physical gifts, Mott's
training skill and Paulson's ambition, not always in that order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was huge for him to go ahead and do that,'' said Martin
Panza, the Hollywood Park racing secretary then and now, referring
to the decision to run Cigar here. ``At the time, everyone (who ran
a track) wanted that horse. It wasn't an easy sale to get him to
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Paulson) was pretty game about running him. In today's
racing climate a lot of owners wouldn't have done it. But there was
more `sportsman' in him. It said a lot about Mr. Paulson, being a
sportsman and saying, `I want people around the country to see this
horse.'''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Hollywood Park began its racing card with a moment of
silence for Paulson, who had once been a member of the track's
board of directors as well as a leading owner.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, who was 78 years old when he died at Scripps Hospital,
probably showed more good horses to more racing fans than any other
owner in the 1980s and 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife Madeleine won Eclipse Awards with eight horses,
including Cigar's 1995 and 1996 Horse of the Year titles and
Arazi's 1991 2-year-old championship.
</P>
<P>
   He and Madeleine won Breeders' Cup races with a record eight
horses and started a record 33.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson himself was honored as the outstanding owner of 1995 and
1996 and outstanding breeder of 1993, and led the nation's owners
in purses each year from 1995 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His major victories in California _ where he had homes in Los
Angeles, Rancho Santa Fe and Palm Springs _ included two Hollywood
Gold Cups (the first won by Blushing John in 1989), a Santa Anita
Handicap (Stuka, 1994), a Santa Anita Derby (Dinard, 1991), a Strub
Stakes (Diazo, 1994), a Hollywood Oaks (Fowda, 1991), a Vanity
Handicap (Escena, 1998) and a Ramona Handicap (Escena, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Many of those horses were named for aviation checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
   Until his battle with cancer took him away from the racetrack
and led to the sales of his breeding farms in Kentucky and Florida,
Paulson was a familiar, affable presence. He enjoyed boasting about
his latest winners, especially when they were the offspring of his
past winners, which was often the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes his confidence was off-target, such as when he chided
newspaper handicappers for failing to pick Stuka to win the 1994
Big 'Cap, neglecting the fact Stuka finished second in the race
only to be declared the winner after The Wicked North was
disqualified for interfering with a third horse.
</P>
<P>
   Moments like that aside, Paulson had a keen mind, and it made
him a giant in the aerospace industry. Airplanes had been a boyhood
fascination for Allen Eugene Paulson, born April 22, 1922 as the
youngest of five boys in a Clinton, Iowa, farm family.
</P>
<P>
   In a 30-cents-an-hour job as a Trans World Airlines mechanic, he
readied planes for Howard Hughes. After stints in college and the
Army Air Corps, he became a flight engineer.
</P>
<P>
   Then living in Burbank, he tinkered with aircraft parts in his
spare time, and in 1952 formed a company to design and build
planes. Twenty-five years later he formed Gulfstream Aerospace
Corporation and became the manufacturer of prestigious private
jets.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 and 1988, when he was 65, Paulson and a crew flew
Gulfstream IVs on two round-the-world trips that established 35
international records. He was named Pilot of the Year by
Professional Pilot Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to get ahead is to put more effort into things
than the other fellows did,'' Paulson said once. ``I found it hard
to pass on opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing is thankful he rarely did.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson is survived by his wife, sons Richard, Jim and Mike, and
daughter Dominique. Plans were pending for a private funeral and a
memorial service in Rancho Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND: Sunday, the second to last day of the Hollywood
Park season, features the Swaps Stakes and two other stakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Swaps, which has attracted Triple Crown runners in some
years, has only one Grade I winner this time, 1999 Hollywood
Futurity champion Captain Steve. The ``now'' horse might be Tiznow,
the popular Budroyale's full brother, who won the Affirmed Handicap
at 10-1 last time out.
</P>
<P>
   Also Sunday, Squirtle Squirt, ridden by Laffit Pincay, can match
Riboletta and Full Moon Madness with a third stakes victory at the
meet by winning the Hollywood Juvenile Championship. His 2-year-old
opponents include Drumcliff, a D. Wayne Lukas-trained colt who
broke his maiden at Belmont Park.
</P>
<P>
   Some human races, too, will be decided between now and Monday.
Bob Baffert, seeking his second Hollywood Park training title, and
Clifford Sise, seeking his first, were tied with 21 victories and
Bobby Frankel had 19 after each went winless Thursday. Jockey
Victor Espinoza has a comfortable 57-48 lead over Corey Nakatani.
</P>
<P>
   It might take more than a training title to get Baffert even for
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the California Horse Racing Board issued a complaint
against the three-time Eclipse Award-winning trainer after a split
urine sample confirmed the presence of morphine in the John and
Betty Mabee-owned Nautical Look when the filly won a May 3 race at
Hollywood Park. The case is to be heard by stewards at Del Mar
during the 43-day meet that opens Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Baffert and owner Mike Pegram were hit with a lawsuit
by breeder George Hofmeister, who charged them with fraud for their
handling of Real Quiet before the 1998 Kentucky Derby and Preakness
winner went to stud this year.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert told the Daily Racing Form the morphine accusation was
the result of ``accidental contamination,'' and the lawsuit ``has
absolutely no merit.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti is a Daily News columnist. His horse racing column
appears on Friday. He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
