<SLUG> BC-UNITED-AIRLINES-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIR CRITICIZES MECHANICS FOR DELAYS IN MAINTENANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines, already reeling from the refusal of many of its
10,000 pilots to work overtime, is now facing similar difficulties
from its 15,000 mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Ron Utecht, United's senior vice president for
maintenance, circulated a letter to mechanics complaining that
flight cancellations and delays related to maintenance had more
than doubled since July 12, the day the airline's contract with the
International Association of Machinists expired.
</P>
<P>
   Utecht added that the number of United airplanes out of service
had also doubled, while the number of mechanics willing to work
overtime had plunged. He threatened to order mandatory overtime if
the airline's maintenance operations did not improve.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several mechanics were issued form letters
informing them that they were engaged in an ``illegal job action''
and could be dismissed if they did not stop.
</P>
<P>
   A United spokesman declined to say how many of its 2,400 daily
flights were affected by the mechanics' actions, but he said that
the impact had been relatively minor.
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Ford, president of the local representing the mechanics,
called Utecht's letter counterproductive. The IAM ``has not
authorized nor encouraged any job action at United Airlines,'' he
said in a statement. ``Threats and counterthreats will not help
United, our members, or the traveling public,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, United has canceled more flights and reported
the worst on-time performance of any major carrier, according to
government statistics. The airline blames unusually bad weather and
the air traffic control system for most of its difficulties. But it
also says that it was caught by surprise when many of its pilots
stopped flying overtime after their contract expired April 12. The
pilots' union also says that it is not engaged in any job action.
</P>
<P>
   United has since cut its summer flying schedule by 4,800
flights, or about 2 percent, to compensate for the crew shortages
and has taken several other initiatives, like adding more time to
its schedules, to try to improve its on-time performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reliability is obviously a core objective for us, and we are
determined to get it back to the levels our customers expect,''
Rono J. Dutta, United's president, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the expiration of the contract with the machinists
approached, United executives said they were confident that the
union would not disrupt the airline's operations. But it appears
that some of the machinists are as upset as the pilots.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the two groups received a majority of the stock in
United's parent company, UAL Corp., in exchange for deep wage cuts
and other concessions that helped return the airline to
profitability and made UAL the largest employee-owned company in
the world. Both are expecting to reap big rewards for their
sacrifices in their new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   United said that it was committed to signing industry-leading
contracts but that the negotiations might take longer than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for airlines to conclude new employee
contracts years after the old ones expire. But the pilots and
mechanics say they were led to believe that United would act
differently.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
