u a BC-NY-PAROLE-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      07-20 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PAROLE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-AIDE TO PATAKI QUESTIONED IN INFLUENCE-PEDDLING TRIAL
</HEADLINE>
  By ALAN FEUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former top aide to Gov. George Pataki came under vigorous
cross-examination Thursday during a trial centering on charges that
a Pataki fund-raiser solicited donations in exchange for political
favors.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony by Patrick Donohue, Pataki's former campaign
finance director, was the highlight of the politically charged
trial, which began two weeks ago. Donohue seemed to be tripped up a
handful of times as the government indicated inconsistencies in his
testimony, in which he denied that he had promised to help win the
parole of three violent felons whose families had contributed to
Pataki's 1994 campaign for governor. Pataki has not been implicated
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   In a hushed voice that at times barely reached the jurors,
Donohue said, for example, that he had no idea that one of Pataki's
volunteer fund-raisers had sought donations from the three families
because they were interested in getting their children freed from
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, however, prosecutors read the jury some of
Donohue's earlier testimony, in which he admitted knowing that the
fund-raiser, Yung Soo Yoo, had taken money from the families and
that they wanted the Pataki administration's help in getting their
sons released.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue was testifying at the influence-peddling trial of Yoo, a
prominent New Jersey businessman who was often called upon to raise
money for the Republican Party among the region's Korean-Americans.
Yoo, 63, is accused of promising the three Korean families that he
would use his clout within the governor's office to get their sons
paroled if they donated thousands of dollars to Pataki's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The trial in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn stems from a 2
1/2-year investigation into allegations that Pataki officials
drummed up campaign contributions with promises of early parole.
While the federal prosecutors overseeing the case have said
numerous times that there is no evidence that Pataki participated
in or had knowledge of the crimes charged, the case has still
proved somewhat embarrassing for his administration, which has
sought to eliminate parole entirely and has made it tougher for
violent felons to win release on parole.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry has resulted in the perjury convictions of two state
parole officials, Ronald Hotaling and Sean McSherry, and the
indictment of a third, Leo S. Levy, on charges of misleading
investigators in the case. It has also led to the intense scrutiny
of a handful of Pataki aides, including Donohue, who has never been
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the governor, has said
throughout the investigation that officials never engaged in
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue's appearance in court Thursday as a defense witness was
greeted with a type of gleeful hunger by federal prosecutors, who
have been investigating him since the start of the case. They
wasted no time pouncing on the witness, opening their
cross-examination with a frontal attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``You understand, Mr. Donohue, as you sit here today, that you
are a target of the investigation of the United States attorney's
office into federal bribery _ you understand that, right?'' a
prosecutor, Margaret Giordano, acerbically asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, ma'am,'' Donohue answered, wide-eyed but remaining calm.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, Giordano tried to get Donohue to admit that he
was aware that the families' contributions were taken in exchange
for assistance in getting the prisoners released. But with
carefully chosen words and abundant politeness, Donohue said
several times that neither he nor Yoo made any specific promises to
the families, who had donated more than $36,000 to Pataki's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Donohue was caught a few times saying something in
open court only to have his own earlier testimony or, in two
powerful instances, tape recordings flatly contradict him.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, he testified that he had never sent documents in
support of the release of one of the prisoners, James Jhang, to the
governor's counsel's office, which often handles clemency requests.
But seconds later, the prosecution played a secretly recorded tape
on which Donohue was heard saying that he had, in fact, forwarded
the documents to the counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Donohue testified that he had met Michael Jhang, the
brother of James Jhang, only once to discuss the case. Again, the
government played a tape on which Donohue was heard saying he had
met Michael Jhang at least a half-dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue explained the first discrepancy by saying that the
counsel's office was where some documents related to prisoners were
typically sent, not that he had actually sent them. He explained
the second discrepancy by saying he was lying on the tape about
having met Michael Jhang numerous times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
