<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM MOTE, 93, MILLIONAIRE AND DEVELOPER OF MARINE CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ William Russell Mote, a millionaire businessman
whose love of the sea led him to build the Mote Marine Laboratory
here into a major research center, died July 18 at his home on
Longboat Key. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Tampa in 1906, Mote, who spent boyhood days wading in
Tampa Bay for crabs and clams, traced his maritime passion to
childhood fishing trips.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, he moved to New York and spent the next three decades
running Republic Carloading &AMP; Distributing Co., a transportation
company, which made him rich. It was sold in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   He never earned a college degree, he told friends, because he
was too busy building his business.
</P>
<P>
   Settling in Sarasota in 1965, Mote wanted to create a marine
laboratory on Florida's west coast. He found that a shark
researcher, Eugenie Clark, was struggling to keep the Cape Haze
Marine Laboratory going, and Mote decided to improve the facility.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, the laboratory's name was changed to honor its
benefactors, Mote, his wife, Lenore, and his sister Elizabeth Mote
Rose. It was moved to its present location on City Island in
Sarasota in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Mote has given the laboratory at least $8 million over the
years. In 1991, Congress chose the laboratory as the home of the
National Center for Shark Research. The laboratory's snook breeding
program has also earned worldwide recognition, with nearly 40,000
hatchlings released into Sarasota Bay in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the International Oceanographic Foundation gave Mote
its Gold Medal Award for promoting the study of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   Mote and his wife, who died in 1991, donated $1 million in 1994
to establish the William R. and Lenore Mote Eminent Scholar Chair
in Fisheries Ecology at Florida State University.
</P>
<P>
   Mote was president of the laboratory's board until his death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, he founded the Mote Vascular Foundation, which supports
efforts to diagnose, prevent and treat vascular disorders. Mote
lost both his legs to vascular problems in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   A laboratory spokeswoman said Mote has no immediate survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-20-00 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
