u a BC-PHONE-SUITS-NYT &LR;      07-20 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONE-SUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
8 STATES SUE LONG-DISTANCE CARRIERS OVER ADS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.J., Ill., Calif., Idaho, Maine, Minn., Mo.)  By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Connecticut and New Jersey were among eight
states that filed lawsuits Thursday against AT&AMP;T, Sprint and
WorldCom, the nation's three largest long-distance telephone
carriers, accusing them of misleading consumers in television
commercials that offer low per-minute rates.
</P>
<P>
   The suits, filed Thursday in the states' courts, claim that the
advertisements, which feature Michael Jordan, the comedian Paul
Reiser and several Looney Tunes characters, distract viewers from
the fine print that briefly appears, showing the actual costs of
signing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially they have resorted to glitzy gimmicks and
graphics, cartoon characters and world-class celebrities, all to
confuse, deceive and distract consumers from information that is
essential to their understanding the real deal on phone company
services,'' said Connecticut's attorney general, Richard
Blumenthal, in a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan pitches 5 cents a minute,'' lumenthal said,
referring to a well-known WorldCom commercial in which Jordan
banters with Tweety Bird. ``But hey, Michael, that's only in the
evenings, or on weekends,'' he said, ``and it's only for people at
their residences,'' and valid for only out-of-state calls.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut was the only state to file suit Thursday against all
three companies, though the other states may file additional suits
in coming months. Thursday, New Jersey filed suit in Superior Court
in Essex County only against WorldCom, formerly known as MCI,
claiming that its ``Five Cents Everyday'' commercials fail to
clearly disclose the $4.95 monthly fee and calling restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut and Illinois are suing Sprint, saying its
commercials that promote rates ranging from 2 to 10 cents a minute
do not adequately disclose monthly fees, allowable calling times
and surcharges, depending on where calls are made.
</P>
<P>
   Commercials for AT&AMP;T, which is being sued by three states,
feature Reiser pithily pitching a rate of 7 cents per minute, while
the words ``All Day, Every Day'' appear on screen. ``What was
confusing is now not,'' Reiser says at the end of the ad. Mandatory
monthly charges and restrictions on the low rates flash in print
too small, and too briefly broadcast, to be read by any but the
most careful viewers, the suits charge.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Siegal, a spokesman for AT&AMP;T, said, ``It's long been our
policy to be open and honest about fees and charges in our
advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, he said, AT&AMP;T sent letters to the 28 million customers
who use its basic-rate service to explain how the company charges
for long distance. ``You really can't do anything else in a highly
competitive marketplace,'' he said. ``It really wouldn't make much
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Lydia Steinberg, a spokeswoman for Sprint, said the company's
ads were clear and accurate.
</P>
<P>
   WorldCom did not comment on the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The eight states _ which include California, Idaho, Illinois,
Maine, Minnesota and Missouri _ sued after months of talks between
state officials and company executives, which began as early as
last November, failed to produce an agreement, Blumenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the suits against the carriers could yield
``potentially millions of dollars,'' depending on the number of
customers affected in each state.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's suit seeks $7,500 for each customer MCI may have
deceived through its commercials as well as other practices that
the state says falsely portray calling-card costs, in violation of
the state's Consumer Fraud Act.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have until late August to respond to the lawsuits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
