<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-20 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8431 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-MARRIAGEPENALTY-HNS &LR;      07-20 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARRIAGE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS MARRIAGE PENALTY TAX CUT 
 

</HEADLINE>
 PENALTY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House on Thursday passed compromise legislation
to provide $90 billion in tax relief over the next five years to
remove the so-called ``marriage penalty'' for dual-income couples
filing joint tax returns
</P>
<P>
   But the 271-156 vote fell short of the 290 votes required to
override an expected presidential veto. Fifty-one Democrats broke
ranks in voting for the Republican-backed measure.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-controlled Senate is expected today to pass the bill,
which would remove federal tax provisions that cause about 25
million dual-income married couples to pay more in federal income
taxes than they would if they filed as singles.
</P>
<P>
   The bill calls for shallower tax cuts than the tax-repeal
proposals that the House and Senate passed earlier this month.
Republican House and Senate leaders said they agreed to reduce the
cuts late Wednesday in an effort to gain President Clinton's
support for a unified House-Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., doubted the
Republicans' sincerity and accused them of playing politics in
advance of their party convention that starts July 31 in
Philadelphia. Republicans know Clinton will veto the bill, said
Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in Japan for an international economic summit, has said
he would veto the GOP measure because it doesn't contain the $250
billion in Medicare prescription drug coverage he seeks for seniors
over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton already has before him Republican-backed legislation to
repeal the federal estate tax. Clinton has said he will veto that
measure because the tax largely applies to the wealthiest 2 percent
of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In dueling news conferences before the House vote Thursday,
Democratic congressional leaders said the GOP is putting politics
ahead of sound policy while Republicans countered that Democrats
are favoring government programs over reducing taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Republicans) have continued to provide tax relief to
those wealthiest among us at the expense of health insurance, at
the expense of prescription drugs, at the expense of child care, at
the expense of college tuition tax credits,'' said Daschle. ``I
fear they want the issue, they don't want the accomplishment.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said the GOP-backed legislation would give an unfair
benefit to nearly 20 million married couples who are either
unaffected by the penalty or enjoy a tax break through marriage
because one spouse earns significantly more than the other.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Democrats unsuccessfully offered a more
sensible marriage-tax repeal which would have made it easier for
all married couples to file singly if a joint filing would result
in a higher tax.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why so many congressional Democrats have voted for the GOP
bills, Daschle conceded that political realities make it difficult
for lawmakers to oppose tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's face it: These are popular tax cuts,'' Daschle said.
``Tax cuts have constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., assailed what he
called the Republicans' ``press-release strategy'' of passing
unsound but popular tax cuts that they will be able to trumpet at
their coming national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders dismissed this accusation, saying that
fairness requires that the federal government not impose taxes that
discriminate against married couples or are assessed on the estates
of people after they die.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to help people keep more money in their own pocket
rather than sending it to Washington,'' said House Speaker J.
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the government
``should be strengthening families'' not penalizing them for being
married.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed marriage-penalty repeal would gradually remove a
disparity in the graduated income-tax system.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, individuals earning up to $26,250 annually are in the
15 percent income-tax bracket. However, a married couple cannot
earn $52,500, twice the $26,250, and remain in the 15 percent
bracket. The 15 percent bracket extends only to joint income of
$43,850.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, two individuals making $25,000 annually would be
taxed singly at 15 percent. But, if they married, some of their
joint income of $50,000 would be taxed at 28 percent, hence they
would be ``penalized,'' in the vernacular of tax accountants.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would remove that over the next five years by
raising the combined income that married couples can earn under the
15 percent bracket to twice that of individuals.
</P>
<P>
   The measure also would allow a married couple filing jointly to
claim a standard deduction that equals twice the singles standard
deduction.
</P>
<P>
   For tax year 2000 that would mean increasing the standard
deduction for married couples from $7,350 to $8,800, a boost of
nearly 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP-backed marriage-penalty and estate-tax repeals come amid
Congressional Budget Office projections of a budget surplus of
$2.17 trillion over the next 10 years, including a $102 billion
surplus next year. Citing the surplus, Republicans have pressed for
tax relief, while Democrats have sought more money for health care
and education. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
